<SLUG> BC-BKN-OLAJUWON </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Raptors told no on Olajuwon deal
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JONATHAN FEIGEN &QL; 
All things considered, the Rockets just couldn't bring themselves
to trade Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   Presented with a chance to rebuild that might not come again,
the Rockets mulled the Toronto Raptors' offer of two lottery picks
plus Kevin Willis and Doug Christie in exchange for Olajuwon, a
12-time All-Star and franchise cornerstone. The Raptors were even
willing to tweak the offer almost any way they could.
</P>
<P>
   But after one last meeting Tuesday morning, the Rockets broke
off negotiations, with coach Rudy Tomjanovich unable to bring
himself to deal the player who had been so central to the success
of the only team for which either has been employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any deal involving Hakeem Olajuwon would be very difficult for
me to make, because I have an emotional tie to him,'' said
Tomjanovich, who confirmed there had been trade talks. ``That's
just the way it is. That's just the way I am. I believe in
(loyalty). We've been through a lot together. I would hope that
situation doesn't come along.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon said he would have opposed a trade and was relieved it
did not go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a great deal to me to finish my career in Houston,''
he said. ``It has been the whole story, from college to now, and it
seems this is a right way for it to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich and Rockets vice president Carroll Dawson
characterized the trade talks as typical of the business,
especially in the days leading up to today's NBA draft. But the
discussions with Toronto could be considered different from most
trade negotiations because they involved Olajuwon and were not
immediately dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said forms of Toronto's offer had been pondered for
almost two weeks, with variations including as many as 11 players
or draft picks. The transfer to the Rockets of Willis, Christie and
the fifth and 12th picks in today's draft were a constant
throughout the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer exactly the details of the deal,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``They were interested. It never got to do-or-die.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was talk. It was never a concrete deal. I will admit there
was talk. There was strong interest there.''
</P>
<P>
   As late as 2:30 a.m. Tuesday, when conversations among Rockets
officials broke up, a definitive decision had not been reached.
</P>
<P>
   But with owner Leslie Alexander on the phone from New York,
Tomjanovich, Dawson and team vice president Robert Barr met at
Westside Tennis Club later Tuesday morning, and the decision was
made to end negotiations with the Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Olajuwon called Tomjanovich and was told the
trade would not be made. Toronto vice president and general manager
Glen Grunwald then announced that while there had been talks, the
deal was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We approached them about it,'' Grunwald said. ``They thought
about it but ultimately said no. The right package couldn't be
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich, however, did not blame the package for scotching
the trade talks. It was simply a matter of the Rockets not wanting
to part with the greatest player ever to wear their uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toronto was interested in Dream. There were talks. They were
told no,'' Tomjanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always talk,'' he added. ``That's just the way it is.
That's just the way of the league. Everybody has to do their job.
We have a department that listens to things. That's just business.
You have to do that. People are going to talk to you. We have no
control over what other people want. This thing is just talk. We
would not be doing our job if we did not listen to all kinds of
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have a chance to talk to Dream and tell him this was not
a deal and how I felt.''
</P>
<P>
   The league's Most Valuable Player in 1993-94 and the NBA Finals
MVP in 1994 and 1995, Olajuwon is the Rockets' all-time leader in
seasons of service, games, minutes, points, rebounds, steals,
blocked shots, free throws made, free throws attempted, field goals
made and field goals attempted. This past season, he averaged 18.9
points (making 51.4 percent of his shots), 9.6 rebounds and 2.46
blocked shots per game.
</P>
<P>
   And Dawson indicated he is still held in the highest regard
despite the fact Rockets officials considered potential deals with
the Raptors enticing because of the opportunity to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't make you unattached to somebody,'' Dawson said.
``I can't tell you how many times I've stood up for the national
anthem with the guy. I've spent the biggest part of my life with
this franchise, and he's been here 15 of those years. If you're a
human being, you're emotionally going to get attached.''
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday morning, after marathon meetings to consider every
piece of information available, that one sentiment made the other
considerations moot. It also sent the Rockets looking elsewhere for
ways to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to do is look at all the options and consider all
options,'' Tomjanovich said. ``That's the draft, free agency and
trades. It's always been like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
