<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS PLAYS WAITING GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Jim Edmonds wants to play this year. But the center
fielder, who had surgery on his right shoulder April 19, also knows
he might not be able to play until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had surgery they told me I might not play at all this
year,'' he said. ``I have to think about playing the next six or
seven years, not just this year.''
</P>
<P>
   While he knows he must be patient, he still wants to help the
1999 club. The team is last in the American League in a variety of
offensive categories, including runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds said the biggest concern with his shoulder involves
swinging the bat. But if he gets the OK to begin baseball
activities _ mid-to late-August at the earliest _ he plans to be
ready to join the lineup quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I stay (with the club) and take a lot of batting practice,
hopefully I'll get enough swings I don't have to stay long in a
rehab assignment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue will be where the team is in the standings. If the
Angels are out of the race, there's no reason for Edmonds to rush
back to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm in shape and ready to play, I want to play,'' he said.
``So we'll have to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Swimming upstream: Right fielder Tim Salmon arrives at the
ballpark every day, does the rehab work on his sprained left wrist
and goes home.
</P>
<P>
   He was hitting .347 with seven homers and 25 RBI on May 3 when
he tried to make a sliding catch of Paul Konerko's sinking liner in
a game against the White Sox. The resulting wrist injury has kept
him out ever since, even though he thought he'd only miss a few
days at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm past the point of frustration _ we're two months into
this,'' he said. ``But it's scarring, so that means it's healing.''
</P>
<P>
   That also means there's no reason to have surgery, though
there's still no telling when he'll be ready.
</P>
<P>
   How desperately do the Angels need him? Going into Tuesday's
game, the Angels hitting in the cleanup spot had a total of six RBI
in June.
</P>
<P>
   Small favors: At least the Angels have shortstop Gary DiSarcina
back. Even though DiSarcina went into Tuesday's game hitting only
.188 (3 for 16) and says it feels like spring training for him, he
is recognized as a team leader on the field and in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, he's still working on some things,'' manager
Terry Collins said. ``Defensively he's fine. He's getting his legs
in shape. I think he'll be OK when we come out of the (All-Star)
break.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina missed the first 68 games of the season with a broken
bone in his left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Hard times: Critics of Collins say he's never won anything as a
manager. But he's been close. In all five major-league seasons
(three in Houston, two in Anaheim), his teams have finished in
second place. That's why this year has been so difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough, it's been very tough,'' he said. ``I've never
been in last place before. We've struggled, but you've got to climb
your way out of it. It's what we're going to do. You just keep
playing and playing and playing until there aren't any more
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: The Angels and Rangers finish their three-game series
tonight beginning at 7:35. Ken Hill (3-7, 4.97 ERA) will start for
Anaheim against Texas' Ryan Glynn (1-2, 7.46).
</P>
</TEXT>
