<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHING CHANGES IN WORKS; MECHE COMING UP FROM TACOMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ For months, the Mariners have held to one philosophy
on the subject of their coveted pitching prospects. They would not
part with a Ryan Anderson, Gil Meche or Joel Pineiro unless they
got a top young major-leaguer in return.
</P>
<P>
   But several factors might be changing that approach: the
performance of rookies Freddy Garcia and John Halama; the Mariners'
standing in the American League West race; and the impending
promotion of Meche from Class AAA Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the M's believe they already have identified
several young (and affordable) pitchers with big-league staying
power, but they might not be able to win the division without
another veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this type of trade, it all depends on who you're getting
back,'' said Woody Woodward, Mariners vice president for baseball
operations. ``I wouldn't rule out anything. If we're in the pennant
race after this tough road trip and we go into the All-Star break
right in it like we are, I wouldn't rule out anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But just because he could be more willing to part with a
prospect doesn't make it any more desirable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make it any easier, not from where I sit,''
Woodward said. ``It just shows me if you get the right young
pitcher, they can get the job done. You have to give them the
chance, and stay with them once in a while when they fail.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the plan with Meche, the Mariners' No. 1 pick in the 1996
draft, who will be promoted from Class AAA to start in Anaheim on
Tuesday. He will replace Paul Abbott, who will be moved to a set-up
relief role. Frankie Rodriguez will make a spot start in Abbott's
place Thursday in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Meche isn't the only pitcher coming. Left-hander Jordan
Zimmerman joined the team Tuesday and another 24-year-old lefty,
Damaso Marte, will be promoted Wednesday. Veteran left-hander Allen
Watson was released to make room for Zimmerman, and right-hander
Melvin Bunch is expected to be sent down when Marte arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Marte, who started 87 of his 104 professional games, will be
more of a long reliever while Zimmerman will be the Mariners'
left-handed specialist. Carrying only one left-hander, as the M's
have for much of this season, is hard to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is,'' said manager Lou Piniella. ``You use one for a
couple of innings, and now you don't have one the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Meche's arrival likely will mean the Mariners carry 12 pitchers.
If that happens, outfielder Charles Gipson would most likely be
sent down. Jay Buhner's status might be unchanged by then; Piniella
said the M's might wait until after the All-Star break to activate
the outfielder from the disabled list, where he's been with a
hamstring strain since mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   The progress of Meche has been one of the most pleasant
developments in the organization this year. During a rough road
trip in early May, when Piniella first floated the idea of bringing
up the Mariners' best prospects, Woodward was watching Meche pitch
at a Class AA game in Portland, Maine. He liked what he saw, and
soon Meche was promoted to Tacoma, where he has gone 2-2 with a
3.24 earned run average in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   His Monday start was scheduled to be a short one, which would
put Meche on schedule to make a final Tacoma start Thursday before
facing the Angels Tuesday. But a line drive off his right forearm
made it even shorter, and Meche left after 25 pitches. Woodward
said the forearm is fine, though the ball ricocheted to Meche's
left thumb, which is giving him trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The injury is not considered serious, and Meche's overall
performance has convinced the Mariners to give the 20-year-old a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the pitches to pitch up here at this age,'' Woodward
said. ``The only concern is not to bring him up before he's had
enough starts at triple-A.''
</P>
<P>
   Meche's poise, long considered one of his best assets, also
helped his cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has to go into it,'' Woodward said. ``It's more than on
the field, it's how a guy deals with everything around the big
leagues. That goes into it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the Mariners keep trying to find the right mix of
pitchers, they clearly hope they're not done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're changing things around a little bit, with the idea of
giving our better young arms a chance,'' Piniella said. ``And we'll
continue to look for a little experience if we can find it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman and Marte could be on their own as lefties in the pen.
Woodward said left-handed relief has been the hardest thing to find
in trades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
