u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EAGLES-MEMBERSHIP-SPI     06-30 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAGLES-MEMBERSHIP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES CHAPTER IN WASHINGTON TOWN BEING SUED FOR EXCLUDING WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MAGGIE LEUNG AND JUDI HUNT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Liberty, truth, justice and equality _ those are the
Fraternal Order of Eagles' cornerstones. But how the Eagles define
equality _ gender equality, at least _ has provoked a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest Women's Law Center is suing the Eagles in Thurston
County (Wash.) Superior Court for refusing to let women become
voting members of the social and service club.
</P>
<P>
   Directly affected are the 53 women already in the chapter at
Tenino, which had its charter suspended. Tenino is about 10 miles
south of Olympia, the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' national leadership defends its ban on women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delegates voted that way,'' Grand Secretary Robert Wahls
said by telephone from Columbus, Ohio. ``Most agreed that it (a ban
on female members) should remain _ that there's no need to change
it, because it's been that way for 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   That tradition clashes with Washington state's law against
discrimination based on race, sex, national origin, religion and
disability, said Lisa Stone, executive director of the Northwest
Women's Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Eagles' leaders declined comment or were unavailable
Tuesday. But the organization's own legal advisory panel determined
in late 1995 that the Eagles were required to admit women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts have consistently upheld legislation designed to
prevent discriminatory membership policies in private clubs when
such policies are based solely on gender,'' the Eagles' Justices of
the Grand Tribunal found. ``Given these interpretations, our
fraternal laws must then yield to prevailing civil law.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Eagles let women become full members. That
change was short-lived, however. In 1998, delegates at the Eagles'
national convention in Spokane ignored the tribunal's opinion and
banned full memberships for women.
</P>
<P>
   That decision has set some Eagles' chapters against the national
leadership. In January, the international organization threatened
to revoke the charters of chapters that continued to admit women.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Tenino chapter's charter was suspended for
admitting women.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Tenino chapter President-elect Janet Tresenriter
promised to fight: ``What we're saying is they can't just decide
they don't want us anymore without facing a tough fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going into the year 2000, and it's silly for men to want
things to stay like they were in the 1800s. They can't keep women
in their place anymore. We won't stand for being second-class
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest Women's Law Center is suing on behalf of the
Tenino chapter, Tresenriter and several other female members.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three of the chapter's 720 members are women, Tresenriter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing, too, because six of them are officers,''
she said. ``If we weren't, those offices would be empty.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling is shared by the Lion's Club, said Jim Knight, one
of its district governors. The Lion's Club started admitting women
about 10 years ago, and Knight is enthusiastic about their
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They filled a void in the membership,'' he said. ``They fill
many different jobs. They're extremely involved, capable and
helpful. I'd hate to see the Lion's Club organization without
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Lion's Clubs include female members, because membership
to the service organization is by invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are chapters where a lot of old-timers say, `We're not
going to have women at this Lion's Club!''' But some of them later
turn out to be the biggest supporters of female members, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, founded in 1898 in Seattle, has more than 1,700
chapters nationwide and in Canada. The organization, which includes
a women's auxiliary, raises money for charities and offers places
to socialize, including restaurants, bars and sports facilities.
</P>
<P>
   National and internationally, other social and service
organizations _ such as the Rotary Club, the Jaycees, the Elks _
include men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with slipping membership, some _ such as the Lion's Club _
have thrown open their doors. And courts have pried open doors at
others, such as the Jaycees and the Elks, which have lost
gender-discrimination suits in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   As for the legal ramifications of the national organization's
ban on women, the Eagles' leadership hasn't discussed it, Grand
Secretary Wahls said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said no other chapters are in hot water with the
leadership over female members. But the Olympia chapter, which has
eight women, recently had its charter suspended. The national
organization cited reasons other than membership.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Tenino and Olympia, five other area chapters have
female members _ two in Seattle and one each in South Whidbey
Island, Spokane Valley and White Center, south of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Olympia suspension, ``We're still open and business
is thriving at the restaurant and bar,'' said manager Nick Hewing.
``It was just ... a way of making us an example because we didn't
listen to orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewing said the Eagles suspended Olympia's charter on grounds
that the chapter was insolvent. ``But we're not insolvent, we don't
owe any money and most interestingly, they never sent us anything
in writing so we could prove it was our women members,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest Women's Law Center suit seeks to revive female
membership, to protect the Tenino's chapter charter. The suit also
asked for unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing is set for July 9 in Thurston County Superior Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
