r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-KAN &LR;      06-30 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME OFFERED AS PRIZE TO RAISE MONEY FOR INVESTIGATION OF SON'S
DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, Mo. _ Ducks parade by a still pond. A pair of mutts
playfully bound toward the water to stir up catfish. The view from
the back porch is the picture of tranquility.
</P>
<P>
   Not for Darrell and Arlyne Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just too hard to stay here,'' she said. ``Too many
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Mitch Krupp, helped build their country home eight
years ago. When Krupp visited, he would start fishing long before
his parents, or the sun, would rise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Krupp died in a mysterious house fire in Winslow, Ark.
The Barneses buried his ashes under an oak tree on a hill
overlooking the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Now they hope their home will give them answers to Krupp's
death. They are giving away their house, 140 miles southeast of
Kansas City, in a contest. They want to raise money for legal bills
and an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   For $100, entrants can submit an essay about why they deserve
the house. The Barneses need 1,850 entries. So far, they have
received about 500, including several from Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is an unusual idea, born from desperation.
</P>
<P>
   On July 26, 1997, Arlyne Barnes received a call about 4 a.m.
Krupp's wife, Pam, said their house had burned. Pam said Krupp, 29,
could not be found.
</P>
<P>
   The Barneses raced to Arkansas. When they reached the house,
they saw nothing but ashes. The couple's van was a black shell.
</P>
<P>
   Before the fire, Pam had checked herself into a hospital
psychiatric ward. Pam told authorities that Krupp had been suicidal
and violent toward her. Authorities say Pam told them after the
fire that Krupp had warned of burning the house down.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell and Arlyne Barnes didn't believe her.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Arkansas have few answers. Krupp's death
certificate lists the cause as ``undetermined,'' not a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case is still open,'' said Capt. Chuck Rexford of the
Washington County Sheriff's Department. ``I don't want to say any
more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   That answer doesn't satisfy the Barneses.
</P>
<P>
   They don't know exactly what happened, but they are confident
their son didn't kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   Their suspicions center on his widow, now Pam Worrell. They say
she showed no remorse and note that she remarried just weeks after
Krupp's death.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell has sued Arlyne Barnes, alleging defamation of
character. In her counterclaim, Arlyne filed a wrongful-death
lawsuit against Worrell.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are also fighting in court over Krupp's insurance
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Rexford told an Arkansas newspaper that he has not found enough
evidence to implicate any suspects. A county judge, in awarding the
insurance money to Worrell, said there wasn't enough evidence to
show she was responsible for Krupp's death.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell declined to be interviewed, but issued a statement that
expressed sympathy for Arlyne Barnes but added that ``her belief as
to the manner and cause of death is unsupported by evidence
collected by the law enforcement agencies and determinations by the
state Medical Examiner's office.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Barneses, who both receive disability payments, their
legal bills now exceed $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   With their debts growing, they found inspiration in a movie,
``The Spitfire Grill.'' In the film, the owners of a small-town
cafe raise money by holding a contest to win the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The Barnes family decided to do the same. The Missouri attorney
general's office says the contest is legal, provided there is no
element of chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Barneses thought a contest would be easier than selling the
house, which they initially tried to do. They took the house off
the market after two months.
</P>
<P>
   They hoped the three-bedroom home, which includes an indoor pool
on a 25-acre tract, would have contestants flocking.
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the best-laid plans don't work out,'' said Darrell
Barnes, Krupp's stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had to extend the deadline from June 15 until Sept.
15. Still, there is no guarantee they will get enough entries. If
they don't reach 1,850, they will return all entry fees.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy. A few years ago, owners of an Olathe coffeehouse
and a Mission cafe failed to attract enough contestants in similar
contests to win their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But the Barneses' contest has created an unlikely side effect.
</P>
<P>
   Entrants are sharing their own tragedies, from terminal
illnesses to unsolved slayings. Others send inspirational messages,
including Bible verses and poetry. Several have entered creative
essays, such as a ``scrapbook'' with the entrants' photos pasted
over pictures of the house.
</P>
<P>
   One of the entrants, James Weese of Kansas City, grew up on a
farm outside Bolivar, Mo. His family lost the property when he was
a child.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Jerry, promised their mother that he would get the
farm back for her. He died in a house fire last year before he
could make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Weese entered the contest to win the house for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty sad. I'd like to help the (Barnes) family out
because it sounds like they need it,'' Weese said. ``I also want to
try to fulfill my brother's dream, since he couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   One girl from Arkansas sent $3 and a sympathetic note.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I don't know you,'' the girl wrote in careful
penmanship, ``I can say that if it were at all possible, I would
take your grief upon myself to relieve you from it.''
</P>
<P>
   A panel of 12 local volunteers will judge the essays on
originality, sincerity, inspiration and desire. Essays can be no
longer than 500 words. The Barneses will have no hand in the
judging.
</P>
<P>
   Still, sorting the entries isn't easy. Arlyne Barnes files them
on her computer and keeps a packed cardboard box of papers in her
study.
</P>
<P>
   She has never doubted that the hard work is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you feel that first kick in your womb, unless you've felt
that, there's no way to explain it. Then you think of all the
memories: the first day of school, his first prom,'' Barnes said as
tears started flowing. ``Then to have your son handed to you in a
box, how can you just let that go?
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe it to him to do all I can.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information or to submit an entry, write to: Win This
Country Home Contest, R.R. 2, Box 644, Buffalo, MO 65622
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
