<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, AREA RESIDENTS WRINGING OUT AFTER FLOODING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE LAMOY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The sunshine, moderate temperature and gentle
breeze Tuesday couldn't erase the destruction left by Monday's
heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   From western Kansas City, Kan., to eastern Kansas City,
residents mopped mud-caked floors and hauled ruined household goods
from damp basements.
</P>
<P>
   And the metropolitan area still wasn't getting an all-clear, as
weather forecasters predicted more rain Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If rain does fall, the conditions are ripe for more flooding,
said Mike Doll, a forecast meteorologist for WeatherData Inc. in
Wichita. ``The ground is pretty saturated,'' Doll said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the weekend should be dry but hot and humid.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, most people in flooded areas were more concerned
about what had already happened. In some areas, rage had supplanted
raging waters.
</P>
<P>
   Among those particularly upset:
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the Argentine area of Kansas City, Kan., who were
cleaning up for the second time in a year. Hard hit were about 30
homes immediately north of Argentine Boulevard between 34th and
42nd streets. The same area was deluged by rains Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``After October, our city officials told us they'd taken care of
everything and it would never happen again,'' said Joe Abarca,
standing among soaked carpets and muddy furniture in the front yard
of his house in the 1100 block of South 38th Street. ``It's like
we're here by ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the area of 40th Street and Oakley Avenue, who were
mopping their basements and repairing cars that had floated down
streets. Water flowing from three directions gathered in the
low-lying area Monday and overwhelmed the sewer system.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents complained that city officials, including City
Council members, had not returned their phone calls. Bettye Pearson
said she contacted several offices at City Hall before she found
someone who could help. The city's sewer maintenance division had
been scheduled to clean a drainage pipe near Pearson's home Monday,
but a city official said Tuesday afternoon that because of the
flood it would be two to three weeks before workers could get to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners along Southwest Boulevard in Kansas City, Kan.
Ruby Morlan, owner of Dagwood's Cafe, was hit for the eighth time
since 1977. She estimated damage at $5,000 from Monday's flooding,
which brought water about a foot deep into her establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Wyandotte County's Unified Government had paid
``lip service'' to help with the cleanup, she said, but in the end,
``We are left to clean up by ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Unified Government spokesman Don Denney said government workers
were doing as much as they could.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bridge collapse, a business collapse; we were
involved in numerous rescues; families have been displaced,''
Denney said. ``Now if we have neglected some people, it is
certainly not intentional. We are doing everything we can. It is
not something that can be resolved overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   For Southwest Boulevard business owners, a long-term solution
has been proposed. A $43 million flood-control project is awaiting
approval from Congress, said Michael Bart, chief of planning and
hydrology for the Kansas City District of the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government would pay 65 percent of the cost, and the
two Kansas Citys would cover the rest. The corps has estimated that
Kansas City would receive about 70 percent of the benefits and
Kansas City, Kan., about 30 percent. Construction would be
concentrated mostly in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, Unified Government Mayor Carol Marinovich declared
a state of emergency, allowing government crews to pump basements
and inspectors to work with homeowners to restore electricity. The
declaration doesn't guarantee state or federal emergency funds,
Marinovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your heart can't do anything but go out to them,'' she said,
referring to flood victims. ``Water can be pretty vicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Marinovich said that officials were focusing on helping
residents clean up and had not begun talking about a solution to
the flooding along Argentine Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was one single cause,'' Marinovich said.
``When you have that much rain in a short time, you have
flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, officials said they had no plans to put a new
tax for flood-control projects on the ballot. In April, voters
defeated a proposal for an 18-month sales tax to raise $45 million
for flood control.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Kay Barnes said a proposed sales tax extension that
residents will vote on in November would generate about $29 million
for various flood control projects. The city is also poised to
begin a major catch-basin repair and replacement program, thanks to
a storm-water management fee that voters approved last November.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Pogge, deputy director of the Water Services Department,
said the department's goal was to clean 14,000 catch basins this
year and get on a cycle of cleaning all catch basins _ about 33,000
_ every two years.
</P>
<P>
   Catch basins are the grates in the street or slots in the curb
through which storm water flows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
