<SLUG> BC-KC-SCHOOLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC SCHOOL BOARD MOVES TOWARD CONSENSUS ON DESIGNATED LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANIKA WHITE AND PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Three Kansas City school board members said
Tuesday they would work cooperatively with superintendent-designate
Jay Edwards even though they were dissatisfied with the selection
process. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe under the leadership of Maj. Gen. Edwards this
district will experience quality-based management,'' board member
Helen Ragsdale said at a news conference at the Board of Education
building, 1211 McGee St. Ragsdale called Edwards ``an individual
interested in making a difference in the lives of all children and
a leader committed to excellence.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ragsdale and board members Lee Barnes Jr. and Terry Riley called
the news conference. At an acrimonious meeting Monday night, those
three and board member Patricia Kurtz abstained on a vote to begin
contract negotiations with Edwards, a retired Air Force major
general and now general administrator of the Oklahoma Corporation
Commission. Kurtz said she abstained because she favored another
candidate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five board members voted to proceed with contract negotiations.
The board is scheduled to vote tonight on a proposed contract. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three board members said they called the news conference
because once news got out that Edwards was the board's choice for
superintendent, they were bombarded with questions from their
constituents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parents and community members, they said, were upset that a
potential superintendent had been named without community input.
Many also expressed concerns about Edwards' qualifications. Some
were worried that because he does not have a traditional education
background. Others wondered if Edwards had a commitment to seeing
African-Americans succeed. Nearly 80 percent of the school
district's population is African-American. &QL; 
Explaining abstentions &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the news conference began, Ragsdale said she, Riley and
Barnes did not want their comments construed as ``a racial
issue.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ragsdale said the three wanted to hire a superintendent who
would ``place a high value on the diversity of the students in this
community.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ragsdale said she abstained Monday night because she wanted
Edwards to answer a few more questions before she voted to move the
process along. She declined to elaborate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said that although Edwards was not his top choice among
the four finalists, he would work with Edwards if a contract were
approved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The three of us are professional people,'' Barnes said. ``We
can work with whomever we end up with.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Riley, when asked if he would vote to offer a contract to
Edwards, Riley said, ``It's a possibility.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be in the best interest of all of us on the board to
work collectively and collaboratively with whomever is selected,''
he said after the news conference. He declined to comment about why
he abstained. &QL; 
Diversity proponent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People close to Edwards in Oklahoma City said the Kansas City
school community shouldn't worry about the superintendent-to-be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, their concerns are unfounded, and it's too bad
they don't know this man like I do. Jay is an individual who gets
things done, and extraneous issues don't cloud his vision,'' said
Bill Burnett, who worked under Edwards when Edwards was commander
of Tinker Air Force Base in Oklahoma. Burnett now oversees the
consumer services division of the Oklahoma Corporation Commission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said that when Edwards commanded Tinker, equal opportunity
was a high priority.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have a biased bone in his body,'' Burnett said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Burnett was hired as an engineer at the commission 18 years
ago, he was the only black person in management. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Edwards' first actions was to appoint Burnett and another
black man serving as interim division heads to permanent positions.
Those two became the first black full-time directors at the
commission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The commission had a reputation for not hiring black people,
Burnett said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Jay has been herethat problem has gone away,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burnett said the commission's most influential and complex
division is led by two black persons. The director and the deputy
director of the public utilities division are black. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burnett said that when he was retiring from the service, he
recommended four possible replacements _ three white candidates and
a black candidate. Edwards chose the black person. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the folks in Kansas City are justifiably concerned
about someone white assuming that position,'' Burnett said of the
superintendent's job. ``I would (submit) that this is a
superintendent you will be trying to keep after three or four
years. I feel real honored to work for him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edwards will be in Kansas City today to meet with the
Desegregation Monitoring Committee. He will tour schools and meet
with select community groups on Thursday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members will hold a forum for the community to meet
Edwards at 7 p.m. Thursday at Central High School, 3221 Indiana
Ave. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
