A4154 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENS-KAN &LR;      06-30 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES URGED TO INFORM, PROTECT TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The National Youth Information Network wants
area businesses to protect teen-agers from harassment and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The network announced the Fair Treatment for Teens initiative at
a news conference Tuesday at the Greater Kansas City Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 youngsters trained in the program will begin today to
ask businesses in the urban core to participate. The first goal is
to get 200 pledges by July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, businesses will be asked to make a pledge to
inform youngsters about their rights as employees and their
obligations when buying on credit. The businesses also will be
asked not to take advantage of youths because of their age or
inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   Participating businesses will receive a seal with a drawing of
three persons and the phrase, ``This merchant supports fair
treatment for teens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, you will see this as a signed trust between
businesses and young people,'' said Pat Schudy, president of the
National Youth Information Network.
</P>
<P>
   This is thought to be the first time a metropolitan community
has united to protect the consumer and employee rights of
teen-agers, Schudy said. Among those endorsing the program are the
mayors of both Kansas Citys, the Council of Mayors of Wyandotte and
Johnson Counties, the Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce, and
the Kansas City Kansas Area Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   An expansion of the program to suburban businesses is planned
for this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that by doing this, youth and businesses will have
better communications,'' said David Wu, 17, who has helped train
other teens.
</P>
<P>
   The Fair Treatment for Teens initiative was developed because
the National Youth Information Network is building a database for
its Youth Information Line of Kansas City and wanted a standard for
its referrals.
</P>
<P>
   Call (816) 561-6050 for more information about the National
Youth Information Network and the Fair Treatment for Teens
initiative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
