<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4156 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-30 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS CAN'T KEEP UP WITH RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Monday will go down as the most discouraging night of
the Angels' season. One of the top 10, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The first-place Texas Rangers came to Edison Field looking
strangely vulnerable to the last-place Angels. The Rangers were on
a six-losses-in-nine-games slide and trying to digest the
undignified image of their 55-year-old pitching coach breaking a
hip rollerblading in the stadium parking lot. The Angels were on a
four-game winning streak more or less coinciding with the return of
shortstop and clubhouse conscience Gary DiSarcina and the overdue
announcement of manager Terry Collins' contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   This would be the start of the Angels' scramble back into the
American League West race after two months of weak hitting,
injuries and... more injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody, somewhere, dared to mention the possibility of a
three-game sweep, which would have put the Angels 3{ games out of
first, a stone's throw even if Todd Hundley were the thrower.
</P>
<P>
   And then reality hit Anaheim like a 500-foot home run as Chuck
Finley got brave and challenged the Texas hitters with fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   Nine to 1, Rangers out-machoed 'em again. Now they've outscored
the Angels here 34-4 dating back to the decisive three-game series
last September. Any wonder only 20,000 Angels fans show up for
these things?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of momentum, a lot of confidence going for us. We
thought we had a chance to make up some ground,'' Finley said after
losing to Mike Morgan, the craftier veteran, on Monday. ``Tonight
we got pushed back to the end of the line.''
</P>
<P>
   The next afternoon the Angels dressed for game 2 of the most
pivotal series of the midseason muttering about how Monday's was
just one game in 162.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have some like that,'' Collins said with a
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   But this was more than that.
</P>
<P>
   This was a loud reminder that there's a class standout in the
Angels' division _ and it's not the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' immediate task is to get out of dead last. Their
next job is to send a faith healer after right fielder Tim Salmon
(sprained left wrist, out since May 4) and center fielder Jim
Edmonds (right shoulder surgery, out since opening night); ``no
timetable'' for the return of either, according to Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Their next order of business should be to move the Rangers out
of the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Ballplayers are big on self-reliance, and in that spirit the
Angels will tell you that if they take care of their own game the
division title will take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   If they really think so, their eyes must be spinning too fast
after Monday's mugging to look hard at the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I see the Rangers, I wonder why this team isn't
(begin ital)more(end ital) than 10 games over .500, where they
stood before Tuesday night's game, and why they can't get past
round one of the playoffs, which the club with the most .500-plus
seasons (seven) in the AL this decade failed to do in '96 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of their batting order _ Ivan Rodriguez, Rusty Greer,
Juan Gonzalez and Rafael Palmeiro _ shames any opponent.
</P>
<P>
   If their nine hitters Monday and Tuesday duplicated their best
major-league seasons, they'd have a lineup averaging .307, 24
homers, 94 runs and 97 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez hit his first-inning homer off Finley with a swing as
casual as one of Fred Couples' warmups.
</P>
<P>
   It's frightening to think what these guys could do with a
complete team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we haven't been as consistent as we'd probably
like to be,'' said Todd Zeile, the Rangers third baseman who hit 31
homers for the Dodgers in 1997 before being bundled in the Mike
Piazza trade.
</P>
<P>
   The past 17 games have included two three-game winning streaks
and losing streaks of four, four and two games.
</P>
<P>
   More unfortunately, the Rangers are weighted down by their
infield defense and their starting rotation, in both cases the
league's worst.
</P>
<P>
   (The team was 43-33 after Monday; the bullpen was 17-3; you do
the subtraction.)
</P>
<P>
   Vulnerable? Yeah, the Angels might have thought so, catching
them as they have in the midst of a grinding month that finds the
Rangers playing 26 of 32 games on the road before the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Monday, Gonzalez's easy 2-iron, nine Rangers runs
against the Angels' putative ace, and the sight of fans fleeing
into the Orange County darkness after the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates had an encouraging word for those
Anaheim fans who might get the idea Texas is unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them to contact the Yankees fans _ 'cause we can't beat
(begin ital)them(end ital),'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   But meanwhile, here in the West, Angels fans might be right. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4159 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-30 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NOT long after daybreak on another hot summer morning, Hakeem
Olajuwon touched the news that touches him and was burned.
</P>
<P>
   He opened the newspaper. He read the headline. And quite
suddenly, the breakfast of an ex-champion was a little harder to
swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised, of course,'' Olajuwon said. ``This is
something that I was definitely not expecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Not after all of the games and all of the years and all of the
mountains he had climbed with the Rockets. To discover they had
been entertaining trade offers for him from Toronto for nearly two
weeks. To find out from the impersonal black ink on a page of
newsprint rather than a face-to-face meeting or a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common courtesy,'' he said. ``I think they owed me not to find
out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Rockets really didn't understand that after 15 years
with the same franchise and 18 years in the same city, it is about
more than just basketball and business. Maybe they really don't _
or can't _ comprehend that one of these well-paid hired guns can
make a connection to a community, and to its people, that does run
in both directions.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all that really matters in the end is not that Olajuwon
had to pick up the phone to call coach Rudy Tomjanovich to find out
what was going on, but that Rudy T did the right thing, the
absolutely right thing, and was the one who pulled the plug on a
potential trade because it pulled too hard on his own emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it. While the decisions on how to run the
basketball operations of the Rockets are always done by committee,
this was a deal that had the support in a simple majority to go
through. But it was Rudy T, living up to the words he preaches
about heart and family, who could not, would not, let it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the man that Rudy is, what is inside of him, the
principles that he stood up for in the end,'' Olajuwon said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hakeem is still not sure if the Rockets understand his own
feelings about the totality of his career, his own sense of dignity
and propriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be a history, a tradition, a natural
conclusion,'' Olajuwon said. ``It all happened here. I can't
picture myself playing anywhere else. If anything, a trade would
have speeded up my plans for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the people making those decisions were
thinking. When I look at my career, it is not just the Rockets or
the University of Houston or the city of Houston. It is all
together as part of one picture. It merges together. There is a
rhythm, a right way it should go to the end of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always thought that my career would end like so many of
the great players of the past in the NBA _ Larry Bird, Magic
Johnson, Michael Jordan. One team. One city. One identity. That
means a great deal to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It all reminds one of the line from Pete Gent's watershed sports
novel North Dallas Forty when Phil Elliott, the wide receiver, is
talking to his head coach: ``Every time I call it a game, you call
it a business. And every time I call it a business, you call it a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon hears the talk about the Rockets needing to get
something for him before he retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is looking at things on a small level,'' he said. ``It is
from that attitude that I feel betrayal. You want to get something
for me? Haven't I been giving for years?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to hear what Rudy told me (Tuesday), that he
wasn't going to talk to Toronto any longer. But I don't want to
hold them to some kind of an obligation. I want to be here if it is
good for the team, good for the city. I don't want them just doing
me a favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon is particularly surprised that the talk with Toronto
would grow in light of a lunch he had with Rockets owner Leslie
Alexander roughly two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about things in general, and Les said that
everything was fine,'' he said. ``He asked me my impressions of the
team, and I told him that I did not think we needed drastic
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Les told me that day was about the rumors concerning
Scottie (Pippen). He assured me that the deal being reported of
Scottie going to the Lakers was not true, and I told him I was
happy to hear that. I believe Scottie will be more comfortable next
season. With him and Charles (Barkley) and myself back, I'm looking
forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon has a new 2-week-old daughter, Aisha, whose name means
``to have a good life,'' and her father says he's doing just that
again, feeling strong and healthy for the first time in more than
two years and looking forward to regaining his rhythm and offensive
touch.
</P>
<P>
   He is not bothered by pain. He is not bothered by the shadow
cast by the 1999 champion San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had them beat bad over there, and we let them come back,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon is bothered by the constant whispers from within the
organization that he has lost his competitive edge, the drive that
delivered two titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you question my drive, you are questioning my character,
and I don't know what I've done in my career to have that happen,''
he said. ``You are questioning my pride. When you step on the
court, everything is gone, and all that matters is winning. I feel
that way in a pickup game. If somebody wants to say I don't have a
competitive drive, they should tell it to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been honest with the team, with the way I play.
What I know now is that last week I was in a meeting with Les and
the mayor, discussing possibilities for a new stadium, helping the
Rockets. And at that same time, the Rockets were talking with
Toronto about trading me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that is the business. But I always look forward to the
games, and I have always wanted them all to be in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   After so many years, a guy can still dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0014 </DOCNO>
