r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     06-30 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELSON'S GAMBLE APPEARS TO BE A WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He told us this draft was going to be a dry hole, and who are we
to doubt Don Nelson?
</P>
<P>
   Don't answer that.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' mad scientist stood at a microphone 12 months ago
and shrugged away his draft-night decision to trade away the team's
No. 1 1999 pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad draft next year,'' Dr. Nelsonstein predicted with breezy
certainty.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there wasn't an amateur basketball player on the
Planet Earth who Nellie thought could help his woeful Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   We laughed. Nelson drove off into the summer sunset, headed to
some beach or U2 concert. And we sat back and waited for the
Phoenix Suns to make the No. 1 lottery pick _ the Mavericks'
longtime dream one _ in the 1999 NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Except it didn't happen, did it? The Suns will draft ninth in
tonight's first round, which is exactly the limbo perch where the
Mavericks always seemed to end up.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Tim Duncans on the draft lists. The player who
might well end up getting picked first, Lamar Odom, keeps dodging
doctors and job interviews. And at least five teams like tonight's
first-round pickings so much, they want out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be eight, maybe nine decent players,'' Nelson
said on draft eve. ``But it's a crapshoot.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right _ 12 months ago. The draft stinks.
</P>
<P>
   Odom went to three high schools in four years, trying to stay
one step ahead of the registrar's office. He also performed the
seemingly impossible by getting booted out of Nevada-Las Vegas.
Then, he tried to renounce his decision to declare for the NBA
draft and return to the University of Rhode Island, where he
apparently seldom attended classes or took tests in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, good luck in Vancouver,'' university officials wisely
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Bulls general manager Jerry Krause has said that Odom
won't return his phone calls. The Charlotte Hornets had an
interview scheduled with Odom, and he neglected to show.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nellie said _ a crapshoot.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, he would be right there, rolling the dice. But due to
previous dalliances, Dr. Nelsonstein is out of playing chips.
Unless, of course, somebody wants to take John ``Hot Rod'' Williams
off his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Quit laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie told us, and he was right. This year's draft is so
diluted by defections, only two seniors _ Utah's Andre Miller and
Miami of Ohio's Wally Szczerbiak _ are expected to be selected in
the first 13 picks of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   One of the defectors, Jonathan Bender, comes to the NBA straight
from his high school prom in the worldly capital of Picayune, Miss.
Another ``project,'' center Aleksandar Radojevic, could get drafted
in tonight's top 10 _ or next week by the Yugoslavian army. Yet
another expected high pick, Duke's Corey Maggette, couldn't even
crack his college team's starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   And these are likely first-round guys that the Mavericks weren't
going to get, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, you've got to give the first round picks a
three-year contract,'' Nelson mused. ``That's why I wouldn't be
surprised if one of these years, some teams are just going to
decline to draft.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those teams is very likely to be Team Nelson. The draft,
in its time-honored forms, seems to bore Dr. Nelsonstein. He would
rather be trading a cow for somebody's bag of beans.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, this could have been the year when Nellie might have
wheeled and dealed his way to the top. The Bulls reportedly
wouldn't mind trading the draft's No. 1 pick. Even Nelson's phone
has been ringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of first-round picks available,'' he said.
``There are a lot of teams trying not to draft in the first
round.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks will select seventh in the second round, 36th
overall, and then again at No. 40.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities were so varied and vague, Nelson declined to
invite any draft prospects in for closer scrutiny. Instead, he
suggests that the team's Nos. 36 and 40 picks may be dispatched to
Europe for feeding and finishing and, maybe one day, the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would probably be the best scenario for us,'' Nelson said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't see himself being intrigued by any of the first-round
offers that have been floating around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever want to say never,'' Nellie said, ``but it just
doesn't look like I'll be doing anything like that at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the pickings would be slim 12 months ago. When we
scoffed, he shrugged and said the Mavericks were going to be so
improved, they wouldn't be a lottery team anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nelsonstein, as it turns out, was half-right. The operation
continues.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
