<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GONZALEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ VOWS HE WON'T GO TO ALL-STAR GAME AS A RESERVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Rangers outfielder Juan Gonzalez, upset at the
fans' voting and a previous snub by New York Yankees manager Joe
Torre, said yesterday he will not go to the All-Star Game this year
if he is selected as a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is not happy that the fans in Cleveland have dominated
the voting for the starters, leaving him a distant fifth among
American League outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. led all AL outfielders in the latest voting
update with 1,752,313 votes, followed by three Cleveland
outfielders: Manny Ramirez (1,095,174), Kenny Lofton (965,148) and
David Justice (753,667). Gonzalez was a distant fifth with 493,038
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's incredible,'' Gonzalez said. ``It's a popularity game.
You don't see real justice in the All-Star voting. But fans in
Cleveland, they vote for their players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all right. Three days off will be good. My concern is
for my team and the game and my numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, last year's American League most valuable player,
should have a good chance of being chosen as a reserve by Torre.
The Yankees manager, who will be the AL All-Star manager, is
responsible for selecting the pitching staff and reserves, and
Gonzalez went into last night's game against the Anaheim Angels
hitting .313 with 22 home runs and 67 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez said he won't go even if Torre does selects him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to go if the fans pick me,'' Gonzalez said. ``But if
the fans don't pick me, I'm not going to go. I'm in the same
situation as 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez wasn't voted in as a starter in 1997, even though he
had won the MVP award the year before. He also wasn't happy that
Torre picked Yankees outfielders Bernie Williams and Paul O'Neill
as reserves that year instead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had better numbers than both of them,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers Spanish broadcaster Luis Mayoral, a close friend of
Gonzalez's, said, ``Juan doesn't speak Shakespeare. But he is very
bright, and inside he has a lot of deep, silent pride. He doesn't
forget.''
</P>
<P>
   The AL starting lineup, as voted by the fans, will be announced
Monday. The reserves and pitching staff will be announced next
Wednesday. The All-Star Game is scheduled for July 13 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has been to only two All-Star Games in his career. He
was voted a starter last year when he hit .293 with 26 homers and
101 RBI in the first half. He was selected as a reserve in 1993.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
