<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ANGELS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURKETT COMBINES ON ONE-HITTER FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Forget those flowers, cards and letters or the
customary box of chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   This will make pitching coach Dick Bosman feel better than
anything: pitchers who throw strikes and change speeds effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Bosman preaches that simple formula and John Burkett followed it
last night in the Rangers' 5-0 victory against the Anaheim Angels
at Edison International Field, with Burkett combining on a
one-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez provided the big blow offensively with a three-run
home run in the eighth inning off reliever Mark Petkovsek. It was
Gonzalez's fourth home run in his past five games.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, who seems to love pitching in Southern California, held
the Angels to one hit through seven innings. He walked one and
struck out seven, including Mo Vaughn three times, before giving
way to Jeff Zimmerman in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing. I really can't explain it,'' Burkett said. ``I
was out there tonight seeing things I haven't seen in a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it feels like someone planted a new arm on me. I
have life on my fastball, and a sharp breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosman, who is in a local hospital with a fractured hip and
underwent surgery yesterday after an inline skating accident,
couldn't have asked for anything more. It was the same approach
Mike Morgan took in his complete game seven-hitter in a 9-1 victory
Monday against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett is 4-0 with a 0.58 earned-run average in his career in
Anaheim. He is also 6-3 with a 2.76 ERA at Dodger Stadium, 35 miles
up the road in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the smog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would have mattered who I was pitching
against tonight,'' Burkett said. ``I was hitting my spots,
executing my pitches, doing everything I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, Burkett has won two consecutive games since
returning to the rotation, reviving hope for the Rangers that their
Opening Day starter from last year is a viable starting pitcher
again.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Rangers have also taken advantage of the Angels'
offensive woes. The Angels have scored the fewest runs in the
American League this year, and injuries to outfielders Tim Salmom
and Jim Edmonds have played a large role in that slump.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels, heartened by the return of injured shortstop
Gary DiSarcina, had won six of seven coming into this series and
were starting to believe they could make a serious run at the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Angels pitcher Omar Olivares matched Burkett for three innings
before the Rangers broke through in the fourth. Olivares started
the trouble by walking Gonzalez to start the inning, then gave up
singles to Rafael Palmeiro and Todd Zeile to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Stevens followed with a sacrifice fly to center to score one
run, and Roberto Kelly singled to center to give the Rangers a 2-0
lead. Zeile stopped at second on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Clayton then hit a grounder up the middle, and DiSarcina
made a nice stop racing to his left. But his backhanded throw for
the forceout at second was low and behind Randy Velarde, rolling
away for an error. Zeile thought it rolled far enough away that he
could score, but Velarde recovered quickly and threw him out at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels stayed close until the eighth. But Mark McLemore
singled off reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa, and Rusty Greer drew a
two-out walk against lefty Scott Schoeneweiss. Angels manager Terry
Collins then tried the right-hander Petkovsek against Gonzalez. It
didn't work as Gonzalez hit a 2-1 pitch into the Angels' bullpen.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
