<SLUG> BC-TARZANA-CALIFORNIA-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TARZAN'S HOMETOWN IMMUNE TO JUNGLE FEVER  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Timely for new `Tarzan' movie release) , (This 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Disney animated film `Tarzan' is at the top of the American
box-office charts, but you would hardly know it in the small town
of Tarzana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   As the name strongly suggests, this modest community on the
western edge of the San Fernando Valley in Los Angeles is where the
legendary ape-man sprang from the imagination of his creator, Edgar
Rice Burroughs.
</P>
<P>
   So successful were the original Tarzan novels that they inspired
Burroughs to rename his property Tarzana Ranch and, in due course,
prompted the town to take the same name. But that is where all
local identification with the jungle hero stops.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Johnny Weissmueller look-alike statues, much less
any memorials to Edgar Rice Burroughs himself. And now that the
Disney movie is out, there is no tie-in merchandise in the stores
and not so much as a banner proclaiming Tarzana to be the film's
spiritual home.
</P>
<P>
   Even the local multiplex cinema is spurning the opportunity to
cash in on a splash of local color, advertising the film with no
more fanfare than its sister cinemas in Hollywood, or Westwood, or
Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   There is a simple, if ugly truth behind this curious reluctance
to jump on the great American marketing bandwagon: Tarzana has
never been much fond of old Tarzan, and the feeling is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   This was a town conceived and developed by hard-nosed real
estate speculators, one that remains far more attached to the
niceties of property values and middle-class living than to the
romance of a connection to the literary jungle.
</P>
<P>
   Tarzana _ or Runnymede, as it was originally called _ was part
of the great land scam on which modern Los Angeles is based.
</P>
<P>
   The proprietor of the Los Angeles Times newspaper, General
Harrison Gray Otis, bought it on the cheap when it was still
pristine farmland, in the second decade of the century.
</P>
<P>
   He then sold it at a massive profit after the city fathers had
successfully stolen enough water from central California to develop
it as a residential suburb.
</P>
<P>
   It was General Otis's ranch that Burroughs bought in the early
1920s as he moved west from his native Chicago. He too had a sharp
business sense, making sure his literary creations were not just
copyrighted but trademarked too _ meaning that they would belong to
his estate in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   Whether through jealousy or personal friction, the townsfolk
never paid Burroughs another compliment after renaming their
community in his honor in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   The public library banned his books, with the excuse that Tarzan
and Jane indulged in immoral premarital acts in the jungle. As late
as the 1960s, the local council refused to countenance a Tarzan
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the trademark, Tarzana has been essentially powerless
to exploit the jungle theme without either having to pay large
royalties to the Burroughs estate or else risk being sued.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the town has preferred to do nothing at all except
put up a lame little display in the local post office that greets
queuing customers at knee-level and passes most of them by
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   While Burroughs' grandson, Danton Burroughs, still lives in town
selling the rights to Tarzan products around the world, he has
never made a dime from his own community.
</P>
<P>
   Tarzana has grown into the most generic of suburban communities,
a drab patchwork of cheap box-style architecture and chain-store
outlets _ about as far from Lord Greystoke's jungle as is
imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   There are people who want to change all that. The Tarzana
Chamber of Commerce has now expressed interest in plugging the
connection more effectively, if only to pull in some tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrival of the Disney film has added further
complications, since the Tarzan name has been taken over _ for the
duration of the animated feature's theatrical life, at least _ by a
mouse with remarkably large ears.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone rash enough to sport a Tarzan bumper sticker risks being
sued at least once. The local gift stores do not enjoy a commercial
relationship with Disney so they are completely out of the loop.
Only McDonald's sports Tarzan posters, and that is because of a
marketing deal made at national, not local, level.
</P>
<P>
   The only business brave enough to make the connection is
Greystoke Furniture on Ventura Blvd. ``You have to embrace the
kitschiness,'' enthuses the manager, Lorenda Starfelt. ``I'd like
to have vines hanging above the entrance way and Tarzan yells
echoing down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, this being Tarzana, she isn't allowed to. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 750-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
