<SLUG> BC-LIFE'S-A-BEACH-US-700&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OFF LIMITS': THE PRIVATIZATION OF AMERICA'S BEACHES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Fourth of July copy!)   (This 700-word ``separate buy'' article _ IDEAL FOR 4TH OF JULY
WEEKEND COVERAGE _ is from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
CAN STAND IN 700 WORDS. TOTAL OF UNCUT VERSION IS 875.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, CONN. _ America has an awful lot of shoreline,
enough, you would imagine, to give everyone a spot to plonk down
their deck chair and crack open the Igloo cooler on hot summers
days like these.
</P>
<P>
   You would be wrong. Nearly every oceanside state _ Oregon is the
loan exception _ allows private homes, associations and indeed
whole towns to section off beaches and headlands for the exclusive
use of residents and locals.
</P>
<P>
   One place more than any other has grown infamous for this
less-than-democratic practice and it happens to be the one in which
we live.
</P>
<P>
   It is Greenwich, Conn., a place that has perfected the art of
repelling the unwashed masses. (New York City is awfully near.)
</P>
<P>
   I remember the first week we arrived, setting out for a run in
the direction of the ocean in search of a seaside route. I never
got near the water. Every roadway was blocked by security posts and
barriers declaring ``Private, Residents Only.''
</P>
<P>
   I was angered then, but nowadays my feelings about such
obstacles are more mixed. The reason is simple and inexcusable: it
is called Greenwich Point, a beautiful finger of land that curls
out into Long Island Sound that only Greenwich inhabitants are
allowed to enter.
</P>
<P>
   It is a 147-acre park with tranquil walks, a stunning view of
Manhattan 35 miles away and, best of all, a fine stretch of gently
sloping beach.
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course we want it all for ourselves. And so, every
spring, we follow the town's instructions and apply for our little
beige beach passes.
</P>
<P>
   For $16 a season ($5 for children), the pass gives us access not
just to Greenwich Point but also on to the ferry that scoots out
twice an hour in high summer to the small island that belongs to
the town way out in the Sound.
</P>
<P>
   It too has a beach, an even better view of the city, soothing
breezes and, best of all, a grand little bar with draft beer and a
well-stocked jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   These passes, you will begin to understand, are somewhat
precious. True, we are allowed to take guests, as colleagues from
several rival British titles discovered to their pleasure (I hope)
when we barbecued lunch and sipped Buds on the island recently.
</P>
<P>
   But if your address is not in Greenwich and you have no friends
here to accompany you, you can forget about trying to share in such
sandy delights.
</P>
<P>
   It nonetheless came as a shock recently to read that our
inestimable police department had resorted to entrapping folk who
were attempting _ God forgive them _ to buy passes on the black
market.
</P>
<P>
   A black market in beach passes? Are you serious? Well, yes.
</P>
<P>
   The sting was set in motion when an enterprising local of the
neighboring town of Stamford named Victor Consoli placed an ad in
the classifieds of our town newspaper, the Greenwich Time.
</P>
<P>
   The ad was a solicitation for beach passes ``for prof'l Stamford
cpl w/child. $100 + expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Consoli was quickly treated with a reply and invited to meet the
would-be vendor at our local McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   How was he to know that some Greenwich busybody had spotted his
ad and alerted the police or that the man who met him with a smile
and a handshake in the restaurant was actually an undercover cop?
</P>
<P>
   He duly handed over the $100 and then he got his surprise.
``That's when I advised him I was, in fact, a police officer,'' our
plainclothes hero later told the Time. ``He was more disappointed
that anything else. Disappointed and shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Consoli was also slapped with a $60 fine. His crime? Violating
some town ordinance that bars anyone who is not a town resident
from acquiring or possessing a beach pass.
</P>
<P>
   Consoli has not been answering his phone. Maybe he should.
Surely there is some Greenwich beach-lover with the heart to invite
him and his wife and child to tag along with them to the Point from
time to time? Perhaps I should be that person. (I do have a guilty
conscious about all this, honest.) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 700. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   While we are talking beaches, tourists on the Outer Banks of
North Carolina have been flocking to watch an engineering feat in
motion. Actually, it is the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse that is in
motion.
</P>
<P>
   Painted with a barbershop black spiral, the 4,800-ton, 208-foot
tower is the largest and most beloved of all of America's aging
lighthouses. Wave erosion has left it precariously close to a
watery demise, however, and earlier this month, the National Park
Service began the delicate task of moving it half a mile inland.
</P>
<P>
   So far, all is well. Elevated onto wheels and a giant rail
track, it is being nudged away from the surf by hydraulic pistons
at the rate of about 70 feet a day. And the moving crew is
confident that by late summer, the lighthouse will be happily
bedded down on its new site.
</P>
<P>
   Big structures have been moved before, after all. Didn't that
large bridge I saw recently from an airplane window down in the
Arizona desert once span a river called the Thames?
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in London,
it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
