<SLUG> BC-CONN-UTLITY-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY EAST SEEN IN DEAL TO ACQUIRE CTG RESOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move signaling further consolidation in a deregulated
utility industry, Energy East Corp. is expected to announce
Wednesday that it will buy CTG Resources, the holding company for
Connecticut Natural Gas Corp., for about $355 million in stock and
cash, people close to the talks said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also assume $220 million in CTG's long-term
debt. Both boards approved the transaction Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Energy East, based in Ithaca, N.Y., is the parent company of New
York State Electric &AMP; Gas. It has been on a buying binge in the
Northeast recently, agreeing to buy CMP Group Inc., Maine's largest
electric utility, for $1.2 billion in cash and assumed debt two
weeks ago. In April, Energy East agreed to buy Connecticut Energy
for $617 million in cash, stock and debt.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of CTG Resources, based in Hartford, will expand
Energy East's operations in Connecticut, particularly in Hartford
and Greenwich, where CTG distributes and sells natural gas to about
142,000 customers in 21 municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal's terms, 45 percent of the common stock of CTG
Resources will be converted into Energy East common stock valued at
$41 a share. The remaining 55 percent of CTG shares will be valued
at $41 a share in cash. CTG shareholders can elect whether they
want stock or cash, which will be divided up depending on how much
demand there is for each. CTG Resources will become a subsidiary of
Energy East.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction price represents a 15 percent premium to CTG
Resources' closing price Tuesday of $35.625, up $1.625, a new
52-week high. . Shares of Energy East fell 12.5 cents, to $26.125.
</P>
<P>
   Energy East was advised by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and the
law firm Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &AMP; Katz. Legal counsel for CTG
Resources was Jones, Day, Reavis &AMP; Pogue.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition meshes with Energy East's strategy to become the
leading energy provider in the Northeast. Wes Von Schack, Energy
East's chief executive, has said that he is seeking more
acquisitions. And in a research report dated June 17, Steven
Fleishman, an analyst at Merrill Lynch, agreed that earlier
acquisitions of Northeast-based companies _ like CMP Group _ were
strategically sound, although, he wrote, some appeared a bit
expensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
