<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURKETT SHUTS DOWN ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ For a team that isn't supposed to have much pitching,
the Texas Rangers have come to town and pitched like Cy Young
himself the past two nights.
</P>
<P>
   One night after Mike Morgan's complete-game victory, John
Burkett _ who entered the game with one victory and a 7.20 ERA this
season _ threw seven shutout innings while allowing only one hit in
the Rangers' 5-0 victory before 22,274 at Edison Field on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is the (begin ital)Angels(end ital) the Rangers
were pitching against.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels went into Tuesday's game with the worst offense in
the American League, ranking last in runs, doubles, triples, RBI,
walks, stolen bases, slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   It was Burkett's longest outing of the season, but that's not
saying much. Burkett (2-3) missed time with a shoulder injury and
spent some time in the bullpen. But following a two-out walk in the
third inning, Burkett retired the last 13 hitters he faced before
giving way to Jeff Zimmerman to start the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman pitched a perfect eighth and John Wetteland followed
with a perfect ninth as the Angels finished with a season-low one
hit, the final 19 batters of the game having been retired.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers pitchers were perfect for eight of the nine innings,
the only Angels baserunners coming in the third inning on a double
by Matt Walbeck and a walk by Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' season-low for hits in a game before Tuesday was
three _ May 15 vs. Tampa Bay and June 19 at New York.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, after striking out for the third time in the seventh,
was booed as he walked back to the dugout. Erstad also struck out
three times, his hitting streak ending at eight.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, the Angels were in it until Juan Gonzalez
smashed a two-out, three-run homer off Mark Petkovsek in the eighth
inning, turning a 2-0 deficit into a seemingly
impossible-to-overcome 5-0 setback.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring four runs in the first inning against the A's on
Sunday, the Angels have scored one run in their last 25 innings.
Going back to last season, the Rangers have now won five in a row
at Edison Field, outscoring the Angels by a combined 39-4.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Omar Olivares (6-6) sailed through the first
three innings, allowing two singles and a walk. But a walk to
Gonzalez leading off the fourth spelled trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro and Todd Zeile followed with singles, loading
the bases for Lee Stevens. Stevens hit a sacrifice fly to center
for the first run of the game and Roberto Kelly's bloop single to
right drove in another for a 2-0 Rangers lead.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares gave up two more hits in the fifth, but escaped. In the
sixth, a diving catch by Erstad in left field saved Olivares
because the next batter _ Royce Clayton _ hit a ground-rule double
to center. Angels manager Terry Collins had seen enough at that
point, lifting Olivares for Shigetoshi Hasegawa.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares, pitching on three days' rest, gave up two runs and
eight hits in 51/3 innings while making 89 pitches. It was the
fifth time in 15 starts he failed to go at least six innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
