<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4206 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDINALS-     06-30 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
If bench players were defined by roles such as the ones used in the
bullpen, Glen Barker would be the Astros' closer. He might not get
into as many games as his teammates, but when he appears, it's
usually because the game is on the line.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barker's legs and Craig Biggio's bat proved to be a winning
combination in the Astros' 5-4 victory over the St. Louis Cardinals
on Tuesday night at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio's two-out single off Manny Aybar in the eighth inning
scored Barker to break a tie, and Billy Wagner pitched a perfect
ninth inning to preserve the win. The Astros' season-high losing
streak ended at four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of cued it off the end (of the bat) and was fortunate
to find a hole,'' said Biggio, who was 2-for-5 with two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Barker, easily the fastest player on the team, entered the game
as a pinch runner for catcher Tony Eusebio, stole second base and
scored on Biggio's line drive up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even see where the ball was,'' Barker said. ``I
didn't know if the shortstop was going to get to it or not. If it
got into the outfield, I knew I was going to score. It's a lot of
pressure, but that's my role. I knew that coming into the season.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to imagine Barker performing his role any
better. Tuesday's steal was his eighth as a pinch runner and his
10th of the season despite appearing in just 29 games. It also
marked the sixth time he has scored in 14 pinch-running
appearances. Five of those runs have either tied or won a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can fly,'' Eusebio said. ``We had to make that move (to get
Barker into the game). After losing four games in a row _ and
looking at the scoreboard and seeing the Reds come back in the
ninth _ we knew we needed this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds pitched well enough to get the win, and he would
have if not for a trouble spot in the eighth inning. Scott Elarton
allowed a pair of RBI singles in relief of Reynolds but became the
winning pitcher after Biggio's first RBI in six days.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK with me,'' said Reynolds, who allowed four runs on
six hits in seven-plus innings. ``We really need a win. It didn't
matter who got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Reds rallied for three runs in the bottom of the
ninth to beat Arizona on Tuesday, the Astros were not able to
reclaim sole possession of first place. Cincinnati leads by
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to start looking at the scoreboard,'' Astros
shortstop Ricky Gutierrez said. ``We just need to play the way
we're capable of playing. We needed that off day (Monday). We
looked like a whole new team.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Cardinals' two errors opened the door for the Astros'
decisive run. After retiring Richard Hidalgo to start the bottom of
the eighth, Aybar coaxed a chopper to third base from Eusebio.
Third baseman Placido Polanco, who had replaced Fernando Tatis to
begin the inning, tried to barehand the ball and couldn't come up
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Within a matter of minutes, Barker had swiped second base and
was waiting to be driven home.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Astros had only seven hits, they showed slight
signs of coming out of their recent funk. It didn't hurt that they
led off three innings with extra-base hits, scoring a run each
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some frustrating days,'' interim manager Matt
Galante said. ``This one wasn't explosive, but maybe it was enough
to get us started on our way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who notched his 18th save, was welcomed back to a
situation he hadn't seen in 10 days. That's how long it had been
since his last save situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fear was pressing, because it had been awhile since
I was last in that situation,'' he said. ``We needed to get this
win. Maybe it will give us a boost.''
</P>
<P>
   A weekday crowd of 34,797 showed up for the first of Mark
McGwire's final three games at the Astrodome, but the only home
runs they witnessed from McGwire came during batting practice. He
was 1-for-4 with an RBI single in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros fell behind for the fifth consecutive game when Tatis
cranked a solo home run into the left-center pavilion in the second
inning. The Astros tied the score in the bottom of the inning when
Hidalgo led off with a double and scored on a groundout by
Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Grounders by Hidalgo and Bill Spiers also led to runs in the
third inning after Jeff Bagwell and Carl Everett led off with hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals pulled within 3-2 in the sixth when Joe McEwing
hit a leadoff double and scored on Edgar Renteria's single to
right. McEwing has hit in 20 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez's team-leading third triple led off the Astros' half
of the sixth, and Biggio's single up the middle reinstated the
Astros' two-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds left the game after giving up back-to-back singles to
open the eighth. Elarton allowed run-scoring singles to McGwire and
Ray Lankford as the Cardinals forced another tie. They were only
the third and fourth (of 16) inherited runners Elarton has allowed
to score this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
