<SLUG> BC-LA-POST-PRODUCTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICTURE ROSY FOR POST-PRODUCTION JOBS IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Post-production entertainment work in Los Angeles
County amounts to nearly $7 billion annually and carries a
decidedly sunny outlook, a survey to be released today shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Entertainment Industry Development Corp.'s report also
showed local post-production companies employ well over 30,000
workers and boldly predicted that figure will expand rapidly as
digital technology takes hold.
</P>
<P>
   The report offers a notable contrast to recent gloomy forecasts
to traditional Hollywood work because of escalating runaway
production to cheaper foreign locations and tightened studio
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market for post-production services will grow
substantially in coming years, fueled by increasing international
demand and new digital platforms such as DVD,'' said the survey.
``The concentration of this industry in Southern California has
created a highly skilled, flexible and adaptable work force
well-suited to help lead the industry into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as a qualified pool of labor exists in the region, the
entertainment industry will remain deeply rooted here.''
</P>
<P>
   Post-production -- performed by hundreds of operations in the
San Fernando Valley, Hollywood and West Los Angeles -- consists of
the work that begins once filming stops, such as editing, visual
effects, sound mixing, titles and music. The report underscores the
massive contribution made by the post-production industry,
accounting for one-fourth of the $30 billion-plus spent annually
worldwide on entertainment production.
</P>
<P>
   Between 75 percent and 85 percent of the estimated $8 billion --
or about $7 billion -- in annual post-production revenues worldwide
remain in Los Angeles, according to EIDC Senior Vice President
Kathleen Milnes.
</P>
<P>
   Pockets of ``post'' business operate in New York, Chicago, San
Francisco, Texas, North Carolina and foreign locations, but Los
Angeles should dominate for the foreseeable future, Milnes added.
``Most of the time, producers have to come back to Los Angeles for
post-production even if they shoot elsewhere,'' she said, citing
the strong need for collaboration and resources in Los Angeles
County.
</P>
<P>
   The EIDC, which supervises permitting for much of the county's
location shooting, authorized the $80,000 report -- paid for with a
combination of city and state funds -- in order to spark interest
among job seekers and educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to demystify the industry, because it's going to
continue to need new employees as people retire and jobs change,''
Milnes said. ``We don't want to end up like Silicon Valley having
to import workers from all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Economist Tom Lieser of the UCLA Forecasting Project agreed that
the expertise and variety of California's post-production
specialists has proved to be a powerful lure for producers and
directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more of a premium being in Los Angeles for the post
work than there is for the location work because the pure costs of
feeding a crew and renting equipment don't loom so large for
decision makers,'' said Lieser, who recently estimated that
statewide entertainment jobs will grow by 10,000 to 200,000 by
2001. ``It's been my feeling we would remain the center of the
industry partly because things are changing so rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Milnes also said industry officials and executives have
expressed optimism about the growth of the post-production
business, which boomed in the past decade as digital technology
took hold in Hollywood. ``Post-production continues to be healthy
and follow a basic upward trend,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Atkin, executive director of the Visual Effects Society,
noted that post-production effects work has picked up by expanding
into areas outside of movies. ``It's not as feature-driven as it
used to be ... we're seeing a lot more in TV and commercials,'' he
added. ``The whole industry is constantly going through a change
and we're in the very little baby steps of where digital technology
is going.''
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that although the major studios perform at
least half of the post-production work themselves, the industry is
highly fragmented with nearly 2,000 individual firms in California.
In Los Angeles County, for example, 91 percent of ``post houses''
have fewer than 20 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Milnes said growth has been taking place both amid the largest
operators, with firms like Burbank-based Four Media and Todd-AO
buying up smaller rivals, and at the entry level. ``There are all
kinds of niche companies popping up that specialize in areas like
audio restoration or smoke and fire,'' she said. ``You also see
midsized companies beefing up divisions as work comes in. There are
changes all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kutchaver, president of Burbank-based Flat Earth
Productions, noted that his company has survived and grown over the
past six years by focusing on growth on the edges of the business
such as providing special effects for ``Hercules'' and ``Xena.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest expansion in the industry has been in TV,'' he
said. ``There are only so many big feature projects and we've been
doing quite well by not grabbing for the big brass ring but six
smaller rings. So we always bought what we could afford and if we
need to work 10 times faster, we hire 10 more people.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
