<HEADLINE>
HOWS TO OPEN SECOND FOOD STORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A partnership of former Hughes Family Markets
executives will take its next step toward reviving the chain's
spirit today with the opening of a second HOWS Markets store.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say HOWS targets the same middle-class customers that
supported the Hughes chain, and the new company's leadership
includes Roger K. Hughes, the former chairman and chief executive
officer of Hughes Family Markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going back to some of our roots,'' said Mark Oerum, a
partner in the new company and a former Hughes vice president.
``We're just back at work and having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The 41,000-square-foot Santa Clarita store is the largest to
date for the HOWS Markets chain, which opened its first store in
Granada Hills in May. Officials say they hope to open another store
in Pasadena this August.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clarita store opens today at 19331 Soledad Canyon Road
at 7a.m.; a ribbon-cutting ceremony is planned for 10a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The new store is in a familiar area for the four former Hughes
executives _ Hughes, Oerum, David Wolff and Steve Strickler _ whose
last initials form the acronym HOWS.
</P>
<P>
   The site is across the street from a former Hughes store that
was converted into a Ralphs last year. The conversion occurred
after both chains were purchased by Portland-based Fred Meyer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have a presence in Santa Clarita,'' said Oerum, who
was vice president of operations for Hughes. ``We think Santa
Clarita has the clientele we're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   And locating near a former Hughes store could draw shoppers who
remember the chain.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clarita resident Virginia Petters said she was a longtime
customer at the former Hughes. She continued to shop there after
Ralphs took over the store, but she said she probably will move
across the street if HOWS can duplicate the Hughes model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always really liked Hughes,'' she said. ``I haven't
gotten used to the changeover (to Ralphs).''
</P>
<P>
   The new store's offerings include home delivery, organic
produce, fresh seafood and a large nutrition section with vitamins
and other natural-foods products.
</P>
<P>
   But HOWS officials say they want customer service to be their
biggest selling point.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff said increasing consolidation in the grocery industry _
including the recently-approved merger between American Stores and
Albertson's _ leaves an opening for smaller operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that it's a good opportunity for the smaller company
to focus on quality and service,'' Wolff said.
</P>
<P>
   And the company has had little trouble finding employees eager
to help it compete.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,500 people applied for about 130 jobs at the two stores,
and many applicants were veterans of other supermarket chains, said
Oerum.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby businesses say they already are feeling the benefits of
the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just from having cars in the parking lot, business has picked
up substantially,'' said James McDonald, store manager for
AutoZone, an automobile parts store located next to the new HOWS.
``The whole complex has picked up again.'' &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
