<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWOON COMES EARLY FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ What did Yogi Berra say about the outfield shadows at
Yankee Stadium _ ``It gets late early out here''?
</P>
<P>
   Yogi should sneak a peek at Edison Field this week, when it has
gotten late so early, it feels like September in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are taking care of their late-season swoon before the
All-Star break this year, rolling over 9-1 Monday and 5-0 Tuesday
night against the Texas Rangers in what looks painfully like last
fall's American League West-deciding series sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure nobody's thinking about last year,'' losing
pitcher Omar Olivares said Tuesday night _ but if they're not,
their collective memory has failed as badly as their hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Dating back to those three losses, the Angels have been
outscored by the Rangers at Edison 39-4 and, pardon our own memory
lapse, it's hard to recall why everybody was so optimistic about
this series.
</P>
<P>
   Yet first-place Texas had come to town looking strangely
vulnerable to last-place Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were on a six-losses-in-nine-games slide and trying
to digest the undignified image of their 55-year-old pitching coach
breaking a hip rollerblading in the stadium parking lot. The Angels
were on a four-game winning streak more or less coinciding with the
return of shortstop and clubhouse conscience Gary DiSarcina and the
overdue announcement of manager Terry Collins' contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   This was to be the start of the Angels' scramble back into the
race after two months of weak hitting, injuries and... more
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody, somewhere, dared to mention the possibility of a
three-game sweep, which would have put the Angels 3{ games out of
first, a stone's throw even if Todd Hundley were the thrower.
</P>
<P>
   And then reality hit Anaheim like a 500-foot home run as Chuck
Finley unwisely tried to out-macho the Texas hitters with fastballs
Monday and Olivares lost his sinker Tuesday and the putative aces
of the Angels staff went down against journeymen Mike Morgan and
John Burkett.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of momentum, a lot of confidence going for us. We
thought we had a chance to make up some ground,'' Finley said.
``(Monday) we got pushed back to the end of the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday they showed they'd absorbed the loud message: There's a
class standout in the Angels' division and it's not the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   They banged out one hit against Burkett and two relievers, who
retired the last 19 Angels hitters. They got this kind of
leadership from Mo Vaughn: strikeout, strikeout, strikeout, on the
heels of Monday's fly ball, strikeout, double-play grounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do is go after 'em again (tonight),'' Collins was
reduced to saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' immediate task is to get out of dead last. Their
next job is to send a faith healer after right fielder Tim Salmon
(sprained left wrist, out since May 4) and center fielder Jim
Edmonds (right shoulder surgery, out since opening night); ``no
timetable'' for the return of either, according to Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Their next order of business should be to campaign for the
Rangers' removal from the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I see the Rangers, which is when they play the
Angels, I wonder why this team isn't better.
</P>
<P>
   Why they aren't (begin ital)more(end ital) than 11 games over
.500, where they stand on the last morning of June. Why they can't
get past round one of the playoffs, which the club with the most
.500-plus seasons (seven) in the AL this decade failed to do in '96
and '98.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of their batting order _ Ivan Rodriguez, Rusty Greer,
Juan Gonzalez and Rafael Palmeiro _ shames any opponent.
</P>
<P>
   If their nine hitters Monday and Tuesday duplicated their best
major-league seasons, they'd have a lineup averaging .307, 24
homers, 94 runs and 97 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez hit his first-inning homer off Finley with a swing as
casual as one of Fred Couples' warmups.It's frightening to think
what these guys could do with a complete team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we haven't been as consistent as we'd probably
like to be,'' said Todd Zeile, the Rangers third baseman who hit 31
homers for the Dodgers in 1997 before being bundled in the Mike
Piazza trade.
</P>
<P>
   The past 17 games have included two three-game winning streaks
and losing streaks of four, four and two games.
</P>
<P>
   More unfortunately, the Rangers are weighted down by their
infield defense and their starting rotation, in both cases the
league's worst.
</P>
<P>
   Vulnerable? Yeah, the Angels might have thought so, catching
them as they have in the midst of a grinding month that finds the
Rangers playing 26 out of 32 games on the road before the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Monday, Gonzalez's easy 2-iron, nine Rangers runs
against Finley, and the sight of fans fleeing into the Orange
County darkness after the fifth inning. Then came Tuesday, and the
wonder that 22,274 came back for more.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates had an encouraging word for those
Anaheim fans who get the idea Texas is unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them to contact the Yankees fans _ 'cause we can't beat
(begin ital)them(end ital),'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Or tell them the unpleasant truth: That here at Edison Field,
where the shadows stretch all the way to autumn, they might be
right. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
