<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S WIN WITH (SURPRISE) PITCHING, DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The Mariners won a game Tuesday night in which
they did not have an extra-base hit, went seven consecutive innings
without a hit and got no hits at all from the first three batters
in their order.
</P>
<P>
   What's that old saying about pitching and defense winning games?
</P>
<P>
   The M's beat the Oakland Athletics 2-1 in 12 innings, getting
nine innings from a starter for the first time all year. They also
got three dominating innings from their bullpen, three double plays
and a clutch hitting-and-baserunning tandem from an unheralded duo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a good ballgame all the way around,'' said manager
Lou Piniella, whose team won for the first time this year without
benefit of an extra-base hit.
</P>
<P>
   John Halama went nine innings, allowing one run on eight hits.
But he was gone by the time Raul Ibanez drove in Charles Gipson on
a one-out single off T.J. Mathews in the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Gipson was running for Edgar Martinez, who singled to start the
inning for the Mariners' first hit since the fourth. He was
sacrificed to second by David Segui, the first sacrifice bunt for
the M's first baseman since 1995. Ibanez followed with a rope to
center that hung in the air a bit. Gipson never hesitated, charging
home for the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone else may not have read that ball that well, but he's a
great baserunner and he showed that tonight,'' Ibanez said. ``I
thought it was (a hit) at first, but it had a lot of backspin, and
it hung up a lot longer than I thought. Fortunately, Charles just
got a great read on it.''
</P>
<P>
   It made a winner of Jose Paniagua, who threw two scoreless
innings, walking none and striking out three, in relief of Halama.
Paniagua, who had been depending on his fastball too much in recent
weeks, changed his grip on his slider, and used the pitch
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Mesa came on to close the 12th for his 17th save in 19
chances, overcoming a two-out, dropped pop fly by shortstop Alex
Rodriguez, who stared blankly into his locker after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's 12th-inning misplay had no bearing on the outcome,
but his first-inning highlight play did.
</P>
<P>
   Halama allowed a leadoff single to Tony Phillips, but was
quickly bailed out by a brilliant double play started by Rodriguez.
Miguel Tejada smashed a grounder up the middle, where Rodriguez
dove for it and _ in one horizontal motion _ shoveled it from his
glove to second baseman David Bell, who stepped on second and fired
to first for the second out. Matt Stairs popped out to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big save,'' Halama said. ``I didn't help myself by
falling behind 3-0, and it was a 3-1 count (to Tejada). I had to
come with a fastball, and I got it on the ground. Alex made the
dive and gets the double play. (Not making that play) could have
turned the whole tables around.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third, the A's loaded the bases with nobody out on a walk
and two infield singles. Phillips came up and hit a comebacker,
which Halama tossed home and Dan Wilson threw to first for a 1-2-3
double play. Tejada ended the inning with a fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and one out in the fifth,
Phillips grounded into an inning-ending double play, started by
Bell at second.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out of danger allowed Halama to last nine innings,
before being lifted in the 10th after 120 pitches. It was his
longest outing as a Mariner, and though he didn't get the win, the
rookie left-hander did lower his ERA to 2.85 in his seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always trying to get ground balls,'' Halama said. ``I
don't want to give up any pop flies. I always want to get ground
balls, especially when they've got runners on base to get the
double play ball. It says a lot for our ballclub that we're capable
of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners ranked second in the American League in double
plays coming into Tuesday's game, and now have 92 this year.
</P>
<P>
   The A's got their only run off Halama in the seventh. Jason
Giambi led off with a single, and Tim Raines negated the
ground-ball double play by sacrificing him to second. Catcher Ramon
Hernandez, making his major league debut, singled home Giambi
before Halama ended the inning by getting two fly outs.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Mariners had scored their only run off A's
right-hander Mike Oquist, who held them to five hits in a
season-high seven innings. The run came in the second, when Wilson
singled in Bell with two outs. The Mariners might have had more,
but Segui was thrown out stealing third during Wilson's at-bat.
Bell did take second on the play, putting him in scoring position
when Wilson rapped his hit up the middle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
