</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE IN 12TH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The Dodgers left the Bay Area _ home to the X Games
_ after winning two of three last weekend against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   While fighting through traffic and what-not, they must've gotten
a peek at the wall climbing competition because they clung on for
dear life through jams in the ninth, 10th and 11th innings Tuesday
night in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Then they lost their grip and fell. In the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Damian Jackson's RBI single with none out in the bottom of the
12th lifted the Padres to a 4-3 win against the Dodgers at Qualcomm
Stadium in the opener of a three-game series. The Padres tied a
club record with their 11th straight win.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres (36-38) have won five straight against the Dodgers
and six of seven against them this season. The Dodgers (34-40)
remain in last place in the NL West, one-half game behind Colorado.
They had five hits off six San Diego pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Davis led off the bottom of the 12th and reached on
defensive replacement Craig Counsell's error at second base. Carlos
Baerga walked and Jackson singled just inside the left-field line
to win it.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers second baseman Eric Young appeared disappointed at being
replaced defensively, though he wouldn't talk about it. But after
watching the Padres get plenty of breaks, he did address how the
Dodgers can do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play to win instead of playing not to lose,'' Young said.
``They played to win. First and second and the pitcher gets a hit
instead of bunting. That was huge.''
</P>
<P>
   That play _ Andy Ashby pulling back from a sacrifice bunt to
single past the vacated shortstop spot _ was prefaced by a bad-hop
grounder that turned a possible double-play ball into a single and
a first-and-second, none-out situation. Ashby's hit tied the score
3-3 after the Dodgers took 2-0 and 3-1 leads thanks to a Todd
Hundley two-run homer in the first inning and a run on a passed
ball in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the only huge play the Padres made. Center
fielder Ruben Rivera, who entered the game as a pinch hitter in the
bottom of the eighth, robbed Eric Karros of a homer in the top of
the ninth and Rivera again chased down a Dave Hansen line drive in
the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would think the pitcher would get a hit there?'' shortstop
Jose Vizcaino said. ``That's why they've won 11 in a row. Things
are going their way. Rivera, he just came in as a pinch hitter and
comes out and saved the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres also didn't wilt despite wasting glorious chances,
beginning with the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Magadan began the inning off Alan Mills with a single to
right. Quilvio Veras tried to sacrifice the runner to second, and
Adrian Beltre couldn't come up with it. Mills did, throwing wildly
to first to allow the runners to move to second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Owens was intentionally walked to load the bases and Reggie
Sanders hit a soft liner to left that Gary Sheffield caught as he
fell. Pinch-runner Woody Williams tried to score but was thrown out
when Beltre cut off the throw and threw to Hundley at the plate for
the double play. Rivera flied out to center to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres again could have scored the winning run off Mills in
the 10th when Baerga doubled with two outs. Jackson and Phil Nevin
walked to load the bases for the second straight inning. But Veras
grounded to second to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego had two runners on in the 11th, but reliever Mike
Maddux got Wally Joyner to ground into a double play to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad-hop bounce on a ground ball that could have been a double
play, things like that,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``When you're winning like that, things fall in your lap.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
