r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     06-30 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURKETT STOPS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ For a team that isn't supposed to have much pitching,
the Texas Rangers came to town and pitched like Cy Young himself
the past two nights.
</P>
<P>
   One night after Mike Morgan's complete-game victory, John
Burkett _ who entered the game with one victory and a 7.20 ERA this
season _ threw seven shutout innings while allowing only one hit in
the Rangers' 5-0 victory Tuesday night before 22,274 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels went into Tuesday's game with the worst offense in
the American League, ranking last in runs, doubles, triples, RBI,
walks, stolen bases, slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   It was Burkett's longest outing of the season, but that's not
saying much. Burkett (2-3) missed time with a shoulder injury and
spent some time in the bullpen. But following a two-out walk in the
third inning, Burkett retired the last 13 hitters he faced before
giving way to Jeff Zimmerman to start the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman pitched a perfect eighth and John Wetteland followed
with a perfect ninth as the Angels finished with a season-low one
hit, the final 19 batters of the game having been retired.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers pitchers were perfect for eight of the nine innings,
the only Angels baserunners coming in the third inning on a double
by Matt Walbeck and a walk by Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have more problems with guys with good
changeups,'' said Angels manager Terry Collins, whose team fell 8{
games behind the AL West-leading Rangers. ``But I don't care who
you face on a nightly basis, you've got to go up with some kind of
a plan and try to carry it out. John Burkett went out with a plan
tonight and carried it out. We didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   After striking out for the third time, Mo Vaughn was booed in
the seventh as he walked back to the dugout. Erstad also struck out
three times, his hitting streak ending at eight.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have played the Rangers well the past two seasons
when the games didn't seem to matter much. But when the series was
played up, the Angels have disappeared. They've been outscored 14-1
in the first two games of the series, looking like a team that
can't handle pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's a series you should get excited about,'' Vaughn
said. ``It's not a pressure-packed situation. It's something you
should enjoy being in. It's why I'm disappointed in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, the Angels were in the game until Juan
Gonzalez smashed a two-out, three-run homer off Mark Petkovsek in
the eighth inning, turning a 2-0 game into a seemingly
impossible-to-overcome 5-0 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had at least one baserunner in every inning and at
least one hit in every inning but the first and ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Omar Olivares (6-6) sailed through the first
three innings, allowing two singles and a walk. But a walk to
Gonzalez leading off the fourth spelled trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro and Todd Zeile followed with singles, loading
the bases for Lee Stevens. Stevens hit a sacrifice fly to center
for the first run of the game, and Roberto Kelly's bloop single to
right drove in another run for a 2-0 Rangers lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make things happen,'' Vaughn said. ``Just two
days ago we were playing solid baseball. I know I've got mechanical
problems right now that I have to work through. Overall, I don't
think we're looking past people. We know we've got to win games and
get ourselves back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since scoring four runs in the first inning against the A's on
Sunday, the Angels have scored one run in their last 25 innings.
Going back to last season, the Rangers have now won five in a row
at Edison Field, outscoring the Angels by a combined 39-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
