<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcome to the club, Columba
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Whenever I meet my chic friend outside
our favorite store, and she's putting a package in the trunk of her
car, I know she's just bought herself another outfit.
</P>
<P>
   I also know the package likely will remain in the trunk until
her thrifty husband is away from home. Only then will she take her
irresistible bargain into the house and tuck it in the back of her
closet.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one day or night, when she's looking especially fetching,
he will remark how wonderful she looks and ask the perpetually
predictable husband-to-wife question: ``Is that new?''
</P>
<P>
   Being truthful, she will reply, ``This has been in my closet a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied that his love is equally thrifty, he will feel so
proud that she can dress elegantly for every occasionwithout being
excessively extravagant like some of her friends. Both will be
happy.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend has a thing for shoes. Perhaps, as a child, she
suffered some trauma during the Second World War that causes her to
hoard shoes like they're going to be rationed again. Whatever the
cause, she buys more than she will ever wear. To shield her husband
from her addiction, she stores shoeboxes under the bed, in the
guest room, in the garage. So far, he seems oblivious.
</P>
<P>
   By now, you're probably thinking that these cases are classic
examples of wasteful wives deceiving clueless husbands, or female
fashion fanatics gone berserk. Not so.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening is more profound than licentious economics or
ruthless deception. What we have here is a tacit agreement between
consenting adults not to communicate about the vagaries of women's
shopping, a concept most men can never fully grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Ever aware of this reality, I find myself in the unprecedented
position of defending a Republican governor's wife against the
slings and arrows of partisan, political criticism. I resent that
such pundits are smirking at the tribulations of Florida first lady
Columba Bush. In her defense, I urge that they get a grip and leave
the poor woman alone.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're one of the few people on the planet who hasn't
heard, let me explain. Columba Bush had the shopping spree to die
for: five days, alone, in Paris. She had hardly arrived back home
in Tallahassee, however, when the press dealt her the most taxing
embarrassment: It announced to the world how much the little woman
had spent shopping.
</P>
<P>
   While passing through customs at the Atlanta airport, Mrs. Bush,
a seasoned shopper and international traveler, did not declare, as
is required, all of her purchases abroad. U.S. Customs allows
travelers to bring $400 worth of merchandise into the country
duty-free.
</P>
<P>
   When her bags were searched, customs agents discovered clothing
and jewelry worth $19,000. The value was easily assessed since
receipts were in her passport. To the lady's credit, she quickly
wrote a check for the $4,100 fine, three times what she would have
been required to pay had she 'fessed up in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation coming out of the Governor's Mansion that I find
most credible is that her primary goal was to keep the amount of
her purchases from her hubby. Had she written a check for the true
amount, the governor might have known just how much of a spree it
was.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb says that he loves his wife and that what happened is
now a private matter between the two of them. For the first time,
the man has dealt with a controversial issue in a way I can relate
to.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mrs. Bush, her punishment is more than cruel. And not
just because of the triple fine or the humiliation of having her
indiscretion heralded around the world.
</P>
<P>
   It's because, for the duration of her husband's political
career, she won't be able to say in response to a compliment: ``I
bought it in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
