<HEADER>
A4428 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-COLUMN01-COX     06-30 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When nice gets us nowhere, we have to get mean
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I'm waiting on a call from my insurance
company. Day after day, week after week, month after month _ six
months in all _ I sit and wait for the right person to light up my
line.
</P>
<P>
   And after I complete these productive work days, I go home and
pick up the mail and listlessly go through letter after letter,
always in search of a long white envelope with an authentic
insurance-settlement check inside.
</P>
<P>
   I'm told my case, No. 98-100085, is a ``sticky one.'' I suspect
this is double-secret insurance company spy code for get lost.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I could quit my job and make our car accident my
full-time gig. Or I could marry Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   See, the real problem here is not that a young woman ran a red
light three days after Christmas and sent us flying across the
horizon. The real problem isn't even that she went to court and got
the ticket thrown out and now it's looking like her company doesn't
want to pay up.
</P>
<P>
   No, the real problem is that I can't get any answers being nice
so now I'm going to have to get mean. Nastiness, rudeness,
obsessive phone calling _ all of it gets results.
</P>
<P>
   Like now. Right here in this little spot, I wanted to tell you
about the number of people, like myself, who are sitting, waiting,
unhappy with the way their insurance claims have been handled. I
called the office of my insurance commissioner three hours ago, and
I still don't have what I need, even though I've been assured by
Patrick and Nina and somebody else that they've got what I need and
will give me what I need and will call me ``right back'' with what
I need. Still, no one's called but some guy who didn't like last
week's column. He was mean.
</P>
<P>
   Some people I know actually like these nasty consumer-rights
confrontations, most notably a certain ex-New Yorker who sits
opposite me at the office. This is a person who can get free Disney
World passes if he is not treated with the right color of kid
gloves at the podiatrist's office. In fact, his phone is ringing
right now, probably Michael Eisner calling to apologize about
something that didn't go quite right on the last Disney trip.
Meanwhile, my phone is silent.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, I thought perhaps the telephones at insurance
companies were equipped for only outgoing calls. I've heard of
weirder things. But then my dad had a little mishap with the Ford
LTD the other day, backed into some woman at the grocery store, and
the insurance company called my parents' apartment that very day.
Twice before dinner, and they eat at 4!
</P>
<P>
   If this lousy insurance claim is the worst thing that happens to
me all year, I'll be awfully lucky, I know. It's the bigger picture
that unnerves me. Shouldn't we be bothered by the fact that
niceness and politeness and sweetness don't get us anywhere any
more?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes people write to me and tell me I'm too liberal.
Sometimes they write to say how brilliant I've become. This week,
though, I'd appreciate phone calls. Like I said, my lines are wide
open.
</P>
<P>
   Plus I want to practice my newfound meanness. On you.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
