<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4431 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HINDENBERG-EYEWITNESS     06-30 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINDENBERG-EYEWITNESS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Hindenberg: What a young girl saw
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Thousands watched the last, slow dance
of the dirigible Hindenburg as it bobbed through the stormy sky
over New York City in the late afternoon of May 6, 1937.
</P>
<P>
   The pride of the Zeppelin Company's air fleet was already more
than 10 hours late completing its first flight of the season from
Germany, but the captain was in no hurry. He'd decided to circle
and wait for a break in the weather to ensure the sort of smooth,
pinpoint descent that had ended each of the Hindenburg's 10
previous flights to America.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of welcomers and sightseers waited southeast of the city
at the ship's destination, the U.S. Navy's air station at
Lakehurst, N.J. Among the eager greeters were the Enssle family of
nearby Roselle Park, including 13-year-old Eleanor.
</P>
<P>
   She was excited about the impending arrival of her uncle, Eugen
Schauble, an engineer in the Hindenburg's control room. He had
already purchased a ticket to bring Eleanor with him on the return
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Just as thrilling for Eleanor was the prospect of seeing the
airship's young cook, Alfred Groezinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was smitten the first time I saw him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She had seen the Hindenburg and its crew many times; her uncle
and several others often stayed at the family's home. The enormous,
rigid airship had become a familiar but still fascinating sight
along the New Jersey coast.
</P>
<P>
   Gleaming silver, with black swastikas towering on its upper and
lower tailfins, the Hindenburg looked like an enormous torpedo.
Filled with explosive hydrogen, it was just as deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Zeppelins, dirigibles _ by whatever name, passenger airships
were counterparts to the most luxurious ocean liners. Germany's
Hindenburg was the biggest, most powerful ever.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800 feet long, it is still one of the largest machines
ever to fly. It would dwarf a Boeing 727 (a mere 153 feet long) and
was not much shorter than the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   And it was hardly light, weighing more than 100 tons. Even so,
it held little more than 100 people, most of them crew. But it was
(ITALIC) fast (END ITALIC): The Hindenburg's four Mercedes-Benz
engines could propel it across the Atlantic at more than 80 miles
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   That made it the Concorde of its day, capable of making the
crossing in 2 1/2 days with a little help from the winds. That beat
the oceanliners below by nearly two days. It beat heavier-than-air
planes by two years; Pan Am didn't start the first regular
tran-Atlantic passenger service until 1939.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindenburg's return flight was already booked, with many of
the 79 ticket holders planning to attend the coronation of
England's King George VI. Their bags were being weighed and sorted
for the expected midnight departure when the Hindenburg sailed into
view.
</P>
<P>
   A light rain swept across the field as the airship's nose
dropped toward the mooring mast. Passengers in the glass-lined
observation deck along the ship's belly waved to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ship could be secured and winched to the ground, it
burst into flames. The Hindenburg was engulfed in half a minute.
This is the scene recalled by young Eleanor Enssle, now Eleanor
Zarr of Palm Harbor, Florida:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy crew hustled about the huge mast as the Hindenburg
approached. I was so excited that I told my mother and father that
I was going to get as close as they would allow me to go with our
special passes. They laughed and said, 'OK.'
</P>
<P>
   They remained at the hangar while I ran, with many others, to a
spot very close to the landing area. When the Hindenburg came into
sight, everyone cheered and waved.
</P>
<P>
   The huge airship was almost standing still when the front lines
were dropped. At that moment, a muffled explosion could be heard.
Fire spread rapidly. Everyone screamed in panic, and people on
board began to jump from the windows.
</P>
<P>
   It was nighmarish. Burning debris began falling toward us. We
had to turn and run toward the hangar. The stench of burning flesh
was everywhere. Some of the passengers were running from the ship
with their clothing and hair on fire.
</P>
<P>
   I was screaming as I ran. I felt I would wake up in a minute and
find that it was all a terrible dream. I tried to find my parents
in this mass confusion, while Navy ambulances and fire trucks tried
to help where they could.
</P>
<P>
   As I looked back at the ship, it was a twisted skeleton melting
from the intense heat of the fire. People were still running from
the wreckage, some having jumped from quite a height at the front
of the ship, which had come down tail first.
</P>
<P>
   I finally found my parents near the hangar. My mother was
hysterical and my dad was crying. As some of the survivors were
ushered into the hangar, we spotted some of the crew members and
asked about my uncle. Several of them said they had seen him jump
from the cat walk around one of the engines as the ship began to
roll in his direction.
</P>
<P>
   One said he had run back into the ship to help. Another said he
saw him running in another direction in a confused state. We
searched frantically and waited for news about survivors, as
ambulances and fire trucks came from surrounding towns.
</P>
<P>
   Someone from the Navy suggested we go to the base hospital,
where the wounded had been taken. We found our car and started to
drive the long road to the hospital. People were running in every
direction. It was dark, and our headlights shone on a figure
wandering through the weeds at the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   My mother screamed: ``Stop the car. That's Eugen up ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, it was my uncle, in a state of shock. As soon as he
saw my mother, he started crying. We put him in the car and took
him to the hospital. That was a sight I will never forget.
Survivors were everywhere. Their conditions ranged from slightly
injured to severely burned. We saw so many of the crew we knew. It
was tragic.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that I learned Freddy Groezinger had survived, but
had burns and was already in another hospital. The doctors examined
my uncle. He had some burns on his face but was discharged in our
care. He was saved from severe burns by his tight, leather helmet
and leather jacket, which were singed black on one side.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to console him because he had lost so many of
his comrades, especially Willie Dimmler. Dimmler had taken his
place in the control room so that my uncle could go out on the
catwalk to look for us.
</P>
<P>
   It was from the catwalk that he jumped to the ground. He tried
to go back to the ship to help, but the heat made him turn away.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Eleanor's uncle recovered from his injuries and lived for
many years. Alfred Groezinger is still alive, in Germany. He and
Eleanor married other mates but remain friends and have visited
several times.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 64 of the 97 passengers and crew members escaped the
Hindenburg. Flights of its sister ship, the Graf Zeppelin, were
halted immediately while investigators from both sides of the ocean
tried to find the catastrophe's cause.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments continue. Some still suspect sabotage; others
blame lightning. Whatever the spark's source, every expert agreed
that hydrogen was the fatal ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even that is being challenged by research that suggests the
fire actually spread through the chemically treated cotton fabric
stretched over the Hindenburg's aluminum frame.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of the Hindenburg's fiery end, advertisements hit
the papers along with the horrifying pictures.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first or greatest dirigible disaster: 73 died when
the U.S. Navy's Akron crashed in a storm in 1933; 46 died when
Britain's R-101 exploded over France in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   But public horror at film of the Hindenburg's near-instant
disintegration _ and the emotional, endlessly replayed account of
radio reporter Herbert Morrison (``Oh, the humanity . . . '') _
insured that it would be the last.
</P>
<P>
   The Zeppelin Company built a replacement for the Hindenburg, but
it never carried a passenger. It was turned into scrap during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   A short video clip of the Hindenburg fire, plus audio of the
radio broadcast, are posted on the World Wide Web:
www.hindenburg.com
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
