<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE     06-30 1492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that President Clinton mobilized
33,000 men and women in April during the height of the NATO-led air
campaign against Yugoslavia. I can't find anything supporting this.
What units were involved?
</P>
<P>
   A: On April 27, Clinton authorized the Pentagon to activate
33,102 members of the National Guard and military reserves. The
Pentagon had made the request that same day in order to enable NATO
to expand its air armada and quicken the pace of its attacks,
according to Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
   The 33,102 was the ``ceiling'' number whose activation was
approved, said Lt. Col. Mike Miloy of the Defense Department, but
the number actually mobilized was ``about 5,000.'' While they had
reported and some were in the ``alert phase'' and preparing for
deployment, the air campaign ended. When that happened, Miloy said,
the need for them to be fully activated disappeared, so the full
33,102 never were deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation recently
granted $10 million to 32 people. How does one apply for such a
grant?
</P>
<P>
   A: Recipients don't apply. They're nominated for the awards by
anonymous talent scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The national anthem used to be sung before every Major League
baseball game. Why don't we see that anymore?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you're referring specifically to televised games, viewers
don't see and hear the anthem because it's usually performed before
the station's telecast begins. But fans at the stadium sould see
and hear it. And at games involving the Montreal Expos or Toronto
Blue Jays, fans would be treated to ``O Canada'' as well as ``The
Star Spangled Banner.'' So if you're concerned about the anthem
being eliminated before every game, it hasn't been. You just don't
often get it on television.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that a Confederate submarine, the Hunley, was
found underneath the football stadium at The Citadel in Charleston,
S.C. How did it come to rest there?
</P>
<P>
   A: The wreckage of the Hunley, a nine-man sub built from an old
locomotive boiler, is under 30 feet of silt and water off the Isle
of Palms near Charleston. What was discovered under a section of
asphalt just inside the Citadel stadium's cinderblock back wall was
the burial place of some of the Hunley's crew members, who died in
an accident. The Hunley had three sets of crew members, and this
was the first. The bodies were believed to have been buried in
Charleston's old Confederate naval cemetery, which was abandoned in
the late 1940s when the city built the stadium that now is home to
the Citadel Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How well is Social Security prepared to deal with possible
Y2K problems?
</P>
<P>
   A: The entire process for providing benefits _ from calculating
benefits to making payments _ is ready for the century date change,
according to the Social Security Administration.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998, the Treasury Department's Financial Management
Service began to issue monthly Social Security payments on systems
that had been fixed and tested, the agency says. Financial
Management Service maintains systems that each year make 860
million payments on behalf of SSA, the Department of Veterans
Affairs, the Internal Revenue Service and other agencies. All the
systems were found to be ``Year 2000 compliant,'' with independent
verification and documentation, according to the SSA.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Adams, assistant deputy commissioner for SSA systems,
expressed the situation in a practical way: ``SSA will make it. We
cannot manually issue 50 million checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is ``The General's Daughter'' a true story or a piece of
fiction?
</P>
<P>
   A: The novel is fiction, but author Nelson DeMille, isn't saying
if the story has any basis in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A Nike commercial shows Tiger Woods using a golf club to
bounce a golf ball several times between his legs, and then he hits
it. Was this a computer-generated stunt?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the real thing, with no trick photography, said Nike
spokesman Mike Kelly. Woods did it ``on the spur of the moment,''
Kelly said, bouncing a ball on a sand wedge and then hitting it
``about 200 yards.'' Kelly said the TV spot was filmed in just four
takes at a golf course in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Walt Disney's old ``Song of the South'' is my husband's
favorite movie. I understand that it's not available for sale on
video in this country, but can be found on international markets.
Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 1946 film _ beloved by some who consider it a classic,
but condemned by others for what they consider a false portrayal of
blacks in a romanticized plantation setting of the fictional Old
South _ isn't available from routine sources such as Blockbuster
(1-800-800-6767) or video suppliers on the Internet such as
www.bigstar.com and www.reel.com.
</P>
<P>
   However, versions of it are listed on the Internet as being
available for mail-order purchase from a source in Florida. Note
that a fan Internet site includes a message that people have
complained about sending in their money and not receiving their
order in a timely fashion, so buyer beware. If you want to order
it, here's where: Ol' Remus Collectibles, P.O. Box 7554, Ensley, FL
32534-0554. The cost is $30 for a copy in English with Japanese
subtitles (originally released on the Japanese market), or $40 for
English without subtitles (originally released on the British
market).
</P>
<P>
   A possible alternative if you're interested only in music is a
26-minute video, ``Disney's Sing Along Songs,'' which includes
``Zip-A-Dee-Doo-Dah'' from ``Song of the South.'' It's available
for purchase on the Internet _ www.bigstar.com is one source _ and
may be available for rental at video stores.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know anything about some deaths in connection with the
arthritis medicine Celebrex? My doctor said there's nothing to it.
</P>
<P>
   A: Officials at the Food and Drug Administration have confirmed
a report in The Wall Street Journal that the painkiller has been
linked to 10 deaths and 11 cases of gastrointestinal hemorrhages
during its first three months on the market. Despite the deaths,
the FDA isn't raising an alarm for the drug, which has been taken
by more than 2 million consumers. Robert DeLap, director of an FDA
office for drug evaluation, said more research is needed before
coming to a conclusion about the safety of Celebrex, which is
manufactured by St. Louis-based Monsanto Co.'s G.D. Searle &AMP; Co.
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both the FDA and Searle indicated that the ``safety
profile'' _ meaning the ``adverse event reports,'' or reports about
deaths, bleeding and ulcers _ were not out of line when related to
the total of 2.5 million prescriptions for Celebrex filled in its
first 13 weeks on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's a steak dinner resting on this. Was Helen Keller
known to be a Communist or socialist? I say she was, but my husband
says not.
</P>
<P>
   A: The 1998 book ``Helen Keller: A Life,'' by Dorothy Herrmann,
confirms your belief. Consider this passage: ``Keller was in fact a
militant socialist who wrote and spoke openly about issues such as
the labor movement, civil rights and birth control, as well as her
admiration for Marx and Lenin. She yearned for marriage and
children and remained bitter that her plans to elope with a young
socialist were thwarted by her family.'' T-bone, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give me an address or a Web site where I can reach
Gary Bauer, who is running for president?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mail can be sent to the Republican presidential contender at
this address: Bauer for President Inc., 2800 Shirlington Road,
Suite 900, Arlington, VA 22206. The Web site _ www.bauer2K.com/ _
has information, or you can call 703-933-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A pit crew member at the Indy 500 was struck by a race car.
Do you have an update?
</P>
<P>
   A: Steve Fried, crew chief for rookie driver Robby McGehee, was
released from an Indianapolis hospital June 13. The Mentor, Ohio,
crewman was working in McGehee's pit early in the May 30 race when
he was struck from behind by driver Jimmy Kite's car, which had
been hit by another car whose brakes had failed. Fried was thrown
into the air and fell face first on the concrete, fracturing his
skull, right eye socket, jaw, left shoulder, several ribs, and
bones in his ear. His brain was injured and his lungs collapsed.
Medical workers said he wasn't breathing when they reached him, and
his heart stopped en route to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Fried, who has begun physical therapy, says he hopes to return
to work later in the Indy Racing League season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
