<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4433 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE     06-30 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is George W. Bush, who is running for the Republican
presidential nomination, the Bush who was involved in a savings and
loan scandal some years ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. It was Neil Bush, one of George W.'s brothers, who was a
figure in the Silverado Banking, Savings and Loan Association in
Colorado. Silverado failed in 1988, costing taxpayers an estimated
$1 billion. Although Neil Bush never was charged with criminal
wrongdoing, he agreed to pay $50,000 in 1992 to settle a civil
lawsuit lodged two years earlier by the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some $10 million in ``genius grants'' was just awarded to 32
people by the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation. Do you
have any details about the MacArthurs and the source of their
fortune?
</P>
<P>
   A: The foundation, which has been making the grants annually
since 1981, doesn't use the word ``genius.'' It prefers to think of
them as grants to people who are ``exceptionally talented and
promising individuals.'' Recipients, selected anonymously, have
five years to pursue whatever interests they desire, with no
strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, a private, independent grant-making institution,
is based in Chicago. It was created in 1978 by John D. MacArthur
(1897-1978), who developed and owned Bankers Life and Casualty Co.
and other businesses, as well as considerable property in Florida
and New York. Catherine MacArthur (1909-81), his wife, held
positions in many of these companies and served as director of the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   One of the nation's largest foundations, it has assets of $4
billion and makes grants totaling more than $150 million annually
through two major integrated programs (Human and Community
Development, and Global Security and Sustainability) and two
special programs (General Program, and MacArthur Fellows).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are people working inside buildings exposed to as much ozone
as those outdoors? In other words, are air handling systems able to
remove ozone from the outside air?
</P>
<P>
   A: While some filters in heating and cooling equipment collect
particles and dust, a gas such as ground-level ozone _ the major
culprit in ``smog alerts'' _ likely would travel through the system
in a similar concentration to that found outdoors, according to
environmental protection officials.
</P>
<P>
   But while some ozone from outside does get inside, levels don't
remain high for very long because air conditioners constantly turn
over the indoor air. Also, ozone indoors attaches itself quickly to
walls, furniture and other objects, futher reducing its levels in
the air. People sensitive to high ozone levels outdoors gain
another benefit by staying indoors: They're likely not to be as
active as if outdoors. The more active a person is, the heavier the
breathing and the greater the chances of sucking in greater volumes
of ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any place I can rent or buy a video of ``With a Song
in My Heart,'' starring Susan Hayward, which was made years ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: You'll have to be patient _ and watchful of the cable channel
American Movie Classics _ if you want to see the movie anytime
soon. It's not for sale or rental in a videotape version.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a Song in My Heart,'' which also featured Rory Calhoun,
David Wayne, Thelma Ritter and Robert Wagner, told the story of
Jane Froman, a singer who in 1943 was seriously injured in an
airplane crash off Portugal while on a USO tour to entertain U.S.
troops overseas.
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox, the studio holding rights to the 1952 movie,
hasn't released it on video, according to Debra Dodds of American
Movie Classics. AMC has shown the film in the past, but its
broadcast rights expired in October. The cable channel is
renegotiating with 20th Century Fox for future broadcast rights,
however, so you might be able to catch it again later. The best way
to follow AMC's schedule in advance is through its monthly AMC
Magazine ($12.95 for 12 issues; 1-888-262-4700).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several photos published recently showed NATO and British
vehicles in the Yugoslavia war zones with an inverted V on the
front. What does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: The inverted V has no symbolism other than its utilitarian
function of being one tool in distinguishing friend from foe in
combat, according to SHAPE (Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers
Europe).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read that all cars sold in Canada have daytime running
lights, whereas in the United States the choices are limited, such
as to some Saturns and Buicks. Can I order a car from Canada or buy
one there and bring it back?
</P>
<P>
   A: You don't need to go to that trouble. And why risk running
afoul of U.S. Customs? Nor do you need an after-market adaption.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive experts say you can achieve the same effect _ the
added safety factor of making your vehicle more visible to others
during the day _ by turning your headlights on as soon as you start
the engine. The headlights on many rental cars in the United States
automatically come on when the ignition key is turned, and some
imports, such as Volvo, also incorporate the feature.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It has been reported that bald eagles have been taken off the
endangered species list. Do you have more details? What does that
mean? Can we now hunt them?
</P>
<P>
   A: The status of bald eagles will change, but they still can't
be hunted. The Clinton administration announced plans May 6 to
remove nearly 30 once-rare bird, animal and plant species from the
government's official ``endangered'' list _ the bald eagle among
them _ declaring victory in staving off their extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Both the bald eagle and the peregrine falcon, which also was
removed, were pushed to the brink of extinction by the use of
pesticides. Eagles also were victims of ranchers and farmers who
killed them, believing them to be marauders targeting their
chickens and domestic livestock.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service reports that there now are
more than 1,500 nesting pairs of falcons. In 1998, wildlife
officials counted 5,748 bald eagles and said that probably was an
``undercount.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1940 law, the Bald Eagle Protection Act, continues to protect
the bald eagle and its cousin, the golden eagle, from hunting and
other direct harm. What will change, once the bald eagle is
officially removed from the endangered list, is that there no
longer will be federal rules protecting its habitat. Those habitat
protection rules are part of the Endangered Species Act of 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Prior to the wedding of Prince Edward to Sophie Rhys-Jones,
it was speculated that Queen Elizabeth would bestow the title of
duke and duchess upon them. Instead, she made them earl and
countess of Wessex. What is the pecking order among British lords,
dukes, counts and others? Can one ``step up'' to a more desirable
title?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ``pecking order'' starts, of course, with royalty (Queen
Elizabeth and her family). The highest heriditary title outside the
royal family is duke, ranking immediately below a prince, and above
a marquess. A marquess is a nobleman ranking above an earl (or
count), while an earl is a nobleman ranking above a viscount.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepping up'' in title is rarely an issue, according to the
British consulate in Atlanta, although it has happened on occasion,
such as when Princess Anne was given the title princess royal for
her charitable work. But then she has royal blood anyway, so that's
not exactly ``moving up.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest son of a duke and duchess, incidentally, is a lord
with the rank of marquess, and younger sons and daughters are
called lords and ladies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the ``57'' refer to in Heinz 57?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's just a slogan, hit upon by Henry John Heinz in 1896,
even though at the time his company (then known as Heinz &AMP; Noble)
made 60 products.
</P>
<P>
   The Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins says the famous
slogan came from a billboard Heinz had seen in New York referring
to ``21 Styles of Shoes.'' Heinz apparently believed that an odd
number would be more noticeable than 60, so 57 was chosen. The
Pittsburgh-based company, by the way, now makes more than 5,000
products.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We hear so much about automobiles putting pollution into the
air. Aren't aircraft at airports also a factor?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, aircraft are a ``significant contributor'' to ozone
problems, said Ronald Methier of the Georgia Environmental
Protection Division. Since many aircraft travel internationally,
their engines are subject to international standards rather than
those of the United States, which are more stringent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article reported that a bronze casket used to carry
President Kennedy's body from Dallas to Washington had been dropped
into the Atlantic Ocean from a military plane years ago. This
information was just made public. Do you have any more details?
</P>
<P>
   A: The documents, released June 1 by the National Archives, said
the federal government was following the wishes of the Kennedy
family when it dumped the coffin into the Atlantic in 1966. Kennedy
family spokeswoman Melody Miller said the destruction of the casket
was appropriate and ``in keeping with the tradition of President
Kennedy's naval service and his love of the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, according to the documents, Sen. Robert F. Kennedy had
asked that the casket be released to the military for destruction,
saying, ``I think it belongs to the family and we can get rid of it
any way we want to.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 18 that same year, an Air Force van picked up the casket
at the Archives and transported it to Andrews Air Force Base, Md.,
where it was loaded onto a C-130. To ensure that the coffin would
sink, three 80-pound bags of sand were put inside, metal banding
was wrapped around it, and it was placed inside a pine box which
also was wrapped with metal tape. The plane flew about 131 nautical
miles off the Maryland-Delaware coast, dropping the casket into
9,000 feet of water in an explosives dumping area.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
