<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4437 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-2SOUTHPARK-REVIEW01-C     06-30 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-2SOUTHPARK-REVIEW01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gay devil, damned Ghandi: `Park' knows no limits
 &HT;    (EDS: Italics noted in story.)
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ITALIC)BOOM! (END ITALIC)
</P>
<P>
   Hear that? That's the tasteless bar crashing to a woefully crude
new level. But what do you expect when you give the ``South Park''
creators 90 minutes (ITALIC) and (END ITALIC) an R-rating? That's
like letting a mischievous 5-year-old take over a day-care center_
the results won't be pretty, but they might be comical.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' will certainly please
die-hard fans. And on that criteria alone, the movie could be
considered a success.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, filmmakers Trey Parker and Matt Stone don't fall into
the trap of padding what's essentially a 30-minute cartoon.
Although the movie is laced with too many profanities, which grow
tiresome and annoying, the hilarious musical numbers and outrageous
sight gags are enough to keep you from checking your watch.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Stone know what their audience likes _ boorish,
foul-mouthed humor. Anything goes in the ``South Park'' world. And
``South Park'' doesn't just push the proverbial envelope, it shoves
it, kicks it and manhandles it.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Stone are nothing if not topical. Their four lovable
tykes_ Cartman, Stan, Kyle and Kenny _ sneak into an R-rated movie,
the name of which we can't print. The film stars Terrence and
Phillip, two Canadian TV stars whose heads split in half when they
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the four kids love the movie _ and so do the other
kids in the small Colorado mountain town. But parents don't like
the effect it has on their children (they're _ gasp _ cursing at
their teachers!), so before you can say, ``Oh my God, they've
killed Kenny!'' the United States declares war on Canada and vows
to execute Terrence and Philip.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves plenty of time for gags. Brooke Shields, Conan
O'Brien, Winona Ryder and the Baldwin brothers serve as comic
targets. You'll also finally get to see what the mumbling,
hood-clad Kenny looks like. And when he dies, he goes straight to
hell, where the Devil is a caring, sensitive gay creature who's
sleeping with Saddam Hussein. We also learn that such folks as
George Burns and Gandhi have been damned forever.
</P>
<P>
   The film's funniest moments are actually the ``Beauty and the
Beast''-like musical numbers. There's Mr. Garrison teaching the
kids to use words such as ``buns'' and ``poo,'' Satan yearning to
live on Earth (``I could be up there and live without a care'') and
Cartman calling Kyle's mom a word that rhymes with ``witch.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the yuks, there's still something disturbing about
cartoon characters cursing as often as they do in ``South Park''.
After the initial shock value wears off, the crass comedic device
wears thin quickly.
</P>
<P>
   If you have young kids, you'd be wise not to take them to this
movie. If you do, you'll probably feel like the parents in ``South
Park'': You'll want to declare war on Parker and Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
