<HEADER>
A4438 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RIBS01-COX     06-30 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RIBS01-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Ribs: Declare your independence from disappointing grill
offerings
</P>
<P>
   By Ann Heller
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Hugh Carpenter writes his rib rules in great big
print:
</P>
<P>
   The first one is: Never, NEVER boil ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Kline, who speaks for the National Pork Producers Council,
gives the same advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under no circumstances should you `parboil' ribs before
grilling. Parboiling robs ribs of flavor and is an unnecessary
step.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bruce Aidells, founder of the Aidells Sausage company and
co-author of ``The Complete Meat Cookbook,'' shudders at the
mention of parboiling, saying ``the result is stringy meat that
lacks juiciness and flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   The flavor, you see, goes down the sink with the water.
</P>
<P>
   So why do so many people do this?
</P>
<P>
   Because they want tender ribs. Now, that sets up an argument on
the issue of tenderness. The measure of doneness, says Kline, is
that the bone should wiggle.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the same thing as falling-off-the-bone tenderness.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what some folks love. Ribs so tender you can suck the
bones right out.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if that's what you want, there are ways to achieve it
other than boiling the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   And as people fire up the grill for the July 4 holiday, we're
here to tell you how to get tender, juicy ribs. We're not talking
sauces here. That's another story. We're talking technique.
</P>
<P>
   All the experts stress cooking the ribs slowly over indirect
heat. Whether using a gas or a charcoal grill, the process is the
same. The meat is ideally placed over a drip pan, with the coals
(or burners) to the side to provide the heat (though you can skip
the drip pan if necessary). Baby back ribs may be done in an hour
and a half, spareribs in two hours. Sauce is applied only the last
15 to 30 minutes to avoid scorching (sweet ingredients scorch
quickly).
</P>
<P>
   Kline has a technique to appease those who like ribs
extra-tender. After the ribs are fully cooked, wrap them in foil,
tuck them in a brown paper bag and seal it to let the ribs finish
cooking in their own heat. Let them sit for one hour. Don't worry,
food can sit out for up to two hours before it's risky to eat.
While the ribs rest, there's time to put the finishing touches on
the rest of the holiday dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, author of the new Great Ribs Book(Tenspeed, $14.95),
suggests a variation of that trick. After the ribs have been
grilled, fully cooked and sauced, put them (naked, not in foil) in
a brown paper bag, meaty side up. Fold and staple the bag shut and
place it in a 140-degree oven for one hour. The ribs steam in the
bag. My added advice: Don't use a supermarket bag made of recycled
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Aidells, though he disparages the notion of parboiling ribs
(cooking them in boiling water), tolerates a second-cousin
technique _ precooking the ribs by poaching them in water that
never goes above a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like quibbling over a bubble, but keeping the
water temperature below 170 degrees (as opposed to the 212 degrees
of boiling water) assures tender ribs. Still, Aidells says, some
flavor leaches out. He'd rather prebake the ribs and finish them on
the grill.
</P>
<P>
   And for those with a standard-sized backyard grill and a
houseful of company on the holiday, precooking the ribs is the only
way to feed the group. Finish them on the grill in minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we've settled that, it's on to the recipes. You get to
decide whether you want the ribs wet _ dripping with sauce _ or
dry, Memphis-style.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: annheller(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
