<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIBS-CROWD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When precooking is the answer
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there are lots of people at the cookout, the only way to feed
them ribs off a standard backyard grill is to precook them and
finish them on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   But if you've sworn off parboiling the ribs, what are you going
to do? Here are some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Wrap seasoned ribs in heavy foil and precook them in a
300-degree oven for 1 to 1 1/2 hours. Save any drippings that
accumulate to add to your sauce. The Pork Producers Council says
the ribs can also be pre-roasted uncovered in a shallow pan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Precook unwrapped ribs in a 200- to 250-degree oven for 2 1/2
to 3 hours. They will be fully cooked at this point but note that
food-safety experts quarrel with cooking temperatures that low.
</P>
<P>
   However you choose to precook them, finish the ribs over a low
fire on the grill, cooking enough to give them a light crust and
heat them through, anywhere from 5 to 15 minutes per side. Brush
with a sauce if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
