<HEADER>
A4440 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIBS-GRILLTEMP01-COX     06-30 0191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIBS-GRILLTEMP01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    That temperamental temperature
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's face it: Regulating the temperature of a charcoal fire is
a challenge, especially when food cooks for a long time. You have
to keep adding briquettes and play with the vents to regulate the
heat. Using an instant-read thermometer, tucked into the top vent
hole, helps keep track of the temperature, but readings don't go
above 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up indirect cooking on a gas grill is more precise. Here
are the instructions from the new ``Weber's Art of the Grill,
Recipes for Outdoor Living'' (Chronicle, $35):
</P>
<P>
   _ Preheat the grill with all burners on high.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adjust the burners on each side of the food to medium heat and
turn off the burner directly below the food.
</P>
<P>
   _ Place ribs on a rack set inside a disposable, heavy-gauge foil
pan.
</P>
<P>
   _ For long cooking times, add water to the drip pan to keep
drippings from burning.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
