<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4441 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIBS-RECIPIES01-COX     06-30 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIBS-RECIPIES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secret of great ribs is the rub, technique
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Chefs and grill experts who have been at it for
years put some pretty strange ingredients in their rubs and sauces.
For a backyard celebration when you just want to feed people,
nothing beats basic old-fashioned barbecued ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Even a novice can handle this recipe, though it does take time.
The magic ingredient is the simple rub. Some cooks baste the ribs
with a homemade pork broth or apple cider or vinegar spiked with
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In Memphis, Tenn., the ribs are often served without a sauce in
order to appreciate the flavor of the meat and the dry seasonings.
The sauce, if any, goes on at the end or at the table.
</P>
<P>
   MEMPHIS-STYLE RIBS
</P>
<P>
   4 slabs pork back ribs or spareribs
</P>
<P>
   Memphis rub (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue sauce of your choice
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a medium fire in the grill, banking the coals to one
side or on either side of a drip pan.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the ribs with the seasoning, using 2 or 3 tablespoons per
slab. Place them on the grill in a single layer opposite the heat
source. Cover the grill and cook ribs slowly for 1 1/2 to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   If desired, wrap the cooked ribs in heavy aluminum foil and
place in a heavy brown paper bag. Let the ribs rest for an hour for
extra-tender ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Serve dry or with sauce on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The basic ingredients in this rub are suggested by the National
Pork Producers Council. The original did not include salt, which I
think is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   MEMPHIS RUB
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons onion powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chile powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Mix all ingredients in a small jar. Store any excess in a sealed
jar in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   An even simpler Memphis rub comes from Melanie Barnard in ``The
Best Covered and Kettle Grills Cookbook Ever'' (HarperCollins). She
also offers her version of a sauce served along with Memphis ribs.
</P>
<P>
   EASY MEMPHIS RUB
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons coarsely ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon crushed red pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine salt and peppers. This makes enough to rub 6 pounds of
pork spareribs. She suggests refrigerating the seasoned ribs for 4
hours before cooking but return them to room temperature. She also
suggests adding soaked hickory chips to the coals while cooking the
ribs for 1 1/2 hours over indirect heat.
</P>
<P>
   RIB SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 cups
</P>
<P>
   2 cups bottled chili sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crushed hot red pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, crushed through a press
</P>
<P>
   In a medium nonaluminum saucepan combine the ingredients. Simmer
over medium-low heat until the sauce just coats a spoon, about 20
minutes. It can be used immediately or refrigerated as long as 1
week.
</P>
<P>
   If you have time to spare and are a purist at heart, try this
recipe from ``The Complete Meat Cookbook'' by Bruce Aidells and
Denis Kelly (Houghton Mifflin, $35). You do need a large, covered
kettle grill. Don't build a big fire. This is slow, low, smoky
cooking, and it requires attention to the grill vents to control
the heat level.
</P>
<P>
   SLOW-COOKED
</P>
<P>
   BARBECUED RIBS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   2 2 1/2- to 3-pound slabs of spareribs
</P>
<P>
   Spice Rub (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups presoaked wood chips or chunks, optional
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue sauce of your choice
</P>
<P>
   Rub the spice rub over both sides of the ribs, using 2 to 3
tablespoons for each slab. For best results refrigerate overnight,
loosely wrapped, but 1 hour at room temperature will do. If
refrigerated, bring to room temperature for 30 minutes before
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a covered barbecue for cooking. Light a mound of 20 to
30 briquettes on one side of the grate and open bottom vents fully.
Place a roasting pan (or aluminum pan) on the other side of the
grate and add 2 inches of water to the pan to provide moist heat
and catch drippings.
</P>
<P>
   If using chips, wrap the soaked wood chips in foil and punch
holes in the foil.
</P>
<P>
   Once the coals are covered with gray ash, lay the foil packet of
soaked chips on the coals. Put the rack on the grill and lay the
ribs on it over the drip pan so no meat is over the hot coals.
Cover the grill, with the lid vents about half open and opposite
the coals so the smoke is drawn over the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the temperature low is important. To check it, stick an
instant-read thermometer into a top vent hole, making sure that any
plastic parts are not in direct contact with the metal lid. Leave
the thermometer in place.
</P>
<P>
   For spareribs slow-cooked with a low fire, you want the
temperature to read 200 to 250 degrees; initially it can be higher,
but it should not exceed 300 and should drop to the lower range
within a half-hour. If not, partially close the lower vent to
decrease the heat. Regulate the temperature by adjusting the bottom
vent. But be sure not to close the vents entirely or the coals will
die out.
</P>
<P>
   Every 45 minutes turn the ribs over and switch their places on
the grill so that you alternate their exposure to the hotter edge
near the coals. If coals need replenishing, add another 5 to 10
briquettes. Another packet of chips can be added as well.
</P>
<P>
   Aidells says the entire process of cooking the ribs can take 4
hours, but if your heat stayed above 250 degrees for long, they
will cook in much less time. Start checking them after 2 hours
until you've become a pro. When they are ready, the ends of the
bones will be exposed, and the meat will begin to pull away from
the bone. If a rib bone is twisted, it should wiggle. If tested
with an instant-read thermometer, the meatiest section should have
an internal temperature of 165 to 175 degrees (because ribs are
fatty, they can be cooked to a higher temperature than other pork
cuts).
</P>
<P>
   When ribs are done, place on a baking sheet or platter and cover
tightly with foil. Wrap the pan with 10 to 20 sheets of unfolded
newspaper and let ribs rest for 20 minutes and as long as 1 hour
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, heat the barbecue sauce. Slice the slabs
into individual ribs and brush with the sauce or serve them dry.
Serve with sauce on the side.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer baby-back ribs, use three 1- to 1 1/2-pound slabs.
</P>
<P>
   SPICE RUB
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chile powder
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 teaspoons cayenne (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons garlic powder or granulated garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground sage
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Mix all the ingredients in a small jar. Any leftover can be
stored for a couple months in a tightly sealed jar.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Carpenter is a cookbook author whose name is permanently
linked to fusion cuisine. He was on the cutting edge with his first
book, ``Pacific Flavors `` in 1988. So it's no surprise that when
it comes to ribs, his come with California style exotic flavors,
and they are all shown off in his newest book, ``The Great Ribs
Book'' (Ten Speed, $14.95). It's full of ideas to celebrate the
independence of a country with roots that span the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his marinades are dependent on sweet ingredients such as
hoisin sauce and plum sauce that frankly might char over indirect
heat on the grill. These ribs might be better cooked in a
250-degree oven. Or use a basic rub and try his marinades as a
finishing glaze on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   This one pairs Southwest seasonings such as chipotle chiles with
toasted coriander seeds and peppercorns.
</P>
<P>
   CHIPOTLE-CORIANDER GLAZE
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for 6 pounds ribs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   4 small shallots, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chipotle chiles in adobo sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup molasses
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dark soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon orange zest, optional
</P>
<P>
   Toast the coriander seeds and peppercorns in a small skillet
over medium heat, cooking just until smoke begins to rise. Cool on
paper towels. Transfer to a spice grinder and grind finely (or
crush in a mortar and pestle).
</P>
<P>
   Mince the garlic and shallots in a food processor. Add the
ground spices and chipotle chiles and mince for 10 seconds. Add the
remaining ingredients and process until the mixture becomes a thick
paste.
</P>
<P>
   The paste can be mopped on the ribs after they have cooked on
the grill for an hour, or on oven precooked ribs. Baste the ribs
and turn several times.
</P>
<P>
   Or to try them Carpenter-style, slather the paste on uncooked
ribs and roast on a rack in a 350-degree oven for about 90 minutes.
For added moisture place a small pan of water at the bottom of the
oven.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
