</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIBS-TIPS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remove membrane to ensure tenderness
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rib experts agree: Ribs will always be tough unless you remove
the membrane that covers the bony side of the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Some markets buy ribs preskinned, but others don't, so flip that
slab over and scrutinize the underside. In his new ``Great Ribs
Book,'' (Ten Speed, $14.95) Hugh Carpenter tells how to remove it:
</P>
<P>
   _ Place the ribs, meaty side down, on a flat surface.
</P>
<P>
   _ Using your fingernail, loosen a little of the membrane along
the end of the last rib bone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grasp the membrane firmly with a paper towel (so the membrane
doesn't slip from your grip).
</P>
<P>
   _ Holding the ribs down with the other hand, pull the membrane.
If it doesn't pull away in one piece, repeat the procedure with the
remaining membrane.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4443 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHPARK-REVIEW01-CO     06-30 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHPARK-REVIEW01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who can resist these South Park kids?
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those foul-mouthed miscreants from South Park say everything
they can't get away with on television in their big-screen debut _
and much, much more.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare to be shocked by the sheer amount of strong profanity in
``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'', including words you'd never
imagined, as creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone insolently wave
their middle fingers at the Motion Picture Association of America.
The pair apparently harbors a grudge against the prudish ratings
board for slapping Parker's benign porn spoof, Orgazmo, with an
NC-17.
</P>
<P>
   The MPAA-baiting ``South Park'' movie reportedly had to be
re-edited three times to avoid the same rating, which is death at
the box office. Despite the double-entendre subtitle's claim, two
minutes of footage was trimmed to secure an R, which will still
keep out teens without fake IDs.
</P>
<P>
   The animated comedy is defiantly crude and offensive. It's also
unrelentingly hilarious. The film's target, not surprisingly, is
censorship. What's most shocking of all is that it's a musical, and
a fairly ambitious one at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off to the movies we will go, where we learn everything that
we know,'' sing Stan, Kyle, Kenny and Cartman (voiced by Parker and
Stone) in the film's opening number, Mountain Town, a send-up of
Belle's ode to her village in Disney's ``Beauty and the Beast''.
</P>
<P>
   The boys sneak into an R-rated movie featuring flatulent
Canadian comics Terence and Philip. Soon they and their third-grade
classmates are parroting the duo's vulgar dialogue. Kenny dies
attempting to emulate T &AMP; P's antics, on a bet from Cartman. Kyle's
moral watchdog mother (voiced by Mary Kay Bergman, who does most of
the film's female characters) leads outraged parents on what
becomes a nationwide crusade against profanity and all things
Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   With World War III brewing between the United States and Canada,
and Chef (Isaac Hayes) on the front lines as part of Operation
Human Shield, the kids from South Park form an underground
resistance movement. Meanwhile, down in Hell, Kenny must prevent
Satan and Saddam Hussein from launching the Apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   For all its rude irreverence, the South Park movie is oddly
prescient in its take on such current hot topics as checking IDs
for R-rated movies, the influence of media on youth and the United
States' role as the world's police force. Of course, it's all
played for side-splitting laughs, as when the adults implant a
V-chip under Cartman's scalp, Clockwork Orange -style, to prevent
him from swearing.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Stone slam countless celebrities, from Conan O'Brien
to the Baldwin clan. They are aided by a number of famous voices,
including George Clooney, Eric Idle, Minnie Driver, Dave Foley,
Brent Spiner and Beavis and Butt-head 's Mike Judge.
</P>
<P>
   The cartoon cut-ups take a swipe at their own limited animation
style, yet the film's computer-generated Hell sequences are much
more impressive than those in the live-action Spawn movie.
</P>
<P>
   Most inspired are the off-the-wall production numbers,
highlighted by the rousing ``What Would Brian Boitano Do?'',
Satan's yearning ``Up There'' and the Les Miz -skewering ``La
Resistance''. That latter culminates in a clever, ``West Side
Story'' -inspired reprise of major musical themes.
</P>
<P>
   The film goes too far with its raw language and raunchy humor _
no matter how liberal your sensibility, you will be offended by
something _ but that is the point. ``Horrific depravity and
horrible violence is OK, as long as people don't say naughty
words,'' one adult says, purportedly quoting the MPAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' is Parker and Stone's
audacious and uproarious ``La Resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
