A4444 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILD-WILD-REVIEW01-CO     06-30 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILD-WILD-REVIEW01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even a great villain can't save this flick
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a good summer for comedic villains.
</P>
<P>
   Their sly and sinister ways _ salted with irony and a pinch of
self-deprecation _ have added much-needed zest to several
intentionally dumb movies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Evil was more amusing than Austin Powers in ``The Spy Who
Shagged Me'' _ or at least more outrageous. ``The Mummy'' had a
decent villain. Granted, he was a second-stringer, but weaselly
enough to be amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but when the villain is both a weasel and a wizard, then
you've got something. Even better when the baddie's played by a
real actor such as Kenneth Branagh.
</P>
<P>
   Branagh (''Henry V'') turns on his declamatory Shakespearean
voice in the wobbly ``Wild Wild West,'' opening today. But his
accent is pure, syrupy Southern. (The Brits do Dixie so (ITALIC)
extremely (END ITALIC) well.)
</P>
<P>
   Branagh plays Dr. Arliss Loveless, a literally sawed-off
Confederate veteran who wants to kidnap President Ulysses Grant and
force him to surrender the U.S. to a grab-bag of foreign powers.
</P>
<P>
   Out to stop him are our heroes James West and Artemus Gordon,
played by Will Smith and Kevin Kline, who alternate between being
super-slick and the Laurel and Hardy of the old West.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is based on the old TV series. It tries to take
advantage of the pairing in last year's Fourth of July weekend hit,
``Men In Black''. That comedy teamed the always likeable Smith with
a deliciously deadpan Tommy Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Director Barry Sonnenfeld's back for this flick, too, and Kline
is a wonderful actor and comedian. (He also plays a great President
Grant.) But the Smith-Kline duo doesn't mesh as well as
Smith-Jones, perhaps because they play rivals who come to like each
other. Their bickering and one-upsmanship are really old hat in the
movies _ or old Stetson, in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the dull ``Wild Wild West'' completely lacks the
originality of ``Men In Black''. The writing is limp, made worse by
a clutter of tiresome racial jokes and puns. There's a couple of
funny sight gags based on gadgetry, including one involving
magnetic collars. But the inclusion of sci-fi shtick seems
desperate. Dr. Loveless' gigantic ``tarantula'' looks like it was
made out of a kid's erector set.
</P>
<P>
   To shoot straight about this flick, it's simply not well
written.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves us with plenty of cornball action, a glimpse of
Salma Hayek in a corset_ and Dr. Loveless. Branagh's lines aren't
terribly clever, either, but the sight of him is a hoot. He putters
around in a wheelchair with a smoking chimney on the back. His
vaudevillian beard makes him look like Mandrake the Madman. His
eyes fairly twinkle when he's up to no good, which he's up to all
the time, even if his manners are perfect.
</P>
<P>
   He's comic relief, indeed. ``Wild Wild West'' proves that
``action-packed'' movies can be awfully listless. But at least this
one isn't Loveless.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schwan writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
