<HEADER>
A4445 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILDWEST-REVIEW01-COX     06-30 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDWEST-REVIEW01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wild, Wild West: Bad, bad, bad
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Wild Wild West'' is a bad, bad movie.
</P>
<P>
   The big-budget film adaptation of the popular 1960s television
series about a James Bond-style 19th-century government agent
reunites ``Men in Black'' director Barry Sonnenfeld with that
film's star, Will Smith. The TV show's premise has been revamped to
suit Smith's wisecracking persona, as well as Sonnenfeld's visual
inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the sci-fi western lacks ``Men In Black'''s sharp
pacing and snappy script. The result is a ludicrous action-comedy
that's neither exciting nor funny. It might have worked as a
big-screen comic book for kids, but the film's high degree of
violence and sexual innuendo _ the first two scenes feature a
decapitation and some naked canoodling in a water tank _ make it
unsuitable for pre-teens.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have circulated for months that ``Wild Wild West'' was
wildly over budget, rising to a reported $160 million from its
original $105 million. The troubled production wrapped several
weeks behind schedule, and Sonnenfeld called the cast back for 10
days of re-shoots in April to add some physical comedy after the
film scored poorly with test audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The potential box-office behemoth _ which features a monstrous
80-foot-tall Jules Verne-inspired mechanical tarantula _ looks to
be this summer's Godzilla . It will open big based on the hype and
then drop off fast once bad word-of-mouth hits the street. The film
appears unlikely to make its bloated budget back during its
theatrical run, which would at least spare us from a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   The inane, threadbare story by brothers Jim and John Thomas _
four other writers are credited for the screenplay _ involves
post-Civil War federal marshals James West (Smith) and Artemus
Gordon (Kevin Kline) being thrown together by President Ulysses S.
Grant to track down diabolical genius Dr. Arliss Loveless (Kenneth
Branagh), who has kidnapped the United States' top scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The two agents spend much of the film bickering over their
conflicting approaches to crime-fighting. It gets old real fast. As
Grant puts it, West tends to shoot first, shoot second, shoot third
and then if there's anyone left alive, ask a few questions. Gordon
is a self-styled master of disguise who invents all sorts of
futuristic gadgets that sometimes work, but always annoy West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon, I think you underestimate the convenience of a
pocket,'' West says after a notebook and pen pop out from his
sidekick's sleeves. Sonnenfeld and company certainly underestimated
the importance of a good script.
</P>
<P>
   The appalling low point in the humor comes when West, a black
cowboy, and Loveless, who lost his legs in the war, exchange rounds
of thinly veiled racial and amputee insults. Otherwise, the verbal
gags are pretty much limited to bad puns, like when West dispatches
a blade-handed henchman, saying, ``No more mister knife guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a few clever visuals, such as snipers emerging from
oil paintings and West being sling-shot beneath Loveless' train,
there's little of Sonnenfeld's usual playfulness. The giant
tarantula is a fairly impressive piece of computer-generated
imagery, but the film's blue-screen effects are rather obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Smith looks dashing in his western duds, although far too much
is made of his character's skin color. He slips in too many
contemporary phrases for a period piece _ calling one character
``butt ugly'' _ and simply isn't all that funny in the role.
</P>
<P>
   Kline, who earned an Oscar for A Fish Called Wanda, provides
paltry comic relief by dressing in drag and ranting incessantly.
Salma Hayek adds nothing more than her ample cleavage as Rita
Escobar, a buxom entertainer who comes between the agents. Branagh
sports a heavy drawl and chews up lots of expensive scenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Wild West'' will be quickly run out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
