<P>
   HINDENBERG-EYEWITNESS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Thousands
watched the last, slow dance of the dirigible Hindenburg as it
bobbed through the stormy sky over New York City in the late
afternoon of May 6, 1937. The pride of the Zeppelin Company's air
fleet was already more than 10 hours late completing its first
flight of the season from Germany, but the captain was in no hurry.
He'd decided to circle and wait for a break in the weather to
ensure the sort of smooth, pinpoint descent that had ended each of
the Hindenburg's 10 previous flights to America. A crowd of
welcomers and sightseers waited southeast of the city at the ship's
destination, the U.S. Navy's air station at Lakehurst, N.J. Among
the eager greeters were the Enssle family of nearby Roselle Park,
including 13-year-old Eleanor. Eleanor remembers the events of that
day. (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
