<P>
   FOOD-RIBS _ Hugh Carpenter writes his rib rules in great big
print: The first one is: Never NEVER boil ribs. Robin Kline, who
speaks for the National Pork Producers Council, gives the same
advice. ``Under no circumstances should you `parboil' ribs before
grilling. Parboiling robs ribs of flavor and is an unnecessary
step.'' The flavor, you see, goes down the sink with the water. So
why do so many people do this? (Dayton Daily News). 16. WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RIBS-TIPS _ Rib experts agree: Ribs will always be tough unless
you remove the membrane that covers the bony side of the ribs. Some
markets buy ribs preskinned, but others don't, so flip that slab
over and scrutinize the underside. Here's how to remove it. (Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RIBS-GRILLTEMP _ Let's face it: Regulating the temperature of a
charcoal fire is a challenge, particularly when food cooks for a
long time. Here are some suggestions. (Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
