 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Read up before lighting the grill 
By Mark Clothier  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first time you tried to fake your way through
being an outdoor cook, you may have ended up with oxymoron meat:
charred but raw.
</P>
<P>
   Had there been a site like Better Homes and Gardens Online's
Summer Cooking School around, you might not have had to settle for
take-out that night.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.bhg.com/food/grillschool/, takes you through the
basics _ how to pile the charcoal, how much lighter fluid to use
and how to light the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Reading it will save you the trouble, and expense, of squirting
lighter fluid on a hill of coals as if you were trying to douse a
flame rather than start one. Once lit, the coals are supposed to be
left to heat up for at least 20 minutes. Mine sat for about 10
minutes, which is why the chicken cooked a bit unevenly.
</P>
<P>
   Grill-master mistakes are not limited to the charcoal grill, and
neither is the Web site's instruction.
</P>
<P>
   A separate section explains how to light a gas grill (one hint:
leave the lid up) and how to cook on and clean a gas grill.
</P>
<P>
   The site is divided into six sections: gas grilling basics,
charcoal grilling basics, key techniques, flavor enhancers, handy
utensils and grilling books.
</P>
<P>
   Study to determine what cell phone does to brain
</P>
<P>
   Ever wondered what holding a cell phone to your ear does to your
brain, but don't have time to hold it there for a few years to find
out?
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at England's Bristol University have the time. A
mobile phone will be placed next to the ear of a model of a human
head for two years to study what high-frequency radio signals do to
the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The July issue of Popular Mechanics magazine has that little
nugget. The magazine can also be reached online, at
www.popularmechanics.com.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the issue is a look at cell phones with Internet access
and a piece on how to goose your iMac so it is Windows-compatible.
</P>
<P>
   Ballparks.com offers a bit of sports-related nostalgia
</P>
<P>
   If you're a sports fan, stadiums and arenas are near-holy
places. If you're a sports fan older than 20, many of those
near-holy places are gone.
</P>
<P>
   A Web site called Ballparks.com is keeping the faith. The site,
www.ballparks
</P>
<P>
   .com, has photographs, trivia and details about old arenas and
ballparks from the major pro leagues of baseball, basketball,
hockey and football.
</P>
<P>
   For most ballparks, outdoor and indoor pictures are included.
The pages usually include interesting bits of trivia about each
stadium or arena. For example, who knew that Detroit's Tiger
Stadium has the only in-play flagpole in the major leagues?
</P>
<P>
   Even more worthwhile, the site has pictures _ sometimes
architectural drawings, sometimes construction images _ of new
stadiums and arenas, including Atlanta's Philips Arena and
Detroit's Comerica Park.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are links to official arena Web sites and official
ballpark Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Bubbly artwork for the stars _ and you
</P>
<P>
   Now you, too, thanks to the Internet, can own what Lily Tomlin,
RuPaul, Rosanna Arquette and Frank Zappa's family own.
</P>
<P>
   The artwork of Allee Willis, a Grammy Award-winning Southern
California songwriter and artist, is selling really campy art under
the name Bubbles. You can see and buy her work at
bubblestheartist.com.
</P>
<P>
   Her paintings, which can be bought from the Web site, range in
price from $65 to $250.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers a catalog of Bubbles' work, searchable by items
in the painting. You can search by hairstyles or for ``paintings
with eyeglasses,'' for example.
</P>
<P>
   As a songwriter, Willis wrote the theme song for the TV show,
``Friends,'' as well as ``September,'' which was performed by
Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire.
</P>
<P>
   The art of Bubbles the Artist is collected by Tomlin, Paul,
Arquette and several Zappas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-28-99 1105EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
