<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY29-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
If all else fails, think of the Web as tech support 
By Bill Husted  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's the world's good fortune that I am not an airline
pilot or a brain surgeon. I learn best after making a horrible
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Microsoft sent me its Windows 98 Update, and I
installed it on my home computer. Everything seemed to go OK
through the installation process, but when the installation was
over, everything on my screen looked as if it had been drawn in
crayon. The colors were way off.
</P>
<P>
   So I clicked on the desktop screen with the right mouse button,
selected Properties and then selected the Settings tab to check the
video setup, since something was obviously wrong with the way
Windows set up my video card. Sure enough, Windows hadn't found the
driver (drivers are the small programs used by your PC to control
various devices such as modems, video cards, sound cards, scanners
and the like). So it installed a generic driver that comes with
Windows and _ as a result _ my computer could only work in its
lowest setting for graphics: 16-color mode. That's like trading in
your Ferrari for a used Yugo.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, I figured. I'll get the floppy disk that includes
the installation program for my Matrox video card. Then it's a
simple matter of opening up the Add/Remove Hardware icon in the
Control Panel folder, putting the disk in my A: drive and telling
the PC to use the video driver on the floppy.
</P>
<P>
   I moved back in September, and things are still in disarray. I
pawed through about 10 boxes of floppy disks _ found some that
contained copy for ads that I wrote back in the 1980s when I worked
for advertising agencies, found disks with old short stories I
tried to write, found everything but the disk for my video card.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the computer still worked fine in 16-color mode. I
could see the screen, and the modem still worked. So I popped over
to the Web site for Matrox, downloaded the drivers for my video
card and was back in business.
</P>
<P>
   That's lesson No. 1 today. The Web is an 24-hour tech support
center. If you need a driver or an update to a program you own,
check the Web first. Most often, you'll find the address for the
Web site in the printed material that came with the product. But
even if it isn't listed there, you can almost certainly find the
address by using one of the search engines.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's move to lesson No. 2. If I had remembered this
lesson, I would have never needed lesson No. 1. Keep all your most
important disks _ the ones you'd need if you ever had to reinstall
Windows or if something goes wrong with your hard disk _ in one
spot. When you computer goes down, there's a natural sense of panic
anyway, and that's the worst time to start scattering the contents
of desk drawers around on a mad search. There will be times when
your computer won't work at all without the necessary disk, which
means you can't always depend on getting what you need from a Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson No. 3 caught me by surprise. When I finally found the
Matrox Web site I realized that, while I knew the name of the
manufacturer, I did not remember the specific model of video card
that I owned. Ordinarily, you could just pop over to the System
icon in the Control Panel folder and read the name under the
hardware section. But since Windows didn't recognize the card, that
option wasn't open to me.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't find the printed invoice that came with my computer,
nor could I find the manual for the video card. So that left me
with the option of opening up the computer to look on the video
card itself or tear into still another box of computer stuff.
Luckily, in this case Matrox has some generic drivers for idiots
such as myself _ these drivers work with all models of Matrox
cards.
</P>
<P>
   So my computer is up and running again. The new version of
Windows 98 is well-behaved. Things are in living color once again.
And I'm a little bit smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
