<SLUG> BC-PARTNERS-AIRLINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES APPEAL RULING ON UNMARRIED PARTNERS LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The nation's largest air carriers have appealed
a federal court ruling that upholds key portions of the San
Francisco law that calls for companies to provide equal benefits to
unmarried partners of employees.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Claudia Wilken ruled last month that
airlines flying in and out of San Francisco International Airport
must comply with certain mandates under the city's Equal Benefits
Ordinance, chiefly that when it comes to benefits, they must treat
their employees in domestic partnerships the same as those who are
married.
</P>
<P>
   That is the intent of San Francisco's ground-breaking Equal
Benefits Ordinance, which went into effect June 1, 1997, and covers
companies that do business with the city.
</P>
<P>
   Wilken excluded health and pension benefits from the requirement
for the airlines, saying only the federal government has
jurisdiction over those areas for the industry. But for other
perks, such as family and bereavement leave and flight discounts,
the law stands, she said. Other contractors outside the airline
industry must provide the same benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ordinance aims to fulfill in economic terms a promise
long-required in city contracts: that parties doing business with
the city not discriminate based on sexual orientation or marital
status,'' wrote Wilken, who is based in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines appealed the ruling Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are important policy issues for the airlines in terms of
who regulates the industry,'' said David Berg, a lawyer for the Air
Transport Association. The ATA, a trade organization for the
airlines, was joined by United Airlines and Federal Express in
suing to overturn the city law. Another contractor challenged the
law on moral grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Berg argues that local governments have no right to pass laws
that dictate how the airlines treat their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Aftergut, chief assistant city attorney and the lead
lawyer on the case for the city, said United Airlines seems to pick
and choose what local laws it chooses to follow. United, the
Chicago-base carrier that is owned by the UAL Corp., is the largest
carrier at San Francisco International Airport and has led the
fight against the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Jan. 11, 1999, United Airlines agreed to comply with Los
Angeles' living wage law,'' Aftergut said. ``Their spokesman said
they did so because the law was reasonable and it was in their
business interests to do so. Why isn't it reasonable and in their
business interests to provide these trivial-cost,
non-discriminatory benefits?''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how the Los Angeles living wage law, which sets a
minimum wage for city contractors, is different from San
Francisco's equal benefits law, Berg said the domestic partners
ordinance would be more administratively cumbersome for the
airlines. And, he added, ``From our perspective, or at least maybe
from United's perspective, living wage, or minimum wage, is
somewhat different. There's a stronger argument that this is
historically an area that is regulated by local jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the recent emergence of the living wage movement, however,
minimum wage has been in the jurisdiction of the federal
government, although states have been allowed to set a higher
standard. Cities rarely got involved.
</P>
<P>
   United spokesman Matthew Triaca declined to comment on the
appeal ``because of the sensitive nature of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists are boycotting United because of its stance on the
domestic partners law.
</P>
<P>
   The law takes effect when contracts between a company and the
city are renewed. United got into the fray when it negotiated a new
contract for a maintenance and kitchen facility at the airport, a
contract the city has threatened to sever because of non-compliance
with the domestic partners edict. Wilken has issued an order
forbidding the city to take action against United for the time
being, pending further court action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
