<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-SECURITY29-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Security systems offer comfort 
By Karen Dean  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Say the words ``home security'' and what comes to
mind?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you envision a few simple deadbolt locks. Perhaps you
picture elaborate laser beams and infrared sensors that would put
the CIA to shame. Then again, your idea of home security may be
faithful Bitsy, the ankle-chewing Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you picture it, Americans are becoming more
security-conscious, and the home security industry is thriving.
According to the National Burglar and Fire Alarm Association,
Americans spent an estimated $14.8 billion on professionally
installed electronic security products and services in 1997 alone.
By the end of 1998, more than 20 percent of households were
estimated to be electronically protected.
</P>
<P>
   The reason seems to be that electronic protection works. Studies
have shown that homes without the benefit of security systems are
two to three times more likely to be burglarized than those
equipped with them. Since burglary is one of the least likely
crimes to be solved, with a rate of only 13.4 percent solved
nationwide, an alarm system may be a comforting solution.
</P>
<P>
   So you think you might want to join the wired brigade? Well, the
good news is that you won't have to cash in that 401(k) to pay for
the system. With prices ranging from $150 for a no-frills system to
upward of six figures for an intricate network of video,
multiple-entry monitoring and infrared sensors, there's a system
for just about every budget.
</P>
<P>
   Before you hop in the car to scope out what's available, take a
look around your house. The easiest and cheapest home protection
comes in the form of sturdy locks and window pins. Even with an
alarm, a thief has a few moments before police arrive, so securing
those entry points can go a long way toward keeping your property
in the house, where it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of any effective security system is to deter, delay
and detect,'' says Officer Ginger Smith of the Gwinnett County,
Ga., Crime Prevention Unit. ``Visible decals and a good combination
of locks, sensors and audible alarms can make your home less
appealing to a burglar.''
</P>
<P>
   Security systems come in two basic forms: hard-wired versions
and battery-operated wireless systems. The hard-wired system links
the indoor sensors to a central control panel by wiring run through
the house. Wireless systems operate by tiny transistors contained
in the door and window sensors that send radio frequencies to a
main control box. During an attempted break-in, either system sends
a message from the sensors to the main control board, activating
the alarm.
</P>
<P>
   While many industry experts continue to feel that hard-wired
systems are more reliable, the wireless alternatives are gaining
popularity and may be more practical in homes without ready access
to interior wiring, such as in an unfinished basement.
</P>
<P>
   Before deciding on any system, experts suggest you consider your
lifestyle and needs. Living with an alarm system requires
adjustments, like remembering to arm and disarm the alarm when
leaving or returning home. Children or indoor pets can make certain
alarms or motion sensors a nightmare to deal with, so you may need
a program with customizing options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many one-size-fits-all systems give a false sense of security
for the homeowner,'' says Jim Callahan of Ackerman Security. ``The
best choice is to have a trained consultant view your home with
you. The choice of options is still yours, but a professional
designer can make recommendations to best utilize the system for
your home.''
</P>
<P>
   Most alarm systems provide perimeter sensors that guard doors
and windows. You can then purchase additional sensors that offer
protection in case an intruder gets inside the house. Motion
detectors are often used to detect motion or heat changes in a
room, which trigger the alarm. Passive infrared motion sensors work
by detecting increases in temperature. But dual-technology sensors
are available that detect motion and heat simultaneously and may
reduce your risk of false alarms.
</P>
<P>
   When you finally decide on a system, you're not limited to
professional installation. The ``let me do it'' syndrome has
reached the security industry as well, and several local companies
offer products and advice for those willing to tackle the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``A knowledgeable do-it-yourselfer can often do as good a job as
many professional installers,'' says Craig Degrenier of
DeKalb-Gwinnett Alarm Co.
</P>
<P>
   A basic self-installed hard-wired system with control panel,
motion detector and three door-and-window sensors can be bought for
as little as $189, with extra window and door sensors for around $5
each and additional motion detectors starting at $30 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless components require a lot less effort to install and
about as much electronics knowledge as setting up a stereo. Place
your door and window sensors, set up for monitoring, and you're
ready to go. Plus, when you're ready to move, the system can be
packed up along with the dishes and taken to your new home.
Retailers such as Radio Shack, Home Depot and Lowe's sell the
wireless components, with prices starting at $150 for a console,
sensors for four doors or windows and a motion detector.
</P>
<P>
   A word of caution for budding do-it-yourselfers, though. Placing
the sensors correctly can make the difference between a
well-functioning alarm and one that consistently cries wolf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that magnetic contacts and motion detectors be
set and aimed accurately,'' says Bill Zelud, editor of Security
Distributing Magazine, an industry guide. ``Failing to place those
correctly can compromise the effectiveness of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you have made your choice _ hard-wired or wireless _ you're
left with the decision of whether to have the system monitored.
Monitoring is an optional cost, but many industry insiders feel
it's critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monitoring is the backbone and what makes the whole system
work,'' says Bruce Goldberg of Brinks. ``That's what guarantees a
quick response to your alarm.''
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring company receives and verifies an alarm, then
notifies the appropriate law enforcement agency. With an
unmonitored audible alarm, you're relying on your neighbors to
finally get tired of hearing that noise and call the police. By
that time, your favorite VCR could be occupying the top shelf in
Bub's Pawn Palace.
</P>
<P>
   While many monitoring companies welcome self-installed
hard-wired systems, not all are so receptive. Many larger
companies, such as Ackerman, Brinks and ADT, will not monitor
systems that were not professionally installed because of concerns
regarding installation procedures or the risk of increased false
alarms.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring is also available for wireless components, with many
retailers offering services when you purchase your system. The
monitoring fees typically are $20 a month and up, often available
without a long-term commitment. But whether hard-wired or wireless,
shopping around in the competitive Atlanta market often results in
a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   Beside providing peace of mind, there may also be a bonus to
your wallet for having a home-security system. Many insurers offer
discounts up to 20 percent to policyholders with security systems.
However, monitoring or professional installation may be required
for the discount to apply, so check with your agent before spending
those savings.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever choice you make, the knowledge of an extra watchful
eye guarding your home and family can give you some added
assurances of safety. And give Bitsy a well-deserved rest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-28-99 1103EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
