<SLUG> BC-CPT-MAC-REPORT29-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Canvas combines graphics applications 
By Charles Haddad  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Canvas is the ClarisWorks of graphics programs. It
tries to integrate in one package all the elements of layout,
drawing and design.
</P>
<P>
   That's a tall order but, at least for beginners and intermediate
users, Canvas succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   But neither I nor most other reviewers would recommend this
program for pros and high-end graphics users. Professionals are
better off using Illustrator, Photoshop and Macromedia for the
specialized tasks these programs were created to do.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say Canvas is a bad program. On the contrary, it
has many strong features. Version 6.0, the latest, offers some big
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   No program, for starters, can combine vector and bitmapped
graphics as well as Canvas. It treats all types of graphic images
as objects, which you can mix easily.
</P>
<P>
   Another Canvas innovation is a technology called SpriteLayers.
This lets you layer various graphic objects, whether text, vector
or bitmapped, with full control over transparency.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive transparency feature is one called Channel
Mask. It lets you apply opacity variations using any of Canvas'
many paintbrushes. Just paint an area of a graphic to make it
transparent.
</P>
<P>
   With a graphics program, it's easy to get overwhelmed by
floating palettes. That was certainly true with earlier versions of
Canvas. But Version 6.0 has gone a long way toward cleaning up its
interface.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can customize Canvas' toolbar, adding just the buttons
and keyboard shortcuts of any feature used most often.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet is the docking bar, which appears just below the
toolbar at the top of the screen. You can drag any palette to the
docking bar, where it will appear for use. Just click on the
palette name, and it drops down for use.
</P>
<P>
   Other improvements include a spelling checker and vastly
improved performance in terms of speed. Even large images can be
handled quickly now.
</P>
<P>
   In conclusion, MacWorld magazine recommended that all current
Canvas users upgrade to Canvas 6.0, the first new version in three
years. ``The new transparency features and bitmap performance
improvements alone are worth the price,'' said the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Canvas, published by Deneba in Miami, retails for $350. An
upgrade is about $100 less. To learn more about the program, check
out the company's Web site at www.deneba.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-28-99 1102EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
