 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Home Depot improves website for advice-seekers 
By Patti Bond  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Do-it-yourselfers will find a heap of help on Home
Depot's remodeled Web site today.
</P>
<P>
   The home improvement giant was expected to launch a new version
of www.homedepot.com this morning. There aren't products for sale
yet, but the ramped-up site lays the groundwork for online sales
that will start in the fall, said Jeff Cohen, group president of
direct marketing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We`re taking the continuous improvement path with our Internet
strategy,'' Cohen said. ``The new site is a major step.'' Cohen
said the site will be updated every three to four weeks with new
features.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference is that the Web site, previously filled
with corporate and shareholder information, has been reworked to
target consumers looking for home improvement advice. The number of
how-to projects was doubled to 120, and each project includes
do-it-yourself steps that are animated with simple graphics that
can be downloaded quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The how-to pages, which include printable lists of supplies and
tools needed to tackle the project, will be a likely starting point
for Home Depot's first attempt at online sales, Cohen said. For
example, a consumer looking for tips on how to change a lock or
install a ceiling fan could have the option of buying a kit to do
so, he said. It's the first hint from Home Depot on what it might
sell online as the company works out pricing and shopping issues.
In the meantime, the supply lists should at least send consumers
running to their nearest Home Depot store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Projects are certainly the centerpiece of our Internet
strategy,'' said Cohen, who noted that the company opted not to
create a separate subsidiary for the electronic commerce venture.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance Warehouse, Home Depot's mail-order subsidiary in San
Diego, will process orders, phone calls and e-mail requests
generated by the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The new site contains twice the amount of information of the old
site, including new features such as paint and wallpaper
calculators that estimate the amount of materials needed based on
room dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the company's electronic commerce launch this
fall, though, may be one of the more significant aspects of its
strategy. Several competitors have already ventured into online
sales.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. recently started selling major
appliances and tools on www.sears.com. And Lowe's Home Improvement
Warehouse sells some tools and other branded products through
manufacturer's sites. Lowe's expects to start selling products on
www.lowes.com in late summer, said spokesman Brian Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
