</P>
<P>
   B-2 _ A general in charge of the nation's B-2 bomber wing
testifies before Congress about the success of the expensive and
controversial stealth bomber over Yugoslavia. Kevin Murphy. 20.
</P>
<P>
   KCSKUL: Kansas City school board votes on a contract for Jay
Edwards, the new superintendent. Edwards also is in town to meet
with the Desegregation Monitoring Committee. Tanika White and other
staff. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARY: Independence, Mo., chiropractor Gary Edwards denies
allegations that he had claimed he was eliminating the AIDS virus
in a north-central Missouri man. The state board of chiropractic
examiners has charged Edwards with misconduct, negligence and
incompetence. This is the first time Edwards has spoken in his
defense. Will Sentell. 20 inches. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TEACH: Missouri and other states get millions more dollars to
hire more teachers to reduce class sizes. Lee Hill Kavanaugh.
Possible graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHERN. Nine-year-old Tonya Khvitko was born in Russia with one
leg that ended at the ankle and one that ended above the knee, the
result of radioactivity from the Chernobyl power plant. Two years
ago, she came to the Kansas City area for prosthetic limbs. Now
she's back so doctors can adjust her prosthetics, thanks to Project
Restoration, a nonprofit group started by a Merriam, Kan., woman.
Stacy Downs. 18. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGE. The 151st Street bridge over I-35 in Olathe, Kan., has
serious problems and may need a $3 million fix; kind of steep for a
bridge that cost less than $4 million when it opened in 1994; seems
the bridge, which sits on rockers to allow for expansion and
contraction, is being pushed by slippage in its abutments;
engineers fear the bridge won't be able to handle normal stresses
if it slips much more. Robert A. Cronkleton. Graphic, Photos.
</P>
<P>
   DRIVE. Whenever a car leaves the driveway at the Trigg house in
rural Gardner, Kan., chances are that 15-year-old Whitney Trigg
will be behind the wheel, with either her mom or dad riding
shotgun. If Whitney wants to drive by herself when she turns 16,
that's the way it has to be. Effective today, Kansas law requires
that 16- and 17-year-olds must have at least 50 hours of
adult-supervised driving experience to qualify for an unrestricted
license. Tom Perrin. 20. Photos.
</P>
