<HEADER>
A4558 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE01-COX     06-30 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For summer fun, invite the kids into the kitchen
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many busy parents have spent months planning activities to keep
children supervised and amused during the summer. Camps, water
parks, amusement parks, sports, countless day trips and logistical
concerns have been planned down to the micro-minute when the school
bell will ring again.
</P>
<P>
   With all that planning, it's possible that parents are
overlooking one of the most interesting activities of all _ and
it's right under our noses, and free. It's the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   So often the primary cook for a busy family just wants to get
the meal onto the table and tends to shoo pesky youngsters out of
the kitchen during the business of preparing a meal.
</P>
<P>
   Summer, when there is no homework and more leisure time,
presents an excellent opportunity to invite the kids into the
kitchen to share the wonders of preparing food, as well as some
first-class quality time.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, an Internet search for ``kids in the
kitchen,'' ``cooking with kids'' and ``kids' recipes'' yielded all
kinds of sites. Some were superficial, with an emphasis on ``fun''
and silly recipes for things like ``Monster Glop.'' With this
approach, a child could get the idea that the kitchen is just an
annex of Toys ``R'' Us instead of the place where one of the most
vital of human activities takes place.
</P>
<P>
   Imparting an appreciation of the kitchen and cookery should
start with letting children help in preparing real food for real
people. There'll be plenty of time for fun.
</P>
<P>
   Why not select a dish most children naturally love and then do a
little homework yourself?
</P>
<P>
   Take pizza, for instance. While they're helping shred the
cheese, you can tell them that genuine mozzarella cheese is made
from the milk of the water buffalo. This and other spellbinding
pizza tidbits can be found at www.ghgcorp.com
</P>
<P>
   /coyej/links.htm.
</P>
<P>
   While the kids are spreading the sauce, you can relate the tale
told at chefexpress.com/history.htm of how pizza got its colors. It
seems that Neapolitan pizza was just plain, flat peasant bread
until it caught the eye of Queen Margherita, who summoned baker
Raffaele Esposito to make some especially for her. To honor the
queen, he garnished the dough with the colors of the Italian flag _
red (the tomato sauce), white (the cheese) and green (basil) _
resulting in something like the pizza we know today.
</P>
<P>
   For hundreds of creative pizza recipes using everything from
artichokes to spinach, call up godzilla.eecs.berkeley
</P>
<P>
   .edu/recipes/pizza/indexall.html.
</P>
<P>
   Some other sites you may want to check are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  members.aol.com/TchrfromOz
</P>
<P>
   /fashion.html _ A History of Fashion, Food, Fun and
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.gourmetspot.com
</P>
<P>
   /foodsatoz.htm _ Epicurious Food Dictionary, Food from A-Z.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.sof.com/believeit
</P>
<P>
   /frame-encyclopedia.html _ The Encyclopedia of Food.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the better cooking-with-kids sites we found include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  members.aol.com/sgrmagnlia
</P>
<P>
   /index.html _ ``Cooking With Young Children'' is aimed at
parents looking for tips.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.mcgees.com/kitchen/kidstuff
</P>
<P>
   .htm _ If you're into the ``Monster Glop'' approach, ``Kids
Stuff'' offers fairly decent recipes with annoying names.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.kitchenlink.com/cgi
</P>
<P>
   /publicframes?page &QC; rcpkids offers plenty of links to
kids-in-the-kitchen sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  suite101.com/welcome.cfm
</P>
<P>
   /kidsinthekitchen _ ``Kids in the Kitchen'' is a well-done site
for older children.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  kidscook.com/kidscook.htm _ ``The Kids Cooking Club'' features
monthly cooking projects. There are membership fees.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pop-Up Pizza
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 25 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour
</P>
<P>
   For the filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped green pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce can tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 1 1/2-ounce package dry spaghetti sauce mix
</P>
<P>
   For the batter:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon oil
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Assembly:
</P>
<P>
   7 or 8 ounces sliced Monterey Jack or mozzarella cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: In a large skillet, brown ground beef and
drain. Stir in onion, green pepper, garlic, oregano, salt, water,
hot pepper sauce, tomato sauce and spaghetti sauce mix; cover and
simmer on low about 10 minutes, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   For the batter: In a bowl, combine milk, oil and eggs; beat 1
minute on medium speed. Add flour and salt; beat 2 minutes or until
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Pour hot meat mixture into 13-by-9-inch pan. Top
with cheese slices. Pour batter over cheese, covering filling
completely. Sprinkle with Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 25 to 30 minutes, or until puffed and brown.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 434 calories, 31 grams protein, 25 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 51), 21 grams carbohydrates, 148
milligrams cholesterol, 1,080 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
