<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4559 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-ICECREAM-SANDWIC     06-30 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ICECREAM-SANDWICH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In summer, nothing's more pleasing than the classic combination
of sweet, crunchy baked goods and frozen delights
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mammaw had a charge account at Ragsdale's Grocery, the kind of
small-town corner store that sold everything from Sweetarts to
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for me and a clattering bunch of kids who lived on that
end of Kuttawa, that was where the school bus stopped. On many
sunny Kentucky afternoons, I'd rush into Ragsdale's, head straight
to the freezer chest, snatch up an ice cream sandwich and shout,
``Charge it to Mammaw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ragsdales were masters at keeping all the Mammaws and Mommas
straight, as evidenced by the stack of charge slips my grandmother
would sometimes present to me and my brothers with slightly stern
admonishments about spending.
</P>
<P>
   But it was hard to resist such a sweet reward after a tough day
at school. There's hardly a more classic, comforting combination
than cookies and cream, whether you dunk some warm chocolate chip
cookies into a tall glass of milk or munch on an ice cold sandwich
of soft chocolate wafers and smooth vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many people are probably more used to getting their
cookies and cream in one fell scoop _ many ice cream brands report
that the ``cookies and cream flavor'' is among their top five
sellers. But as we head into the high ice cream season (July is
National Ice Cream Month), we can't resist trying some new
combinations and reviving some old favorites.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a special treat for the holiday weekend, get the ice
cream maker cranking now on some white chocolate ice cream, and
then sandwich it between orange-flavored chocolate cookies and
freeze for a day or so. Dreamy.
</P>
<P>
   Or try old-fashioned ginger-molasses cookies with vanilla ice
cream (for an extra punch, spike the ice cream with ginger, too).
Break out the star-shaped cookie cutters for an Independence Day
flair.
</P>
<P>
   If you're expecting a crowd and want to get a head start, you
can do no better than the classic icebox cake, which marries thin
chocolate wafers with whipped cream. After a couple of days of
mingling in the refrigerator, you get a cake so heavenly that folks
will claim angels delivered it from above.
</P>
<P>
   With just a few assembly skills and a little imagination, you
can create your own combinations with your choices from the cookie
aisle and the ice cream freezer. There are so many great ice cream
flavors, from rich caramel dulce de leche to the funky Chunky
Monkey, that there's no end to the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   And they're so easy to assemble that you can have cookies and
cream ready and waiting in your freezer throughout the hot months
ahead. After all, the two go together like summer and fun.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK TREATS
</P>
<P>
   With all the choices available in grocery stores these days, the
list of possibilities for quick-fix cookies-and-cream concoctions
is as long as the grocery aisle. Just crumble your favorite cookies
and mix them into a complementary softened ice cream, then refreeze
until you're ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can make a cookies-and-cream milkshake: Pour a cup of
milk, two to four scoops of ice cream and two to four broken
cookies into a blender and give it a whirl.
</P>
<P>
   Or make your own ice cream sandwiches. We cruised the cookie and
ice cream selections at a couple of Atlanta-area grocery stores and
came up with these combinations just to get you started:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Archway Oatmeal Cookies with dulce de leche or pralines and
cream ice cream. These large, flat, soft cookies are the perfect
discs for sandwich making. Dulce de leche is the cool, new,
ultracreamy caramel flavor of the summer _ Haagen-Dazs, Breyer's
and Starbucks all have versions of it. Many praline-flavored ice
creams have crunchy, sugar-coated nuts, which will add extra
texture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pepperidge Farm Chocolate White Chocolate Chunk Cookies with a
Godiva dark chocolate ice cream. The Pepperidge Farm chocolate
chunk cookies are nicely shaped and freeze well. Godiva has a new
line of chocolate ice creams that are as rich as you'd expect.
Together, these make a pretty high-class pair.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keebler's Fudge Stripe Cookies with Ben &AMP; Jerry's Chunky
Monkey ice cream. The fudge stripe cookies have an ideal thickness;
the only trick is to put the striped side on the inside of the
sandwich. The ice cream slips off the side that's all fudge. The
banana flavor in the Chunky Monkey, or other banana-flavored ice
creams, makes banana splits finger food.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gingersnaps with lemon sorbet or black cherry frozen yogurt.
Choose any brand of thick, old-fashioned gingersnaps and pair them
with a lemon sorbet or Mayfield's black cherry frozen yogurt for a
quick, refreshing and low-fat treat. This will quickly become a
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pillsbury's slice-and-bake Peanut Butter Cookies and milk
chocolate or fudge swirl ice cream. We especially like this combo
with Breyer's chocolate ice cream with fudge swirls.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
