<HEADER>
A4560 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPE2NDTAKE01-     06-30 1700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPE2NDTAKE01-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Coffee Liqueur Cream Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes Chilling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Freezing time: 1 hour; then overnight
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if there are enough rapturous words to describe
this pie, at least as far as this chocolate and coffee ice cream
lover is concerned. It's simple, should be made ahead, and is best
served with a light meal, because it's heavy. And heavenly.
</P>
<P>
   24 chocolate sandwich cookies (such as Oreos), crushed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 quart chocolate ice cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coffee liqueur, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 cup toffee candy bars, crushed (such as Hershey's Nuggets)
</P>
<P>
   1 quart vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sweetened whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Mix crushed cookies with butter and press into a deep 9-inch pie
pan. Chill for 30 minutes. Stir chocolate ice cream to soften and
blend in 1/4 cup coffee liqueur. Spoon into pie shell; carefully
spread to the edges. Sprinkle with crushed candy bars and place in
freezer 1 hour. Soften vanilla ice cream and add 1/4 cup coffee
liqueur. Spoon over the chocolate mixture and carefully spread to
the edges. Freeze overnight. Garnish by piping whipped cream around
the pie. Cut into wedges and serve with a drizzle of coffee liqueur
over the top. _ From: The Culinary Connection (www.culinary.com)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 655 calories, 7 grams protein, 38 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 68 grams carbohydrates, 112
milligrams cholesterol, 379 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   White Chocolate Orange
</P>
<P>
   Frozen Dream Creams
</P>
<P>
   Makes 48 mini-sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Freezing time: 20 minutes, then overnight
</P>
<P>
   Chef Marcel Desauliners was inspired by the Good Humor
Creamsicle when he created these dream creams. Don't be daunted by
the lengthy directions; he's very detailed, but the methods are
easy and the effort well worth it for the white chocolate ice cream
alone. You may choose to use the orange syrup to taste. This recipe
makes mini-sandwiches _ if you want to make larger ones, divide
dough into three sections rather than six.
</P>
<P>
   For the ice cream:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup julienned orange zest
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces white chocolate, chopped in 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups whole milk, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   4 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   For the cookies:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound (2 sticks) unsalted butter, cut in 1-ounce pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced orange zest
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon orange liqueur
</P>
<P>
   For the ice cream: Heat the orange juice, 1/2 cup granulated
sugar and orange zest in a 3-quart saucepan over medium-high heat.
When hot, stir to dissolve the sugar. Bring to a boil. Allow to
boil for 20 minutes until syrupy. Transfer to a 4-quart bowl and
cool in an ice-water bath to a temperature of 40 to 45 degrees,
about 10 minutes. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate until
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 inch of water in the bottom half of a double boiler over
medium heat. With the heat on, place the white chocolate and 1 cup
of the milk in the top half of the double boiler. Use a rubber
spatula to stir until completely melted and smooth, about 7 to 8
minutes. Transfer the mixture to a 1-quart bowl and set aside until
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining milk, heavy cream and 1/4 cup granulated
sugar in a 3-quart saucepan over medium-high heat. Stir to dissolve
the sugar. Bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   While the cream mixture is heating, place the egg yolks and the
remaining 1/4 cup granulated sugar in the bowl of an electric mixer
fitted with a paddle. Beat on high 2 minutes. Use a rubber spatula
to scrape down the sides of the bowl, then beat on high until
slightly thickened and lemon-colored, 2 1/2 to 3 minutes. Timing is
important. If at this point the cream has not yet started to boil,
adjust the mixer speed to low and continue to mix until it does
boil. If the eggs are not mixed until the point when the boiling
cream is added, undesirable lumps may form.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the boiling cream into the beaten egg yolks and whisk to
combine. Return to the saucepan and heat over medium-high heat,
stirring constantly. Bring to a temperature of 185 degrees, about 1
minute. Remove from the heat and transfer to a 4-quart bowl. Add
the melted white chocolate mixture and stir to combine. Cool in an
ice-water bath to a temperature of 40 to 45 degrees, about 20
minutes. When the mixture is cold, freeze in an ice cream freezer
according to manufacturer's instructions. Transfer the semifrozen
ice cream to a 2-quart plastic container. Use a rubber spatula to
fold in the chilled orange mixture until thoroughly combined.
Securely cover the container, then place in the freezer for several
hours before assembling the ice cream sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   For the cookies: In a sifter combine the flour, cocoa powder,
salt and baking soda. Sift onto a large piece of wax paper and set
aside until needed.
</P>
<P>
   Place the butter, 1/2 cup granulated sugar and the brown sugar
in the bowl of an electric mixer fitted with a paddle. Beat on
medium for 4 minutes until fairly smooth. Use a rubber spatula to
scrape down the sides of the bowl. Beat on high 2 minutes until
smooth. Scrape down the bowl again. Add the eggs, one at a time,
while beating on medium for 1 minute and scraping down the sides of
the bowl after each addition. Add the minced orange zest and orange
liqueur and beat on high 1 minute. Operate the mixer on low while
gradually adding the sifted dry ingredients until incorporated,
about 1 minute. Remove the bowl from the mixer and use a rubber
spatula to finish mixing the dough until thoroughly combined.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the dough to a clean, dry, lightly floured work
surface. Divide the dough into 6 equal portions, and shape each
into a log approximately 10 inches long, 1 1/2 inches wide and 3/4
inch high. Tightly wrap each log in plastic wrap. Refrigerate the
logs for 4 hours until dough is very firm.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the dough from the refrigerator and discard the plastic
wrap. Use a sharp serrated knife to cut each log into 16 slices
1/4-inch thick. Arrange the slices on 4 nonstick baking sheets.
Bake the cookies on the top and center racks of the preheated oven
for 6 minutes until slightly dry in appearance, rotating the sheets
from top to center halfway through baking time (at that time also
turn each sheet 180 degrees). Remove the cookies from the oven and
cool to room temperature on the baking sheets, about 20 minutes.
The cookies may be stored in a tightly sealed plastic container
until you are ready to assemble the ice cream sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Place half the cookies on wax paper (makes cleaning
up a snap). Using a tablespoon, portion white chocolate orange ice
cream onto each of the cookies and then top with a second cookie.
Gently press, then smooth edges with spatula. Wrap 3 to 4 at a time
in plastic wrap. Then place all wrapped cookies in an airtight
container and freeze overnight. _ From: ``Death by Chocolate
Cookies,'' Marcel Desauliners (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 131 calories, 2 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 52), 14 grams carbohydrates, 55 milligrams
cholesterol, 72 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Coffee and Cream
</P>
<P>
   Icebox Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 1 to 2 days
</P>
<P>
   The Nabisco Famous Wafer Roll was so famous for so many years
that you won't find the thin chocolate wafers in the cookie aisle
but on the shelf near the ice cream and frozen foods where the ice
cream toppings are found. To be safe, buy two boxes of cookies,
because some break. This variation adds coffee and hazelnuts. It's
best sliced after 2 days in the refrigerator. Divine.
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon instant espresso powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   44 Nabisco Famous Chocolate Wafers
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped, toasted hazelnuts for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup crushed chocolate wafer cookie crumbs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Lightly grease a 6-cup loaf pan. Line the pan with two pieces of
overlapping plastic wrap, allowing the excess to hang over the
edges of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, combine the cream, espresso powder and sugar. Whisk
until the cream holds firm peaks. Spoon about 2/3 of the whipped
cream into the prepared pan. Tap the pan firmly on the counter to
even the cream and eliminate any air bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at a short side (width) of the pan, arrange cookies in
the cream, standing them on their edge in a row like dominoes.
Stand them close together, leaving about 1/4 inch space in between
them. Do the same with a second row of cookies, slightly
overlapping the cookies from the second row with the cookies in the
first row. Continue until you run out of room.
</P>
<P>
   Press down on the cookies gently. Cover them with the remaining
cream. Smooth the cream with a spatula, gently pressing to make
sure any gaps between the cookies are filled. Tap the pan on the
counter several times to eliminate any air pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the cake with the excess plastic wrap and refrigerate at
least 24 hours, preferably 2 days. When ready to serve, peel the
plastic wrap from the top and gently tug on the plastic to loosen
the cake from sides of the pan. Set a cutting board on top of the
pan and invert the cake onto the board. Lift the pan off and gently
peel away the plastic wrap. Mix the hazelnuts with the cookie
crumbs and sprinkle over the top of the cake. Slice carefully with
a warm knife. _ From: Fine Cooking, June/July 1999
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 225 calories, 2 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 62), 20 grams carbohydrates, 50
milligrams cholesterol, 85 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
