<HEADER>
A4561 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPES1STTAKE01     06-30 1628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPES1STTAKE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ice cream sandwiches a little bite of heaven
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers or Humphrey Bogart and
Lauren Bacall.
</P>
<P>
   Some partners were made for each other, like cookies and cream.
Combinations like chocolate cookies and coffee-flavored whipped
cream or white chocolate ice cream and orange-flavored chocolate
wafers.
</P>
<P>
   We offer all sorts of possibilities for combining cookies and
cream below, including pie, cake and ice cream sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Ice cream sandwiches, in particular, can be a nice treat on a
hot summer day. They can be a little tricky to assemble, so our
best advice is to experiment until you get what you want.
</P>
<P>
   One idea is to simply spread slightly softened ice cream onto
cookies and sandwich. Gently press, smooth edges with a spatula,
wrap individually in plastic wrap and then freeze in an airtight
container.
</P>
<P>
   Some other ideas: Use a spatula to sculpt scoops of ice cream
into flat rounds approximately the same diameter of the cookies,
then freeze them into discs before sandwiching them between
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Or use a pastry bag to pipe softened ice cream onto flat sides
of cookies. Then wrap and freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Give it a try with some of these recipes below or with your
favorite store-bought cookies and ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Grasshopper Ice Cream Sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   Makes 15 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes Refrigeration time: 1 hour Freezing
time: 2 to 4 hours, divided Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The next time the kids scream for ice cream, break out these
mint-and-chocolate-flavored ice cream sandwiches, named for a
famous cocktail. But these are even better.
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon each baking soda and salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups quick-cooking rolled oats
</P>
<P>
   1 quart (approximately) mint chocolate chip or mint chocolate
ripple ice cream
</P>
<P>
   1 square (1 ounce) semisweet baking chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   For cookies: In a medium bowl, sift together flour, cocoa,
baking soda and salt; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In mixer bowl, combine butter and sugar; beat until fluffy. Beat
in egg yolk. Add vanilla and mix to blend.
</P>
<P>
   Add flour mixture alternately with the water, blending until
smooth after each addition. Stir in rolled oats. Cover dough with
plastic film and refrigerate until firm (about 1 hour).
</P>
<P>
   With an ice cream scoop, place 15 mounds of ice cream onto
baking sheet. Flatten each with spatula to a 3-inch round. Freeze
ice cream until solid, 1 to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. On a lightly floured board or
pastry cloth, roll out dough to a thickness of about 1/8 inch. Cut
out cookies with a 2 1/2-inch-diameter cutter. Transfer to
ungreased baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until cookies are barely firm when touched lightly, 8 to 10
minutes. Let stand on baking sheets for 1 to 2 minutes, then remove
to wire racks to cool.
</P>
<P>
   While cookies are cooling, melt semisweet chocolate with oil in
a small, heavy pan over low heat. Over half the cookies, drizzle
melted chocolate from the tip of a teaspoon or from a cone made
from aluminum foil or parchment paper. Set cookies aside until
chocolate is firm.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble sandwiches, place plain cookies, flat sides up, in
rows on a shallow-rimmed baking sheet. Place an ice cream round
atop each. Top each with a chocolate-drizzled cookie and press
together gently. Return to freezer until solidly frozen, 1 to 2
hours. Individually wrap sandwiches in foil; freeze for up to 2
months. _ From: Primary Color
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 229 calories, 4 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 29 grams carbohydrates, 47
milligrams cholesterol, 148 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Ice Cream Sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 35-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A takeoff on the classic chocolate wafer/vanilla ice cream
sandwich, these have been fancied up with chocolate and coffee
sauces for a special plated dessert.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces bittersweet chocolate, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons strong brewed coffee, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 pints good-quality coffee ice cream
</P>
<P>
   For the chocolate sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup plus 1 tablespoon unsweetened cocoa, sifted
</P>
<P>
   For the coffee sauce:
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup brewed espresso
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cup plus 2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325 degrees. Butter a 10-by-15-inch rimmed
baking sheet and line with parchment paper. Butter the paper and
refrigerate until the butter is firm, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, melt the butter and chocolate over low
heat, stirring occasionally. Let cool.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, beat the sugar and egg until blended. Beat in
the coffee, vanilla and melted chocolate. Sift together the flour,
cocoa, baking powder, cinnamon and salt. Stir the dry ingredients
into the chocolate mixture until combined. Spread the batter out to
the edges of the baking sheet in an even layer; smooth the top.
Bake for about 15 minutes, or until the center is just set but not
dry. Let the chocolate wafer cool in the pan for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Run a knife around the edge of the wafer. Cover the pan with a
cutting board and invert; peel off the paper. Let the wafer cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the chocolate wafer in half to form two 7 1/2-by-10-inch
rectangles. Spread the ice cream evenly on one of the rectangles
and cover with the other. Poke a few holes in the top with a fork
or a toothpick for decoration. Wrap the ice cream sandwich in
plastic wrap and freeze until firm, at least 2 hours. The ice cream
sandwich can be frozen for up to 2 days.
</P>
<P>
   For the chocolate sauce: In a small saucepan, melt the butter in
the cream and milk over moderate heat. Stir in the sugar and boil,
stirring occasionally, until slightly thickened, about 3 minutes.
Remove from the heat and whisk in the cocoa until smooth. The sauce
can be refrigerated for up to 2 days. Rewarm before serving.
</P>
<P>
   For the coffee sauce: In a small saucepan, combine the coffee
and sugar over low heat. Stir occasionally until sugar dissolves.
Increase heat to medium-high and boil for 5 to 8 minutes, until the
syrup is slightly thickened and coats the back of a spoon. Remove
from the heat; the sauce will continue to thicken as it cools.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, cut the ice cream sandwich into 8 triangles. Drizzle
the coffee sauce in a spiral on 8 dessert plates. Set an ice cream
sandwich in the center of each and spoon the warm chocolate sauce
on top. _ From: Food &AMP; Wine, September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 640 calories, 7 grams protein, 32 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 89 grams carbohydrates, 127
milligrams cholesterol, 278 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Ice Cream and Ginger Molasses Cookie Sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40 minutes Chilling time: 3 hours Cooking
time: 15 minutes Cooling time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   These ginger-molasses cookies make for delicious sandwiches.
They are very large and filling _ you can make smaller cookies and
more sandwiches if you prefer. We used our star-shaped cookie
cutters for more festive presentation.
</P>
<P>
   For the cookies:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable shortening, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup firmly packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsulfured (light) molasses
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the sandwiches:
</P>
<P>
   1 pint vanilla ice cream, softened slightly
</P>
<P>
   Fresh strawberries, hulled, sliced
</P>
<P>
   For the cookies: Sift together flour, baking soda, ginger,
cinnamon, cloves and salt into a medium bowl. In a large bowl,
combine butter, shortening and brown sugar. Using electric mixer,
beat butter mixture until fluffy. Add egg, molasses and peel; beat
until blended. Add dry ingredients; mix just until incorporated.
Cover; chill 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Butter or spray 2 baking sheets.
Place sugar in small bowl. Using wet hands, form dough into 12
equal pieces; shape pieces into balls. Roll in sugar to coat.
Transfer to prepared sheets, spacing 2 1/2 inches apart. Bake until
cookies are pale golden and cracked on top but still soft, about 15
minutes. Cool on sheets 1 minute. Transfer to racks; cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   For the sandwiches: Place ice cream in medium bowl. Place 6
cookies on work surface, flat side up. Top each with 1/3 cup ice
cream. Spread to 1/4 inch from edge of cookies. Top each with
second cookie. Press to adhere. Place in freezer. Freeze until
firm, at least 2 hours. Can be made 1 day ahead. Wrap tightly; keep
frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange sandwiches on plates. Garnish with berries and serve. _
From: Bon Appetit, March 1996
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 697 calories, 7 grams protein, 30 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 39), 103 grams carbohydrates, 97
milligrams cholesterol, 735 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
