A4562 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP01-COX     06-30 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little extras add spice to cheese soup
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Donna Murphy asked for a beer cheese soup like one she
enjoyed in the mid-'80s at the former Caperni's in Smyrna (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Several readers, including Pam Mulholland, sent their recipes.
Most called for beer, Velveeta cheese and cream. Mulholland's has
the extras of finely chopped onions, celery, carrots and peppers.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Velvet Beer Cheese Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 cup minced celery
</P>
<P>
   1 cup minced or grated carrots
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced green pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced red pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups beer (or chicken broth)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds Velveeta cheese, cut in 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a large Dutch oven, melt the butter. Saute the onions,
celery, carrots and pepper until limp, about 8 minutes. In a large
saucepan, heat the beer, half-and-half and milk over medium-high
heat, but do not bring to a boil. Stir the flour into the
vegetables and mix well. Add the boiling water to the vegetable
mixture and stir well. Slowly add the milk mixture and stir well.
Add the cheese. Reduce heat to low and stir until cheese melts.
Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 522 calories, 23 grams protein, 38 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 66), 23 grams carbohydrates, 105
milligrams cholesterol, 1,652 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mark Spieler asks for a reprint of Orange Mini Chocolate Chip
Cookies he said ran in this newspaper several years ago. A search
of the archives did not turn up the recipe, so we're hoping that if
it did run here, a reader clipped it and will share it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beverley Wesley is looking for Victorian Ribbon Cake for her
son's December wedding. She said it has two spice layers and one
yellow layer with an apple filling. She'd also like to know the
origin of the cake.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mary Beth Kyle has searched for years for the recipe for a
dark, chewy, spicy cookie called Spice Fruit Cookies made at
Dewey's Bakery in Winston-Salem, N.C. They include finely chopped
coconut, raisins, molasses, loads of ginger, cinnamon, cloves and
allspice. For 20 years she's tried to duplicate the taste and said
that years ago the bakery turned down a request for the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting the column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Send food news to Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. The
deadline is noon two Mondays before publication.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
