<HEADER>
A4608 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-ARTICLES-BOS &LR;      06-30 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-ARTICLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN LIGHT PRAISED BY USERS, CRITICIZED BY PUBLISHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Connecticut tax consultant Jeffrey Dexter, the convenience of
being able to search a database of trade magazines on the Internet
from his home office 24 hours a day, and pay only $1 to $4 for each
complete article, is ``terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend about $15 to $30 a month for articles in places like
Appraisal Journal and Journal of Real Estate Management, and the
cost per article is far less than if I had to subscribe to a bunch
of periodicals,'' said Dexter, who used to pay publishers as much
as $7.95 an article. Now he uses Northern Light Technology.
</P>
<P>
   But to Blaise Simqu, an executive vice president at Sage
Publications, Northern Light is a threat to his company's future. A
publisher of nearly 200 academic and professional journals, Sage
depends on annual subscriptions of $65 for individuals and up to
$240 for institutions. If a nonsubscriber can selectively print out
the full text of a Sage publication for a few dollars through
Northern Light, why subscribe to Sage?
</P>
<P>
   So Simqu has made sure Northern Light does not have access to
the Newbury Park, Calif., company's periodicals.
</P>
<P>
   These divergent views of Northern Light underscore why the
Cambridge-based firm has attracted so much attention: high praise
from users and e-commerce watchers, who say the company's research
engine is first-rate; and vociferous criticism from some publishers
who feel financially threatened by nonsubscriber access to the full
text of their magazines' articles.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Lexis/Nexis and Dow Jones Interactive, the most popular
corporate databases for newspaper and magazine article searches,
Northern Light is focused on doing detailed searches for small
businesses and consumers. Northern Light combines the search engine
features of a Lycos or Yahoo with an academic and professional
database similar to Lexis/Nexis.
</P>
<P>
   From its www.nlsearch.com site, Northern Light has combined
access to more than 150 million World Wide Web pages with a
sophisticated database of 6 million articles from 5,400 magazines,
newspapers, scholarly journals, newswires, and other periodicals.
The result is a single ``research engine,'' and a pay-as-you-go
database service.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Light, which was formed in 1995 and debuted on the
Internet in 1997, also offers information from Investext, a
compendium of Wall Street analyst reports on specific company
stocks. And this month it began offering a government documents
search site called usgovsearch.com that indexes more than 20,000
federal Web sites with more than 3.8 million individual government
and military Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to make government more accessible, the new site
enables the user to find information from immigration and banking
regulations to medical research and the status of legislation.
Created with the Commerce Department's National Technical
Information Service, the service costs $5 per day, or $30 per
month.
</P>
<P>
   Using Northern Light's research engine to find specific articles
and related Web sites is free. It is only when articles are
retrieved and printed out that the firm charges individuals and
small business owners up to $4 per article.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Light's most popular service is also its most
expensive. Investext, which contains Wall Street analysts' reports,
costs upward of $6.50 per page.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses can pay a flat monthly fee to use Northern Light for
more intricate searches, for which the results are grouped into
custom folders. And while Yahoo and other portals can perform basic
searches, Northern Light, which has a staff of librarians to help
organize the unwieldy and amorphous Web, specializes in more
advanced searches.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Light's database and organized results ``adds depth to
your Web searches and gives you more power than anyone else can
offer,'' according to PC magazine, which cited Northern Light as
the best tool for advanced searches.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other kudos for its sophisticated searching software,
Northern Light Technology (named after a famous 19th-century Boston
clipper ship) has attracted $35 million in a third round of
investments, from such big names as Reuters, Hewlett-Packard Co.,
and Times Mirror Corp., which publishes many newspapers including
the Los Angeles Times and the Hartford Courant.
</P>
<P>
   With the new funds, Northern Light plans to spend about $20
million on a nationwide print, radio, and television advertising
campaign this fall from Mullen, the Wenham-based ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Wide Web is as much a part of people's personal and
business lives that we want to be the first place they go to,''
said C. David Seuss, president of the 80-employee Northern Light.
Seuss was cofounder of Spinaker Software Co., one of the nation's
first children's educational software firms, which he sold in 1994
for $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Seuss, who would not discuss Northern Light's revenues,
acknowledges that the company's biggest success is Investext. The
company, he added, is preparing to offer on-line market research
studies, for a price tag of upward of $100 per full report. But so
far few of the major market research and consulting firms have
signed on.
</P>
<P>
   And some industry analysts question the company's financial
model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, the idea that people will pay for each article
has limited appeal,'' said James D. Nails, senior analyst for
business information services at Forrester Research Co. in
Cambridge, Mass. ``Northern Light can establish a few niches, but
they won't knock off Dow Jones Interactive or Lexis/Nexis. Still,
they have a very good product in their research engine but I think
their business and distribution model holds them back.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Northern Light is quick to point out that it offers
more information sources than either Lexis/Nexis or Dow Jones,
there are some noteworthy omissions. For example, investor Times
Mirror Corp. offers the Hartford Courant through Northern Light but
not the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Northern Light has not signed up business periodicals
such as Business Week, Forbes, and Fortune, although it provides
links to each of their Web sites. Also missing are major trade
magazine publisher Cahners Publishing Co. of Newton, Mass., and the
influential New England Journal of Medicine and publications of MIT
Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get about $8 for each copywritten article accessed through
our Web site, and hardly anything through Northern Light,'' said
Janet Fisher, MIT Press associate director for journals publishing.
For each article purchased through Northern Light, the publisher
receives about 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said Northern Light gained access to some of their
periodicals, such as the quarterly Journal of Economics, through a
company that legally sells scores of journals to research libraries
and had the right to sublicense them.
</P>
<P>
   Seuss maintains he has had few complaints from academic
publishers, and is currently negotiating with Cahners. But he
acknowledges Northern Light could not come to agreements with
others such as The New York Times Co., which owns The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some publishers _ including those whose publications are
available through Northen Light _ view the firm as harmful to their
bread-and-butter business of selling subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who provides full-text articles over the Internet is
shooting themselves in the foot unless they control it from their
own Web site,'' said Mary Ann Liebert, publisher of Genetic
Engineering News, a 40,000 controlled-circulation biweekly and a
group of biomedical journals, the most expensive of which costs
$1,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Liebert maintains that only a handful of articles from each
issue are available on Northern Light, never the full text.
</P>
<P>
   And Simqu of Sage Publications said: ``Our financial model is
based on yearly subscriptions, which support a lot of people, and
for Northern Light to sell full-text copies of our journal articles
for a few bucks to nonsubscribers means we cannot continue
publishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Seuss counters he is adding more publications each month and the
overall business is growing daily.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, users of the service depend on it, while corporate
librarians are effusive in their praise. At Fuld and Co., a
40-person competitive intelligence firm in Cambridge, Northern
Light is used to find very specific information. The company also
uses Lexis/Nexis, Dialog, and Dow Jones Retrieval.
</P>
<P>
   Said Helene Kassler, Fuld's director of library and information
services: ``No one company offers everything, so you still need to
use different search engines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
