</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S WORLD CUP IS WORLD CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the most overhyped and tedious sporting event in the
history of recorded civilization _ the National Basketball
Association playoffs _ has finally ended, we can direct our
attention to a genuinely interesting competition. I refer, of
course, to the ongoing World Cup of women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Before I start raving, let me make two things clear. One: While
I may indulge in the occasional condescending, misogynist slur
(See: ``Monistat Moment,'' below), I am not antiwoman. I am really
a gender-neutral misanthrope.
</P>
<P>
   Two: I am not rooting for the United States. They are a splendid
team, perhaps the most exciting professional sports franchise in
the country right now. Mia Hamm is as good as billed, if not
better, and the phrase ``supporting cast'' does not do justice to
the many genuine stars on the team with her.
</P>
<P>
   But my loyalties lie with the defending champions, the Lady
Herringheads from the Land of the Paper Clip. (See: ``I Married a
Norwegian,'' Feb. 16, 1994.) If I could have found a North Korean
flag, I would have been waving it at Foxborough on Sunday night.
And yes, I will be rooting for the stolid Lady Volkswagens from
Germany in their match against the Americans Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Those caveats aside, I haven't had this much fun since last
summer, watching the real World Cup. (Sorry . . . I warned you.)
There's nothing not to like about the women's game. It's fast, it's
skillful, and there's plenty of scoring to assuage the Yankee Goal
Whiners, e.g. ``It's soooo boring, they never score . . . '' The
stakes are high, and each team is playing hard. I have yet to see
an Alexi Lalas-level loafer/layabout besmirch the Women's World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Several commentators have opined that the women play cleaner,
and fake injuries less than the men. A Cup spokesman went so far as
to suggest that female players were more ``ethically evolved'' than
the men. What bosh. The game is plenty physical, and the women
writhe in affected agony after insignificant fouls with masculine
aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   Did you see Saint Mia give that Korean gal a shove in the back
on Sunday, while the ref's back was turned? That's what I call a
Monistat Moment. I should perhaps explain that Monistat and
Budweiser are the two primary sponsors of ESPN's soccer telecasts,
which you can watch without commercial interruption.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's the bottom line on women's soccer? Every so often,
Media Central issues ukazes on how to behave (Abstain!) or what to
think (Serbs _ bad!). The latest directive reads: Women's Sports
Have Arrived. This follows by about 18 months the diktat, Women
Enjoy Watching NFL Football, which proved to be totally false.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that women's sports have arrived on high school
and college campuses. At many schools, sports like women's
swimming, volleyball, basketball are 10 times more exciting than
the men's versions. I only wish I had a daughter to serve up to the
Stanford sports kombinat. In the professional arena, women's tennis
and figure skating have definitely arrived. There also seems to be
a great deal of attention paid to women playing golf, which is a
bourgeois leisure activity, and not, strictly speaking, a sport.
</P>
<P>
   Will women's professional soccer succeed here as a television or
stadium sport? No, it won't. Men's soccer hasn't yet found its
audience. As far as the women's game is concerned, men won't watch
it, and most women have better things to do than gawk at the TV for
hours on end. The local professional team draws an average of 1,400
spectators a game, which is what happens when Nike, Gatorade,
Budweiser, and Monistat aren't pouring mega-bucks dollars into
media promotions.
</P>
<P>
   So catch it now; it's the greatest show on earth. China plays
Russia for control of the Eastern Hemisphere Wednesday as Sweden
challenges Norway for control of the Scandinavian peninsula.
Thursday it's Brazil versus Nigeria _ the team that dares to play
without a defense! _ for control of the Southern Hemisphere, plus
USA versus Germany. And remember: Heia Norge!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
