<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-HOTEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIANS TOAST FALL OF SERB-OWNED HOTEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ It took a Manhattan bartender of Albanian
descent armed with a thick New York accent and a case of free
liquor to take over the Serb-controlled Grand Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The state-owned hotel _ best known for its bad food, large
insects, and Serb paramilitaries hanging out in the lobby _ was the
latest battleground in the fight for control of the war-torn
capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A bizarre sequence of events that began with a hostile takeover
of the dimly lit hotel bar Sunday night ended Tuesday with a group
of American Albanians who fought alongside the Kosovo Liberation
Army announcing that a new board of directors controlled by ethnic
Albanians would run the hotel now that Serb forces _ and most Serb
civilians _ have left for Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ours now,'' Uk Lushi, 28, a member of the KLA's Atlantic
Brigade, a force of about 40 American Albanians, triumphantly
announced Tuesday after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo, seriously, it's like we liberated the place,'' said Lushi,
who led the takeover of the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, about 100 ethnic Albanians would be allowed
to return to the jobs they were summarily fired from 10 years ago
when Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic came to power.
</P>
<P>
   They, like tens of thousands of other ethnic Albanians in
state-run industries ranging from coal mines to universities, lost
their jobs as part of a long campaign by Milosevic to give Serbs
and Serbian interests preference in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The drab, filthy 367-room Grand Hotel _ now packed with about
400 reporters, photographers, television crews, and international
aid workers paying up to $150 a night _ has long been a dark symbol
of Serb domination over Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   For years before the war, a sign over the front door read, ``No
Dogs, No Albanians.'' The government-controlled media churned out
Serb propaganda from a second-floor suite. Serb intelligence agents
operated from rooms on a heavily guarded fourth floor.
</P>
<P>
   Menacing-looking Serbs in red jumpsuits with patches that read
``Society for Peace and Tolerance'' are usually reclining in broken
chairs sipping coffee in the lobby. KLA soldiers say many of the
men are members of the rogue paramilitary units that carried out
Milosevic's campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' against Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Zeljko Raznatovic, better known as Arkan, the leader of a
murderous Serb paramilitary force and a convicted war criminal, has
long held a partial interest in the state-run company Sloga, which,
until Tuesday, ran the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear if the few remaining Serbs will be able to keep
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a job, but I'm afraid I'll be killed if I stay here,''
said Ivan Ivic, a Serb porter who said he would not return to work.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, Yugoslav Army and paramilitary forces camped out
in the hotel's basement _ a dark den with disco-like blinking
lights, a pool hall, and a bowling alley. Investigators for the
international war crimes tribunal in the Hague are looking into
allegations that ethnic Albanian women were raped by Serb forces in
the basement, according to tribunal spokesman Paul Risley.
</P>
<P>
   A set of stairs descended into the underground maze of bars and
the bowling alley. An unclothed female mannequin lay on the floor.
The ``Bar Grand'' was ankle-deep in debris that included soiled
mattresses, camouflage uniforms, burned maps and army documents, a
black bra, a broken high-heeled shoe, reams of pornographic
magazines, and dozens of empty bottles of Jack Daniels and Johnny
Walker Red.
</P>
<P>
   The coup at the Grand Hotel began with a tense standoff Sunday
night between the Serb employees and the KLA representatives. A
spokesman for British peacekeeping forces said the hotel director,
a Serb, agreed to a meeting about who would control the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The director was invited to stay on in a four-member board of
directors that would include three ethnic Albanians, but he chose
to quit rather than work with them, said KLA members present at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA won the battle for control not by packing machine guns,
but free liquor. In a public relations stunt, they announced that
drinks were on the house. A crush of reporters stormed the bar.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel director called British forces, who for awhile
tolerated the party with loud Albanian folk music. Serb bartenders
cursed in Serbian, and one smashed a glass on the floor. British
paratroopers with drawn machine guns surrounded the front of the
hotel and made it clear last call was 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was evil in that hotel,'' said Hairia Hussein, 45, an
ethnic Albanian thrilled to be returning to her job as a dishwasher
in the hotel restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting our jobs will be like independence day for us,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
