<HEADLINE>
TYCO INTERNATIONAL TAKES UNGLAMOROUS ROAD TO RICHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The call came in the other day when Dennis Kozlowski was at work
in his two-story office building off a leafy New Hampshire road,
the modest kind of place you might mistake for the home of a
small-town daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   It was an update on the latest business prospect, but there was
nothing small about the idea of Tyco International buying Williams
Plc, the world's biggest maker of fire extinguishers. Discussions,
which appear to have stalled this week, were reported to be in the
$6 billion range.
</P>
<P>
   For all the modest appearances, this is business as usual for
Kozlowski, the chief executive who has built Tyco into a giant
conglomerate with unglamourous business interests across the globe
and even below the ocean's depths.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco, unofficially based in Exeter, N.H., has spent more than
$25 billion on an acquistion tear over the last two years. Today,
the low-profile conglomerate you may have never heard of or
confused with the toy company of the same name has a stock market
value worth more than those of Gillette Co. and Raytheon Co. put
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never started out with a game plan to be a $76 billion
company,'' said Kozlowski, referring to Tyco's stock value. ``But I
always envisioned one that had to grow ever year in order to be
successful and satisfy shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the combined revenues of Tyco's companies may reach an
annual rate of $25 billion by the end of the year and its army of
employees number about 80,000. Billions in cash flow from those
businesses fund many acquisitions, while others deals are paid for
in stock or borrowed money.
</P>
<P>
   For all the scale of its businesses, Tyco's corporate operations
remain practically skeletal. The Tyco staff in Exeter numbers 70.
The company holds its annual meetings at law offices near Tyco's
official headquarters in Hamilton, Bermuda. Count the number of
shareholders, excluding insiders, at a Tyco annual meeting and you
may not need two hands.
</P>
<P>
   But shareholders have had little to complain about at Tyco, a
stock that has nearly quadrupled in the last three years. Kozlowski
has enjoyed rewards as well, including a compensation package last
year valued at as much as $74.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year ago, Kozlowski's name was floated in press reports
as a possible chief executive candidate to succeed Dennis Picard at
Raytheon Co., where he is a director. It quickly became clear that
would have been a step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously his company was growing so fast he chose to not even
consider that,'' said Warren Rudman, the former U.S. senator from
New Hampshire and a fellow Raytheon director. ``Certainly we
thought he would have been a terrific candidate had he wanted to
become one.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyco was a conglomeration of many businesses long before
Kozlowski took over as chief executive in 1992, but its sprawling
empire has grown many fold through new acquisitions and internal
growth in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Tyco's companies are organized into four operating groups
and all new acquisitions fit into one of those business lines. Some
could be called mundane but very profitable, like Tyco's group of
companies that make pipes, fittings, flow meters and other
equipment for industrial use.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco's fire and security services unit, the world's largest,
accounted for a third of operating profits last year. It includes
ADT, the big security company purchased two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company's disposable and specialty product group, which
consists mostly of healthcare-related businesses like U.S. Surgical
Corp., accounted for another third of operating profits last year.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco's electrical and electronic components business contributed
only 19 percent of operating earnings in 1998 but has been the
focus on some of the company's biggest recent deals and its most
dramatic internal growth story.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco agreed to buy AMP Inc., the biggest maker of electronic
connectors, for $11.3 billion last November, outbidding hostile
suitor AlliedSignal Inc. Just last month, Tyco agreed to shell out
$2.87 billion for Raychem Corp., a big maker of electronic wiring
and tubing.
</P>
<P>
   But Tyco's most promising electronics venture of the moment is
rooted in a company it bought 25 years ago. The cable business
acquired in 1974 from Simplex Technologies is now laying fiber
optic lines across oceans to connect continents for expanding
telecommunications traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Business exploded this year and Tyco's companies have won
contracts for $2 billion of work in the last seven weeks alone.
``We saw more data being traferred to this fiber optic cable before
the Internet,'' said Kozlowski. ``Once the Internet came along, it
blew all all our projections away.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyco executes big acquisitions month after month by following
several rules without fail. The two big musts: never do a hostile
deal and cut costs aggressively so new acquisitions do not drag
down Tyco's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlowski got an up-close look at the wreckage hostile deals
create long ago, when he first joined Tyco and Joseph Gaziano was
running the company.
</P>
<P>
   Gaziano, one of the origial greenmailers of the 1970s, pursued
several hostile deals and ended up as the winning suitor for the
Ludlow Co. of Needham, Mass. after a two-year battle. He sent
Kozlowski in to run the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good people had migrated out of the company and we were
picking up the pieces,'' said Kozlowski. ``Hostiles never made a
lot of sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyco's ability to cut costs has been on display at AMP, where
managers had already identified up to $400 million in potential
cuts. Tyco quickly increased the target to nearly $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   One typical line item under scrutiny at AMP: the company's fleet
of aircraft at the disposal of executives and customers. ``Their
take was not to touch that,'' said Kozlowski. ``Our take was to get
rid of the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of go-go conglomerates is littered with companies
that stumbled at the pace or clobbered themselves by paying too
much. Many big Tyco shareholders think there is little chance Tyco
will do either in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be naive to assume there are no risks,'' said Dale
Dutile, an analyst at MFS Investment Management, which owns about
33 million Tyco shares. ``But they've clearly proven in the past
they are terrific negotiators, they are phenomenally good business
operators and they have a lengthy track record.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Kozlowski about comparisons sometimes made between Tyco and
the much larger General Electric Co. and he is flattered, but only
to a degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're growing our earnings at 50 percent a year and GE is
growing at something less than that,'' he said. ``We believe that
we have quite a few years to run out at way above average earnings
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozlowski believes more acquisitions, probably at the same pace
of about 10 per year, will continue for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely no finish line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
