<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAIN-GANG-SHERIFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERIFF SEE LESSONS IN CHAING-GAN APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's the subject of protest letters by outraged human rights
activists from Australia to Sweden, and his controversial new chain
gangs have been rejected by a half-dozen communities in his home
county. His political opponents say he's exploiting a law-and-order
platform to reach higher office.
</P>
<P>
   But if his past is any sort of prologue, Bristol County Sheriff
Thomas Hodgson won't budge an inch. He fully intends to make his
jails the toughest in the land, controversy be damned.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Dartmouth and Freetown selectmen joined four other
Massachusetts cities and towns who don't want his inmates, wearing
red jumpsuits and chained and padlocked at the ankles, working in
their communities. Hodgson replies that there are plenty of other
towns willing to use the free labor, including Swansea, Taunton,
and Rehoboth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to do our work, and we are going to keep doing
it,'' he said. ``This is the right thing for the taxpayer, and
frankly, I am not going to apologize for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The chain gangs are simply the latest in a string of get-tough
jail reforms that have thrust the 45-year-old sheriff into the
media spotlight since he took office in the summer of 1997. And
some observers say that's exactly what Hodgson wants.
</P>
<P>
   As a Republican in decidedly Democratic country, Hodgson is
considered a rising star in the party, they say. Making headlines
by cracking down on inmates has positioned him as a contender for
higher statewide office, although he denies any interest in it.
</P>
<P>
   In a suit jacket, tie, and pinstriped shirt, Hodgson's work
attire hints more at his former profession _ bookkeeper and
consultant _ than his current job. But shortly after taking the
job, Hodgson had to deal with an escape attempt, inmate unrest, and
lawsuits surrounding decrepit conditions at the Ash Street Jail in
New Bedford, the country's oldest active jail.
</P>
<P>
   But Hodgson _ his sense of discipline shaped by Catholic
military school and years as a police officer in a Maryland resort
town _ said his reforms follow a straightforward mantra: Life is
hard, so jail should be harder.
</P>
<P>
   In Hodgson's world, inmates can't smoke. Televisions have been
banned in cells and the weight rooms remain padlocked. Inmates must
rise by 7 a.m. and have beds made by 9. Medical care isn't free.
Even a haircut costs $5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a place where you get a membership to a gymnasium and
a weight room,'' he says. ``If you want to smoke, if you want to
pick out your own breakfast cereal, stay in your community and
don't victimize people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, among them former sheriff candidates, have accused
Hodgson of tightening the screws to the danger point, practically
daring inmates to sue or revolt. Unfazed, Hodgson proudly points
out that defendants awaiting trial seek jail time elsewhere, while
some of his inmates want transfers out.
</P>
<P>
   But Hodgson said his reforms also include compassion. The work
crews are voluntary, the inmates have their own choir, and
incarcerated fathers can read to their children by mailing them
cassette tapes. Those who are motivated can study in Bible classes
or earn a high school equivalency diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics grudgingly praise Hodgson's efforts to make
inmates more accountable, toughen up jail life, and keep victims'
rights on the front burner. But he sometimes takes his beliefs too
far, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is he goes in the right direction, but then he
escalates and bites off more than he can chew,'' said Robert
Furtado of the Massachusetts Corrections Officers Federated Union.
``The guy is hard, ridiculously hard. The chain gangs set us back
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the voters of Bristol County's 16 towns and four
cities thought otherwise. Last November, Hodgson became the first
Republican in decades to win office in the largely Democratic
county. He does not face reelection until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   With 13 brothers and sisters, Hodgson had an ordinary upbringing
in Chevy Chase, Md., an affluent Washington suburb.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from a Catholic military high school in
Washington, Hodgson studied accounting at Xavier College in
Cincinnati, but soon grew bored. Within a year, he'd joined the
police department in Ocean City, a Maryland resort town of 7,000
whose summertime population swells threefold.
</P>
<P>
   He spent 6 1/2 years with the department, studied at the
Southern Police Institute in Louisville, Ky., and rose to acting
lieutenant, supervising crime prevention programs and the narcotics
division.
</P>
<P>
   His experiences on patrol helped develop the values he uses in
his current job: that defendants and inmates need to prepare for
life after jail, which means life behind bars must be regimented
and instill responsibility. He has conceded he is not ``the
inmates' first choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have senior citizens struggling on fixed incomes. We don't
want street criminals coming (to jail) for the winter,'' he said.
``We don't want to make it better on the inside than the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his passion for law enforcement, Hodgson quit the
department in the mid-1980s to work in the family travel business.
At the time, he said, the day-to-day grind on the job made him feel
like he was ``in a very negative world that skews your perspective
about people, which was contrary to my whole upbringing and
everything that I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson said he was still drawn to police work, a self-described
man of compassion who wanted to deal with ``the challenges of human
behavior every day. It is one of the most noble professions.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Hodgson took a job with an office supply company in
Quincy, Mass., then went to work for his brother-in-law's
accounting firm in New Bedford, Mass., where he first entered
politics. He ran succcessfully for City Council in 1988,
campaigning in a Democratic stronghold for law and order, and
against a needle exchange referendum that eventually was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   His law enforcement experience and public appeal as city
councilor caught the eye of then-Bristol County Sheriff David
Nelson, who hired him in 1994 as his assistant deputy
superintendent for investigations, where he oversaw, among other
things, internal affairs and the K-9 unit.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson was destined to become sheriff. Nelson, a Democrat,
resigned mid-term in 1997 after 13 years on the job. That June,
then-Governor William Weld picked Hodgson to complete Nelson's
term.
</P>
<P>
   His first day on the job exploded. An inmate escaped over Ash
Street Jail's 20-foot wall, but was captured while peering into
neighbors' homes. Hodgson added more razor wire to the top of the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, acting on a tip about another planned
jailbreak, Hodgson locked down the jail and called in the State
Police for a two-day shakedown. The raids yielded several makeshift
weapons and gear used for escapes.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson then ordered a 23-hour lockdown that lasted for months.
In response, prisoners rioted, threw feces at guards, smashed
porcelain toilets, and flooded the ancient cellblock. They spat on
Hodgson.
</P>
<P>
   But the crackdowns didn't end, and Hodgson's philosophy didn't
change. His party, and the people, began to take notice.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor has Hodgson, who is single, running for Congress next year
against US Rep. James P. McGovern, a Democrat in his second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt he is a rising star in the Republican
Party,'' said John Brockelman, executive director of the
Massachusetts Republican Party. ``Winning in Bristol County was
quite a feat.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hodgson said he has no plans to run and does not face
reelection until 2004. ``I went out and campaigned for this job,
and told the people what needed to be done. I have an obligation to
fulfill that, since they elected me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
