<SLUG> BC-NY-KORNBERG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER FOR NYC OFFICERS SAYS HE LOVES THE CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even for a lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg is a pretty
unpopular guy.
</P>
<P>
   Street protesters know him by sight and hound him as a
``racist'' or worse. Fellow lawyers have called him ``pathetic''
and ``reckless.'' A Daily News columnist recently denounced him for
peddling ``mud and fog . . . mischief and poison'' and declared
that he owes ``the whole city an apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg has attracted this fire by serving as a defense
attorney in both of the high-profile police-brutality cases that
have set this city on an edge of racial tension unseen for nearly a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, Kornberg represented Officer Justin Volpe, who
halfway into his trial admitted that he did indeed shove a stick up
the rectum of Haitian immigrant Abner Louima in a station-house
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, Kornberg is defending Sean Carroll, one of the
four officers charged with murder for firing 41 bullets at African
immigrant Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   At least as provocative as his pick of clients are his methods.
Before Volpe pleaded guilty, Kornberg told the jury that Louima's
injuries were inconsistent with ``nonconsensual'' sodomy and that
the feces on the bathroom wall contained another male's DNA,
suggesting, without explicitly stating, that Louima had been
wounded in an act of gay sex, not police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   After Volpe's guilty plea, which proved this suggestion wrong,
both Dennis Saffron, chief lawyer for the conservative Center for
the Community Interest, and the Rev. Al Sharpton _ who agree on
almost nothing else _ publicly reviled Kornberg for subjecting
Louima to ``a second rape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that Al Sharpton's come forward on this,'' Saffron
says. Sharpton's own famous accusation a decade ago _ that an
upstate district attorney raped Tawana Brawley _ set off some of
the city's bitterest racial tensions in modern times.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Sharpton was found liable for slander for his statement,''
Saffron went on, ``while the law holds Kornberg absolutely
unaccountable.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes too far to draw precise parallels: Sharpton meant to
stir things up, while any social repercussions from Kornberg's
remarks are byproducts of an age-old courtroom practice.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the activist and the lawyer _ arguably, the city's most
provocative in their respective fields _ will hold much sway here,
these next several months, over the course of race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg's remarks have also reopened the question of how far a
lawyer should go in the pursuit of freeing a client.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Lieberman, former ethics commissioner for the New York Bar
Association, called Kornberg's tactics ``highly reckless.'' Russell
Gioiella, the lawyer for one of Volpe's codefendants who was
acquitted, called him a ``pathetic'' man who just wants ``to keep
his name in the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg, who soon turns 65, sat in his small, disheveled office
in Queens one recent afternoon and waved off the whole barrage of
attacks with a bemused sneer, as if he had been through worse.
</P>
<P>
   He said three doctors were lined up to testify in support of his
theory about Louima's wounds. The fact about the DNA came from the
FBI's file on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want to jump from that to `gay sex,' that's their
leap,'' Kornberg said with a shrug. ``It's not my leap. I never
said that, directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' he went on, ``I have a right, as a defense counsel, to
present to a jury, within the confines of the law, a reasonable
explanation of what happened, based on what doctors would have
testified to. Suppose that I didn't do that. Wouldn't I be remiss
in my duty?''
</P>
<P>
   He changed tack and advised Volpe to plead guilty after four
fellow officers testified against him.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg turned solemn when asked about the change of plea. ``I
regret,'' he said carefully, ``that my client in this case didn't
tell me the full story before the trial started.''
</P>
<P>
   If Volpe had told him the full story, would Kornberg have let
him go to trial? ``No,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg, a wry and voluble man, is a native New Yorker who
talks freely to the press and adorns his walls with tabloid
clippings about himself, including one that ranks him among the
city's 10 best criminal defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Kornberg made his first splash, 15 years ago, in the
Louima case of its day, but on the other side. In the course of
defending an alleged drug dealer, Kornberg produced evidence that
the police forced his client's confession by torturing him with a
stun gun.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg not only won his client a $600,000 settlement, but
sparked an investigation that resulted in the resignations of five
police commanders and the criminal conviction of three officers and
a sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, Kornberg represented a huge
rapist-murderer, whom the tabloids nicknamed The Jolly Green Giant,
by arguing that he was genetically compelled to act violently. The
man was convicted, but the strategy, known as ``the XYY Chromosome
defense,'' has been widely emulated.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Kornberg has gained prominence for defending
police officers: one charged with possessing $3 million worth of
cocaine (acquitted), another accused of rape (sentence reduced),
and four officers charged with killing a car thief (three had
charges dismissed, the fourth was acquitted).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have one type of client; it's been cop, robber, cop,
robber,'' Kornberg said. ``I don't judge my clients. I represent
them. It's my job. Without me doing my job, you might as well take
away the judge, the jury, the prosecutors. It takes all of us to
play the game of court. Know what I'm talking about?''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gillers, professor of ethics at New York University Law
School, agrees. ``It's the defense lawyer's job to put evidence in
the best light, not necessarily the true light,'' Gillers said.
``Society gives him that job, and we excuse him from what would
otherwise be morally dubious acts.''
</P>
<P>
   This aspect of the job, Gillers added, can take ``a psychic
toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg waved away this notion. ``Nah,'' he said. ``I love
every minute of it. I love the challenge of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name his proudest achievements, he cited four jury
trials, involving police officers or firefighters, that ended in
acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was special,'' he said, ``was the thrill in seeing the
audience, packed with cops or firefighters, cheering the jury's
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he confirming the charge, leveled by some critics, that
Marvyn Kornberg is, above all else, a showman?
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a showman?'' he scoffed. ``A guy who goes before a jury
and gets his point across? If that's the definition of a showman,
then I'm a showman and a darn good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether summing up a case, cross-examining a witness, or
spinning a verdict on courthouse steps, Kornberg has always had a
flair for the dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Drama lay at the heart of his interest in becoming a lawyer. The
revelation came when he was a teenager, the only child of a
drycleaner and a dress-shop saleswoman, living in a fourth-floor
walk-up in the Bronx. One day, he went to a movie called
``Boomerang!'' starring Dana Andrews as a lawyer who, in the final
reel, proves his client innocent of murder by pointing a gun at his
own head and pulling the trigger, to show that the alleged murder
weapon doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg still remembers vividly the suspense and exhilaration
of that climax. ``I saw that,'' he recalled, ``and I said, `That's
for me!' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
