<SLUG> BC-WOM-SENIOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETING IN SENIOR GAMES, LIFE BEGINS AT 50 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Sheila McKenna was growing up in Fairhaven, Mass., she was
a bona fide jock, playing basketball, volleyball, and softball. But
her name was never in the local paper, and her picture was there
just once, when her high school basketball team won the
Narragansett Girls' League championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now McKenna _ 40 years older and still a jock _ has four folders
full of newspaper clippings and certificates that brag of her
accomplishments. Her peers are not high school kids, though, but
people from age 50 and older who either want to rekindle their
athletic prowess or ignite it for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Their outlet is the National Senior Games Association.
Sanctioned by the US Olympic Committee, the Games have qualifying
state events every year, and National Senior Games every other
year. Since the Senior Games started in 1985, participation has
grown from 2,500 at the first National Games in 1987 to 12,400
expected this fall in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The summer games have 18 sports including track and field,
volleyball, racquetball, and swimming, as well as badminton,
shuffleboard, archery, and horseshoes. The first Winter Games will
be held next February in Lake Placid., N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Osgood is the assistant state coordinator of the
Massachusetts Games, which began in 1991. Earlier this month, he
said, nearly 900 people participated in 22 sports at Spingfield
College. And though the oldest member was racewalker George Conway
of Milton (age 96), the Games are not geared to the oldest senior
citizens, the longest retired, or the non-athlete.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is divided into age groups _ 50-54, 55-59, and
so forth. ``It's picking up now because the baby boomers have
turned 50,'' Osgood said.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood said his organization tries to spread the word though
councils on aging, recreation departments, senior centers, and an
ambassador program _ athletes telling others what it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna, a former former physical education teacher and coach at
Attleboro High, spent every weekend this month participating in
state Senior Games in Connecticut, Massachusetts, and Rhode Island.
He will go to the nationals in Orlando, Fla., in October. She's
qualified in track events, basketball, and the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna, who works about 24 hours a week for a Hallmark dealer
in Attleboro, usually goes for a run at 5:30 or 6 in the morning,
runs with a coach on Thursday evenings, and goes to the YMCA a few
afternoons a week to play basketball with high school girls or just
practice free throws.
</P>
<P>
   So being sedentary is obviously not an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, the adrenaline constantly flows, I've never been
one to just sit around,'' McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   When she was in high school, there was not even a rover position
on the basketball team (just three forwards and three guards who
stayed on their side of the court). At Bridgewater State, there
were no intercollegiate sports for women.
</P>
<P>
   She learned of the Senior Games in 1993 and got a group of
college alums together to form a basketball team. They won the
States, and qualified to go the Nationals, but McKenna was shut out
for being too young. She was 54, and the starting age then was 55.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna has since added track events to her repertoire, and runs
20 to 25 miles a week training for her 200-, 400-, 800-, and
1,500-meter runs. She'll compete in all of those in the nationals,
as well as the long jump and on a basketball team of women from
Connecticut (``I'm the token out-of-stater.'')
</P>
<P>
   While her times are not world records, they were good enough to
notch her a ninth place in the 1,500 and sixth in the 800 meters in
the 1997 nationals in Tucson, Ariz. Her best time for the 1,500 is
6:56 (world record for women 55-59 is 4:57.5), for the 800 is 3:24
(world record, 2:22), and 400 is 1:28 (1:04.5).
</P>
<P>
   McKenna is realistic about the physical limitations of a senior
athlete, noting that her husband, Jack, used to tell her ``good
luck'' before a meet. Now he says, ``good luck and don't get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Once when she was playing basketball, she stepped on someone's
foot when she was driving a lane, and was in an air cast for two
months. When she was running the 400 meters in the nationals two
years ago, she pulled a hamstring, but had it taped so she could
compete in the 800-meter race the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing basketball in high school, my worst injury was a black
eye, on a jump ball from an elbow,'' she said, shaking her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your mind of an athlete is still 18, but the body is almost
59,'' said McKenna, whose birthday is next month.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Burguess, of Wellesley, is an ``ambassador'' whose job is
to drum up support for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   But she said it's hard, in part because people think Springfield
is too far to travel to compete in the state games, or because they
think of playing bridge or traveling as better activities for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Burguess, 66, acknowledges that she ``was never a sportsminded
person . . . my school offered field hockey and that didn't appeal
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   She started running three years ago ``to stay in shape,'' and
took up racewalking to join her mother, Estelle Frendberg, 86, who
participates in the Senior Games. But that turned out to be too
boring for Burguess, who now competes in the 100-, 200-, and
400-meter races, and high jump. She trains with triathlete Phyllis
Mays, also 66.
</P>
<P>
   Burguess, an administrator for the corporate comptroller at
Bose, has set her goal at improving her high jump of 3 feet, 6
inches, at which she placed third in the Nationals two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am stuck there, I'm platooned,'' she said. ``I'm thinking
big things, and want to get a trainer.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenna's goal, meanwhile, is to add another sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really like to learn the shot put,'' she said. ``I don't
know, I just want a field event.''
</P>
<P>
   And like most of the other seniors involved in the Games, she
likes not just competing, but remembering how different it was when
she was introduced to sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``My basketball uniform in high school was my one-piece gym
suit, and my mother had to cut out felt letters and sew them on my
uniform,'' McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is a big deal for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
