<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4633 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-30 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACERBIC PLAYWRIGHT KNEW THE PERILS OF `REFORM' POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When William Alfred, the professor and playwright, died in May
at 76, many theater-goers and generations of Harvard students
mourned this gentle man and his mischievously acerbic view of life.
Alfred was unusual among American intellectuals because of his
attitude toward ``reform.'' He was against it.
</P>
<P>
   His masterpiece for the stage, ``Hogan's Goat,'' takes place in
Alfred's native Brooklyn in 1890, where, in Fogarty's Saloon, the
tough old mayor, Ned Quinn, responds to demands from the Party of
Reform for his resignation:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Party of Reform''! Ah, yes, reform!
</P>
<P>
   A Lutheran lawyer with a flytrap mouth
</P>
<P>
   And a four-bit practice of litigious Swedes
</P>
<P>
   In a closet rank as rats down by the river!
</P>
<P>
   A lecherous broker with a swivel eye
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't trust with Grandma in a hack!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I once asked Alfred about the inspiration for ``swivel eye'' in
Quinn's diatribe. ``Theodore Roosevelt,'' he replied. ``My family
distrusted him and most reformers.'' T.R. at least accomplished
genuine, long-lasting changes in labor laws and other areas. His
imitators have debased the notion into a priggish defeatism. In
today's politics, ``reform'' is a synonym for distrust of the
people.
</P>
<P>
   At Manhattan's American Place Theatre in 1965, many in the
audience belonged to reform Democratic clubs still battling Tammany
Hall. They gasped at Quinn's gamy speech but were won over by a
lyrical script and a first-rate cast, some of whom found later
success in movies and television: Ralph Waite, Cliff Gorman,
Barnard Hughes, and Conrad Bain. A luminous young actress, Faye
Dunaway, played Kathleen Stanton, whose eloquent doubts about the
price of politics infuse the play with a power to make it worthy of
an overdue translation to film or cable television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like a theater that belongs to the whole people. And
by that I mean a theater where you can have complicated things
being talked about and yet not in complicated ways,'' Alfred once
said. ``I want the theater to have the force and attraction of
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred was a true populist, suspicious of the antipdemocratic
attitude behind the ``reform'' impulse. In ``Hogan's Goat,'' the
villain is a reformer. Today's Party of Reform offers a melange of
moral superiority and ambitious meddling, often peddled by the
fiercely naive and the criminally feckless. They evoke Walter
Bagehot's remark in 1879 that ``nothing is more unpleasant than a
virtuous person with a mean mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The term-limits putsch is aimed at punishing voters who do not
vote the way the lords of ``reform'' want them to. Those wishing to
``reform'' campaign finance by limiting money think voters are too
stupid to know which corporations have rented out candidates and
for how much.
</P>
<P>
   The special prosecutors and independent counsels who intimidate
and harass under the banner of ``reform'' carry writs from a
craven, buck-passing Congress that fears that Congress itself can
never properly exercise its duty of oversight, investigation, or
even (gulp!) impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1955 work, ``The Age of Reform,'' Richard Hofstadter
notes that ``early civic reform was tainted with nativism,'' citing
the observation of Lincoln Steffens that ``educated citizens of
cities said, and I think they believed . . . that it was the
ignorant foreign riff-raff of the big, congested towns that made
municipal politics so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, municipal politics is cleaner and less corrupt than that
practiced among the shady lanes and shady dealings of those
citadels of ``reform,'' the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred's background was working class. His mother was a
telephone operator and his father a bricklayer, who, after his son
gave him a tour of Harvard College, gave a common-sense judgment:
``I'm really impressed by the quality of the bricks used here.''
It's true. Well-laid bricks last longer than most reforms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
