<HEADER>
A4635 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELTIC-TIGER-BOS &LR;      06-30 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTIC-TIGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PROSPERITY LURING MANY BACK TO IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER AND MADELINE GAUGHRAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than a century, Ireland has served as a source of cheap
labor as starvation, political troubles, and unemployment drove
millions to the United States. Now, the tide of migration is
flowing back across the Atlantic as thousands of Irish natives and
some descendants of previous emigrants seek to participate in the
largest expansion in the island nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   In economic terms, the shift is as significant as the famines
that ravaged the island in the 1840s, said Boston College professor
Kevin O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in memory, Ireland is associated with
progress and prosperity,'' O'Neill said. Members of New England's
Irish diaspora who have returned tell of a newly energized society
where booming high-technology based businesses have transformed
Ireland's once-moribund economy into the so-called ``Celtic
Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround was a long time coming; Ireland was badly
handicapped by the separation in 1920 of Northern Ireland and its
industrial base. Central planning also cooled the economy and
emigration kept its population around 3 million from 1926 to 1971.
In 1988 and 1989 alone, double-digit unemployment prompted 131,000
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Now skilled workers are returning like never before. From 1996
to 1998, 88,000 people moved to Ireland, versus 55,000 who left.
mdOf those, 11,500 moved from the United States to Ireland while
8,400 moved the other way, data show. Unemployment is 6.4 percent
in Ireland, well below the European average of 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a real mood swing,'' said John McManus, formerly a
cash-management officer at Fidelity Investments in Boston who moved
to his native Dublin in February to become an electronic-commerce
consultant. ``We were always being told we're the poor man of
Europe, but now it seems like we've really got our act together.''
</P>
<P>
   McManus, 29, and friends who never left are members of a rising
yuppie class that supports chic new restaurants and Gap stores. The
Irish government hopes this same crowd will invest directly in
Ireland's future by buying shares in Telecom Eireann, the national
telephone monopoly, when it is privatized in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to an Ireland that ``feels like it's an equal to
the rest of Europe,'' said Francis Costello, a trade consultant who
was a top aide to former Boston mayor Raymond L. Flynn and to
former US representative Joseph P. Kennedy II.
</P>
<P>
   Those positions made Costello a prominent member of Boston's
Irish community, but now he too is in the process of moving his
family back to Ireland, where he grew up. He is drawn by what he
says is a new focus on business and trade rather than on the
difficulties Ireland suffered as a British colony.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gotten rid of a lot of psychological baggage,''
Costello said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists attribute Ireland's comeback to tax breaks
established 30 years ago aimed at drawing foreign investment; the
momentum for an end to the violence in Northern Ireland; and
Europe's drive to create a single market. For many US companies
seeking a foothold for doing business on the Continent, Ireland's
educated work force, relatively low wages, and familiarity with
American ways make it an attractive choice.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions attracted local companies, including
computer-storage maker EMC Corp. of Hopkinton, Mass. and
medical-instruments maker Boston Scientific Corp., to build
facilities in Ireland along with other major technology firms like
Microsoft and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable outcome: Exports accounted for 79 percent of
Ireland's gross domestic product in 1997, compared to 28 percent in
Germany and 11 percent in the United States. Those sales boosted
Ireland's gross domestic product by 9.1 percent in 1998, about
three times the growth rate of France. In 1997, Ireland's
per-capita GDP of $19,140 was larger than Britain's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a gazillion little high-tech companies there to work
for,'' said James McConnell, 38, currently a product manager for
Bostik Inc., a Middleton, Mass. adhesives maker. He plans to return
to Dublin for business school this summer and says he might stay
there.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of the technology sector has also produced a feedback
effect: startup Irish companies are making their own investments in
the United States. Partly to lure more, Governor Paul Cellucci led
a trade mission to the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the visit wasn't lost on many Irish business
executives, long accustomed to deferring to home offices in Boston
and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has changed,'' said Annette Kennedy, vice president
for human resources at Trintech Worldwide in Dublin. Founded by
several Irish partners in 1986, the company lately has taken off on
sales of software for secure transactions over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has offices in California, Texas, and New Jersey and is
contemplating an initial public offering of stock, just like its
young American rivals in the Internet sector. Ireland works fine as
a business base, she says: ``We're considered the Silicon Valley of
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Irish company on the rise is Iona Technologies PLC of
Dublin, aided by board member John Cullinane, the Cambridge, Mass.
software entreprenuer. Cullinane recalls when he was introduced to
Iona in 1992 it was among a group of companies charging expenses on
credit cards to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   Now Iona has annual sales of $84 million and employs 175 at an
office in Cambridge. ``Our executives live more in a plane than in
a country, but in the software industry I don't think it matters so
much where you're based,'' said Iona spokeswoman Sarah Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Few expect Ireland can sustain its present growth rate, but
government economists still hope for annual expansion of five
percent through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest worry is inflation, partly because Ireland is
receiving billions of dollars in aid from the European Union for
infrastructure projects like roads. The Republic also cut interest
rates under the terms of the European Monetary Union, matching
programs in Germany and France where a priority is the creation of
new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But in Ireland the problem is finding qualified people for open
positions. At an Irish government-sponsored job fair in Boston last
week, recruiters from 20 companies tried to fill 2,300 skilled
jobs, stressing intangibles like quality of life and retirement
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The fair drew some like Tom Seaberg, a 46-year-old controls
engineer from Des Moines interested in returning to his family's
native land even if it means making a lateral career move. What's
the lure? ``It's beautiful country, and there are friendly
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, the Trintech executive, worries that some job
candidates might be put off by the high cost of living in Ireland,
where income tax rates approach 46 percent. ``Some people might
have a romantic idea of coming to Ireland and it's not what they
expected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But relaxed immigration rules are also making it easier for
workers without Irish backgrounds to arrive, including Balkan
refugees, says Aidan Browne, a partner in the Dublin law firm of A
&AMP; L Goodbody LLP who represents clients in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, immigration could ease the pressure on wages and
enable Ireland's expansion to continue, Browne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go into any Dublin bar and most likely you'll be served by a
German or French kid,'' Browne said. ``The Irish are moving up the
value chain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
