<HEADLINE>
WITH LIGHT TOUCH, PROGRAM HELPS YOUNG JEWS RENEW THEIR FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most daunting and worrisome challenges facing
American Jewish leaders is the large numbers of Jews doing little
or nothing to practice their religion.
</P>
<P>
   Though they celebrate important holidays like Yom Kippur or
Passover, many Jews are Jewish because of their heritage, not
because they are deeply committed to their faith.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs of hope: strategies and organizations
working to spur a religious revival among Jews and ensure the
future vitality of America's Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most successful is Aish Hatorah, an educational
program started in Israel that offers seminars on everything from
ethics to dating and takes a much less formal approach than the
typical synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that traditional synagogue services can seem
intimidating and rote, the program's founders say Aish Hatorah
tries to provide a more inviting and intimate setting, especially
for young, single Jews who find no compelling reason to join a
temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's look at the options Jews have,'' said Rabbi Eli Glaser,
director of Aish Hatorah's Boston branch. ``In elementary school
years you prepare to be a bar or bat mitzvah and once you're done
that's usually it. In college you've got Hillel. And then once you
have a family you join the synagogue. But the non-affiliation rate
among Jews between 25 and 40 is very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bernten, 40, who has been a regular at Aish Hatorah's Boston
program since it opened four years ago, said the center is a more
comfortable place to absorb Jewish lessons than a synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more one-on-one than the synagogue and more
personal,'' said Bernten, who runs a travel agency. ``The rabbis
are regular people. You don't feel like they're up there on the
pulpit and you're down here. You really can talk to them without
feeling embarrassed about what you don't know. You can really
relate to them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Aish Hatorah has become one of the city's most
successful Jewish education programs. Since it opened a center four
months ago, more than 2,500 people have walked through its doors.
It has 2,700 people on its mailing list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the success has to do with the fact that it's a
completely different Jewish education than we're used to,'' Glaser
said. ``When I was growing up they taught us a lot of the what _
this is what we do _ but not the why. Why do we do this? What's the
point of keeping kosher or learning Hebrew? The typical Jewish
education does a lot more to turn people off than to turn them on.
It's very shallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Operating in more than 100 cities on five continents, Aish
Hatorah is at the core of the recent explosion of Jewish learning
and spirituality. In Los Angeles, Aish Hatorah has attracted
several Hollywood luminaries, including Jason Alexander, Elliot
Gould, and Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have used you in my life about 25 years ago,''
Spielberg said in a recent statement issued by Aish Hatorah.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser would not have chosen to become a rabbi if it were not
for Aish Hatorah. He discovered the program in 1990 when he was
visiting relatives in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he was a sportswriter for the Baltimore Sun and
before that he had been doing the same thing at the Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had grown up very secular and I didn't have much of a
connection to Judaism,'' Glaser recalled. But after attending a few
programs at Aish Hatorah, Glaser began to sense that Judaism,
despite its ancient roots, could have meaning for a Jew living in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was continuity to Jewish history and if I wanted to blow
it off I felt I was blowing off something significant, whereas
before I didn't really think it was that important,'' Glaser said.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to America and his life as a sportswriter, but the
spiritual seed planted in Israel continued to grow and Glaser soon
grew dissatisfied with journalism. ``Writing about touchdowns and
three-point shots was just entertainment and I wanted to do
something more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Glaser returned to Israel, where he spent five years
studying to be a rabbi. He was ordained in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best decision in my life,'' he said. ``What we do
here makes a difference in people's lives. It's tremendously
fulfilling. This is a very dynamic place.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The Pew Charitable Trusts has allocated more than $2 million
to study the impact of religion on the lives of America's newest
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Churches, synagogues, and mosques have played and continue to
play an important civic, social, and cultural role helping
immigrants incorporate into American society,'' Pew officials said
in a recent statement. ``The importance of religion, however, has
often been downplayed compared to other social and economic
factors.''
</P>
<P>
   To help rectify the situation, Pew has awarded grants to the
University of Houston, New York University, the University of
Southern California, and the Social Science Research Council in New
York to examine the ties between religion and immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   --Thanks to a New York-based Jewish organization, a few computer
clicks can allow people to experience Shabbat services from the
comfort of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by Rabbi Ephraim Buchwald, director of the National
Jewish Outreach Program, ``Virtual Shabbat'' takes users on an
interactive tour of the prayers, rituals, customs, and songs
associated with Shabbat services.
</P>
<P>
   The newly released CD-ROM is an effort to use the latest
technology to try and motivate Jews to strenghten their religious
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtual Shabbat'' costs $19.95 and can be ordered by calling
1-800-44-Torah. The CD-ROM can be previewed at www.njop.org.
</P>
<P>
