<HEADLINE>
LEVELING THE PLAYING FIELDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She tips her Giants cap as she rounds third base, a mass of
strawberry blond curls flying free as she bows from the waist to
acknowledge the cheers of her teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The theatrical gesture marks the last game and first grand slam
of one 8-year-old girl's debut season on the softball diamond. Even
her chronically indifferent big brothers look impressed.
</P>
<P>
   That my daughter is a ham comes as no surprise. That she is an
athlete continually astounds. In her freckled face and unruly
ringlets, I catch a glimpse of my childhood self. But there is
nothing of me to recognize in the power hitter who sails toward
home plate with a swagger as big as her smile.
</P>
<P>
   In this summer of Mia Hamm and the US women's soccer team, I
watch Katie's last glorious hit of the softball season and see the
single, unambiguous legacy of modern feminism. Battles yet may rage
at this century's end in the relentless culture wars about working
motherhood, glass ceilings, pay equity, and sexual harassment, but
the playing field, at least, has been won.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle of Higher Education reported last month that 40
percent of college athletes last year were women, 5 percent more
than the year before. What's astonishing is less the numbers than
the speed with which they were realized. In a single generation,
young women have gone from the cheerleading squad to the varsity
team, from the sidelines to the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was Congress and the courts, not the coaches, who
propelled girls onto the playing fields when Title IX of the
Education Amendments of 1972 mandated an equal allocation of
resources to women's sports at colleges that receive federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   No single antidiscrimination act has had such a dramatic,
measurable impact on the lives of girls and women.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's stars of the US women's soccer team, including the
irrepressible Hamm, were part of the first generation of American
girls who knew there would be a spot for them on a varsity team,
who knew they would be as eligible as their male classmates for an
athletic scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Talent did not immediately translate into opportunity, however.
It wasn't until eight years ago that there even was a World Cup
tournament in soccer for women. Hard to believe when you consider
the phenomenon of the US women's team this remarkable summer.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a million people have bought tickets to their
World Cup games. There were sellout crowds in Chicago and New
Jersey. There were 50,000 screaming fans in Foxborough at the
height of a heat wave. More than 1 billion viewers watch them on
television worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup for women has given our daughters role models on
the athletic fields who actually look like them, ponytails and all.
That's no small matter in my house where Katie's bedroom walls are
plastered with posters of last year's heroic boys of summer _
Chicago Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa and St. Louis Cardinals first
baseman Mark McGwire (the cherished pictures of the homerun kings
torn clandestinely from the pages of her brother's Sports
Illustrated for Kids).
</P>
<P>
   With the success of the US women's soccer team, female athletes
even are poised to reap some of the financial rewards long reserved
for men. Mia Hamm is a spokeswoman for more than a dozen companies.
She is the centerpiece of Nike's latest multimillion-dollar
marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Adidas, the world's largest manufacturer of soccer equipment, is
one of the sponsors of the World Cup tournament and is using
photographs of members of the US women's team in its
advertisements. Can beer commercials be very far behind?
</P>
<P>
   I was alone in front of the television set on a recent evening
when I first saw the Nike commercial featuring Mia Hamm and Michael
Jordan going one-on-one in a number of different sports to the
sound of a female voice singing ``Anything you can do, I can do
better . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Come here, Katie,'' I called breathlessly to my daughter, who
had moved seamlessly from batting practice to shooting hoops in the
driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, that's Mia Hamm with Michael Jordan in this commercial.
She's being treated as though she is as big a star as he is!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, so?'' asked the puzzled power-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Silly Mom. Imagine thinking that Madison Avenue could sell my
daughter something she already owns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
