<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TEXAS GOV. BUSH REACHES OUT TO CALIFORNIA'S LATINOS  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ In his first political foray into California,
George W. Bush raised the hopes Tuesday of Republicans eager to win
back the White House and collected millions of dollars for his
campaign _ but he failed to impress Jose and Marilu Hernandez at
the Del Mar Fair.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited three-day visit of the Texas governor _ the
runaway front-runner in the polls _ generated genuine excitement
among California Republicans, who haven't tasted victory in a
presidential campaign since 1988, when Bush's father, former
President George Bush, carried the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush the younger immediately showed himself as a different kind
of Republican by distancing himself from a controversial California
proposition that antagonized minority voters, especially Latinos
who deserted the GOP in large numbers last year. ``We wouldn't have
had a 187 in my state,'' the Texas governor said of Proposition
187, the 1994 ballot measure that outlawed health, welfare and
education for illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In his two campaigns for governor, Bush had broad support from
Latino voters _ something California GOP candidates have not
enjoyed recently. Dan Lungren, the Republican candidate for
governor last year, won only 20 percent of California's Latino
voters, about half the support Bush received from Latinos in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, between a breakfast fund-raiser in San Diego and a
lunch fund-raiser in Irvine, Bush tried out his distinctive style
of campaigning at the Del Mar Fair. He jumped on a stage at Plaza
de Mexico while a mariachi band played the classic ``Cielito
Lindo'` for a perfect photo op _ a setting dotted with pinatas and
colorful flags, and flanked by girls in jewel-colored Mexican
dresses and boys in giant velvet sombreros.
</P>
<P>
   And he briefly addressed the crowd in Spanish, although his
words were not as grammatically correct as those used by Democrat
Al Gore in his visit to California last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Es un gran honor para mi, de estar contigo,'' he said, with a
heavy accent. ``It's a great honor for me to be with you.``
</P>
<P>
   He then promised his campaign would leave no one behind, because
``no puedes leer, no puedes realizar los suenos Americanos'' _ ``If
you can't read, you can't realize the American dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   But although Bush's appearance piqued the curiosity of many
Latinos, he also left many skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Hernandez, who works for a property management firm, and
his wife, Marilu, surrounded by their six children, said they were
unconvinced. ``He didn't say much,'' Hernandez said. ``We all want
a better future for our kids, but he's going to have to visit us
more often.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Hernandez said he was a Republican, he said he still
wasn't sure that the GOP could be trusted because of issues like
Proposition 187. ``You give him the vote, and then, olvidalo _
forget it,'' Hernandez said in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Another in the crowd, Jesus Garcia, a fair employee from San
Diego, who was sitting with his two teenage boys, said, ``I've
heard he's going to help us. He's promising a lot. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush spoke briefly at the fair, he gave longer speeches to
his donors. He raised $480,000 at breakfast, $400,000 at lunch and
$2.3 million last night at a dinner in Los Angeles. He expects to
raise $1 million more Wednesday and $450,000 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, the strength of the Bush tidal wave was
evident among loyal Republicans and a few curious Democrats, even
eight months before the primary and with a packed field of
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no turning back,'` Bush told the Irvine crowd of 400.
``I not only intend to win the primary, I intend to win California
in the general election, and I intend to become the next president
of the United states.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want our great nation to be prosperous, but prosperity must
have a purpose _ to make sure the American dream touches every
willing heart,'' said Bush, who made a fortune in the oil
exploration business and then as an owner of the Texas Rangers
baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   The mood for the California tour was set in tony La Jolla, where
nearly 500 big-money donors turned out for a $1,000-a-head
breakfast of fruit salad and yogurt with Bush at the Hyatt Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipation was palpable as Bush entered the room to a
standing ovation, then hopped from table to table, delivering bear
hugs, pumping hands, posing for photos and grinning in response to
words of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speeches to supporters contained few policy specifics but
instead painted a broad _ and often eloquent _ picture of
``prosperity with a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed an era of responsibility, educational reform and
``positive'' values in the White House, while promising ``to match
a conservative mind with a compassionate heart.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clear dig at Vice President Gore, the Democratic
front-runner who once took credit for creating the Internet and has
pledged to ``keep the prosperity going,'' Bush said that Democrats
``no more invented prosperity than they invented the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of government is to create an environment in which
entrepreneurship can flourish,'' he said. ``We can be prosperous if
we can reduce the taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also promised to reach out to ``struggling families who
live on the outskirts of poverty'' and urged greater support for
churches in the fight against poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government can hand out money, but what it cannot do is put
hope in our hearts,'' he said. ``This is done in churches and
synagogues and mosques, and charities that warm the cold of
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush mentioned foreign policy concerns only in general terms.
``This is still a world of terror and missiles and madmen, and we
are plagued by aging weapons and failing intelligence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``America must seize the moment,'' he added. ``We must lead.
Because our greatest export to the world is and always has been
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He received his strongest applause with his appeal to voters who
have grown tired of scandals in the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be a president who sets a tone, an agenda,'` he said to
cheers. ``I will not use my office as a mirror to reflect public
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush will make appearances in Los Angeles and Sacramento
Wednesday before attending a fund-raiser Wednesday night in San
Francisco. Thursday, he will be in Silicon Valley and Fresno.
</P>
</TEXT>
