<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULATION-UN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW POPULATION POLICIES HAVE AIDED WORLD'S WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By RAMON G. MCLEOD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  The 1994 Cairo population conference called for a radical shift
in the international strategy for slowing the world's population
growth: Instead of focusing on birth control, improve the lot of
women and they will have fewer children.
<P>
   That strategy seems to be taking hold and will be at the center
of discussions Wednesday when the United Nations begins a three-day
special session to assess and update the Cairo accords.
</P>
<P>
   Birth control is still a large part of population reduction
strategies, particularly in the poorest of poor nations, but the
main emphasis at the conference will be on progress toward gender
equality, not birth control distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Cairo, the approach to family planning was a fairly
narrow concept. You tried to provide people with information about
having fewer children, make condoms and birth control pills
available, have population targets and so on,'' said Carl Haub, a
demographer at the Population Reference Bureau, a Washington, D.C.,
demographics think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was fine 25 years ago, particularly since so many
countries then had nothing at all; most of the developing nations
didn't even have clinics where people could get information,'' he
said. ``But this is a different time and this is a much, much
broader approach, one that goes right to the core of culture,
family life and the relations between men and women,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic reductions in world population growth were never
expected in the first five years after Cairo. Nevertheless, there
has been a modest decline in the rate of growth, though some of the
momentum for a slowdown predated the conference.
</P>
<P>
   There will still be 6 billion people on Earth by October and
world population is growing 1.33 percent annually, but that is down
from 1.46 percent in 1995. Demographers are beginning to predict
ever-slower growth.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the most likely scenarios show that there will be 8.9
billion people in the world by 2050. That is well below U.N.
estimates of 9.5 billion made in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth rates have come down, but no one should be complacent.
Ten billion people will still be living in the world in a few
decades and that is an extraordinary number,'' said Abubakar
Dungus, a spokesman for the United Nations population division.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in population strategy that was codified at Cairo was
born out of hard evidence from countries like Korea and Italy that
improvements in women's health, education, social status and
political power were typically accompanied by lower birthrates.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have now is an approach that starts with individual
women and recognizes that when women have real choices and
resources to make decisions about their lives and the lives of
their children, they will have fewer children,'' said Amy Coen,
president of Population Action International, a Washington, D.C.,
population research organization.
</P>
<P>
   Coen noted that when families have the confidence that their
children will survive, they tend to have fewer of them. She also
noted that in numerous surveys and studies of women in high
fertility countries show that women understand that fewer children
means a better life for them and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Gender equality was a major goal of the Cairo accords and since
then, 76 countries have reported taking significant measures on
gender policy and law, according to a United Nations survey.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the U.N. survey found that 54 countries have reported
new components and significant measures to improve reproductive
health. The most common of those, added to reproductive health
programs since Cairo, was the prevention and treatment of sexually
transmitted diseases, including AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest disappointment of the post-Cairo era, and one sure
to be discussed in the U.N. sessions this week, has been the
failure of the developed nations to live up to the financial
promises that were made in Egypt five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, for example, needs to triple its current
funding from $600 million this year to $1.9 billion to meet its
obligation.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been battling with the Clinton administration since
1995 over population funding and, led by conservatives fearful that
U.S. money will be used for abortions, has cut population funding
by 30 percent during that time.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
