A4650 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-LAWSUITS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-30 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-LAWSUITS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CLINTON, CONGRESS AGREE ON LIMITING Y2K SUITS  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA and HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silicon Valley gained its biggest political victory ever
Tuesday, when Congress and the White House agreed on a law to limit
future lawsuits caused by year 2000 computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking protection from a potential $1 trillion onslaught of
lawsuits if computers malfunction because they can't recognize
years after 1999, high-tech powerhouses like Intel, Microsoft and
Sun had made passage of the bill their top legislative priority.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he would sign the compromise bill, which
could be approved by the Congress and sent to him before the long
July 4 weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would delay the filing of Y2K lawsuits for up to
90 days, giving companies time to fix any problems. It would also
make it harder for consumers to bring and win Y2K lawsuits, and
would limit punitive damages in certain cases.
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy the White House, which had threatened to veto earlier
versions of the bill, lawmakers agreed to changes that would make
it easier to pursue some class-action lawsuits and would increase
the damages that could be assessed against companies that act in
bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major statement that the Silicon Valley and the
high-tech community have a very, very positive impact on the
political debate,'` said Harris Miller, president of the industry
trade group Information Technology Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups remain adamantly opposed to the legislation,
saying it sacrifices consumers' legal rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a compromise, it's a complete surrender to the money
interests of the computer industry at the expense of millions of
consumers and small businesses,'' said consumer advocate Ralph
Nader.
</P>
<P>
   His colleague James Love, director of the Consumer Project on
Technology, was more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sucks; it's a total cave-in; it's terrible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which had previously passed the House and
Senate in slightly different versions, had become a political
football. High-tech firms, business groups and most Republican
legislators sought strong protection against Y2K lawsuits, saying
they could threaten the U.S. economy. But consumer advocates,
plaintiffs' lawyers and many Democrats, including President Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore, argued that the bill went too far to
protect big business.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate leaders, along with chief lobbyists from the
opposing business, consumer and trial lawyer associations, met all
day Monday and Tuesday to fashion a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators met until about midnight Monday. Sen. Christopher
Dodd, D-Conn., who acted as liaison between congressional
Republicans and the White House, was on the phone with Clinton
again at 1:30 a.m. going over more details.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise fell into place during the last 16 hours of talks
when both sides moved on the two stickiest provisions, said Marc
Pearl, general counsel and chief lobbyist for the ITAA.
</P>
<P>
   One issue was how liability would be allocated in cases with
multiple defendants. ``Deep-pocket'' firms like Intel and Microsoft
were worried about being forced to pay huge amounts of damages
beyond their share of responsibility for a problem, in cases where
co-defendants were unable to pay their shares.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise limits a company's penalty in joint cases to
twice the damages it caused if it acted in good faith. But if a
company acted in bad faith, it could be forced to pay triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients have been very concerned about the `deep-pockets'
problem,'' said Matthew Kreeger, attorney at Morrison and Foerster
in San Francisco, which represents both major hardware and software
companies and smaller startups. ``I think our clients will be very
satisfied with this compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The other issue concerned class-action lawsuits. The compromise
would allow defendants in class-action lawsuits seeking $10 million
or more in damages to shift the cases to federal court. The
previous House and Senate bills set that amount as low as $1
million. Business groups sought the limit to deter frivolous
class-action suits from being ``shopped around''' to find the
friendliest state court.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gore urged Clinton to veto the bill unless it offered
more consumer protection. Gore's stance unleashed a firestorm of
criticism in Silicon Valley even as the vice president was courting
the tech industry in his bid for the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, a spokeswoman for Gore said the vice president
wasn't quite ready to endorse the compromise bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're reviewing the final language as we speak,'' said
spokeswoman Melissa Ratcliff. ``The vice president has always
believed in a compromise that would balance all interests. It
appears that progress has been made, but until the final language
has been reviewed closely, the VP is going to reserve judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley lobbyists and corporations hailed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased that a compromise has been reached,'' said
Roberta Katz, president of the Technology Network of Palo Alto, a
political lobbying group formed by 140 top Silicon Valley firms.
``This issue was an important one, not just for the high-tech
industry, but for the country at large.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This really was a meaningful compromise,'' said Intel Corp.
spokesman Bill Calder. ``This was clearly one of the most
significant legislative items for the technology community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This compromise is good for both consumers and industry,''
said Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Atherton. ``Fair and effective Y2K
legislation must provide some limits on Y2K suits while providing
redress for real damages. This bill does that, and I'm urging my
colleagues to support it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
