<HEADER>
A4653 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HORMEL-AMBASSADOR-SFC     06-30 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORMEL-AMBASSADOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 2-YEAR BATTLE, NATION'S FIRST OPENLY GAY AMBASSADOR IS 
 SWORN IN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ San Francisco philanthropist James Hormel was sworn
in Tuesday as the first openly gay U.S. ambassador, culminating a
nearly two-year Senate confirmation battle that elevated his
nomination to an obscure Luxembourg posting to a high-profile fight
over gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   A small contingent of religious conservatives, who led the fight
to block Hormel's nomination, held one last press conference
outside the State Department, calling the heir to the Hormel
meat-packing fortune a ``homosexual poster boy'' who is unfit to be
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, a crowd of some 200 friends, relatives, supporters, gay
activists and officials _ including Hormel's partner, Tim Wu, his
former wife, Alice, and her husband, Jim Turner _ gathered for a
champagne reception in the gilded and marbled Benjamin Franklin
Room overlooking the Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we send a message that neither race nor creed nor
gender nor sexual orientation should be relevant to the selection
of ambassadors for the United States,'' Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright declared after administering the oath of office
to Hormel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those glorious days when the nice guy finishes
first,'' she added, to a roaring cheer.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unusually large and celebratory swearing-in, attended
by a large press contingent and dozens of supporters who flew in
from San Francisco. Most ambassadorial oath-taking passes with
little notice, the press is seldom admitted and the secretary of
state rarely presides.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel thanked the Clinton administration and his congressional
supporters for refusing to back down from his nomination. ``What an
incredible privilege it is to be standing before you today,''
Hormel, who remained largely silent during the controversy, told
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Paying frequent tribute to his family, Hormel noted that the
Bible used for his oath was inscribed by his father in 1901, and
that one of his daughters wore her grandmother's dress for the
swearing-in.
</P>
<P>
   He praised Luxembourg as a steadfast U.S. ally ``where thousands
of Americans lost their lives'' liberating the tiny European
principality in 1944 and 1945. Hormel noted that General George
Patton was buried there.
</P>
<P>
   Referring several times to ``the challenging times'' of his
confirmation fight, Hormel expressed gratitude for the support he
said he received from all parts of the country, saying his favorite
was a letter from a 93-year-old grandmother who wrote: ``I have
prayed to live to see this day.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sens. Dianne Feinstein of California and Edward
Kennedy of Massachusetts, who tried unsuccessfully to push Hormel's
nomination to a Senate vote, lauded Hormel as a highly qualified
appointee who was opposed only because he is gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Jim's appointment, we open a door,'' Feinstein said, ``that
this country is prepared once and for all to put aside bigotry and
prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Nominated by President Clinton in October 1997, Hormel was never
confirmed by the Senate. Applying a long-standing Senate
prerogative, three conservative Republicans _ James Inhofe of
Oklahoma, Tim Hutchinson of Arkansas and presidential candidate Bob
Smith of New Hampshire _ put a ``hold'' on his nomination to
prevent a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said Tuesday that she had rounded up 61 votes to break
the holds and confirm Hormel, but Majority Leader Trent Lott
refused to schedule a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any honorable question about his (Hormel's)
qualifications to be ambassador,'' Kennedy said, calling opposition
to the nomination ``irresponsible and unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton finally made the appointment during the Senate's
Memorial Day recess, taking advantage of a constitutional provision
that allows presidents to install nominees when the Senate is not
in session.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Supervisor Susan Leal, who joined dozens of other
local supporters at the reception, flew in on the red-eye to
attend. ``I wouldn't have missed this for the world,'' Leal said.
``He's been through an incredible ordeal. He is a person who has
served his community in San Francisco and who wants to serve his
country and is qualified to do so, and the only reason he was
stopped is because he is gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe had made one last-ditch effort several weeks ago to
protest the appointment, threatening to hold up all pending Clinton
nominees, including Larry Summers as Treasury Secretary, unless
Clinton promised not to make any more recess appointments without
first notifying the Senate. Clinton agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-year-old Hormel served as a former assistant dean of the
University of Chicago law school and delegate to the U.N. Human
Rights Commission. He is a prominent San Francisco philanthropist
who sits on the boards of the symphony and the Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   He has also been a generous contributor to Democratic candidates
and gay causes, helping to found the Human Rights Campaign, the
nation's largest gay advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly the entire Washington office of the Human Rights Campaign
attended the reception. Executive Director Elizabeth Birch called
Hormel's swearing-in ``tremendously historic because a very
important barrier was removed'' to high-level government
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Religious conservatives warned that Hormel would use his
ambassadorship to Luxembourg, a grand duchy with a population that
is barely half of San Francisco's, to promote a ``gay agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Andrea Sheldon, executive director of the Traditional
Values Coalition, opponents focused their objections on Hormel's
sponsorship of a section in the San Francisco Public Library that
is devoted to gay literature. Hormel's critics held him accountable
for the section's selection of sexually explicit material,
including references to pedophilia, although he was not involved in
the selection of the content.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon said Hormel steadfastly ``refused to denounce pedophilia
and incest and we are still outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's press conference, Sheldon displayed pictures of the
Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence, a group of transvestites from San
Francisco who dress as nuns. ``These are people who mock Christians
and engage in outrageous anti-Christian bigotry,'' Sheldon said.
``Mr. Hormel seems to think they're appropriate and funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon accused gay activists of using Hormel as a ``homosexual
poster boy to say, `Please accept us.' We say you can dress James
Hormel up in high-society acceptance, but he promotes standards
that are not acceptable'' to most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Birch said that Sheldon ``should find an opportunity at some
point to celebrate fairness and nondiscrimination and lift herself
out of bigotry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
