<TEXT>
<P>
   CD mini reviews
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Dollar and Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Test''
</P>
<P>
   Test. Aum Fidelity. 5 tracks. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Hearing this volatile New York quartet rip and roar, a listener
might be reminded of the old gospel song that warns of ``the fire
next time.'' Test, a guerrilla musical collective that has honed
its extraordinary dynamic range by gigging for spare change in
Manhattan's subways, rises to the apocalyptic occasion on its debut
disc. Recorded live and on the cheap in a Brooklyn loft, this
hour-long performance is thrillingly explosive, yet also defies the
truism that free jazz is a lot of unstructured noise.
</P>
<P>
   Almost criminally unknown and underrated, multi-reedists Daniel
Carter and Sabir Mateen could be urban legends on leave from a
Thomas Pynchon subplot. Such colorful fantasy shatters, though,
when they begin to act as twin lightning rods, surging with
sometimes convulsive bursts of raw energy. In the tradition of
1960s jazz giant Eric Dolphy, Carter and Mateen also have a keen
sense of lyrical and harmonic balance. It's what allows their
contrasting lines to flow with the organic logic of a spiraling
double helix. Bassist Matt Heyner and drummer Tom Bruno sustain the
flexible pulse that underwrites the concept's inherent risks. And
any group that dares both a flute duet (``Alen's Flight
Preparation'') and a boisterous call-and-response sermon (``What R
U Going To Due?'') is taking risks. Test pulls it off: This is one
of the best albums of the year.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``This Moment Is Mine''
</P>
<P>
   Chante Moore. Silas/MCA. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Terry McMillan can continue her writing hiatus in peace. Chante
Moore has taken up the best-selling author's ``Find a guy and
thing's will be fine'' credo and made a No. 2 R&AMP;B hit out of it _
``Chante's Got a Man.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chante has more than that. Three albums into her career, her
soprano is still a wonderful, spiraling instrument. Unfortunately,
it plummets to the redundant depths of the opening track ``If I
Gave Love.'' Which is _ what? _ producer Rodney Jerkins' third or
fourth reworking of his first No. 1 hit, Brandy and Monica's ``The
Boy Is Mine.'' Things pick up when Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis apply
a formula that works on ``Easy,'' a ballad reminiscent of such
patented Jam &AMP; Lewis heavy-breathers as Janet Jackson's ``Funny How
Time Flies.'' After that, it's all cooing, candlelight, and only
occasionally, something meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
