<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pretenders still swagger like punks
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To borrow a plot line from ``Austin Powers,'' the Pretenders
lost their mojo right around 1986, the year they released the album
``Get Close.'' Band leader Chrissie Hynde and her cohorts had
always been fans of the pop hook _ ``Brass in Pocket'' and ``Back
on the Chain Gang'' are paragons of radio-friendly songcrafting _
but they balanced the hummable hits with an aggressive edge.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Get Close'' sounded disturbingly toothless, and on
subsequent releases, Hynde has relied all too often on easy,
eager-to-please melodies. (The icky 1994 power ballad ``I'll Stand
By You'' had to be a career low point.)
</P>
<P>
   On ``Viva El Amor!'' the band displays some of its old swagger.
Much of the album has a loose, raw feel, and Hynde's lyrics are
wonderfully sassy: ``Bail me, jail me but they're never gonna nail
me _ pharmaceutically,'' she sneers on the pro-pot rocker
``Legalise Me.'' On the leadoff track, ``Pop Star,'' Hynde laments
``they don't make 'em like they used to.'' But the Pretenders have
done just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viva El Amor!''
</P>
<P>
   Pretenders. Warner Bros. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
