<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Paths of Glory' marked the road ahead of Kubrick
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``The Thin Red Line'' and ``Saving Private Ryan'' in
stores, video renters have a choice between two powerful anti-war
films. But there's another one worth a look, re-released this week
on VHS and DVD along with other films celebrating the work of the
late director Stanley Kubrick. (His final film, ``Eyes Wide Shut,''
opens July 16.)
</P>
<P>
   His 1957 drama, ``Paths of Glory,'' not only put him on the map
as a filmmaker, it established some of his signature directorial
touches: the restless tracking shots, following characters through
dirty trenches or glistening marble corridors; the close-up of
faces racked with emotion. And for all its cumulative power,
``Paths'' maintains a precision and chilliness that marked the rest
of Kubrick's films.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Douglas plays Col. Dax, a French criminal lawyer turned
officer in World War I, who gets the order from Gen. Mireau (George
Macready, in an overripe, villainous performance) to lead his men
on a suicidal charge against a German stronghold called the
Anthill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthill'' is a perfect, ironic name for the target, since the
movie demonstrates how easily lower members of the military
hierarchy get stomped, like bugs. When the offensive against the
Germans fails, Mireau and his colleague Gen. Broulard (Adolphe
Menjou) demand that an example be set. Three men are selected,
supposedly at random, to be tried for cowardice. In the words of
Broulard, ``There are few things more fundamentally encouraging and
stimulating than seeing someone else die.''
</P>
<P>
   Dax volunteers to defend the trio before the tribunal. More
travesty than trial, the procedure allows no character witnesses,
and mention of the soldiers' past honors and efforts are
inadmissible. It's such an obvious railroad job, Dax says, ``There
are times when I'm ashamed to be a member of the human race, and
this is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick delights in contrasting the foxhole realities of the
fighting stiffs with the pampered, oblivious world of their
commanding officers. Most of the movie unfolds in and around a
chateau. The mansion, whose every arch and ornament seems built as
a tribute to man's alleged enlightenment, serves as counterpoint to
the film's depiction of civilized savagery.
</P>
<P>
   When we first encounter Mireau and Broulard, the generals aren't
discussing strategy but the tastefulness of the carpeting. While
the three condemned soldiers shiver their last night away in a dank
stable, the officers waltz with their wives to an orchestra. As he
butters a bit of pastry, one general happily says, ``The men died
wonderfully.'' Though ``Paths of Glory'' never breaks from
realistic conventions, its critique of the military mind-set
foreshadows Kubrick's wild, Cold War masterpiece, 1964's ``Dr.
Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick caps ``Paths of Glory'' with a coda set in a makeshift
pub: A terrified German girl (Susanne Christiane, who would become
Kubrick's second wife) is forced to sing before jeering French
soldiers. The tense moment turns into a scene of melancholy beauty
as the sound of the girl's voice unlocks the memories and tears of
the tired men. Sentimental, yes, but also moving.
</P>
<P>
   More than four decades after its release ``Paths of Glory''
remains a rigorous and unsettling statement against the strategic
inhumanity that can erupt during wartime, even among supposed
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
