<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Thin Red Line'' (R) _ Less a war movie than a meditation
on life, death, love, hate, man and nature. Terrence Malick puts
his unmistakable stamp on the drama of an Army division's struggle
to capture Guadalcanal from the Japanese during World War II.
Fueled with voice-overs, gorgeous images and sudden violence, it's
superbly strange, an epic that feels intimate but distant at the
same time. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Still Crazy'' (R) _ A brilliantly acted comedy with poignant
undertones. Twenty years after giving in to factions, jealousies
and divine intervention, a fictional '70s British rock group named
Strange Fruit attempts a reunion tour. The movie is both a
celebration and an elegy, telling us that rock 'n' roll dreams die
hard. The ensemble cast is terrific, with Bill Nighy a standout as
the lead singer. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Hi-Lo Country'' (R) _ Woody Harrelson, Billy Crudup and
Patricia Arquette form a love triangle in this uneven but absorbing
drama set in the fading West in the years after World War II.
Arquette is miscast, but director Stephen Frears (``The Grifters'')
is an expert at building tension that you know just has to erupt.
Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Varsity Blues'' (R) _ James Van Der Beek plays a high school
football player in this insulting mix of beery teen humor and
rampant sexuality. It simultaneously ridicules its small-town
characters while insulting audience intelligence. That's some
accomplishment. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Mighty'' (PG-13) _ Kieran Culkin's mighty mite is just
one plus in this fine family film that is down to earth and magical
at the same time. Culkin is an undersize genius suffering from a
degenerative illness who bonds with a lonely 13-year-old giant
(Elden Henson) with self-esteem problems. The strong supporting
cast includes Sharon Stone, Harry Dean Stanton, Gena Rowlands and
Gillian Anderson. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Outside Ozona'' (R) _ The characters in this story about a
band of strangers driving through the desert at night are as
superficial as the blue eye shadow and pink lipstick that star
Penelope Ann Miller has to wear. The writing never rises above
homespun philosophizing, such as ``Sometimes you're the windshield,
and sometimes you're the bug.'' Watching this, you'll sympathize
with the bug. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
