<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RUSHMORE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Rushmore' scales comedic heights
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Rushmore'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   A 15-year-old scholarship student at Rushmore Academy, Max
Fischer (Jason Schwartzman) devotes himself to every
extracurricular activity offered: martial arts, the debate team,
beekeeping, whatever. He's very proud of his fencing skills. And he
runs the school's theater club, directing a gritty stage version of
``Serpico'' or, better yet, a Vietnam drama complete with live
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   But then his crush on an elementary school teacher (Olivia
Williams) takes precedence over these things. And when middle-aged
tycoon Mr. Blume (Bill Murray, in brilliant sad-sack form) also
falls for Williams, Max declares war.
</P>
<P>
   This wonderfully eccentric comedy is the second film from
director Wes Anderson (``Bottle Rocket''). Unfolding in a parallel
universe removed from the ``reality'' of other high school movies,
it creates its own sort of dream logic, finishing off with the
generous shapeliness of a Shakespearean comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Its vision of romantic fulfillment manages to be both tongue in
cheek and heartfelt. The movie captures the heady solipsism of
being a teenager, the time when anything seems possible, and love
feels like a matter of life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
