<SLUG> BC-CMGI-CMGI </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Venture Firm Plans Big Boost For AltaVista  &HT;     By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Online venture firm CMGI Inc. yesterday said it will buy an 83
percent stake in Palo Alto-based AltaVista, Compaq Computer's
powerful but lightly marketed Internet search engine, for $2.5
billion in stock and debt.
<P>
   The deal had been in the works for some time and intensified
after Compaq quashed plans to spin off AltaVista. CMGI plans to
meld AltaVista into its portfolio of 40 Web companies, including
financial site Raging Bull, in a bold move to create an online
behemoth rivaling Yahoo and Excite &LR; Home.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, the world's largest PC-maker, will continue to bundle
AltaVista in its machines.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista is the Internet's 10th-most popular site, with 10.7
million visitors per month, according to MediaMetrix in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, CMGI, of Andover, Mass., CMGI will own most
of Alta Vista, a Palo Alto company. Compaq will receive a
16.4-percent equity stake in CMGI, making Compaq its largest
outside shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI shares rose $12.63, to $110.31 yesterday, while Compaq rose
$1.06, to $23.38.
</P>
<P>
   The search engine sale hardly surprised industry insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has stumbled revamping its distribution strategy and
digesting last year's buyout of Digital Equipment Corp., which had
previously acquired AltaVista. Earlier this month, Compaq it &LR; 
 &LR; warned of a second-quarter loss from pricing pressures.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI executives estimate sales generated by AltaVista will
nearly double the $168 million that CMGI collects from its other
dot.com properties.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call yesterday, CMGI CEO David Wetherell said
Compaq spent only $1 million this year promoting AltaVista. He said
CMGI and Compaq will plunk down $50 million each marketing
AltaVista over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The AltaVista acquisition marks a major shift in strategy for
CMGI, which has financed Internet startups such as No. 3 search
service Lycos, and reaped big dividends when those companies went
public or were acquired. CMGI made a cool $1 billion from the sale
of GeoCities, in which it held a 28 percent stake. Yahoo acquired
GeoCities for $4.05 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI intends to spin off AltaVista in an initial public stock
sale at a date soon to be set, Wetherell told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
