<SLUG> BC-BIZWOMEN-BIZWOMEN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Women-Owned Firms Seeing Huge Growth  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Women-owned businesses continue to grow faster in numbers, revenues
and employees than businesses in general, according to a new study
of the top 50 U.S. metropolitan markets.
<P>
   During the past seven years, the number of women-owned
businesses nationwide jumped 42 percent, to 9.1 million, stated a
report issued by the National Foundation for Women Business Owners
and Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women-owned businesses grew approximately one-and-a-half times
faster than for businesses overall over the past seven years,''
said NFWBO spokesman Bruce Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   The study measured the number of women-owned firms in each
market, their revenues and their employees. It also measured the
growth rate in each of these categories for each market.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco ranked 17th in a category that averaged number of
women-owned firms, employees and revenues. It ranked only 27th in a
category that measured average growth rate in these three
categories.
</P>
<P>
   During the past seven years, the number of women-owned
businesses in the San Francisco area increased 36 percent, to
91,000.
</P>
<P>
   The number of employees at San Francisco area women-owned firms
grew 131.4 percent since 1992, to 345,000. Nationwide, employment
at women-owned firms grew 108 percent over the same period, to 27.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, revenues of women-owned firms in the San Francisco
area jumped 157 percent, to $54.2 billion. In all 50 markets,
revenues increased 132 percent, to $3.6 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland area ranked No.20, with 91,900 women-owned firms,
250,200 employees and $36 billion revenues. The San Jose area
ranked No.32, with 60,500 firms, 172,200 employees and $24.8
billion revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In the growth rankings, the Oakland area ranked No.21 and San
Jose ranked No.22.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers, however, are not indisputable. They are based on
analysis of 1987 and 1992 U.S. Census data with the trends
projected forward.
</P>
<P>
   The top five metropolitan areas for women-owned businesses
ranked by average number of firms, employment and sales are: No.1
New ,York followed by Los Angeles-Long Beach, Chicago, Philadelphia
and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The five metro areas experiencing the fastest growth of
women-owned businesses between 1992 and 1999 are: Portland,
Ore./Vancouver, Wash.; followed by Seattle/Bellevue /Everett,
Wash.; Phoenix/Mesa, Ariz.; Houston, Texas; and Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
