A4670 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-FINGER-BOS &LR;      06-30 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FINGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLE YET SOPHISTICATED TEXAS TALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MY GRANDFATHER'S FINGER 
By Edward Swift, with photographs by Lynn Lennon. 
University of Georgia Press, 246 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Edward Swift was a little boy living in the Big Thicket of
east Texas, he saw Maria Tallchief dancing ``The Firebird'' on a
television set his uncle Frank may have stolen. This fired in him a
desire to be a ballerina, despite his grandmother's observations
about how a ballerina looked like a ``bitch hiking up her legs.''
When his mother went into Woodville to shop, young Eddie Jr. would
follow behind, en pointe, in his ballerina outfit _ a T-shirt,
moccasins stuffed with old nylons, and a green wool skirt.
</P>
<P>
   This apparition excited a lot of comment in east Texas, as it
would just about anywhere, but Eddie Jr.'s mother, Pearl, took it
all in stride. And years later, Swift's latest book exacts sweet,
hilarious revenge. Nobody in Woodville was in any position to cast
the first stone _ and in fact nobody anywhere would be.
</P>
<P>
   A common human problem is that every person likes to think that
he or she is the norm from which the universe departs at its own
peril. The lesson of this book is that every individual is an
eccentric, and normality is a figment of the imagination. Swift's
sympathy goes out to everyone who refuses to submit to an arbitrary
notion of normality.
</P>
<P>
   Swift's own family was chock-full of unusual people. When his
grandfather lopped off his finger with a machete when out at work
in the logging business, Eddie's aunt Coleta pickled it in a little
green jar and used it to terrify children into good behavior; the
little green jar with the pickled finger in it became and remains a
family heirloom and talisman. (A photograph of it appears on the
last page of Swift's book.)
</P>
<P>
   Swift's uncle Frank had a weakness for painted women who reeked
of cigarettes, bourbon, Listerine, and Evening in Paris; one of
them confessed to Eddie Jr. that she made her living as a
``stripteaste artist.'' ``The very sound of the word produced such
excitement I could hardly speak. I was sure that I was an artist
too, but I had no idea what kind. How I admired Jean for knowing
exactly what kind of artist she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the eccentrics in the Big Thicket were in the family,
not by any means. Hardy Cain escaped from his wife to make violins
he could barely play in a fallout shelter called Rapture's Heights.
``When walking through the woods, he often came upon a tree with
music trapped inside it.'' Mrs. Margaret Woodcock liked to go to
the city dump to collect old sacks of other people's letters,
``which she read and reread with the greatest interest.'' Sister
Louise Owens, costumed in an old wedding dress which billowed out
of the windows of her VW Bug, traveled from church to church to
give her dramatic reading, ``The Samarian Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   These people, and dozens of others, pass through the pages of
``My Grandfather's Finger,'' a series of interlocked
autobiographical essays. Many of them were originally written as
newspaper magazine articles. It is unclear whether the 39 pictures
by Lynn Lennon were commissioned by the newspaper or by the
University of Georgia Press, but they are sensitive and memorable.
Occasionally Swift's effort to produce the last-line ``kicker''
that newspaper editors love shows. But in every other respect,
Swift's essays transcend their genre because of the simplicity and
sophistication of his art, his economy of means, his sense of time
and place, and the precision of his ear in hearing and notating the
melody of common speech. ``For a long time, Mother felt that Carole
Lombard had hung the moon.'' Or ``I'm not so sure Eva Gay enjoyed
hearing this, but she heard it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Swift was different himself, and felt the difference,
even if he couldn't articulate what the difference was, he
understands the differences of other people, even the people who
were closest to him, and therefore the hardest to understand. Like
his mother: ``I can tell you what she was all about. Quite simply,
she was about sadness. She was about transcending sadness with
laughter. She was about the language, how she heard it, and how she
spoke it. It was music. She was like a soprano singing Rossini. The
second time through she embellished the line. She tried never to
repeat herself, not even her embellishments, but of course, she did
repeat herself, she repeated herself constantly; still she never
stopped trying for something new the second time around. That's
what she was all about.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be obvious to readers of Swift's novels _ especially
``Splendora,'' ``Principia Martindale,'' and ``Mother of Pearl'' _
how his childhood and adolescent experiences fed into and nurtured
his art. Many people yearn for exotic escape; Swift did too, at the
Fain Theater, where he sold popcorn and where Randolph Scott's
low-slung belt and Debra Paget left indelible impressions on him,
``especially when she was forced to jump into an active volcano in
order to appease the gods.'' But something far more exciting lay
right in front of Edward Swift's nose, and he has had the sense to
recognize it. He found a way to make his childhood nurture his
whole life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
