<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4671 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-GROWABUSINESS_SF     06-30 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON  
 GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON  &HT;     Analyzing a Career Change 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
I am a clinical psychologist who has been practicing for over 40
years and wish to make a career change to organizational
psychologist. My next step is to market myself and I don't find
that easy. I welcome any ideas how to proceed.
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Networking may be an overused word, but that is a place to
start.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Crandall, a Tiburon author of eight business books
including ``Marketing Your Services: For People Who Hate to Sell,''
suggests contacting trade associations in the field you are about
to enter.
</P>
<P>
   For example, get in touch with the American Society for Training
&AMP; Development (www.astd.org), which has more than 70,000 members,
publishes tons of information about professional development and
hosts conferences. If you attend a local chapter meeting, you can
mingle with other consultants as well as company human resources
specialists who might be interested in your expertise.
</P>
<P>
   You might also check out the Society for Human Resource
Management (www.shrm.org), which also has local meetings, and the
Institute of Management Consultants (www.imc.org.au).
</P>
<P>
   Besides schmoozing, you should probably read a few books on
marketing. IDG Books and its ``For Dummies'' line has several on
starting a small business, with applicable chapters on marketing.
Entrepreneur's Magazine and a bunch of other publishers have
similar books.
</P>
<P>
   To make further contacts and win free publicity, Crandall also
recommends writing guest columns or articles for trade publications
or the growing array of online magazines that are hungry for
content. You might also offer yourself as a guest expert on a radio
show.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to specialize in training or testing employees or
consulting services for management, you might call the human
resources department of target customers and offer to give a free
lunchtime seminar or question-and-answer session about stress
management or other workplace issues. Demonstrating your expertise
might pave the way to a professional relationship or win you
referrals.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget your clients and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Even though you are changing fields, Crandall notes that many of
your current or previous clients might run organizations that need
a human resources specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Or they know those who do.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than call everyone who might have faith in your
competence, send out letters to let them know you are moving from
working with individuals to working with organizations. Tell them
how much you appreciated working with them and how much you would
welcome new leads.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Negotiating With the IRS
</P>
<P>
   Q: &LR;   &LR; I am a sole proprietor and am about $10,000 behind in
paying my 1998 federal taxes. What advice can you offer on how my
small business can put off paying or strike a bargain with the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: The first thing experts say is not to slide into more
difficulties by failing to pay your estimated quarterly tax
payments this year. ``Make sure you don't fall behind another
year,'' advises tax consultant Carolin Petersen. ``You don't want a
domino effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, conduct a good cash-flow analysis of expenses and profits
and figure precisely what you can afford to pay per month to get
out of your tax debt. Then approach the IRS and make your own
proposal; do not wait for the IRS to approach you.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen, who has run her tax mediation business from Lodi since
1981, knows a thing or two about dealing with the feds. She was the
first woman special agent for the IRS Criminal Investigation
Division in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Often the IRS is willing to negotiate a payment arrangement over
the phone. ``They're increasingly willing to work out installment
agreements and not file liens so long as taxpayers come to them
with a feasible plan to pay off their unpaid taxes in 36 to 48
months,'' Petersen said. In some cases, the IRS might even stretch
payments to five years, but be ready to show your financial
statements and projections.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, if you could pay $300 a month for 36 months, you
would basically be paid off. (Interest charges will run 8 percent
per year on unpaid taxes and there is not much you can do about
that.)
</P>
<P>
   The IRS typically sends out four notices of nonpayment, one
every five weeks, and then a certified notice demanding payment in
30 days. Rather than wait, Petersen advises calling the IRS
toll-free number (800) 829-8815.
</P>
<P>
   If you are assertive and adept at negotiating, Petersen suggests
you might call the IRS yourself to work out a repayment schedule.
You can also deal with attorneys, CPAs and consultants, but that
can be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Again, be sure to pay your estimated quarterly tax payments. If
you fall behind, the IRS can use that as a reason to declare you in
default of any back taxes payment agreement.
</P>
<P>
   I presume you are $10,000 behind on your personal tax payments,
not payroll taxes. The feds will not negotiate installment payments
on unpaid payroll taxes, and if you fall behind a single quarterly
payment on your payroll taxes, the IRS is likely to send out a
revenue officer. ``If you don't pay promptly, they'll shut you
down'' said Petersen. ``Never bleed payroll taxes to pay personal
taxes first.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRS also has an ``Offer in Compromise'' that allows
taxpayers to negotiate a reduction in back taxes. But Petersen says
it is an expensive, complex exercise that can take nine to 18
months to arrange and is economical only for companies that owe
$30,000 to $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
