<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BAD-COMPANY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASED TO BE IN ONE ANOTHER'S COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer's rock reunions just keep coming: Bruce Springsteen
and the E Street Band, the J. Geils Band, Foreigner, Motley Crue,
Bad Company, and more. It almost seems like a master plan to have
everyone descend at once into sheds and arenas across the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very interesting, isn't it?'' says Paul Rodgers, lead
singer with Bad Company. ``But I can assure you that it's entirely
coincidental on our part. I'd hate to have people think, `Oh, look,
these other groups are getting together, so Bad Company is doing
it, too.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, Bad Company was the least likely to reunite,
at least with its original lineup. Members hadn't played together
in 20 years _ the most extended absence of any of this summer's
reunion acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a farewell tour that has been a long time coming,''
says Rodgers, 49.
</P>
<P>
   There was a watered-down version of BadCo that played sheds in
the late '80s and early '90s, but the Original Bad Company, as the
revived group is called, features Rodgers and Simon Kirke (both
formerly of the band Free), Mick Ralphs (formerly of Mott the
Hoople), and Boz Burrell (formerly of King Crimson). They were the
all-star nucleus that enabled Bad Company to rule rock radio in the
'70s with such hits as ``Feel Like Makin' Love,'' ``Shooting
Star,'' ``Rock 'n' Roll Fantasy,'' and ``Can't Get Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But they stopped performing in 1979, after having risen to
arenas such as Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were exhausted, and there was a lack of inspiration,''
Rodgers recalls during a recent phone interview from the road.
``The death of (Led Zeppelin drummer) John Bonham also really
affected me. . . . And I wanted to stay home with my family for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers has since made six solo albums (the sixth comes out in
the fall) and was part of a short-lived band, the Firm, with
Zeppelin's Jimmy Page, in the '80s. Then, two years ago, the
original members of Bad Company met in London at the funeral of
Peter Grant, who had managed Zeppelin and Bad Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time since we broke up that we had been in
the same building together,'' says Rodgers. ``We knew we also had
to get together to discuss various catalog matters eventually. One
thing led to another, and I said to Mick, `What would really be
interesting is if we put out an anthology and put new material on
it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That happened with the recently issued ``Original Bad Company
Anthology,'' which has the above-named hits, plus four new tracks _
two written by Rodgers and two by Ralphs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the feeling that this isn't just a nostalgia trip, that
there's a sense of the band moving forward,'' says Rodgers, who
still refers to this as a farewell tour but admits, ``You can never
say never.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The band has a definite chemistry that is uniquely Bad
Company,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers feels the band's blues-based songs are still relevant,
especially ``Shooting Star,'' about becoming a rock burnout. Yet,
he also retains a personal investment in many songs, which helps
explain why he's agreed to this reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I sing `Rock 'n' Roll Fantasy,' I realize that it's still
a rock 'n' roll fantasy to stand up there,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECYCLING-RECYCLING_S     06-30 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECYCLING-RECYCLING </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Retired Timber Goes Back to Work  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
You don't have to go to virgin forests to find old-growth timber.
You can find it at the Port of Oakland, abandoned airfields in San
Francisco's Presidio and old warehouses in Fremont.
<P>
   Architects, interior designers and homeowners are discovering
the beauty, environmental cachet and increasing availability of
``reclaimed'' wood.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a new word in building circles to describe the
phenomenon: deconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1950s, when bulldozers became the popular way to tear
down old buildings quickly and waste was not a major worry, taking
buildings apart piece by piece was the way things were done.
</P>
<P>
   Now the environment is a major concern, and there has been a
revival of businesses that take buildings apart by crowbar to save
the timber rather than turn it to rubble. About the only drawback
is that it is time- and labor-intensive process and the final
product is not necessarily cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, EcoTimber of Berkeley expects revenues from its
reclaimed timber sales to climb from about $100,000 last year to
$500,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   The company currently has embarked on the largest local harvest
of urban lumber at the recently closed Naval Fleet Industrial
Supply Center in West Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   In an innovative collaboration of businesses, government and
social service agencies, Oakland's Youth Employment Partnership is
putting 150 high school dropouts and welfare recipients to work
tearing out more than 2 million board feet of timber at six World
War II-era warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   The salvaged old-growth redwood and Douglas fir is being
remilled and marketed by EcoTimber.
</P>
<P>
   The company started out in 1992 importing hardwood from
certified well-managed forests. Because that market was relatively
small, the company branched into selling redwood and other products
from second-growth forests, then added salvaged timber to its
product line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reclaimed wood provides the same benefits of old-growth timber
and alleviates pressure on virgin forests and overflowing landfills
at the same time,'' said Jason Grant, co-founder and marketing
director of EcoTimber. This year, reclaimed timber will account for
close to 15 percent of the company's anticipated $4 million in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   One customer is outdoor clothing retailer Patagonia, which uses
salvaged Douglas fir for store fixtures. ``There's no need to chop
down new timber when there's plenty to be had through
deconstruction,'' said Peter Noone, director of new store
development for Patagonia. ``And the rustic character of the
reclaimed wood works with the image we want to present.''
</P>
<P>
   Old warehouses and other urban buildings are not the only source
of reclaimed wood. So are dead or damaged trees removed from city
streets, parks, back yards, old orchards, even river and lake
bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   EcoTimber sells tongue-and-groove flooring salvaged from red
elms that used to grace the streets of Sacramento. Toppled Monterey
cypress trees in Golden Gate Park similarly have been turned into
usable lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Tiller used such cypress planks to make a deck in the
Berkeley hills. ``I like the fact that it was windfall,'' said Ian
MacLeod, who designed and built the project. ``It did not involve
cutting down new trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Imperfections and nail holes are often perceived as ``character
marks,'' according to EcoTimber's Grant. ``It's wood with a story
behind it.'' Old-growth timber also has tighter grain, fewer knots,
and is harder and more stable than plantation-grown stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not necessarily cheap. Reclaimed lumber, especially
premium grades, often costs as much as or more than new product.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why. At the old Naval Supply Center in
Oakland, the total budget to tear down all six warehouses is about
$4 million, including $2.9 million in welfare-to-work and other
grants. It also will take more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Each crew of 40 Youth Employment Partnership trainees and a
five-person staff will take more than four months to dismantle each
sprawling warehouse, pull out the nails and sort the lumber. By
contrast, a six-person demolition crew could do the job with a
bunch of bulldozers in about three weeks at a quarter of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   However, about $500,000 worth of timber will be reclaimed and
resold from the total project. In addition to saving landfill and
forests, the program addresses a host of inner-city social and
economic problems, according to Chris Thomas, director of
deconstruction for YEP's welfare-to-work program.
</P>
<P>
   Pay starts at $6.50 an hour for the disadvantaged youths
participating in the program. There are raises and bonuses for
completing training in forklift operation, lumber identification,
career planning and other skills. Child care, transportation and
general education classes also are part of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of hard work,'' said Michelle Davis, 20. ``But I
always wanted to get into construction and I've learned to cut pipe
and work a forklift.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawntell Chavis, 22, said she likes getting $7 an hour and
gaining experience in lead paint abatement and other skills.
</P>
<P>
   Before EcoTimber got involved, most of the salvaged timber at
the Port of Oakland was shipped overseas to Chile and Scotland,
where it went into pubs and other construction.
</P>
<P>
   There can be problems using reclaimed timber as framing
materials because many jurisdictions require that it be regraded.
That costs time and money. However, there is growing interest in
the material for rustic flooring, paneling and exposed interior
beams.
</P>
<P>
   At EcoTimber's yard in Berkeley, hand-hewn beams from barns go
for as much as $15 a linear foot. Old oak flooring goes for $6 a
square foot, compared to $3.50 for new oak.
</P>
<P>
   EcoTimber is committed to building a broader market for
reclaimed wood. So are several other Bay Area businesses. They
include:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Beyond Waste _ Started five years ago, this Cotati company has
salvaged former Army buildings at Crissy Field in the Presidio and
private warehouses in Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   CEO Pavitra Crimmel got the idea for the company when she was an
employee at another Sonoma County nonprofit called Garbage
Reincarnation and saw a lot of good wood going into the local
landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized we could help save the environment while creating
jobs,'' she said. Even though it takes longer to take a building
apart piecemeal, she suggests it may not delay a project if
builders and developers plan ahead. For example, in many cases
builders can begin work on a demolition permit while awaiting final
approval of a building permit.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of Beyond Waste's $150,000-a-year business is
reclaiming lumber. The company recently received a $50,000 grant
from San Francisco to help it solicit more deconstruction bids in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Building Resources _ This division of San Francisco Community
Recyclers sells about $180,000 a year of salvaged doors, windows
and an increasing amount of recycled timber. It has worked with
Beyond Waste, taking apart buildings in the Presidio and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Caldwell's _ This San Francisco salvage yard started in 1956 and,
despite the onslaught of bulldozers at that time, focused more on
preserving than wrecking. Partner Rob Caldwell, the founder's son,
said 35 to 40 percent of revenues come from reclaimed lumber and
about 95 percent of the company's jobs are done by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Often Caldwell's gets the materials for free. Besides salving
their conscience, owners save substantial landfill costs, which can
run up to $900 for a large truckload.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Black's Farmwood _ Michael Black, who grew up on a tobacco farm in
Ohio and worked as a carpenter in Marin last summer, started this
company in San Rafael in January. He got the idea after his
grandmother told him she planned to burn down her long-abandoned
150-year-old barn.
</P>
<P>
   Black salvaged the beautifully weathered white oak siding (which
sells at EcoTimber for $4.50 a foot). He also took apart six other
barns in Ohio with a crowbar, chain saw and truck. He has since
hired a supplier in the East and is expanding in the West.
</P>
<P>
