<SLUG> BC-R-OBIT-KAREKIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAREKIN I, ARMENIAN PATRIARCH, DIES AT 66
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating for all needing.)  (nk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Catholicos Karekin I, the spiritual leader of Armenian Orthodox
Christians worldwide, who faced the enormous task of reinvigorating
his ancient church after the fall of Soviet Communism, died Tuesday
at his pontifical residence in Echmiadzin, near the Armenian
capital, Yerevan. He was 66.
 &HT;    The cause of death was throat cancer, for which he received
treatment in the last year in New York, said a spokesman for the
Diocese of the Armenian Church of America.
 &HT;    An Oxford-trained theologian fluent in English, French and other
languages, he held the title Supreme Patriarch and Catholicos of
All Armenians, with a flock of more than six million.
 &HT;    Head of one of the world's oldest churches, he was a leading
exponent of ecumenism among Christians and was well known among
church leaders in Europe, the Middle East and the United States.
 &HT;    In March, returning to Armenia from New York, he stopped at the
Vatican, where he and Pope John Paul II made plans for the pope to
visit Armenia in July. As Karekin's health deteriorated during the
spring, the pope tried to schedule a private visit this month but
called it off because of his own health problems.
 &HT;    Karekin became head of the Armenian Apostolic Church in April
1995; he was the first such leader elected in centuries within an
independent Armenia.
 &HT;    The nation, with a population of about 3.5 million, had emerged
only four years earlier after seven decades of rule by the Soviet
Union. Even before the Soviet domination of the present republic,
Armenia was often divided up and ruled by countries including
Russia, Turkey and Syria.
 &HT;    Karekin was the 131st in a line of church leaders stretching
back to St. Gregory the Illuminator, who converted King Tiridates
III of Armenia in 301. Christianity became Armenia's official
religion a decade before the conversion of the Roman Emperor
Constantine.
 &HT;    Along with churches in Egypt, Syria, Ethiopia and India, the
Armenian Church belongs to the branch of Orthodox Christianity that
did not accept the definition of Christ's nature as human and
divine promulgated by the Council of Chalcedon in 451.
 &HT;    He visited the United States in May 1998 of last year to help
celebrate the 100th anniversary of the Armenian Diocese.
 &HT;    In an interview then, he said he faced three major challenges in
revitalizing the Armenian church: overcoming the negative
influences of Soviet-sponsored atheism, persuading Armenians that
Christianity is a way of life and not simply an ideology, and
persuading them that faith offers spiritual and moral sustenance.
 &HT;    The Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, general-secretary of the National
Council of Churches, who met several times with the catholicos,
recalled him as unaffected and considerate. During a visit to
Echmiadzin, she went to early morning prayers and saw him beckon
her to stand beside him.
 &HT;    ``I know you don't know the language _ I'll translate for you,''
Ms. Campbell recalled him saying.
 &HT;    ``That just amazed me,'' she said. ``He never saw himself as too
lofty to be a teacher when you needed help.''
 &HT;    Karekin was born Neshan Sarkissian in Kessab, Syria, on Aug. 27,
1932. After graduating from a seminary in 1952, he was ordained a
celibate priest and took the name Karekin in honor of an earlier
church leader.
 &HT;    He studied at Oxford from 1957 to 1959, served as a seminary
dean and then became an aide to Catholicos Khoren I, head of the
Catholicate of Cilicia, a self-governing see within the Armenian
church. He was also sent as an observer to the Second Vatican
Council.
 &HT;    He became a bishop in 1964 and an archbishop in 1973 and later
was elected Catholicos Coadjutor of Cilicia, to succeed Khoren I.
After Catholicos Khoren died in 1983, Karekin made visits to the
Vatican, the Church of England, European Protestant churches and
the Coptic Church of Egypt.
 &HT;    As head of the separate Cilician see, he was seen as a long shot
to succeed the Armenian Apostolic Church's long-reigning head,
Vasken I, who died in 1994. But after favorable statements were
made by Armenia's president, opinion began to shift toward him and
he was elected in a gathering of 400 church delegates.  
 
 BC-OBIT-BIRD-NYT  
 VERE BIRD, 89, WHO LED ANTIGUA TO INDEPENDENCE  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vere C. Bird, a child of the slums and a Salvation Army drummer
who carried the Caribbean island of Antigua to independence and
then sired the family dynasty that has led and dominated the
country ever since, died June 28 in the capital, St. Johns. He was
89.
</P>
<P>
   At his death after a long illness, the Caribbean News Agency
quoted his son, Lester Bird, who is also his successor as prime
minister, as saying, ``He raised us and produced us to continue in
his footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear from the context if he meant Antiguans generally,
or himself and his brothers. In fact Vere Bird had done both,
changing the political and social destiny of the island and
becoming what native Antiguan writer Jamaica Kincaid described as a
family patriarch ``who thinks that the government is his own
business.``
</P>
<P>
   Despite drug and gun-running scandals that touched his family
and government, Bird was regularly returned to office until he
retired in 1994, paving the way for his son. At his death, his
oldest son, Vere Bird Jr., was the agriculture minister while a
younger one, Ivor, a former Cabinet member who has been tainted by
scandal, directed the family-owned radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Vere Cornwall Bird Sr., who was born in a ramshackle shanty and
never went beyond grammar school, was a large, athletic and
powerful man with a preacher's voice and a sharp tongue. As in the
case of so many who were to become leaders of independent Caribbean
states, he first tasted power and attained prominence as a labor
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The basis of his popularity among the 65,000 citizens on the
islands of Antigua and Barbuda was established in the early 1940s,
when these dots in the leeward chain were sugar-producing colonies
ruled from London and dominated by planters.
</P>
<P>
   Like Norman Manley and Alexander Bustamante in Jamaica, Eric
Gairy in Grenada and Dr. Eric Williams in Trinidad, he used
organized labor to confront both the planters and the colonial ties
that maintained their power. As president of the Antigua Trades and
Labor Union, he led sugar cane workers in strikes for higher wages
during World War II. He also pressured plantation owners to turn
over plots and home sites to the sugar harvesters who had been
their tenants.
</P>
<P>
   The union soon branched off into the Antigua Labor Party and in
the late 1940s, Bird won his first election to what was then still
a colonial legislature. In 1951, when universal suffrage was
introduced, the party led by Bird won every seat in Parliament, a
feat it would regularly repeat. In 1981, when Antigua became fully
independent, he became prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as tourism replaced the sugar production as Antigua's
economic mainstay, Bird's record of nationalism and populism seemed
to pay increasing dividends to his person and to his family.
According to Franklin W. Knight, a historian at Johns Hopkins and
the author of ``The Caribbean,'' Bird became one of the ``unusual
number of charismatic, caudillo-style politicians'' produced in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The Antiguan political opposition charged that under the Birds'
rule, the island became a haven for international con men; in
recent years, U.S. government agencies have identified Antigua as a
key transit point for South American cocaine bound for Europe and
as a money laundering center. Ms. Kincaid, whose memoir ``A Small
Place'' dealt with growing up in Antigua, described the place in
this later period as ``a monument to rottenness.''
</P>
<P>
   Several scandalous revelations lay behind the criticisms. In May
1990, a court in Tel Aviv indicted an Israeli officer on charges of
illegally shipping assault weapons to Vere Bird Jr. in order to
have them forwarded to the members of the Gacha drug cartel in
Columbia. When islanders responded with protests and signs
proclaiming ``The Birds Must Go,'' the younger Bird resigned his
Cabinet post as minister of public works, but no charges were filed
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years earlier, a Canadian company called Space Research
owned by Gerald Bull was permitted to test howitzers on the island.
After a newspaper that was later shut down by the government
reported that the company was shipping arms to the white minority
government of South Africa, Space Research quietly withdrew. In
1990 Bull was in the news again when he was shot to death in
Belgium, where he was reported to be working on a gigantic cannon
for Saddam Hussein of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 Ivor Bird was fined $75,000 after being caught with a 25
pound shipment of cocaine as he boarded a plane at the airport
named for his father. The following year U.S. officials expressed
concern about the arrival on the island of what they described as
organized crime groups from Russia, reportedly involved in money
laundering, drugs, arms sales and extortion. Another scandal
involved efforts by the ruling family to sell off the sands of a
highly unusual pink beach.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such embarrassments, Bird countered with speeches
reminding residents of the time when the only work available was
backbreaking labor of cutting cane and when drinking water came
from dirty ponds. He would make these speeches into his 80s,
accompanied by his wife, Lydia, his daughter Lisette, and his sons,
who also included Curtis, a lawyer, and Roswald, a teacher. His
household also included a mistress named Cutie Francis.
</P>
<P>
   His body will lie in state at Antigua's Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-OBIT-WAYNE-ART-NYTR &QL; 
(ATTN: N.C., Fla., Calif.) &QL; 
MARSHALL WAYNE, 87, OLYMPIAN WHO RILED HITLER IN '36 GAMES &QL; 
 &LR; (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) &QL; 
(nk) &QL; 
 &UR; By DEAN HENSLEY &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; The Times-News in Hendersonville, N.C. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HENDERSONVILLE, N.C. _ Marshall Wayne, who displeased Adolf
Hitler by winning gold and silver medals in diving in the 1936
Berlin Olympics and was later shot down over Italy fighting the
Nazis, died June 16. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   He died at Pardee Hospital in Hendersonville after suffering a
cerebral hemorrhage while working on a book at home, said his
sister, Dever Antes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had met Ernest Hemingway and had wanted to write stories
like Hemingway's for a long time,'' said Ms. Antes, also of
Hendersonville.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Antes said her brother spoke with Hitler and the Nazi leader
was very displeased with Wayne for winning the gold medal in the
platform diving competition. Wayne also won the silver medal in the
3-meter springboard diving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler wanted his man from Germany to win it, so he wasn't too
happy at all seeing my brother win,'' Ms. Antes recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She said the family lived in Miami close to a pool where Wayne
did most of his practicing. He excelled at diving in high school
and at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   While serving in World War II as a colonel in the Army Air
Forces, Wayne's plane was shot down in Italy and Italians helped
Wayne get to a British Aid Station and then to England for surgery.
The fall from the plane had torn ligaments and tendons in his leg,
Ms. Antes said.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Wayne became a Pan American Airways pilot, and
retired as a captain in 1972, the same year he moved to
Hendersonville.
</P>
<P>
   His love for the Olympics landed him a spot on the 1996 Atlanta
Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic torch was making a run through town and Wayne was
invited to take part in the ceremony,'' Ms. Antes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother was wearing a fake medal around his neck and when
he climbed out of the car downtown, someone shouted, `Hey where'd
you get that medal?' And Marshall said, `From the '36 Olympics in
Berlin.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his sister, Wayne is survived by his daughter,
Marilyn Wayne of San Pedro, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne's other daughter died a couple of years ago, Ms. Antes
said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Times-News on Hendersonville, N.C., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
