<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ LOS ANGELES _ Gov. George W. Bush, in California on a
three-day fund-raising swing, is expected to announce he has topped
$20 million for his presidential campaign. Reports are the figure
could be as high as $30 million. We look at how that compares with
the rest of the field. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   GOP-THEPACK _ They've become the pack_ everyone other than
George W. Bush. And while they all trail in the polls, each of
Bush's challengers says it is not over yet. As the jockey for
position to pass Bush should he stumble, they fall into two broad
camps. (Sherman, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-PORK _ WASHINGTON _ The House Budget Committee holds a
hearing on unnecessary business subsidies, featuring an array of
congressional and private critics of ``corporate pork.'' The
concern comes amid new reports of overpayments to federal
contractors. (Malone, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES _ WASHINGTON _ Environmental Media Services holds a
discussion on the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers' proposed
restoration project for the Florida Everglades. The $7.8 billion
comprehensive plan will be presented to Congress on Thursday.
(Lipman, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   INS-CRIME _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of
the House immigration subcommittee, holds a news conference to
criticize Immigration and Naturalization Service policies that led
to the release of serial killer Raphael Resendez-Ramirez. (Dart,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   US-MIDEAST _ WASHINGTON _ Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
hailing the ``birth of new hope'' in Israel with the recent
election of a new prime minister, prepares to meet with President
Clinton Thursday amid hopes of jumpstarting the stalled Middle East
peace process. (Deans, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-VIOLENCE _ ATLANTA _ One of metro Atlanta's largest
churches is holding a week-long conference for teens on how to stop
violence and commit themselves to God. Close to 3,000 teenagers
from around the country have come to New Birth Missionary Baptist
Church this week to talk about resolving conflicts peacefully and
to talk about their solutions to problems facing youths. An
afternoon prayer service for schools nationwide is scheduled at a
metro school board office today. (Hill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH P(HOTO.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-ENVOY _ Profile of Gordon Giffin, former Atlanta lawyer
who is kicking up dust in his current post as U.S. ambassador to
Canada. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
