   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning a page of Kosovo coverage:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Bela Crkva) _ Grief and religion vs. forensics
and justice: Albanians clamor for war-crimes teams to come to their
villages so the dead, after mass graves are checked, can at last be
buried properly. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Brussels) _ Developments on settling Russia's
role in the NATO peacekeeping force in Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Others as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Ehud Barak, the prime
minister-elect, is to seal his government's coalition today as the
Shas Party agrees to join. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-U.S. (Washington) _ The U.S. has released 5,000 pages of
Chile-Pinochet-Allende documents that could shed light on the U.S.
role in a turbulent time in Chile's history. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-AID (Washington) _ Congressional action on the $12.6
billion foreign aid bill. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM (Washington) _ The Senate Foreign Relations
Committee approves the nomination of Richard Holbrooke as envoy to
the U.N. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Developments in the
effort to save the Northern Ireland peace plan as a deadline
arrives. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OCALAN (Istanbul) _ Folo on the conviction and death
sentence for Abdullah Ocalan, the Kurdish rebel leader, by a
Turkish court. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-ABORTION (Washington) _ The House is voting on a
proposal to give states more power to ban trips by minors across
state lines to obtain abortions without parental permission. By
David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-EDUC (Washington) _ A House committee tries to gut the
100,000 teacher proposal, the centerpiece of the Clinton-Gore
education initiative. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   HUBBELL-STARR (Washington) _ Webster Hubbell and Kenneth Starr
appear in court to seal their plea agreement agreement. By Neil A.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-EVERGLADES (Washington) _ Vice President Gore is to bring
to Congress the final plan on saving the Florida Everglades, and
asks lawmakers to approve the $4 billion needed from the federal
government. A matching sum would come from the state. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Chicago) _ President Clinton, in Chicago, talks about
Medicare, the surplus and the Chicago Cubs. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   ST-PETE-RACE (St. Petersburg, Fla.) _ St. Petersburg tries to
figure out how to make amends for a racial incident that occurred
30 years ago but still mars its reputation today. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-MAYOR-INDICT (San Diego, Calif.) _ A civil grand jury, a
rare institution in American, issues a non-criminal indictment
against its mayor, claiming she exceeded her authority in an effort
to keep the Major League baseball franchise, the Padres, in town.
By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CUBANS (Miami) _ Four Cuban boat people intercepted just
yards off the Florida coast will be allowed to stay in the United
States at least temporarily, federal officials said Wednesday. By
Pamela Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART (Undated) _ Despite previous estimates that mitral
valve prolapse affects 5 percent to 35 percent of the population, a
new report has found that the condition, in which a valve in the
heart is abnormally long and floppy, is much less common and much
less serious. By Holcomb B. Noble. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ Federal Reserve policy-makers are
expected to announce a quarter-point increase in short-term
interest rates at the conclusion of their two-day meeting.
(Announcement set for 2:15 p.m. EDT) By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   3M-OUTLOOK (St. Paul, Minn.) _ Try as it may, the Minnesota
Mining and Manufacturing Corp. is having trouble shaking Wall
Street's perception of the company as a boring, low-technology
drone whose glory days ended with Scotch tape and Post-it notes.
The problem, however, is not just image: earnings have been
sluggish in the last two years, and the company's management has
come under increasingly sharp criticism. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BANKS (Washington) _ Looking ahead at Thursday's
expected House vote on a bill to overhaul financial services
regulation, repealing the Glass-Steagall Act. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   FRONTIER-QWEST (Undated) _ Frontier says it will explore Qwest
Communications' revised offer. Other developments. By Laura M.
Holson.
</P>
<P>
   PROCTOR-ANIMAL-TESTS (Undated) _ Proctor &AMP; Gamble says it will
end its use of animal tests for beauty, fabric and home care and
paper products, except where required by law. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-WARNING (Undated) _ Coca-Cola warns that second-quarter
earnings will be hurt by recalls and bans on its drinks in Europe
and declining sales in some of its major overseas markets. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 11 a.m., stocks were slightly lower, as
investors awaited a decision by the Federal Reserve. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 0.53 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 down 0.72
percent, and Nasdaq is down 0.5 percent. The 30-year bond was
yielding 6.10 percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-AIRBUS (Undated) _ Looking at the battle between Airbus
Industrie and Boeing after Boeing agreed to buy 17 wide-body Airbus
planes from Singapore Airlines so that the airline can buy 10 new
Boeing 777's. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-COPPER (Undated) _ Merrill Lynch announces settlements
with the Commodity Futures Trading Commission and the London Metal
Exchange in connection with the 1995 Sumitomo copper trading
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-BANKS (Rome) _ In the latest round of European bank
consolidation, two of Italy's biggest banks, Banca Intesa, the
nation's second largest, and Banca Commerciale Italiana, the No.4,
are expected to approve today a merger that would create Italy's
largest banking group with assets of about $290 billion. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Beijing) _ The Chinese government appears to be
stiff-arming the United States on resuming WTO talks, raising
speculation they have lost interest for now. Also, parting remarks
of Ambassador James Sasser, who leaves Thursday. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   SAMSUNG-MOTOR (Tokyo) _ Samsung Group of South Korea applies for
court receivership for Samsung Motor Inc., though it still hopes to
sell the troubled 15-month-old carmaker after failing to persuade
Daewoo Motor Co. to take it over. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By
Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America'' and William Safire's ``Essay.''
</P>
