<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4718 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-WEST-HNS &LR;      06-30 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-WEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILD WEST,' MILD AT BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Men in Black'' was a triple scoop of school's-out giddiness:
hip, funny, casual about plot and not overawed by its special
effects.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Wild Wild West,'' the same actor-director team shoots
again, and misses by a Hollywood mile. These pictures need a light
touch and a lot of attitude, but this time you can hear heavy
breathing in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Like the '60s TV series that inspired it, ``Wild Wild West''
counts on a loony premise to carry it off. It was a spy spoof full
of gadgets and attractive women, which was common enough at the
time, but the setting was the American West, post-Civil War era.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of sleek modern equipment, these secret agents used
wooden and brass gizmos powered by steam, a la Jules Verne, which
made the show unique and caught the public's eye (it ran four
seasons).
</P>
<P>
   The movie offers affable Will Smith as Jim West, the more
two-fisted of the show's secret-agent duo. West's buddy is Artemus
Gordon (Kevin Kline), a prissy inventor and master of disguise who
fights with brains instead of guns. Kline is nice casting _ his
Gordon has refinement and wit missing in the impulsive West. And
Smith thrives in a team: ``Men in Black'' worked partly because he
could riff off the deadpan demeanor of co-star Tommy Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the chemistry isn't here, and it's probably more the fault
of the roles than the actors, who seem game enough. The TV Jim West
(Robert Conrad) was rough, ready and studly, and not much else.
This would seem to give the filmmakers plenty of room to make
something interesting out of the role, but other than playing off
the racism endemic to the Old West, they don't. So Kline is left to
operate in a vacuum, which he can do _ but you can't help feeling
that a nice opportunity's been muffed.
</P>
<P>
   There's the slimmest excuse for a plot here, but in classic
blockbuster fashion it only serves the bare purposes of bringing
the main characters on screen and justifying the special effects.
</P>
<P>
   West and Gordon are assigned by President Ulysses S. Grant to
find out why America's top scientists are being abducted. The
answer is a conspiracy headed by a die-hard supporter of the
recently defeated Confederacy, the grotesque Dr. Arliss Loveless
(Kenneth Branagh), who wants to assassinate the president and divvy
up the country. Branagh sports an elaborately trimmed beard and
chews the scenery _ why not? _ and gets another chance to fool
around with the Southern accent he used in ``The Gingerbread Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Salma Hayek also is on hand, in a role that openly tweaks the
general uselessness of the female ``love interest'' in this kind of
buddy film.
</P>
<P>
   OK, this is supposed to be the big July 4 Will Smith
extravaganza, but the real star is The Tarantula, a huge, walking
contraption that's a combination tank, personnel carrier and weapon
of destruction _ all shaped like a colossal spider. It's Loveless'
invention, and it's intended to bring the United States to its
knees. As this monster clanks across the Western desert, the
special-effects team is in heaven. (The other chief gadget is the
handsome train car assigned to the two agents that's full of
elaborately silly gimcracks and weapons.)
</P>
<P>
   Director Barry Sonnenfeld, who began his career as a
cinematographer (and employs the outstanding Michael Ballhaus in
that role here), relishes loving attention on the look of the film,
an off-kilter vision of 19th-century luxury. He showed a nice
satirical touch in ``The Addams Family'' and its sequel, but he
can't seem to get anything going here _ it's like an Artemus Gordon
contrivance that won't quite work.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters: It's summer, and you already can hear kids
on the street singing the movie's hip-hop theme song (performed by
Smith). It's all about marketing, and this picture needs it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1449EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
