   SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ They are the great matching cornerstones of late
medieval literature: ``The Canterbury Tales,'' verse narratives
studied by college English majors in the original Middle English,
but requiring translation into ``modern'' English for the lay
reader; and ``The Decameron,'' composed in Latin prose and
translated almost immediately into romance languages. By LARRY
SWINDELL. Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SOUTH PARK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Think of the most horrendously offensive elements of
Comedy Central's crudely animated and even more crudely written
``South Park'' _ whether that be singing and dancing feces; Chef's
R-rated, libidinous songs; or any assortment of jibes aimed at
women, racial minorities, gays, organized religion or the disabled.
Now take those elements and multiply them by, oh, say a thousand.
Now you might have some idea of what to expect from the network's
new spinoff film, ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut,'' the most
unapologetically offensive movie to ever come out of Hollywood. And
did I mention it's also hilarious? By TODD CAMP. Story will move in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WILD WEST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Anyone who bothers to complain about ``Wild, Wild
West'' because of its African-American star _ Will Smith plays
James West, essentially the first Secret Service agent _ misses the
point. The original series didn't exactly radiate historical
accuracy either. And never has a star seemed to enjoy himself so
much as Smith. His uncomplicated sunniness makes him look as if
he's never missed a night's sleep in his entire life. And he's so
contemporary he might as well be the only cowboy on the range to
carry a cell phone and a pager. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story will move
in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VAN ZANDT-CD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Master songwriter and Fort Worth native Townes Van
Zandt died in 1997, but his music lives again today with the
release of ``A Far Cry From Dead,'' a collection of rerecorded
versions of favorites such as ``Pancho and Lefty'' and ``To Live Is
to Fly'' assembled by his widow, Jeanene, and respected Nashville
producer Eric Paul. The 13-track CD also includes Van Zandt's final
composition, the chilling ``Sanitarium Blues.'' By DAVE FERMAN.
Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   T E X A S &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHAPMAN-TEXAS AT LARGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The Fourth of July is a big time in Sanderson, always
has been. There will be an antique car show, rodeo, baseball
tournament, American Legion barbecue, old settlers' reunion and a
street dance. ``We call it a concert so the Baptists will come,''
Terrell County Judge Dudley Harrison said. But there will be more
than just fireworks at this year's celebration. This is the year
that Sanderson begins its comeback. Maybe. By ART CHAPMAN. Story
will move in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F O O D A N D D I N I N G &QL; 
 &QL;
