<HEADER>
A4744 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FROZENTREATS-TEX     06-30 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROZENTREATS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROZEN SUMMERTIME FAVORITES GROW UP WITH A SOPHISTICATED TWIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kids shouldn't have all the fun this weekend. Jolly up the
festivities for the grown-ups with some upscale takes on childhood
summer favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Add a splash of tequila to the Popsicles, some white wine to the
lemonade, and have yourself a sparkling Fourth. And don't forget to
run through the sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Cool comforts
</P>
<P>
   Popsicle: Invented by 11-year-old Frank Epperson when he left a
mixing stick in a glass of juice on a windowsill. In 1922, he
introduced the Epsicle and, wisely, later changed the name to
Popsicle.
</P>
<P>
   Granita: A classic frozen mixture of water, sugar and liquid
flavoring such as fruit juice, wine or coffee. Ices are stirred
often while freezing to yield a granular texture.
</P>
<P>
   Sorbet: Smoother than a granita but lighter and softer than a
sherbet; sorbets never contain milk.
</P>
<P>
   Sherbet: A combination of water and sweetened fruit juice. It
can also contain milk, egg whites or gelatin. It's heavier than
sorbet but lighter than ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   KIWI MARGARITA POPS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 11 pops
</P>
<P>
   6 kiwifruit, peeled and cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup tequila
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 cup orange liqueur
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   11 craft sticks
</P>
<P>
   Process first 5 ingredients in food processor until smooth.
Spoon mixture evenly into 1/4-cup molds; freeze 30 minutes or until
firm. Insert wooden sticks and freeze at least 5 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per pop: 94 calories, 0 fat, 12 grams
carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _Southern Living
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SANGRIA POPS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 20
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce can frozen lemonade concentrate, thawed and undiluted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   20 wooden craft sticks
</P>
<P>
   Stir together first 5 ingredients until sugar dissolves. Pour
evenly into 1/4-cup molds; freeze 30 minutes or until firm. Insert
wooden sticks and freeze at least 5 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per pop: 79 calories, 0 fat, 17 grams
carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _Southern Living
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE FLOAT POPS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 20
</P>
<P>
   1 quart orange sherbet, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup orange soft drink
</P>
<P>
   20 wooden craft sticks
</P>
<P>
   Stir together sherbet and orange soft drink. Spoon evenly into
1/4-cup molds; freeze 30 minutes or until firm. Insert wooden
sticks and freeze at least 5 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per pop: 61 calories, 1 gram fat, 13 grams
carbohydrates, trace protein, 3 milligrams cholesterol, 19
milligrams sodium, 12 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _Southern Living
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ROOT-BEER GRANITA AND VANILLA PARFAIT
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 cups root beer, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 pint (2 cups) vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Pour 2 cups of root beer into ice trays to depth of no more than
1/2-inch (keep remaining root beer refrigerated until ready to
use). Freeze trays overnight, along with tall glasses or parfaits.
</P>
<P>
   Unmold cubes into food processor fitted with metal blade.
Process, pulsing until just crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Place straw in each glass, leaning alongside. Layer parfaits by
alternating scoops of root-beer granita and vanilla ice cream,
ending with scoop of ice cream on top. Pour remaining root beer
into glasses at table. Serve with mini Tootsie Rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 415 calories, 15 grams fat, 70
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 60 milligrams cholesterol,
155 milligrams sodium, 30 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _Brasserie T, Chicago
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WATERMELON GRANITA-FILLED LIME CUPS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   12 limes (reserve 2 tablespoons juice)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   4 cups watermelon cubes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup currants or raisins
</P>
<P>
   Crushed ice (optional)
</P>
<P>
   To make lime cups: Cut limes in half lengthwise; cut around pulp
of each half with sharp knife, leaving peel intact. Scoop out pulp,
using spoon to loosen pulp from peel. Reserve 2 tablespoons lime
juice for granita. Set lime cups aside.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together sugar and water in small saucepan; heat to
boiling. Cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Place watermelon in container of food processor; pulse to puree.
</P>
<P>
   Place colander over bowl; pour pureed watermelon into colander
to strain out seeds, forcing watermelon through with back of spoon,
if needed. Stir reserved lime juice and cooled sugar mixture into
pureed watermelon. Pour into 13-by-9-by-2-inch pan; freeze until
firm, about 4 hours. To serve, scrape frozen watermelon mixture
with spoon to make granita. Stir in currants for ``seeds.'' Mound
granita in lime cups; serve on bed of crushed ice.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 119 calories, trace fat, 31
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 4 milligrams
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _Brasserie T, Chicago
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MOCHA JAVA GRANITA
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sparkling mineral water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup instant espresso powder
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cocoa, preferably Dutch process
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   25-ounce bottle sparkling mineral water
</P>
<P>
   Lemon twists, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   In small saucepan, bring sugar and 1/2 cup sparkling water to
boil; cook 1 minute until sugar is completely dissolved. Remove
from heat and gradually stir in espresso powder and cocoa. Set
aside and cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   In 9-inch square, metal pan, combine espresso mixture, vanilla
and 25-ounce bottle sparkling mineral water. Freeze 4-6 hours until
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Using a fork, chop granita into fine chunks. Serve immediately
in wineglasses or dessert dishes; garnish with lemon twists and if
desired, serve with fancy cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 111 calories, trace fat, 28
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 2 milligrams
sodium, 2 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _Perrier
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BASIL-VERMOUTH ICE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white vermouth
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   4 peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   Strip leaves from 1 basil sprig and set them aside. Tear
remaining basil into pieces and place in saucepan, stems and all.
Add water, sugar, vermouth, lemon juice and peppercorns. Slowly
bring to a boil. Remove from heat, cover and let stand for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Strain liquid through a sieve into a metal mixing bowl. Slice
reserved basil leaves into thin strips and stir into liquid. Place
in freezer and freeze until half-frozen. Whisk to break up ice
crystals and return to freezer. Continue freezing and whisking
until mixture is stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Scoop into martini glasses and garnish with tiny sprigs of
basil.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 137 calories, 0 fat, 34 grams
carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _Martini &AMP; Rossi
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
