<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-PARK-HNS &LR;      06-30 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PARK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTH PARK': BIGGER, LONGER AND SILLIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a while, Trey Parker and Matt Stone seemed like a couple of
alpha males with a broken funny bone. Parker's flaccid porn lampoon
``Orgazmo'' and the duo's participation in ``BASEketball'' (they
starred), didn't exactly court brilliance. And their Comedy Central
animated series, ``South Park,'' had a spiteful elan that longevity
had been tamping into redundancy.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker and Stone's intrepid, shockingly indispensable and,
yes, take-no-prisoners hysterical ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and
Uncut'' has a crafty focus and ultimately a genius the equivalent
of walking into a glass door. Who knew it was there?
</P>
<P>
   As television, ``South Park'' was Parker and Stone's calling
card, and it only grows weary as it finds itself in a TV-censor
headlock, reiterating its agenda to bust convention's chops while
getting mired in some pretty standard fare of its own. Funny as it
often is, the show, about four kids and their eponymous Colorado
town, rarely has had the offensive scope and pointed verve of the
inaugural ``Spirit of Christmas'' short that launched ``South
Park'' into the subconscious of thousands via the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Crass, reactionary, shallow, the show was a diabolical
``Peanuts'' _ or an anti-``Simpsons,'' a series whose unsinkable
wit made Parker and Stone look like a couple of trigger-happy
button-pushers interested in seeing what their brand of juvenilia
could get away with next.
</P>
<P>
   Simply, it was their warm-up for the facetious bloodletting that
is ``Bigger, Longer and Uncut,'' a wicked musical satire that
manages to nestle itself smack in the midst of the censorship vs.
First Amendment debate that chews it up and spews it out as pop
culture detritus.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing _ not Saddam Hussein, not the Baldwin brothers, not even
Gandhi _ is sacred or safe. The film's fire-breathing gets under
way in the snowbound Dr. Suess-y opening number (written by Parker
and Hollywood schmaltz composer Marc Shaiman, who gets an
impossible make-over and animated cameo as the piano accompaniment
for the chintzy emcee Big Gay Al).
</P>
<P>
   The show's bite-size, middle-school regulars _ Cartman, Stan,
Kyle and Kenny _ are elated to see their heroes Terrance and
Phillip's ``R''-rated foray into big-screen flatulence. Terrance
and Phillip's show gives the boys the revelation that will drop
their jaws and change their lives: Compulsive swearing. Soon every
Brian Boitano-loving 12-year-old in South Park has busted into an
outrageous foul-language freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   TV characters have had to become movie characters to shift the
bad-influence argument from television to film. It's a shrewd,
awesome indictment of the faux malleability of young minds that
explodes into a war between South Park's youth and their irate
parents led by Kyle's mother, Sheila Broflovski. The adults are
looking for someone to blame, so they aim their contempt at Canada,
Terrance and Phillip's home.
</P>
<P>
   Armageddon ensues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger, Longer and Uncut'' is a seismically satiric grab-bag
of artifacts, allusions, current events and kitsch that, unlike the
virtually plotless ``Spy Who Shagged Me,'' is dumped into the
film's three fine-tuned acts. Along with co-writer Pam Brady,
Parker and Stone have imagined the film, which Parker directs, as a
taloned Gilbert and Sullivan-mock-Broadway musical with a libretto
taut enough to make you renew belief in people breaking into song.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it works here not only because it's absurd but
because it's a brand of levity that serves as a respite from the
apocalyptic war being fought over Canada's American infiltration.
</P>
<P>
   The parents coalition strategizes to have Terrance and Phillip
electric-chaired in the midst of Big Gay Al's USO execution
extravaganza. Residents of South Park enlist in the Army to
obliterate the Canadians. ``Canada Sucks'' burnings are held _ and
even Canadian popster Alanis Morissette gets tossed in as tinder.
The kids, meanwhile _ led by Gregory, an urbane ``Les Miz'' reject
_ want to end the government practice of loading millions of
Canadians onto trucks and moving them to internment camps.
</P>
<P>
   This is merciless, but Parker and Stone use cynical insanity to
mock the misfired righteousness that obstructs common sense and
good parenting. How many mothers would jump at the chance to insert
an electro-shock V-Chip inside her potty-mouthed son, as Mrs.
Cartman does to Eric? It's just that much easier to let the
government wash your kid's mouth out with soap than to do it
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   One of the elements often overlooked about ``South Park'' is its
multitextured, arts-and-crafts look, which is key to its
subversiveness. On a big screen, laid out in all its homemade
pop-collage glory, ``South Park'' is a bracing aberration. It's a
world with the dimensional width of a portable ant farm. The
inhabitants look as if they were conceived from a still life done
on a Technicolor Etch-a-Sketch with an assortment of Peanuts and
Fisher Price roly-poly people for models. Parker and Stone use
their movie as an opportunity to imbue ``South Park'' with computer
effects that jab at movie digitalization.
</P>
<P>
   They kill Kenny early, and his afterlife is spent in a hell that
looks like the cover art of any metal record come to Satanic life.
His face still swallowed by his hood, Kenny, of course, remains his
construction paper-and-cardboard self now living in
computer-generated-imagery hell. It's a stark contrast to his
Colorado home. In hell, he's lorded over by a muscle-bound Satan
and his sexed-up paramour, Saddam Hussein, a magazine photo imposed
on a drawn body.
</P>
<P>
   The lovers are plotting to take over the world amid the first
amendment hells-a-poppin' on Earth. Theirs is a ridiculous,
astonishingly civil send-up of gay relationships.
</P>
<P>
   We learn that Satan's a closeted Samaritan in a joyless romance
who's been brainwashed to accept his evil role just because he
happens to be the devil. Parker and Stone have made the Lord of
Darkness the most developed, recognizably human gay character I've
ever seen in a Hollywood movie.
</P>
<P>
   It's terrifying to think that ``South Park'' would have
something inspiring to sing about the gay lifestyle _ or figure
skater Brian Boitano, for that matter _ when the image machine is
content to keep the stereotypes rolling off the assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no shame in finding supreme brilliance in a movie
peopled by a clique of vulgar friends who curse with more skillful
abandon than some hip-hoppers can rap.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Stone have given us scathing but optimistic savagery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
