<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4793 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     06-30 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COWBOY IN LA _ AND ON THE AIRWAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his hugely successful cookbook ``A Cowboy in the Kitchen,''
author and Reata executive chef Grady Spears writes: ``Back when I
was punching cows, if you'd told me I was going to be a chef
someday, I would have doubled up in laughter and fallen off my
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for Spears to be on horseback any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Reata restaurants, prosperous in Fort Worth and Alpine,
Texas, will be joined in September by a third on Rodeo Drive in Los
Angeles. Spears' cookbook, a well-written and illustrated
compilation of Reata and Trans-Pecos recipes, will be joined by two
other Spears works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cowboy Cocktails'' will be a collection of western drinks and
bar food. It is expected out in February. ``The Great Steak Book,''
full of beef recipes, grilling instructions and marinade recipes,
is expected in May.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough to keep the onetime cowboy out of the
saddle, he will soon begin production on a 26-week TV cooking show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is kind of weird,'' Spears said. ``I never did think about
doing a television show until I met Torri Randall in Los Angeles.
She asked me if anyone had asked about doing a TV show, and when I
told her no, she asked if I was interested. I said, `I guess.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Randall has produced several TV cooking shows for public
television and became interested in Spears after seeing a copy of
``A Cowboy in the Kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, she got the book for Christmas and loved it,''
Spears said. ``Now we are in pre-production, and it's been crazy. I
never even thought about doing this. It's like the book _ I never
thought about doing that either.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that planning is under way, Spears has become excited
about the project. Every segment of the cooking show will be shot
on location. That means someone's ranch, and that means Spears will
feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not going to be a set,'' he said. ``Sets are really
sterile; you have the same kitchens, the same things around you.
This is going to be on different ranches.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall has been in Texas to scout locations. Obviously, some
segments will be shot at Al Micallef's picturesque CF Ranch in
Alpine. Micallef is co-owner of the Reata group.
</P>
<P>
   Local rancher and horsewoman Kit Moncrief has offered her ranch
as a location, and ``they are really excited about that,'' Spears
said. ``Their minds are just kind of running. Everybody has been so
helpful; we're going to have more things to shoot than we ever
thought about.''
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour shows will be shot in February, weather
permitting. Spears said the shooting will probably take at least a
month and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do things related to the cookbook,'' he said.
``Actually, we'll feature recipes from all three books. We'll have
segments on `Chuck Box Secrets,' things like seasonings, blends and
sauces.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he never really thought of doing his own TV series,
Spears has done quite a bit of television. ``The more you get in
front of the camera, the more comfortable you get,'' he said. ``I
think shooting on locations will be easier than a studio. You don't
get bored with it. There is always something new.''
</P>
<P>
   The new series, also called ``A Cowboy in the Kitchen,'' will
crowd an already busy schedule for Spears.
</P>
<P>
   Spears will shepherd all of the events from his home in Texas.
He says he has no intentions of moving his base.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to LA, after about four days, I'm ready to come home
to Texas,'' he said. ``I'll never leave Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sample of Spears ingenuity from ``A Cowboy in the
Kitchen'' ($29.95, Ten Speed Press):
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CATFISH CAKES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 10
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds boneless, skinless catfish fillets, cut into 1-inch
dice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno pepper, stemmed, seeded, and minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely diced red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup thinly sliced chives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups fresh or dried white bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lime zest
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a skillet over medium heat. Add the catfish,
onion, peppers and garlic. Saute until the vegetables are wilted
and the catfish is cooked through, about 5 minutes. In a large
bowl, combine the cooked fish and vegetables, mayonnaise, chives,
cilantro, mustard, crumbs, egg, zest, salt, and pepper. Form the
mixed ingredients into 10 3-ounce patties. Pack the mixture fairly
tight so it will stay together while cooking. Set aside on a plate.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the peanut oil in a pan until smoking slightly. Dust each
cake with flour and gently slip it into the hot oil. Fry the cakes
for approximately 2 minutes on each side, or until they are golden
brown. Do not crowd the cakes; it is better to cook in batches.
Remove the cakes and drain them on a paper towel-lined pan. Serve
hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 318 calories, 24 grams fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 18 grams protein, 102 milligrams cholesterol,
167 milligrams sodium, 67 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
