<HEADER>
A4804 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     06-30 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAYING IT IN PIXELS, ROUND 2 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Digital cameras are getting better and faster and cheaper at a
motor-drive pace. A year ago the price of megapixel cameras, so
called because they capture images made up of more than a million
picture elements, fell below $1,000 for the first time. Now we are
seeing the first 2-megapixel cameras in the same price range, and
the best one so far is the Nikon Coolpix 950.
</P>
<P>
   The Coolpix 950 is available from several web-based retailers
for about $800. The camera is in demand among serious amateur
digital photographers not only because of its excellent image
quality, but also because it allows greater control over shutter
speed, contrast, image quality, brightness and metering _ features
that make the rest of us appreciate the simplicity of
point-and-shoot cameras. But fear not: the Coolpix 950 can also
turn out superior shots without requiring a lot of twiddling.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, the camera is so good overall that its handful of
flaws stand out in sharp contrast, and become more vexing. And
because it is the first digital camera that I have seriously
considered as a replacement for my ancient but beloved
35-millimeter Leica, the Coolpix 950 may have inadvertently
persuaded me that I may not want a digital camera after all _ or at
least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   But first, let's focus on why the new Nikon is so good. For
starters, it takes sharp, detailed pictures. Like all other digital
cameras, it records the images not on film, but on a silicon sensor
called a charge-coupled device, or CCD. The Coolpix 950 has a
half-inch CCD that can capture 2.1 million pixels.
</P>
<P>
   With digital cameras, the difference between a shot captured at
2.1 megapixels and one at, say, 1.6 megapixels, is more apparent to
the printer than to the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the lowest-cost, sub-megapixel digital cameras today
gather enough picture information to make a decent 4-inch by 6-inch
print, but with any size larger than that the image begins to break
up because often there are not enough pixels to fill the area. As a
result, the cheaper digital cameras are used mainly for instant
photography where image quality is not paramount, or for small
pictures like head shots for an employee data base, or pictures of
the new baby for a web page.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the first megapixel cameras boasted that they had
sufficient resolution to make a decent 8-by-10 print, but not all
of them did. The new Nikon and other 2MP cameras pass the 8-by-10
test easily. (If you do not anticipate printing such large
pictures, you may be happier with a less-expensive megapixel camera
like the excellent Kodak DC-265.
</P>
<P>
   The Coolpix 950 is just a bit too large and heavy to fit
comfortably in a pocket, but it feels solid and secure in the hand.
With its two-piece, hinged design, and a swiveling lens unit, it
does not look like a conventional camera. One can frame and focus
the shot through the lens in the view-finder, or on a 2-inch color
liquid crystal display on the back.
</P>
<P>
   The camera stores its images on a matchbook-sized Type 1 Compact
Flash card. The card that comes with the Nikon holds 8 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   And here is where some little things about the Nikon began to
annoy me. Eight megabytes is a very stingy amount of storage for a
2-megapixel camera. While one can reduce the image quality and size
to fit more shots on the card, most people who spend this kind of
money for a 2MP camera will want to shoot at the top
(1,600-by-1,200 pixels) resolution with minimal image compression.
Doing so limits the number of shots that can be saved on the basic
card, to 16 shots at normal compression, which causes some loss of
image quality, or even just 1 shot with no compression. After that,
the card has to be emptied by discarding shots or transferring them
to a PC.
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to buy a larger-capacity card, but a 64-megabyte
Type 1 card costs $160 or more. Or, Nikon could have added a
slightly larger Type II slot, which would have enabled the Coolpix
950 to use IBM's expensive but clever new 340MB Microdrive. But it
didn't. And it placed the Compact Flash card slot on the bottom of
the camera, which means that to change memory cards, tripod users
have to break down and then set up their shots all over again.
</P>
<P>
   And to transfer the images to a computer, Nikon includes only a
serial port cable, which is agonizingly slow. It should have used a
faster USB port, or an even faster IEEE 1394 (Firewire) port.
</P>
<P>
   The Nikon eats batteries like a goat, going through a set of
double-A alkalines in about a half hour. So, if you plan to spend
the day shooting pictures, you should also plan to pick up a couple
of sets of rechargeable nickel metal hydride (NiMH) batteries
(about $10 for a set of four, plus $8 or so for a recharger). For
indoor work, an AC power converter is a must. Instead of standard
equipment, however, it is a $59 option.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, the Coolpix 950's many positives (image quality,
feature set, zoom lens, superb macro focus, and so on) far outweigh
its negatives (occasionally poor low-light focusing, battery
gluttony, limited memory, port problems, et cetera).
</P>
<P>
   Because it is so good overall, the Coolpix 950 caused me to
think about giving up the Leicaflex my father loaned me some 30
years ago. (I'll return it soon, Dad, I promise.) The Leica is
magnificently un-digital, as rugged and heavy as a brick, but it
takes great 35-millimeter pictures.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, thanks to a new service called Kodak Picture CD, it can
take great digital pictures, too _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak, in partnership with the Intel Corporation, has made it
easier for people to get involved with digital photography. The
photographer takes a roll of film to be processed, checks the box
for Picture CD, and receives back not just a set of prints, but
also a compact disc that contains high-quality digitized images of
all the shots plus an assortment of simple photo-editing programs.
</P>
<P>
   Let's compare: I can spend $1,000 (counting accessories) on the
Nikon, and I'll have a top-quality digital camera that gives me the
instant gratification of seeing all my shots on the camera's LCD
screen. I'll never have to buy film or visit a processing lab
again. In just a few minutes, the images are in my computer, where
they can be cropped, touched up, sent to grandma by e-mail, posted
on a web site, or printed. Plus, digital cameras are cool.
</P>
<P>
   Or, I can take any existing 35-millimeter camera _ even one of
the cheap disposable kind _ shoot a roll of film, drive to the
drugstore, and get a Kodak Picture CD back along with my prints in
48 hours for an extra $8.95 to $10.95 on top of the photo
development charges. Eventually, Kodak and Intel say, they will
offer one-hour CD service. Even at a 48-hour turnaround time, it is
a bit faster than sending the film to one of several mail-order
developers, like Seattle Filmworks (www.seattlefilmworks.com), who
post the customer's digitized prints on a password-protected web
site 24 hours after the film reaches the company.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's nationwide network of film processing labs, using
powerful Intel workstation computers, scan the 35-millimeter shots
at a resolution of 1,536-by-1,024 pixels and scan Advanced Photo
System shots at 1,536-by-864 pixels. This is not as sharp as
Nikon's 1,600-by-1,200, but better than most digital cameras today.
Then I can transfer the photo files from my disk and manage them
any way I like, just as if they came from a digital camera.
</P>
<P>
   For those who are committed to the idea of digital photography,
buying a digital camera makes sense. For those who are intrigued
but still unsure, the Picture CD route is a less-expensive way to
get started.
</P>
<P>
   And that raises the old obsolescence bugaboo that is so familiar
to people who own anything with a computer chip in it.
</P>
<P>
   The Leicaflex, despite once being dropped from a hot-air
balloon, takes pictures today that are just as sharp as the ones it
took in 1969. I can't imagine using the same digital camera for 30
years, when I know that a better-faster-cheaper camera will be
available from Nikon and other companies by this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spend $1,000 on a 35-millimeter camera, you get a very
good camera that you're probably planning to keep for a number of
years,'' said Jon Pepper, chief editor of the digital imaging
newsletter Digital Focus (www.digfocus.com). ``Technology products
get cheaper and cheaper, but if you have to replace them every few
years, maybe they're not that great a value.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
