<HEADER>
A4813 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOSANGELES-TOURBOX-LA     06-30 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSANGELES-TOURBOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR GUIDANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRIFFITH OBSERVATORY: The observatory can be reached from either
Vermont Avenue or Hillhurst Drive off Los Feliz Boulevard. As you
near the observatory, ignore the sign that says ``Observatory
traffic use tunnel'' and instead bear left, away from the tunnel.
Climb the hill and park on the right-hand side of the roadway at
the first opportunity, then walk up. (The tunnel guides you to a
parking lot that is tiny and frequently jammed.) During summer, the
Hall of Science (no admission) is open from 12:30 p.m. until 10
p.m. daily. Planetarium and Laserium shows are also presented at
the observatory. Planetarium info: (323) 664-1191. Laserium info:
(818) 901-9405. Visit www.griffithobs.org on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   SUNSET BOULEVARD: Particularly on the drive through Pacific
Palisades and Brentwood, be advised that the LAPD is especially
vigilant on enforcing the 35 mph speed limit. In Hollywood, lunch
for two at Carney's can be had for about $13; the cross street is
Kings Road.
</P>
<P>
   THE GETTY CENTER: Getty Center Drive has offramps from both
directions on the 405 Freeway. There is no admission charge for the
museum, which is open 11 a.m. to 7 p.m. Tuesdays through Fridays,
11 a.m. to 9 p.m. Saturdays and 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Sunday. It is
closed Mondays and major holidays. Parking is $5 and a reservation
is required. Information: (310) 440-7300. It's recommended to call
for a reservation at least a week in advance, but demand varies
depending on events at the museum, and sometimes a slot can be
found on short notice; www.getty.edu on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   MULHOLLAND DRIVE: There is an exit for this road from both
directions of the San Diego (405) Freeway. One advisory on the
route: There is one stretch of the drive where Mulholland Drive and
Coldwater Canyon Avenue coincide, and if you're traveling east, you
must make a sharp left turn. It's about six miles in; watch for the
signs.
</P>
<P>
   LONG BEACH AQUARIUM OF THE PACIFIC: Take the Long Beach (710)
Freeway south to its termination, then follow the ``Aquarium''
signs. The complex is open 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. every day but
Christmas. Admission is $14.95 for adults, $11.95 for seniors 60
and up, $7.95 for children ages 3-11. Parking is $2 an hour to a
maximum of $6. Information: (562) 590-3100;
www.aquariumofpacific.org on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON LIBRARY: The entrance is at the corner of Orlando
Road and Allen Avenue in San Marino. During summer, the library is
open 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Tuesday through Sunday. Admission is
$8.50 for adults, $7 for seniors 65 and up, $5 for students 12 and
up. Children under 12 are free. Admission is free for everyone on
the first Thursday of every month. Information: (626) 405-2100;
www.huntington.org on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   MALIBU/ZUMA BEACH: Parking at the state beaches at Zuma at Point
Dume is $6 daily. For lunch at Duke's (Las Flores Canyon at Pacific
Coast Highway), sandwiches are $7 to $14, salads are $3 to $11,
fresh-fish main courses are $8 to $12.
</P>
<P>
   OLVERA STREET: It is at the confluence of three streets on the
northeastern edge of downtown L.A.: Main and Alameda streets and
Cesar E. Chavez Avenue. Parking can be found on Main near Chavez.
On weekends and holidays, parking costs $5; on weekdays it is $1.25
per 20 minutes, to a maximum of $7.50. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
