<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4817 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     06-30 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR MEAL WILL GO BETTER WITH THIS CAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Debbie Collins e-mails a request for a Coca-Cola cake. Here's
one from the Internet at www.wwki.com, a radio station Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The second offering was sent in by Susan Harrison of Bedford,
Texas, who saw the recipe for spaghetti salad we ran last week. She
clipped this recipe from the Fort Worth Star-Telegram some time ago
and writes that it always gets raves.
</P>
<P>
   COKE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8-10
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Coca-Cola
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar and flour in large bowl. In a saucepan, combine
butter, shortening, cocoa and Coke; heat until butter is melted.
Pour over flour mixture and stir well by hand. Add buttermilk,
soda, eggs, vanilla and marshmallows. Mix well by hand and spoon
into a well-greased 9-by-13-by-2-inch pan. Marshmallows will tend
to lump in one place; distribute them thoroughly in pan. Bake in
preheated 350-degree oven for 45 minutes or until cake tests done.
Spread with frosting while cake is still hot.
</P>
<P>
   Frosting:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons Coca-Cola
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1 pound powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   About 5 minutes before cake is done, combine butter, Coke and
cocoa, and bring to a boil. Stir in other ingredients and pour over
hot cake while it is still in the pan. Topping will be thin, but
will thicken as it cools on the cake. Cool in pan until cake is
completely cool before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 809 calories, 38 grams fat,
117 grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 93 milligrams
cholesterol, 301 milligrams sodium, 42 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   SPAGHETTI SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serve 8-10
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spaghetti, broken in half
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon poppy seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 medium cucumber, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, diced
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce bottle Italian dressing
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons seasoned salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   Parsley sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Cook spaghetti according to package directions. Drain, rinse
with cold water, drain well. Transfer to a large bowl. In a medium
bowl, whisk together salad dressing, cheese, seeds, seasoned salt,
paprika, garlic powder and peppers until well blended. Stir in
cucumber and onion. Pour over spaghetti and toss lightly to coat
evenly. Cover and refrigerate at least 2 hours or up to 24 hours.
Garnish with tomatoes and parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 369 calories, 20 grams fat, 41
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, trace of cholesterol, 504
milligrams sodium, 48 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
