<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE SANDERSON SETTLES ON A PRICKLY SOLUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fourth of July is a big time in Sanderson; always has been.
This year, the festivities will include an antique car show, rodeo,
baseball tournament, American Legion barbecue, old settlers'
reunion and a street dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it a concert so the Baptists will come,'' Terrell
County Judge Dudley Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be more than just fireworks at this year's
celebration. This is the year that Sanderson begins its comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Bypassed years ago by Interstate 10 from San Antonio to El Paso,
Sanderson has quietly dried up.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of the people counted in the 1990 Census have
left. The 1,000 remaining residents have watched the economic
mainstays of wool and the railroad disappear like sand through
their fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we've been hurt so bad,'' Harrison said. ``We've seen wool
prices fall to 12 1/2 cents a pound. The loss of the wool subsidies
cost this community about $3.5 million a year. We lost our rail
yard, and that cost $5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, there is a rebound. The Legislature has declared
Sanderson the ``Cactus Capital of Texas.'' The Senate Resolution
recognizes cactus as ``renowned for its remarkable ability to
thrive in conditions that include periodic drought, dust, extreme
heat and flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   It says that the people of Sanderson are kind of like that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the week we're going to make it all official,''
Harrison said of the state proclamation. ``We finally got it
through the Legislature and signed by the governor. We're going to
present it to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson, 120 miles northwest of Del Rio on U.S. 90, steps out
of the dusty West Texas shadows this weekend to assume its crown as
Cactus Capital. Harrison said that the effort to develop tourism
has helped the economy some, but that getting the visitors to West
Texas is one thing and keeping them there is another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a little museum,'' he said. ``We have wonderful
churches, a fine school system, but no big parks, or swimming
holes. Nothing to hold them.''
</P>
<P>
   The city and county are developing plans for a network of
walking trails in the surrounding mountains. Birding is big in
Sanderson, Harrison said, and if the community can develop birding
trails, people might come and stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got every old lady in town busy filling feeders,''
Harrison said with a laugh. ``This could give everybody a shot in
the arm. It could uplift this whole community.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
