<HEADER>
A4825 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-30 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS' UNION IS NOT WHAT I'D PRESCRIBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just what we need: unionized doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, we already have some _ about 40,000 doctors belong to
various unions, according to the The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   But when the American Medical Association voted last week to
promote unionization on a national scale, the 290,000-member
doctors' group opened the door to ... well, it opened the door to a
patient's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, is this John Doe? Mr. Doe, Dr. Schmoe won't be able to
perform your liver transplant tomorrow because he and the other
doctors here at the hospital are involved in a labor dispute with
the hospital management.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you telling me that my doctor _ the dedicated surgeon who
is scheduled to perform a delicate, demanding and urgently needed
operation for the purpose of saving my life _ won't be operating
because he's ON STRIKE?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one way of putting it, I suppose. Don't worry, Mr. Doe,
we'll get back to you just as soon as the strike is over. Nothing
is more important to Dr. Schmoe than your health and welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy, you say? Cheap shot, you say? Doctors are professionals
who would never risk their patients' lives by going on strike, you
say?
</P>
<P>
   That's what they say, too.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA says its unionization push is designed to give doctors
more clout in dealing with managed-care insurance operations such
as HMOs _ to benefit patients, in other words, not jeopardize their
interests.
</P>
<P>
   But when has a labor union ever acted in the interest of anyone
or anything other than the union? In their single-minded
determination to advance the union's agenda, plenty of labor
organizations have gone so far as to ignore the interests of their
own members; it would be a historic occasion indeed if a union
should ever give a moment's thought to the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a doctor's union be less self-serving than any other
labor organization?
</P>
<P>
   A staff and wire report in the Star-Telegram quoted the AMA's
chairman, Dr. Randolph D. Smoak:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not for all physicians. This will not be a traditional
labor union. Your doctors will not strike or endanger patient care.
We will follow the principles of medical ethics every step of the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jane M. Orient, executive director of the Association of
American Physicians and Surgeons, offered a dissenting opinion in a
statement distributed by the U.S. Newswire:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Association of American Physicians and Surgeons (AAPS)
opposes the AMA's decision to organize doctors into an AMA union.
This move is not about protecting patients, but about furthering
the AMA's political power and strangle hold on medicine, and can
only result in a blot on the professionalism of physicians and
decreased trust of doctors ....
</P>
<P>
   ``If it walks like a union and quacks like a union, you can be
sure it will look like any other big labor organization with a
mission of protecting itself and its leadership. Patients can only
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The AMA says that its union movement will involve only salaried
doctors who qualify as employees under federal law. But a bill
being debated in Congress could give self-employed doctors the
right to participate in collective bargaining as well _ a
development that would make the Mr. Doe-Dr. Schmoe scenario far
less fanciful than it might seem at first glance.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what would happen if there were a nationwide doctors'
strike: lifesaving operations canceled, hospital emergency rooms
disrupted, desperately needed medicines left unprescribed.
</P>
<P>
   And if the doctors walk, won't the nurses and the ambulance
drivers walk with them?
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing for disgruntled airline pilots to leave
passengers stranded in airports by calling in sick, for striking
UPS drivers to let packages pile up on loading docks, for refuse
workers to refuse to pick up garbage. We're talking about major
inconvenience, gigantic aggravation.
</P>
<P>
   Unionized doctors could shut down the health-care system. People
could die.
</P>
<P>
   And what would lead us to believe that it won't happen?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
