<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-SENAT     06-30 2515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-SENATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JAMES BENNET  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    On the windy Friday in February that the Senate acquitted her
husband of perjury and obstruction of justice, Hillary Rodham
Clinton turned her attention to her life after his presidency.
 &HT;    From before the first vote that day until long after the last,
she met with her friend Harold Ickes on the second floor of the
White House, in the family quarters, to weigh whether for the first
time to promote herself rather than Bill Clinton for public office.
 &HT;    Hillary Clinton felt flattered that Democrats were begging her
to run for the Senate from New York, an idea she had laughed off
when Rep. Charles Rangel, the mischievous Manhattan Democrat, first
suggested it in a Chicago church last October.
 &HT;    She was delighted with the shift under way in her public image,
from passive victim to political heavyweight. After all her policy
work and speechifying, it had galled her to watch her popularity
spike upward in the past year as she turned her lapidary smile to
the world and suffered through the revelations of her husband's
affair with that woman.
 &HT;    Now, for four hours, as she and Ickes _ a scarred veteran of New
York politics and a former aide to her husband _ moved from the
living room to lunch in the family dining room and back to the
living room, she plumbed the risks of a race for the Senate seat
that Daniel Patrick Moynihan had decided to vacate.
 &HT;    Would she really want to be one of a hundred senators? Could she
survive a street fight with a nasty opponent? Could she stand the
pawing of New York City's feral reporters?
 &HT;    The backing and forthing with Ickes had fitting precedent. Half
a century ago, a woman Clinton regards as a role model, Eleanor
Roosevelt, mulled running for the Senate from New York at the
prompting of a former adviser to her husband. He was also named
Harold Ickes; he was the father of Hillary Clinton's friend.
 &HT;    But like so many parallels between the century's two most
compelling first ladies, this one illuminates as many differences
as similarities. Hillary had summoned her Harold, while Eleanor was
importuned by hers. Pulled between her lofty aims and her cautious
nature, Hillary was embarking on months of painstaking cogitation,
while Eleanor almost immediately turned her Harold down.
 &HT;    ``I feel very strongly that running for office is not the way in
which I can be most useful,'' she wrote him on May 26, 1945, just
days after he raised the idea. She did not want to burden her
children with another office-holding parent. She also did not want
to burden herself with having to follow what she called ``the party
line.''
 &HT;    ``I hope to continue to work with the Democrats and for them,''
Eleanor continued briskly, ``but I think the knowledge that I will
be free of any obligation may at times be very healthy.''
 &HT;    ``Free of any obligation'' _ it is an expression lustrous with
meaning for political spouses, and particularly for first ladies of
the United States. Since Martha Washington likened herself to a
state prisoner, first ladies have felt oppressed by arranging
flowers or delivering speeches, by wielding influence or not enough
of it, by the private compromises and the planetary humiliations.
 &HT;    Eleanor Roosevelt feared continued limitation in winning office
for herself. Hillary Clinton glimpses freedom, or so her friends
and advisers say _ freedom to participate in politics fully, with
her own constituents, on her own terms, for her own purposes.
 &HT;    Hillary Clinton is about to become a liberated woman. Come
January 2001, for the first time since she moved to Arkansas as a
26-year-old lawyer in 1974, she will be able to walk her own path
regardless of her husband's political career. While most people
provided such an opening might be fantasizing about anonymity and a
long break, Clinton is methodically exploring her options for
staying in the spotlight.
 &HT;    If she does not pull out of the New York race in June, she is
likely to announce an exploratory committee in July, knowing that
that will be regarded as throwing her hat in the ring. With that
announcement, the Clintons would neatly reverse roles, at least
regarding New York. She would step forward to present herself as a
leader, while he would be relegated to behind-the-scenes,
supporting chores.
 &HT;    To be sure, since she graduated from Yale Law School and opted
for Bill Clinton and Arkansas, it has become unremarkable for women
to compete for higher office.
 &HT;    As she pondered the Senate race, Clinton was standing in the way
of another woman, Rep. Nita Lowey of Westchester County, and an
older but far less traditional political spouse, Elizabeth Dole,
was running for president.
 &HT;    Clinton's race would be path-breaking, but only because she
would be undertaking it while her husband was still in office. In
that sense, it would certainly be pioneering for Clinton and for
first ladies, but not for women generally. She is too late for
that.
 &HT;    But so what? Clinton did not sacrifice her ambition to her
husband's so much as yoke them together. As a result of that
decision, it has been her fate to be judged more for how she has
stood by her man than for what she has accomplished with him and
more for what she represents as a woman than for what she has done
as first lady.
 &HT;    As it happens, she has done quite a bit. And the flip side of
the loyal role she has played is that she regards his
accomplishments as hers too. When she was saving his presidency
last year _ condemning unnamed conspirators and then sticking with
him after he admitted they were right about his affair _ she was
also saving her own.
 &HT;    By now, Hillary Clinton is operating under the presumption that
she will run for the Senate, and she is looking for a house in
Westchester County. Her goals remain rather vague, but her ambition
for service and confidence in herself remain intact and vaulting.
It is just that Bill Clinton is no longer the best vehicle.
 &HT;    But that does not mean that she will run, and that points up
another difference between the Clintons. When it comes to politics,
he works from the gut as well as from his beloved polls, while she
is more cerebral. The risks and challenges of a race excite him.
They scare her. This is a defining life decision for her, perhaps
the biggest she has made since her marriage, and in the end she may
decide not to gamble her popularity and political clout.
 &HT;    She does not want to lose. Horse-race polls don't mean much now,
but the ones that showed her running away with victory have been
replaced by others showing at best that she might squeak by
Giuliani. And some of her advisers are more worried about a
possible challenge from Rep. Rick Lazio, the Long Island
Republican, or even Gov. George Pataki.
 &HT;    ``One of the lures of being senator is you're out on your own,''
one of her advisers told me. ''One of the liabilities is you lose
on your own.''
 &HT;    Paradoxically, Clinton's record in her husband's office is
clearest where it is least relevant to the voters who might elect
her. Far more than in the United States, Hillary Clinton has found
her own voice overseas. She has spent more days this year in North
Africa than in New York. And abroad, she conducts a sort of shadow
presidency, with advisers borrowed from assorted agencies and an
aging 707 whose port engine periodically bursts into flames.
 &HT;    She does it with what amounts to her own foreign policy,
promoting issues of women's rights, health care and development
that her husband addresses rarely, and almost always with her at
his side. In her speeches abroad, she seldom even mentions the
president, not wanting to muddy her message of female empowerment
by acknowledging that her influence derives from his power.
 &HT;    Yet Clinton's passion for that role could be a problem in New
York, where it plays into what her advisers view as her chief
liability: the suspicion that she would have her eye on concerns
far from Binghamton or the Bronx. It has probably not helped her
that in her remarks about a possible race, she has tended to dwell
on why New York is big enough for her, rather than vice versa.
 &HT;    ``New York is truly a microcosm of America,'' she recently told
reporters in Manhattan. Chuck Schumer has advised Clinton that if
she decides to run, she will have to devote herself completely to
the race. ``You can't be both first lady and candidate,'' he says.
 &HT;    As first lady, she has had two luxuries that will vanish if she
presents herself as a candidate: picking and choosing what issues
she wants to address and falling back on exhortation rather than
specific proposals to solve the problems she raises.
 &HT;    Her record of passionate concern for children would surely give
her great credibility on issues like gun violence in the schools,
which after Littleton she is turning into a crusade. (``I have not
stopped thinking about it,'' she told me.)
 &HT;    When I asked her what specifically she hopes to accomplish as a
senator or citizen, she began by replying, ``Well, you know, I'm
concerned about a broad range of issues.''
 &HT;    Then she gathered speed. ``You know, much of what I care about
falls into the broad categories of creating conditions for children
to grow up and be healthy and well educated and productive
citizens. And so that means I'm interested in everything from
economic policy to education policy to adoption and foster care and
welfare policy to health care.'' She laced her fingers together as
she added, ``I think that all of these social, political, economic,
cultural issues intersect.''
 &HT;    Clinton is widely viewed as more liberal than her husband, but
there is not much evidence to support that. In Arkansas, it was
Hillary who persuaded Bill to advocate the testing of public-school
teachers. The efficacy of the test is debatable, but there is no
question it angered some of their staunchest liberal supporters.
 &HT;    ``You know, people think she's such a big lib,'' says Maggie
Williams, Clinton's former chief of staff and one of her closest
friends. ``I think she's extremely conservative. I think she has
more in common with people in upstate New York than in New York
City, in a lot of ways.'' Williams calls Clinton ``patriotic and
practical. She thinks it's important to spend money on social
programs, but she wants to know that they work.''
 &HT;    Maybe so. But until she stands on her own politically, none of
us can know.
 &HT;    After Clinton stuck by her husband through the Lewinsky scandal,
she came to present a fat target for those who found her wanting as
a feminist. And it is hard not to wince these days over some things
she says, at times so self-righteously.
 &HT;    ``We can point to many problems around our world today where
women _ for reasons of history, culture, discrimination, prejudice
_ are used to lift up patriarchy, are used really as objects in
order for others to exercise power,'' she said in commemorating
International Women's Day this year.
 &HT;    Clinton makes no apologies for her decisions last year. In the
interview, she said at first that ``people have to make their own
judgments about that,'' but then went on to suggest they had no
business doing so. A bit paradoxically, she presented her actions
as evidence of her independence and self-sufficiency.
 &HT;    ``I would hope that young women _ women of all ages _ understand
how important it is to live your own life according to your own
values,'' she said, unspooling one of those lengthy sentences
characteristic of either Clinton, ``and not be constantly looking
over your shoulder to think what anybody else is thinking about you
or saying about you, because ultimately, at the end of the day, you
have to live with yourself and you have to do what you think is
right. And again, my choices may not be someone else's choices.''
 &HT;    When it comes to the Clintons, it is hard to separate the
personal and the political. Regardless of her feelings for him,
leaving her husband last year would have brought down a presidency
she believes in to her bones.
 &HT;    Some of the Clintons' closest associates have regarded their
relationship for years as a partnership with staged shows of
affection _ ``what they had to for the moment,'' as one of them put
it to me. Even some of Hillary Clinton's friends wonder if she will
stay with him after they leave the White House.
 &HT;    But politics did not keep the Clintons together, according to
other, closer friends of Hillary. She considered leaving him last
year, they say, but her daughter and her marriage vows stopped her.
Most important, they insist, she still loves him.
 &HT;    ``She loves him, and she doesn't have to, but she does,'' one
said. Part of the reason, this friend said, is their intellectual
bond: ``Whether you think they're changing things for better or
worse, they're always going to have something to say to each other
about it.''
 &HT;    But maybe it is time to leave wondering if the Clintons truly
love each other to the historians and to focus on the
accomplishments, failures and ideas that define his presidency and
would define her Senate race.
 &HT;    If Clinton runs, she is likely to limit her husband's role,
though he will try to meddle. Indeed, it has not escaped some of
her friends that being forced onto the sidelines would be
excruciating punishment for him, as, without a campaign of his own,
he watches his wife and his vice president run.
 &HT;    But Hillary Clinton wants to find out what she can do on her
own, they say. Further, having her husband front and center would
make her look weak.
 &HT;    And therein lies a delightful switch. For years, White House
aides have praised Hillary Clinton's ability and contributions
while in the next breath minimizing her influence in order to build
up the president. Now, Hillary's allies are unself-consciously
treating her husband the same way.
 &HT;    ``She'd be a fool not to work with him very closely on this,''
one of them told me. ``It will, however, be Hillary Rodham
Clinton's campaign. It'll be her voice, and it'll be her persona. I
see him playing very much a behind-the-scenes role.''
 &HT;     c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (James Bennet, formerly a New York Times White House
correspondent, is a staff writer for The New York Times Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
