<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLANNING AND BUILDING OF YOUR OWN POND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A well-designed pond can be a pleasant addition to any property.
The hardest part of installing a pond is digging the hole _ unless
you rent a backhoe. Unlike other home building projects, pond
building does not require precise measurements or accurate scale
drawings. Still, depending on the size of the pond, it will take
some planning.
</P>
<P>
   Because large ponds of more than 10 feet in diameter can affect
the environment surrounding your property, they should only be
installed after careful planning. This includes choosing the most
propitious site, ideally a wet hollow, then consulting with local
authorities, like the state Water Resources Board, to make sure
your project complies with all construction guidelines and with
wetland protection legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas the federal government may have jurisdiction over
wetland projects, and you may have to obtain special permits before
proceeding. Once the planning is complete, you will have to hire a
contractor with a bulldozer to excavate the site.
</P>
<P>
   Constructing a large pond is obviously not a do-it-yourself
project, but installing a smaller pond is within the skills of the
average do-it-yourselfer. You still need to check first with local
authorities to make sure the project complies with all codes and
zoning laws. Some building codes, for example, require a perimeter
fence around any pond that has a depth greater than 18 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Look over your property to choose the best site for the pond.
The land should be relatively level and free of obstructions like
tree stumps, roots and large rocks. If you intend to add aquatic
plants and fish to the pond, it must receive at least four hours of
direct sunlight each day.
</P>
<P>
   Next map out the general shape of the pond with a long rope on
the ground. The rope makes it easy to adjust and readjust the
outline until you are satisfied that the pond shape will fit nicely
into the surroundings. When the outline is in place, begin digging.
For a simple pond, you only have to dig the hole to one level, but
the pond will be more interesting if you make shelves for various
aquatic plants around the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider the depth. If you plan to stock the pond with
fish, it must be a minimum of 18 inches deep. The water level will
be a few inches lower than the banks around the pond, If you want
the water to be 30 inches deep, then dig a hole 36 inches deep.
</P>
<P>
   When the hole is dug, check the banks to make surer that they
are level. To do this, rest a long 2 by 4 across the hole and check
it with a level. Cut down the high spots or build up the low spots
to level the banks.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the soil is especially dense, the hole will not hold
water. You must install a waterproof liner. There are two types of
liners: preformed and flexible. Preformed liners are large plastic
or fiberglass tubs molded into a rigid shape. The ground must be
excavated to accept the right shape and dimensions of the liner.
</P>
<P>
   It is easier, and less expensive, to install a flexible liner.
Flexible liners are large blankets made of plastic, like
high-density polyethylene and polyvinyl chloride, or a synthetic
rubber, like ethylene proplylene diene monomer. They are available
in thicknesses ranging from 20 to 60 mils thick. The thicker liners
are more expensive. While they are more durable, they are also less
flexible and may be hard to shape to the contours of your pond.
</P>
<P>
   Liners come in a variety of colors. Black works best because it
makes the pond look deeper and it is easier to hide around the
edges of the banks. When purchasing a liner, check to see if the
manufacturer offers a warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Before installing the liner, place a 1/2-inch thick layer of
newspapers over the pond bed. The newspapers will pad the surface
and protect the liner from any sharp objects, rocks or twigs that
might puncture it. Eventually, the newspapers will absorb ground
moisture and decompose to form a clay-like substance that will
contain water should the liner develop a leak.
</P>
<P>
   Place the liner over the opening and lightly press down to make
it fits the contours of the hole. When working on the liner, be
sure to wear soft-soled shoes so you don't damage it. When the
liner is in place, position a few smooth rocks on the edges to hold
it while you fill the pond with water. Fill the pond slowly,
because the weight of the water may cause the liner to shift so it
needs readjustment. When the pond is full, add more rocks around
the edges to hold the liner in place. Trim away any excess liner
with tin snips or heavy- duty shears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
