<HEADER>
A4850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      06-30 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Life of the Leek
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some of my leeks were too small to harvest so I left them in
the ground last year, and now they are about to flower. Will they
still be good to eat after flowering? I don't want to harvest them
now. I want to enjoy the flowers, but it would be nice if I could
eat them afterward.
</P>
<P>
   A. Just remember how much you enjoyed those alliumlike flowers
when you harvest and eat what remains of the leeks. As a biennial,
leeks, members of the same family as onions, shallots and chives,
have their own agenda. They spend the first growing season stocking
up on energy and storing food in their underground storage bin _
the part of the leek that we eat. By harvesting in the first fall,
you are the beneficiary of the leek's efforts. If you wait until
after flowering, during the second growing season, the leek is the
beneficiary. It uses that energy up as the plant devotes everything
to setting seed before it dies.
</P>
<P>
   As its second spring arrives, the leek begins to create its
flower stalk. To support the flower, the center of the edible
portion becomes woody and inedible. Taking energy from storage to
produce a flower reduces the size of the leek and gives it a
sharper flavor. The best tasting overwintered leeks are harvested
early in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Not all leeks are winter hardy, so if you intend to leave your
leeks in the ground to overwinter, choose a hardy variety like Bleu
Solaise, Siegfried or Laura, and mulch them after the ground
freezes.
</P>
<P>
   Sources for winter-hardy leeks include Fedco Seeds, P.O. Box
520, Waterville, Maine 04903, (207) 873-7333 (for free catalog; no
phone orders), and Cook's Garden, P.O. Box 5010, Hodges S.C. 29653,
(800) 457-9703, free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Hardiness Zones
</P>
<P>
   Q. Garden books often give numbered climate zones for perennials
and trees. How strictly do I have to follow these numbers? If I
live in Zone 5 (the lower Catskill region of New York State), can I
try something listed as Zone 6? Do all writers agree on the zones
for these plants, or is there some doubt I can benefit from?
</P>
<P>
   A. Hardiness zones, geographic regions classified by averages of
the lowest winter temperature that an area will normally reach,
have been used as a guide to choosing perennials, trees, shrubs and
ground covers since the first zones map was published in 1927 by
Alfred Rehder of the Arnold Arboretum of Harvard University. The
idea has continued to be refined, and the latest version, published
by the Agriculture Department, goes from Zone 1 (temperatures
regularly falling below minus 50 degrees) to Zone 11 (never falling
below 40 degrees). Each zone represents a 10-degree difference, and
each is further divided into A and B zones of 5-degree increments,
with the A's cooler than the B's.
</P>
<P>
   Winter-hardiness information is sometimes not foolproof when an
area's growing conditions vary widely. In the 1954 edition of the
``Western Garden Book,'' Sunset Publishing divided the Western and
Pacific Coast states into 24 zones, taking into account summer high
temperatures, humidity, rainfall, elevation, latitude, the
influence of the ocean and other characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how many divisions are made, the general
conditions may be different from the actual conditions in the
microclimate of a spot in your yard. Microclimates depend on
elevation, openness to the wind, surrounding sheltering material
and available moisture, among other things that can effect
temperature at any moment. You may live in a region that is
generally Zone 5, but some parts of your garden may be a bit warmer
or cooler than others, though probably not an entire zone.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, averages can be misleading. Borderline plants
may do fine for years and then get wiped out by one of those
winters that hark back to childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Experts differ on assigning hardiness zones to plants, but then
individual plants and individual test sites also differ. Just as
you can move from doctor to doctor until you find a diagnosis you
agree with, if you look in enough books, you might find one where
the plant you are interested in is listed as Zone 5, instead of
Zone 6. Whether or not you want to take the risk against the advice
of the majority is up to you. As long as you're not my
stockbroker. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
