<HEADER>
A4852 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-IPO-STOCKS-N     06-30 2653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-IPO-STOCKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 RIDING the BUBBLE of the INTERNET BOOM  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By PO BRONSON  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    For a homeless shelter's annual charity auction not long ago,
Steve Jurvetson, a venture capitalist, donated a breakfast with
himself at Buck's Restaurant.
 &HT;    Buck's is a bustling diner in Woodside, Calif., a
single-intersection hamlet nestled into an oak grove at the base of
the San Mateo County foothills. The booths at Buck's are
upholstered in ocher Naugahyde and the menus have the feel of
political-action newsletters and the owners are mighty proud of
their coffeecake.
 &HT;    Buck's also happens to be the place where Netscape and many
other high-tech companies were hatched.
 &HT;    ``Breakfast at Buck's'' was sold off by way of the Internet site
Ebay at the end of February; 78 bids after the auction started, a
budding Manhattan entrepreneur named Mark Hernandez offered to pay
$4,400 for the privilege of flying out to Silicon Valley two weeks
later to present his business idea.
 &HT;    That might sound like a lot of money to have breakfast with
someone, but Jurvetson is a venture capitalist with a reputation _
young, enthusiastic, open-minded.
 &HT;    He can be found at Buck's most mornings. He bounds in like a
kangaroo, exuberant, flashing a joyous smile, his youthful face
tanned from his noon-hour games of ultimate Frisbee.
 &HT;    He is generally more dapper than his colleagues, wearing a
charcoal Czechoslovakian hand-made suit over a cobalt shirt with
faint royal blue pin-stripes. His tie picks up these colors
perfectly; the black wing tips on his large feet shine. In the
plastic window of his wallet is the bridal portrait of his wife of
eight years, Karla, who is a psychiatrist at Stanford.
 &HT;    He has a prototypical resume for a Silicon Valley VC: earned
bachelor's and master's degrees from Stanford, designed microchips
at Hewlett-Packard, learned management consulting at Bain &AMP; Co.,
returned to Stanford for his MBA and then beat out 250 other
applicants for a position at Draper Fisher, the venture firm.
 &HT;    Prototypical resume, except for the date column: As an
undergrad, he tricked the registration computer _ which blocked
signing up for more than 20 units _ by penciling in just two units
of credit on what were five-unit classes. In this way, he was able
to take eight classes at once and finish in two and a half years
with an A-plus average.
 &HT;    Think that's fast? The conventional wisdom in Silicon Valley is
that it takes three years to learn the craft. Jurvetson made
partner in six months. He was 28.
 &HT;    Venture capitalists' favorite unit of measurement is the factor
X. They live life on multiplication scale, and anything less than X
is inconsequential. When they invest, they ignore 12 percent or 15
percent or 18 percent returns. They start to take notice when they
see potential for 10X returns.
 &HT;    In this lingo, Jurvetson blasted through college at nearly 2X
the normal rate, and made partner at 6X speed. Now he's
accelerating _ straight into what could be a precarious stretch of
road.
 &HT;    Only 32, Jurvetson is in for the summer of his life, with no
fewer than 11 of the Internet-related companies he has backed (Wit
Capital, Goto.com, Tumbleweed and Netzero among them) at various
points along the road to an initial public offering.
 &HT;    The brand name he has built for himself with investments in a
couple of other successful Internet start-ups _ his firm's
specialty and the hottest destination for venture capital _ will be
put to the test. That's because the market's taste for Internet
stocks appears to have soured.
 &HT;    Dave Marquart, a Silicon Valley veteran who was the only venture
investor in Microsoft and the co-lead investor of Sun Microsystems,
warns: ``To be a bona fide venture capitalist, you have to go
through a complete cycle. Those who've entered the business since
the mid-'90s have never seen a down cycle. Everything has been to
the right and up _ very up.''
 &HT;    To understand why Jurvetson is a folk hero for so many of those
looking to convert their dreams and visions into Net wealth,
consider what happened in February 1996.
 &HT;    Sabeer Bhatia was an immigrant from India with zero experience
running a company, zero experience in consumer products and zero
experience in software. (He had been a hardware engineer at Apple.)
He was Jurvetson's age less two years, or J - 2. Bhatia had already
been turned down by 21 other venture capital firms. He had produced
no prototype, not even a graphic printed on a piece of paper.
 &HT;    What he did have was what Jurvetson called ``hallucinogenic
optimism'' and one intriguing idea, which he sketched out on a
conference room white board.
 &HT;    Jurvetson invested $300,000 to buy 15 percent of the project.
Less than two years later, the company that emerged from that
meeting, Hotmail, was sold to Microsoft for $400 million. Jurvetson
became an instant legend, the guy every young entrepreneur wants to
meet, even if it means paying 250X the cost of breakfast at Buck's.
 &HT;    Increasingly, successful venture capital firms are sheltering
themselves from the hail of unsolicited business plans by invoking
the Inverse Rule of Referrals: All good ideas come by referral, so
if it didn't come by referral it must not be a good idea.
 &HT;    Here's how a typical venture firm might catalogue the incoming
slough. Administrative staff scans the first paragraph of the cover
letter for a referral by a ``trusted third party,'' which is
entered in a database. Partners scan the database; they'll look at
the plan only if they trust the referral.
 &HT;    But Draper, Fisher, Jurvetson has cultivated a reputation for
ignoring that rule. The firm is located in Seaport, a sailing
harbor in Redwood City _ psychologically far from VC ground zero,
Sand Hill Road (but close enough to zip there in 10 minutes for a
meeting).
 &HT;    The problem with referral networks, as DFJ sees it, is that as
the venture capitalists age, so does their referral network,
cutting them off from the original thinkers. At DFJ they say they
read every one of the 5,000 plans sent to them each year. Theirs
was the first venture capital firm to run an advertisement.
 &HT;    DFJ is a ``seed'' firm, meaning it gets in on the first round of
financing for nascent businesses. ``Getting companies started is
the hardest part,'' says Tim Draper, the firm's founder, ``and it's
the most rewarding _ both financially and personally.''
 &HT;    To Jurvetson, it's even more rewarding than being an
entrepreneur. ``I get bits and pieces of several success stories,
sort of a highlight reel,'' he says.
 &HT;    Jurvetson has succeeded so far by making himself accessible to
the kind of young people who he figures come up with unusual ideas
_ as opposed to what the industry calls ``Me, Too'' product. One
recent month's ``Me, Too'' was on-line gift registries. He saw 30
business plans on that concept. The month before, it was
Web-calendar companies. He saw three Web-calendar plans out of Sun
Microsystems' employees alone.
 &HT;    Having lunch in San Francisco one day, he bumped into an old
friend who said he had left Netscape to found his dream start-up;
without much tact, Jurvetson jokingly blurted out, ``I hope it's
not another Web-calendar company!'' His friend's face fell. They
always think they're the only ones with the idea.
 &HT;    ``Truly original thinkers tend not to be entrepreneurs who've
spent 10 years at Cisco and can be trusted to know what they're
doing,'' Jurvetson explains. ``They tend to be 26 years old and
highflying. They often have a very childlike mind, with some
naivete. We're impressed by people who don't know what can't be
done.''
 &HT;    Just as the wild success of venture capital firms has made them
magnets for business plans, it has made them extremely popular with
fund investors (which tend to be pension plans, university
endowments and insurance companies). At a typical VC firm, money
under active management has gone up 40X; the number of partners to
manage that money has gone up only 4X. It's now common to raise
$350 million to $500 million every couple of years.
 &HT;    When Draper Fisher Jurvetson mailed out prospectuses for its
most recent fund, the firm received 3X the pledges it needed. The
partners drew the line at $180 million _ but even that is a huge
sum to deploy among early-stage firms, and easily the biggest fund
DFJ had ever raised.
 &HT;    VC firms have a fat incentive to raise more and more money,
because they get paid in two ways. First, when investors in a
specific fund are paid back after a set period of time has elapsed
(typically 10 years), the venture firm keeps 20 percent of all the
profits. Second is the gravy train: a 2.5 percent annual management
fee paid by investors, regardless of performance.
 &HT;    To deal with all the incoming money, most firms are ratcheting
up the size of investments, especially on secondary rounds, when a
company that has survived the seed stage needs large cash
infusions.
 &HT;    That means sticking with start-ups that have a high likelihood
of growing not just big but gargantuan, with billions of dollars in
annual sales. The Amazon of pharmacies, the Amazon of insurance,
the Amazon of auto parts _ consumer markets so big that even a
small slice of them guarantees a stellar payoff. They're not really
start-ups, they're bulk-ups. They put on weight fast and flex their
muscles and try to scare competitors off the beach.
 &HT;    But as Jurvetson sees it, something has been forgotten in this
process. Sure, it's cool to make so much money. And sure, it's cool
to be able to buy hair dye and condoms from the privacy of home.
But on-line superstores aren't creating new markets, and though
they might evolve the technology of E-commerce, they're not
revolutionizing it. They're just big Web sites. Where's the
adventure in that kind of venture?
 &HT;    Seed investing requires a special kind of hunger. Jurvetson's
parents were immigrants from Estonia, and he was reared in Dallas
by the creed that what he was to make of his life was entirely up
to him; there were no entitlements.
 &HT;    In an undergraduate psychology class, he answered a series of
Enneagram questions meant to divine his character type. He so fit
the description of a Type 3, the Performer (as in star performer),
that he was asked back in following semesters to lecture about the
traits of Type 3's: tremendous need for achievement, with an inner
drive to do something beyond the ordinary.
 &HT;    That drive is why he belongs dead center in the creation zone of
the new economy: where there's constantly a new goal to keep him
from getting bored, and where he has all of Silicon Valley as an
audience to perform for.
 &HT;    He seems very similar in character to the headstrong young
entrepreneurs he deals with, and perhaps that is partly why they
mind-meld with him so well.
 &HT;    At no time was this more clear than the day he drove across the
Dunbarton Bridge to meet Joe Chen, the CEO of a very new start-up,
See U There.com. Chen had 12 employees working in the living and
dining rooms of his Union City home. Jurvetson admits he's a sucker
for this kind of raw fertile atmosphere, and he grooved on it for a
while that day, talking to the employees and soaking up their
ambitious energy.
 &HT;    The whole point of money is that it's transferable legal tender,
that it retains its value no matter who possesses it _ your million
dollars is just as valuable as my million dollars. With venture
capital, that's not always the case.
 &HT;    Chen already had two other venture firms ready to give him the
million dollars he needed.
 &HT;    ``Literally, they are screaming at us, asking when we are going
to close the deal,'' Chen explained as we sat down at his
conference table in the garage. But he would rather have
Jurvetson's million dollars. His pitch: a plan to build an Internet
site to capture the largely untapped $60 billion market for event
planning. Jurvetson seemed inclined to invest (and two days later,
did).
 &HT;    Chen is J + 1 years old. He wanted Jurvetson's technical
fluency, but also a certain kind of cultural chemistry _ the
difference between working with someone who is just like your
father and working with someone who is just like you. As Chen puts
it, ``He's not some stiff suit walking in here.''
 &HT;    ``The hotmail story reached us even in Singapore,'' says
Eng-Siong Tan, the CEO of a start-up called Third Voice. Tan is J +
4 years old. ``It resonated and became part of the folklore of the
valley that he was willing to invest where 21 other firms had
passed. We knew Steve would be someone who gets our idea.''
 &HT;    Tan and eight other Singaporean engineers uprooted and came here
cold. They crammed into a cement-block storage warehouse in Foster
City, their front door an aluminum roll-up gate. In November, Tan
pitched Jurvetson.
 &HT;    Third Voice would make software that allows users to post
comments, viewable only by other users, directly onto the front
page of any Web site. It's the Web equivalent of empowering people
to spray-paint the State Capital. Jurvetson got it: This could do
to on-line chat what Ebay did to classified ads.
 &HT;    Internet companies are like Bazooka bubble gum. It takes a lot
of chewing and manipulation _ a tremendous amount of effort _ to
get the first bubble started. Then, with the slightest additional
effort, a mere exhale, it expands 100X. For a while it's customary
to double in size every month. That's what Tan is about to go
through. He's ready to exhale.
 &HT;    The first of Jurvetson's 11 IPO-bound companies _ Wit Capital,
an Internet investment bank _ went public early in June, right on
the heals of a disastrous week for Internet stocks. In late May,
Juno Online and Ziplink not only failed to post triple-digit
first-day returns, they both dropped below the offering price. Two
other IPOs were postponed.
 &HT;    Suddenly the center of the Internet boom seemed to a lot of
people like a scary place to be. But Wit went out and and finished
its first day up 85 percent _ a figure that would have been a
disappointment just months before, but now looked strong. And
Jurvetson sounded as chipper as ever.
 &HT;    Yes, some of the insane pops of early 1999 probably won't be
back, but Jurvetson says that only means offerings are being priced
more fairly and supply and demand are synching up. But the Internet
is the economy, he insists; businesses that still think it's just a
fad are in denial.
 &HT;    Of his IPO-bound companies, only one is considering putting off
its public offering by a quarter, he adds, and there is nothing in
his voice to suggest fear or unease about the future. That's what
the Type 3 description doesn't capture: This is a guy having time
of his life. The default setting on his face is a birthday-boy
smile.
 &HT;    And why not? ``I get to have the Steve Jobses of the next
century come to me and make their pitch. I can't define a better
recreation activity, let alone a job, that would be better than
that.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Po Bronson  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Po Bronson is a writer based in San Francisco. His nonfiction
book about Silicon Valley, ``The Nudist on the Late Shift,'' is due
out in June.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
