<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4854 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GOLF-GAME-NYT &LR;      06-30 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GOLF-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH MATCH ON THE GREEN (BUT TAKE TURNS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, golf. A venerable game of patience, practice and exquisite
concentration. A game of nuance and constant incremental striving
for perfection. The lush greens inspire a Zen-like contemplation of
the landscape. Custom dictates a sportsmanlike demeanor toward
one's fellow players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extreme golf'' would seem to be an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   After all, golf does not require hair-trigger reflexes,
outstanding agility or physical prowess. Unlike most extreme
sports, golf does not require players to hurtle through the air,
flip upside down or cling to sheer vertical surfaces. In fact,
there are few athletic pursuits less extreme than golf.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the makers of Links LS, a popular golf simulation,
have upped the computer golf ante with Links Extreme, a CD-ROM
billed as ``golf with attitude.'' It marries the precision of golf
to the lurid lighting and wanton violence of a pulse-pumping
computer game (and of course, the chukka-chukka-chukka heavy metal
that denotes ``extreme'' athletic programming on MTV and ESPN2).
</P>
<P>
   The Links Extreme tour roster consists of players suitably
attired in ``extreme'' Gen-X clothing _ baggy jeans, cargo pants,
stocking caps and backward baseball hats are de rigueur. After
selecting a golfer, you have two choices: driving practice or
course play.
</P>
<P>
   Driving practice lands you in Armadillo Al's Demolition Driving
Range, where cows, animatronic characters and slow-playing golfers
can be blown sky-high with golf ball grenades. Pebble Beach meets
``Apocalypse Now.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you've perfected your swing, it's time for a visit to the
Mojo Bay Resort and Country Club, located somewhere between
Jamaica, New Orleans and the Twilight Zone. Ghoulishly illuminated
by a blood-red sunset, Mojo Bay is dotted with palm trees,
alligator-infested swamps and skeletons that speak in an unplaced
Creole accent.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to convey menace on a golf course _ the openness,
clear sight lines and rolling hills make for an inherently
reassuring landscape. The spooky lighting and rustling noises
aren't really scary. But they are a kitschy reminder that something
dangerous is supposed to happen here.
</P>
<P>
   The trick-or-treat ambiance also highlights the performance of
the ``extreme'' golf balls, which allow you to hex your opponent's
shots and watch them boomerang or corkscrew into the water.
Meanwhile, your shots can go through trees, fly 400 yards with
rocket propulsion, skip over water or seek the pin with submarine
radar (a hollow plinking sound echoes until the putt sinks).
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, this couldn't be further from real life, where a
golf ball is a golf ball is a golf ball. On the other hand, every
golfer has experienced a shot that veers inexplicably at the last
minute or sticks to the green or sails farther than it should.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most of these flukes can be explained by weather. But
whenever physical objects do something unexpected, there's an
element of superstition. There are times on the golf course when
you're blessed and times when you're cursed. At Mojo Bay, that is
an assurance, rather than a sneaking hunch.
</P>
<P>
   The other ``extreme'' course mode is Deathmatch Golf. This is
self-explanatory. You have at your disposal a number of artillery
balls: the Big Bertha (the blast radius is a city block), the
Howitzer (a ``circus tent-sized festival of destruction''), the
13-pound Frag Bomb and a small but effective grenade.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the pyrotechnics, the game retains a distinctly
golf-like formality. This is not a Quake free-for-all. Players take
turns. The hitting order on the first tee must be agreed upon.
There is also a decision about the maximum damage per hole, whether
explosive balls are allowed on the first tee and whether players
can be resurrected after their health score reaches zero _ and if
so, what is the penalty and the number of health points restored,
not to mention mulligans and gimmes.
</P>
<P>
   You can regain health points by making a birdie, an eagle or a
double eagle. If both players are within the blast radius of an
artillery ball and die simultaneously, the hole carries over. If
both players survive, the person with the lowest golf score wins.
In case of a tie, whoever has the most kills wins.
</P>
<P>
   It's very civilized, notwithstanding the exploding shells and
flying limbs. Unlike most computer death matches, there is no
fight-or-flight anxiety or rapid fire. All destruction is carefully
considered. Sometimes it's a tough call. For example, does one use
a 3- or 4-iron with the grenade, taking into account the sand traps
and wind conditions?
</P>
<P>
   The pace is deliberate, and the targets are static. It's trench
warfare on a golf course: Verdun with caddies, or croquet with a
body count.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still very sociable. You can play with up to three
other people. You can arrange tee times for nine holes of
Deathmatch Golf on the Internet. As with many online multiplayer
games, Links Extreme allows for chat, using either text or voice
messages.
</P>
<P>
   It speaks well for online games, a pursuit whose reputation has
been tarnished of late. On-line games combine two of our biggest
cultural bogeymen: computer games and the Internet. Critics
(universally non-gamers) tend to focus on the imagery and the
hotblooded competition.
</P>
<P>
   But few people realize how much agreement and consent has to
happen before two or more people can play a game, be it tennis or
Quake.
</P>
<P>
   Games are defined by rule systems; no matter how sweaty and
anarchic the action appears, there are always rules that must be
universally accepted by the players. As any parent knows,
persuading an adolescent to accept rule systems is a difficult
trick. On-line games persuade them to accept rule systems on a
routine basis, and that has a value, in and of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Death match, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Links Extreme, published by Microsoft; CD-ROM for Windows 95, 98
and NT 4.0; $34.95; for ages 13 and older.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
