<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-$ADV04-     06-30 1811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUMMER SCHOOL GROWS BIGGER THAN EVER
 &HT;    600&AMP;adds With SUMMER-DATA. For release Sunday, July 4.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Summer school enrollments are being pushed to
record levels across the United States by two new waves of students
_ younger ones who are lagging behind their classmates and older
ones trying to surge ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer school is bigger than it's ever been in my 22 years in
the field,'' said Michael Casserly, executive director of the
Council of the Great City Schools.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 million students _ one out of every 10 in the elementary
and secondary grades _ will be attending accredited summer schools
this year. More than 4 million others will be involved in organized
learning activities ranging from Bible school and arts and crafts
sessions to short courses in computers, science, history or foreign
languages.
</P>
<P>
   A Cox Newspapers survey found that seven of the nation's 10
largest school districts are enrolling more students this summer.
Their combined summer enrollments will jump to well over 600,000
this year, an increase of more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many districts are following a recent trend of mandatory
remedial programs in math and reading. But summer schools have been
growing steadily throughout the 1990s, according to a recent
federal report.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, only 15 percent of public elementary schools receiving
Title I poverty aid used the federal funds to subsidize summer
programs. That had risen to 41 percent by last summer, and is
expected to be higher this year.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly said at least 22 of the 56 large school districts that
belong to his Washington-based Council of the Great City Schools
not only offer summer school, but make it mandatory for a
significant number of students. That helps combat the biggest
shortcoming of traditional summer schools _ an average dropout rate
of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is a wonderful reflection of the national concern
that all kids meet high standards,'' said Education Secretary
Richard Riley. ``Kids who fell behind used to be socially promoted
or flunked; either course was bad for them. Now there's a consensus
that it's better to send them to summer school.''
</P>
<P>
   Only about one-fifth of the grade-schoolers and two-fifths of
the high school students in summer school come there for the
traditional reason: retaking a course they had failed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the U.S. Department of Education reported in May that
most summer students fall into two categories: low performers or
highly proficient.
</P>
<P>
   Low performers may never have failed a course, but they do so
poorly on standardized reading or math tests that they are urged or
required to go to summer school.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Walker of Waco, Texas, said her son Alvin ``ended up
enjoying it last year,'' when he had to pass reading in summer
school in order to be promoted to third grade.
</P>
<P>
   This year, like nearly two-thirds of last summer's students in
Waco, Alvin was promoted to the next grade without problems. ``This
summer he gets to sleep late,'' Mrs. Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Top performers, on the other hand are volunteering for extra
courses in order to get through school faster, study an unusual
subject, or improve their chances of admission to a prestigious
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I want to do when I am older and go to
college, and summer gives me a chance to pick up different ideas,''
said Alex Ridder, a junior at Kent Denver High School in Colorado.
As part of a one-week course in environmental journalism, he
paddled a canoe past dead fish floating on the Anacostia River
after a summer storm flushed raw sewage into storm drains in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional adds follow.)
</P>
<P>
   Like other parts of the fragmented U.S. education system, summer
schools vary a lot. Few are further apart than the widely admired
programs in Long Beach, Calif., which stresses remediation, and the
Parkway school district in Missouri, which stresses enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids are absolutely in a meat-and-potatoes program,'' said
Chris Steinhauser, the summer school superintendent in Long Beach.
There, 3,900 of the 15,000 students in second and third grade,
along with 450 fifth-graders, were sent to summer school by the
district or their parents for basic courses in reading or math.
</P>
<P>
   Each teacher concentrates on teaching a small group of students
with similar deficiencies under a tightly controlled curriculum
designed by the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have time to waste on nonproductive activities. If
it's language arts, then for four hours, they read, they write,
they spell,'' Steinhauser said. ``A lot of people were critical of
that, but it worked. So now a lot of places are copying us.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposite philosophy is applied with equal enthusiasm outside
St. Louis in the suburban Parkway school district, where summer
school superintendent Craig Larson scoffed at ``drill and kill''
remedial classes as ``insane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If all you do in the summer is take a kid who hated the
regular school day, and make it even dryer and uglier in the
summer, why would that work?'' Larson asked. ``Our goal is to get
the kids excited about school so they progress academically without
you marching into the room to make them do the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkway this summer is offering classes that range from ceramics
and medical biology to bicycle maintenance and a social studies
course in which students research and debate a specific public
policy. Last summer's topic: President Harry Truman's decision to
authorize the atomic bombing of cities in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The 21,000-student district, which also operates two satellite
summer programs in poor areas of St. Louis, this year has more than
8,000 summer students _ one-sixth of them from outside the
district.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   There are still many holdouts against summer school, especially
in states that don't generously subsidize it.
</P>
<P>
   Given a limited amount of money to help its disproportionate
share of low-performing students, Palm Beach County, Fla., decided
to concentrate on before-school and after-school programs, instead
of mandatory summer school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes much more practical sense than waiting (until) a
student has failed and trying to fix that in a couple of weeks over
the summer,'' said Bettye (cq) Roth, director of curriculum and
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, summer school is that it usually helps
students, and hardly ever harms them, said Harris Cooper, an
education expert at the University of Missouri-Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students who go to summer school achieve more academically
than the same kind of students who don't go,'' he concluded after
leading a team of researchers whose ``meta-analysis'' of more than
300 studies of the effect of summer school programs is to be
published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that kids' brains don't turn off in June,
that they are capable of learning no matter what the weather is
outside,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that summer school still leaves plenty of time
for a child to drift freely through ``those lazy, hazy, crazy days
of summer'' celebrated by singer Nat King Cole. The average summer
program lasts five weeks and takes 16 hours a week less time than
the average child spends watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   Summer school also combats ``summer slide,'' in which knowledge
of fact-specific skills like spelling and arithmetic fades away
during the vacation months, said sociologist Karl Alexander at
Johns Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that the children from lower-income households (in
Baltimore) improved at the same rate as those from upper-income
households during the regular school year,'' Alexander said, ``but
they slid back during the summer, while the others continued to
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   To a smaller extent, today's higher demand for year-round
special education and for courses in English as a second language
also contributed to the growth of summer school. That may help
explain why Hispanic students are nearly twice as likely as
non-Hispanic whites to go to summer school.
</P>
<P>
   Another, stronger source of support for the trend is the oldest:
a desire to find safe daytime activities for the youngest
schoolchildren. Summer school first became popular in the United
States after 1916, when child labor laws made it harder for
grade-school children in big cities to find paying summer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Child safety and supervision re-emerged as issues in the 1990s,
after changes in the economy, family structure and welfare laws
meant more children are being raised within families in which the
only parent or both parents work.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many summer schools that end around midday help out
working parents by pairing up with a low-cost afternoon recreation
program sponsored by a parks department, youth organization or
other community group.
</P>
<P>
   ``In poor families, in particular, in our mobile society, there
are not always a lot of relatives around to mind the kids,'' said
Linda Lopez, a school board member from Tucson's Sunnyside
District, where about 3,000 of the 15,000 students attend summer
school.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many studies have shown that organized educational or
recreational programs before or after the regular school day reduce
juvenile crime. Many people believe summer school might do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the main thing is the kids get more one-on-one attention
from the faculty in the smaller classes in the summer, so their
skills don't get rusty,'' Lopez said. ``Otherwise, it can take four
to six weeks to play catch-up when they return in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A big argument for all-year schools has been that if you break
the 180-day pattern into 45-day segments separated by three-week
vacations, kids forget less during the breaks,'' said teacher Marge
Eberts, a columnist on the Web-based Family Eduction Network.
``Summer school goes one step further, giving them extra days and
hours of instructional time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing slowing the trend is the cost: it takes a bundle to
retrofit an old school for air conditioning,'' said Steve
Jongewaard, (cq) professor of education at Hamline (cq) University
in St. Paul, Minn. During a heat wave in Chicago last summer, some
children in 100-year-old schools were passing out.
</P>
<P>
   But summer school can be especially helpful for ``kids whose
families can't afford to send them to camp or take them on
educational trips to Colonial Williamsburg or the Grand Canyon,''
Jongewaard said. And on a practical note, he added, ``For a child
on the free or reduced-price lunch program, it's also valuable as a
place to get something to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Raven Hill of the Cox Newspapers Washington Bureau contributed
to this article.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
