<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS REGISTRY TIP: LOOK, BUT DON'T TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have heard a lot about the Microsoft Windows registry. What
is a registry and what is it used for?
</P>
<P>
   A. The registry is a vast and detailed database of information
that Windows uses to keep track of your system's settings and
configuration information. Each time you add a hardware device like
a modem or scanner, install new programs or adjust your system's
settings, new data are added to the registry file. This file is so
important to your computer's health that Windows will not run
properly (if at all) if the registry is damaged or corrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The registry is organized into six main parts that contain
different data about your computer. You can see the registry
hierarchy by going to your Start menu, selecting Run and typing
``regedit.'' The names on the HKEY folders tell you what settings
files are inside.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to edit your registry files manually, but it is
highly advisable not to do anything more than just look. If you are
not careful (or don't know what you are doing), tinkering with the
registry could severely affect your computer's ability to operate.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, fully reinstalling the Windows operating system
is the only way to fix a damaged registry. There are several ways
to back up your Windows 95 registry, and some are more complicated
than others. One of the easiest methods is going to the Registry
Editor, selecting Export Registry File from the Registry menu and
saving it in a safe place. Double-clicking on this backup file
restores it to the registry. The Emergency Recovery Utility program
on the Windows 95 CD-ROM will also back up your registry for you.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows Registry Checker tool in Windows 98 backs up the
registry file for you each time you boot up. If you tend to leave
your computer on for extended periods without rebooting, you can
run the Registry Checker by typing ``scanregw.exe'' in the Run
window. The checker will try to fix a damaged registry or revert to
a previous copy if it finds anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For registry maintenance, Microsoft offers a utility called
Regclean that can help weed out old entries. You can find this
update in the Windows area of
support.microsoft.com/support/downloads.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com or postal mail to Questions, Circuits,
The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959.
This column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
