   IMMIG-EMERGENCY-CARE (New York) _ They look like any of the
anxious patients who walk into the city's polyglot emergency rooms.
But there are telltale signs: Sometimes they arrive with luggage
and with tourist visas in their pockets. Often they hand over
crumpled notes from their doctors back home in China or Africa.
They are known as medical immigrants, poor or middle-class
foreigners who scrape and save to fly to New York, solely to seek
treatment at city emergency rooms, where federal and state law
mandates that they must be examined and treated if their problems
require immediate care. By Randy Kennedy.
