u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CARD-SHUFFLER-NYT     06-30 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CARD-SHUFFLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERIZED MACHINE STEPS IN TO SHUFFLE CARDS BY THE TON
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the organizers of last month's European contract bridge
championships in Malta had 10 days to shuffle and deal about
200,000 hands of cards, they turned to Per Jannersten. ``That's
getting to be a ton of cards,'' Jannersten said, speaking
literally.
</P>
<P>
   While Jannersten attended the match, he did not personally do
the work. Instead the tournament, like all international
competitions, relied on the Duplimate Mark IV, a computerized card
shuffling machine developed and produced by Jannersten's company,
Jannersten Forlag (www.jannersten.com), in Avesta, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works flawlessly,'' said Brent Manley, editor of The Bridge
Bulletin, the magazine of the American Contract Bridge League. ``It
would take you about forever to do by hand what this machine
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Jannersten insists that the Duplimate is not only far faster
than the human hand but also far better. Studies show that human
card shufflers aren't nearly as good at mixing up cards to
guarantee the maximum variety in bridge games, Jannersten said.
``They don't take enough time,'' he said, and people are also more
prone to errors.
</P>
<P>
   With the Duplimate, software running on a standard Windows-based
computer figures out the shuffles and deals for each of the four
players at the card table. In theory at least, extremely patient
players could simply let the software do its work, examine the
result on their monitors and then pick their way through decks of
cards, pulling out the cards the computer says should be in their
hards.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Jannersten's machine valuable to tournament
organizers who value their sanity is a low-slung box that connects
to the personal computer. At one end, a bin accepts a package of
playing cards specially marked with tiny bar codes on the face of
each card. When the PC downloads its virtual deal into the
Duplimate's memory, the unit's microprocessor works with a bar code
reader as it picks out the correct cards and has them delivered to
the right players through a series of moving belts. The cards fall
into one of four slots, each labeled for a specific playing
position.
</P>
<P>
   The Duplimate, especially in its earlier incarnations, strongly
resembles the once mighty but now nearly extinct computer punch
card reader; the first Duplimate was built in 1989. That's not
entirely surprising given that its most direct ancestor was an
extremely complicated electrical and mechanical card sorter, also
made in Sweden and distributed by Jannersten Forlag, that relied on
playing cards with tiny holes punched in them .
</P>
<P>
   But by the late 1980s, international bridge officials were
becoming concerned that cheaters might be identifying cards by
reading their punched-hole patterns. Although Jannersten seriously
doubted that such cheating was actually happening, he nevertheless
hired engineers and designers to produce a much more sophisticated,
fully electronic dealing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Duplimate can turn out an infinite number of
identical sets of hands _ or boards, as they are known in bridge _
it has largely been responsible for the development of the
tournament game known as barometer bridge, said Manley, of The
Bridge Bulletin. In that game, large numbers of players use
identical hands generated by the Duplimate. At the end of each
round, all the teams' results are calculated and the teams are
ranked. ``It's the horse race of bridge,'' Jannersten said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the machines, which start at more than $2,000, are not
for everyone. Although some individuals in Scandinavia have bought
Duplimates for their homes, Jannersten said that most units went to
either bridge federations or large clubs. (An Australian company
makes a less sophisticated sorter that competes with the
Duplimate.)
</P>
<P>
   But there is hope that some form of Duplimate may be coming to a
card table near you soon. Late this summer, the company plants to
introduce a semimanual sorter that will sell for ``several hundred
dollars.'' It will be aimed at players who measure their cards in
ounces rather than tons, Jannersten said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
