<HEADER>
A4881 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FIRST-COMPUTER-AR     06-30 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FIRST-COMPUTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGONY, ECSTACY, AGONY: ENTER THE COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By EDWIN ROTHMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Edwin Rothman, 66, an osteopathic physician from Haverford,
Pa., recently bought his first computer, a 400-megahertz mail-order
machine. His immediate goals? To use the Internet to pursue his
rare-book collecting, to get up-to-the-minute information on his
investments and to send e-mail to his four grandchildren. Rothman,
while no stranger to gadgets, has never used an ATM, has never
turned on the cellular phone that came with his car and always
bypasses an automated phone answering system in favor of a live
voice. Here are excerpts from a diary of his foray into the
computer world.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY, MAY 17 _ Entered my house and was suddenly aware of four
huge cartons sitting on the floor. My personal computer had
arrived. I panicked, even though everyone had told me, ``In one
week, you'll be a pro.''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY, MAY 18 _ Purchased the obligatory computer table.
Waited for call from local cable television company, which supplies
Internet access, about hooking up computer _ which, of course, is
still in boxes.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY, MAY 19 _ Cable company finally called back with
information about installing line for computer. Was told to have
computer ready to run. Informed company's representative that it
was easy for him to say but not easy for me to do.
</P>
<P>
   Finally got up the nerve to open cartons, looking for how-to
documents. Called my son and asked for help. ``Dad,'' he said,
``you always told me to read the instructions before you do
anything. Take your own advice.''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY, MAY 20 _ Played round of golf but didn't enjoy it. All
I could think of was my computer. Arrived home. Found that Jimmy, a
carpenter working at my house, had assembled table. It was sitting
there, waiting for its computer. Was completely unnerved and had a
drink.  &QL; 
FRIDAY, MAY 21 _ Hooray! Pulled computer from boxes, connected all
the cables, turned it on (all with help from Jimmy, again). Boot-up
was successful.
</P>
<P>
   Aggravation with Windows 98. Read start-up booklet, but was
unable to follow instructions. Shut down computer, restarted it and
was admonished by message on screen. Afraid to restart.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY, MAY 22 _ Asked a computer-literate friend to help.
After watching him moving and clicking mouse for one hour, I told
him to leave. Then my son arrived and basically did the same thing.
Told him to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Cable company guy arrived and soon I was successfully hooked up
to Internet. But after 10 minutes of aimless wandering of the Web,
shut down computer in great deal of frustration. Decide to get a
computer tutor.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, MAY 23 _ Purchased ``Windows 98 for Dummies'' at local
bookstore. Was clerk laughing at me?
</P>
<P>
   Booted up computer in hope that some divine being would allow me
some semblance of understanding of Windows. Alas, it was not to be.
Shut down system. ``Windows 98 for Dummies'' is no help, which says
a great deal about my technical aptitude.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY, MAY 25 _ Tutor arrives and departs several hours later,
leaving me confused and disappointed. Too didactic, not practical
enough. Don't even learn how to e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Hired new instructor to be here in two days. Hope and pray that
she will be more helpful.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY, MAY 27 _ I did it! Successfully sent e-mail to my
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   New instructor arrives, and three hours later I have a headache.
Felt this instructor was more practical and less pedagogical,
though still feel like a neonate.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY, MAY 28 _ I just finished spending a half-hour with my
computer-literate daughter. Perhaps I should hire her as an
instructor, gratis, of course.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY, MAY 29 _ Turned on computer, thought I knew what to
do, again wandered aimlessly on the Internet. Evidently the
computer is more intelligent than I, or I am less intelligent than
I thought. My frustration level is climbing. Having trouble with
e-mail again.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, MAY 30 _ Thank goodness for my son-in-law. He contacted
online provider, righted problems with e-mail, and I am a new
person. Now I know my daughter made the right choice in spouses.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY, JUNE 1 _ Really, really frustrated. Informed that
several e-mail messages were sent to me, but I am unable to
retrieve them. Either I am stupid or the computer is not
functioning properly _ not a very enticing choice.
</P>
<P>
   Call son-in-law, but reach daughter instead. She talks my way
through the e-mail problem. Now I know my son-in-law made the right
choice in spouses.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY, JUNE 2 _ Received and sent e-mail. I must be getting
proficient! I still have not surfed the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Later, absolute panic sets in. Returned from dinner and received
e-mail. While aimlessly moving icon, I removed the Start menu from
the desktop! Called online help and was put on hold for 15 minutes,
during which time I kept opening and closing different menus, to no
avail. In desperation, I punched different keys and saw the start
menu. Turned off computer. I envisioned a sleepless night.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY, JUNE 3 _ Finished one-hour lesson with instructor,
explored Internet and search engines. Disquietude still exists,
almost two weeks since this irreverent, inanimate (although I'm not
sure about that) computer entered my life.
</P>
<P>
   Later, my wife started first lesson and immediately called to
me, ``Dear, I just set up my own user name.'' Trouble beckons. I'll
have to share this as I share everything else.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY, JUNE 4 _ Love libraries and bookstores. Haven't been to
one in two weeks, having spent most of my spare time in front of
this machine. Spent one and a half hours in Barnes &AMP; Noble. For
five minutes, I rapidly skimmed over new fiction and nonfiction.
Remainder of time, I perused the plethora of books regarding
Windows 98. Purchased the one with the simplest pictures. I must be
reverting to my childhood.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, JUNE 6 _ Became adventurous. Found Web site for Winston
Churchill (I'm a big fan) but soon got lost. I didn't know what to
do next, so I went to check my stock portfolios. I could not
remember what name and password I used previously, so I entered
various ones, to no avail. So I closed everything and played
solitaire. Won a game. There's still hope for me.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY, JUNE 8 _ Realism has set in. I can send and receive
e-mail, and it's fun, but I find that my other objectives still
elude me.
</P>
<P>
   But I vow to keep working at it, confident that someday,
neophytes will come to me for advice and I will answer, ``Don't
worry, in one week you'll be a pro.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
