<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH STUMBLES ON GOLD RUSH IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ ``Conservative'' is collecting $4.5 million
over three days for his Republican presidential campaign.
``Compassionate'' is speaking Spanish on a stage at the Del Mar
Fair while a mariachi band plays ``Vaya Con Dios.''
</P>
<P>
   On his three-day trip through California, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush is giving the contributors to his presidential campaign an
explanation of what it means to be a ``compassionate
conservative.'' It means, for example, the government needs to
``confront illegitimacy'' while offering ``practical help to women
and children in crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is conservative to reform welfare by insisting on work,''
Bush told about 400 Orange County Republicans Tuesday. ``It is
compassionate to take the side of charities and churches that
confront the suffering that remains.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the public speech, but Bush is teaching Republicans
something much more critical than the meaning of his campaign
slogan.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush essentially came here to raise money _ loads of it _
from California Republicans, he also brought a message the
California GOP didn't hear very well during the 1998 elections:
Ignore the state's burgeoning Hispanic population and lose.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's first non-fund-raising stop in California came at the
Plaza de Mexico at the Del Mar Fair. Young folklorico dancers took
the stage. People shouted ``Viva Bush'' as he worked the 4-H
exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate spoke in Spanish to the crowd and told reporters
afterward that Proposition 187, the anti-illegal immigration ballot
initiative, wouldn't work in his state. ``I said when it first came
out that I'm against the spirit of 187,'' Bush said. ``I felt like
every child ought to be educated regardless of the status of their
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, said the same thing
recently when asked whether illegal immigrant children should be
kicked out of school. Conservative groups that put Proposition 187
on the ballot lambasted Davis for his remarks and said they would
mount a recall effort. Now, the Republican presidential candidate
is bringing a similar message to California, where 70 percent of
Hispanics who went to the polls in 1994 voted against Proposition
187, which nonetheless was approved.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the Republican Party in the last election,
including former Attorney General Dan Lungren's brutal 20-point
loss to Davis, was blamed significantly on a divisiveness that
arose because of the GOP's support of Proposition 187.
</P>
<P>
   ``All wisdom is based on the last election,'' said Bruce Cain, a
political scientist at the University of California at Berkeley.
``You tend to take the lessons from the last election and apply it
to the next. A lot of what we're seeing now is what was learned
from the last campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also avoided throwing himself entirely behind Proposition
209, the ballot initiative that ended public affirmative action
programs in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the spirit of no quotas and no preferences,'' Bush
said. ``But I think it's important to say not what you're against
but what you're for. As you know, in our state I'm for increasing
the pool of applicants, opening the door so that more people are
eligible to go to the university system.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Texas was moving toward a system based more on
economic need than racial preferences. ``I've learned you cannot
lead by dividing people,'' Bush has said repeatedly in his
fund-raising speeches. ``I'm a uniter not a divider.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's trip to California was intended to introduce himself to
voters. But the introduction is a lot more complicated than anyone
could have predicted for a general election that is 17 months away.
</P>
<P>
   When GOP presidential candidate Lamar Alexander visited
Sacramento recently, he took a cab, alone, from the airport to his
campaign stop. The Bush campaign, with a huge press corps in
attendance, already looks presidential. The campaign has chartered
an MD-80 aircraft dubbed ``Great Expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush picked up nearly $480,000 at breakfast Tuesday in La Jolla.
The haul that morning was supposedly a record for a federal
candidate in San Diego. Outside the ballroom, supporters were
literally kneeling on the tightly woven carpet writing out $1,000
checks _ the federal limit _ before heading in for a handshake, a
continental breakfast, and Bush's nearly worn speech about what it
means to be a compassionate conservative.
</P>
<P>
   The line-up for the rest of the fund-raisers was equally
massive: $400,000 at an Irvine luncheon; $2.3 million at a Los
Angeles dinner with at least 1,920 contributors, including actress
Bo Derek, who sponsored a table; $250,000 at Sacramento events
Wednesday; $800,000 at a San Francisco dinner Wednesday night;
another $300,000 at a Silicon Valley event Thursday; and $150,000
in Fresno.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Bush campaign announced that it had raised at
least $35.5 million in the first six months of the year, swamping
the $18.5 million raised by the apparent Democratic front-runner,
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
