<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STERN-ARCHITECTURE-AR     06-30 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STERN-ARCHITECTURE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YALE ARCHITECTURE DEAN'S REMODELING JOB: HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can the New York architect Robert A.M. Stern, famous for
replicating old-money architecture right down to the eyebrow
dormers, shed his gray shingles to become a hipper, populist
educator in tune with the restless talents of tomorrow?
</P>
<P>
   When Yale University president Richard C. Levin announced last
fall that he had appointed Stern, who calls himself a modern
traditionalist, as the new dean of the Yale School of Architecture,
the news roiled the design community. Nor did it go down easily
with the 150 Yale graduate students in architecture, for whom a
Walt Disney Corp. board member (he was appointed in 1992) was quite
possibly the last candidate on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the astonishment of many in the field, Reed Kroloff,
editor of the slick Architecture magazine, wrote in October 1998:
``Who's got the mojo to lead the fabled school into the 21st
century? Are you sitting down?'' He went on to condense Stern as
``the suede-loafered sultan of suburban retrotecture, Disney party
boy and notorious academic curmudgeon.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stern gave his first speech as dean, 10 students walked out
to protest the unilateral process by which the dapper Stern had
been selected: he had not been one of the four paraded contenders
for the job. Then, Levin surprised everyone by naming him.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rocky start.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, who graduated from the school in 1965, bridles at the
suggestion that such blatantly traditional projects as the Thornton
Wilder-esque master plan for Celebration, the Disney town in
Florida, or the model house in Wilton, Conn., for This Old House
magazine, might represent the gamut of his esthetic sensibility.
``Listen, I was trained as a modernist under Paul Rudolph,'' Stern
said, invoking Yale's eccentric but much admired architecture dean
during the 1960s. ``I don't know what they thought I was going to
do. Open a Ralph Lauren shop?'' He spoke in the low growl, a mock
rage, that is his trademark.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the work in the architect's Manhattan firm ranges
widely, from the proudly Jeffersonian School of Business for the
University of Virginia to a pulsating, kaleidoscopic vision for
redeveloping parts of Times Square. In addition, he taught design
and architectural history at the Columbia Graduate School of
Architecture, Preservation and Planning starting in 1970 and is the
author of a three-volume series on New York City's history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with an academic year behind him and a general thaw in the
students' reception, Stern is well on his way to reinventing
himself as a happening dean, the school's first unmarried steward
since Charles Moore in the late 1960s. Key to the transformation is
a bachelor pad, a duplex loft in downtown New Haven, Conn., for
entertaining. It is two blocks from the school, in a Renaissance
Revival building overlooking the town green and next to an Ann
Taylor boutique.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of new energy on tap reveals itself at the loft's street
entrance, with the realization that the 60-year-old Stern lives in
a third-floor walk-up. Inside, from the swatch of Andy Warhol's
pink and yellow ``Cow'' wallpaper, the Bang &AMP; Olufsen compact-disk
player and the black rubber rug in the living room to the Philippe
Starck clear polycarbonate chair in the kitchen, the loft is
stridently modern.
</P>
<P>
   The furnishings are a role call of classics by Le Corbusier,
Jean Prouve, Charles and Ray Eames, George Nelson, Eero Saarinen,
Robert Venturi and Norman Foster, with a few rusty finds from
Lafayette Street rakishly thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   The loft design was treated like any other project in Stern's
professional office, right down to a half-inch-scale cardboard
model, with photocopied images of paintings and furniture, in the
exact shade, the better to envision room arrangements. ``It was
like having your mother for a client,'' said Roger Seifter, a
partner in the Robert A.M. Stern firm, who ran the three-month
project. ( Stern paid for the furnishings and takes care of the
rent.)
</P>
<P>
   His plan was one large room, ideal for entertaining a first-year
class of 40 students. ``He saw his position as a social one,''
Seifter said. It would be hard to imagine anything farther from the
lobbylike salons, chockablock with stuffed sofas and the
marble-lined foyers published so frequently over Stern's name in
Architectural Digest. (Lore has it that they informed Tom Wolfe's
descriptions of the too-good life in ``Bonfire of the Vanities.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``In New Haven, I get to have my downtown feeling,'' said Stern,
who spends two nights a week there during the school year but
otherwise lives in a small apartment on Manhattan's Upper East
Side, seldom straying south. ``Going downtown doesn't fit into my
schedule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also owns a ranchburger in East Hampton that he renovated
into a stately shingle house.
</P>
<P>
   The architect is divorced and has a son, Nick, 31, an
independent theater producer who once worked as a Disney Imagineer.
``He's trying to be hip and downtown, like I am,'' Nick Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A.M. Stern threw a number of receptions in the late
spring to let students and faculty know he was on their wavelength.
Devin O'Neill, who just graduated and is working for the architect
Deborah Berke in Manhattan, has made the off-campus trek to the
loft. ``There's a lot of wow! furniture,'' O'Neill said. ``It was
nice to actually see some of the pieces that I only know from
books.''
</P>
<P>
   A glimpse into the pantry revealed shelves lined with rows of
oversize martini glasses and stacks of black cocktail napkins in
two sizes. The shelf paper is a silver plastic emblazoned with a
three-dimensional Op Art pattern. ``I'm not Mr. Party Boy,'' Stern
said while directing an assistant to restock the smaller black
cocktail napkins. ``But part of the role of this loft is to help me
develop a sense of esprit and to get to know the students.''
</P>
<P>
   The swank loft as platform for a chance-taking dean (and perhaps
to convert those unimpressed by the 16,000-square-foot log cabin he
designed for Michael Eisner) is not lost on some who have seen it.
Mark Shafiri, a recent graduate, described Stern on campus as a
constant but inscrutable presence. ``The loft is an apt metaphor
for his personality,'' he said. ``The formal rooms in front are
done up just as they should be as the home of a famous New York
architect. Then in the back there's this grungy abandoned space
that's stripped out and quite mysterious.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the view through the arched windows in the living
room is a charming vista of a typical New England green, the scene
out the rear-view window in the bedroom is of a large, spiraling
concrete parking garage ramp. ``My personal Guggenheim,'' Stern
said.
</P>
<P>
   A faculty member noted that, excluding the Le Corbusier
leather-covered chaise, there are no seats for two to sit on at the
same time. The rarefied gallery effect was underscored by Stern's
curatorial pride in showing off a chair in the front hall made of
irregularly-cut clear plastic tubing; it was designed by the
Campana brothers of Brazil, young stars of a recent show at the
Museum of Modern Art in Manhattan. ``I have the only piece in the
country besides the one at the museum,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Does the loft work? A half dozen students from the graduating
class seemed appreciative of Stern's obvious effort to win them
over. They noted that he was the first dean since Paul Rudolph to
live near the school and were impressed by how quickly he was able
to get new computers installed in the school.
</P>
<P>
   Stern's boldest academic move last spring _ inviting
nonagenarian architect Philip Johnson to teach a class with the
outspokenly theoretical Peter Eisenman _ backfired with some
students. Stern sent out press releases and a television crew
showed up for class, several students said. ``It was a media event
that went overboard,'' Shafiri said, ``but it wasn't education any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleased that the new dean wants to restore some of Yale's star
power _ Stern has scheduled Daniel Libeskind and Frank Gehry to
teach in the fall _ Eric Clough, a student, said of the studio,
``Half the class was concerned with it being a gimmick, while the
other half was taking advantage of these amazing people.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarra Cotterman, now working for a small firm in New Haven, was
one of the dissenters. ``I would rather have really good teachers
interested in new ideas, not in themselves,'' she said, dismissing
the august Johnson as ``just a nice old man who's done a lot of
buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern also attempted to reintroduce a grade point system in an
effort to raise competitive excellence. The students fought it,
then admired Stern for listening _ and backing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He desperately wants to be successful,'' said Eisenman, who
has known Stern for more than 30 years. ``But if history is going
to remember him as a great dean, he has to have the pulse of the
moment, and he can't retreat into academia, egotism or ideology.
Luckily, there are many faces of Bob.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
