<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4910 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-WILDWEST-TEX     06-30 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WILDWEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH'S CHARM, BRANAGH'S LUNACY SALVAGE `WEST' REMAKE AS A GUILTY
PLEASURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who bothers to complain about ``Wild, Wild West'' because
of its African-American star _ Will Smith plays James West,
essentially the first Secret Service agent _ misses the point. The
original series didn't exactly radiate historical accuracy, either.
</P>
<P>
   And never has a star seemed to enjoy himself so much as Smith.
His uncomplicated sunniness makes him look as if he's never missed
a night's sleep in his entire life. And he's so contemporary, he
might as well be the only cowboy on the range to carry a cell phone
and a pager.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the joke. In the 1960s TV series, also set in the
United States just after the Civil War, Robert Conrad had the
square-jawed, wind-me-up stiffness that seemed a product of the
era; he's a graduate of the Bill Shatner School of Fine Actin'. At
least in this movie derived from the series, Smith seems a lot more
comfortable, possibly because his clothes fit. (Conrad might have
gotten in so many fights because his outfits looked a couple of
sizes too tight _ that could account for a lot of tension.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie turns partners James West and Artemus Gordon, played
by Kevin Kline, into a pair of squabbling buddy cops forced to work
together by their superior, President Ulysses S. Grant (also played
by Kline). West's and Gordon's separate investigations eventually
put them on the trail of the same man, former Confederate
strategist Dr. Arliss Loveless (Kenneth Branagh).
</P>
<P>
   Loveless is short here, but unlike the TV series Loveless
(Michael Dunn), whose diminutive stature made him the original
Mini-Me, the movie's Loveless is a Civil War survivor who exists
only as a torso and head. Loveless' plan is to take over the United
States with his grotesque mechanical inventions and auction off the
country to European powers.
</P>
<P>
   Salma Hayek is Rita, who's tailing Loveless to find her father;
she joins up with West and Gordon, who compete for her attention.
She's what they used to call in old westerns The Girl. But ``West''
features other old-fashioned touches, like the bad guys attacking
Jim West one at a time, and at an old-fashioned leisurely pace,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The movie features a number of genuinely witty visual touches,
such as sheep grazing on the White House lawn and a cornet-size
hearing aid perched in an ear of one villain. And the inventions by
the scientific visionaries Gordon and Loveless have the
rivet-studded gimmickry inspired by science-fiction visionary Jules
Verne; the production design sends up modern technology taking over
the world. (That was a part of the old show as well, but only
because the series was trying to keep up with the James Bond movies
of the era.)
</P>
<P>
   Many of Loveless' inventions _ like a giant mechanical spider
the size of a skyscraper _ are not only obvious replacements for
his legs, but for his loss of potency as well. His motorized
wheelchair cranks out an oily cloud of smoke as it chugs across the
West. And Loveless' posse is a group of brainy, beautiful women _
the World's Smartest Supermodels.
</P>
<P>
   ``West'' also makes blithe fun of racism. It uses ``Blazing
Saddles'' as a point of departure, as well as Bob Hope comedies
such as ``Son of Paleface,'' in which the hero's modernism was also
part of the joke. ``West's'' irony is so pervasive that when the
movie tries to play it straight _ such as a scene in which West
explains that he was raised by Indians _ it comes off like a joke.
The movie works better when it doesn't try to explain anything,
since nothing in the real world could possibly account for it.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is part of a tradition of acting started by Eddie Murphy.
Like Murphy, Smith satirizes the upright cool of action heroes. He
doesn't take himself seriously for a second, yet that doesn't
detract from crowds' enjoyment of Smith. (That's also a tribute to
Smith's considerable charisma.) This makes Smith like a modern-day
version of Bob Hope and Bing Crosby: quick-witted and laid-back at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Smith couldn't be luckier in having a director like Barry
Sonnenfeld. (This isn't Sonnenfeld's first time at the TV
series-into-movie dance; he made his directing debut on ``The
Addams Family'' and also handled its sequel.) Sonnenfeld's
directing style is flashy yet simple. He stages all the action at
the center of the frame, and the principals seem to have a small
spotlight on them _ his movies are set up like elegant versions of
``Mad'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   A former cinematographer, Sonnenfeld envelops his stars with
enough glamour that they take their places on screen by natural
right. (Think about how Sonnenfeld italicized John Travolta's
essence in ``Get Shorty.)'' Smith gets a movie-star entrance in
almost every scene, drawing and spinning his pistols whenever he
walks into a room.
</P>
<P>
   As the eccentric master-of-disguise Artemus Gordon, Kline is
lost, because his furtive twinkle can't compete with Smith's
outsize easiness. Kilne registers most impressively in his
vaudevillian turn as President Grant, who wears his oblivious
arrogance like a signet ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``West'' also has the Sonnenfeld knack for collapsing the story:
The movie goes straight from setup to climax, leaving out the
entire second act. (Sonnenfeld first used this trick in ``Men in
Black.)'' At 107 minutes, the movie seems barely as long as the
video for the Will Smith song ``Wild, Wild West.'' Like the song,
the movie is a propulsive sample, snatching from every available
source and blithely exploiting what has worked before. (The song
may be the most aggressive double sample in history, plundering
both Stevie Wonder's ``Sir Duke'' and Kool Mo Dee's ``Wild, Wild
West.'')
</P>
<P>
   Through the movies, Smith has freed himself from the fate that
seemed to be the final resting-place of all former rap stars _ an
NBC sitcom _ and launched himself into rap's biggest comeback. He's
grown into the assurance he played at having on TV. He's become
skilled enough that he can hold his own in scenes with Branagh,
where the most interesting dueling emerges; they bait each other
with race and disability insults.
</P>
<P>
   It's Branagh _ playing Loveless as a fatty, salty piece of
Southern ham with a lewd, hungry gleam in his eye _ who has the
most unforgettable moment in the picture. At the helm of the
gargantuan tarantula as it stalks across the plains of Utah, this
would-be conqueror gleams with the loony serenity of a true madman.
He rolls away with the picture.
</P>
<P>
   If not for him, ``Wild, Wild West'' would end up a lot like its
star, Will Smith _ brazen, slick, handsome and, at its center, a
little bland. Despite all the noise, smoke and gunplay, this action
comedy could be called ``Mild, Mild West.'' But it's undeniably one
of the most astounding blends of pop culture ever to be seen in a
movie, and on its own could make up for the cultural imperialism of
pictures like ``Phantom Menace'' and ``Tarzan.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Wild, Wild West''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Barry Sonnenfeld
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Will Smith, Kevin Kline, Kenneth Branagh, Salma Hayek
</P>
<P>
   Length: 107 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ sexual innuendo, adult language and violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
