<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWNES-VANZANDT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNES VAN ZANDT'S WIFE HELPS HIM LIVE ON IN POSTHUMOUS CD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before he died in January 1997, Townes Van Zandt used to tell
his wife, Jeanene, that he might not have been famous when he was
alive, but that once he passed away she would be ``a very busy
girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanene didn't know what the Fort Worth native and genius
songwriter meant; there was little chance of a Jimi Hendrix-like
post-mortem popularity explosion. Van Zandt never sold many
records, even though he'd been a major influence on people such as
Lyle Lovett, Steve Earle and the Cowboy Junkies _ covered by
everyone from Willie Nelson and Merle Haggard to Bob Dylan to
Seattle grunge band Mudhoney. He was known more for his hard living
than for his music.
</P>
<P>
   But 2 1/2 years after his death at age 52, Van Zandt is about to
get at least as much attention as he ever did alive, maybe more _
all because of a handful of tapes he casually passed along to
Jeanene shortly before his death.
</P>
<P>
   This week saw the release of ``A Far Cry From Dead,'' a
collection of 13 songs Van Zandt recorded primarily between 1989
and 1991. The music includes Van Zandt favorites such as ``Pancho
and Lefty, To Live Is to Fly, Snake Mountain Blues, For the Sake of
the Song,'' and two previously unheard tunes, including
``Sanitarium Blues,'' the last tune Van Zandt recorded.
</P>
<P>
   He gave the recordings to Jeanene with a cryptic ``Hang onto
these, babe,'' and she just set them aside until months after his
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was archiving his stuff and I wondered what was on them,''
says Jeanene Van Zandt, a Corpus Christi native who met her husband
in Austin in December 1980. ``So I called Eric (Paul) and we had
Thanksgiving dinner and started listening and I was like, `Holy cow
_ I never heard Townes sing and play this good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Paul is a respected Nashville producer who has worked with Kris
Kristofferson, Emmylou Harris, Johnny Cash and Nelson. He, too, was
stunned by what he was hearing. But like Jeanene, he didn't know
what to do with the tapes. Then Jeanene heard about the possibility
of a Van Zandt live CD that would include, she says, subpar
performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset,'' she says. ``I thought it'd destroy his career.
And then his voice came into my head saying, `Remember those tapes?
You've got everything you need.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She and Paul began working on the tapes, adding musicians over
the basic guitar-and-voice tracks that Van Zandt had laid down.
They didn't have a label, so to pay for the studio and musicians,
Jeanene sold off some stock she had been saving. The two of them
would sit in a Nashville studio with the lights off and candles
burning; there would be pictures of Van Zandt all over and, in a
little heart-shaped tin, his ashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go somewhere I take the tin,'' Jeanene says.
``When we started doing the record it was like, `Come on, Townes,
we're going to the studio.' I figured he'd want to be there. Townes
taught me a lot in 15 years, and it all came out _ I'd say `I want
butterfly wings' and Eric would know what I mean. I think in terms
of flowers; he knows how to make flowers show up on tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul says the hardest part was assembling the beginnings and
endings of the songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intros and exits were all fabricated,'' he says. ``Townes
didn't play intros. He'd just start. I strengthened what we had
with guitar and dobro when his guitar wasn't enough. The songs took
on their character at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   The most troublesome (both to record and to listen to) was Van
Zandt's final composition, ``Sanitarium Blues.'' Recorded as a
spoken poem, it describes, in chilling detail, being sent to a
sanitarium, receiving shock treatments, and the confusion he felt
upon being released. ``They hose you down, make sure you're
clean/Wrap you up in hospital green/Shoot you full of Thorazine/The
sanitarium blues,'' he sings in a clenched, despair-drenched voice.
</P>
<P>
   The CD was completed last year, and Jeanene and Paul didn't know
what to do with it. People at Arista Records were talking about Van
Zandt's music; Paul took the finished tapes to the label on a
Thursday and got a call back Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric told me they wanted the record,'' Jeanene says. ``And
when I put down the phone it was like a veil between me and the
other side had opened and I saw him there, smiling, for just a
second, and he was gone. All of his and my dreams were coming true,
and I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
