<SLUG> BC-FILM-SOUTHPARK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTH PARK' MOVIE HAS LOTS OF YUKS, BUT IT'S TOO YUCKY FOR KIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of the most horrendously offensive elements of Comedy
Central's crudely animated and even more crudely written ``South
Park'' _ whether that be singing and dancing feces; Chef's R-rated,
libidinous songs; or any assortment of jibes aimed at women, racial
minorities, gays, organized religion or the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Now take those elements and multiply them by, oh, say a
thousand. Now you might have some idea of what to expect from the
network's new spinoff film, ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut,''
the most unapologetically offensive movie ever to come out of
Hollywood. And did I mention it's also hilarious?
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of being drawn and quartered by parents who
accidentally stumble into this cartoon with their children, I'll
preface my praise with a stiff warning: There has NEVER been a
motion picture more inappropriate for children, even though it's
seemingly aimed at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park'' creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone have always
approached humor with the subtlety of a snickering 13-year-old boy,
so it stands to reason that the adventures of four foul-mouthed
Colorado youngsters (think Peanuts with profanity) would appeal to
kids. But director Parker has packed his film so full of
adults-only subject matter, even open-minded parents would be
insane to allow their preteens to see it.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of the ``South Park'' movie mirrors the inevitable
backlash the film will incur. Kyle, Stan, Kenny and Cartman sneak
into an R-rated movie starring their TV heroes Terrence and
Phillip, a pair of Canadian comics infatuated with flatulence.
</P>
<P>
   After the boys pick up a number of colorfully profane phrases,
their enthusiasm for the film infects all of South Park's children,
leading to a mass epidemic of cursing. Parents, led by Kyle's
outspoken mother, band together to vanquish the source of this ugly
new trend, declaring war on the most likely culprit ... Canada.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to summarize the action beyond this, because so much
of the film can't be discussed in a family newspaper. Suffice it to
say that, if there's a group out there not offended by something in
this film, its omission was purely unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Stone seem to have set up a checklist of everything
they knew they couldn't get away with on television and then fired
it all at audiences machine-gun style. The odd thing is, when your
jaw isn't lying on the floor in front of you, it's working overtime
laughing, albeit nervously, at stuff you're embarrassed to find
amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's previous effort as director, 1998's porn-biz parody
``Orgazmo,'' shared a similar sensibility in that it proudly
proclaimed itself an adult comedy. It's refreshing that in a
society increasingly obsessed with protecting its children from
anything inappropriate, some filmmakers still produce grown-up
entertainment without the slightest interest in how children will
perceive it.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning is simple; it's not for kids. And neither is
``South Park.'' Let's hope that as theaters start cracking down on
the carding of patrons of R-rated films, they pay special attention
to this one.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry kids, this cartoon's for grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Trey Parker
</P>
<P>
   Voices: Trey Parker, Matt Stone and Isaac Hayes
</P>
<P>
   Length: 80 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ Though it barely avoided an NC-17 _ for nonstop
profanity, adult subject matter, cartoon violence and crude humor
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
