<HEADLINE>
BOCCACCIO WAS AHEAD OF CHAUCER'S `TALES'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend eyed with curiosity an edition of Boccaccio's ``The
Decameron,'' which I had obtained at a flea market. To my surprise,
she asked, ``What is that?'' She's intelligent, well-read and in
possession of good, all-around knowledge of literature, but she
hadn't heard of Giovanni Boccaccio or ``The Decameron.''
</P>
<P>
   So I asked whether she had heard of Chaucer, not quite realizing
that I was truly adding insult to injury. Of course she'd heard of
Geoffrey Chaucer, and knew ``The Canterbury Tales'' rather well.
Whereupon I remarked that Chaucer derived his scheme for the
``Tales'' from Boccaccio's signature work.
</P>
<P>
   They are the great matching cornerstones of late medieval
literature: ``The Canterbury Tales,'' verse narratives studied by
college English majors in the original Middle English, but
requiring translation into ``modern'' English for the lay reader;
and ``The Decameron,'' composed in Latin prose and translated
almost immediately into romance languages.
</P>
<P>
   Chaucer's birth year is uncertain, but the circa date usually
given is 1340. That would have him junior to Boccaccio by 27 years,
although they are generally thought of as contemporaries because
they wrote at the same time. They never met, although each was
aware of the other's work. But Boccaccio came first.
</P>
<P>
   He began writing ``The Decameron'' in 1348, the year of the
Black Death, and the fabled plague is the springboard for his
extraordinary serving of 100 stories.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of strangers meet in a Florentine church. The Black
Death is all around them, and their inspiration is to flee Florence
to spend some time in the uninfected hills of Fiesole. The 10
people (seven women, three men) are inspired to pass time by
telling stories.
</P>
<P>
   They agree on a format that entitles each member to be queen or
king for a day, as ``ruler'' of a program wherein each of the 10
will tell a story. Ten stories for 10 days, and thus the title.
</P>
<P>
   Chaucer adopted this same narrative method. He brought together
two dozen English folk, all being pilgrims to Canterbury, on their
way there to worship at the shrine of Thomas a Becket, the
``blessed martyr.'' They take lodging at the Tabard Inn in
Southwark, and there the host _ the charismatic Harry Bailey _
organizes the storytelling among the pilgrims, offering a free
dinner to the person relating the best story.
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrims are joined at the inn by several other people,
including one Geoffrey Chaucer, described as an author. Each in the
original party tells one story, so the Chaucerian tally of
narratives approaches Boccaccio's total by only about one-fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Chaucer's tales, like Boccaccio's, offer a full range from
chivalry, romance, tragedy and farce, and both compendiums are
rooted in folklore. There are keen differences, though, in the
tale-spinning casts of characters.
</P>
<P>
   Boccaccio's people are all young and tend to hold romantic
dispositions toward life. The Chaucer pilgrims are rather older and
more hardened by life, with a few youthful exceptions. The pilgrims
to Canterbury represent a cross section of 14th-century English
life, and all are identified by their vocations. Only three of the
pilgrims are women: two nuns and the resourceful Wife of Bath.
</P>
<P>
   Chaucer's cast is more distinctive, emerging as vivid
personalities as they deliver their stories and react to the tales
told by others. Yet Boccaccio was an innovator in bringing common
people into literature, with Chaucer again following his literary
lead.
</P>
<P>
   So you, too, know Chaucer better than Boccaccio? Be advised that
the latter, a bawdy satirist at his best, ranks with Dante and
Petrarch in forming the great literary triumviate of the Italian
Renaissance. G.H. McWilliam's 1972 translation of ``The Decameron''
may be the best one. It's a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor emeritus for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
