<HEADER>
A4915 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREDERICK-FORSYTH-TEX     06-30 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREDERICK-FORSYTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JACKAL' AUTHOR CHANGES GEARS, TO `PHANTOM' FANTASY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After nearly three decades of topping bestseller lists with
thrillers such as ``The Day of the Jackal'' and ``Icon,'' Frederick
Forsyth could have been forgiven for resting on his literary
laurels and churning out more techno-whodunits.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 60-year-old Forsyth is risking his high place on
the literary ladder with the November publication by St. Martin's
Press of ``The Phantom of Manhattan,'' which its author describes
as ``fantasy, with the theme of sin and redemption, emotions I
don't normally touch on, even a tad of religion.'' The Phantom of
the title is the infamous Phantom of the Opera. Forsyth's decision
to extend that character's fictional existence with a ``what if''
yarn has already cost him a publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bantam, my publisher in the United States, passed on this
book,'' Forsyth said in a rare phone interview from his home in
England. ``My agent had made it plain to me that going outside my
usual subject area was taking a chance. Clearly, both agent and old
publisher preferred a topic that was money in the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Forsyth was ready to gamble, spurred on, he says, by
conversations with close friend Andrew Lloyd Webber, who wrote the
ultrasuccessful musical ``The Phantom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This all started one night a few years ago when Andrew and I
had dinner,'' Forsyth recalls. ``We were musing over the claret
about whatever might have happened to that Phantom guy, and with
his great love, Christine, if he turned out to have survived the
fire at the end of Andrew's musical. We kept on talking about it. I
began to get some ideas. It grew from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Always a painstaking researcher, Forsyth began an exhaustive
study of 1895-96 Manhattan, guessing that the Phantom might have
fled there from Paris to hide himself in New York City's teeming
underworld.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I felt about this character, I decided he would not
only remain there but thrive there, although as a mysterious sort
of power rather than someone very visible,'' Forsyth said. ``I
reckoned that would be the combination; that he became reclusive
but powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth didn't take long crafting ``The Phantom of Manhattan''
once he'd completed his research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had certain parameters mandated by the original `Phantom of
the Opera,' so I didn't have to invent many main characters,'' he
said. ``I suppose it took me six months to write the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth's agent placed the novel with the Thomas Dunne imprint
of St. Martin's Press, which is diligently gearing up to promote
this unexpected book from such a well-known author. Even Forsyth
isn't confident that longtime fans will snap up his new title.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent has made it plain this must be a one-off unless it
takes off like a brush fire,'' Forsyth said. ``If this book is a
turkey and I write a second in the same vein, there would be
problems placing it (with a publisher). I accept that. But 60
million people have seen Andrew's musical, and if just 10 percent
of them were sufficiently intrigued by my book to buy it, well,
that certainly would be enough. As for my longtime fans, well, I
hope they'll give it a try, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth exploded onto the literary scene in 1972 with ``The Day
of the Jackal,'' a gripping tale about a fictional assassin
stalking French leader Charles de Gaulle. Along with John Le Carre
(''The Spy Who Came in From the Cold,'') Forsyth led a new
generation of novelists who based their well-written thrillers on
real people and world tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been based in East Germany while writing for Reuters''
wire service, Forsyth said. ``I wrote `Jackal' out of instinct,
with no background in writing novels, no earlier attempts at
writing novels that had been rejected. I didn't have to make much
up, really. The book did well, and I was able to go on from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Day of the Jackal's'' success inspired other writers to
tackle the genre and other publishers to print their novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frederick Forsyth made thrillers respectable,'' bestselling
author Tom Clancy said in a recent Star-Telegram interview. ``When
he wrote `The Day of the Jackal,' he redefined the genre ... nobody
has done it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Forsyth said, confining himself to thrillers became
monotonous.
</P>
<P>
   Then came dinner with Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with ``The Phantom of Manhattan'' written and at the
printer's, Forsyth can only wait nervously and hope for the best.
St. Martin's is demonstrating corporate faith by publishing the
book in November (it will probably be in bookstores by late
October), the heart of the literary Christmas shopping cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early news has been encouraging,'' Forsyth said. ``Reaction
from buyers for the larger book chains has been positive, and
that's the first hurdle. So the books will be out there, very
visible. But people still have to buy enough of them. I expect
we'll know for certain if we've succeeded or not by December.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
