<HEADLINE>
HOW TO NAIL `HAMMER' THEME MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find a recording of ``Harlem Nocturne,'' the
theme music from the ``Mike Hammer'' TV series starring Stacy
Keach? _ J.D.C., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: If you're looking specifically for the version that was used
on ``Mike Hammer,'' it shows up in two compilations of TV songs:
``Mission Impossible: Cult TV Themes'' from Silva America and
``25th Anniversary Edition TV'' from Breakable Records.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, there are more than two dozen versions of
``Nocturne'' recorded by different artists, including Ray Anthony
on ``Best of Ray Anthony,'' Les Brown and his Orchestra on ``Great
Les Brown,'' Tito Puente on ``Revolving Bandstand'' and Kenny Blake
on ``Interior Design.''
</P>
<P>
   All those alternate versions and ``25th Anniversary Edition TV''
are in stock at CDNow, an online retailer at www.cdnow.com. You may
be able to special-order them from other music stores.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for a poem that used to be read by my pastor. All
I remember is ``A careful man I want to be/A little fellow follows
me.'' Can you help? _ L.H., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The poem, attributed to Lee Fisher, has been reprinted often
in Christian and Boy Scout publications under the title ``A Little
Fellow Follows Me.'' Here's one version:
</P>
<P>
   ``A careful man I want to be,/A little fellow follows me;/I do
not dare to go astray,/For fear he'll go the self-same way,/I
cannot once escape his eyes/Whate'er he sees me do, he tries;/Like
me he says he's going to be,/The little chap who follows me.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks that I am good and fine,/Believes in every word of
mine;/The bad in me he must not see,/The little chap who follows
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must remember as I go,/Through summer's sun and winter's
snow;/I am building for the years to be/That little chap who
follows me.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who wrote ``The Hunchback of Notre-Dame,'' and what was the
history behind the author? _ M.D.H., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The Hunchback of Notre-Dame'' is the English title of
``Notre-Dame de Paris,'' a French novel written in 1831 by Victor
Hugo.
</P>
<P>
   Hugo, who lived from 1802 to 1885, was one of France's most
successful poets and playwrights at the time ``Notre-Dame'' was
published. He wrote the book to fulfill an 1828 contract for a
historical novel, finishing it more than two years past deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victor Hugo: A Biography,'' a recent book by Graham Robb, was
published in paperback last month.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
