<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV18-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JULY 18, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My 60-year-old house has an equally old detached garage in my
back yard and there is no electricity going out to this garage.
Instead of stringing a heavy overhead extension cord out there (as
I have been doing in recent years) I want to install a permanent
underground power line that will supply electricity for the garage.
I want to tap into a weatherproof outdoor outlet on the back of the
house by hooking up an underground cable that will run out to the
garage. I've been told there is a type of electric cable that can
be buried in the ground safely without having to use conduit. Is
this true, and if so can it be connected to the existing outdoor
outlet box on the house?
</P>
<P>
   A: The cable you refer to is called UF type cable, but you
should check with your local building department to make sure the
cable is approved for use in your community. Also, be sure the
circuit you are tapping into is adequate for the load you will be
adding. For example, if you are going to run power tools or a
heater you may have to add a separate circuit. The cable can be
laid directly in the ground, but usually it has to be buried about
12 inches to 16 inches underground. In addition, it is a good idea
to lay a wood plank over the cable to protect against accidental
damage when digging in the future, although this is not required in
all communities. Where the cable is exposed as it goes from the
outlet box down into the ground it should be enclosed in a length
of rigid conduit as shown here.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have lived in our present house for about three years and
had the exterior shingles painted the first year. Within a couple
of months, and while the weather was still warm, this paint started
to peel. The painter says this is due to air pollution since
several neighbors also have a peeling problem. Could the peeling
problem have anything to do with the fact that we added insulation
in the floor of our attic after we moved in?
</P>
<P>
   A: I doubt if air pollution could be the cause. Peeling could be
due to condensation developing in the attic after the insulation
was added _ if there is not enough ventilation in the attic.
However, condensation usually occurs during or immediately after a
cold spell, so I'm inclined to think that is not your problem. I
think the problem is most likely due to the fact that the shingles
were painted instead of being stained. Wood shingles should never
be painted _ only stained or treated with a wood preservative so
that the wood can ``breathe'' properly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When our very old house was renovated about 15 years ago all
the windows were replaced, some (but not all) with Anderson
windows. There are no problems with the Anderson windows, but many
of the other windows, which are also double-paned, have developed
condensation between the inner and outer glass. Vision has been cut
down severely and it is impossible to clean the dirt out of the
inside. Short of replacing these windows, are there any suggestions
you can offer to clean the windows and solve the condensation
problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: This depends on how the windows were made originally. Some
double-pane glass units are sealed and can never be taken apart and
cleaned or re-sealed, while others can be repaired by a
professional glazier who is equipped to do repairs of this kind.
But not all pros do this work, and not all double-pane glass can be
repaired without replacing the unit entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The concrete wall in my basement is cracked and water comes
in after a heavy rain. I filled the crack with hydraulic cement
some time ago, but now this cement has started to crack out so that
water is coming in again. What is the best way to permanently solve
this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: Assuming you did the patch job properly then it's likely that
the only permanent cure is to work from the outside. Your best bet
is to call in a professional to excavate around the outside down to
the footing and clean the concrete to fill in the crack from the
outside. After applying a waterproof membrane coating to the
outside of the wall and laying drain tile (perforated plastic pipe)
and gravel on top of the footing to carry ground water away, he
will finish up by putting down another 6 inches of coarse gravel
before replacing and backfilling with soil.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``UF UNDERGROUND ELECTRICITY CABLE TO
GARAGE'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Underground electric cable connected to weatherproof
box on house wall supplies electricity to a detached garage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
