<HEADER>
A4964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-BOOK-REVIEW-     06-30 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHADOW: FIVE PRESIDENTS AND THE LEGACY OF WATERGATE': PRESIDENCY
AS BLOOPER SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Woodward's mode of operation is by now ordained. He talks to
everybody who will talk to him and decorates the results with some
local color. This time out, he begins with President Gerald R.
Ford's pardon of Richard M. Nixon (``Aug. 1, 1974, was a hot
Washington summer morning with the humidity heavy in the air, but
inside Richard Nixon's air-conditioned White House it was
unnaturally cool'') and works his way up or down through Jimmy
Carter, Ronald Reagan and George Bush, concluding with Bill
Clinton, who occupies more than half of this fat new book.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the material is familiar, and Woodward's opinions are
generally unexciting. His theme consists of presidential lapses,
starting with Ford's announcement, from which he never recovered:
``There is no Soviet domination of Europe, and there never will be
in a Ford administration.'' Woodward construes the Nixon pardon as
a seminal act of the Ford presidency, above all an act of loyalty
to Nixon. In Woodward's generous view, Ford made the correct
decision but executed it poorly.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter episodes focus on the corruption charges against Bert
Lance, the administration's budget director _ ``My faith in the
character and competence of Bert Lance has been reconfirmed'' _ and
on Hamilton Jordan, the president's chief of staff, who was mired
for months in ``a sticky personal criminal investigation.'' In
Woodward's unremarkable judgment about these unremarkable events,
the president recognized that his claim to a high moral ground
``helped me get elected, but it also came back to haunt me later
on.'' In short, Carter ``did not always tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   It took six years before the Reagan presidency was touched by a
major scandal, but it was a dandy, involving arms sales to Iran,
the diversion of profits to the Contras, CIA machinations and the
dubious activities of William J. Casey, Caspar W. Weinberger,
Robert C. McFarlane, Vice Adm. John M. Poindexter and Lt. Col.
Oliver L. North. Woodward's main source for this complicated tale
is evidently George P. Shultz, Reagan's secretary of state, who
played the part of the white hat amid a company of connivers. The
lesson is that if you expect kindly treatment at Woodward's hands,
be forthcoming in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward concludes the Reagan chapter with a question he posed
to Lawrence E. Walsh, the independent prosecutor: ``How will
Iran-Contra be remembered in history?'' Walsh answers: ``I think
it'll be remembered as a non-sordid disregard of constitutional
restraints. I think the president was wrong, he was defiant, he was
deliberate, but he wasn't dirty.'' That's about as interesting as
the conclusions come.
</P>
<P>
   Bush owed his first brush with scandal to his son Neil, fingered
as the ``poster boy'' of the Silverado Banking, Savings and Loan
Association. The president lamented, ``They're out to get my boy,
they're out to get me.''
</P>
<P>
   A little later, Bush's chief of staff, John Sununu, was caught
using government planes for personal trips, $500,000 worth over two
years. Then came the Tailhook embarrassment and the moment during a
presidential debate when the president was caught looking at his
watch. Nor could he escape repeated charges that he was ``in the
loop'' on Iran-Contra.
</P>
<P>
   None of this makes for exhilarating reading. In a relatively
fresh summing up of the Bush career, Woodward maintains that the
president built his career as the patron of other Republican
presidents: ``He had not acquired the political skills that many
politicians develop through struggle and adversity. As a new
president, he was not as well equipped as he should have been to
handle the inevitable scandals. The investigations and conflicts
were distasteful to him. The controversies almost dazed him.''
</P>
<P>
   But all these events are just appetizers for the Clinton
presidency, featuring Monica S. Lewinsky, Linda R. Tripp, Paula
Corbin Jones, Webster L. Hubbell, Robert S. Bennett, Ronald H.
Brown, James Carville, Kenneth W. Starr and other casualties of the
time, which the nation has long since wearied of hearing about.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward digs especially into the scandal-management team of the
Clinton defenders, which was riven by dispute. More than once we
are reminded, the president assured his lawyers regarding his
dealings with women: ``I'm retired.'' To Clinton's remonstrance
that ``I get the sense that you don't believe me,'' Dick Morris
replied, ``Mr. President, my job is to run the pump and the motors,
not to fix the hole in the bottom of the boat.'' Not long after
this exchange, Morris resigned when it was revealed that he had a
relationship with a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, the president's lawyer, figures substantially in
``Shadow'' as a lawyer who dares to talk to and about his client,
especially as doubts began to increase about the boss' story.
Bennett says he took comfort in the adage that ``the worst defense
lawyers are the ones that believe their clients.'' The one lawyer
who seemed to be thoroughly enjoying his role was William H.
Ginsburg; we learn that he and Ms. Lewinsky shared a 1985 Chateau
Haut-Brion at Nathan's restaurant in Georgetown, and he made all
the talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes, with Washington anecdotes, opinions and
persiflage. Woodward seems to be developing some larger point about
the shadowy side of national politics, but the connections between
the various presidents do not repay much study. When the material
is not recooked, it tends toward gossip; the result is an overlong
inside-the-Beltway collage.
</P>
<P>
   SHADOW
</P>
<P>
   Five Presidents and the Legacy of Watergate
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Woodward
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 592 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $27.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMESTAED-ART-NYT &LR;      06-30 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMESTAED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER'S AWAY, SO THE LANDSCAPERS PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere in the attic of this old Maryland farmhouse is a faded
picture of my grandparents Grace and Carroll Raver standing in the
front yard in front of four sticks just barely taller than
Granddad, and he was not a tall man.
</P>
<P>
   These sticks are Norway maples, probably dug from the woods
(because why would a farmer pay for a tree) and planted next to the
road to shade the house. They put in a privet hedge, too, kept low
to frame the changing fields of wheat and corn and soybeans across
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been around 1902, because that's when your
great-grandfather died,'' Mother said, as we sat on the front porch
sipping Scotch one evening a few weeks ago. A light wind rustled
the big leaves of the trees _ now 60 feet tall _ and a catbird
screeched from a branch in the thick canopy.
</P>
<P>
   Great-Granddad built the house around 1890 to shelter his 13
children, and some of their names are still carved up in the attic
rooms. But his wife, Caroline, died young (probably of exhaustion)
when her last child, Ralph, was only 4, so my newly married
grandparents got the farm _ and a brood of youngsters to boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace was only 16 when she eloped with Carroll,'' said Mother,
who is 86. I know the legend. How Grace climbed in the buggy with
the cake her mother had baked for the church supper and drove right
by the church, heading for Baltimore and the preacher.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at my favorite old maple, the one right next to the
porch. I used to read Nancy Drew mysteries in its wide branches,
and you could escape from the upstairs bedroom by climbing out on
the porch roof and walking right into its arms. Half those branches
are gone now, sawed off by Eugene Yelton, our faithful tree man,
who has nursed them through hurricanes and hailstorms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Yelton loves that tree,'' Mother said, and so does she,
since it shades her bedroom. ``I'll be afraid he'll tell me it's
got to come down and he'll say, `Oh, she's doing fine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The latest disaster came one afternoon in June 1998. My mother
was setting the table for lunch when she noticed that the sky
looked strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had this yellowish streak all around the horizon and very
black clouds above that,'' she said. ``I thought I better go up and
put the windows down when the hail came.''
</P>
<P>
   When the storm was over, the yard was full of fallen limbs. The
black walnut was uprooted. The English chestnut was ripped down the
trunk like a toothpick. And the maples had lost half of their
branches.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, we sat on the porch surveying the survivors.
``Those two in the middle really should go, Mom,'' I said in my
ruthless New Yorker voice. ``It's beginning to look like the Addams
family lives here.''
</P>
<P>
   I let the privet hedge grow up about five years ago to screen
out the houses that had cropped up on Elijah Blizzard's cornfields,
and to muffle the sound of the cars and trucks that roar by on
their way to the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we just plant some young trees in front of the old
ones,'' she said, ``and when they get going, we can cut down the
maples.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that sounds like a reasonable idea, but Norway maples are
notorious for sucking all the moisture and nutrients from anything
except poison ivy. And their leaves, which are as big as butter
plates, can shade a young tree right out of existence.
</P>
<P>
   I just said, ``Hmmm,'' thinking of this hedgerow I wanted to
plant. A couple of sugar maples, maybe, mixed in with lots of other
trees and shrubs, like spruce and cedars, dogwoods, magnolias,
viburnums and highbush blueberry. A wildlife habitat about 50 feet
wide, straight up to the front porch.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Maryanne Connelly, a landscape architect, had
suggested the idea years ago. On her first visit to the farm, she
hacked a sightline through the ancient mock oranges so my mother
could see out the kitchen window.
</P>
<P>
   When Mom went away for a couple weeks, I called Maryanne. What
if we got a little plan together, and an estimate, just to test the
waters? So that's what we've been up to the past few nights,
batting around ideas from Maryland to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Could we have sycamores, like the ones down by the stream? No,
they need moisture. How about a horse chestnut, like those beauties
in Central Park? Too grand. A Katsura? Too formal.
</P>
<P>
   We settle on Franklinia alatamaha, the tree the 19th-century
naturalist John Bartram found in Georgia. And magnolias, which have
a country feel. Redbud and viburnums, like the black haw by our
stream.
</P>
<P>
   And Maryanne thinks big: eight Norway spruce, a dozen red cedars
and a dozen Hamamelis virginiana, my favorite witch hazel. Plant
lovers tend to want one of everything. ``But the most dramatic
landscape comes from keeping to a few,'' Maryanne said. ``And a lot
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   So we added a dozen purple lilacs, 19 highbush blueberries, 50
viburnums, 15 red twig dogwoods. And a dogwood developed by Rutgers
University that's resistant to anthracnose but as close to the
Florida dogwood as you can get: Cornus x Rutgan.
</P>
<P>
   Close to the house are 60 Rosa rugosas, which the birds will
love for the hips, and I'll think I'm in Nantucket. (Or is this
plan starting to look like the Hamptons?)
</P>
<P>
   The cross section that came through the fax machine at the local
convenience store was beautiful. I could see what Maryanne meant by
starting low at the road and sloping up and back down to the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different types of birds live at different heights,'' Maryanne
said. ``By giving them a shrub layer, understory and a canopy,
you're giving them a place to work'' _ as in working the trees for
bugs and nest-building materials, not to mention flowers and
berries.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the fun part: pricing this dream list. I drove over to
TDH Nurseries, which was started 34 years ago by Tom, Dick and
Harry Irvin on a farm in Phoenix, Md. They grow their own trees and
shrubs, and cater to the horsy set, so their prices are comparable
to New York's: $11,410 for the plants, wholesale, multiplied by
2.5, the general cost factor for site preparation and planting. The
installed price: $28,525, give or take a couple thousand.
</P>
<P>
   And I hadn't even figured in the cost of taking down four
century-old maples. I called Yelton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in Canada hunting bear,'' said Shirley, his wife. ``He'll
be down towards the last of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, as I came up from the meadow, I found Yelton
out under the maples.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think your mother will go for this,'' he said, shaking
his head as he went from tree to tree. He gave me his rough
estimate: $1,600 to remove the two damaged trees by the walkway,
$2,000 for the others, which are still relatively strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the stumps and roots ground up?'' Yessir. ``That'll
be another $125 each.''
</P>
<P>
   So now we're up to $4,000 for removing four trees. Add another
$1,000 for bulldozing the privet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to take that old yew, too,'' he said, squinting, as
if he'd heard of heartless types like me. As he got in his pickup
and gave his maples one last nod, he repeated, ``Your mother will
never go for this.''
</P>
<P>
   I know she won't. Next time I went down to the woods, I looked
around for some young tulip poplars. And I saw a silver maple that
might do just fine in the yard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
