<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ingredients will come together for clusters of showers and
thunderstorms to develop across the upper Mississippi Valley and
advance into the Great Lakes region Thursday. An unusually fast jet
stream, marked by winds as strong as 150 mph near an altitude of
30,000 feet, will extend from the Pacific Northwest to the northern
Rockies and Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, moderate to moderately high humidity will gradually
build northward from the Gulf of Mexico. Finally, a potent
disturbance in the energetic jet stream will arrive and lift humid
air. The coming together of these ingredients will set the stage
for thunderstorms, some with heavy rain and a few with the
potential to spawn severe weather.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of potent thunderstorms will erupt near a weak warm
front near northern Oklahoma and Kansas. Some storms will reach
severe levels in areas where intense sunshine heats the ground and
destabilizes the atmosphere. Clusters of storms will migrate
eastward toward the Mississippi Valley later Thursday. Damaging
winds will pose the greatest threat.
</P>
<P>
   After a respite of lower humidity in the Northeast on Wednesday,
humidity will surge back into the region, accompanied by scattered
showers and thunderstorms. In the Southeast States, isolated heavy
thunderstorms will flare in the humid heat of the afternoon near
the Carolina and Georgia coasts. Heavy thunderstorms will also
barrage parts of northern Florida with heavy rains, particularly in
the panhandle, where the inland-moving sea breeze lifts tropical
air.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: RAINLESS IN BOSTON
</P>
<P>
   With a matter of hours remaining in June and a front weakening
over southeast Massachusetts, Boston was poised to set a rare
record late Wednesday. No measurable rain had been observed at the
airport last month, a feat matched only in March, 1915. Boston's
weather records date back to 1871. Only a trace of rain was
recorded last month (and March, 1915), but such meager rain seems
more impressive in June, a month when humidity, showers and
thunderstorms build. Humidity was generally low in June, but, when
it was high, any showers and storms that developed, bypassed
Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
