<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lightweight Alternative With Zip for the Road
</P>
<P>
   For those on the go, ``companion'' computers, bigger than a
Pop-Tart and smaller than a breadbox, might be just the right size.
Compaq's Aero 8000, released last month, boasts quite a bit under
the hood for a lightweight alternative.
</P>
<P>
   It runs on a zippy 64-bit, 128-MHz SH4 processor and also
features a smart card reader and writer built right into the unit
for those needing file security on the road. The device comes with
a voice recorder and 16 megabytes of RAM, which can be upgraded to
64 MB.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a 7-hour standard battery life and the ability for
remote users to synchronize the unit with servers running Lotus
Notes, Novell Groupwise and Microsoft Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   At 10.75 inches wide, 8.5 inches deep and 1 inch thick, the Aero
8000 is big for its class. It weighs 2.9 pounds and offers a
10-inch screen and a keyboard that, at 95 percent the size of a
regular notebook keyboard, will allow most adults with
average-sized hands to actually type on it. The basic model lists
for $949.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests a question: as these companion computers (which
usually run Windows CE) get more powerful, why not just spend a
little extra for a low-end laptop running Windows 98? The Aero
8000, a product in that awkward, in-between phase, seems like a
good compromise for those who don't mind trading power for less
strain on the shoulder and wallet.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Biersdorfer
</P>
<P>
   AOL Giving Subscribers Incentives to Stay Home
</P>
<P>
   America Online's next generation of software, AOL 5.0, will be
introduced this fall. The release will have a number of new
features intended, apparently, to tempt users to eschew the greater
Internet in favor of remaining on America Online's proprietary
site.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a wish list derived from America Online users and focus
groups, the new software will offer an online appointment calendar
and the first search feature capable of hunting for content both on
the Internet and on America Online's proprietary channels.
</P>
<P>
   Users who log on via a broadband connection will automatically
be served richer content as well. For instance, a broadband user
searching the movie listings might see a short video clip along
with the usual reviews.
</P>
<P>
   And by the end of the year, users of the new You've Got Pictures
feature will be able to drop off a roll of film at a store with an
Eastman Kodak processor (there are 40,000 nationwide) and pay an
extra $5.95 to digitize the images, scan them and send them to an
America Online account within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   How well will such ambitious features work? Beta testing on
You've Got Pictures started in three cities last month. But one
limitation is already apparent. The feature will be introduced
before a companion editing program becomes available. So
grandparents will just have to live with red eye for a while. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Slatalla
</P>
<P>
   Miniature Pinball With Buzz, And a Bunch of Apes on the Run
</P>
<P>
   Two innovative new games for Nintendo Game Boy and Sony
Playstation systems are finding new uses for idle hands. On the
smaller-scale Game Boy, Nintendo delivers Pokemon Pinball, a Game
Boy cartridge that outdoes ordinary pinball wizardry by challenging
players to collect 150 little monsters by flipping and tilting the
ball around the fast-moving but sometimes disorienting
matchbook-size color LCD screen. Because a whole pinball field
won't fit on the device's tiny screen, players see half the board
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   But the real innovation happens off-screen: Pokemon Pinball is
the first Game Boy cartridge to include a built-in force-feedback
mechanism, causing the device to vibrate. Holding it is akin to
containing a handful of bumblebees.
</P>
<P>
   A single AAA battery powers the cartridge, which is fatter and
taller than ordinary Game Boy cartridges. Other Game Boy developers
will probably follow the game's tremulous lead and slip in a little
shaking of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Sony presents a different sort of challenge with Ape Escape.
Players usually manipulate only one of the controller's dual
free-wheeling knobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ape Escape demands that players put both thumbs to use. The goal
is to travel back in time and capture a slew of mastermind monkeys
on the loose. A series of training sessions is intended to help
players put the opposition into opposable thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hutsko
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Memory-Starved Palm Owners Can Take Resourceful Steps
</P>
<P>
   Though the new wafer-thin Palm V got points for size and style
from gadget lovers, it came with only two megabytes of RAM _
considered paltry by Palm pals who like to load up with plenty of
third-party applications.
</P>
<P>
   The 3Com Corp. offers no memory upgrade options for the Palm V,
but a few enterprising folks have taken matters into their own
hands, safely stuffing an eight-megabyte chip inside the device.
</P>
<P>
   In an illustrated Web page translated from his original Japanese
(www.asahi-net.or.jp/TG7T-KSWG/newpalmve.htm), Toshio Kashiwagi, a
Palm V owner, describes gently melting the sealant on his unit with
a blow dryer so he could pry it apart and add the bigger memory
chip.
</P>
<P>
   For those Palm V owners who don't possess quite the same level
of fearlessness, a company in Sunnyvale, Calif., will do the job
for you. The Electronic Fast Integration Group (www.efig.com) will
take the Palm V that you send them and install the eight-megabyte
chip for $249.
</P>
<P>
   John Figueroa, the vice president for engineering at EFIG, said
that he announced the service on March 13 in an Internet newsgroup
and that his company had already upgraded more than 500 units for
RAM-starved Palm V owners.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't yet own a Palm V, EFIG will sell you a new one
(complete with cradle and software) with the extra memory already
installed for $649. The company also offers an optional extended
warranty for an additional $40, which might come in handy because
the EFIG upgrade voids 3Com's warranty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Biersdorfer
</P>
<P>
   Software Will Let You Mingle With the Crowd at a Web Site
</P>
<P>
   Although e-mail, chat rooms and instant messaging have turned
parts of the Internet into a conversation parlor, surfing the Web
is still a solitary activity. Or it was before Gooey, a new
communal Web-surfing program.
</P>
<P>
   Gooey, which can be downloaded free at www.getgooey.com, places
a rectangular box on your screen. When you visit a site, the box
lists other Gooey people who are at the same site at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   You can then send messages to anyone else _ or everyone else _
who is scrolling through the site with you. You can also start what
Gooey's founders call ``dynamic roving communities'' by leading
other members to sites you are visiting.
</P>
<P>
   More than 32,000 people have downloaded Gooey since it came out
in June, the company said. ``It's like there are walls between
those who are surfing the Internet,'' said Shai Adler, co-chief
executive of Hypernix Technologies, Gooey's parent company. But
with Gooey, he said, ``there's a way to communicate with all those
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooey members can also share something else: flashing ads on the
Gooey box. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Guernsey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smaller Than a Regular Mouse, But Big Enough for Travelers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most laptops give you two options for a pointing device, either
a touchpad or a trackball, and many mobile users don't like either.
Unfortunately, most tray tables aren't big enough for a mouse. And
many of the smaller laptops, in the subnotebook class, have
eliminated the serial and ports and the mouse ports to save weight.
</P>
<P>
   Targus took a look at the problem and came up with the USB
Mobile Mini Mouse. About a third the size of a regular mouse, it's
still big enough to be used by travelers with large hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked some really big guys to test it and they were happy
with it,'' said Richard Heim, director of product marketing at
Targus.
</P>
<P>
   The product, with an expected price of $29.95, will be available
after Aug. 1 through retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen C. Miller &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHO SANG THAT? The International Lyrics Server (www.lyrics.ch) a
popular source of music lyrics, is back on line after a five-month
legal hiatus. After reaching an agreement with the National Music
Publishers Association, the site no longer features full lyrics but
does allow users to enter a phrase to find a song or artist. For
example, who sang the line ``lawyers dwell on small details''? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BREAK IT TO ME BY E-MAIL First, the good news: it's easier to
give bad news by e-mail. A study of 117 Boston University
undergraduates found that people can deliver bad news with less
distortion by using e-mail than they can in person or over the
phone, according to a recent issue of Information Systems Research.
</P>
<P>
   But the article's authors did not address the issue of the
effects of receiving bad news through e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
