<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHULTZ-FURNITURE-2TA     06-30 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHULTZ-FURNITURE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD SCHULTZ: THE MAN WHO GARDENS WITH FURNITURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARTO, Pa. _ Most people look at a lettuce and see salad.
Designers look at a lettuce and see lettuce green.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you think of that color on a chair?'' Richard
Schultz, a furniture designer, asked, pointing to the bright floppy
head sticking out of the ground in a vegetable garden fenced by
tall wire tangled with wild purple roses. A chair in the garden is
apple green, last month's flavor, which the designer chose by
walking into a local paint store with an apple in his hand, picked
from the tree behind his studio.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz, 72, has spent the last 45 years getting to know his
materials. As much as the metals and plastics that inspire
innovation in furniture, they are the lettuces, leafy ferns, the
light and shadow and lichened stone walls of the 49-acre,
19th-century farm he shares with his wife, Trudy.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz is not a gardener. But he has cultivated the outdoors,
planting designs in the landscape to see if visual relationships
will grow. The two small houses, barn, gardens and pond that sit
within a circus of woods have been his laboratory for experimenting
with furnishing the outdoors handsomely, and accommodating man-made
objects thoughtfully in the most fragile, temperamental of
settings: nature.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of perfection can be tough to compete with. The
rolling property is spotted with furniture, prototypes, sculpture
and garden follies that look like sketches tossed out on the grass.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz is the author of the Leisure Collection, a sculptural
series of outdoor tables, chairs and chaise longues designed for
Knoll Associates in 1966 that is one of the most well regarded
collections of modern outdoor furniture ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   Design dealers and collectors are bringing it back into season,
as are hoteliers like Andre Balazs, whose new hotel, the Standard,
in Los Angeles features 24 chaises stretched like sunning models by
the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked high and low, and there's nothing better out
there,'' Balazs said. ``It is extremely elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz isn't in many of the design histories. But pieces of the
Leisure Collection are included in the collections of the Museum of
Modern Art, the Victoria &AMP; Albert and the Louvre. ``It's brilliant
design in a field where it's difficult to find anything more than
passable,'' said Stanley Abercrombie, the editorial director of
Interior Design magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz left Knoll in 1972, starting his own business, Richard
Schultz Design, in 1992 with his son Peter, now 40, an architect.
They produce his 1966 collection (Knoll gave them the original
machine tools); the newer Topiary line, begun in 1992, and
Confetti, a group introduced this spring. Prices range from
approximately $500 for a side chair to $2,000 for a chaise longue.
</P>
<P>
   The long-running success of Schultz's lithe sling-seat furniture
may have to do as much with the lack of serious modern
outdoor-furniture design as it does with the virtues of his first
collection, still as crisp to see and sit in as a summer-weight
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz's career as an outdoor furniture designer wasn't meant
to be that, in fact. He studied industrial design at the Institute
of Design, the Chicago school founded by the former Bauhaus
instructor Laszlo Moholy-Nagy. Schultz took his first job with
Knoll Associates in New York in 1951, where he was made apprentice
to Harry Bertoia, the Italian-born sculptor who created the iconic
wire chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Trudy Schultz moved to the Pennsylvania German
countryside in 1955 to be close to the Knoll factory in East
Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1960s, Florence Knoll, who founded the company in
1946 with her husband, Hans (who was killed in an automobile
accident in 1955), asked Schultz to design outdoor furniture for
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She tried using Bertoia's chairs outdoors, but they didn't
hold up, as manufactured then,'' Schultz said, sitting out on his
simple white screened porch last week, drinking iced tea. The
sky-blue ceiling, which might easily have been a designer's touch,
is traditional to the area. Bird song went off in the background
like weekend fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came back, fuming. `There should be some decent outdoor
furniture that doesn't fall apart,''' Schultz recalled her saying.
``It had nothing to do with esthetics; it had to do with
maintenance.''
</P>
<P>
   The designer began with his materials: noncorrosive aluminum and
something that couldn't have been more pedestrian in its elegance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women's summer shoes used to be made out of what looked like a
woven plastic,'' he said. ``A mill in Massachusetts made the stuff,
a vinyl-coated polyester yarn. We got them to make it stronger and
more durable, then weave it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he had never designed outdoor furniture before, Schultz
made the lucky mistake of bringing to it a level of sophistication
associated with contemporary indoor design. But modern designs
showed to great advantage outdoors, where they added sharp shape
and discipline to soft foliage and rough irregular textures like
stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early modern designers, Breuer and Gropius and people like
that, they knew something which one finds out,'' Schultz said.
``And that is that modern furniture looks better when it's not in a
modern interior but placed beside more primitive materials.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, Schultz has taken a different tack. He has
investigated forms of furnishing that will be assimilated into
their surroundings. The two recent lines include sheet-aluminum
chairs that are stamp-punched with a variety of cuts to let light
pass through the forms. The lattice creates an artist's
chiaroscuro, or natural dappling, that Schultz hopes will help the
furniture dissolve into its setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of this was imitation shrubbery,'' Schultz said. ``A
chair that looks like a shrub that's been trimmed to look like a
chair.'' They are a kind of garden pun.
</P>
<P>
   The designer has also created larger garden follies, including a
pyramid constructed from 2-by-4's and sheet metal stamped to look
like brick, which is routinely sold as a skirting material for the
bases of mobile homes. The pyramid sits in wooded solitude in a
patch of ferns, which appeared shortly after it was completed, as
though by alien visitation from the stars.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Schultz also developed a quick trick for training views. He
pruned one long, low hedge that borders the driveway between his
studio and the house with a draftsman's precision, to underscore
the untamed hedges and trees beyond it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of a natural vista, if you have one element
which is a little geometric, it's enough to define a great amount
of space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape has been furnished sparely, like rooms with
spectacular views that need only enough furniture to view them
from: a pair of butterfly chairs, designed by Jorge Ferrari-Hardoy,
beneath the giant sheepdog of a willow by the pond; a group of
Topiary chairs and table, like an ornamental fountain, tucked into
the crux of two stone walls.
</P>
<P>
   Indoors, the furnishing is as simple as that of the porch, which
opens the old house as expansively as if it were also outdoors. The
scarred, wide-plank wood paneling in the dining room behind the
Bertoia chair might be the trunk of a tree. Upstairs in a bedroom,
yellow polka dots sponge-painted on the walls could be lemons
ripening to drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always afraid to add on to the house, or introduce too
much into the landscape, for fear that I would ruin it,'' Schultz
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very simple, no sophistication,'' he added, but by that
it was clear that his long career and his life in the country have
brought him to appreciate those qualities as the quintessence of
design.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very pure,'' said Mrs. Schultz, who presented the visitor
with a gift of fresh lettuces from her garden for the trip back to
the city, as though they were food for thought.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz's collections are available from Richard Schultz Design,
Palm, Pa.; (215) 679-2222; or www.richardschultz.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
