<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-SAM-ART-2TAKES     06-30 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-SAM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1977, SUMMER OF PARANOIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Will also move with an ``a'' code to high speed points) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SAM ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the summer of 1977, New York lost its mind.
</P>
<P>
   A mountain climber named George Willig scaled the World Trade
Center. Terrorist bombs linked to Puerto Rican nationalists
exploded at Manhattan office buildings and department stores. The
temperature hit 104 degrees, nearly breaking the record high. A
Consolidated Edison blackout triggered looting that resulted in
more than 3,000 arrests. Elvis Presley died. Studio 54 opened. The
Bronx's most dysfunctional family, the Yankees, revived their
legendary World Series rivalry against the Dodgers. Abe Beame was
struggling to avoid being the first elected mayor in more than half
a century to be defeated for a second term. And, oh yes, a
psychopathic serial killer armed with a .44-caliber revolver and
dubbed Son of Sam held New York hostage as no crime figure had done
in the decades since a disgruntled former Con Ed worker, George
Metesky, periodically vented his rage as the folkloric Mad Bomber.
</P>
<P>
   Spike Lee's latest film, ``Summer of Sam,'' which opens Friday,
is not a documentary. But it vividly captures the depravity of a
city that had lost its bearings as well as its mind. Thousands of
movies have been made in and about New York, but relatively few
have produced such a hyperreal snapshot of the ever-changing city
at a particular point in time. Most moviegoers' short list would
probably include ``Marty,'' ``Breakfast at Tiffany's,'' ``Midnight
Cowboy,'' ``The French Connection,'' ``Annie Hall,'' ``An Unmarried
Woman,'' ``A Thousand Clowns'' and Lee's ``Do the Right Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That metaphorical summer of 1977 lasted from March to October
and fell midway through five years when New Yorkers were
desperately grasping at competing visions. One concluded that the
real good old days were the 1950s and that in the ensuing two
decades the city had passed its prime and had grown unmanageable. A
second vision defined New York as a resilient immigrant mecca
where, once the crater-size potholes were fixed, the streets would
again be paved with gold.
</P>
<P>
   Those two views of New York are encapsulated in the gritty
on-screen soliloquies that serve as bookends to ``Summer of Sam.''
As the film opens, the newspaper columnist Jimmy Breslin is
standing in today's squeaky-clean Times Square. Business is
booming, he intones. Crime isn't. Then, for the generation of
moviegoers who weren't even born when the events depicted in
``Summer of Sam'' unfold, he recalls: ``Well, it wasn't always like
this. This film is about a different time, a different place, the
good old days, the hot, blistering summer of 1977.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee authentically recreates an anarchic epoch that was,
anomalously, shaped by the last gasps of an anything-goes sexual
revolution, by bankers and bond raters who decided to punish New
Yorkers for being too profligate, and by the biggest police manhunt
in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   Son of Sam, who taunted the police and the press with bizarre
handwritten notes, was, Breslin wrote, the first murderer he knew
of who also understood how to wield a semicolon. Nonetheless, this
was largely a tabloid story, a spine-tingling tale of ordinary
people in the Bronx, Queens and Brooklyn who were gripped by fear
of a random stalker and driven to a collective nervous breakdown.
For New York's tabloids, these  &UR; were &LR;  the good old days, maybe the
last of them, the last time a self-perpetuating story routinely
sold hundreds of thousands of additional copies a day.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, Lee was a Morehouse College sophomore home in
Brooklyn with nothing to do but experiment with his new Super 8
movie camera. He produced a home movie, ``Last Hustle in
Brooklyn,'' and returned to Morehouse that fall to declare his
major as mass communications.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The good old days' _ I sound like an old geezer,'' Lee said
in an interview. ``Today, it's cleaner, the air's better, the
schools are worse, the cops are worse, there's more guns.'' Crime
is down, he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Summer of Sam,'' the killings are, fittingly, the backdrop
against which a fictional story of love, hate and alienation plays
out. Fittingly because the .44-caliber killer's rampage, too, was
splattered across a much bigger canvas. As city editor of The Daily
News then, my job was to digest the daily mayhem and blast it on to
the front page.
</P>
<P>
   A Sense of Stability, But Not for Long
</P>
<P>
   After the go-go years of Mayor John V. Lindsay's administration,
New Yorkers cherished a modicum of stability under his successor,
Beame. But that momentary stability was rudely shattered when
Beame, an immigrant and a product of the by-now dysfunctional
Democratic machine, found himself having to order the first
municipal layoffs since the Depression. After allowing the city to
borrow beyond its means for years, banks suddenly shut the spigot.
</P>
<P>
   Naysayers were ascendant.
</P>
<P>
   Hulking skeletons of half-built schools stood as grim reminders
that spending on public works had evaporated. To save on overtime,
firefighters were dispatched to blazes in dial-a-cabs to relieve
those ending their shifts. Tuition was imposed at the City
University of New York. ``Planned shrinkage'' of city amenities was
suggested so that what remained of the city might be more
manageable. And Americans shunned the place they loved to hate,
prompting the immortal Daily News headline: ``Ford to City: Drop
Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   A brief outbreak of boosterism fueled by the nation's
bicentennial celebration and the hoopla surrounding the first
Democratic National Convention held in New York in 52 years _ a
convention that would nominate Gerald Ford's successor _ produced
an artificial euphoria in 1976. But, arguably, the city never fully
recovered its self-confidence until 1980, when Edward I. Koch, who
defeated Beame in 1977, rallied New Yorkers to meet the challenge
of a transit workers strike. (It was also Koch who, confronted by
an elderly woman who urged him to ``make it like it was,''
acknowledged the limits of nostalgia: the good old days were never
as good as we remember.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was a different time. New York was a different place.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Ritchie, played by Adrien Brody, personifies
another transition: the psychosexual liberation of a pre-AIDS
generation. He is shunned by former friends in a largely
Italian-American section of the Bronx not only for daring to be
different, but for doing so in another neighborhood. In Manhattan,
yet. ``Saturday Night Fever,'' which opened that same year, ended
with John Travolta realizing that he had outgrown Bay Ridge,
Brooklyn. He headed for Manhattan, which was synonymous with hope.
In ``Summer of Sam,'' the weird worlds of Manhattan's Studio 54,
CBGB's and Plato's Retreat seem less like a brave new world to Mira
Sorvino and John Leguizamo than an alien planet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, when the blackout struck, ``Superman'' fortuitously was
being filmed at the Daily News building. The newsroom was bathed in
generator-powered klieg lights, which made it more difficult than
usual to distinguish between fantasy and reality. When the director
introduced himself, Michael J. O'Neill, the paper's editor, was
appreciative but unfazed. ``I've got a lot of actors pretending to
be journalists working for me, too,'' he said. The Daily News had
only recently been diagnosed as suffering, like Son of Sam, from a
split personality. It was seeking to retain those loyal blue-collar
readers who hadn't already fled to the suburbs while also appealing
to other New Yorkers who might have ordinarily considered the paper
too lowbrow. We were aiming to be irreverent, but respected. Not
respectable.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Rupert Murdoch landed in New York and overnight
transformed the chronically ailing New York Post from the city's
real old gray lady of journalism into a scandalous ingenue. He
challenged The Daily News to a duel to the death. Thanks to the
insatiable ego of newspaper publishers, the duel has lasted longer
than anyone would have predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Journalism On a Rampage
</P>
<P>
   Another transition was going on, too. The clatter of typewriters
(one of which I actually saw thrown during a fight in The Daily
News) was giving way to the tap of computers, which imposed a
disorienting silence. (To compensate, the keyboards were outfitted
to emit a beep when a key was struck; it was quickly disconnected
because the newsroom chirped like an overstocked aviary.)
</P>
<P>
   Screaming headlines could still shatter the silence, though.
</P>
<P>
   That summer's journalistic excesses were judged harshly by some
critics, who even suggested that the overheated tabloid and
television coverage may have incited Son of Sam, although he had
already struck several times before he was publicly identified that
March as a serial killer. But the terror was palpable, and ``Summer
of Sam'' reproduces it with chilling intensity. Responding to the
killer's presumed preferences for women with long dark hair, many
women wore their hair up or dyed it blond. Young couples shunned
discos because they thought the killer targeted disco denizens. The
police waved away cars from lovers' lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Breslin was the only journalist who received a letter from Son
of Sam, though several other columnists appealed to the killer to
surrender to them instead. (The Daily News experience with people
giving themselves up was spotty. One slow Sunday a few months
earlier a conscience-stricken fugitive showed up at the Daily News
offices to turn himself. Nobody wanted him.) The police visited The
Daily News several times to fingerprint everyone who had handled
the letter so detectives could isolate Son of Sam's prints. That
raised a disturbing question: If the police couldn't take
fingerprints from volunteers under ideal conditions, how were they
going to get the killer to cooperate?
</P>
<P>
   We tried to be as helpful as possible. We analyzed the letter
from every angle, finally, hoping to elicit any clue, even printing
a picture of the postmark. Clues were few. Sam, some sort of father
figure, according to the killer, was a 6,000-year-old man
(inspired, as it turned out, by his 64-year-old Yonkers neighbor)
who spoke to him through a dog (a black Labrador whose name in real
life was Harvey).
</P>
<P>
   The police analyzed lyrics from a 1967 Jimi Hendrix album that
might have inspired Son of Sam, and even considered comparing the
handwriting on motor-vehicle applications by white men between the
ages of 20 and 30 until detectives discovered that 250,000 people
fit that description in Queens alone. Everybody, including a local
organized crime boss whose failure to protect the neighborhood from
disorganized crime was costing him respect, had his list of
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   From Tragedy To Absurdity
</P>
<P>
   The capture of the .44-caliber killer that August prompted
understandable relief, not just because Son of Sam no longer posed
a threat, but because of who he wasn't. In the film, Spike Lee
plays a television news reporter who ventures into a black
neighborhood for the ``darker perspective.'' He interviews a woman
who, echoing the emotions of members of ethnic and racial groups,
expresses relief that the killer wasn't black. In real life, a news
radio headline blaring from the radio of a taxi the morning after
the arrest prompted the driver, presumably still shaken by the
city's fiscal crisis, to ask my wife: Why would a young man not
only transform himself into a killer, but also jeopardize a secure
civil service job in the Post Office?
</P>
<P>
   After the arrest of David Berkowitz, tragedy degenerated even
further into farce. The tabloids outbid each other for old letters
from Berkowitz to his girlfriends. (The Daily News paid $200 for
one batch of letters and published them before The Post, which had
paid $500.) One defense lawyer peddled taped interviews with his
client. And a psychiatrist who had probed Berkowitz's canine
delusions concluded, paraphrasing Freud, ``Sometimes a dog is just
a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer, like the film, didn't end that year until October. The
assorted characters who constituted the Yankees somehow got it
together and won the World Series, thanks to the sixth game heroics
of Reggie Jackson. He wore number 44.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
