<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLIMT-DISPUTE-NYT &LR;      06-30 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLIMT-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIA REFUSES TO CEDE KLIMT PAINTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five important paintings by Gustav Klimt plundered by the Nazis
and claimed by their Jewish owners' descendants under a new
Austrian law will not be returned, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Austria's restitution commission rejected most of the
arguments made by the heirs of Adele and Ferdinand Bloch-Bauer. The
commission did agree that 16 Klimt drawings and 19 porcelain
settings should be returned to the Bloch-Bauer descendants, who
live in the United States and Canada, and postponed a decision on
``Portrait of Amalie Zuckerkandl,'' another Klimt painting they
claim.
</P>
<P>
   E. Randol Schoenberg, a lawyer for four of the five Bloch-Bauer
heirs, said he was disappointed. ``Even in the beginning, we had
our doubts about the resolution in Austria to do the right thing,
but we also always had hope, based on all the nice pronouncements
made at the time the law was passed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg asked Elisabeth Gehrer, the Austrian culture
minister, to disregard the commission's ruling or ask it to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Heidimarie Glueck, her spokeswoman, said that Mrs. Gehrer could
not legally overrule the commission, but added that the heirs could
take the case to the Austrian courts.
</P>
<P>
   Told of this response, Schoenberg said, ``If the only way we can
get a fair hearing is to go to the courts, it's something we will
have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Now worth tens of millions of dollars, the paintings include
Klimt's ``Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer I,'' one of his best-known
works. The case is complicated because Mrs. Bloch-Bauer, who died
in 1925, had asked her husband in her 1923 will to give the five
paintings to the Austrian National Gallery after his death. But
Bloch-Bauer, who died in exile in 1945, left them to his family.
His descendants contend that his wife's will was only a request,
not legally enforceable, and that he would never have donated
anything to Austria after the Nazis seized his property.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the family agreed to donate the works to Austrian
museums in exchange for export licenses for some 30 other
paintings. ``It was evident that there was a bargain for the
drawings and the porcelain,'' said Rudolf Wran, the head of the
commission, but not the paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Wran said the commission had resolved two other cases, returning
a vast trove of Old Master paintings and objects to the Austrian
branch of the Rothschild family and a smaller collection of works,
including a painting by Gentile Bellini, to the Lederer family. So
far, it has two other cases to consider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
