<HEADER>
A5013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-ANNIVERSARY-     06-30 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-ANNIVERSARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 2 YEARS, `ONE COUNTRY, TWO SYSTEMS' SHOWING SIGNS OF WEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ This former British colony passed its second year
under Chinese rule Thursday, and to a growing number of critics
Hong Kong is taking on a disquieting resemblance to its motherland.
</P>
<P>
   As Hong Kong prepared for the commemoration, highlighted by the
unveiling of a Reunification Monument next to its futuristic
Convention Center, there is mounting concern that it is losing its
image as an oasis in freewheeling China, one where the rule of law
prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hong Kong was supposed to be a semiautonomous region
within China for 50 years after the handover _ under the
Chinese-British agreement known as ``one country, two systems'' _
recent events suggest that the one country is rapidly subsuming the
two systems.
</P>
<P>
   On June 26, Beijing overruled a Hong Kong court on a landmark
immigration case, using a legislative mechanism that deeply
troubled legal experts but was requested by the territory's
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   A few days earlier, the U.S. Senate had passed a bill that
stipulated that Hong Kong be treated like the rest of China in
exporting American technology with military applications. The move
was in response to a congressional report on military espionage and
China in which Hong Kong was portrayed as a staging ground for
smuggling technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Hong Kong doesn't constantly bang away at the differences
between it and China, the rest of the world is going to start
treating them the same,'' said Michael DeGolyer, director of an
academic project that surveys attitudes about Hong Kong's return to
China. ``If that happens, Hong Kong is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   That Hong Kong's autonomy should be threatened is no surprise,
said academic experts, lawyers and democracy advocates. Before the
handover, many people had predicted that no treaty between Britain
and China would be a match for the ineluctable march of Chinese
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first year after the change, worries that China would
meddle were obscured by the Asian financial crisis, which plunged
this prosperous enclave into its worst recession since World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   China largely stayed out of Hong Kong affairs, leaving the local
government to battle rising unemployment, a swooning stock market
and currency speculators. Now, though, as the economy begins to
recover, worries about Hong Kong's rule of law and autonomy are
resurgent.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal by Beijing of the Court of Final Appeal here was
its first overt interference in the Hong Kong legal system. The
Chinese government was acting at the behest of the local
authorities, who feared that the ruling would open the door to more
than one million immigrants from mainland China. But critics said
the decision could a set a precedent for Beijing to overturn any
unpopular ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule of law is the cornerstone of Hong Kong's success,'' a
democracy advocate, Emily Lau, said. ``If we don't have the rule of
law, then we're just another Chinese city.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Hong Kong Bar Association, Ronny Tong, said:
``I'm an optimist, and I would like to think this is a one-off
situation. But the government keeps giving out mixed signals.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Justice Secretary Elsie Leung has refused to rule out
asking Beijing to intervene in future court rulings.
</P>
<P>
   But the No. 2 official, Anson Chan, said Wednesday that
Beijing's action ``was an exceptional decision made in exceptional
circumstances.'' Mrs. Chan, who had just returned from a trip to
the United States and Canada, said officials there had expressed
doubts about Hong Kong. Among the skeptics was Rep. Christopher
Cox, R-Calif., who led the committee that investigated accusations
that China had acquired military secrets from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with Mrs. Chan, Cox said he was concerned that
China could divert technology from Hong Kong by smuggling it across
the border on trucks that belonged to the Chinese army, which has
maintained a garrison in Hong Kong since the change in government.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Chan said Cox had accepted her invitation to visit Hong
Kong to inspect its customs procedures. But she conceded that he
was not alone in harboring doubts about the separation between Hong
Kong and China.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong has not been helped by a recent Chinese government
decision to bar U.S. military planes from landing here. That
extends a ban imposed on American warships. Experts said China was
sending a chilly message in the aftermath of the bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Although China is entitled to take such action, analysts said it
simply reinforces the perception that Hong Kong _ two years later _
is in danger of becoming an afterthought rather than an exception.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
