<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-READ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TASTY READ FOR SUMMER CONSUMPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sweet Potato Queens' Book of Love
</P>
<P>
   by Jill Conner Browne
</P>
<P>
   (Three Rivers Press, $12, paperback)
</P>
<P>
   Ask a middle-aged Southern woman her preference in home decor
and she'll have one major request: The living room should be large
enough to house a throne.
</P>
<P>
   Southern women are raised for thronedom. There are twirling
classes, the Merle Norman lessons, the cheerleader clinics. All
training is aligned toward puberty, when the sweet young things
will blossom into precious womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   Thing is, we don't all peak at the same time. Many of us reach
tiara status long after we'll ever see a size 6 again. And forget
makeup and rooting for the home team. We don't need no stinkin'
batons.
</P>
<P>
   And so goes the premise for ``The Sweet Potato Queens' Book of
Love.'' These women of a certain age know the world and are ready
to impart their knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   This Jackson, Miss., court of self-anointed queens (all named,
appropriately enough, Tammy) sallies forth in tiny sequined shifts,
opera-length white gloves and most important, majorette boots with
tassels.
</P>
<P>
   The Sweet Potato Queens know all that's important in life and
love. They know to avoid men who have been plastically enhanced. Or
toupee-topped. Or who still live with their mamas.
</P>
<P>
   The Queens know that every woman needs five men in her life at
all times to reach nirvana. That would be a man who can fix things,
a man to dance with, a man who can pay for things, a man to talk to
and a man to sleep with. Those men amassed, the Queens can go on to
take care of daily business.
</P>
<P>
   That business would be consuming the four major food groups:
sweets, salt, fried and au gratin. It also means renting a
rock-star bus and having a lingerie-trying-on party in it on the
way to Graceland.
</P>
<P>
   The subtitle of ``The Sweet Potato Queens' Book of Love'' is ``A
Fallen Southern Belle's Look at Love, Life, Men, Marriage and Being
Prepared.'' Fallen is incorrect. These Southern belles have risen
again and have rightfully taken their thrones.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is foods editor for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/.MDNM/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
