<HEADER>
A5003 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERMAN-POPMUSIC-TEX     06-30 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERMAN-POPMUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOSE IS LOOSE; LOOK OUT, BIG APPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After more than a decade as a well-regarded North Texas musician
(first with Tarrant County-based pop poppins, more recently with
his project TOOMuchTV) and with a growing reputation as a painter,
Broose is decamping for New York, fed up with what he says is a
lack of support for the arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've drained the well dry here,'' says Broose, 33, whose last
name is Dickinson. Born in San Francisco, he grew up from the age
of 9 in Arlington, Texas. ``I've done as much as I can. I want to
be somewhere that there's more inspiration; you can only go to the
DMA (Dallas Museum of Art) so many times. A lot of people around
here say they're supportive of the arts, and they're really not.
And neither are any of the local publications.''
</P>
<P>
   What he's leaving behind as a musician is a number of fine CDs
with pop poppins, several solo CDs and cassette releases, and the
smart pop-with-lounge-touches of TOOMuchTV's 1997 ``TOOMuch Is Not
Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   What he's leaving behind as an artist is even more interesting.
He works in oils and acrylics, favoring icy blues, deep greens and
blues, and mixing the easily identifiable with curving, rounded,
almost liquid shapes and shadows.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is slightly unsettling, dark and vivid. ``Weathered
Downtown,'' a portrait of a melting Dallas skyline, is instantly
reminiscent of Van Gogh's ``Starry Night;'' other works, such as
``The Emotion Booth'' and ``The Subterranean Stream,'' have an
inky, rich tone.
</P>
<P>
   Several paintings are meant to be viewed while listening to
songs on nearby CD players; the music is gentle acoustic guitar.
Broose says he doesn't know what the connection between his music
and his artwork is, except that he wants both to be
``atmospheric.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the weird things about music and art is I have zero
education in music _ all my education went to art,'' says Broose,
who sold the rights to his 1994 solo CD, ``As an Individualist,''
to Dallas Carpe Diem Records for $3,000, which allowed him to study
at the San Francisco Art Institute for several months. ``I know
what I'm doing technically with my art. I play pop music because
it's what I was raised on _ it's simple enough for me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Broose says he plans to do both in New York. He'll try to get
gallery representation and record a second TOOMuchTV CD. Exactly
how he's going to pay the rent and eat, though, is still up in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not expecting to get any attention in New York,'' he says.
``A lot of what I do is based on impulse; I don't worry about it. I
should be able to set up some acoustic shows. Whether or not I
enjoy it, it'll be a positive experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to draw people on the street for $10 or wait tables,
that's fine. I'm going to try to survive up there as long as I can
_ if not, I'll come back. All I know is it can't get any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
