<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVE-COMBO-TEX     06-30 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVE-COMBO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVE COMBO TRAVELS OFF THE BEATEN PATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you've hitched up the Winnebago and taken a few cross-country
trips.
</P>
<P>
   Do it on a regular basis for the next 20 years and you'll know
what it's like to be Brave Combo, the ``nuclear polka'' kings from
Denton, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time Grammy nominees, who celebrated their 20th
anniversary last month, have crisscrossed America with their brand
of world music featuring polkas and mambos. They've been to Europe
and Japan, but most of their travels have been on the interstates
and back roads of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people go for the Eiffel Towers of the world,'' said Carl
Finch, the band's founder. ``We try for the more obscure.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not fit the myth of life on the road with a rock 'n' roll
band, but Brave Combo usually takes the road less traveled.
</P>
<P>
   They've developed a philosophy of travel and have found plenty
of undiscovered gems. In Bakersfield, Calif., they found Merle
Haggard's daughter holding court in a karaoke bar. They found Louis
Prima's former sax man, Sam Butera, performing in the Tropicana
Hotel lounge in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   As for hotels, let others have the Waldorf; Brave Combo prefers
the Great Plains Motor Inn in Lincoln, Neb. It's the kind of place
that uses water glasses, not plastic cups, and the rooms are
comfortable whether it's a bitter winter or a scorching summer.
</P>
<P>
   The six-piece band eschews the traditional tour bus for a
nondescript, custom-built GMC truck dubbed ``The Donut.'' The name
is derived from the preferred breakfast food of police and state
troopers around the country. The band hopes that law-enforcement
authorities will be more forgiving if Brave Combo is pulled over
for speeding or other driving violations.
</P>
<P>
   A typical five-day round trip is like the one took last March,
to Minneapolis and back. Along the way, there were stops in Chicago
and St. Louis, ending with an all-night ride through an ice storm
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly flying first-class, but band members have seen
and played at some great national landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   They shared a stage in Central Park with hip country band
BR5-49, played under the Brooklyn Bridge, and had the Pacific Ocean
at their backs while performing on the Santa Monica Pier.
</P>
<P>
   They've seen the Grand Canyon many times and were awed by Utah's
Monument Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, they're still wowed by the Marfa lights in far West
Texas, and they love to take U.S. 281 through the Hill Country to
Austin or San Antonio. They're fascinated with the giant monument
to Texas hero Sam Houston that stands along Interstate 45 outside
Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Some of their favorite offbeat sights include Rock City, a
series of lava formations near Minneapolis, Kan., and Bedrock USA,
a Flintstones-themed amusement park in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cornfields, wrecks, mom-and-pop motels and Red Roof
Inns,'' bassist Bubba Hernandez said. ``And it's cool things like
hiking up Mount Rainier after a gig in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the sights, there is the fun of simply getting there.
</P>
<P>
   Percussionist Joe Cripps remembered a recent episode at an
Arkansas truck stop, where the Donut broke down and the band was
stranded. They encountered people who were eccentric, to say the
least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two old guys (farmers) were getting diesel fuel and putting it
in milk jugs,'' Cripps said. ``They got in a spat with the lady
running the cash register and were yelling. But one of them looked
over at us and said `What's wrong with y'all?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The irate but helpful farmer looked under the hood, found that
the starter cable was disconnected, fixed it temporarily and told
the band members how to make a permanent repair when they had more
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could probably write a book on road stories,'' trumpet
player Danny O'Brien said. ``It's been like one surreal, strange
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   For Finch, the memories begin in May 1979, driving to shows in a
Honda Civic with a trailer hitched to it. Compare that with last
summer's exotic but frantic trip to Europe, where they played one
concert in Sweden and had to catch an all-night train to Finland 30
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a concert in the late 1980s in Switzerland, when
Hernandez couldn't decide whether the boisterous crowd was cheering
for Brave Combo or preparing to riot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played one encore, stopped, then another encore and
stopped,'' Hernandez said. ``By the fourth encore I was pretty
scared. People were stomping their feet. I was beginning to freak,
looking for a way out. After the sixth encore we stopped, and they
were fine. They were shaking all of our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0259 </DOCNO>
