<HEADLINE>
LEARNING LIFE'S LESSONS IN A GARDEN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (For release Thursday July 8)  
(rk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did it start with the tale of Jack and his beanstalk?
</P>
<P>
   This glorious idea that we can be saved by a scattering of seeds
and growing green vines that stretch toward the heavens?
</P>
<P>
   Gardening books line the shelves of bookstores, waiting to be
plucked by baby boomers whose back yards have become their private
sanctuaries _ a retreat from corporate pressures, cell phones and
clamoring kids.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban neighbors garden, creating a new tableau for each
season ... impatiens in the summer, azaleas in the spring, mums in
the fall, even a fountain pond with water lilies and giant goldfish
that survive the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Carmona gardens, too, coaxing vegetables and succulents
from the soil of his small yard in southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Even more importantly, as director of garden programs at the
Community Environmental Council in Santa Barbara, Carmona nurtures
the hidden, tender soul of teen-agers who have become brittle and
hard.
</P>
<P>
   There is much talk lately of saving our kids.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, says Carmona, we overlook the obvious: giving them
perspective, a sense of worth, appreciation for the preciousness
and fragility of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what's going on,'' says Carmona. ``They're missing
simple things. All kids see are action packed, shoot-em-up
adventures where everything magically comes together and is OK
again. We're just products of our environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Reverence and gentleness emerges in the midst of green, growing
things, Carmona says. Gardens are cool, tranquil spots where
breathing slows.
</P>
<P>
   ``When given the opportunity to garden, they do,'' he says.
``It's not about lecturing to them. They sit down in this garden
and all of a sudden, they start talking about their feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   And the young gardeners become a part of something larger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about participation,'' says Carmona of his community
gardening projects. ``They understand that they have a role and a
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Other lessons to be learned:
</P>
<P>
   Seeds poke tendrils through the dirt, budding ever so slowly.
Watch with patience.
</P>
<P>
   Castoffs often turn into beautiful, thriving plants. Use for
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting flowers keeps a plant blooming. Never give up.
</P>
<P>
   Roots must go deep for times when water is scarce. Find inner
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the human touch that really counts. Life is limited, a
set amount of time. What are your priorities? What do you want to
do with that time?'' Carmona asks. ``Develop a plan around those
priorities so your life has meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
