<HEADLINE>
HORMEL'S GAY PARTNER SEES SILVER LINING IN CONFIRMATION BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Timothy Wu, the gay partner of James C. Hormel,
said Wednesday that Hormel's successful 18-month fight to become
the new U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg was a victory for human
rights and for minorities across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said the nation's consciousness was raised by the fight over
Hormel's nomination when a handful of Senate conservatives blocked
the nomination because he is gay .
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that the process was generating very important dialogue
of how do we Americans define equality and what matters most when
you're applying for a job,'' he said. ``I think it has brought the
whole national dialogue on basic human rights forward, that
includes womens' rights, the rights of minorities and ethnic
minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle for Hormel's nomination, fought on a national stage,
inspired an outpouring of public support, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, 66, a San Francisco businessman and philanthropist, heir
to the Hormel meatpacking fortune and former dean of the University
of Chicago Law School, was nominated by President Clinton for the
post in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton bypassed the Senate logjam created by Hormel's
conservative opponents when he gave Hormel a recess appointment
while Congress was not in session. The appointment enables Hormel
to serve as ambassador until the end of this Congress in January
2001, which is also when the Clinton administration leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright administered the oath of
office to Hormel on Tuesday and he plans to leave for Luxembourg
within a month.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said he and Hormel received hundreds of supportive letters,
e-mails and phone calls from people across the country. Wu said it
was ``affirming'' that there was ``such overwhelming support that
people should be judged for a job based on their qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire experience demonstrated that ``your average person
believes in basic human rights for everybody,'' Wu said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said negative comments about homosexuals during the debate
over Hormel's confirmation ``would have been more upsetting or
hurtful or angering if they had resonated with mainstream America.
But they so clearly didn't. Comments like that were made, but fell
on very deaf ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative groups accused Hormel of advocating pedophilia and
incest because he donated $500,000 for what became a wing in San
Francisco's public library that contains books on homosexuality.
Hormel's supporters say he didn't select the contents of the
library and that virtually all the materials can be found in the
Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said he and Hormel gave each other mutual support on bad days
when the burden of becoming the nation's first openly gay
ambassador seemed especially heavy.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the days that Jim got really down, I would cheer him up and
tell him it's never easy being the first,'' Wu said. ``The first is
always scrutinized more closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel and Luxembourg's current ambassador to the United States,
Arlette Conzemius, have something in common: They are both firsts.
Conzemius is the first woman ambassador in Luxembourg's history.
</P>
<P>
   Wu, 36, the son of Merrill Lynch stockbroker, was born in New
York City, raised in Singapore and Hong Kong and studied political
science as an undergraduate at Princeton University before getting
a Harvard law degree in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation from Princeton, Wu became the youngest person
and the first Asian-American elected to Princeton's Board of
Trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said he worked as a producer for CBS News in New York before
becoming a fundraiser for nonprofit organizations in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   After Hormel goes to Luxembourg in the next month, Wu will
relocate to Washington where he will become a White House fellow
for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Wu is one of 16 fellows who will help draft and review
legislation, respond to Congressional inquiries, write speeches and
conduct policy briefings.
</P>
<P>
   Calm and softspoken, Wu said he and Hormel have been partners
for almost four years after they met through their common interest
in philanthropy and nonprofit organizations. Wu is a member of the
board of directors of several organizations concerned with human
rights and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hormel accepted Clinton's 1997 nomination to be
ambassador to Luxembourg, Wu said he and Hormel discussed it at
length, knowing they would both face bitter criticism from
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we thought all along it would have been a cake walk, this
would have been more difficult,'' he said. ``But we went into this
with our eyes open... What we went through was nothing like the
civil rights struggles of the 1960s.''
</P>
<P>
   Wu said he and Hormel never lost confidence that, ultimately,
Hormel would get the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through all of this, Jim never gave up on the integrity of the
process,'' Wu said. ``This was the will of the public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
