<HEADLINE>
DAY OF THE LONG GOODBYE AT WIMBLEDON AS BECKER, COURIER DEPART 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ It was the day of the long goodbye at
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Becker's swan song at the tournament that made him a
power-tennis icon ended on a dispirited note with a straight-set
loss to Australia's Patrick Rafter in the Round of 16. Jim
Courier's weather-beaten three-day event against Britain's
sixth-seeded Tim Henman concluded in the local hero's favor with
the American distraught over a botched line call in the
next-to-last game of their 4-hour-30-minute struggle. And
10th-seeded Goran Ivanisevic, a three-time finalist who described
himself as suicidal upon losing last year's final to Pete Sampras,
intimated after Wednesday's anemic fourth-round exit to
eighth-seeded Todd Martin that he might not want to expose himself
to this kind of pain again next year.
</P>
<P>
   But the day's most painful bow was taken by Germany's
ginger-haired Becker. First, his serve said goodbye to him, and
then, traumatized by 13 double faults and eight lost service games,
he bid farewell to Wimbledon, and his beloved Center Court, 6-3,
6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does have a presence out there, but his game wasn't really
firing today, and I felt like I couldn't hit the ball much
better,'' Rafter said.
</P>
<P>
   The nonsentimental Rafter admitted he didn't ``really care''
that he'd spoiled Becker's last hurrah: ``I don't feel bad for
beating him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the quarterfinals, Rafter faces Martin, who downed
Ivanisevic, 7-6, (7-3), 6-3, 6-4; and Henman meets the unseeded
Cedric Pioline, who ousted 13th-seeded Karol Kucera, 6-4, 5-7, 7-6
(7-5), 4-6, 6-3. Henman is now the sole Briton left in the hunt
following Greg Rusedski's 2-6, 7-6 (7-4), 6-3, 6-1 collapse
Wednesday against seventh-seeded Mark Philippoussis, Sampras'
quarterfinal opponent. Sampras delivered 20 aces in his 6-3, 6-4,
6-2 rout of Canada's Daniel Nestor.
</P>
<P>
   Becker had handled Rafter in two previous encounters, but both
of those victories occurred before the Australian distinguished
himself as a Grand Slam artist to be reckoned with _ not to mention
a latter-day Becker of sorts with his acrobatic serve-and-volley
technique _ by winning back-to-back U.S. Opens in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Becker was victimized by a slew of vicious passing
shots and managed just eight aces himself. In fact, he seemed to be
at odds with the very weapon that earned him the sobriquet ``Boom
Boom'' on these lawns and made him a three-time champion (1985,
1986 and 1989) and four times a runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no timing on my serve at all, almost throughout the
whole match,'' Becker said. ``Every time I served it was a
struggle, and for my part, it was very unfortunate that I wasn't
able to give him and the crowd a better match for my last match.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his Wimbledon match record stands at 71-12 and his 116-25
record on grass remains the best of any active player, including
the five-time Wimbledon champion Sampras. And a proprietary Becker
has called Center Court his birthplace ever since he stormed
unseeded to the 1985 championship at 17.
</P>
<P>
   After saving one match point with a service winner but
surrendering the second with a misguided backhand half-volley,
Becker made his last bow in the direction of the Royal Box. Its
occupants marked the 31-year-old's official retirement from the
Grand Slam stage by joining the commoners in giving him a standing
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an incredible ride,'' Becker said. ``I'm thankful I
was able to have the chance to come back and play decent tennis and
now its time to go do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker had originally retired from Slam strife at Wimbledon in
1997, when he fell to Sampras in the quarterfinals and told the
stunned winner he was quitting during their netside handshake.
Becker decided to play one last Wimbledon when he realized that,
with a second child on the way in August, he would be quitting the
tour altogether this summer to concentrate on his family.
</P>
<P>
   The 61st-ranked Courier, now 28, briefly quit tennis last
summer, but he was lured back by the prospect of playing Davis Cup,
and his decision proved to be felicitous when he upset both Henman
and Rusedski in the first round at Birmingham in April, a coup that
enabled the United States to host Australia in the second round at
Longwood Cricket Club next month.
</P>
<P>
   But Courier's inspiring campaign here at Wimbledon, where he
reached the Round of 16 for the first time since his run to the
final in 1993, ended with Wednesday's 4-6, 7-5, 7-5, 6-7 (5-7), 9-7
defeat to Henman. The match had been halted by rain Monday evening
with Henman ahead by 4-3 in the third set and was further delayed
by Tuesday's washout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, he's probably as strong as they get,'' Henman said,
``and for me to beat him 9-7 in the fifth is very satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Courier Wednesday, Henman showed his mettle by erasing
three match points at 5-6 of the fifth set with a spurt of
brilliant serving. An ace down the middle saved the third match
point, and a perfect copy of that ace earned Henman the game for
6-6. Then, Courier came unglued in the 15th game of the set when
Henman's apparently wide backhand approach volley was ruled in,
creating a break point that Henman converted for 8-7. During the
changeover, Courier flung a cupful of ice backwards over his
shoulder and also received a warning for foul language, but his
tantrum, and the match, ended quickly when Henman held at love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like calls affecting the outcome of matches, but they
do, and it's a fact of professional tennis, and I should have
finished the match before and then I wouldn't have had to worry
about it,'' said Courier, who felt the Monday postponement helped
him ``in that it cooled Tim off, because he was playing ... it was
like an alien abduction out there, someone invaded his body and
turned him into the greatest volleyer in the universe. And today he
came back on earth a little bit, which was nice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
