<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON PLANS CAMPAIGN SWING TO TARGET GOP STRONGHOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton will devote the
maiden campaign swing of her Senate race to targeting traditional
Republican strongholds across upstate New York, campaign aides said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to visit five communities in four days after
notifying the Federal Election Commission next Tuesday that she is
creating an exploratory committee to raise funds for her Senate
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for Clinton's campaign to succeed
retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., said the first lady
deliberately chose central New York and the Albany area to begin
her summer-long ``listening tour'' with small groups of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a great place to start,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a kickoff campaign statement, said: ``I'm eagerly
looking forward to listening to New Yorkers and hearing directly
what's on their minds about the issues affecting their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Present plans call for Clinton to officially announce her
candidacy later this year. Her ``listening tour'' for the remainder
of the summer constitutes the second-phase of a year-long
exploratory effort that has already taken the first lady to New
York state 12 times since January, including a house-hunting trip
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The predominantly rural upstate area being visited by Clinton
hosts traditional GOP strongholds represented in Congress by
nine-term Rep. Sherwood L. Boehlert, R-N.Y., as well as Democratic
bastions such as Albany, N.Y., represented by six-term Rep. Michael
R. McNulty, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   This region is critical for any statewide candidate because it's
a swing region.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton launches the next phase of her Senate campaign amid
mounting GOP criticism of her use of Air Force jets on campaign
trips to New York.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Chairman Jim Nicholson announced that he will visit four
upstate cities on Thursday _ Elmira, Albany, Rochester and Buffalo
_ to challenge Clinton's unreimbursed use of Air Force executive
jets for her travels thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxpayers should not foot the bill for her campaign forays to
New York,'' Nicholson said in a statement, adding that the
Republicans' tour ``will send a clear message _ `Pay your bills,
Mrs. Clinton, and quit making the taxpayers pick up the tab.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson defended Clinton's use of Air Force planes, saying her
trips are ``wholly appropriate and completely consistent with her
activities as first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   FEC guidelines require a Senate or House candidate who uses a
government plane to reimburse the treasury for the hypothetical
commercial airfare for the itinerary _ not the actual cost of
operating the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Using that formula, Clinton will begin reimbursing the treasury
the required share of her future campaign travel once she has
established her exploratory committee, aides say.
</P>
<P>
   By launching her so-called ``listening tour'' at Moynihan's farm
at Pindars Corners, a crossroads where Moynihan has an office in a
19th century schoolhouse office, Clinton will be able to saturate
upstate media markets. Her four-day swing will take her by
motorcade and small plane to Oneonta, Cooperstown, Utica, Syracuse,
and Albany before returning to the nation's capital on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Luntz, a GOP pollster who has served as a strategist for
Republican New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, says upstate New York
will be the most important battleground for the 2000 Senate race in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstate is the key to the race,'' says Luntz, who is urging
Giuliani to seek the Senate seat, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Republicans are underestimating her,'' Luntz
says. ``Republicans who assume she's going to crumble, if and when
she officially announces, are foolish. She will be much stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Luntz says a crucial swing constituency in a Clinton-Giuliani
contest would be the ``3 M Bratwurst Moms'' _ middle-aged, middle
income, white ethnic moms who live in the upstate region. Such
voters have voted Republican in the past, but have defected to
Democrats in the last two elections.
</P>
<P>
   These voters ``should be a Hillary Clinton voter, but at this
point it is the one group of women who aren't necessarily behind
her,'' says Luntz, who helped then-Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.,
mastermind the 1994 congressional campaign manifesto ``Contract
with America'' that helped Republicans take control of the House
and Senate for the first time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the first first lady in history to seek elected office
while in the White House, trails Giuliani statewide, 50 percent to
40 percent, according to the latest public opinion survey, a Zogby
International poll completed Monday. Giuliani showed strength in
the suburbs where he reaps 63 percent of the hypothetical vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won 55 percent of likely voters in New York City
compared to Giuliani's 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may get a boost from a possible GOP primary battle that
could pit Giuliani against four-term Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., in a
Republican primary in September 2000 _ barely two months before the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton beats Lazio, 47 percent to 31 percent in a hypothetical
race posed in a Luntz survey completed on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also can count on considerable Democratic financial
support for a race that could cost $20 million. Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., a Clinton ally, announced Wednesday that the
national Democratic Senate Campaign Committee that he heads this
year has already raised $12 million _ almost a 50 percent boost
over what had been raised at a comparable period in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming Clinton, Torricelli said that Democrats'
recruitment of ``top tier candidates'' is playing a part in
achieving record fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said he hopes to raise $60 million to help Democrats
win Senate races in 2000. Republicans now control the Senate,
55-45.
</P>
<P>
   Antipathy to Clinton runs high across New York, according to
Luntz' survey, with 44 percent of Giuliani's support coming from
anti-Clinton voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You already have the most polarized electorate in the country
for a Senate race,'' Luntz said. ``Hillary is the deciding factor.
Voters are determining who they are voting for by what they think
of Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's challenge is to ``let the people of upstate New York
who could care less about New York City _ let them know what he has
done down in new York and tell them he could also do that in
Washington,'' Luntz said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
