<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER QUESTIONS INS ON RELEASE OF SUSPECTED KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of a House panel demanded Wednesday
that Attorney General Janet Reno explain why Immigration and
Naturalization Service officials had released suspected serial
killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, who remains a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a waste of lives that could have been prevented,'' said
Rep. Lamar Smith, head of the House Judiciary's immigration
subcommittee. ``It's time for the Department of Justice to explain
how that could happen and what they are going to do to prevent it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, INS officials acknowledged that Resendez-Ramirez was
deported to Mexico on June 2 after earlier being captured by Border
Patrol agents for illegally crossing into the United States near
Santa Teresa, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has said it was unaware that Resendez-Ramirez, 39, was
wanted for questioning in three killings in Texas and one in
Kentucky when he was detained on June 1. He is suspected in at
least two slayings in Texas and two in Illinois after he was
deported.
</P>
<P>
   INS Commissioner Doris Meissner said the Justice Department's
inspector general would investigate the release. INS is a part of
the Justice Department and it oversees the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Resendez-Ramirez case has raised serious questions about
INS' knowledge of the case and procedures used in encounters with
Resendez-Ramirez,'' Meissner said in a statement. ``These issues
include why Resendez-Ramirez had multiple entries in the (INS
computer) system and was not detained and whether INS knew about
Resendez-Ramirez's criminal activities after being contacted by
local law enforcement earlier this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said the agency also would conduct an internal audit to
review ``the effectiveness of our current systems in an effort to
avoid any similar situation in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, R-Texas, said Resendez-Ramirez's release could have been
prevented if the INS computer identification system were connected
to the FBI's National Crime Information Center's database, which
allows law enforcement authorities to determine whether a person
has a criminal history or is wanted for a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The INS system _ called IDENT _ contains information such as
fingerprints and photographs of illegal immigrants who are detained
by INS officials. The system was developed in 1994 to track illegal
border crossers and became widely used between 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While the system is primarily a database about how many times a
person has illegally crossed the border, it does contain some
criminal background information, according to Meissner.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol agents also have access to the FBI's crime
database through a separate system but do not routinely run a check
on all of the 1.5 million illegal immigrants who are detained along
the U.S.-Mexico border each year.
</P>
<P>
   When people are detained by INS for illegally crossing the
border, their fingerprints are entered into the system for
identification. Before the system was installed, those caught
crossing the border illegally routinely used aliases.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez was detained by Border Patrol agents in Texas
and New Mexico nine times between January 1998 and June 1999,
according to records obtained by Smith's office. Smith said a
person must illegally cross the border about 10 times before his or
her case is referred for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is a suspect in the deaths of:
</P>
<P>
   _ Christopher Maier, 21, in Lexington, Ky., on Aug. 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr. Claudia Benton, 39, of Houston, on Dec. 17, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife Karen, 47, in Weimar,
Texas, on April 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ Josephine Konvicka, 73, of Fayette County, Texas, on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   _ Noemi Dominguez, 26, of Houston, on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   _ George Morber, 80, and his daughter, Carolyn Frederick, 52, in
Gorham, Ill., on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe Resendez-Ramirez travels by freight train
because the deaths all occurred near train tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year officers investigating Benton's killing found
fingerprints on his car and sent them to the Texas Department of
Public Safety, which later matched the prints of Resendez-Ramirez.
The FBI issued a warrant for his arrest on May 27.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by
e-mail at jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
