<HEADLINE>
AD AGENCY CONSOLIDATION CONTINUES WITH HOLLAND-INGALLS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Continuing a wave of industry consolidation, the fifth
largest ad agency in Massachusetts, Holland Mark Martin Edmund of
Boston, said Wednesday it has agreed to buy the fourth largest
agency, Ingalls of Boston, for an undisclosed amount.
</P>
<P>
   When the deal is completed, New England's four largest ad
agencies will have been sold within the last two years, said Skip
Pile of Pile and Co., a Boston consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of Bill Davis, a new agency that will be
known as Holland Mark Edmund Ingalls projects combined annual
billings of $180 million and revenues of $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether there will be layoffs, Davis said: ``It's
premature to get into that because we're just beginning the due
diligence process. We may have to eliminate positions because of
overlap. But the long-term goal is to build a bigger agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two agencies employ about 180 people.
</P>
<P>
   The new agency's combined list of clients includes Citizens
Financial Group, The Boston Globe, T.J. Maxx, and USTrust.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last two years, New England's three largest ad
agencies _ Arnold Communications, Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos,
and Mullen _ have been bought by huge communications giants looking
to offer global clients a wide range of services from Web site
marketing to traditional advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the chief owners of the region's three biggest shops
were nearing retirement age, and selling their agencies was a way
for them to cash out their investments.
</P>
<P>
   Such considerations were not a part of the Ingalls deal.
</P>
<P>
   In a rapidly changing environment, large ad agencies and tiny
boutique agencies can thrive, but the middle ground is fast
becoming inhospitable terrain _ especially for independent agencies
without access to additional resources.
</P>
<P>
   Such agencies are too big for small clients and too small for
big clients that have bulked up on acquisitions of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The middle is no place to be,'' said Adweek New England editor
Judy Warner, who reported a few weeks ago that Ingalls was shopping
itself around.
</P>
<P>
   The booming economy has meant explosive growth for big agencies
such as Arnold and Hill Holliday, but ``both Ingalls and Holland
Mark have been struggling a bit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Times have indeed been challenging for Ingalls. Raytheon Co. has
taken most of its ad business elsewhere. Two top officials left.
Looking for a boost, Ingalls recently restructured.
</P>
<P>
   Given Ingalls' troubles, speculation on the deal's price tag was
all over the map, ranging from $3 million to $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   By combining forces, Holland Mark and Ingalls hope to offer
clients the best of both worlds _ the size and resources of a large
agency along with the nimbleness and the higher level of client
service that are the advantages of a small agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked ourselves, `In what ways can we continue to build our
clients' brands and do it smarter and better?' We needed more
resources to do that,'' said Davis, 41, before referring to the
proposed Ingalls deal. ``This positions us for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a one plus one equals three situation,'' said Ingalls
chairman Bink Garrison, 51.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison will hold the title of chairman at the new agency and
report to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the dream job _ to work with clients, to work on new
business, and to work in the community,'' Garrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to be determined is where the new agency will be housed.
Ingalls is based in South Boston; Holland Mark occupies a Back Bay
building owned by an investment group that includes Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Each agency has different strengths. Holland Mark evolved into
an ad agency from a background of direct marketing. (Its sister
company, database marketer TPC of Burlington, will not be a part of
the union of Ingalls and Holland Mark.)
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls has more of a national reputation, and Garrison has a
higher profile in the Boston business community than Davis.
</P>
<P>
   One added bonus for Holland Mark: It was in danger of losing its
USTrust account after Citizens, an Ingalls client, recently
announced plans to buy USTrust. Now there's a good chance the
business will be handled by Holland Mark Edmund Ingalls.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1911, Ingalls has gone through many reincarnations. Its
acquisition by Holland Mark is simply the latest.
</P>
<P>
   Said consultant Pile of the proposed union of Holland Mark and
Ingalls, ``This is healthy for both companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
