<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR DE FRANCE RACE DIRECTOR LETS VIRENQUE BACK IN RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Two weeks after he banned almost 20 riders and officials
in hopes of producing a Tour de France of renewal and redemption,
Jean-Marie Leblanc, the race's director, admitted failure
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are beaten,'' he said at a news conference called to
announce that the bicycle race would admit Richard Virenque, a
French star, and Manolo Saiz, a Spanish team official, as ordered
Tuesday by the governing body of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blow by the International Cycling Union,'' which is
known as the UCI for its initials in French.``We have been
prevented from completing our attempt to restore the image of the
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a failure,'' Leblanc said. ``But it is not a failure we
are going to accept. We are going to try and correct it legally.''
</P>
<P>
   With the race scheduled to start Saturday in western France, he
said that Virenque would participate.
</P>
<P>
   Virenque was the leader of the nine Festina riders who were
expelled from the last Tour after team officials admitted to a
systematic program of using illegal performance-enhancing drugs.
Six of the riders said they had engaged in doping, but Virenque was
one of three riders who have denied knowingly using the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Frenchman, who now rides for the Polti team in
Italy, is still under formal investigation in that case, which
nearly scuttled the race as riders protested police tactics in
investigating doping. Virenque was also questioned by the Paris
narcotics police in another drug scandal in May.
</P>
<P>
   Hugely popular among female teen-agers , Virenque has been
widely mocked in print and on television for his repeated denial of
charges against him documented by his former trainer, team doctor
and team director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing against Richard Virenque as a man,'' Leblanc
said Wednesday. ``We simply said that his name and image are the
incarnation of doping and that's why we excluded him.''
</P>
<P>
   Virenque's presence is certain to be controversial with fans,
even though 60 percent of those questioned in a recent French poll
said that he should be allowed to ride the Tour. He was its top
climber from 1994 through 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Since the last three winners of the Tour will be absent in the
180-man field, Virenque becomes a favorite now.
</P>
<P>
   Will Leblanc shake his hand and congratulate him if he wins this
86th Tour de France? ``Ask me in three weeks,'' the race director
replied.
</P>
<P>
   After he was banned June 16, Virenque and his team appealed to
the UCI, whose disciplinary commission reversed the decision on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It based its order on a little-noticed clause that says teams
must be invited to a race at least 60 days before it starts. Since
the Tour named its first entries on May 12, which was 51 days
before Saturday's start, those teams were technically invited
illegally. Therefore anybody banned was technically uninvited
illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding vexed, Leblanc noted that the Tour had used the same
selection date for the last 10 years and nobody ever objected.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to discuss the political infighting implicit in the
UCI order. ``I accept the term snub, but it is not a U-turn'' in
the fight against doping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we can have a great Tour de France, clean from
the business that polluted it last year. We're convinced that
things are heading in the right direction and we're going to
demonstrate that in the Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc said it would not have been possible to stage the race
while defying the UCI order. As he pointed out, the organization
furnishes judges, timers and other officials, while authorizing the
points for victories that riders covet in salary negotiations.
Also, Leblanc said, ``We're lawful.''
</P>
<P>
   The banning of Saiz, the director of the ONCE team, was not
related to a drug scandal, although he was questioned in the
Festina affair. The Spaniard was punished because of crude remarks
characterized by Leblanc as ``insults to the race and the country''
he made when he withdrew his team last year to protest actions by
the French police.
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc's news conference was held after a major sponsor, French
bank Credit Lyonnais, said it was considering an end to its
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will keep supporting a Tour, which has been wonderful for
many years,'' a bank spokesman said. ``We will keep supporting a
Tour which is attempting to restore its image.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the Tour cannot restore its image, we will pull out.''
The bank will decide after the race, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
