<SLUG> BC-COKE-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA ESTIMATES LOWER QUARTERLY SALES DUE TO EUROPE RECALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citing the recall of its soft drinks in Europe in June _ the
biggest in company history _ Coca-Cola Co. estimated Wednesday that
its beverage sales fell 1 percent to 2 percent in the second
quarter compared with sales in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in the company's European division, which includes
Belgium, France and other countries where Coke was ordered off
store shelves after a contamination scare, are expected to fall 6
percent to 7 percent, the largest drop in any of Coke's six global
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairly damaging blow that occurred as a result of the
recall,'' said Skip Carpenter, a beverage analyst for Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, adding that before the recall began June 14,
``their Continental Europe business was seeing some good momentum
in a lot of markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Other markets appeared unimpressive, too. In the United States,
typically Coke's star performer, sales are expected to be flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volume trends for the quarter reflect the difficult global
economic conditions that remain in many key markets,'' the company
said in a statement. ``In addition, during the month of June, the
company has experienced a negative impact on sales in several
countries within the Greater Europe Group as a result of the recent
temporary product withdrawal in Belgium and France.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola did not say how much the sales drop would affect
earnings in the second quarter. Profit was already expected to
fall, to 41 cents a share from 47 cents a share in the quarter a
year earlier, according to First Call Corp., which tracks company
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has been mired in a bad year, with profit already down
for two consecutive quarters. Starting last August, the company's
sales declined in many of its biggest markets around the globe,
including Germany, Japan and Brazil, largely because of economic
downturns. That slowdown has also affected some of its large
bottlers, which have posted gloomy results, too. In the United
States, a price increase in many stores has caused sales to drop
off.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by Coke to buy additional brands to expand its overseas
business have been stymied by regulators in Europe, Mexico and
Australia. In addition, fears that Coke's products were
contaminated, which arose after hundreds of people in Belgium
complained of nausea, dizziness and other symptoms after drinking
Coke and Fanta, led to government-ordered recalls of an estimated
15 million cases of drinks in Belgium, France and Luxembourg. Three
factories in Europe were shut until the bans, which went into
effect June 14 and June 15, were lifted June 23.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, mold was discovered inside bottles of Bonaqua, a
mineral water sold by Coke, and that brand was recalled in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The volume declines were expected by Wall Street, which reacted
positively to the news. Shares of Coca-Cola rose 81.25 cents, to
$62, on a day when the rest of the market advanced smartly.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it expected its volume in Latin America to be
flat or down 1 percent, compared with 12 percent growth in the
second quarter of last year. In Africa, which grew 18 percent in
the second quarter of last year on a small base, volume is expected
to fall 1 percent to 2 percent, the company said. The company's
Asian and Middle Eastern business, which grew 7 percent in the
second quarter last year, is expected to decline 1 percent to 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola chairman and chief executive M. Douglas Ivester said
in a statement that ``the worst is behind us'' and predicted
improvement in the second half of the year and next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1913EDT &QL; 
