u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      06-30 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TOPS $36 MILLION IN FUND-RAISING RACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush has raised an
unprecedented $36.2 million for his Republican presidential
campaign, making him the undisputed winner in both parties of the
White House money race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's four months of fund-raising collected more money than any
presidential candidate in U.S. history has raised in their race for
a party's nomination. Bush now has raised about twice as much money
as all seven of his GOP presidential nomination opponents combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am humbled by the response. I am amazed, amazed at the
outpouring of support,'' Bush said during a Los Angeles news
conference. ``This is a campaign that has a wide range of people
who are willing to help. I am gratified.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has raised twice as much money as Vice President Al
Gore, the Democratic front-runner, who reported collecting about
$18.5 million. His lone challenger, former Sen. Bill Bradley,
raised about $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans will always do better than Democrats'' in raising
money, Gore said Wednesday, ``but out ideas and policies had more
support from the American people. And that will be the case again
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, the eventual Republican nominee in 1996, had raised
what was then a record $13.58 million by this time in his election
cycle. By the time the Republican primaries were over in 1996, Dole
had raised $31.3 million. Dole, of course, lost to President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton raised $29 million during the year and a half leading up
to the Democratic Party's nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Steve Forbes spent $37 million in his unsuccessful
1996 Republican primary bid, but that was his own money. Forbes,
who is running again now, has raised $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it into a race for vice president,'' University of
Texas government professor Bruce Buchanan said of the Republican
primary field.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reminded reporters that his father, former President Bush,
lost his 1992 re-election bid just 11 months after receiving a 92
percent favorable rating in public opinion polls. Bush said he is
taking nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money doesn't win. It's a pretty good start,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush jokingly said the fund-raising was due to his ``wonderful
personality.'' But he added that Americans are ``hungry for
something,'' a better and less divisive future.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign finance chairman, Don Evans, said the
fund-raising demonstrates a true groundswell of support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a country that is starved for a leadership they can
trust,'' Evans said. ``These are dollars from the hearts of people
who love this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said more than 75,000 contributions were raised by 2,500
volunteers who pledged to raise $10,000 each. But Evans said that
alone would not have raised this kind of money since Bush first
formed his exploratory committee March 7.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he will decide sometime next month on whether
to take federal matching funds. A candidate who accepts federal
matching money is bound by state-by-state spending limits as well
as a total primary spending limit of about $48 million.
</P>
<P>
   Those spending limits could put Bush at a competitive
disadvantage against a self-financed candidate like Forbes who
would not be bound by the limits. While Bush might be equal to
Forbes in total money, the spending limits would give Forbes the
advantage in states like Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal matching fund system also gives some of Bush's
opponents incentive to stay in the race despite his major
fund-raising advantage. If Bush's opponents have qualified for
federal matching funds, they may want to stay in the race until
after they collect their money next January.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, signaling the financial competition between them, on
Wednesday demanded that Bush give back all the campaign funds that
came from special-interest political action committees. Bush
campaign staff members said they had not yet sorted through the
money to determine how much PAC money they had raised.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, former American Red Cross president and wife of
the 1996 GOP nominee, said Wednesday that she definitely is running
for the Republican presidential nomination next year. Her
exploratory committee has raised about $3.4 million so far, about
one dollar for every 10 that Bush has collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just that he (Bush) is garnering an enormous amount
of money, which he is,'' said Rice University political scientist
Bob Stein. ``He's also making it difficult for the other candidates
to even get to the starting line, and it's not clear they ever
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign reported that the contributions, which are
limited to a maximum of $1,000 a person, came from people in all 50
states. Texas accounted for 30 percent of all the contributors. The
average donation was $480.
</P>
<P>
   The size of Bush's campaign fund led to questions about whether
the American system of political finance has caused the public to
believe the system is corrupting.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to have to develop a level of public trust
with anyone in public office. That's what leadership is about,''
Bush said. ``If people think candidates can be corrupted by $1,000
contributions then they shouldn't vote for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he favors several campaign finance reforms, including
instant contribution disclosure on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best policy for campaign reform is to let the sun shine
in,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's nearest Republican rival in fund-raising, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona with $4 million, campaigned Wednesday in New
Hampshire on the need for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told that there is no room for this issue in
Republican primaries. I intend to make room for it,'' he told about
200 cheering supporters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain wants to ban soft money, the donations from unions,
corporations and individuals that do not fall under federal limits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed banning soft money from labor unions and
corporations, but not from individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent Wednesday raising even more money for his campaign in
Los Angeles, Sacramento and San Francisco. He also attended a
program honoring teachers in Los Angeles and a youth mentoring
program in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign enjoyed several lighter moments Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush discussed meeting movie star Warren Beatty on Tuesday
night in a closed meeting with Hollywood big shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's secretly in love with my mother,'' Bush said in
reference to former first lady Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shook his (Beatty's) hand and said, 'Hi, I'm George W.' He
said, 'I'm Bulworth.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty earlier this year starred in the comedy as Bulworth, a
U.S. senator from Los Angeles who has arranged his own murder and
decided to tell the truth about American politics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush also had a brief statistical clash with Los Angeles Mayor
Richard Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush likes to say in his speeches that he is ready to be
president because Texas, if it were a separate country, would have
the world's 11th largest economy. But in introducing Bush at the
Virginia Road Elementary School, Riordan announced that Los
Angeles, if a separate country, would have the world's 11th largest
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Mayor, you and I have got to have a little discourse about
whether Los Angeles is the 11th largest economy in the world,''
Bush said. ``I think you meant 12th.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush also again defended his recent series of mistakes in the
names of countries and their peoples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I mispronounce the name of a country doesn't mean
I don't understand how to lead,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What America is going to have to be comfortable with is: Do I
know how to set clear goals. Do I know how to lead, and do I shoot
straight. That's all I know how to do.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Julie Mason and The Associated Press contributed
to this report. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
