<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      06-30 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A GATHERING TWILIGHT, CLINTON CONTINUES TO PUSH HIS AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Conn., Ill.) (gm) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Two days ago, a local politician introducing President
Clinton at a fund-raising luncheon in Westport, Conn., said that
Clinton was entitled to a ``victory lap'' of public valedictories
as he completes his final 18 months in office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton bristled at his host's well-meaning remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I'm on a victory lap or a final lap,'' Clinton
told the crowd of contributors, a smile disguising his impatience
with those ready to write him off. ``They're beginning to talk to
me as if I'm _ there is a sort of ring of eulogy about all of this.
As far as I can tell, I'm reasonably healthy. I still show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Say this about Bill Clinton: He will not go gentle into
political oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past six days, he has given a major domestic policy
speech laying out his priorities for the next year, conducted a
75-minute endurance test of a news conference and announced that
his budget team had found an additional trillion dollars in federal
surpluses over the next 15 years. He also unveiled the most
sweeping set of proposals for remaking Medicare in the program's
34-year history, which he pitched to senior citizens here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called on Republicans in Congress to set aside
partisanship and embark with him on a ``season of progress'' on
Medicare and Social Security, education, gun control, health care
and campaign financing. Clinton said the public is pleading for at
least a temporary truce in the partisan bickering and rancor that
have characterized his six and a half years in office.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Clinton and the Democrats are at least as
responsible as the Republicans for the capital's polarization.
Clinton now wants progress on his agenda _ and his legacy _ and
says he is willing to compromise with the GOP on taxes in order to
get it.
</P>
<P>
   He swears that he is serious about wanting to get things done
before presidential politics and congressional campaigns swallow
Washington's energy. Responding to Republicans who doubt his
sincerity _ and even some in his own party who would prefer to run
their campaigns against a do-nothing Republican Congress _ Clinton
said there is a still a narrow window for bipartisan agreement on
critical national issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, some other people here really believe that because the
presidential season has already started, the battle for Congress
has already started, even though it's a year and however many
months away, that the best politics is just to run out the clock
and wait until the next election and hope that the country is doing
so well and we enjoy the lazy days of summer so much, nobody will
notice,'' Clinton told a group of students at Georgetown University
on Friday. ``I don't agree with that, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech at the White House on Tuesday detailing his
Medicare proposal was similarly suffused with the spirit of sweet
reason. He hailed the participation of several Republican leaders,
saying ``their presence here today indicates that we can all raise
concerns about each other's ideas without raising our voices.'' He
said ``it augurs well for this announcement today and for the
welfare of our republic.''
</P>
<P>
   But inside that velvet glove of accommodation was the
president's mailed fist of partisan aggression. Clinton said that
the nation's leaders had not only an opportunity but an
``obligation'' to remodel Medicare for the onslaught of the baby
boom generation early in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The clear message is that if Clinton's health care plan is
rejected or weakened, it will be the fault of the parsimonious
Republicans who prefer to give the nation's economic bounty to the
wealthy, in the form of cuts in capitals gains and estate taxes,
rather than to the deserving elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's health and education plans follow a familiar pattern:
He proposes generous new programs that poll well with the public
and challenges Republicans to act on them.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, with Medicare. Polls show that a subsidized
prescription drug benefit is extremely popular with the public and
the new budget surplus projections afford Clinton the luxury of
proposing it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was warmly received here Wednesday when he pitched his
Medicare proposal to an audience of several hundred senior citizens
at the Chicago Cultural Center.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the audience, Frances Krause, 79, expressed hope
that the president can persuade Congress to pass his Medicare
proposal, or at least the prescription drug part of it. But Mrs.
Krause, a registered Republican who often splits her votes between
the two parties, said that Republicans may try to block the plan to
prevent Clinton from getting credit for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he's for they're against,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
