<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, July 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ Confirming market expectations, the
Federal Reserve says it has raised its target for the federal funds
rate, which determines borrowing costs throughout the U.S. economy
and beyond, by a quarter-percentage point to 5.0 percent. It left
the less frequently used discount rate unchanged at 4.5 percent. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Ehud Barak, the prime
minister-elect, seals his government's coalition as the Shas Party
agrees to join. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Bela Crkva) _ Grief and religion vs. forensics
and justice: Albanians clamor for war-crimes teams to come to their
villages so the dead, after mass graves are checked, can at last be
buried properly. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FUNDRAISING (Los Angeles) _ George W. Bush, shattering
presidential fund-raising records, raised $35.5 million in the
first six months of 1999, nearly 10 times as much as his closest
Republican rival and millions more than Vice President Al Gore.
Bush's fund-raising prowess has virtually dried up the pool of GOP
money for his rivals. Bush, at a news conference in Los Angeles,
says his campaign is still counting donations and termed the $35.5
million figure a ``minimum number'' after a fund-raiser in
Sacramento. By Richard Berke
</P>
<P>
   DETECTIVE-INDICT (Denver) _ Using deception and a network of
sources to ferret out personal information, from Ennis Cosby's
credit card records after his murder to the home addresses of
organized crime detectives in Los Angeles, a convicted felon built
a million-dollar-a-year business here selling information that
ended up in the hands of everyone from the tabloid press to a
reputed member of the Israeli Mafia. James Rapp, 39, and his wife,
Regana Rapp, were indicted last Friday on two counts each of
racketeering, in a case that is the first known criminal
prosecution against the growing business of peddling confidential
information. The couple face up to 24 years in prison a $1 million
fine. The case against the Rapps is the biggest test of whether
practices that on their face are deceptive are also illegal. By
Douglas Frantz. (2,500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-EMERGENCY-CARE (New York) _ They look like any of the
anxious patients who walk into the city's polyglot emergency rooms.
But there are telltale signs: Sometimes they arrive with luggage
and with tourist visas in their pockets. Often they hand over
crumpled notes from their doctors back home in China or Africa.
They are known as medical immigrants, poor or middle-class
foreigners who scrape and save to fly to New York, solely to seek
treatment at city emergency rooms, where federal and state law
mandates that they must be examined and treated if their problems
require immediate care. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART (Undated) _ Despite previous estimates that mitral
valve prolapse affects 5 percent to 35 percent of the population, a
new report has found that the condition, in which a valve in the
heart is abnormally long and floppy, is much less common and much
less serious. By Holcomb B. Noble. (600 words)
</P>
