<SLUG> BC-LOVERS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM REVIEW: THE LOVERS ON THE BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
OUR RATING: 4 STARS 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Leos Carax's deliriously romantic, prohibitively
expensive ``The Lovers on the Bridge'' has been hung up on the
other side of the Atlantic for some eight years. But now, with a
``Martin Scorsese Presents'' credit attached, this art film to end
all French art films can finally be seen in America.
</P>
<P>
   It was well worth the wait. Even in its direst depictions of
Paris' lower depths, there's a stunning, classic compositional
sense to practically every frame (the cinematographer, Jean-Yves
Escoffier, went on to shoot ``Good Will Hunting''). And the
virtuoso sequences _ water skiing down the Seine as Bastille Day
fireworks explode and sparkle, a shadowy night tour of a fine art
gallery, the tiled walls of a Metro station ablaze with flaming
posters _ simply steal your breath.
</P>
<P>
   And the film's main location, the Pont Neuf, Paris' oldest
bridge, is itself a wonder to behold. Not because it's a minor
architectural masterpiece in a city full of major ones, but because
it's an utterly convincing replica, complete with blocks' worth of
surrounding urban banks, that was built on a lake in Montpellier.
</P>
<P>
   As for the film's story, it incorporates just about every great
theme of French cinema into an archetypal ode to the marvelous
madness of love. The saving, killing, healing, hurting,
disorienting, disturbing, deluding, creative, confusing and
confounding powers of passion are Carax's subjects, and he
orchestrates them into an intoxicating _ yet somehow credible _
symphony of transcendent emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Lavant plays Alex, a barely functional addict who lives on
the bridge _ which has been closed to traffic for a two-year
retrofitting _ with an older bum, Hans (Klaus-Michael Gruber). One
night, Michele (``The English Patient's'' Juliette Binoche), an
artist who's going blind, squats on one of ``their'' benches. Hans
wants the interloper to leave immediately; Alex, quite rightly,
sees her as a potential lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed she is for him, and he becomes hers as her condition
deteriorates. Despite the degradation of their hand-to-mouth
existence, they have terrific fun with one another and share
immensely tender moments. They remain chaste, too, partly because
of Michele's obsession with a lost lover and partly because of a
secret she's keeping. The film's cockeyed, squalid updating of
courtly love somehow resonates deeply, and the unlikely purity of
it makes the lovers' climactic, unavoidable betrayals ring with
extra notes of poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are as accomplished as the film's formal
elements, with Lavant ranging from near-catatonia to the kind of
self-interested and self-sacrificing extremes only deep human
connections can inspire. Binoche's exquisite instincts for just how
much feeling should be displayed or held back in any given
situation get a real workout here, and she's up to the task as
Michele ricochets from despair to hope to resignation to cold
calculation. It's Binoche's richest work ever, on a par with her
performance in Krzysztof Kieslowski's ``Three Colors: Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Carax has only made one other feature since 1991, ``Pola X,''
which recently received a cool reception at the Cannes Film
Festival. It's easy to imagine his aesthetic and romantic fancies
flying out of control. But they reach a kind of unique, perfect
pitch in ``Lovers'' that, indeed, may not be repeatable. Genius and
madness, as often as they are lumped together, almost never achieve
such a sublimely coordinated union. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
