<HEADER>
A5082 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-PROMOTION-HNS &LR;      06-30 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-PROMOTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT ISSUES GUIDE TO ENDING SOCIAL PROMOTION AT SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration on Thursday will
recommend some practical steps to school administrators on how to
end social promotion, the practice of passing academically troubled
students to the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley will unveil the guide,
``Taking Responsibility for Ending Social Promotion,'' at a visit
to an elementary school here. The 72-page booklet lays out some
strategies for insuring that students get the help they need and
don't find themselves in the 10th grade not knowing how to read or
do simple arithmetic.
</P>
<P>
   The guide suggests:
</P>
<P>
   _ Providing summer school for students who fail to meet the
academic standards of each grade level.
</P>
<P>
   _ Offering after-school programs, homework centers and
year-round schools to help kids who are falling behind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keeping younger students together with a teacher for more than
a year to build bonds that enhance learning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Setting out clear academic standards for students and their
families and communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social promotion is not good for children,'' Riley told
reporters at a breakfast meeting. ``We always had high standards
for some children. But now we're talking now about high
expectations for all children, high standards for all children.
That's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The booklet will go 15,900 school districts plus about 1,100
education organizations and state education officials, Education
Department spokeswoman Julie Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Concern over the practice of promoting poorly performing
students is a response to stories about children who reach high
school and even graduate without mastering basic educational
skills, including reading and writing.
</P>
<P>
   Ending social promotion is one of few areas of education where
Democrats and Republicans agree. President Clinton talked about the
ill effects of social promotion in his State of the Union address.
And in May, Clinton unveiled an education plan that included giving
states four years to end social promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is part of Clinton's goal of adding 100,000
teachers to reduce class size in the early grades.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also oppose social promotion. Texas Gov. George
Bush, the early front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination, spoke out against social promotion this year and won a
$173 million appropriation to help Texas public schools end the
practice.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republicans differ with Democrats on what Washington's
role should be. The Clinton administration wants to make federal
education dollars to states contingent on those states doing away
with social promotion. The administration also proposes spending an
extra $800 million for remedial programs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want to include ending social promotion as an option
for states receiving an estimated $13 billion in federal aid to
education. In the debate over reauthorizing the Elementary and
Secondary Education Act taking place in Congress, Republicans want
to dispense the money in block grants that states could spend for
any educational purpose they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Ten states already have explicit policies forbidding social
promotion. Last year, the California Legislature approved a law
requiring school districts to hold back children who don't meet
specific academic criteria and provide them with summer school to
get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   In 2003, New York will require all its high school students to
obtain a regents diploma in order to graduate. Earning the diploma
requires passing rigorous state exams and is tougher to obtain than
a locally issued diploma with less stringent requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Houston, executive director of the American Association of
School Administrators, said that ending social promotion is a moot
point since virtually no school district in the nation has a policy
specifically approving it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes great politics,'' he said. However, he praised the
administration for seeking to provide more money for remedial
programs.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
