<HEADLINE>
WILL THE REAL SAM PLEASE STAND UP?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a party the other day at Roseland in New York to celebrate
the opening of  &UR; Spike Lee &LR; 's ``Summer of Sam,'' writer-producer
 &UR; Victor Colicchio  &LR; told  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  he'd been logging on to chat
rooms to discuss the movie, which is about serial killer  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Berkowitz &LR; , known as ``Son of Sam,'' and his reign of terror in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's led to some real twilight-zone dialogues,'' he said. ``I
was communicating with people all over the world as far away as
Guam, and I was having what I thought was an intelligent dialogue
about Son of Sam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started getting all these Kosovo questions like how would
Son of Sam compare to today's missiles and what would be the battle
results. I'm in the middle of explaining that one cannot compare a
crazed serial killer like David Berkowitz to artillery, like this
wasn't the kind of person you send into combat. Suddenly, after
half an hour in the chat room, I realized that these were weaponry
weirdos who thought Son of Sam was a generation of ``surface to air
missile (called Sam). The Internet can ... be a brave new world of
total miscommunication.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Speaking of goofs, the credits on the movie misspell the
name of actor  &UR; Ben Gazzara &LR; , who laughed it off and foresaw the
error as the answer to a trivia  &LR; game in the year 2500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPEAKING AND SELLING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Celebrities are getting into the museum act, or it's the other
way around:  &UR; Kevin Kline &LR;  narrates the audio tour of
``Impressionists in Winter,'' currently at the Brooklyn Museum of
Art ( &UR; Candice Bergen &LR;  did it when the show was here).  &UR; Steve &LR; 
 &UR; Martin &LR;  narrated last year's Picasso show at the Museum of Modern
Art in New York, and  &UR; Lyle Lovett  &LR; does a presentation at the
Contemporary Art Museum in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   _ When  &UR; Florence Moore &LR;  called the J. Jill catalog, she was
informed, by a recording that ``all of our satisfaction
associates'' were busy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The waiting room at BMW of San Francisco is equipped with two
data-ports so that customers can transmit from their laptops while
their cars are getting the once-over.
</P>
<P>
   _ The newest Nokia cell phones will be smaller and made of
chrome, setting them apart as ``objects of desire,'' phone
designer &UR; Frank Nuovo  &LR; told Civilization magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ So you're in the market for a trendy status symbol: The Wall
Street Journal says the personal trainer has been replaced by the
art adviser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PREPARE FOR HAPPINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Society of Happy People, with headquarters in Irving,
Texas, is preparing for August 8, National Admit You're Happy Day,
with a list of 100 Happiest Events, Inventions and Social Changes
of the Century, including No. 7, indoor malls; No. 9, the Disney
empire; No. 16, dry cleaning; No. 46, Mood Rings; No. 58, acrylic
nails; No. 98, call-waiting, three-way calling, caller ID,
conference calling; No. 100, Captain Kangaroo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Cover the armrests with plastic:  &UR; Michael Nathanson &LR; ,
president of MGM, is reported by Premiere magazine to have
suggested that real-life spontaneous bleeders be invited to the
premiere of the forthcoming movie ``Stigmata.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jeane Kirkpatrick &LR; , former UN ambassador and foreign policy
adviser to  &UR; Elizabeth Dole &LR; , was issued a $45 ticket in Maryland
this week for leaving her dog in a car while she went shopping. A
witness told the Washington Post she didn't take this well.
Meanwhile, the Utne Reader reports that People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals put an ad in the April edition of Prison Legal
News asking that inmates write letters supporting a campaign to
free circus elephants, who have lost their freedom, too.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tim Ernst &LR;  reports that after studying the Balkan War at
school, his 12-year-old daughter,  &UR; Amanda &LR; , said she didn't ``know
why  &UR; Slobodan Milosevic  &LR; doesn't like Albanians. After all, they're
just people with white hair and pink eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to say honestly what I think each of my brothers
would have ended up doing (if they hadn't become actors): bank
robbery for Daniel; running a strip club or being a male stripper
for Stephen; Billy would be a Catholic priest, of course, just to
further drive women insane; and I would be living on a Caribbean
island, with an Internet newsletter, the Matt Drudge of Saint
Bart's.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Alec Baldwin in Cosmopolitan magazine.
</P>
