A5089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CHERNOMYDIN-57     06-30 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHERNOMYDIN-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRIME MINISTER TO HEAD RUSSIA'S GAS MONOPOLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Cementing the relationship between the Kremlin and big
business, Viktor Chernomyrdin was installed Wednesday as chairman
of Russia's biggest company, the natural gas monoply Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
   The move returns the former prime minister, who recently served
as Moscow's envoy to the Balkans, to the company where he began his
career.
</P>
<P>
   It also gives President Boris Yeltsin and his allies greater
influence over a lucrative company and potential source of campaign
funds during the coming political year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chernomyrdin is considered to be loyal to Yeltsin and his
family,'' said Andrei Piontkovsky, a leading political analyst.
``He may not channel financial flows to the family. But he will not
allow Gazprom to channel them to coffers that are not approved by
the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Housed in a towering skyscraper in Moscow, Gazprom has long been
one of Russia's most powerful and mysterious companies.
Paradoxically, its political influence has increased with the
collapse of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   While many of Russia's banks and holding companies were hurt by
the financial crash, Gazprom has gained. As a result of the
devaluation, its natural gas exports have become even more
profitable. Gazprom announced a $475 million profit on gas exports
for the first quarter of 1999, a three-fold increase compared with
last year.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, last years' economic crisis swept away many of
the economic reformers who were trying to force Gazprom to be more
open about its financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Boris G. Fyodorov, who served as Russia's chief tax collector
before last August's devaluation of the ruble, clashed with
Gazprom's chief executive, Rem Vyakhirev, over Gazprom's failure to
pay back taxes. Fyodorov even moved to seize the company's
property.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fyodorov is no longer in the government, and company and
government officials collegially negotiate the amount of tax
Gazprom will pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is kind of feudal relationship,'' Piontkovsky said. ``The
amount of tax that is paid is determined, not by law, but by ad hoc
discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's interest in Chernomyrdin's new appointment was
clear on Tuesday when Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and Aleksandr
Voloshin, the Kremlin chief of staff, came to Gazprom's
headquarters on the eve of the shareholders' meeting. The Russian
government holds a 38 per cent stake in Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who led Gazprom before he was picked as prime
minister in 1992, was elected Wednesday as chairman of the company
by a new 11 member board.
</P>
<P>
   Vyakhirev, the previous chairman will retain his seat on the
board. He will also continue to serve as the company's chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Russia commentators on Wednesday painted Chernomyrdin as a
counterweight to Vyakhirev, who was deemed to be too politically
untrustworthy by the Kremlin. Russia is bracing for parliamentary
elections in December and presidential elections next summer. And
there has been speculation in Moscow that Vyakhirev might throw his
support behind Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   While Luzhkov has been trying to position himself to succeed
Yeltsin, he has been stoutly resisted by the Kremlin, which is
looking to groom its own candidate, possibly Stephasin.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent slight, the government even refused to give the
mayor permission to take a poltical trip by helicopter to nearby
farms, saying the flight plans had not been submitted in time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Natural gas is not the only monopoly where the Kremlin has moved
to solidify its control. Last week, Voloshin was named chairman of
United Energy Systems, Russia's electrical utility. Anatoly B.
Chubais, the former pro-market Kremlin aide, who remains as adviser
to Yeltsin, is president of the utility.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision will give Chernomyrdin more of a political
base. He has his own party, Our Home is Russia. But he is too
unpopular to mount a serious bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin is often been lampooned as a wooden and
inarticulate speaker. And his role in bringing an end to NATO's war
with Yugoslavia has earned him the enmity of many nationalists and
left-wing legislatures, who complain that he was too supportive of
the Western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chernomyrdin is in a position to help other candidates
and forge alliances with stronger politicians. And he has indicated
that he would keep his hand in politics in his new position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot and will not mark a retreat from active politics,''
Chernomyrdin said this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
