<HEADER>
A5097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-BANKS-NYT &LR;      06-30 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 BIG ITALIAN BANKS AGREE TO MERGE; 3-WAY DEAL IN FRANCE FALTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Two major moves to consolidate European banking went in
different directions Wednesday as two of Italy's biggest banks
agreed to a friendly merger and efforts by the French government to
negotiate an amicable solution to a three-way bank merger broke
down.
</P>
<P>
   In Milan, the boards of Banca Intesa, the second-largest bank in
Italy, and Banca Commerciale Italiana, the fourth-biggest, approved
a $15 billion share swap creating what will be Italy's largest
banking group, with assets of roughly $290 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, the participants in a $38 billion hostile bid by
Banque Nationale de Paris for two French rivals, Societe Generale
and Paribas, failed to negotiate an end to their five-month old
duel, leaving it up to investors to decide the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The failure by the governor of the Bank of France, Jean-Claude
Trichet, to negotiate and end to the battle clears the way for
French banking authorities to approve a sweetened $19 billion bid
by Societe Generale for Paribas. The two banks' plans to unite was
upset when Banque Nationale launched its hostile bid for both banks
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors cheered the luckless outcome of the talks, which ended
early this morning. Societe Generale's share price rose by as much
as 4.3 percent, to 173 euros, or $178; the Paribas share price rose
almost 4 percent, and Banque Nationale's shares rose as much as 3.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   While French government officials insisted they were ``neutral,
if not indifferent'' to the outcome, they made clear that they
sought a French solution. Many analysts interpreted the government
willingness to allow the talks to end as a sign that it believes
that investors, mainly large funds from the United States and
Britain, will choose the larger three-way alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, the effort to bring together Banca Intesa and Banca
Commerciale Italiana went smoothly, though it too came about only
after government intervention to steer the course of bank
consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Unicredito Italiano, another large Italian
bank, had made a bid for Commerciale that the Bank of Italy, the
central bank, rejected as hostile. Last week, the Bank of Italy's
president, Antonio Fazio, cleared plans for the merger announced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under their deal, Banca Intesa will exchange 1.65 of its shares
for each Commerciale share, for 70 percent of Commerciale, with an
option to acquire the rest. The banks said they expect savings
before taxes of about $865 million over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Intesa itself is the product of a merger two years ago of the
Cariplo savings bank and the Banco Ambrosiano Veneto, two powerful
groups in Italy's heavily industrialized north.
</P>
<P>
   Ripples of the merger will be felt beyond Italy, with
connections reaching into the heart of French and German banking.
Credit Agricole of France, Intesa's largest shareholder, will
retain about 13 percent of the merged group. Agricole, together
with the new combination and Commerzbank of Germany, now a major
Commerciale shareholder, will hold almost 17 percent of Credit
Lyonnais, the giant French bank that the Paris government recently
took public after bailing it out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
