<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MULTICULTURALISM' AT WIMBLEDON? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Edits thruout)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``Predominantly white.'' That's the Wimbledon rule to
watch out for when you suit up for a scuffle on the grass. No clown
ensembles, thank you, as may be seen elsewhere on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that way in a couple of other departments, too,
like the balls and the faces.
</P>
<P>
   That started to change in 1957 when a dark-skinned woman from
New York named Althea Gibson won a Big W singles title. Eighteen
years later Arthur Ashe, barred from playing kids tournaments in
his hometown, Richmond, Va., because of his complexion, made it to
the winner's circle. Twelve years after that the tournament
radicalized further by adopting yellow balls.
</P>
<P>
   There went the neighborhood, right? Right. It got better.
</P>
<P>
   So if quarterfinalist pals Venus Williams and Alexandra
Stevenson win their next two matches and arrive in Saturday's
final, will it be historic?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. Never have two teen-agers collided for the title.
There's more. Never has a qualifier (Stevenson) gone so far. And
more. It would be the altitudinest major female finale: Venus, at 6
feet 2 inches, an inch taller than Stevenson. Additionally, no
19-year-old from Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., (Venus) has ever faced
an 18-year-old from San Diego (Alexandra) for the big door prize.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, the final would be predominantly unwhite. That would
make the neighborhood even more intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965 Ashe, relatively new on the scene, asked reporters why
they kept referring to him as the ``Negro'' _ the word then _
``Davis Cupper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't write `Willie Mays, the Negro center fielder,' do
you?'' was Arthur's wry rebuke. ``I thought we were beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   We should have been.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, after the rookie Stevenson had gone for the
bundle with one electrifying all-or-nothing forehand blast on the
dead run, the reporters' questions were about pigmentation rather
than celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The kid had a right to celebrate after she'd nervelessly
canceled a match point against her in the tiebreaker with that huge
forehand. The nifty shot down the line boomeranged the match to
her, 2-6, 7-6 (10-8), 6-1, over Lisa Raymond, another American who,
at No. 37, ranks 49 lengths ahead of Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson is the product of a mixed union: black father, white
mother. Is that such a big deal? Ask some of the descendants of one
of the guys who made the United States _ Thomas Jefferson _ if
that's a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Stevenson was asked about being one of the first
pair of African-Americans (presumably she and Venus, a 3-6, 6-3,
6-2, victor over Anna Kournikova) in the quarters.
</P>
<P>
   She had a good answer. ``I represent both African and Caucasian,
so I think it's great for both sides. Without race or anything I
think it's great because we're both friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Excellent. Shouldn't we be past the race thing _ but not
interracial friendship?
</P>
<P>
   Still, racism came up because her mother had said Alexandra had
been called a despicable name at a junior tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was called `nigger' once, but there's racism everywhere in
the world,'' Stevenson said. ``I'm not going to say who did it. It
has no relevance. It doesn't matter any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after the press conference, Alexandra, an imposing kid of
caffe latte shading, was thinking about labels, like
African-American, and decided maybe she's an M.C.
``Multicultural,'' she chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm eight parts: English, Welsh, Cherokee, Irish,
Italian, Swedish on my mother's side. African and French on my
father's. I love 'em all.''
</P>
<P>
   Who is her father?
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Is she in touch with him?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   That's her right.
</P>
<P>
   A story in the Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel states that the name
Julius Erving appears on Stevenson's birth certificate as the
father, alleging it may be the same Erving, now retired, of
basketball renown at the University of Massachusetts and with the
New Jersey Nets of the ABA and Philadelphia 76ers of the NBA.
Despite a photo of Alexandra's alleged birth certificate in the
paper, Erving denied he's the father in the Sun-Sentinel story.
Alexandra's mother, Samantha Stevenson, a sometimes sportswriter
and TV reporter for Boston's Channel 7 in 1974, declined to comment
on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Good genes, if true. But is it really any of our business? Is
her family tree either, even though she's a peach of a player who's
fallen from it?
</P>
<P>
   Should I write that Alexandra Stevenson is the first
multicultural member of Wimbledon's last eight? Risky unless we've
examined the family trees of all those to go before. No thanks. I'm
not in the genealogical forestry business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Williams and Stevenson?'' says the Italian journalist, Gianni
Clerici. ``Who cares who their parents are? I call Venus espresso
and Alexandra cappuccino. It would be a tasty final.''
</P>
<P>
   I call them bright American kids on a wonderful ride toward the
end of the rainbow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
