<SLUG> BC-PROCTER-ANIMAL-TESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE ANNOUNCES END TO MOST ANIMAL TESTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio) (rk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. said Wednesday that it would
immediately end animal testing for 80 percent of its consumer
products, from shampoo and color cosmetics to household cleansers
and dishwashing detergents.
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights groups, which had engaged in a protracted battle
to force P&AMP;G, the maker of Crest toothpaste, Tide detergent and
Pampers diapers, to end testing on animals, reacted with guarded
praise to the company's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The ban includes all shampoo and hair-styling products as well
as tissue and towel, skin care, household cleaners and laundry and
dishwashing products. The remaining 20 percent of the products not
covered by the ban include those that are required by law to be
tested on animals, such as drugs and certain food items, like those
containing pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   For the goods included in the animal-testing ban, ``science and
technology have advanced to the point where we can confirm the
safety of these finished products through nonanimal alternatives,''
said Larry Games, the company's vice president for global product
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, animal rights groups were quick to point out that P&AMP;G's
new policy applies only to existing products. The company
acknowledged that it reserved the right to use animals to test
certain new products that fall into the categories of goods
included in the ban. That stipulation led animal rights groups to
urge caution in effusively praising the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``History is made in small steps, and today P&AMP;G has taken one of
them,'' said Mary Beth Sweetland, the director of People for the
Ethical Treatment of Animals, which is one of P&AMP;G's staunchest
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Among multinational consumer and cosmetics businesses, P&AMP;G has
been one of the last holdouts to abandon animal testing. As a
result, P&AMP;G in recent years became a high-profile enemy for animal
rights groups looking for a new target.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G said its policy change, however, was prompted by the
availability of new testing methods and the company's own internal
goals. But public pressure was clearly a factor, analysts and the
animal rights groups said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that had something to do with it,'' said Jeff
Hallmark, a director of the Animal Rights Community, based in
Cincinnati, P&AMP;G's hometown, which had been at odds with the company
for more than a decade. What is more, he said, ``the majority of
their competitors making similar products have all changed. They
are just following a trend and are very late to follow the trend.''
</P>
<P>
   An official of the Food and Drug Administration said P&AMP;G was not
breaking any new ground with its ban because the products included
are those containing chemicals and other ingredients that have
already undergone extensive animal testing. ``So there is really no
necessity to do further testing to determine the safety of those
ingredients,'' said Dr. Mack Holt, director of the FDA's office of
animal care and use.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G said, however, that it had long been committed to finding
effective alternatives to animal testing. The company said that
over the last 15 years it had invested nearly $100 million in the
study and development of alternative research methods.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and the company said the shift was also in line with
P&AMP;G's ambitious goal to significantly increase its sluggish sales
growth and decrease its cumbersome product development cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The company, for example, should see cost savings from replacing
expensive animal testing with cheaper methods. The alternative
methods are also often faster than animal-testing procedures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
