<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPE EXPERT TESTIFIES IN CISNEROS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An audio recording expert testified Wednesday that
some tapes of telephone conversations between former Housing
Secretary Henry Cisneros and his onetime mistress are ``copies of
copies'' that could nonetheless be used as evidence against
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Koenig of Manassas, Va., the government's tape expert,
told U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin that copies or duplicates
are usually entered into evidence in criminal trials when the
original recording does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors with Independent Counsel David Barrett pared their
list of tapes they want to use to 26 from 34 when Cisneros goes to
trial in September on conspiracy charges. The reduction was made on
Sporkin's request to expedite a pre-trial hearing, now in its
second week.
</P>
<P>
   Koenig said none of the tapes in Barrett's possession is an
original.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are duplicates of the original information,'' Koenig
said, adding that at least five tapes are ``duplicates of
duplicates.''
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin called those ``a double whammy,'' but he did not signal
how he may rule on motions by Cisneros' lawyers to keep the tapes
from jurors when the case goes to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes are crucial to Barrett's conspiracy case against
Cisneros, who is accused of orchestrating a cover-up with Linda
Jones to conceal $250,000 in hush money paid to her after their
love affair ended in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend Cisneros, 52, sought to hide the financial
arrangement with Jones to protect his 1993 nomination to head the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, a job he held until
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The two are named in a 21-count indictment handed down by a
federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 50, testified last week that she taped telephone calls
with Cisneros out of fear that he would cut off financial support
to her if he moved to Washington. Jones testified as part of an
agreement that would reduce the 3 1/2-year prison sentence she
received for bank fraud, money laundering and obstruction of
justice in a case prosecuted by Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, formerly known by her married name, Linda Medlar, kept 88
tapes of telephone conversations made over several years.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also told prosecutors he wanted testimony about
whether there has been wholesale redactions, editing and splicing
of the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   When he did break off support, Jones said, she went public with
charges that he broke a verbal pledge to provide her $4,000 a
month. She filed a civil lawsuit claiming a breach of contract and
later settled for $49,000.
</P>
<P>
   She also went on a national television show in a paid interview
and accused Cisneros of lying about the payments to FBI agents
conducting a routine background investigation into his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett originally sought to introduce 34 tapes into evidence at
the Sept. 7 trial. The hearing into their admissibility is expected
to continue after the July 4 holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Koenig testified Wednesday just hours before the 21-year-old
independent counsel law expired. The expiration does not affect
ongoing investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett declined comment on the demise of the law that was
enacted in the fallout of the Watergate scandal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
