<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-TECHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION FAULTS PROGRESS OF NEW FLIGHT-CONTROL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The union representing technicians who certify and repair
air-traffic control equipment said Wednesday the Federal Aviation
Administration's billion-dollar purchase of a delay-plagued
Raytheon computer display system has fallen even further behind
schedule. The union questioned whether it will be installed
anywhere by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   By announcing their concern, the Professional Airways System
Specialists have ripped apart a carefully bound public front
involving the FAA and the unions responsible for the air-traffic
control system.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, the FAA, PASS, and the National Air Traffic
Controllers Association jointly announced a delay in the STARS
(Standard Terminal Automation Replacement System) program _
designed to replace aging air-traffic control systems at facilities
that control the crowded, busy airspace within a 50-mile radius of
the nation's 172 largest airports.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, STARS was supposed to be installed in September 1998
at Boston's Logan International Airport, and at Washington's Ronald
Reagan National Airport earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But when the FAA announced that STARS would be delayed
indefintely, the agency also said that modified versions of the
system that would use current comptuer systems, rather than new
ones, would be installed and tested at two small airports _ in
Syracuse, N.Y., in December, and in El Paso, Texas, early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the unions, including PASS, supported the move.
But Wednesday PASS said that timeline isseven weeks late. ``To have
a project slip by seven weeks over the course of eight weeks is the
type of slip that does not make us feel good about the delivery of
this system,'' said Tom Brantley, national vice president of the
union.
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokesman William A. Shumann, while acknowledging that
``some software development and human factors issues took us longer
than initially anticipated,'' said the display system of STARS is
still scheduled to be installed in Syracuse in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not fallen behind schedule,'' he said. ``When we
developed that time schedule two months ago, we included some
contingency time within that schedule, and we have used that to
solve the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   STARS is being developed for the FAA and the Department of
Defense by Raytheon Co. Raytheon spokesman David Polk said the
company had no comment on the criticism by PASS.
</P>
<P>
   PASS has been in contract negotiations with the FAA, but
Brantley said the union's concern had nothing to do with
bargaining, but rather with the FAA's ability to field a working
air-traffic control system.
</P>
<P>
   Because of delays, the FAA said must buy off-the-shelf color
controller displays made by Lockheed Martin Corp. for five radar
approach centers including those at New York's LaGuardia and John
F. Kennedy airports, and Washington's National.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
