<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO SEEK NEW TALKS ON MIDEAST PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The announcement Wednesday that Israeli Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak has formed a coalition government paves
the way for a new push to achieve peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, long eager for this moment, now will
press Barak to reopen talks on all fronts _ with Syria, the
Palestinians, and other Arab leaders to revitalize economic ties
throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one predicts a quick deal on any track, only that new
negotiations could begin before summer's end.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Wednesday to Shimon Peres, the acting speaker of
Israel's parliament, Barak said he would present his government
early next week, paving the way for the transition to his
administration from defeated leader Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   In the key decision over the makeup of the coalition, Barak
brought in the ultra-Orthodox Shas party, which has dovish views on
giving back territory to the Palestinians and the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   Shas' 17 seats brings Barak's coalition to 59 seats in the
120-member Knesset, or parliament, but outside the coalition he
will be able to draw upon a well of support. Arab-backed parties
add another 10 seats to the coalition on peace votes, and the
far-left Meretz party brings 10 more. In all, Knesset watchers can
count a possible 87 votes in the parliament for peace initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who remained closed-mouthed in the bargaining for
coalition partners, decided against including the right-wing Likud
Party in the government, a decision that analysts say will enable
Israel's new leader to negotiate more freely with the Syrians and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The downside, said analysts, is that Barak has sidestepped one
of most divisive issues in Israel today _ the secular-religious
divide. By including Shas in the coalition, he will be ignoring a
major message in the recent elections that secular Israelis wanted
the religious to have a smaller voice in government.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to give Shas four ministries _ Labor, Health, Religion
and Infrastructure _ but he also forced them to give up the
powerful Interior Ministry, which the party held under Netanyahu.
The Interior Ministry now could go to Meretz, as a possible
enticement to expand his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak's choice of Shas shows where his emphasis will be _ with
the peace process,'' said Mark Heller, a political analyst at the
Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   But the question now is, which peace process?
</P>
<P>
   While US Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk this week
said the Clinton administration wants Barak to open talks with the
Syrians and the Palestinians, there is widespread perception in
Washington, Jerusalem, Cairo and other Arab capitals that the most
substantial movement will happen on the Syrian track.
</P>
<P>
   That is partially because Barak has stated he wants to pull his
troops out of southern Lebanon within a year. Barak could pull the
troops unilaterally, risking further confrontations with Hezbollah
guerrillas in Lebanon, or he could do it in conjunction with a
Syrian peace deal that would involve giving back part or all of the
Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel today, giving back the lush and hilly Golan, which
overlooks the Sea of the Galilee and sits atop much of Israel's
water resources, would be extremely difficult. But it would be much
easier than solving the long-intractable issues with the
Palestinians, including the future of Jerusalem, the return of
refugees and water rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak will give greater priority to the Syrian front, but
we're still a long way from the big breakthrough,'' Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian President Hafez Assad has said he wants the talks to
begin exactly where they left off several years ago. He has said
Israel had agreed to the principle of returning the Golan, which
was captured from Syria more than a quarter-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   But recently Assad, in an interview with British biographer
Patrick Seale, made comments about Barak that were stunningly
positive, calling him a ``strong and honest man. ... It is clear
that he wants to achieve peace with Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Assad has given other ``signals'' to US officials
that he is ready for peace talks with Barak, Indyk said. An
administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the messages have come through French and European Union officials,
as well as through cables filed to Washington by US Ambassador to
Syria Ryan Croker.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility for movement with Syria has left Palestinian
officials anxious and nervous about being left behind. The
Palestinians have communicated this fear in all directions, to
Washington, to King Abdullah of Jordan, to Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and to Assad himself.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat recently sent envoys to see
Assad, but the Syrian president has given them no indication that
he will work in concert with the Palestinians toward a
comprehensive peace deal, said a Palestinian official, speaking on
the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of movement toward a final settlement with the
Palestinians, Barak would more likely take smaller steps and
fulfill parts of the deal made last year between Netanayahu and
Arafat at the Wye plantation in Maryland, predicted US officials
and Palestinian analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Barak will make some symbolic moves toward the
Palestinians ... but the Lebanon and Syrian issue seems to be the
foremost concern and priority,'' said Hisham Ahmed Fararjeh, a
political scientist at Bir Zeit University in the West Bank. ``The
kind of diplomatic overtures we are seeing, by Barak toward Assad,
and by Assad toward Barak, backed up by statements made by the
Clinton administration, give almost every indications needed that
there will be a serious move on the Syrian track.''
</P>
<P>
   After Barak forms his government next week, he will then make
plans to visit Washington for a short trip, perhaps three days
later in July, according to the Israeli Embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real feeling that there's an opportunity of gettign
the peace process back on track, but much difficult work needs to
be done,'' said an Israeli government official in Washington. ``We
shouldn't be over optimistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
