<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIPPING-TIPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A TIP, PODNER: DON'T STIFF THE STEER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the last weekend in May when a tourist at the Fort Worth
Stockyards had his photograph taken with Ron Sitton, a
fifth-generation Fort Worth cowboy. Sitton, 45, was astride his
longhorn steer, Pecos Bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work for tips, sir,'' Sitton told the tourist. The tourist
refused to tip. Harsh words were exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next is the subject of some dispute. The tourist
told police the steer used its shoulder to pin him to a tree. When
he squeezed free, the tourist said, the steer charged him.
</P>
<P>
   Sitton says that Pecos Bill, being a steer and not a bull,
wouldn't charge anyone and never touched the tourist or endangered
bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, no one was injured. But something about this story
bothered us.
</P>
<P>
   We did not know we were supposed to tip longhorns. We might have
assumed that the longhorn was a city employee, and therefore not an
appropriate subject for a tip.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard of tipping cows but didn't know that meant giving
them money.
</P>
<P>
   This Stockyards incident made us wonder: Just whom else are we
leaving off the tip list, at our potential peril?
</P>
<P>
   Lest we be considered rude, we checked out Emily Post's
Etiquette. And she reminded us of a few folks who should be on the
tip list:
</P>
<P>
   The florist who delivers: $2, even though you are the recipient
of the gift. Some florists won't take the tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tell them thanks, but they should save their money to
send flowers another time. It works. People remember that and call
us,'' said James Johnson of Swofford's Florist in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The guys who move your furniture: $15-50 each, mostly because
they move and arrange your belongings, and etiquette demands that
you acknowledge all that hands-on work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tipping is very common. It's also common to offer lunch and
something to drink,'' said John Garrett of Garrett Transportation,
an Atlas Van lines agent in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The barber or hairstylist: 10 to 15 percent. Most of us know
that but sometimes forget that a similar tip goes to a separate
colorist, and a separate tip of $1-$3 should be offered to the
shampoo person. You do not want them to turn on you. Be nice.
</P>
<P>
   Garbage collectors: $25 or so at Christmas, Post says, although
if your garbage collector is a city employee, as almost all are
either directly or by contract, gratuities normally are not
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't allow our employees to accept tips or to salvage,''
said Dave Balbierz, district manager for Fort Worth Waste
Management.
</P>
<P>
   Carpet installers: $5-$10 apiece for those who pull up old
carpet, put down new and then have the good grace to clean up.
</P>
<P>
   The car wash: $1, usually in a jar where employees pool the
tips.
</P>
<P>
   Room service: 15 percent, cash. Most folks do that, but not
everyone knows that Post recommends that amount even if a room
service charge is added into the bill. After all, they are there in
your hotel room and it is best that everyone stays in a good mood.
</P>
<P>
   In restaurants where there is no table service, Post recommends
a 10 percent tip.
</P>
<P>
   And when you have your photograph taken with a longhorn? Even
with your own camera? Although she offers suggestions on tipping
for 55 different occasions, and etiqutte advice on everything from
wedding invitations to how to eat a papaya, Post does not discuss
tipping cowboys or longhorns. But from where we stand, it looks
like money well-spent.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
