<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHADOW-OFSLAVERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORS AIM TO BANISH SLAVERY'S SHADOW ON RELATIONSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her mama taught her ``real good'' how to leave a man, just as
her grandmama taught her mama. What they didn't teach her was how
to make a relationship work.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Brenda Lane Richardson sees it, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called her Emma and pictured her waking in the slave
quarter, starting her day by gritting her teeth, bracing for
trouble and knowing she could expect only two responses from men,''
Richardson said about her great-grandmother in a letter to her
mama.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one who was white would rape or beat her; the one who was
black would have to look the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of slavery, she said _ and her sista-friend Dr.
Brenda Wade agrees _ is the cloud hanging over African-American men
and women for more than 100 years, perpetuating the myth of being
inferior and rendering them almost incapable of having loving
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a book that explores the emotional legacy that slavery
has on intimate relationships among African-American men and women,
Richardson and Wade have melded their life experiences and
expertise to write ``What Mama Couldn't Tell Us About Love: Healing
Advice for Overcoming the Emotional Legacy of Slavery, Celebrating
Our Light'' (HarperCollins, $24).
</P>
<P>
   Their objective is to help end the lingering rift between black
men and women and change the way they relate to one another by
getting them to make peace with their history and embrace their
ancestral strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson and Wade, affectionately known as ``The Brendas,''
are scheduled to lead The Greatest Untold Story seminar July 9 in
Seattle at the Unity convention, a gathering of minority
journalists from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Relationships have long been the subject of discussions among
African-Americans, as well as a running topic in the black news
media and a growing number of self-help books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some African-American woman who has given up, who has said
`There are no good men' or `I'm always going to be alone,' will
read the book and realize she can no longer rely on statistics,''
Richardson said. ``While the statistics may say there aren't enough
men available ... God wants us to have love and wouldn't give love
to some of us and leave others wanting.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is an ordained minister, journalist and author of the
award-winning novel ``Chesapeake Song.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade is a family psychologist, Essence magazine columnist and
former TV host of ``Can This Marriage Be Saved?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The key message here is that we are not irrevocably flawed,''
Wade said. ``But because of the unique backdrop of our history,
because of the social context that we live in, African-Americans
have issues that are particular to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although history shapes every human being's experience, the
black experience is singular because of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Wade said that because of the strength and resiliency of
African-Americans, they have not only survived but flourished. But
it doesn't mean there weren't deep emotional scars, different even
from those of Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Said Richardson: ``Sometimes when I speak to white groups, they
come over and say, `We enjoyed what you had to say, but why can't
you people just get over it?'
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell many stories of immigrants, but I try to explain to
them that their relatives came by choice and after being here many
generations and losing their accents, they in effect became
``white'' and that meant all of the privileges that go with being
white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people, on the other hand, were forceably brought here in
chains. We were not allowed to speak our language or practice our
customs. The people who owned us told the world we were uneducable,
that we smelled bad, were prone to violence and were heathens.
Those beliefs became universal.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors say this affects the way black men and women relate
to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Although they believe it is important to acknowledge the
long-term effects of slavery, Wade and Richardson caution that this
isn't a book about blaming white people; nor it just for
African-American women.
</P>
<P>
   ``If every white person in America disappeared today,'' Wade
said, ``we'd still not be free because of lingering negative
images.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof, she said, is in the large numbers of depressed
African-American men and women who come through the doors of her
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underneath, there is pain, anger, shame and fear, and unless
we can acknowledge those feelings, we turn it on ourselves,'' she
said. ``What I want African-American women to see is that any
emotion you face loses its power when you acknowledge it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, ``What Mama Couldn't Tell Us About Love'' reflects
the authors' struggle in their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to write ``What Mama Couldn't Tell Us About Love'' more
or less evolved from Richardson's attempt to save her marriage.
</P>
<P>
   From Wade, she said, she learned to take ``that finger of
blame'' she was pointing at her husband and point it at her own
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to ask myself, `What is there about me that attracted me
to this person?' '' she said. ``What do I need to understand about
my own history that led me to this relationship? I realized I had
to learn more about myself and stop blaming my husband. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I began a sort of archaeological dig,'' she said. ``This is a
country where people learn to quickly put the past behind them.
That's good in terms of trying to make money or buy a house, but
not in building a relationship. Our history affects us emotionally,
and it certainly affects us in relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors believe, however, that blacks also inherited
strengths from their ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found is that if we could unlearn harmful beliefs we
could unearth some of these tremendous strengths,'' Richardson
said. ``We can use them to improve our relationships, to attract
new relationships and create lives of abundance for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strengths are gifts that we often take for granted, for
instance our faith in God. No matter how high and mighty we get,
that's something that remains with us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
