<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILIPEPPERS-CD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILI PEPPERS ARE RED HOT AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along with Nirvana, Nine Inch Nails, Pearl Jam and Ministry, the
Red Hot Chili Peppers that helped bring alternative rock into the
limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1984, they toiled in small clubs, barrelling through
humorous live shows that had them tagged as a novelty act but all
the while honing their funk-punk sound. Luck was on their side in
'91, when they released ``BloodSugarSexMagik,'' their commercial
breakthrough, which exposed a new generation of kids to a rap-rock
sound that has since become common.
</P>
<P>
   As the hits rolled out, the money rolled in, and soon the
pressures of becoming so big so fast took their toll: singer
Anthony Kiedis' drug habit worsened, guitarist John Frusciante
left, and everyone else grew sick of the cycles of being in a
popular rock band.
</P>
<P>
   Frusciante's departure led to the arrival of Jane's Addiction
guitarist Dave Navarro, whose refreshing work on ``Blood's''
follow-up, ``One Hot Minute,'' is the only good thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Time passed. Navarro left. Frusciante rejoined. Kiedis cleaned
up. The time and the changes have done the Peppers a world of good:
``Californication,'' their first disc in four years, is a solid and
refreshing collection of songs that prove the guys are far from
being over.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, ``Cali'' is their most unique effort musically, in
that the band doesn't focus on one style of music. There's a reggae
tinge to ``Around the World;'' the single, ``Scar Tissue,'' is a
sober, melodic pop song; ``I Like Dirt'' and ``Savior'' are
inventive chance-takers; and ``Parallel Universe'' is a hypnotizing
rocker. Bassist Flea's sidewinding bass lines _ the band's
trademark _ are what give the disc cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   Lyrically, the band was heavily inspired by their home state of
California. As Courtney Love did on Hole's ``Celebrity Skin,'' the
Peppers don't necessarily rip apart LA as much as they write about
their place in it. There's not a lot of poetry going on here, but
it does beat the heck out of ``Give It Away.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5119 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-`HANNIBAL'-REVIEW-TEX     06-30 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`HANNIBAL'-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HANNIBAL' WON'T QUITE SATISFY APPETITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
 &HT;    c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hannibal''
</P>
<P>
   by Thomas Harris
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte, $27.95
</P>
<P>
   Too much consumer anticipation is never a good thing. We've
recently been reminded of that by a film, ``The Phantom Menace,''
and now the same message is driven home by a book titled simply
``Hannibal.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as George Lucas' fourth ``Star Wars'' installment suffers
by comparison with its more distinguished predecessors, so Thomas
Harris' third Hannibal Lecter novel pales when compared with ``Red
Dragon'' and ``The Silence of the Lambs.'' By objective measure,
``The Phantom Menace'' is a far better-than-average movie. The same
can be said for ``Hannibal'' as a book, if we could just separate
it from the Harris novels that came before.
</P>
<P>
   But we can't. The megasuccess of ``The Silence of the Lambs,''
the 11 years that enthralled Harris fans have spent waiting to see
what happened next to Hannibal the Cannibal and FBI agent Clarice
Starling, the somehow-endearing monster's pursuer/soulmate, the
near-unprecedented media hype in the four months between when
Harris unexpectedly turned over the new novel to his publisher and
``Hannibal'' hit bookstores, have combined to make us expect
nothing less than a masterpiece, and ``Hannibal'' just isn't that.
Instead, it's decent work from a very talented writer who
eventually resorts to trickery and mechanical plot twists for a
flawed, unsatisfying conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Harris picks up the lives of Lecter and Starling seven years
after the not-so-good doctor disappeared after helping Starling
track down a nasty serial killer nicknamed Buffalo Bill. The
ensuing years have been better to the monster than the agent.
Lecter has resurfaced in Florence, Italy; there, as the mysterious
Dr. Fell, he has been named curator of an ancient library.
Lecter/Fell enjoys his new life; indeed, Harris notes, he has
``hardly killed anybody'' since arriving in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   Starling, on the other hand, has been stymied in her career,
enduring a series of dead-end assignments thanks to the enmity of a
government official she alienated while pursuing Buffalo Bill and
her bad habit of saying things she shouldn't to supervisors.
``Hannibal'' begins with Starling participating in a drug raid that
turns bad; a master marksman, she kills five people before the
smoke clears, including a very bad mother who chooses to shoot it
out while cradling her infant son.
</P>
<P>
   Tabloid coverage alerts Lecter to Starling's professional
dilemma. He can't resist sending her a note. Although Lecter is
careful to conceal where he is, this new contact precipitates a
renewed effort to find him, and not just by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Mason Verger, an obscenely rich prior Lecter victim, once lost
much of his face and body to Hannibal the Cannibal. For years he
has nurtured an unhealthy appetite for revenge while alternately
indulging several other obscene hobbies involving small children.
Verger wants Lecter to suffer the same sort of tortuous indignities
and is willing to spend whatever it takes to get what he wants.
When the same government official who has persecuted Starling
becomes Verger's bribed minion, the pieces are in place for an
explosive, bloody outcome.
</P>
<P>
   What we get is heavy on the blood and light on the explosion.
Having created a new monster to join the Lecter/Starling dance,
Harris is unable to blend him into the story mix in any believable
way, even by the elastic boundaries of fiction. This is partly
because Harris is resorting to such an obvious literary trick: In
an attempt to keep Lecter sympathetic to readers, the author makes
Hannibal the target of an even greater monster. Lecter, Harris
wants us to assume, mutilates and/or kills only people ``who
really, really deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Harris' tendency, when scene-setting or
bloodletting, to change tenses in midparagraph. Action described in
the past tense suddenly is written about in the present; this is a
common device used by writers who want to emphasize certain
passages by interrupting reading rhythm. It's useful one or two
times in a book, but Harris tries it by the dozens, and after a
while it becomes annoying rather than mesmerizing.
</P>
<P>
   Do these things make ``Hannibal'' a bad book? Not at all. Thomas
Harris is an excellent writer, period. Some of his descriptive
passages, especially when introducing readers to Lecter's Florence,
are good enough to be carved in Italian marble. This author is
obviously a scholar; his references to writers, artists,
philosophers and poets both famous and obscure always ring true.
And Hannibal Lecter is a fine, unique character.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Hannibal'' is only a good book, not a fine one. Its
conclusion is a substantial disappointment, more convenient than
curious. To enjoy fiction, readers often have to suspend disbelief,
but Harris pushes that rule too far.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the reclusive author has to care. On its first morning
of publication, ``Hannibal'' was No. 1 on Amazon.com's bestseller
list. It will sell a million copies before fall. Film rights have
been sold for eight figures. Harris can buy Florence and all the
libraries in it if he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he could, and should, have done better. ``Hannibal'' is
an 80 percent effort by a 100 percent writer.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
