<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN MASSACHUSETTS NOT SHARING IN ECONOMIC BOOM: STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER KAMINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- While dramatic growth in local technology and
knowledge-based industries has spurred an economic boom pushing the
Boston area far ahead of the national average, a study released
Wednesday suggests the windfall has not fully reached the rest of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The report, conducted by the Massachusetts Taxpayers Foundation
_ a nonprofit organization that analyzes government spending and
the economy _ found the state is composed of two ``sharply
distinctive'' economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tendency to assume that if the eastern
Massachusetts economy is booming . . . it means it is happening
across the state,'' said Michael J. Widmer, president of the
foundation. ``This study shows that the two different economies
need to think differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Greater Boston, the so-called ``inside Route 495'' sector, is
powered by high-tech and knowledge-intensive industries, including
management consulting, software, private universities, money
management, insurance, and high-tech manufacturing, which have
proved to be big money makers.
</P>
<P>
   The second economy, ``outer Massachusetts'' _ areas north, west,
and south of Interstate 495 _ has an economic base similar to the
rest of the nation, which is dependent largely on older
manufacturing industries that have not been the recipients of such
striking prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   While unemployment in the Boston area has hovered near record
lows, hitting 2.5 percent in May, other parts of the state posted
higher joblessness: 3.8 percent in Pittsfield, 4.1 percent in
Lawrence, and 5.2 percent in New Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowledge-based industries make up a stunning 79 percent of
the Greater Boston economic base, compared to 44 percent in the
rest of the state and 42 percent in the nation as a whole,''
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   The survey suggested that some of Boston's knowledge-based
industry growth has begun to spill over to the rest of the state,
but not enough to make up for the great economic losses incurred
during the '80s recession.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Ann Economics president Edward Moscovitch, the study's
consultant, said both regions have recovered at relatively the same
rate, with strong employment growth, but outer Massachusetts has
not reached its prerecession employment level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I understood quite how dramatically the rest of
the state had been hurt by the recession,'' Moscovitch said,
highlighting one reason he says it is significant to view the state
as two economies. In some parts of the state, he said, the
``employment rate dropped by 25 percent _ that's what the Great
Depression was.''
</P>
<P>
   Western Massachusetts politicians say this is not news to them.
The difference between the two economies must be acknowledged in
policy-making issues, they say, because they have very different
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are basically two different economies, and it is the
Boston economy that drives everything'' on Beacon Hill, said state
Representative Daniel E. Bosley, a Democrat from North Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to ensure that we take into consideration the outer
reaches of the state. There are very different economic dynamics
and problems,'' Bosley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Nakosteen, a professor at the University of
Massachusetts-Boston, said Boston's economy is stunningly strong
because of its remarkable ability to support new industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been much more difficult to turn those other areas
around,'' Nakosteen said. In the outer areas of the state ``most of
the people that are unemployed or underemployed can't find the work
they want, while Boston can't find enough workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some economists, though, point out that pockets of outer
Massachusetts have been able to support technology-based economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is quite as simple as inside 495 and outside
495,'' said Alan Clayton Matthews, an economics professor at
UMass-Boston. ``The boom has spread past 495, but hasn't reached
the edges of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the state's central cities have gained ground.
Unemployment for May was 2.9 percent in Worcester and 3.2 percent
in Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Outer Massachusetts needs knowledge-based industries to invest
in its communities to create the type of economic growth now
visible in the Boston area, said state Senator Mark C. Montigny, a
New Bedford Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government should be targeting the economic resources of
the private sector and bring them to the outlying areas,'' said
Montigny, chairman of the Senate's Ways of Means Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
