<HEADLINE>
BUSH SHATTERS FUND-RAISING RECORDS, BASKS IN LIMELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush stunned the
political community Wednesday with news that his presidential
campaign so far has raised $36.25 million _ a record for a
presidential primary race and an amount that could spell the end
for some of his less financially fortunate GOP rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is beyond expectation,'' a clearly pleased Bush said in Los
Angeles on the final day of the second campaign reporting period of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am humbled by the response,'' said Bush, who was midway
through a money-raising campaign swing across California.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can imagine, I'm amazed at the outpouring of support.
This is a campaign that has got a wide range of people what are
willing to help. People from all around the country. I am
gratified, and that's that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And campaign officials noted that the second-quarter total
certainly will increase once all the last-minute contributions are
counted.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has been accused by some of riding on his famous
family name and being vague on the issues, his ability to spin hay
into gold has astonished political observers.
</P>
<P>
   In just four months, Bush has raked in more money than any other
candidate has raised during an entire presidential primary race.
</P>
<P>
   GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole received $31.3 million in
contributions during an 18-month period in the last presidential
primary, while President Clinton raised $29 million in the same
period, according to Federal Election Commission figures released
by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And by this time in the 1996 race, Clinton had raised $19.5
million, Dole had $13.6 million and Texas Sen. Phil Gramm reported
$11.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   While it was all smiles for Bush staff members on the campaign
trail Wednesday, other GOP presidential campaigns had less
breathtaking news to report.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole had raised between $2 million and $4 million,
former Vice President Dan Quayle had gathered about $3.1 million,
Sen. John McCain of Arizona had less than $5 million and
businessman Steve Forbes and social conservative leader Gary Bauer
each have raised between $2 million and $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio had $1.6 million, former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander had raised more than $2 million and
Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire had received about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore had received up
to $18.5 million so far, and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey
has surpassed expectations by raising a little more than $11.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's money came from 75,600 contributors who gave an average
of about $500, according to Don Evans, his finance chairman and
long-time friend. He raised nearly $8 million in the first quarter
and $28.3 million in the second quarter, which ended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Texas was very good to its native son. About 30 percent of all
donors were from the Lone Star state and more than a third of the
money _ $11.9 million _ came from Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Federal campaign finance laws limit donations to each candidate
to $1,000 for individuals and $5,000 for political action
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unprecedented. There never has been anything like it
in the history of American politics,'' Evans said. ``I think what
this says is there's a lot of people starved for leadership in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the money still pouring in, Bush may decide to forego
accepting federal matching funds _ a move that would allow him to
raise an unlimited amount of money for his primary campaign. Bush
said he would make that decision in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   When asked in Los Angeles what he attributed the record support
to, Bush quipped: ``A wonderful personality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hungry for something, and I am gratified,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined to urge his GOP rivals to quit now while
they're behind and endorse his candidacy instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I encourage them to give it their best shot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush continued to flex his money-raising muscles Wednesday in
vote-rich California, which is considered strong Democratic
territory. He raised $2.3 million Tuesday night at a Los Angeles
event, and fund-raisers were held Wednesday in Sacramento and San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, he visited a south-central Los Angeles
elementary school where a non-profit, public-private partnership
program is retraining teachers in an effort to maximize technology
benefits in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Bush toured the school and briefly spoke to teachers. One of
them, Desiree McNeal, said she was so impressed by Bush's remarks
about educating all children that she may vote for him, even though
she has never before supported a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I wasn't open to him at all because I'm a Democrat,''
she said. ``Now that I heard him speak, I think maybe he does
(care.)''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also held his first extensive news conference of his
California trip, repeating earlier comments that he will not rule
out selecting a vice presidential candidate who favors abortion
rights, even though he opposes abortion except in cases of race,
incest and protecting the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   He also defended himself against critics who say he doesn't have
the background to be president _ a criticism that was fueled last
week when he mixed up the small European countries of Slovenia and
Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I mispronounce the name of a country doesn't mean
I don't understand how to lead,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Later in Sacramento, Bush played football in the blazing heat
with youths involved in a mentoring program. On the first play,
Bush, playing quarterback, barked: ``66-77-36D25, hut, hut.''
</P>
<P>
   He then lofted a touchdown pass to former Heisman Trophy winner
Tim Brown, who now plays for the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
