<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS RALLY AS FED ANNOUNCES RATE HIKE, ADOPTS NEUTRAL BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FED-RATES-NYT) 
(th) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Both the stock and bond markets rallied Wednesday
after investors got a surprise they liked from the Federal Reserve.
The central bank signaled that a quarter-point increase in its
short-term interest rate target could be enough to keep inflation
in check.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks rose 21.21 points, or
1.57 percent, to a new high of 1,372.66. The Nasdaq composite index
climbed 44.01 points, or 1.66 percent, to a new high of 2,686.12.
The S&AMP;P's previous high was in May and the Nasdaq's in late April,
both just before the Fed indicated, after its May policy meeting,
that a rate increase was in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average jumped 210 points in the 13
minutes after the 2:15 p.m. announcement and finished the day at
10,970.80, up 155.45 points, or 1.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, the price of the 30-year bond jumped 1 9/32,
to 90 6/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction
from the price, fell to 5.96 percent from 6.06 percent on Tuesday.
The yield on the 2-year note, which is more sensitive to Fed
interest rates moves, dropped to 5.52 percent from 5.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed announcement also had a calming effect on much more
vulnerable emerging markets, especially in Latin America. Brazil's
Bovespa index jumped more than 300 points after the news, to close
up 2.2 percent. More important, interest rates on emerging market
bonds dropped sharply in comparison to rates on comparable U.S.
Treasury securities.
</P>
<P>
   Fed policy makers, meeting in Washington, announced that they
had raised their target for the Federal funds rate, which is the
interest on overnight loans between banks, to 5 percent from 4.75
percent. That move was expected and led several major banks to
raise their prime lending rates a quarter-point to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Fed surprised investors by shifting its
interest rate outlook. Policy makers are now neutral, rather than
leaning toward higher interest rates, as they were coming into
Wednesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts argued that the Fed's announcement does not
mean there will not be another rate increase. That will depend on
how fast the economy continues to grow and how tame inflation
remains.
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board reported Tuesday that its consumer
confidence index in June jumped to its highest level in more than
30 years, an indication that consumers may keep spending.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rally in copper, which jumped to a 1999 high of 75.95
cents a pound Wednesday, could be reflecting a worldwide economic
rebound and put some more pressure on prices, at the same time.
Also Wednesday, the price of oil for August delivery broke out of
an eight-week trading rage to a 1999 high of $19.29 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Some more indications on economic growth will come Thursday,
with the release by the National Association of Purchasing Managers
of its manufacturing index for the nation, and on Friday with the
employment data for June.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the rally in interest rates since last week could
keep key rates _ like those for mortgages _ from rising much more,
a fact that would make a significant slowdown in growth less
likely. The yield on the 10-year note Wednesday was 5.78 percent, a
quarter-point below its recent high and less than a quarter-point
above where it was when the Fed gave its May signal of an interest
rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a little bit of this celebration is unwarranted,''
said Thomas McManus, the equity strategist at NationsBanc
Montgomery Securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
