<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-GUNS-BOS &LR;      06-30 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISSUE COMES DOWN TO THE SAME STICKING POINT: GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ The war may be over in Northern Ireland, but the
fighting is not. In Ireland, it always comes down to guns.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen months after the signing of the Good Friday Agreement,
life for ordinary people in Northern Ireland has never been better,
and yet the peace process is stalled. The formation of a
power-sharing cabinet, which will return local government for the
first time since it was suspended in 1972 at the height of the
Troubles, is being held up by a dispute over the IRA's weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant unionists, led by David Trimble, the first minister
of the new local parliament, say that democracy cannot take root
when one of the main political traditions, in this case
republicanism, maintains an armed wing. Trimble argues persuasively
that the IRA has to do more than say it is committed to seeking a
united Ireland through democratic means. If the republican movement
has given up the armed struggle, Trimble asks, what does it need
arms for?
</P>
<P>
   But the Good Friday Agreement does not link disarmament to the
setting up of the cabinet, nor does it make the disarmament a
prerequisite for two members of Sinn Fein, the IRA's political
wing, to take their seats in that cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams argues just as persuasively as
Trimble that his party won those seats in a democratic election,
and are entitled to take them.
</P>
<P>
   Now that violence has been largely contained, the dispute over
what to do with the IRA's weapons illustrates Northern Ireland's
real problem: the lack of trust.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Friday Agreement is often called a peace treaty, but it
is really a political settlement. It established political
institutions and set in motion a series of events, such as the
release of paramilitary prisoners, the creation of cross-border
bodies to represent mutual interests on the island, and the reform
of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, all of which are crucial to
giving Northern Ireland a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   Besides guaranteeing that Northern Ireland will remain part of
the United Kingdom as long as a majority of its citizens want, the
agreement allows unionists the opportunity to maintain that
majority by convincing enough nationalists that their rights and
aspirations will be respected, and their standard of living higher,
in Northern Ireland. But it also affords nationalists the chance to
convince unionists that a united Ireland makes more sense
economically and culturally, that unionists who account for less
than 2 percent of the British population would have improved status
and representation in a united Ireland where they accounted for 20
percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   What the agreement did not do, however, was create trust. The
unionists don't believe the republicans when the latter say they
have given up violence as the way to achieve a united Ireland.
Unionists, wary of the double speak they believe to be a cultural
trait of Catholics, say some IRA members will go back to war if the
scope and pace of change is not to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   The republicans don't believe the unionists when they say that
they have learned from the past, when institutional discrimination
and gerrymandering consigned Catholic nationalists to second-class
citizenship. They see the unionist obsession with the IRA's weapons
as a contrived objection.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists can't seem to understand the deep mistrust that not
only republicans but nationalists of all stripes have of them. Many
don't accept that they discriminated against Catholic nationalists.
They don't see as a double standard that while they are calling for
the IRA's guns to be turned in, more than 100,000 legally-held guns
exist in Northern Ireland, nearly all in the hands of unionist
civilians. Unionists consider those privately and legally held guns
necessary protection.
</P>
<P>
   But that is just what republicans and loyalists who hold guns
illegally consider their weapons _ protection against each other
and against the Irish and British governments, which they trust
only slightly more than each other.
</P>
<P>
   The unionist determination to make the surrender of weapons a
condition for formation of the executive plays right into the hands
of cynics within the IRA who believe the peace process is a con,
that despite all the flowery rhetoric about parity of esteem and a
new way of doing things in Northern Ireland, the unionists still
hold a veto and still always get their way.
</P>
<P>
   But the refusal of the IRA to make even a token gesture on
weapons plays right into the hands of the unionist naysayers who
have tried to sabotage the peace process at every turn by claiming
that the IRA is playing a game in which it will go back to war as
soon as it has wrung every conceivable concession out of the
British and Irish governments.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA argues that turning in its weapons would be tantamount
to a surrender it did not make. The IRA also points out that none
of its previous incarnations were forced to give up guns when they
said they had decided to pursue politics.
</P>
<P>
   Within the IRA, weapons take on a quasi-religious quality. In
1969, when the Troubles exploded, loyalist mobs simply walked in
and took over Catholic neighborhoods in Belfast. Nationalist
families were burned out while the mostly Protestant police stood
back and did nothing. The IRA, which had been dormant for years,
consisted of a bunch of old men with a few rusty guns. Graffitti
went up in nationalist areas suggesting that IRA stood for I Ran
Away.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy-handed treatment by police of civil rights marchers
and the refusal of the police to stop loyalists while
simultaneously cracking down on nationalists breathed life back
into the new Provisional IRA, which built up an arsenal and vowed
never to be caught unarmed again. The humiliation of being caught
unarmed had a profound effect on the IRA. It believes that without
weapons it is out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists say that until the IRA is out of business, there will
be no real democracy in Northern Ireland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2014EDT &QL; 
