<SLUG> BC-BRUCEWOOD-PREMIERES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUCE WOOD PREMIERES PIECE SET TO GERSHWIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Two years after moving to Fort Worth from
Austin, modern dance choreographer Bruce Wood, 38, expands in two
new directions this weekend with a pair of premieres at Bass
Performance Hall.
</P>
<P>
   It's been an up-and-down year for the Bruce Wood Dance Company,
a midsize modern-dance troupe that keeps 10 dancers employed full
time. Cancellation of a performance at the Majestic Theatre in
Dallas last fall was followed by successful events in Fort Worth at
Bass Performance Hall. Wood continues to occupy a special slot on
the local dance scene _ not competing with the classical Fort Worth
Dallas Ballet, and working with a higher budget and bigger ambition
for national recognition than the older Contemporary Dance Fort
Worth and Jubilee African American Dance Ensemble, the city's other
major modern dance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Wood holds to the dream of establishing a company that will tour
internationally from a Fort Worth base.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the two premieres on the weekend program was
commissioned through the Bass Performance Hall Education Program.
Setting ``Rhapsody in Blue'' to the famous score by Gershwin was a
challenge for Wood, who had never had a commission involving a
specific piece of music.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Buratto and Stephen Seleny, who direct the education
program, gave Wood a list of 15 concert works to choose from; he
wrote proposals for five works, and Buratto and Seleny settled on
the Gershwin. After its premiere this weekend, the work will be
performed for schoolchildren, starting in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never set anything 18 minutes long straight through,''
Wood says. ``It took me a while to get into it. I had to dig a
little deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood describes the result as technical and difficult for the
dancers, and as less commercial than previous settings of this
immensely popular music.
</P>
<P>
   The tango-based music of Astor Piazzolla, the Argentine composer
who died in 1992 and who has since become one of the most
frequently performed composers in Europe and America, provided the
inspiration for the other new work, ``Zero Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly erotic, with the female dancers costumed in underwear,
``Zero Hour'' is described by Wood as ``stark, brutal and edgy.''
</P>
<P>
   The one borrowed work on the program is ``Waiting for Sunrise,''
a setting of '50s music by renowned modern-dance choreographer Lars
Lubovitch, with whom Wood worked in New York.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
