<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5137 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELLABS-NETCORE-BOS &LR;      06-30 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELLABS-NETCORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLABS TO PAY $575M FOR NETCORE SYSTEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Within two months of shipping its first product, Netcore Systems
Inc., a 2 1/2-year old developer of data switches to handle
Internet traffic for both long distance and regional telephone
companies, Wednesday said it will be acquired by Tellabs Inc., for
$575 million in Tellab stock.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Netcore, of Wilimington, Mass., is the latest in
a flurry of consolidation moves by major telephone equipment makers
to acquire the next generation of technology that combines voice,
data, and video. Just last Friday, Lucent Technologies Inc.
announced it was spending $900 million to acquire Nexabit Networks
Inc. of Marlborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known Tellabs for more than a year and believe that our
products and technology are an excellent fit with their
equipment,'' said Ash Dahood, Netcore's founder and chief
executive, who will remain at the company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal catapults Lisle, Ill.-based Tellabs into the big
leagues with Lucent Technologies Inc. and Nortel Networks Corp. to
compete against Cisco Systems, the leading supplier of
sophisticated devices called routers that are sold to phone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   With Netcore's product, called the Everest Integrated Switch,
Tellabs will be able to send ``packets'' of voice and data traffic
using either an existing technology called asynchronous transfer
mode, or ATM, on a single network or the newer Internet protocol
technology, or IP, which is easier and less expensive to maintain
than current circuit-switched networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Netcore, Tellabs will be able to go to the regional
telephone companies who are transitioning into the ATM switching
and IP routing over the next 10 years,'' said Polina Ialamova, a
telecommunications analyst at Madison Securities in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   For Netcore investors, the Tellabs acquisition is also a
lucrative deal. Of the $35 million invested in Netcore, Matrix
Partners of Waltham, Mass. was both the early and lead investor.
Its nearly $8 million investment in Netcore is now worth about $100
million in Tellabs stock, according to Andrew Marcuvitz, a general
partner at Matrix.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrific return for us, but then these are strange
times and we are happy to be part of it,'' said Marcuvitz, who
recalled that six months ago, both companies were in negotiations
when Tellabs broke off discussions ``and did not want to take the
plunge.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, several deals between Tellabs'competitors and small
telecommunicaitons suppliers were completed and in April, Tellabs
announced a 2-for-1 stock split. Company president Brian J. Jackman
has stated that he expects sales to triple from $1.67 billion last
year to $6 billion by 2003. Last January, Tellabs officials said
the company would make at least one acquisition, after it failed to
acquire Ciena Corp., a fast-growing telecom networking equipment
maker, in a highly publicized courtship. That failed purchase
raised questions about whether Tellabs would have new routing
technology to compete with larger rivals like Lucent and Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said Wednesday's belated acquisition of
Netcore helped answer those questions. Jackman said the purchase
will dilute the company's per-share earnings by between 1 cent and
2 cents this year. However, Netcore's contribution to earnings in
2000 will have a neutral to slighlty positive impact.
</P>
<P>
   Tellabs shares, which have risen 97 percent this year, closed
Wednesday at 67 9/16, down 1 13/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
