<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5139 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     06-30 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE ACTION PUTS FLAG, FIRST AMENDMENT ON A COLLISION COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 4)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Shoot if you must this old gray head, but spare
your country's flag,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thus did Barbara Frietchie cry out against desecration of Old
Glory as Stonewall Jackson marched his Confederate soldiers through
Frederick, Md., a town whose residents were sharply divided in
their sympathies between North and South.
</P>
<P>
   Poet John Greenleaf Whittier recorded Jackson's response to the
elderly woman's fervent appeal:
</P>
<P>
   ```Who touches a hair of yon gray head/ Dies like a dog! March
on!' he said.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident has become a thrilling part of America's folklore
although there are serious questions about the historical accuracy
of Whittier's account.
</P>
<P>
   Like Francis Scott Key's graphic description of the Star
Spangled Banner weathering the British bombardment of Baltimore's
Fort McHenry during the War of 1812, Whittier's poetry defined for
all time the flag as a symbol of American defiance against those
who would destroy the Union.
</P>
<P>
   We have other symbols with equally powerful meanings. One of
them, the First Amendment, has stood for more than 200 years as a
firm protector of the freedom of speech, religion, the press and
the right of assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Now those two great symbols _ the flag and the First Amendment _
are on a collision course with each other.
</P>
<P>
   The substance of the conflict is whether mutilation of the flag,
which has become a practice of rebels who disapprove of actions
taken by the federal government, is an act deserving of punishment
before the law or whether it is protected by the First Amendment as
an act of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   By a 305-to-124 vote, the House has approved a constitutional
amendment which would permit Congress to draft legislation banning
desecration of the flag. Since that tally is larger than the
two-thirds vote required for approval of proposed amendments, the
measure has moved to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   If it also can muster a two-thirds vote of approval, it then
will be up to three fourths of the state legislatures to give their
assent. If that happens, legislation banning desecration of the
flag could become law.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, which has failed to muster a two-thirds vote of
approval for anti-flag-burning amendments in recent years, is
expected to vote on the issue later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Not many Americans realize this weekend, as we celebrate the
223rd anniversary of the signing of the Declaration of
Independence, that two of our most honored institutions could
conflict with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the flag nor freedom of speech is mentioned in the
Declaration of Independence, but both became symbols of American
liberty when the founding fathers were forging a republic from 13
newly freed British colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Since the flag is a visible symbol of America's struggle to
maintain its liberty and its opposition to tyranny, more Americans
probably feel protective of the Stars and Stripes than worry about
the freedoms guaranteed by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most thrilling experiences for visitors to the
Washington area is spending time at the Marine Memorial, with its
bronze figures depicting the raising of the Stars and Stripes on
Iwo Jima in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   And we are seeing more and more presidential hopefuls
surrounding themselves with billowing flags and red-white-and-blue
bunting that proclaim their love of the Star Spangled Banner.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment, however, is not a visible symbol. It is
part of our Constitution, which is our Bible of democracy, but is
not something citizens can see each day or something that excites
them to patriotic fervor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the amendment is as important as the flag.
</P>
<P>
   This is not, however, a classic clash between liberals and
conservatives. In 1989, when the Supreme Court struck down
anti-flag burning legislation as unconstitutional, two of the most
conservative justices, Antonin Scalia and Anthony Kennedy, were
part of the five-member majority.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being political conservatives, appointed to the
court by Ronald Reagan, they are advocates of what is often
described as ``strict construction'' of the Constitution and
respect for the ``original intent'' of the founding fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike such giants of the recent past as Chief Justice Earl
Warren and Associate Justices Hugo Black and William Brennan, the
conservative justices believe the court should limit itself to
interpreting the Constitution rather than expanding its precepts
into new laws.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is an old one. We who served our country in the
military in time of war have an especially warm place in our hearts
for the flag we defended. But we should remember that the First
Amendment embodies values for which we fought, including a
guarantee to the right to oppose government actions openly, angrily
and sometimes obnoxiously.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, as former Attorney General Richard Thornburgh once told
a group of us, legislation can be written to protect both the flag
and free speech. If so, we should follow that course. If not, we
should oppose efforts to weaken the First Amendment, which is basic
to the American way of life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
