<HEADLINE>
KINGS CAUTIOUS ABOUT FREE AGENCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ROGER PHILLIPS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' power play was impotent last season, rushing
defenseman Steve Duchesne is looking for a contract, and NHL
free-agency begins today.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Kings leapt at the opportunity, committing $15
million over four years to Duchesne. This year, given an identical
situation, the Kings will pass on the disappointing Duchesne,
operating under the premise that one $4.25-million buyout in a
lifetime is one too many.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Kings are expected to be extremely judicious this
year during the NHL's free-agent shopping season. They won't sign
Duchesne, and they aren't expected to pursue any unrestricted free
agent who is seeking an expensive long-term commitment.
</P>
<P>
   But then, with Colorado's Theo Fleury far and away the most
impressive talent available, the list is not nearly as tantalizing
as a year ago, when Brett Hull, Doug Gilmour, Ron Francis and
Curtis Joseph topped the slate of unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're interested in a long-term contract for an
older guy,'' Kings general manager Dave Taylor said this week. ``I
don't think we're going to be signing an older guy to a five-year
deal. Those contracts in general have not been good for the teams.
We don't have glaring weaknesses at this point but there may be a
couple of areas where we can upgrade ourselves. The biggest need
coming out of last season was to upgrade the offense, and I think
we've done that (by trading with the New York Islanders two weeks
ago for star right wing Zigmund Palffy).''
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean Taylor will be completely inactive. Taylor
said he would like to improve the Kings' skill, speed and grit on
the third and fourth lines, and if he can do so through free agency
without making a long-term commitment, he will pursue the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   One player who would fill Taylor's criteria on the ice (but
probably is seeking a lengthier, more expensive commitment than the
Kings are willing to give) is right wing Pat Verbeek of the Stanley
Cup champion Dallas Stars. Verbeek, 35, made $3.2 million this
season. Taylor was not at liberty to discuss other teams' players
for fear of tampering charges, so there was no comment on whether
the Kings would be interested in Verbeek. ``I can't say we're going
to sign any players,'' Taylor said, ``but I think we're going to
talk to agents and investigate every possibility. If there's a
chance to improve the club and it makes sense, we'll move forward.
It would have to make financial sense as well as the help it would
give us on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to upgrade our team speed and our team
skill. In the past, we've had a lot of big players and gritty
players, but they were not overly mobile. If we can add somebody
into the mix who brings skill but also adds a physical element, I
think that would be a good addition.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the unrestricted free agents, numerous restricted
free agents hit the market today, though no significant ones will
change uniforms for a very simple reason: If they sign an offer
sheet with another team, their team will be certain to match it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the prominent restricted free agents are Boston goalie
Byron Dafoe, Dallas defenseman Richard Matvichuk, Detroit winger
Darren McCarty, Edmonton winger Bill Guerin, Nashville winger
Sergei Krivokrasov, New Jersey winger Jason Arnott, New York
Rangers defenseman Mathieu Schneider, Pittsburgh defenseman Darius
Kasparaitis, Pittsburgh forward Alexei Kovalev and Vancouver winger
Markus Naslund.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor will be busy enough signing his own restricted free
agents, a list headed by right wing Glen Murray, defenseman Mattias
Norstrom, goalie Stephane Fiset and newly acquired center Brian
Smolinski, who is expected to agree to play for the same salary,
roughly $1.75 million, that he received last season from the
Islanders. Other Kings restricted free agents include forwards
Craig Johnson, Vladimir Tsyplakov, Sandy Moger and Steve McKenna.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are not expected to sign veteran unrestricted free
agents Doug Bodger, Russ Courtnall, Ray Ferraro and Dave Babych.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve goalies Manny Legace and Ryan Bach also are unrestricted
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list of some of the NHL's most prominent unrestricted
free agents, by position, with their teams, ages, last year's
salaries and statistics:
</P>
<P>
   FORWARDS
</P>
<P>
   RW Theo Fleury, Colorado (31 years old, $2.4 million, 74 games,
39-52-91); LW Dave Andreychuk, New Jersey (35, $2.5 million, 52,
15-13-28); RW Nelson Emerson, Ottawa (31, $1.3 million, 65,
13-24-37); LW Valeri Kamensky, Colorado (33, $1.9 million, 65,
14-30-44); RW Joe Murphy, San Jose (31, $3.8 million, 76,
25-23-48); RW Pat Verbeek, Dallas (35, $3.2 million, 78, 17-17-34);
C Bob Carpenter, New Jersey (35, $904,910, 56, 2-8-10), C Joe
Juneau, Buffalo (31, $2.2 million, 72, 15-28-43); RW Ray Sheppard
(33, $1.7 million, 74, 25-33-58).
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSEMEN
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Diduck, Phoenix (34, $825,000, 44, 0-2-2), Alexei
Gusarov, Colorado (34, $912,500, 53, 3-10-13); Ulf Samuelsson,
Atlanta (35, $2 million, 71, 4-8-12); Steve Duchesne, Philadelphia
(34, $3.75 million, 70, 6-22-28); Sylvain Lefebvre (31, $1.35
million, 75, 2-18-20), Mark Tinordi (33, $2.675 million, 48,
0-6-6).
</P>
<P>
   GOALIES
</P>
<P>
   Kirk McLean, Florida (33, $2.55 million, 30, 9-10-4, 2.74); Ken
Wregget, Calgary (35, $1.2 million, 27, 10-12-4, 2.53).
</P>
</TEXT>
