<HEADLINE>
BELFAST PEACE TALKS GO PAST DEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern and Northern Ireland's political
leaders talked past a midnight deadline Thursday in an effort to
break an impasse threatening the peace settlement that has promised
to end sectarian violence in the British province.
</P>
<P>
   Agreement would clear the way to achieving a critical goal of
the April 1998 accord _ the creation of a power sharing executive
for the Northern Ireland Assembly and the transfer of authority to
the new legislature from the British government.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking that path has been the refusal of Sinn Fein to promise
any disarmament by its Irish Republican Army allies before the May
2000 deadline agreed to in the original settlement; the province's
largest party, the Ulster Unionists, demands that Sinn Fein be
barred from taking up its seats in the new cabinet in the absence
of such a pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein has said it cannot deliver that result and that the
2-year-old IRA cease-fire represents a credible commitment to
nonviolence. The Ulster Unionist President David Trimble has
responded, ``No guns, no government.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal being worked on through the third day of intense talks
on Wednesday envisaged a statement by Sinn Fein of unequivocal
acceptance of the IRA's obligation to disarm by the May 2000 date
in the original settlement, in exchange for letting the party take
up its seats in the new cabinet now.
</P>
<P>
   The timetable for disarming and the monitoring of compliance
would be entrusted to the International Commission on
Decommissioning headed by John de Chastelain, a retired Canadian
general who drew up a critical report on the arrangement for
presentation to the negotiators. The first actual handover of
weapons would occur in the fall, and parties that did not live up
to the terms of disarmament could face suspension from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   But while the negotiators settled on the general shape of a
possible deal, they fought in typically hard-bitten manner over the
words to nail it in place. ``Both sides agree on what's necessary
now,'' said a spokesman for Blair. ``What the two sides need to be
persuaded of is the quality of the commitments being made.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, the head of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic
and Labor Party and a winner of the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize, said,
``It's hard for one side in this community to trust the other with
the way they've been fighting each other over the centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Adams and Trimble emerged from the talks late at night to
blame the other for producing the deadlock. But both said the peace
settlement was the best opportunity for peace in Northern Ireland
and stressed that they were still hoping for a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Signing onto a deal of these dimensions posed great risk to
Trimble since it would represent a significant climb down from his
demand for an immediate start to disarmament. It could also bring
about a challenge to his leadership from hardline members of his
party.
</P>
<P>
   Blair telephoned President Clinton Wednesday evening to brief
him on the day's progress. The president has said he was willing,
if asked, to contact individual leaders the way he did through the
end of the negotiations in April, 1998, that produced the original
agreement. Those talks ran 17 hours past their deadline.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   All the principals took note of the crucial nature of the day as
they entered the Stormont Castle Buildings. That is where they had
met during the two years it took to produce the so-called Good
Friday agreement aimed at ending three decades of sectarian
violence and where they returned this week to prevent the accord
from collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to make this D-day for the people of these
islands,'' said Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein. ``It's whether
the imperative of the majority of the people of the North and South
who voted for this agreement and whether the two governments'
commitment to the agreement is stronger than those who want to tear
it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, who is also first minister of the new Northern Ireland
Assembly, said that the ``moment of truth'' had arrived for the
republican movement that Adams heads. ``The phrase `republican
movement' means two things, a political party and a private army,''
he said. ``It must decide today which of the two things it prefers.
It cannot keep both any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The midnight deadline was set six weeks ago by Blair, who with
Ahern has been in Belfast since Monday jointly conducting the final
talks as they did 14 months ago. Back then declaring a firm
deadline for a halt to talking produced an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, new legislatures in Scotland and Wales assume their
powers, and in setting the deadline Blair hoped to mark a
historically simultaneous start-up of the Northern Ireland
Assembly. Blair was due in Edinburgh on Thursday morning to speak
at the ceremonial opening of the Scottish Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated that the hard-fought peace agreement has been
followed by 14 months of missed deadlines and stalled motion, the
two prime ministers have suggested that failure to take the next
crucial step would force them to review the whole accord.
</P>
<P>
   It would also leave a menacing vacuum in the public affairs of
the province at the outset of the tensest season in Northern
Ireland, the summer months of the Protestant parades that are
resented and protested by the minority Catholic community.
</P>
<P>
   Blair interrupted his talks Wednesday to meet with leaders of
the Protestant Orange Order to reassure them after the
government-appointed Parades Commission decided on Monday to block
their members from marching from Drumcree Church in Portadown
through the Catholic Garvaghy Road neighborhood this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In years past that march was a showdown that convulsed the
province, and dissident Protestant paramilitaries have threatened
to go on the attack now in response to Monday's ruling. Ronnie
Flanagan, chief constable of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, said on
Wednesday that his force had intelligence that there were people
determined to exploit the occasions with violence.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has flown in 1300 troops to help police, and Flanagan
warned the organizers of the parades to keep troublemakers out of
the marchers' ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who bring large numbers of others onto the street have
a responsibility to look beyond that event,'' he said, ``and if it
is predictable, as it was predictable last year, that there are
malevolent people in the wings willing to use the peaceful protest
as a cover for wreaking violence, then I believe those who would
seek to bring large numbers onto the streets have a responsibility
to take that into account.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
