<SLUG> BC-WINNING-SIBLINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIBLING ARTISTS ARE CARD-CARRYING WINNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a national art contest with 70,000 entries, what are the
chances that a brother and sister from Arlington, Texas, would be
two of the 12 winners?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really surprised,'' said Alicia Templin, 14. She and
her brother, David, 12, drew two of the birthday-card designs
singled out by judges in the contest for kids sponsored by
Hallmark. The 12 winning entries will be part of the summer lineup
of greeting cards produced by the reigning U.S. card king.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the judges thought that was pretty weird, too,'' David
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Templins, teen-agers that they are, tend to describe their
success with words such as ``weird.'' Both entered four designs in
the contest, including the two chosen pictures: Alicia's candle
bowing from a cake to its candle friends and David's floppy-eared
dog sitting atop a birthday cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one they chose was actually my favorite one, so it was
kind of weird that they chose it,'' Alicia said.
</P>
<P>
   What may be truly weird, though, is that the two kids are still
surprised by their tandem success. They have won other art contests
together. It seems that if one of them wins something, they both
win. And win they do. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   This year, both placed in a themed art competition at the
Southwestern Exposition and Livestock Show and Rodeo. They also
came in first and second in a cover design competition for the
Star-Telegram's Class Acts section for young readers. At the State
Fair of Texas last year, both won in several categories _ in the
adult division.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark's card contest is the most widespread recognition the
Templins have received. As part of their prize, the brother-sister
artists recently toured the Hallmark Cards headquarters in Kansas
City, Mo. And in August, Hallmark will send them to Easton, Penn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where Crayola headquarters are,'' Alicia said. ``I
think we're going to actually get to see how crayons are made.''
</P>
<P>
   The Templins have lived with art all their lives. Their father,
Gary Templin, is a graphic design artist; their mother, Crystal
Templin, is a computer artist. The elder Templins also run an art
school called Art Smart in their home _ ``which is why our house
looks like an art studio,'' Alicia said _ that attracts as many as
120 students during the school year.
</P>
<P>
   David and Alicia help with teaching the classes, and they both
picture art in their distant futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to do clay animation,'' David said. ``So I'm not sure,
but I may want to do that when I grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely want to do something in art,'' Alicia said. ``I
might even want to be an author and illustrator for children's
books.''
</P>
<P>
   For now though, they're just creative kids who tend to finish
each other's sentences and seem unfazed by the weirdness of their
awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got a fifth place or something like that ... . Did I
get two second places?'' Alicia said, trying to recall what she won
at the State Fair of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got two second places,'' David said. ``It was me that got
fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   Check out the Templins' artwork on their Web sites: Alicia's is
at www.polo.8m.com; David's is at www.monsters.8m.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
