<SLUG> BC-OUT-FEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE OF USER FEES UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIOUX FALLS, S.D. _ Three-fifths of the way into the emotional
tug-of-war that is the National Forest Fee Demonstration Program,
both sides of the political issue can only guess its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is language proposed to make it permanent and language
proposed to do away with it,'' U.S. Forest Service director Mike
Dombeck told reporters last week during the Outdoor Writers
Association of America's conference here.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year pilot project to raise maintenance funds by
charging access fees to National Forest visitors is scheduled to
conclude in September 2001. However, detractors think the Clinton
administration-backed proposal could be made permanent as early as
this summer. To that end, U.S. Congresswomen Lois Capps (D-Santa
Barbara) and Mary Bono (R-Palm Springs) have reintroduced their
Forest Tax Relief Act to abolish the program.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, the estimated 40 million annual visitors
to the four surrounding National Forests _ Los Padres, Angeles, San
Bernardino and Cleveland _ must pay $5 a day or $30 a year per
vehicle for an ``Adventure Pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Dombeck justified the program using what could be called ``80-80
reasoning'': 80 percent of the funds go directly to the forest
where they are collected, and 80 percent of the people surveyed by
the Forest Service and an independent polling group favor the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective is a quality of life issue. Besides,'' Dombeck
said, ``99.99 percent of the (Forest Service) land is available
free.''
</P>
<P>
   That provides little solace for the vocal minority opposing the
fee program.
</P>
<P>
   Alasdair Coyne, conservation director for Keep the Sespe Wild, a
Ventura County environmental group working to eliminate the
``Adventure Pass,'' challenged Dombeck's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lie,'' Coyne said of the forest areas users can visit
free of charge. ``They have 100 National Forest sites around the
country that are under fees of various sorts through the Fee
Demonstration Program. In Southern California, the program
encompasses four National Forests and their entire mass. So, right
there, that probably represents more than one-tenth of a percent of
public land, even if Dombeck is misinformed.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the ``quality of life issue,'' Coyne argues that
implementing National Forest user fees ``is the first step to
commercializing America's public lands, lands which belong to the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Both camps do agree the National Forests need a major financial
boost. Reports indicate the national recreation budget has not
increased this decade, forcing Forest Service officials to use
money normally earmarked for maintenance to cover rising business
expenses, including overhead and salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to get money to build new stuff, but once you build
it it's difficult to get money to maintain it,'' Dombeck explained.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the money is the point of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to address funding. We've never disputed that,'' Coyne
said. ``We have to persuade Congress to fork over more funding. It
shouldn't come out of National Forest visitors' wallets. It already
comes out of their tax dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forest Service officials estimate only $12 from every
taxpayer goes toward National Forest services, of which recreation
is but one part.
</P>
<P>
   The question then beckons: Should Americans be responsible for
paying more in taxes to support the National Forests?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of appropriating money that is already available
from tax dollars,'' Coyne answered, ``not a matter of raising
taxes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
