<SLUG> BC-MA-GUN-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BACKS RIGHT OF ATTORNEY GENERAL IN GUN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to fix garbles)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a first-in-the-nation ruling that shook the
ever-shifting legal ground on gun control, the state's highest
court ruled Wednesday that the state Attorney General has the right
to impose safety measures on gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision by the state Supreme Judicial Court paves
the way for the implementation of restrictions banning the sale of
cheap handguns and requiring safety locks and hard-to-pull
triggers.
</P>
<P>
   Though many of the regulations were bolstered by a state gun
control law enacted last year, the ruling expands the Attorney
General's independent power to impose such restrictions on guns,
which have not been held to the same consumer safety standards
imposed on other products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first court in the country to hold that an attorney
general has that power,'' said Dennis Henigan, legal counsel for
the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence in Washington. ``It is
significant nationally because many states have similar consumer
protection statutes directed at the prevention of unfair trade
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an ominous ruling for the gun industry, which has
continued to beat back gun control and safety measures in Congress
in recent weeks and in several state legislatures which have passed
laws prohibiting cities from suing the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's ruling underscored the authority of the Attorney
General to apply consumer safety laws to guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problems in this area are that this could give
encouragement to other attorneys general,'' said Robert Ricker,
executive director of the American Shooting Sports Council, the
Georgia-based gun industry trade group that sued to block
implementation of the gun safety guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``And also, it's going to complicate any attempt by the
Massachusetts state legislature to correct or streamline what was
done last year,'' Ricker said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly said the decision recognizes
the power of his office to bring common-sense safety precautions to
the sale of handguns. The safety regulations were imposed by his
predecessor, Scott Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the case itself will return to the Superior Court to work
out some of the actual details -- whether it be childproofing or
requiring that so called `junk guns' be prohibited in this state,''
Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ricker and other industry spokesmen say that they simply
have not come up with designs that could make a gun child-proof _
as the regulations would require _ or to create locks that keep a
gun out of criminal hands without limiting the owner's
accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   If upheld, the regulations could address some of the same
concerns voiced by Boston public health officials and politicians
in cities nationwide who are suing the gun industry to force design
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Welsh, Mayor Thomas M. Menino's policy and planning
director, said the city's suit against gun manufacturers would move
forward, even if tougher safety regulations are adopted because the
city wants to prevent the flow of illegal weapons from other states
with looser laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We claim there's clearly a distribution scheme to flood our
markets with guns that are cheap, easily concealable, and that
don't have safety devices on them,'' said Welsh. ``There's any
number of contiguous states in the country that have absolutely no
regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Harshbarger broke new ground in issuing consumer
protection regulations aimed at banning cheap so-called Saturday
night specials, as well as guns without traceable serial numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations also call for child-safe designs, such as
triggers too stiff for a child to pull, and for safety measures
such as an indicator showing the number of cartridges left in the
gun to reduce accidental shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're common-sense safety provisions to deal with
childproofing and trigger locks and safe guns for law-abiding
owners,'' Harshbarger said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects both the will of the legislature and the power of
the attorney general to deal with these issues in a common sense
way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, the day before the regulations were to be
phased in, the American Shooting Sports Council filed suit,
claiming that the attorney general did not have the authority to
dictate the design and manufacture of products, and that some
regulations conflicted with existing federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Suffolk Superior Court Judge Diane Kottmyer issued
a preliminary injunction blocking the implementation of the
regulations, saying that Harshbarger had overstepped his bounds.
</P>
<P>
   The SJC Wednesday overturned that injunction in a 21-page
decision that sent the case back to Superior Court for further
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Michael Crowley contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
