<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL APPROVES HOLBROOKE, BUT FLOOR VOTE STILL UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Richard Holbrooke's long-delayed nomination to be
the chief U.S. diplomat to the United Nations won the approval of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on Wednesday, but the date
of a final vote on the nomination on the Senate floor remained
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   While Holbrooke's supporters had hoped that the nomination would
be approved quickly by the full Senate, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott's office reported that a number of lawmakers were
blocking a final vote for unspecified reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One senator, Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, announced last week that
he would block the vote until the State Department resolved a
dispute _ unrelated to Holbrooke's nomination _ involving the
department's treatment of a budget analyst in the U.S. mission to
the United Nations in New York. Grassley has described the analyst
as a whistleblower.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lott said Wednesday that more senators had
decided to follow Grassley's lead and impose a so-called hold on
the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, John Czwartacki, said that unlike Grassley, the
other senators took the action anonymously, which is permitted by
Senate traditions. Rules intended to promote consensus in the
Senate permit a single Senator to block a nomination vote
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials involved with Holbrooke's
nomination, speaking on condition they not be identified, said they
were still optimistic that Holbrooke's nomination would be
confirmed shortly by the full Senate and that the veteran diplomat
could begin work at the United Nations this summer.
</P>
<P>
   They said the new delays to the nomination may simply be
bargaining chips by senators interested in promoting special
projects at the State Department or seeking other favors from the
administration. ``We don't think this is anything terribly
serious,'' said one senior official.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote by the Foreign Relations Committee had
originally been seen as the final hurdle in Holbrooke's year-long
quest for the United Nations post.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of Holbrooke, the former U.S. ambassador to
Germany and the architect of the 1995 peace agreement that ended
the war in Bosnia, was stalled for months by two federal ethics
investigations. One ended with his exoneration. The other ended
with a settlement in which he agreed to pay $5,000 to settle civil
charges that he had violated federal lobbying laws.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and supporters of Holbrooke had feared that the panel's
chairman, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., might try to kill the
nomination, as he killed other prominent Clinton administration
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   But Helms, who once said that he could not recall a nomination
``with so much ethical baggage attached to it,'' signaled in June
that he would support Holbrooke. And when it came time for the
committee to vote Wednesday, the nomination was approved along with
several others on a voice vote, with no opposition and no debate.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley has insisted that he will not lift his hold on
Holbrooke's nomination until the State Department agrees to
reinstate the budget analyst, Linda Shenwick, to her job in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Shenwick, a 20-year veteran of the State Department, is being
transferred against her wishes to Washington, an act she describes
as retaliation by the department for sharing information with
lawmakers and reporters about waste and fraud at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Grassley's colleagues said Wednesday that they were
urging him to drop his ``hold'' on Holbrooke's nomination, arguing
that it was improper to hold the nomination hostile to a civil
service dispute that should be resolved elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is irresponsible to hold up a nomination for an important
position in order to try to settle a personnel dispute,'' said Sen.
Joseph Biden of Delaware, the ranking Democrat on the Foreign
Relations Committee. ``I hope and expect Senator Grassley will
cease and desist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
