<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN MAKES CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM A TOP ISSUE  
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, N.H. _ Putting the overhaul of the campaign finance law
squarely at the center of his presidential bid, Sen. John McCain
Wednesday called on the Republican rank-and-file to rise up against
a system he branded ``an elaborate influence peddling scheme in
which both parties conspire to stay in office by selling the
country to the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same day that Texas Gov. George W. Bush said that his
campaign had raised $36.3 million, dwarfing all his rivals, McCain
portrayed himself as a fighter against the status quo and began an
effort to turn his signature issue into a rallying cry for
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told there is no room for this issue in Republican
primaries,'' McCain told several hundred people crammed into town
hall here. ``Well I intend to make room for it,'' he said, drawing
cheers, applause and whoops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will call for the reform of our political system everywhere
I go in this campaign,'' the Arizona senator said. ``I will ask my
supporters to make campaign reform their top priority, and I'll
challenge my opponents to declare their independence from the
political welfare state. Because I'm not running for president to
be someone. I'm running to do something. This is your country, my
friends and I'm running for president to give it back to you.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's effort to pass legislation to ban the unlimited
donations to political parties known as ``soft money'' and put a
tighter rein on issue advocacy advertisements has so far been
futile. It has put him sharply at odds with the Republican
congressional leadership, which staunchly supports a system that
has proved an advantage to their party. His stand has also
alienated the leaders of such powerful Republican constituency
groups as the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, the senator cast a bet that the issue could
catch fire with rank-and-file conservatives and set him apart from
the other candidates in the crowded Republican field. He accused
lawmakers of his own party of sacrificing their ideals to placate
large donors.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, in part because of his chairmanship of the Senate
Commerce Committee, has emerged as the second most well-financed
Republican candidate, raising $6.5 million, including a $2 million
transfer from his Senate campaign account.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation he is sponsoring would make no changes in how
presidential candidates raise money for the primary campaigns. It
would ban ``soft money'' _ the unlimited, and unregulated,
donations the political parties take to get around the limits that
the law sets on donations to candidates and parties for federal
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his years in Congress, McCain is trying to position
himself as a challenger to status quo politics. Hanging from the
front of town hall on Wednesday was a picture of him as a rakish
young Navy pilot before he was shot down in Vietnam and held as a
prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
   He portrayed his struggle to cut down the money in politics as
another test of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it were true that Americans don't care about campaign
finance reform _ and I don't for one moment believe it is,'' McCain
said, ``I would not give up this fight. I would rather not be
president than win that high office on false pretenses. How could I
ask Americans to enlist in the fight against national cynicism
while I support the underlying cause of the public's disgust with
politics?''
</P>
<P>
   Several times, McCain emphasized that he was a conservative. He
called on Republicans to support his bill and show that ``you still
believe in the cause Ronald Reagan fought for, the cause you
elected a Republican Congress to serve, the cause of less
government and more freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   To make the issue seem more concrete to voters, he charged that
during the writing of the 1996 Telecommunications Act, ``every
company affected by the legislation had purchased a seat at the
table with soft money.'' As a result, he said, the lower prices
promised by competition did not materialize.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Republican-controlled Congress had increased the
number of special interest provisions inserted into spending bills.
He also scored Congress for wasting billions of dollars on unneeded
weapons systems. And on tax policy, he said, the failure to make
larger tax cuts or to reshape the tax code was the result of tax
breaks for special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine the promises we could keep and the good we could do if
politicians stopped treating the federal Treasury as a duty-free
shop for soft-money donors,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did not spare President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore, whose aggressive fund-raising practices in 1996 provoked
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans care very much that the Lincoln bedroom has
become a Motel 6 where the president of the United States serves as
bellhop,'' McCain said. Referring to Gore's attendance at a
fund-raiser in a Buddhist temple he added, ``Most Americans care
very much when monks and nuns abandon their vows of poverty and pay
tens of thousands of dollars to have communion with the vice
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign finance legislation that McCain sponsors with Sen.
Russell Feingold, D-Wis., died in a Senate filibuster last year.
Its House sponsors had hoped to pass it before Memorial Day to put
pressure on the Senate. But Speaker Dennis Hastert put the issue
off until September. McCain on Wednesday signaled that he would now
try to bring the issue to the Senate floor next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
