<HEADER>
A5155 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SCURRY-LADN     06-30 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SCURRY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCURRY BRACES FOR CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the United States wins the Women's World Cup at the Rose
Bowl, goalkeeper Briana Scurry promises not to run naked down
Colorado Boulevard in Pasadena, as she did in Athens, Ga., after
the U.S. won the Olympic gold medal in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Scurry's previous streaking experience happened only
because a reporter caught her off guard early one morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Illustrated called me at, like, eight in the morning
one day when I was half-asleep and asked me what I would do if we
won,'' said Scurry. ``I didn't want to be like everybody else, so I
said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey Briana, when have you ever been like everyone else?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' she said, laughing. ``Goalkeepers are different. I'm
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Scurry and her U.S. teammates face Germany in the
quarterfinals of the 1999 Women's World Cup at Jack Kent Cooke
Stadium in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Scurry, a master of making her job look easy, has compiled a
75-8-5 record in five years as the Americans' top keeper, recording
51 shutouts. That causes some to wonder if she gets bored with the
U.S. attacking so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'm like, `OK, do something,' '' admitted the
27-year-old. ``Come at me with a ball -- anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Scurry said she doesn't mind the inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have nothing to do, that means everyone's doing their
job,'' she said. ``I can sit back and watch all day; that's fine
with me. You know, I'm not back there smoking cigarettes like
people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry is able to laugh about it, but she realizes her days of
spectating from afar are behind her. After giving up one goal in
three previous Women's World Cup Group A qualifying matches, the
U.S. faces a tougher task in defeating Germany to avoid
elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Looming in the future is perhaps a date with Brazil on Sunday
and either China or Norway in the July 10 final at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is going to need me in this tournament,'' said
Scurry. ``Teams are going to get to us a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't have a lot to do when we're playing (at this
stage), I'm surprised. I know it's going to be big-time games; I
know I'm going to be battling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more one-on-ones, a lot more breakways, a lot
more players going right at me. I'm going to need to be at my
best.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Tony DiCicco admits he has to get Scurry more
involved, even when the game is in the opponents' end of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hasn't had to venture too far from her goal line,''
DiCicco said. ``We're asking her to expand her influence into the
entire penalty area, and in some cases beyond. We don't need a
(Jorge) Campos, but we do need her to cover more ground back there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Briana is key for us and we need her to be at her best.''
</P>
<P>
   Soaking up the atmosphere off the field, Scurry enjoys being in
the spotlight. She's relishing her role as one of the only
African-Americans on the team. Fellow goalkeeper Saskia Webber is
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Scurry was born in Texas, attended grade school in Minneapolis,
then started her high school soccer career in Dayton, Ohio, where
she was one of six African-Americans in a student body of 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in white suburbia,'' she says. ``But I never had any
doors closed to me growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she's hoping to open the doors for other African-Americans,
few of whom play soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been one of the only mainstays on this team the last five
years, so it's definitely something people notice,'' said Scurry of
being African-American. ``In all the articles you read, it's
mentioned. But I want to embrace that role. I want to be a role
model. I want to do well for my community to show we can excel at
any sport, even if it's a sport that very few African-Americans
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll start a windfall of activity for soccer in the
inner city. All I want to say to African-Americans is give this
sport a try.''
</P>
<P>
   She did just that, giving up her first love, basketball, to give
soccer a shot in high school. And while most U.S. National team
players earn their invitations through U.S. youth or club programs,
Scurry turned a brilliant high school career into a scholarship at
Massachusetts. It was there she blossomed, finishing her career
with a 0.56 goals-against-average to impress DiCicco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the fact I sort of made it through the back
door,'' said Scurry. ``I wasn't in the circles of known players. I
was a small town girl from Minnesota. I just kept playing and
hoping and performed to the best of my ability. I'm a true
depiction of that kid who fought her way to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Since there was more pavement than grass growing up, Scurry was
a heck of a basketball player, but she chose soccer because she was
better on a national level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold five or six basketball records at my high school,''
said Scurry. ``My mom keeps telling me to try the WNBA.''
</P>
<P>
   So what would have happened if she had chosen basketball?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be in the WNBA, there's no doubt. I would have been a
power forward and I had a good vertical (jump) to guard centers.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry hasn't ruled out a WNBA career after soccer, but first
things first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to win this thing,'' Scurry said of the World
Cup. ``It's here, we're ready, now it's just a matter of getting it
done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
