r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NICKELODEON-DIVERSITY     06-30 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICKELODEON-DIVERSITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERSITY RULES IN NICK PROGRAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Cosby is playing with Gak, hiding a chocolate golf ball in
the gooey mess on talk-show host Rosie O'Donnell's desk and talking
about his new animated series, ``Little Bill.'' Based on Cosby's
books of the same name, the series is being developed by
Nickelodeon's new New York-based digital animation studio, with
plans to begin airing it in late October.
</P>
<P>
   Cosby talks affectionately about the character he has created,
saying he ``thinks a lot. He wants to know, but he doesn't know.''
Cosby says that he went to other ``network people'' with his
project before he found a home for it with Nick Jr., the
Nickelodeon network's preschool programming block. ``The Nick Jr.
people are absolutely wonderful about this fellow,'' Cosby says.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful, indeed. With the addition of ``Little Bill'' to the
network's lineup, Nickelodeon executives are out to show once again
that good, risk-taking television can mean a healthy bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Since the network debuted _ and especially in the past decade _
Nickelodeon executives have broken the traditional rules of
children's programming, rewriting the formulas for success by
putting girls in starring roles and creating a kind of colorblind
TV wonderland populated by characters of diverse colors and
cultures. Kids are black, white _ sometimes even blue. It's a
world, execs say, where every kid, like ``Little Bill,'' fits in.
</P>
<P>
   It's apparent that the philosophy has worked as a programming
strategy. Nick is the 900-pound gorilla of children's television,
controlling 56 percent of viewers ages 2 to 11 who watch children's
programming. It's a billion-dollar multimedia business taking in
more than half of all advertising dollars spent on kids' TV.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for its success is that Nick has just one
demographic: Kids. Nick has to be adventurous to keep the rugrats
tuned in and interested.
</P>
<P>
   Nick also has the additional benefit of selling blocks of time
during the day, rather than individual shows, to advertisers. New
programs don't need instant advertiser support. As one exec says,
``by letting something live in Nick Jr. for a while, we don't have
to worry about getting the big rating right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Those explanations may seem reason enough to justify
cutting-edge editorial content, but the folks at Nick say it's more
than that. They say the risk-taking comes from a deep conviction
that shows need to be ``authentic.'' They say it's less about
taking calculated, demographic-pleasing risks than it is about
telling great stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is to connect kids to kids and to their world
through entertainment,'' says Cyma Zarghami, vice president and
general manager for the network. ``We have to reflect kids' world
both in the way things look and in the stories we tell. That could
mean anything from a single-parent home to a diverse mix of
characters in any situation.''
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledges that Nick execs pay attention to statistics and
research about who kids are and what they're doing, but adds that
Nick's growth in creating programming that reflects diversity has
been ``much more organic.''
</P>
<P>
   History seems to bear out her assertions. Take the 1994 launch
of ``Gullah Gullah Island,'' for example.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Johnson, senior vice president of Nick Jr., says that Nick
bigwigs were looking at the effect a show like ``Barney'' had with
its music, and were simply looking for an authentic musical family
to star in the network's preschool show when they came across Ron
and Natalie Daise in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   It was the character of the couple that made them right for
Nick, Johnson says, rather than a desire to create the first
preschool program to revolve around an African-American family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron did a lot of the taking care of their son. He was a manly
man doing family-oriented things,'' Johnson says. Nick decided to
locate the show in Buford, S.C., where the Daises live and where
Ron is a historian of Gullah, a culture descended from West Africa
that is indigenous to the Sea Islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not just going into the project to show color. We were
putting color and culture together in a way that made it feel more
exciting and genuine,'' Zarghami says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mystery Files of Shelby Woo,'' a show launched in 1996
starring Irene Ng (''The Joy Luck Club,/) had the same ``organic''
development.
</P>
<P>
   The show, says Zarghami, was originally titled ``The Mystery
Files of Shelby Wink.'' When directors decided to recast the lead,
they found Ng and decided to change the show's concept to reflect
her East Asian culture.
</P>
<P>
   Nick's edgy content got its biggest boost about five years ago
when a partnership was formed between Nick and Tollin/Robbins
Productions. Programming executive Albie Hecht turned to Mike
Tollin and Brian Robbins, the former star of ``Head of the
Class,''to create a sketch comedy show for kids. The result was
``All That,'' a show featuring ethnically diverse cast members, an
ultracool theme song by TLC and live performances by hip-hop bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the Nickelodeon landscape was pretty white bread
at the time,'' Robbins says. ``We wanted to make a very urban
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins found Nickelodeon execs simpatico with his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the places I've worked,'' Robbins says, ``Nick is the
most free place to sort of develop and grow a show without all the
nerves and panic you get in other places.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All That's'' success led to other Tollin/Robbins pitches,
which led to successful projects including the spinoff show,
``Kenan &AMP; Kel,'' the spinoff film, ``Good Burger,'' and last year's
``Cousin Skeeter,'' all of which have brought more viewers _ and
money _ to the network.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Zarghami insists that the bottom line is good stories.
``The thing about those characters in `All That' is that they tell
great kids stories. As long as we continue to tell great kids
stories, we'll continue to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   She says this is exactly what brought Cosby to the network.
</P>
<P>
   Zarghami was in the meeting with Cosby when he pitched ``Little
Bill.'' Cosby talked for a long time about his books and what he
wanted to do with the TV series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wanted to tell his stories,'' Zarghami says. ``And
when he got here, he realized we were the people who would bring
his stories to life.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
