<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART VALVE DEFECT LESS PREVALENT THAN PREVIOUSLY THOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than two decades, the major medical journals have been
filled with reports of the high incidence and devastating
complications of a heart condition called mitral valve prolapse. It
was called the most common heart defect in young people and the
most common heart-valve disease among people of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 14 million to 28 million Americans were believed to
have the condition. And scientists, physicians and journals warned
that it could lead to a number of serious illnesses, including
heart failure, stroke, reduced blood flow and infection of the
heart. Patients were advised to monitor their condition, see their
doctors regularly and to be sure to take antibiotics before any
minor surgery or visits to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out that most of the people who thought they had
the heart condition _ and lived in constant fear of its
consequences _ did not.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers reported Thursday in The New England Journal of
Medicine that only about 2 percent of the population _ rather than
the 5 percent to 15 percent (and in some cases the estimates were
much higher) _ were found to have the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the study showed that even among people who do have
it, occurrences of most of the serious complications said to have
resulted from the condition are no higher than they are among those
who do not.
</P>
<P>
   Mitral valve prolapse is a condition in which a valve that
allows blood to flow from the upper left chamber of the heart to
the lower chamber is abnormally long and floppy. In some patients,
mitral valve prolapse may cause the blood in one chamber, the left
ventricle, to leak backward into the upper left, the atrium. This
can upset the rhythm of the heart, overwork and weaken the heart or
cause it to become infected.
</P>
<P>
   Patients who have the condition described symptoms like
shortness of breath, chest pains and palpitations. But these
symptoms can have other causes as well _ anxiety or fatigue, for
example _ and do no necessarily indicate a heart-valve malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this study we may have tempered the notion that mitral
valve prolapse is the most common cardiac valvular abnormality in
industrialized countries,'' said Dr. Lisa A. Freed, the lead author
of the report.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The diagnoses of prolapse cases increased sharply in the late
1970s and early '80s as new ultrasound technology enabled
physicians to examine hearts easily and noninvasively.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Dr. Emelia Benjamin, the senior investigator, the
earlier studies had been done with a form of echocardiography
called M-mode technology that often resulted in overdiagnosis. The
new research made use of technical refinements designed to
minimized the false results.
</P>
<P>
   In the 3,491 participants whose hearts were observed, the
examiners found only 84, or 2.4 percent, with mitral valve
prolapse. And among those 84, the rates of resultant medical
complications were no higher than those in the general population.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found previous estimates were incorrect in
suggesting that the heart condition occurs more commonly in women
than men; incidence was found to be the same in men and women, the
authors said. A companion study in the journal found that the
condition is not more common in people under 45 years old who had
suffered strokes or ministrokes, contradicting conclusions from
previous research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very compelling information,'' said Dr. Claude
Lenfant, director of the Heart, Lung and Blood Institute. ``It
means that people who have been diagnosed with mitral value
prolapse should consult with their physician to discuss their
health status.'' He said that further studies should be done to
corroborate the findings and achieve a fuller understanding of the
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, some patients' conditions were worsened by
misdiagnoses and a failure to detect the true cause of their
symptoms, though this question has not been studied, Dr. Freed
said. She added that patients diagnosed as having the valve
condition were most commonly treated with antibiotics to ward off
infection that might be caused by the leaking of blood from one
chamber back into another.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do have the condition, this remains the primary
treatment: It is when the leaking becomes severe and results in
infection that serious complications can occur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
