<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OK'S GOP-BACKED ABORTION MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When George W. Bush faced the abortion question, he
answered in non-committal terms, saying it would not be a litmus
test for a running mate. Elizabeth Dole was equally subdued, saying
abortion is low on her list of legislative priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort by Republican presidential candidates to distance
themselves from the fiery abortion debate faced its first serious
challenge Wednesday _ not from political opponents but from the
House of Representatives, where a Republican-backed measure to
limit abortion rights for minors was overwhelmingly approved.
</P>
<P>
   And in the coming months, as the legislation heads to the Senate
and other bills are introduced, Republican candidates might find
they are doing an impossible balancing act: being antiabortion and
non-controversial at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the issue that won't go away,'' said Gary Bauer, a GOP
presidential candidate who has made ``family values,'' and abortion
in particular, a central campaign theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the fact that the issue is on the Hill means it's fodder
for reporters' questions,'' agreed Stuart Rothenberg, a political
analyst. ``I think Bush and Dole have made it pretty clear they
don't want to get bogged down talking about these more inflammatory
questions. But they are going to have to respond to it whether they
like it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill approved Wednesday would make it illegal for an
adult to help a pregnant teenager dodge her state's parental
consent laws by going to another state for an abortion. A pregnant
minor in Massachusetts, for example, could no longer evade the
state's abortion requirements _ that one parent give consent or a
judge grant special permission _ by having an adult drive her to
Vermont, where parent consent laws don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, any adult other than the girl's parents or
guardians who took her across state borders for that purpose could
be charged with a federal misdemeanor. The maximum penalty would be
a year in jail and $100,000 in fines, plus parents whose daughters
had abortions could file a civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation passed 270-159, with 206 Republicans and 64
Democrats in favor, but it fell 12 votes short of being safe from
the veto threatened by the Clinton administration. Two members of
the Massachusetts delegation, Representatives J. Joseph Moakley of
South Boston and Richard E. Neal of Springfield, voted for the bill
that also passed in the House last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not right to love some abstract devotion to abortion
rights more than the safety and security of that child and the
honor of the parents,'' said House Majority Leader Richard Armey of
Texas. House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, also from Texas, said about
taking a girl to another state for an abortion without her parents'
permission: ``This is criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Such strong terms on abortion have to date been excluded from
the mainstream Republican presidential campaign. Bush, the
front-runner with vast amounts of campaign cash, seems unharmed by
accusations from the conservative wing of the party that he does
not oppose abortion enough. Asked earlier this year whether
opposing abortion would be a requirement for his vice presidential
running mate, Bush's response was downright bland: ``I rule nothing
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush might not escape so easily as the Republican-controlled
Congress continues to thrust hot-button social issues into
limelight. So far this year the House has addressed putting prayer
in schools and legislating a national day of ``solemn prayer,
fasting and humiliation before God.'' The same may be true for
Dole, as well as another GOP candidate, Representative John Kasich
of Ohio, who according to a spokesman is ``pro-life but feels that
the debte has become too boisterous, too divisive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, for one, is nearly building his campaign around holding
other candidates accountable for their stances on abortion. A
spokeswoman for Senator Bob Smith said his presidential campaign
has every intention to ``keep talking about abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the other candidates _ Buchanan, Keyes, Bauer _
already have talked about abortion,'' Karen Hickey said, referring
to Patrick J. Buchanan and Alan Keyes. ``I don't think anyone
fighting for the Republican platform can avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress seems poised to keep raising the issue. The issue of
what opponents call partial-birth abortion is likely to come up for
debate later this year. The bill that passed Wednesday now goes to
the Senate, where similar legislation died last year. But Democrats
expect the measure to pass this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the White House vetoes the legislation called the
``child custody protection act,'' the ramifications could be felt
among the Republican presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Bush's perspective, there is nothing he can do,'' said
political analyst Rothenberg. ``They're setting the agenda up there
on Capitol Hill, and he has to react to it on the tarmac. ... So
far, he's been able to pull it off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
