<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-CHINA-NUKE-NYT &LR;      06-30 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERGER ANSWERS COMMITTEE'S QUESTIONS ABOUT SECURITY IN NUCLEAR
WEAPONS LABS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Mich.) (rk) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's national security adviser,
Sandy Berger, made an unusual closed-door appearance Wednesday
afternoon before a Senate committee to answer questions about how
the White House has handled the allegations of nuclear espionage by
China.
</P>
<P>
   One official who attended the meeting, before the Select
Committee on Intelligence, said that Berger repeated previous
accounts of how he first learned about the issue in April 1996 and
first informed Clinton in July 1997, after receiving a more
detailed briefing.
</P>
<P>
   The session was polite, but had some tart moments, according to
the official.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators wondered why Berger was not more concerned after
the 1996 briefing, the official said, with one senator noting that
Berger thought the 1996 briefing was important enough to be relayed
promptly to Congress but not serious enough to tell the president.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, the Department of Energy told Berger that China had
likely stolen design information about America's most sophisticated
nuclear weapon, the miniaturized W-88 warhead.
</P>
<P>
   Berger backed Energy Department efforts to improve security in
1996, but he told the senators he did not interpret the briefing
with the same degree of urgency that some others have, the official
said. In news interviews, Berger has said the briefing was general
and preliminary, while other participants have said it was more
specific. The senators had copies of the slides used as part of the
briefing, but White House aides have said there is no formal
transcript of the session.
</P>
<P>
   This month, a presidential intelligence advisory board said
Berger's briefing in 1996 was not detailed enough to trigger a
broad presidential directive to tighten security at the nation's
weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1997 briefing did prompt Clinton to issue such a
directive in February 1998, though the advisory board found ``it
should have been handled with more dispatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the Senate committee and of the advisory board
have said they are concerned about the lack of adequate records at
the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Berger has had to change his account of when Clinton was first
informed about the espionage, a revision White House aides say
resulted from there being no record of Berger's 1997 discussion
with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., who chairs the intelligence
committee said in an interview after Berger's appearance: ``I
thought we had a good meeting, but I think the fact remains that a
lot of these issues were handled at the NSC in a sloppy, if not
inept, way.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to discuss what transpired at the meeting, which was
technically not a hearing. Normally, aides to the president do not
testify before congressional committees. Presidents typically cloak
their deliberations with aides under the doctrine of executive
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Berger, P.J. Crowley, said: ``It was a good,
constructive meeting and Mr. Berger used the opportunity to explain
to members how the administration took appropriate actions in 1996
and 1997 to address a serious problem of lab security and
counterintelligence in a very serious way.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said, ``Mr. Berger clearly and
effectively responded to the questions as to what actions he took
in 1996.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
