<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUBBELL-STARR-680&AMP;ADD     06-30 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUBBELL-STARR-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR ACCEPTS NEW GUILTY PLEAS BY HUBBELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, on
Wednesday formally declared an end to the Arkansas phase of his
wide-ranging investigation as he accepted two new guilty pleas from
Webster Hubbell, once the No. 3 official in the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell, a longtime Arkansas friend of the Clintons, pleaded
guilty to a felony count that accused him of concealing from
investigators legal work that he and Hillary Rodham Clinton did in
connection with a complex Arkansas land deal that investigators
said was a sham transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Although Starr and Hubbell, whom he had indicted three times,
improbably shook hands warmly inside the courtroom on Wednesday,
they fell to bickering outside in separate news conferences as to
what the guilty plea meant, differing over whether it involved Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Although the count to which he pleaded guilty included
references to Mrs. Clinton's legal work while she was a lawyer in
Arkansas, Hubbell asserted that he did not admit to that part of
the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters that it was ``absolutely not true'' that he
pleaded guilty to lying to regulators to cover up Mrs. Clinton's
involvement, and only admitted concealing a separate matter from
regulators. ``Mrs. Clinton did nothing wrong in connection with
that or any other transaction,'' Hubbell said.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr, following Hubbell to a bank of microphones in front
of the courthouse, said Hubbell pleaded guilty to the entire felony
count, including the section that referred explicitly to Mrs.
Clinton and her work on the land deal.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell also pleaded guilty to one misdemeanor count from a
separate indictment charging that he failed to pay federal income
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Judge James Robertson accepted a recommendation from Starr's
office that Hubbell, a second-time offender, serve no jail time. He
has already served 18 months in jail for defrauding his partners in
the Arkansas law firm where he once worked with Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell will only have to pay a $100 mandatory special
assessment fee on the charge of deceiving regulators, and $25 on
the tax charge. The court did not order him to make restitution of
the $820,000 he is said to owe in back taxes, but he is expected to
face a civil enforcement action from the Internal Revenue Service
on that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who has spent more than five years investigating the
Clintons and their associates, told the court that he welcomed the
plea agreement largely because he has decided it would be in the
public interest to bring the work of his office to an end soon. He
said this was especially important in light of the fact that
Congress has decided to let the independent counsel statute lapse
at midnight on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   More surprisingly, Starr said he was uncertain that he would get
a jury to convict Hubbell. The last two cases Starr's office
prosecuted ended in mistrials as jurors could not agree on a
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent experience has indicated to us that it is
extraordinarily difficult to identify and find jurors who are able
to set aside totally their understandings and preconceptions, and
the like,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   He also told reporters he had two avenues of investigation open
and an obligation to write a final report about his wide-ranging
inquiry, which began with an Arkansas land deal known as Whitewater
and eventually included President Clinton's intimate relationship
with Monica Lewinsky. Last December, the president was impeached by
the House of Representatives on the basis of a referral made by
Starr about the Lewinsky matter, but he was acquitted by the Senate
on Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Starr declined to discuss the two remaining investigations. But
lawyers involved in the cases have said they center on whether Mrs.
Clinton was truthful in denying a role in dismissing employees from
the White House travel office, and the behavior of Nathan Landow, a
Democratic fund-raiser from Maryland, in Starr's investigation of
allegations that Clinton had groped a White House volunteer,
Kathleen E. Willey, in the Oval Office.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The disagreement as to precisely what Hubbell was admitting
guilt about has to do with the wording of the plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In court on Wednesday, Robertson asked Hubbell if he pleaded
guilty to Count 1 of the indictment, and he responded, ``I do.''
Count 1 refers explicitly to Hubbell's concealment of work done by
himself and ``the 1985-86 billing partner,'' which was Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The written plea agreement says that ``defendant Webster L.
Hubbell agrees to plead guilty to Count 1'' of the indictment. But
it goes on to say that he will admit that he failed to disclose to
federal banking regulators that his law firm represented someone
who was linked to a business that the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. was investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell contended that he confessed only to that transgression
and not to the remaining parts of Count 1. Starr responded that it
would be unusual to have a defendant admit to each element of a
count. In fact, Count 1 is 89 paragraphs long.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela H. Bucy, a former federal prosecutor who now teaches law
at the University of Alabama, said it was routine to have a
defendant ``allocute'' or specify only a portion of what he is
pleading guilty to. ``Both sides are being pretty clever here,''
she said. ``The way the plea agreement is crafted they can both
claim victory for their point of view.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
