<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-COCAINE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 arrested in biggest drug bust at Atlanta airport in 5 years
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two people toting small carry-on bags walked into the
waiting arms of federal drug agents at Atlanta's Hartsfield
International Airport, nabbed in the largest cocaine bust there in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Clement, 48, and Jamilla Jones, 25, were arrested Tuesday
as they stepped off a flight from St. Thomas carrying 66 pounds of
the drug, said John Andrejko, special agent in charge of the
Atlanta office of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Clement and Jones face federal charges of conspiracy to
distribute cocaine, possession with intent to distribute cocaine
and importation of controlled substances into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The pair, believed to be drug couriers, had stashed the cocaine
in the luggage, the zippers glued shut, Andrejko said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very unique way of transporting the drug because you
could not open the bag. You had to cut it open,'' he said. ``The
drug was packaged in 1- and 2-kilo quantities. It was the largest
cocaine bust since 1994 at the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   But federal agents fear the quantity confiscated could be a
portent of larger drug shipments expected to come in through
Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the airport has been jockeying to provide more
direct flights from Atlanta to the Caribbean and Latin America,
said airport spokesman Miguel Southwell. Hartsfield last year added
direct service to six Latin American countries and expanded its
frequency of flights to Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the airport more attractive as a shipping point for
drug traffickers, Andrejko said.
</P>
<P>
   The shipment confiscated Wednesday was headed for North
Carolina, Andrejko said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though drug traffickers haven't abandoned the Mexican
border-southwest U.S. connections, the Caribbean and Latin America
as shipping points started gaining popularity in the last year and
a half,'' Andrejko said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
