<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FUNDRAISING-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BREAKS FUND-RAISING RECORDS, CREATING HUGE OBSTACLE TO
CHALLENGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON, MCCAIN, GORE-EVERGLADES) 
(rm) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ George W. Bush announced Wednesday that his
campaign has amassed $36.3 million in four months, smashing all
records in presidential politics and assuring that he will have the
resources to dominate, if not overwhelm, the Republican field
throughout the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   The amount is so enormous _ more than any other candidate has
ever collected over an 18-month primary season _ that some
Republican strategists predict it will force other candidates to
bow out long before the first votes are cast early next year. A
huge treasury also makes it virtually certain that Bush will forgo
federal matching subsidies and the spending limits that accompany
them. That would mean that his campaign could far exceed the
ceilings of nearly $50 million in the primary season and not worry
about specific spending caps in pivotal battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's Republican opponents, while admittedly daunted by his
fund-raising prowess, accused his campaign of trying to steamroller
them through a system that some described as flawed _ or even
corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, in a speech in New Hampshire on
Wednesday, vowed to make campaign reform a central issue in his
quest for the Republican nomination. Again and again, he said, he
will campaign against what he declared was ``an elaborate
influence-peddling scheme in which both parties conspire to stay in
office by selling the country to the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher who is the
only other candidate who plans to forfeit public subsidies, found
fault with the Bush money machine. ``What George Bush has proven
today is not that he can raise money, but that he is inextricably
tied to Washington lobbyists and special interests,'' said William
Dal Col, Forbes' campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush numbers came one day after several newspapers,
including The New York Times, reported in articles about fund
raising by various campaigns that the Bush campaign would take in
more than $20 million, which still would have been a record.
Campaign officials insisted that they did not put out misleading
figures, saying they did not want to be accused of toying with
expectations. ``We did not want to mislead anybody,'' said Karen
Hughes, the campaign's communications director, explaining that she
and her colleagues told reporters only that ``we've exceeded our
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The previous record was set by Bob Dole, the Republican nominee
in 1996, who collected $31.3 million over an 18-month period. Even
as an incumbent, President Clinton that year took in $29 million in
the entire primary period. By this time in 1995, Clinton had taken
in $19.5 million; Dole had raised $13.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am humbled by the response,'' Bush said at a news conference
in Los Angeles before he traveled to Sacramento to raise still more
money at a lunch and to San Francisco Wednesday night for a
fund-raising dinner. ``I am, as you can imagine, amazed at the
outpouring of support. This is a campaign that has got a wide range
of people that are willing to help.'' He added, ``People are hungry
for something and I am gratified.''
</P>
<P>
   Marla Romash, deputy chair of Vice President Al Gore's campaign,
insisted that her candidate did not need so much money to compete.
She said Gore, who has collected only half as much as Bush, will
adhere to federal spending limits. And she predicted that the Bush
campaign would ``probably raise and spend somewhere near $70
million.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're seeing a lot of people writing a blank check to
a blank slate,'' Ms. Romash said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Bush addressed another sell-out crowd of
roughly 800 people at the Westin St. Francis Hotel in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   While his advisers have said privately for weeks that he would
not need federal money, Bush came the closest thus far to
acknowledging that. ``I will make a decision on that in mid-July,''
he said, adding, with a smile, ``I think this helps make the
decision easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the burden of a spending ceiling, Bush can continue
soliciting huge amounts of money throughout the primary season. The
only candidates who have refused federal money in the past have
been Forbes, Ross Perot and former Gov. John Connally of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Yet it should be a cautionary tale for Bush that Connally, who
was widely viewed as a formidable contender in the 1980 Republican
primaries, ended up capturing only one delegate _ at a cost of $13
million.
</P>
<P>
   Don Evans, a Texas oilman who is Bush's national finance chair,
said he had no idea how much the governor would ultimately raise.
``There's an unprecedented amount out there,'' he said. Evans said
he did not have breakdowns of how much the campaign raised in each
state.
</P>
<P>
   The actual report that covers the second quarter of the year
does not have to be filed with the Federal Election Commission
until July 15. But Evans said donations were received from more
than 75,000 individuals in every state, with an average
contribution of $480. He said 70 percent of the contributors were
from outside Bush's home state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The only other candidate who will be able to compete financially
with Bush is Forbes, who has vowed to be competitive with Bush.
They are the only two Republicans who will have the money to buy
extensive television advertising in this expensive _ yet vitally
important _ state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proved to be such an able fund-raiser that he has piled
up nearly twice as much as the 11 other Republican contenders
combined. They have raised, collectively, about $20 million thus
far, not including transfers from their existing campaign
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But even the fund-raising figures do not tell the full story of
how Bush is in an enviable position financially. While figures were
not available, the Bush campaign has been rather careful in not
spending money too early. Other campaigns are already having
trouble making ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Bush had no apologies for his success in
a system that critics say has become corrupt. ``People are going to
have to develop a level of trust with anyone who seeks public
office,'' he said. ``That is really what leadership is all about.
If people think that a candidate is going to be corrupted by a
$1,000 contribution they should not vote for that person.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stayed clear of endorsing some of the changes in the law
put forth by McCain. Yet the governor said he would advocate some
reforms. He called for ``instant disclosure on the Internet'' of
contributions. He said the $1,000 limit that an individual can give
to a presidential campaign _ a figure that has not changed since
laws enacted after Watergate more than two decades ago _ should be
raised.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush opposes elimination of political action committees or
of unregulated soft money donations, he said he would favor banning
what he described an ``involuntary contribution'' to federal races.
That would be when a worker from a corporation or labor union is
forced to give money but does not know where it will end up. ``I
believe that the soft money accounts given by corporate America
where there is no active participation by the stakeholder would be
a good reform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The financial outpouring for Bush has been apparent on his
debut, three-day campaign swing up and down California this week.
At one fund-raiser after another, he was welcomed by large, excited
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Bush held a dinner at the Century Plaza Hotel
in Los Angeles, for years a must-stop on the political fund-raising
circuit. But Brad Freeman, Bush's finance chairman in the state,
told the crowd, ``There have never been more people seated in this
room. We've added eight tables to the stage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
