<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Thursday, July
1, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   GORTON (Washington) _ At age 71, Slade Gorton would be retired
from many jobs in the outside world. But in the Senate, where
septuagenarians could form their own caucus, Gorton is young enough
to be the son of one of his colleagues, Strom Thurmond. As Gorton
gears up to run for fourth term -- at the end of which he would be
79 -- he is bracing for the inevitable questions about his age and
fitness. Gorton is making sure he isn't vulnerable on that score.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' and ``w''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   SEC-MICROSOFT (Seattle) _ Microsoft chief financial officer Greg
Maffei said Wednesday the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission
is investigating the software giant's accounting policies for
setting aside reserves covering such things as returned software
and undelivered upgrades. In a conference call with analysts and
reporters, Maffei said the company is ``cooperating fully'' with
the investigation and expects it to have no impact on its business
and financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Richman. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BANK-SETTLEMENT (Seattle)_ US Bankcorp settles suit with State
of Minnesota that alleged the bank was illegally selling customer
information to telemarketers. Minnesota AG says settlement made
sense after bank said it would no longer disclose customer
information to third parties for purposes of marketing
non-financial products.
</P>
<P>
   By Jane Hadley. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE-CAMP (Seattle) _ Speak Swahili in two weeks? Kids ages
6 to 9 will attempt to do just that at the World Language Summer
Camp, which offers total immersion in eight languages, including
Russian, Arabic and Korean. The camp, a precursor to the John
Stanford International School, has 250 students in two, two-week
sessions. The only cost is $15 for materials. No wonder more than
1,000 families bid for a slot.
</P>
<P>
   By Cecelia Goodnow. (Story will move in the ``a'' and ``l''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   LONGSHORE-WORKERS (Seattle) _ West Coast ports could be shut
down after 5 p.m. Thursday, the expiration of the contract between
the International Longshore and Warehouse Union and the Pacific
Maritime Association.
</P>
