<HEADER>
A5188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-EVERGLADES-NYT     06-30 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-EVERGLADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE TO PRESENT $7.8 BILLION PLAN FOR EVERGLADES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of negotiations among
environmentalists, farmers and thirsty Florida cities, the Clinton
administration will formally present a plan on Thursday to redirect
billions of gallons of water a day into the Everglades in what
supporters say is the largest effort at environmental restoration
in history.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for spending $7.8 billion over 20 years, half the
money coming from Florida and half from the federal government,
largely to undo a 1,700-mile network of canals and levees built
from the late 1940s to the early '70s to prevent floods and provide
water and land for homes and farms.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers say the system, which flushes out to sea water
that used to meander through the Everglades, has cut the population
of wading birds by more than 90 percent, hurt marine fisheries and
coral reefs by reducing the salt content near shore, and threatened
what is left of the Everglades itself, a vast ecosystem that has no
parallel in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're talking about here is restoring the nation's most
endangered ecosystem,'' said Stuart D. Strahl, vice president of
the National Audubon Society, who is based in Miami. ``The
Everglades have been ditched, diked and drained.''
</P>
<P>
   Without re-plumbing, Strahl said, not only will the Everglades
die, but the farms and cities will also run out of water. ``This is
probably the poster child for sustainability in our hemisphere
right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even sugar farmers, often the natural opponents of those who
want to preserve the Everglades because the farms compete for the
water and their runoff pollutes the ecoystem, are in close
agreement on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``With over 50 inches of rain a year, it's unconscionable that
we're running out of water,'' said Malcolm S. Wade Jr., a senior
vice president of the U.S. Sugar Corp. When the shortages come, he
said, the growers will not have the political muscle to compete for
the water. ``We've got to be successful,'' Wade said, ``or we've
got problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The Everglades transcends politics, and the plan has bipartisan
backing, including support from the camps of two presidential
hopefuls. One is Vice President Al Gore, who said in a statement
released Wednesday: ``Working closely with with the people of
Florida, we have made great strides in restoring this incomparable
landscape. But if future generations are to know the Everglades as
our predecessors did, we must go the next step and restore the
precious flows that are its very lifeblood.''
</P>
<P>
   The other is Florida's Gov. Jeb Bush, the brother of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the leading contender for the Republican
presidential nomination. Members of Jeb Bush's staff were in
Washington on Wednesday to drum up support in Congress, which will
be asked soon to approve the first $1.2 billion for early projects.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 4,000-page plan, no one is sure what the finished
project will look like, partly because no one is sure how to mimic
the natural water cycle of flow, flood and drought that the last 50
years of work has destroyed. The project, which Gore will present
to Congress, includes ``adaptive management,'' meaning provisions
for making big changes as the work goes forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to insure that the right amount of water gets to the
right place at the right time,'' said David E. Guggenheim,
president of The Conservancy of Southwest Florida, explaining the
complications of a first-of-a-kind effort.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, the plan calls for capturing and keeping in the
Everglades most of the 1.7 billion gallons of water now carefully
sent to the Atlantic or the Gulf of Mexico. In the late 1940s that
seemed like a good idea, but Michael Collins, an official of the
agency that manages water flows in the Everglades, said, ``The gap,
the time that we started realizing something was horribly wrong,
was less than 10 years, maybe less than five, after construction.''
</P>
<P>
   An early sign was damage to the ocean environment where salt
water was diluted by bigger-than-natural flows of fresh water.
Guggenheim said, ``We've managed to make fresh water a pollutant.''
</P>
<P>
   But agreeing on what needs to be done is just one step; the next
question is how. The plan calls for storage techniques never tried
in the Everglades, like a surface reservoir of 62 square miles,
just 4 to 8 feet deep. Even some supporters think the water might
evaporate or seep into the porous soil before it could be useful.
</P>
<P>
   The initial design is for more than 60 separate projects,
including removing dikes and building barriers at the eastern edge
of the Everglades, where urbanized Miami gives way to sawgrass and
alligators. Backers do not even agree among themselves, though, on
which dikes should be removed and which barriers erected.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Park Service and the Fish and Wildlife Service,
both parts of the Interior Department, have come to support the
plan, after changes made since a draft was issued in April. Top
officials of the two agencies cited a promise to divert a bigger
volume of water to the Everglades, and a commitment to expedite
land acquisition to protect the Everglades, among other steps. Just
what land should be bought, and how much, is still contentious.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2104EDT &QL; 
