<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-30 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE AGING VETERAN AND A ROOKIE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The raucous cheering from behind the
ivy-covered wall had long since given way to polite applause, and
this was the surest sign that Boris Becker was on his way out on
Center Court.
</P>
<P>
   On Court 5, one long mis-hit away from tennis' most hallowed
turf, Alexandra Stevenson was completing a Houdini-like performance
that was Becker's trademark when he first won Wimbledon in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Becker win?'' asked Stevenson,
qualifier-turned-quarterfinalist, having barely survived a match
point and outlasting Lisa Raymond in three sets. ``I hope he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker was at that moment misplaying his last Wimbledon point, a
backhand half volley wide, and surrendering to Patrick Rafter in
straight sets. With a shrug and a smile, the likable German said
farewell to the court that 18-year-old Alexandra Stevenson has
dreamed of playing on since she was the 9-year-old charge of Pete
Fischer, Pete Sampras' former coach.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting the proximity of Court 5 and that this is her first
appearance in the main Wimbledon draw, Stevenson said, ``I've never
been close.''
</P>
<P>
   She won't make Center Court Thursday in her quarterfinal match
against Jelena Dokic, but Stevenson can count on remaining in the
middle of deepening intrigue. Her coming-out party as a tennis
professional has turned, sadly, into an enervating inquiry on race
and sex.
</P>
<P>
   These are subjects that sell spectacularly at Wimbledon, and
elsewhere. ``Let's please talk about my tennis,'' Stevenson pleaded
Wednesday after reading a statement to clarify earlier statements
made by her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Too late. The dialogue that began with comments Samantha
Stevenson claimed were misrepresented has escalated into a tabloid
feeding frenzy. And a Florida newspaper report, as well as The
Associated Press, Wednesday claimed that the name Julius Winfield
Erving II is listed as the father on the birth certificate of
Alexandra Winfield Stevenson, who was raised solely by her mother.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball legend was quoted by The AP as saying, ``This is
not the time to talk to anyone about personal business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' Alexandra Stevenson said after her 2-6, 7-6
(10-8), 6-1 takeout of Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' said Samantha Stevenson, standing in the lobby
of the players' tearoom, about the time Venus Williams walked by,
with an impish smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear there's more up with you today,'' Williams told her
friend's and fellow quarterfinalist's mother. ``You're having quite
a week.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone understands the position Alexandra Stevenson is in, it
is Williams. You may recall that her run to the final in her first
U.S. Open two years ago became a forum for her father, Richard, to
literally phone in charges of racism on the women's tour.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Stevenson, a freelance sports journalist whose work
appears in The New York Times, said Wednesday that the last thing
on her mind was controversy, or attention. She said she was ``being
generous with colleagues,'' some of whom attached sexual innuendo
to comments she made about protecting her daughter from other women
in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   As for her revelations on tennis racism, which included a racial
epithet directed at her mixed-race daughter a year ago at the
Wimbledon junior qualifying, she said much of that was nothing that
people had not heard before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't take back what I said because I didn't say anything
wrong,'' Samantha Stevenson said.
</P>
<P>
   No one here has argued that, and no one should. At the very
least, an insider's perspective is entitled to a proper hearing. I
just wonder if this was the appropriate time, and place.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Stevenson wanted to talk more Wednesday about her
parts in high school plays, and why wouldn't she? She already had
chilling personal material, with Fischer in jail for child
molestation and her best friend and childhood hitting partner, Eric
Basica, suffering from cancer and e-mailing her from back home in
California. Before this week, people knew little, if anything,
about Alexandra Stevenson. Now, maybe they know too much.
</P>
<P>
   The case that this has distracted from her tennis is more
difficult to make. Stevenson Wednesday shrugged off a disquieting
first set, saved the second-set tie breaker, at 5-6, with a running
forehand pass and then crushed Raymond with a grass-court power
game that Becker once made a living on here.
</P>
<P>
   Becker, in fact, had recently noticed Stevenson, a can't-miss
6-footer with heavy, blistering strokes, on a nearby practice
court, and had commented to someone that the American teen-ager
reminded him of himself. The mid-1980s version, that is. Not the
one who waved goodbye to Center Court, at about the time Alexandra
Stevenson moved one step closer, baggage and all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
