A5198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      06-30 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INVESTIGATORS NOW SEEK INSURANCE FRAUD SUSPECT IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Miss., Tenn.)   (bl)  
 By KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal investigators hunting for Martin Frankel, the
Connecticut money manager wanted in a huge insurance fraud, believe
that they have traced him to Europe and are actively pursuing leads
there, law enforcement officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the hunt for Frankel were among several revelations
in the fast-moving scandal Wednesday, as a Connecticut criminal
lawyer disclosed that he has been authorized to represent the
financier and Mississippi regulators said that they had filed
orders to liquidate three insurance companies in his crumbling
corporate empire.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel has been missing since May 5, when firefighters were
called to his mansion in Greenwich, Conn., and found smoldering
documents stuffed in fireplaces. Since then, federal prosecutors
and regulators in several states concluded that Frankel fled as a
years-long scheme to drain cash from a series of insurance
companies he controlled was coming unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   To date, no one is completely sure how much money is missing
from the insurance companies, but court records and insurance
regulators place the number in the hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The government officials declined to specify which European
countries are the focus of their search or whether an arrest is
imminent. But the fact that an active hunt appears to be under way
in Europe is a strong sign that Frankel may have left behind clues
of his destination or has made mistakes while on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's apparent decision to contact the Connecticut lawyer,
Hugh Keefe, is the first sign that he has interest in maintaining
some contact with federal prosecutors pursuing the case.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Keefe said he was recently contacted by
Frankel, and was asked to represent him. Keefe said that although
he has not been formally retained, he has agreed tentatively to
represent Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   Keefe said he had not met with Frankel in person, and does not
know how the money manager learned of him. He declined to discuss
any details of their conversations, but said that Frankel ``seemed
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   While Keefe has been in contact with federal authorities
involved in the case, he denied a report Wednesday in The Hartford
Courant that Frankel has asked a lawyer to contact federal
prosecutors to discuss possible surrender terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has absolutely not expressed an interest in turning himself
in,'' Keefe said. ``That is absolutely false.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Keefe declined to specify the reasons he
contacted the government on behalf of Frankel. But he said that, in
such cases in general, a client reading news stories about warrants
being issued for their arrest may wish to have a lawyer find out
details, such as the underlying charge and the name of the lead
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's decision to approach a lawyer ran counter to the
advice he has provided to at least one of his former associates. A
lawyer retained by a former girlfriend said that his client was
called by Frankel shortly after he fled his home.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the woman said that Frankel urged her not to hire
her own lawyer, and that he would provide one for her. The lawyer,
who spoke on condition that neither he nor his client be
identified, said that Frankel cautioned the woman that ``lawyers
are our enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who met Frankel through a personal ad, told her
lawyer that in the same conversation, she also spoke to at least
one of the women who disappeared with Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left on the cell phone numbers of several of the women
identified as having fled with Frankel went unreturned, and
attempts to reach them through their pagers also failed.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi filed its final orders of liquidation against the
three insurance companies late Tuesday, after insurance regulators
determined that the companies are insolvent and efforts to revive
them would be futile.
</P>
<P>
   The companies were subsidiaries of insurers controlled by Thunor
Trust, a Tennessee investment vehicle that federal investigators
believe were secretly controlled through a complex corporate
structure by Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   The liquidation order the final administrative step in taking
control of the companies and the first step toward raising money to
pay policyholders claims. ``This starts the clock toward paying
claims,'' said Mississippi Insurance Commissioner George Dale.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies involved are Franklin Protective Life
Insurance Co. and Family Guaranty Life Insurance Co., both units of
Franklin American Corp., and First National Life Insurance Company
of America, a subsidiary of International Financial Corp.
Regulators declared them insolvent with total liabilities of $21.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Rusty Haydel, the executive director of the Mississippi
Life and Health Insurance Guarantee Association, said he believed
money would be available to pay some claims within a week or so.
But he said it would probably be at least two or three months
before the reserves of the three companies have been replenished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
