<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World could grow old ungracefully with population explosion
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Baby boomers have ushered in most every major trend
over the past 50 years. But it was their grandparents who were part
of the most radical demographic change of the past half-century _
the dramatic increase in longevity.
</P>
<P>
   This trend raises a tough question. Fortune (July 19) asks: Will
the elderly live so long that society can't cope?
</P>
<P>
   Recent evidence points to a population explosion among senior
citizens that may amount to the biggest demographic change of the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``One projection says there will be nearly 37 million boomers
aged 85 and over by the year 2050 _ more than twice the
government's best guess,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Writer David Stipp says economic disaster may result unless far
more stringent policies are put in place now on everything from
raising the retirement age to trimming Social Security and Medicare
entitlements.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Fortune looks at how Coca-Cola's chief executive
officer, M. Douglas Ivester, is weathering ``a storm of troubles,''
including but not limited to the recent recall of company products
in Belgium and France. Despite a company overflowing with trouble,
says Fortune, Ivester swears that he's in firm control of ``the
most noble business on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   A market upside down
</P>
<P>
   One of the big changes on Wall Street in the last three months
was the rotation of stock buying into industrial, or cyclical,
stocks after big, blue chip growth stocks had dominated the market
for so long. Investors were suddenly afraid that their highly
valued growth stocks would be hammered by rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But Smart Money (July), in its midyear investment guide, says it
would be a mistake for investors to bail out of one category of
stocks and into another, since the new group may be the next to go
out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   The message is to diversify, the magazine says. It recommends 10
``undervalued'' stocks in five industry groups: Lear and Dana in
the auto parts group, Black &AMP; Decker and Maytag in consumer
cyclicals, Newport News and L-3 Communications in defense, Ispat
International and Metals USA in steel, and Synopsys and BMC
Software in technology.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ In a rare profile of Warren Buffett, Business Week (July 5)
says the billionaire investor is becoming more of a buyer of
companies than an investor in stocks. His Berkshire Hathaway has
acquired seven diverse companies for a total of $27.3 billion in
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Worth (July/August) offers readers its ratings and forecasts
for 840 mutual funds, with advice from five mutual fund gurus.
</P>
<P>
   _ Companies with ``dot.com'' in their names aren't the only
successful start-ups these days. Inc. (July) profiles 10 successes,
including a superstore for flowers, an ice cream maker, a store for
pets and a service station for boats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
