A5201 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-MUSIC-TEX     06-30 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-MUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN MUSIC HITS A HIGH NOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, when he first hit the national Christian music
scene, Steven Curtis Chapman figured that if he worked as hard as
he could, toured till he dropped and got really lucky he might,
just might, someday sell 40,000 copies of a CD and be able to pack
'em in at youth conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't turn out that way.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out a whole lot better.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Chapman _ who has sold more than 4 million CDs,
won three Grammys and regularly sells out large halls _ will
headline Celebrate Freedom '99, which is expected to draw 100,000
people, by far the largest one-day pop music event in North Texas
all summer.
</P>
<P>
   The free all-day concert will be at Southfork Ranch in Parker,
Texas. Sponsored by Christian radio station KLTY/94.1 FM, CF '99
will feature more than a dozen acts, including such top names as
Avalon, Twila Paris and Rebecca St. James.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of where he and Christian music were at the dawn of
the decade and where they are now is not lost on Chapman, a
personable Kentucky native who could easily be the one-man
personification of the genre's astounding growth in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun and interesting to see where God will
take this music,'' Chapman says. ``We don't want to lose sight of
why we're doing this, but it is exciting for me to hear a dc Talk
record on a pop station and see their videos alongside mainstream
acts. In terms of growth, we're all still amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   As well he might be. According to the Recording Industry
Association of America, gospel/Christian music has gone from $160
million in annual sales in the late '80s to nearly $900 million
last year. Christian music sales total more than classical, New Age
and jazz combined. Half of all Christian music sells in mainstream
retailers, such as Tower Records, Wal-Mart and Blockbuster. And the
top three markets for Christian music are New York, Los Angeles and
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Christian performers such as Michael W. Smith, dc Talk, Jars of
Clay, Point of Grace and Chapman regularly sell more than 300,000
copies of their CDs, often a lot more, and draw sellout crowds at
arenas and amphitheaters once reserved for rock bands.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there's the mainstreaming of gospel via
performers such as Kirk Franklin. Twenty years ago, a gospel
performer selling a million copies of a record was unthinkable.
Franklin has now done it several times, and other artists, such as
Fred Hammond and God's Property, have been nearly as popular.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has been possible for several reasons, not the least
of which was how angry and despairing rock music was at the dawn of
the '90s. Chapman and KLTY promotions director Keith Nelson point
to what Chapman calls the ``void'' left by grunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were sick of the `die, die, die' negativity of metal
and grunge,'' Nelson says. ``Christian music brought positivity to
the forefront and filled a tremendous need in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was more than just young people seeking an alternative to
Pearl Jam, says Frank Breeden, president of the Gospel Music
Association. Baby boomers, he says, were growing older and raising
families. They were looking for answers and stability that hadn't
been provided by culture _ music and everything else _ of the
hedonistic '70s and greed-filled '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Christian music, he says, was simply part and parcel of that.
</P>
<P>
   From a practical standpoint, the decade has also seen an
improvement of the sonic quality of Christian recordings. Chapman
and Breeden say that at the outset, frankly, Christian records
simply sounded weak next to those by secular singers and bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a real awakening taking place around the turn of the
decade among the major labels,'' Breeden says. ``A lot of people at
labels were saying, `We have to do better than this _ we can't do
it with lame art.' Labels allocated a lot more of their budgets for
production and better producers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Breeden says one of the most important aspects of the rise
of Christian music was the full-scale participation of the genre in
SoundScan beginning in 1996. SoundScan is a computerized system of
tracking CD sales; it shows exactly who is selling how much, and
where.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd never had point-of-sales tracking before,'' he says. ``It
was important because it confirmed Christian music sales were as
strong as we thought they were. ... It also gave us immediate
feedback about what was selling where, which led to detailed
marketing and promotion around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect of all this was greatly increased sales _ but just as
important, the assumption that the music would sell and that people
could and would listen to both religious and secular music. In the
'80s, Chapman says, a Christian artist such as Amy Grant who
crossed over to pop was criticized more sharply (and more often)
than today, when it's common to see and hear Christian artists
competing with secular ones.
</P>
<P>
   And that, in a way, has led us to Chasing Furies, a sibling trio
that will be on the Celebrate Freedom bill. Sarah, Josh and Rachel
Meeker grew up in Fort Worth but left for Colorado four years ago,
formed the band in 1997 and signed with Sparrow Records (home to
Chapman and numerous other top acts) in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Performers such as Chasing Furies represent a generation of
Christians who grew up with the idea that pop and Christian music
could go hand in hand and who used more secular influences in their
music and their overall approach than any other generation of
Christian performers.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Meeker, 22, is the Furies' main songwriter and vocalist _
and her cultural/musical background includes listening to both the
dance-pop of Depeche Mode and the lighter, breezier acts such as
Over the Rhine and Innocence Mission.
</P>
<P>
   Meeker says she wants the band to appeal to hip young people _
and knows that, in some cases, it's a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time that I quit listening to Christian music _
the quality just wasn't where I wanted it,'' she says. ``And when I
started singing I wasn't sure a Christian label would want us. Or
that they'd support a band that wants to play in clubs and minister
to those people. There's whole groups of people that can't or won't
go to churches _ they're in the (clubs) of every city, and that's
where we want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people, she says, won't ever listen. But that's OK; at
least, she says, Chasing Furies is in a position to try to reach
those who have an open mind about Christian music. Which is to say,
more people than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation is a searching generation,'' she says. ``If
the music is from our hearts, it'll be stuff that other people want
to have. It has meat to it, and I think people grasp that.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrate Freedom '99
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: 10 a.m.-midnight
</P>
<P>
   at Southfork Ranch, Parker, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Free at Kroger or Family Christian stores
</P>
<P>
   Information: (972) 299-5589
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman writes on pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
