<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-SALES01-COX     06-30 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SALES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lower sales to hit Coke's bottom line
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co., for only the second time in more than a
decade, said Wednesday that its worldwide case sales will fall for
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drop in second-quarter volume will occur in Europe,
where the company recalled 14 million cases following a health
scare in Belgium, France and several other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The recall will depress profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earnings per share in the quarter will reflect the loss of
sales in several key markets resulting from the European
situation,'' the company said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Case sales will drop an estimated 6 percent to 7 percent in
Europe, pulling down total worldwide volume by 1 percent to 2
percent. Before the recall, analysts had been predicting about a 3
percent decline in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Volume will be flat ihat only one interest rate boost will be
enough to fight inflation _ a decision that puts corporate profits
back in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But some strategists worry the Fed's lone rate increase was too
small to have the intended inflation restraining impact. If so,
that could make further rate increases necessary _ and at greater
cost to the markets.
</P>
<P>
   That's the mixed review given to the Fed's decision on Wednesday
to raise short-term interest rates by a quarter of a percentage
point, to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the Fed eased the threat of further rate
increases any time soon by dropping the ``bias'' toward tighter
credit that it adopted in May after a flurry of bad inflation news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earnings have got the stage pretty much to themselves now,''
said Charles L. Hill, research director of First Call, an
organization that tracks analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Fed had retained the bias towards higher rates, people
would still be talking about interest rates. Now earnings will be
the focus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect sent stocks surging along a broad front. The
technology-loaded Nasdaq composite rose 1.7 percent, outperforming
the blue chip Dow Jones industrial average, which rose 1.4 percent.
Both the Nasdaq composite and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 set
records.
</P>
<P>
   The gains probably would have been bigger had the Fed's rate
increase not been so widely anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market also rallied, sending 30-year Treasury yields
back below 6 percent for a time. The mark closed at an even 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the quarter-point rise in the federal funds rate
_ what banks charge each other for overnight loans _ will
eventually ripple through the economy in the form of higher rates
on auto, appliance and home equity loans. Business loans will also
rise. Major banks reacted by announcing they would raise their
prime rate to 8 percent from 7.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a quarter percentage point is going to make it
so people can't afford to buy more goods,'' said Gary Thayer, chief
economist for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. ``But I do think
some families might decide to delay purchases, waiting for a better
bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This increase won't stop consumer spending,'' said Bruce
Bittles, market strategist for J.C. Bradford &AMP; Co. in Nashville. He
cited Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan's well-known concern that the
stock market's wealth effect on consumer spending is one of the
economy's big problems.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Legacy South strategist Phillip M. Larkins
questioned the Fed's decision to return to a neutral posture on
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had raised rates half a percent and then gone back to
neutral, or raised rates a quarter point and kept the bias
tendency, it would have made more sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rate increase was almost universally anticipated, mostly
because of Greenspan's June testimony before Congress in which he
defended the concept of a ``pre-emptive'' strike against inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement Wednesday, the Fed explained that it
dropped the rate bias because ``much of the financial strain'' that
hurt the economy in last fall's global economic crisis had eased.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also noted that while labor markets have continued to
get tighter, productivity growth ``has contained inflationary
(wage) pressures'' caused by the tight markets. Now, with higher
rates and rising bond yields out of the way, investors can focus on
the second-quarter earnings reports that will be released over the
next five or six weeks, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said second-quarter earnings reports ``will be terrific,''
rising 15 percent year-over-year, compared with 10 percent in the
first quarter. He said profit growth probably will rise 20 percent
year-over-year in the third quarter. According to Sam Stovall, a
sector strategist for Standard &AMP; Poor's, the rise in interest rates
will probably have the least impact on industries that make
consumer products that are always in demand _ drugs, personal care
items, beverages, tobacco, paper.
</P>
<P>
   The worst performers are likely to be industries that depend on
an expanding economy, such as heavy machinery, consumer cyclicals
such as autos and appliances, banks and other interest-sensitive
sectors, and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
