<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-BANKS-NYT &LR;      06-30 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE TO TAKE UP FINANCIAL OVERHAUL LAW
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After more than 20 years of failed votes in
Congress, and hundreds of millions of dollars spent on lobbying,
lawmakers are on the verge of the first broad display of support to
remake the nation's financial system.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a Senate vote on May 6 to approve sweeping
deregulation that would make it easier for banks, insurers and
securities companies to enter each other's businesses, the House
will take up its own version of the measure on Thursday. The bill
has been written by both Republicans and Democrats, and it has
enjoyed broad support from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   If the House approves the legislation, as some lobbyists,
administration officials and lawmakers predicted Wednesday, it
would be the first time in more than 20 years that both houses of
Congress, in the same term, voted to repeal the Glass-Steagall Act
of 1933 and nearly six decades worth of other legislation rooted in
the nightmarish experiences of the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   No one who favors a new law is celebrating yet. The
legislation's course through Congress has always been perilous, and
a few big obstacles remain. In particular, the House and Senate
bills contain other important, and possibly irreconcilable
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists in both houses have embarked on a
strategy of delaying resolution of the most contentious issues that
have in the past stymied the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, many longtime veterans of the struggles over
changing the financial services industry said Wednesday that the
chances were better ever that Congress might act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The train seems to be on the track toward a far more
concentrated financial services industry,'' said Kenneth Guenther,
a top lobbyist for the Independent Community Bankers Association,
who has spent 18 years in legislative battles over the issue. ``If
it passes, the push will be to resolve the difficult issues in
conference and have the conference write the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the proposed legislation to overhaul the financial
system was little more than a powerful vehicle for the fund raising
efforts of many lawmakers, as the industry lobbyists fought
furiously to a stalemate. In the last session of Congress alone,
the three industries have poured $86 million into campaign war
chests, according to an analysis by the Center for Responsive
Politics, a nonpartisan research group.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the political investment may be paying off. With
traditional lines blurring between the insurance, securities and
banking businesses, industry lobbyists who were once at odds are
now largely in accord on most of the central issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so close to having legislation, closer than we've ever
been before,'' said Dan Zielinski, a spokesman at the American
Insurance Association, which represents 375 property and casualty
insurers. ``It's because the market has advanced to such a degree
that everyone has decided it's in their interests to have this
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are differences that must be worked out for there
to be a new law. President Clinton has threatened to veto the
Senate measure, which was adopted by a 54-44 vote along party
lines. In the fight between the Treasury Department and the
chairman of the Federal Reserve, the Senate sided with Alan
Greenspan, the Fed chairman, giving his agency a greater regulatory
role in monitoring nationally chartered institutions.
</P>
<P>
   It also diluted the requirements that banks make loans to
minorities, farmers and others who have had relatively little
access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the House approved a bill by a single vote, but the
measure died in the Senate. This year, as privacy issues have
dominated the agenda for both regulators and lawmakers, the House
measure is the subject of a big last-minute fight over whether it
should enable customers to prohibit the sharing of information
about them between affiliated companies and outsiders, such as
telemarketing firms.
</P>
<P>
   Some liberal Democrats and conservative Republicans want to give
consumers the ability to curtail the sharing of information, so
that, for instance, Citigroup's Salomon Smith Barney unit would not
be able to share information with Citigroup's Travelers unit.
</P>
<P>
   Industry groups oppose such a provision and have pledged to
campaign against any legislation that forbids affiliates of the
same company from sharing customer information. As a result, an
alternative has emerged that would give customers the right to only
block information from being provided to third parties. But large
financial conglomerates would still be able to share the
information between affiliated companies.
</P>
<P>
   If the privacy issues are worked out, then lobbyists, members of
Congress and administration officials said they expected the
legislation to pass by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old saying that practice makes perfect and I think
that's true here,'' said Phil Anderson, a top lobbyist for the
American Council of Life Insurance. ``We're looking forward to a
big vote tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
