<P>
   (NYT10) GAINESVILLE, Fla. -- June 30, 1999 --
STAINED-GLASS-CEILING-2, 06-30 -- Jim Mayo visits with Valerie
Storms, 44, a chaplain at Shands Hospital at the University of
Florida since 1991. As a chaplain, Storms said, she has noticed
that gender doesn't matter so much to the sick. ``When people are
in the hospital, they're so vulnerable and sometimes scared,'' says
Ms. Storms. ``I think in this setting it's different because people
are in a place they're not used to, and they will talk to anyone
who will offer a comforting word.'' (John Moran/The Gainesville
Sun)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) GAINESVILLE, Fl. -- June 30, 1999 --
STAINED-GLASS-CEILING-1, 06-30 -- Heidi Kreider, 37, Emmanuel
Mennonite's pastor for eight years tells stories of worshipers who
come to her church for one service and never return. ``They said,
'We have just one problem, and that is that you're a woman,''' she
explains. Other clergywomen tell similar stories of on-the-job
bias. (Jon M. Fletcher/The Gainesville Sun)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BELA CRKVA, Yugoslavia -- June 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-GRAVES-3, 6-30 -- Ethnic Albanian Qame Gashi, left, weeps
while waiting outside a farm warehouse that has been converted to a
makeshift morgue on Wednesday. Gashi was waiting to see if one of
the 64 remains unearthed by a forensic team with the International
War Crimes Tribunal were of her husband. Thousands of survivors of
the massacres in Kosovo want to bury their dead. But nearly all are
waiting for investigators to bear witness to what Albanians call
the Serbs' crimes. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BELA CRKVA, Yugoslavia -- June 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-GRAVES-2, 6-30 -- A forensic team with the International
Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia removes the body of an
ethnic Albanian on Wednesday. Investigators found 64 bodies of
ethnic Albanians killed allegedly by Serbs. Thousands of survivors
of the massacres in Kosovo want to bury their dead. But nearly all
are waiting for the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former
Yugoslavia to come, exhume the dead, however shabbily buried, and
bear witness to what Albanians call the Serbs' crimes. (Tyler
Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) VELIKA KRUSHA, Yugoslavia -- June 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-GRAVES, 6-30 -- A skull and bloodstained clothes as found on
the floor of a shed on Wednesday. Thousands of survivors of the
massacres in Kosovo want to bury their dead. But nearly all are
waiting for the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former
Yugoslavia to come, exhume the dead, however shabbily buried, and
bear witness to what Albanians call the Serbs' crimes.(Tyler
Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FINKSBURG, Md. -- June 30, 1999 -- HOMESTEAD, 6-30 --
Somewhere in the attic of this old farmhouse is a faded picture of
young trees that were barely as tall as the man who planted them
around 1902. The trees now encompase the home providing shade and
nobility to the aging home. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- June 30, 1999 -- STERN-ARCHITECTURE,
6-30 -- Robert A.M Stern, dean of the Yale School of Architecture,
talks to students during a party in his loft. When Yale University
Presdient Richard Levin announced last fall that he had appointed
Stern to the post, the news roiled the design community. (Thomas
McDonald/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- June 30, 1999 -- CIR-PAID-SURFERS, 6-30 --
James and Lisa Grove check their email at home earlier this month.
The Groves have recruited more than 1,700 Internet surfers to put
up with on-screen ads in exchange for payment. (Michael Quan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HAVERFORD, Pa. -- June 30, 1999 -- CIR-FIRST-COMPUTER,
6-30 -- Dr. Edwin Rothman, 66, with a computer keyboard in front of
his collection of rare books at his home earlier this month.
Rothman, who has never used an A.T.M., never turned on the cellular
phone that came with his car and always bypasses an automated phone
answering system in favor of a live voice, recently bought his
first computer and has written a diary of his foray into the
computer world. (Tim Shaffer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MILBRAE, Calif. -- June 30, 1999 -- CIR-HOAX, 6-30 --
Charles Hymes, a Hewlett-Packard engineer who runs a nonprofit Web
site that exposes hoaxes, in his home-office earlier this month.
Hoaxes can spread through the Internet faster than viruses, to
which they have been compared. It is harder to figure out which
messages are true, especially when many people check their powers
of critical thinking at their Internet portals. (Peter DaSilva/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
