<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Wednesday, 06/30/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) ABOARD THE FERRYBOAT DOVER, in the English Channel --
June 30, 1999 -- EU-DUTYFREE-DEMISE-2, 6-30 -- During the last day
of duty-free shopping (that Europeans have savored for five
decades) feelings here are mixed. ``When they bring in the French
taxes, we'll be able to bring in as much as we like,'' says Melvyn
Lethaby who, with his daughter, Michelle May, totes their booty of
discounted beer and cigarettes Wednesday on the way home to Kent in
England. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) DOVER, England -- June 30, 1999 -- EU-DUTYFREE-DEMISE-1,
6-30 --Vehicles streaming off the Channel ferry Calais, the Dover's
sister ship, Wednesday on the last day of duty-free shopping. The
European Union's decision to end such shopping was made eight years
ago on the basis that duty-free sales skew Europe's vaunted single
market. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- June 30, 1999 -- SBC-AMERITECH, 6-30 -- SBC
Communications Chairman Edward Whitacre Jr. during a meeting with
analysts in 1998 over the proposed merger between his company and
Ameritech Corp. SBC and Ameritech inched closer to merging into the
nation's largest local phone company with tentative approval from
federal regulators. (Marilyn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BELA CRKVA, Yugoslavia -- June 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-GRAVES-4, 6-30 -- Ethnic Albanian women wait outside a farm
warehouse that has been converted into a makeshift morgue on
Wednesday. The women were waiting to identify relatives whose
remains were unearthed from a mass grave by a forensic team with
the International War Crimes Tribunal. Thousands of survivors of
the massacres in Kosovo want to bury their dead. But nearly all are
waiting for investigators to bear witness to what Albanians call
the Serbs' crimes. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DENVER -- June 30, 1999 -- OBIT-BERGER, 6-30 -- William
Berger, who used a fortune he made in mutual funds to create a vast
collection of British art, at the Denver Art Museum in 1997. Berger
died Tuesday at University Hospital in Denver. He was 73. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- June 30, 1999 -- COMMANDANT-FLOATER, 6-30
-- Gen. James Jones, left, receives the U.S. Marines battle colors
from Gen. Charles Krulak during a ceremony where Jones became the
32nd commandant of the corps on Wednesday. The ceremony took place
at the historic Marine Barracks, the oldest post in the Marine
Corps. Jones, 55, is a native of Kansas City, Mo., but spent his
formative years in France. Jones returned to the United States to
attend the Georgetown University School of Foreign Service, where
he received a bachelor of science degree in 1966. Among his
personal decorations: the Silver Star Medal and a Bronze Star Medal
with combat ``V'' for valor. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- June 30, 1999 -- SUMMER-SAM-4-B&AMP;W, 6-30 --
David Berkowitz, aka Son of Sam, in police custody on August 11,
1977. Son of Sam, who taunted the police and the press with bizarre
handwritten notes, was, the journalist Jimmy Breslin wrote, the
first murderer he knew of who also understood how to wield a
semicolon. (Fred A. Conrad/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- June 30, 1999 -- SUMMER-SAM-3-B&AMP;W, 6-30 --
Reggie Jackson's Yankees triumph in 1977. Their World Series
victory over the Los Angeles Dodgers was one of the few positive
notes during a metaphorical summer of '77, perhaps best remembered
for the actions of the serial killer David Berkowitz - aka Son of
Sam. (Larry Morris/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- June 30, 1999 -- SUMMER-SAM-2-B&AMP;W, 6-30 --
Cooling off in near-record highs in June, 1977. Spike Lee's latest
film, ``Summer of Sam,'' which opens Friday, is not a documentary,
but it vividly captures the depravity of a city that had lost its
bearings as well as its mind in the summer of '77. (Neal Boenzi/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- June 30, 1999 -- SUMMER-SAM-1-B&AMP;W, 6-30 --
Bedford Stuyvesant looters act swiftly as store alarms are silenced
by the blackout in the summer of 1977. The looting resulted in more
than 3,000 arrests. (Tyrone Dukes/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- June 30, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 6-30
-- A well-designed pond can be a pleasant addition to any property.
The hardest part of installing a pond is digging the hole _ unless
you rent a backhoe. Unlike other home building projects, pond
building does not require precise measurements or accurate scale
drawings. Still, depending on the size of the pond, it will take
some planning. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) DENVER -- June 30, 1999 -- DETECTIVE-INDICT, 6-30 -- A
handcuffed James Rapp, right, is led in led to a police vehicle on
Monday. Rapp, 39, and his wife, Regana Rapp, were indicted by a
Jefferson County grand jury on two counts each of racketeering in a
case that is the first known criminal prosecution against the
growing business of peddling confidential information. (The Denver
Post/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- June 30, 1999 -- HOUSE-FACADES, 6-30 --
Suburban houses, like this one in Long Island, are being made with
an increasingly popular artificial stucco and foam. In Southern
states, many wood-frame homes built with these materials have
experienced water damage. (Fred A. Bernstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- June 30, 1999 -- FOOD-ICECREAM-SANDWICH-COX,
6-30 -- Old-fashioned ginger-molasses cookies with vanilla ice
cream; use of star-shaped cookie cutters adds an Independence Day
flair. There's hardly a more classic, comforting combination than
cookies and cream, whether you dunk some warm chocolate chip
cookies into a tall glass of milk or munch on an ice cold sandwich
of soft chocolate wafers and smooth vanilla ice cream. (William
Berry/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) EXETER, N.H. -- June 30, 1999 -- ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS,
6-30 -- Dennis Kozlowski, the chief executive who has built Tyco
into a giant conglomerate with unglamourous business interests
across the globe and even below the ocean's depths. ``I never
started out with a game plan to be a $76 billion company,'' says
Kozlowski, referring to Tyco's stock value. ``But I always
envisioned one that had to grow ever year in order to be successful
and satisfy shareholders.'' (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) GAINESVILLE, Fla. -- June 30, 1999 --
STAINED-GLASS-CEILING-2, 06-30 -- Jim Mayo visits with Valerie
Storms, 44, a chaplain at Shands Hospital at the University of
Florida since 1991. As a chaplain, Storms said, she has noticed
that gender doesn't matter so much to the sick. ``When people are
in the hospital, they're so vulnerable and sometimes scared,'' says
Ms. Storms. ``I think in this setting it's different because people
are in a place they're not used to, and they will talk to anyone
who will offer a comforting word.'' (John Moran/The Gainesville
Sun)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) GAINESVILLE, Fl. -- June 30, 1999 --
STAINED-GLASS-CEILING-1, 06-30 -- Heidi Kreider, 37, Emmanuel
Mennonite's pastor for eight years tells stories of worshipers who
come to her church for one service and never return. ``They said,
'We have just one problem, and that is that you're a woman,''' she
explains. Other clergywomen tell similar stories of on-the-job
bias. (Jon M. Fletcher/The Gainesville Sun)
</P>
<P>
