<HEADER>
A5211 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EGRETS-FIREWORKS-TEXA     06-30 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGRETS-FIREWORKS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCELING FIREWORKS FOR EGRETS IRKS MANY IN DALLAS SUBURB 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARROLLTON, Texas _ This year, the Independence Day celebration
in this Dallas suburb will be for the birds.
</P>
<P>
   Migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
   There will be flag waving, music, speeches and food, but, in
deference to its feathered transients, Carrollton will forgo the
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council voted this week to eliminate a 12-minute
pyrotechnic display from its two-hour Fourth of July party Thursday
night at a city park that is also home to an egret rookery.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very upset about it,'' said City Councilman Andrew
Olivo, the only member who voted in favor of the fireworks at a
special meeting Sunday. ``There is no legal reason for not doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   No legal reason, perhaps, but abundant political and public
relations motives.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Carrollton became embroiled in a long-running
controversy after it bulldozed an egret rookery. Residents of
nearby neighborhoods had complained about the noise and odor from
the stand of trees where the birds gathered each spring to hatch
their young.
</P>
<P>
   In violation of the 1918 Migratory Bird Act, work crews advanced
on the rookery before sunrise July 23. Trees were felled and pushed
into a pile, along with many young birds nesting in them.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of egrets took flight and circled overhead, filling
the morning sky with a density that some residents mistook for
smoke. At least 300 birds were killed and 250 injured.
</P>
<P>
   As public outrage grew, the city spent nearly $130,000 to care
for injured birds and release the survivors back into the wild.
Last month, the city paid a $70,000 fine levied by the U.S. Fish
and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have certainly learned a lot in the past 10 months, and our
community will greatly benefit from our heightened environmental
sensitivity,'' Mayor Milburn Gravley said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some Carrollton residents think that sensitivity has
reached the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said John Kampschroeder, commander of the
Carrollton VFW Post. ``They're walking on tiptoes. I can't
understand the birds getting all this attention and we have to
alter our lifestyles.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the bulldozing controversy, the city designated
land for a new rookery and created the Wildlife and Environmental
Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, that committee looked at the plans for the
fireworks show and approved them, said Randy Beckham, owner of
Pyrotex Inc., which had a $12,000 contract with the city to stage
the display.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not going to destroy the rookery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Beckham conducted a test at the site, which is 1,900
feet from the rookery. A brief series of explosions startled the
egrets, many of which flew from their roosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Lanier (chairman of the Wildlife and Environmental
Advisory Committee) was willing to allow the show. But by the next
morning, I knew it was off,'' Beckham said.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A special meeting of the City Council was held Sunday and the
fireworks portion of the celebration was scuttled. The city
apparently will still have to pay Pyrotex Inc. the contract amount.
</P>
<P>
   Olivo, the lone dissenting voice, said he believes the council
was too sensitive to its ``previous problem'' with the egrets.
While the noise and lights from the fireworks may have frightened
the birds, he said, the display would not have been an act of
aggression against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not going after the birds,'' he said. ``It's a
national holiday. Everybody else is doing it. It's the last Fourth
of July celebration in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Kampschroeder, while critical of the City Council's decision,
said he could ``see their point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This city has taken a torpedo (over egrets),'' he said. ``What
if something happened? What if a fire started in those trees where
they roost? You can bet that everyone would say that Carrollton
planned it to get rid of those birds. I can understand why they
would be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
