u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRONTIER-QWEST-NYT &LR;      06-30 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTIER-QWEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRONTIER AGREES TO TALKS ON BUYOUT OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Frontier Corp. said Wednesday that its management and
advisers would begin exploratory discussions with Qwest
Communications International after reviewing the revised $12.7
billion hostile offer made by Qwest last week.
</P>
<P>
   The move is a step forward for Qwest, the fourth largest
long-distance telephone company, which is trying to woo not only
Frontier, but also U S West from the embrace of its rival, Global
Crossing. But Frontier made clear that the discussions with Qwest
were preliminary. Still it could foreshadow what U S West, the
smallest of the Bell telephone companies, is likely to decide when
its board meets this week to discuss whether to entertain
discussions with Qwest too.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier, the fifth largest long-distance carrier, agreed in
March to be acquired by Global Crossing in a stock swap valued at
$11.1 billion. U S West also agreed to merge in May with Global,
which offered $30 billion in stock. Under the terms of their merger
agreements with Global, both U S West and Frontier were barred from
talking to Qwest unless Qwest's bids could reasonably be expected
to be superior to Global's offers. Qwest's first bid June 13 _ a
combination of cash and stock _ did little to inspire U S West and
Frontier, so Qwest revised its bid last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discussion and careful consideration of information not yet
available to Frontier are necessary before the board would be able
to make any final determination,'' Frontier said Wednesday. At the
same time, the company said it was proceeding with its merger with
Global Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, whose executives have remained relatively
silent yet assured in the past few weeks, issued a statement saying
it was confident that ``once the Frontier board completes its
exploratory process, it will reaffirm our existing agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing and Qwest are racing to build a global
fiber-optic network to transmit data via the Internet, and U S West
and Frontier have the cash and customers that each company needs.
Qwest chief executive Joseph Nacchio said he was pleased with
Frontier's decision and eager to begin discussions. He said
Frontier chief executive Joseph Clayton called him early Wednesday
morning after Frontier's board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But as of late Wednesday, neither company had signed the
confidentiality agreement necessary to begin talking. Qwest's
proposed confidentiality agreement with Frontier, said people close
to the talks, has a ``stand still'' provision that says Qwest
cannot initiate a tender offer or submit a revised proposal, even
if Global Crossing raises its bid. Qwest has balked at that
provision, which could stall its plans to begin sharing company
information by today.
</P>
<P>
   If U S West's recent conversations with investors are indicative
of what executives there are thinking, U S West may also be open to
Qwest's overture. Representatives of U S West have been quietly
polling the company's largest investors in the past week regarding
a proposed three-way combination of Qwest, U S West and Frontier,
said an investor.
</P>
<P>
   The investor said the question U S West was wrestling with was
which combination would become the better company in the long-run.
Qwest is further along in its development than Global Crossing,
although several of Global's projects are expected to be completed
within the year. In addition, U S West is mulling over whether the
two kinds of stock proposed in the Global Crossing merger provide
the best alternative for shareholders, said the investor.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be the first time U S West and Qwest talked about a
combination. People close to the talks said that U S West chief
executive Solomon Trujillo had had discussions with Nacchio the
weekend before U S West agreed to merge with Global Crossing.
Trujillo, those people said, told Nacchio that he was considering
merging with a company he did not identify and asked if Qwest was
interested in talking. Those people said that Nacchio did not have
enough time to analyze the proposed combination before the Global
announcement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
