<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHEN-$ADV04-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOAN CHEN TURNS TO LOVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB GRAHAM  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &LR;   &LR; _ Just after the first film Joan Chen directed
has opened, the news comes that she has signed up for her second, a
love story starring Richard Gere and Winona Ryder.
</P>
<P>
   The budget will be $50 million, exactly 50 times the cost of her
debut feature, ``Xiu Xiu: The Sent-Down Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could make 50 movies with that money,'' she says at a
neighborhood cafe near her home in San Francisco. ``This time, I'm
going to blow it all on one.''
</P>
<P>
   If she is at all pressured by the conflicting demands of cell
phone calls from her agent about the latest project, answering
questions about her troubles with China over the first film and
taking care of her new baby, she doesn't show it. She's
good-humored and focused.
</P>
<P>
   It's not accurate to describe Chen as an
actress-turned-director. The star of Bernardo Bertolucci's ``The
Last Emperor'' and David Lynch's ``Twin Peaks'' intends to keep
acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I keep directing, I will age 10 years sooner,'' says the
38-year-old Chen. But right now, the opportunity is too good to
pass up.
</P>
<P>
   The Gere-Ryder project, called ``Autumn in New York,'' will
start shooting there after Labor Day. The autumnal angle is that
love arrives late for the character Gere plays, a womanizing
restaurateur in his late 40s. Ryder is an art student in her early
20s.
</P>
<P>
   Working conditions on the new movie promise to be somewhat
better than they were for the first. Chen and her crew bent the
rules to film ``Xiu Xiu'' on the border between Sichuan and Tibet,
and the displeased Chinese authorities cracked down on her.
</P>
<P>
   They imposed a sizable fine and banned her from working in
China, where she was born and became a big star while still in her
teens. It is extremely unlikely that ``Xiu Xiu'' will ever be shown
there, although video cassettes will surely circulate on the black
market.
</P>
<P>
   Gere, a famous follower of the Dalai Lama, has had his own
troubles with the Chinese. His 1997 movie ``Red Corner,'' about an
American framed for murder in China, was never allowed to be shown
there, either.
</P>
<P>
   Chen says ``it is pure coincidence'' that she and Gere, who
already had been involved in the ``Autumn'' project for two years,
will now be working together. She does not expect it to interfere
with her efforts to improve her standing with Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is a great job opportunity,'' she says. ``I don't
want to politicize it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Chinese have reduced her fine by 50 percent, to
$50,000 _ ``It's still a big traffic ticket, believe me.'' She
plans to go back for face-to-face talks about the work ban, which
she describes as ``temporary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Xiu Xiu'' (pronounced show-show) is about a 15-year-old
Chinese girl who is ``sent down'' to a province on the Tibet border
during the Cultural Revolution. The girl is supposed to become a
horse herder but is ill-used by a series of men passing through the
isolated camp she shares with a Tibetan herdsman. In its own way,
it is a love story, too.
</P>
<P>
   The film attracted attention on the festival circuit and went on
to win top awards from the Taiwan film industry, including best
picture, director, actor and actress. Some people think the Chinese
government would have been content to ignore ``Xiu Xiu'' but the
Taiwan awards made the film newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   The film commemorates the last generation to come of age during
the discredited Cultural Revolution, which limped to an end in
1976. Chen identifies with that generation herself, although she
was never ``sent down.'' At age 15, Chen left high school to appear
in her first movie and became famous when it was released.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Shanghai, where both her parents still work as
physicians, and has been a resident of San Francisco for the past
seven years. She lives in the Cow Hollow district with her husband,
cardiologist Peter Hui, and their 8-month-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Chen credits the self-discipline she learned from her parents
not only for her ability to steer a movie to completion under
difficult conditions but also for the success of her marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents told me that happiness requires discipline. In my
profession, I travel so much, I'm away so much, how to keep my
marriage, how to maintain this thing, this happiness, is through
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was weak or lost discipline, I would have lost my
marriage. I was away for five months for `Xiu Xiu,' and we must
have the discipline to be faithful to each other. Both of us are
still quite young, and I think desirable for other people.''
</P>
<P>
   That is one of Chen's understatements _ her luminous beauty as
the No. 1 wife in ``The Last Emperor'' made her an international
star.
</P>
<P>
   Her San Francisco connections are strong _ her daughter, Angela,
was born here _ and touch on her professional life in unusual ways.
She found Lu Lu, the young star of ``Xiu Xiu,'' in a San Francisco
school that teaches English to immigrants. (``Xiu Xiu'' is in
Chinese with English subtitles.) Just the other day she met Ryder,
star of her next movie, for the first time at the home of Ryder's
parents, who turn out to be neighbors of Chen's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xiu Xiu'' is not a story about the Red Guard, Chen says.
``That has been told many times. What hasn't been told is the story
of the children.'' It is about the loss of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said Lu Lu had ``the physical vulnerability and the
innocence'' for the role but also ``the inner toughness.'' In that
regard, it is impossible to escape the idea that Chen is describing
herself as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
