<HEADER>
A5223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASK-DIETITIAN01-COX     06-30 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASK-DIETITIAN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decaf tea has some of same benefits as regular
 &HT;    By Karen Collins
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does decaffeinated tea contain the same health-promoting
substances found in regular tea?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Researchers say that although a small amount of the
natural phytochemicals in tea may be lost in the decaffeination
process, content in decaf tea is only slightly lower. Laboratory
research suggests that the phytochemicals, called flavonoids, found
in tea could help prevent stomach cancer (and possibly colon
cancer) by blocking the effects of carcinogens and by working as
antioxidants (like vitamins C and E) to prevent cell damage that
can lead to cancer. Other research suggests these flavonoids may
help fight heart disease by keeping blood cholesterol in a
less-damaging form. Human studies so far, however, are unclear
about just how strong the actual benefits are.
</P>
<P>
   For now, experts emphasize that while tea _ regular or
decaffeinated _ could be a positive addition to a healthy diet, it
cannot compare with the major impact of eating a mostly plant-based
diet with plenty of fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there supplements I can take to make me burn more
calories?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Chromium and ginseng are recommended by some salespeople
and magazine articles, but research has shown that they have no
effect on calorie-burning rate. Neither does ephedra (also called
ma huang), despite its stimulant, caffeinelike effect; and ephedra
has been linked with serious health risks.
</P>
<P>
   Metabolic rate seems to be partly inherited, but is decreased by
over-zealous dieting and as a result of some eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Keep your calorie-burning rate at its natural level by staying
physically active (ideally including some form of strength
training) to maintain muscle tissue, and eat a balanced diet that
meets nutritional needs. If you do this, and eat according to
body's hunger signals for how much you need, your weight should
stay at a healthy level regardless of exactly how fast you're
burning calories.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If smoked foods are not recommended, what about liquid smoke
flavorings?
</P>
<P>
   A: Foods that are smoked or grilled over an open flame and smoke
contain substances known as polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons _ PAH
for short _ that can initiate the development of cancer cells, and
frequent consumption of smoked foods is linked to a possible
increase in risk of stomach cancer and perhaps other cancers.
Liquid smoke flavoring is made from water and smoke concentrate, so
it does contain PAHs, but studies have found that the small amount
each person would use is insignificant. If you miss the smoked
taste in certain foods that you used to prepare with smoked meats,
you can feel comfortable using liquid smoke in soups, sprinkled on
fish, and so on. You might also explore other seasonings to flavor
your food, such as onions, garlic, ginger and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If I select a dish based on low-fat foods like pasta, chicken
or vegetables, does the sauce really matter?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely! Hollandaise and bearnaise sauces contain egg
yolks and a quarter- to a half-stick of butter per serving. The fat
in Alfredo sauce comes from cream, butter and Parmesan cheese. You
can get about 30 grams of fat just from these sauces! If you really
crave one of these dishes, enjoy it on occasion. But the fat
content of your meal will be much lower if you stick with sauces
that are tomato-based (such as marinara) or broth-based. White clam
sauce is another good choice; it contains olive oil, but generally
in a modest amount, and it's a healthier fat than butter.
</P>
<P>
   These Ask a Dietitian questions were answered by Karen Collins,
M.S., R.D. of the American Institute for Cancer Research.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
