<HEADER>
A5224 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-CHEN-$ADV04-2NDT     06-30 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHEN-$ADV04-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SAN FRANCISCO _ as well.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   She and her crew traveled twice to the Tibet border, to catch
the changing seasons. They didn't let the Chinese authorities know
exactly what they were doing, nor did they get script approval.
Some of the footage was smuggled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be hard, but I didn't know enough to
expect that it would be this hard,'' she says now. ``It was
incredible pressure being the producer, the director and the
caretaker.''
</P>
<P>
   The caretaker? ``Yes, I was responsible for everything, from
money and the political situation to providing coffee, cookies and
chocolate bars in my backpack. Lunch came from 2 1/2 hours away,
and by the time it arrived it was cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, lunch was yak. ``Yak meat actually tastes good,'' Chen
says. ``It's actually quite tender. Yaks are so huge, it looks like
the meat would be tough. It's mostly boiled. We brought some spice
with us, mostly soy sauce and sugar. We had to eat it every day, so
we instructed the kitchen to try to make it a little differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The role of a Tibetan herdsman, who falls in love with Xiu Xiu
but for reasons the film explains cannot act on it, was played by a
Tibetan classical actor with the one-word name Lopsang. Chen
describes Lopsang as a man ``who is one with nature _ he has inside
him a Buddha.''
</P>
<P>
   He not only provided a line for the film _ ``Everywhere is the
same'' _ but when he is not working as an actor he assists a
Tibetan sky burial master. (In the traditional sky burials, corpses
are dismembered and left on mountain peaks for the vultures.)
</P>
<P>
   Chen says Lopsang studied classic theater and became the most
famous Shakespearean actor in China. ``In `Hamlet,' there is this
ghost that comes back, this father figure, and they see death at a
different level, in a spiritual way. He has this simplicity and
honesty that actually is very rare in a civilized society. He
wouldn't even know how to say a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL ADD END) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chen, surprisingly, describes herself as ``not sociable.'' In
San Francisco, she spends as much time as she can taking care of
her baby. ``I like staying at home,'' she says. ``Actually, it's a
very boring and stable life.'' When she goes out, she likes to
visit her neighborhood cafe, where she is discreetly welcomed but
not fussed over, or goes to a bookstore on Clement Street. She also
rides the Muni.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to take the bus because then I can listen to music on
earphones or sometimes read and not have to think about driving or
parking.''
</P>
<P>
   She listens to the Western classical music she grew up with _
Tchaikovsky, Prokofiev and Dvorak _ and has a tendency to reread
the books she loves. She has read Nabokov's ``Lolita'' ``probably
seven times'' and Gabriel Garcia Marquez's ``Love in the Time of
Cholera'' five times.
</P>
<P>
   She also likes art books. ``As a director, if I develop in this
area, there are images that inspire me. Edward Hopper. Georgia
O'Keeffe, Andrew Wyeth. That's how I learned America.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
