<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONDURAN-IMMIG-COLUMN     06-30 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAN-IMMIG-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG CITY: A BOY'S FANTASY TURNED HARDHEADED URBANITES
SOFTHEARTED
</HEADLINE>
  (With HONDURAN-IMMIG)  
(nk) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now that all of us supposedly savvy New Yorkers have
been conned by a 13-year-old Honduran who speaks no English, what
is there to say to him? Only a simple, heartfelt message:
</P>
<P>
   Bienvenido a Nueva York! Nuestra casa es tu casa!
</P>
<P>
   No one belongs in this city more than Edwin Daniel Sabillon, the
teen-ager who arrived telling of an epic journey from Honduras.
Those details happen not to be true, but his is still a
quintessential New York success story.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin got off the bus Sunday afternoon with $24 and a bag of
cookies. By Tuesday, without benefit of a single phone call from
Howard Rubenstein, his trip was making front-page news:
``Incredible Journey,'' one headline aptly put it. The mayor and
the police commissioner were attending to his needs; literary
agents were wondering if the book and movie rights would command
six or seven figures.
</P>
<P>
   Without a single pitch meeting, Edwin devised an irresistible
plot: Village boy loses family in hurricane, journeys across
continent, wanders big city looking for dad. ``Wizard of Oz'' meets
``Huckleberry Finn'' meets ``Home Alone II.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the story needs a little adjustment, but it still has
commercial potential. It's a variation of ``The Music Man.'' This
time, instead of the slicker going to the provinces to hustle the
bumpkins, the bumpkin comes to the city, but the result is the
same: The slickers are seduced by the bumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   It is a reasonably happy ending, partly because Edwin now stands
to get help for the genuine troubles in his life, partly because
his tale is a useful reminder that New Yorkers can be the world's
biggest saps. While putting on a tough front, we're prone to
falling for a tale like Edwin's because it touches our hidden
fears.
</P>
<P>
   The story of a naif lost thousands of miles from home resonated
with the many people here _ half the population _ who came from
somewhere else. Far from the safety net of families, New Yorkers
competing for scarce jobs and paying exorbitant rents could play
out through Edwin their own worst-case scenarios: One or two
calamities, they imagine, and they too could be wandering the mean
streets, impoverished and homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists have always worked hard to satisfy the appetites of
tender-hearted New Yorkers, but it is not easy to maintain the
production of newsworthy pathos. The facts all too often get in the
way, as I discovered when I was assigned to the homeless beat
nearly a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The beat had plenty of grim stories, but the victims were
generally not the sort of victim that readers identify with: a
sober, industrious person in desperate shape because of bad breaks
and society's indifference. The homeless men I met seemed afflicted
mainly by drugs, alcohol and mental illness. They didn't spend a
lot of time cursing the indifference of society.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though, I found a promising candidate named Jimmy, an
affable, articulate young guy living in a shantytown on Donald
Trump's land along the Hudson River in the West 60s. His wooden
shack had a closet neatly arranged with dress shirts, ties and a
half-dozen suits.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy seemed to be over the cocaine problem that had landed him
in the streets. He had a part-time job at a soup kitchen, where he
ladled out food and talked about how much he enjoyed helping his
homeless neighbors still struggling with their demons. He said that
he wanted to find a full-time job and move into an apartment, but
that he was being thwarted by prejudice against the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to work,'' he said, ``but if you don't already have
a home and an address, you can't get past the job interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Eager to document this injustice, I accompanied him on a
job-hunting expedition. We started at the state unemployment
office, which sent him to the Swingline factory in Long Island
City. He was promptly hired.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the sad story I'd anticipated, but I kept monitoring
his progress. Three days later he quit the job. ``I don't like the
commute,'' he explained. A week later he disappeared from the
shantytown along with his wardrobe and his neighbors' possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbors in the shantytown were furious at the theft, but
they did not share my astonishment at his duplicity. Nor were they
surprised that a member of the press had fallen for a line. They
seemed to realize one of the secrets of media relations in New
York: To make it here, sometimes all you have to do is make it up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
