u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-V-CHIPS01-COX     06-30 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-V-CHIPS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Today is V-Day as TV sets get censoring chips
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As of today, federal law requires that half of all
televisions larger than 13 inches have the V-chip, an electronic
tool to censor violent programming, offensive language and sexual
situations. The other half must be equipped by Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some tips from the V-chip Education Project,
co-sponsored by the Center for Media Education and the Henry J.
Kaiser Family Foundation. For more information:
www.vchipeducation.org or at (877) 282-4478.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does the V-chip work with the TV ratings?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ratings that flash on screen at the beginning of a show _
V (violence), S (sex), L (crude language), SD (suggestive dialogue)
or FV (``fantasy'' violence) _ contain an electronic signal that
registers how the program has been rated. V-chips receive and
understand the electronic rating signals.
</P>
<P>
   By following the screen directions, parents can ensure that
programming rated is included in their V-chip programming
``strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it possible to block all shows that contain violence?
</P>
<P>
   A: No matter how you program your V-chip, some shows with
violence, including those shown on BET and NBC, and even some
children's shows, will not be filtered out by simply selecting
``V'' or ``FV.'' News and sports are exempt. The best way to block
most violence is to use the age-based ratings to determine what
programs are not appropriate for your children.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it activated when I turn on my TV?
</P>
<P>
   A: The chip won't operate unless you select the option to
activate it. Then, a display of the ratings menu will appear,
allowing you to pick those you wish to block.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do I prevent my children from undoing the V-chip?
</P>
<P>
   A: You must have a personal ID number, just as you would with an
automatic banking card. This will be your password to change
settings and activate the V-chip.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do I have to buy a new TV to get a V-chip?
</P>
<P>
   A: A V-chip set-top box can be attached to your old TV set.
Check to see which stores carry them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I override the V-chip settings if I want to watch a
program?
</P>
<P>
   A: Turn it off by entering your code number and following the
directions for your TV set. Reactivate it the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will V-chip-equipped sets cost more?
</P>
<P>
   A: Manufacturers say the technology will add little, if
anything, to price.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
