<HEADLINE>
SAFETY FIRST: BULLS TAKE DUKE'S BRAND AT NO. 1
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They passed on the risk and potential of Lamar
Odom, the explosiveness of Steve Francis and an open invitation to
Wally Szczerbiak's world. In the end, the Chicago Bulls went
straight to the low post to rebuild their franchise, taking the
burly Duke forward Elton Brand on Wednesday night with the No. 1
pick of the National Basketball Association draft.
</P>
<P>
   After days of speculation over who would be taken first, or
whether he would trade the pick, Bulls General Manager Jerry Krause
went the safest route possible in selecting the 6-foot-8 inch,
275-pound Brand, the college player of the year, before a nearly
sold-out gathering at the MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the heritage and the championships, there is a lot of
pressure,'' Brand, who left Duke after his sophomore season, said
of playing for the Bulls. ``I'm looking forward to meeting that
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great anticipation. I didn't know who would go 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver picked Francis, the skywalking Maryland junior, with
the second choice, and Charlotte nabbed UCLA point guard Baron
Davis with the third pick. Odom, the draft's biggest enigma from
Rhode Island _ who wavered until the last minute about whether he
even wanted to enter the draft _ was taken fourth by the Los
Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Bulls drafted Michael Jordan, they weren't the best
team in the NBA,'' Odom said when asked about the Clippers'
tradition of losing. ``They have a new great arena, I'll be living
in L.A. If you ask for more than that, you're greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of the evening involved the Toronto Raptors passing
on Szcerzbiak, the Miami of Ohio all-American, and plucking
Jonathan Bender out of Picayune (Miss.) High School. Their plan was
to then trade Bender to the Indiana Pacers for Antonio Davis. The
Pacers, forgoing experience and maturity for the promise of youth,
were apparently ready to gamble on the 6-foot-10, 205-pound
18-year-old, who broke Michael Jordan's scoring record in the
McDonald's High School All-American Game.
</P>
<P>
   Szcerzbiak, the first senior taken, was drafted sixth by the
Minnesota Timberwolves. The host Wizards had the seventh pick, and
their selection of Connecticut swingman Richard Hamilton nearly
brought the house down with applause. Hamilton increased his stock
dramatically with a superb run through the NCAA tournament,
culminating in UConn's first national title. The only decibel level
close was when Francis raised his arms as he walked up to the
podium to shake the hand of Commissioner David Stern; in one,
scintillating year at Maryland, he became a D.C.-area fan favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Cavaliers took Utah's Andre Miller with the eighth
pick. Miller, the senior all-American, was part of a very strong
point guard contingent that included Davis, Duke's William Avery
and Arizona's Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Suns took the University of Nevada-Las Vegas forward
Shawn Marion with the ninth pick and the Atlanta Hawks, one day
after moving Mookie Blaylock to Golden State for Bimbo Coles, Duane
Ferrell and their No. 21 pick, took Terry with the 10th pick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
