<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUTYFREE-DEMISE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIFIED EUROPE ENDS MOST DUTY-FREE SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE FERRYBOAT DOVER, in the English Channel _ Wednesday
was the last day of duty-free shopping bounty that Europeans have
savored for five decades, and Stella Horton knew it.
</P>
<P>
   With determination and vigor, Mrs. Horton, long a buyer of
duty-free goods on the ferries that ply the Channel, set about
snapping up what she assumed would be the final bargains in the
closing hours before these sales within the 15-nation European
Union end at midnight Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Into her shopping basket went cigarettes at $2.50 a pack instead
of $6.50 in Britain and scotch at $20 instead of $30 a bottle.
Total outlay: $160. Total saving over British retail prices: $180.
</P>
<P>
   So slick was the duty-free shopping that she and her companion,
Dennis Pointer, both retirees from Ramsgate, England, didn't even
have to disembark when this car ferry _ a floating temple to
discount sales of everything from single malts to CDs _ berthed
briefly at Calais, France, then turned back for the 22-mile run to
Dover, England.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mrs. Horton and Pointer were shopping, duty-free
operators like the P&AMP;O Stena Line, which runs this ship, and
airport authorities across Europe were scrambling _ worried about
what the end of duty-free shopping in and offshore European Union
nations would mean for their own prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's decision to end such shopping was made
eight years ago on the basis that duty-free sales skew Europe's
vaunted single market. The International Duty-Free Confederation, a
trade group made up mainly of airports and ferry companies, fought
unsuccessfully to preserve the system, arguing that more than
140,000 jobs in the $6.5 billion annual business would be at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Many have sought to devise alternate ways of selling such goods.
Some are absorbing part of the costs themselves to keep discounted
prices in their stores. German ferry operators are contemplating
switching the destination of their ``butter cruises'' to
neighboring Poland, outside European Union limits, just as Finnish
ferry operators now say they will run duty-free shopping trips to
Estonia, also outside the union.
</P>
<P>
   Some British airport stores will continue to offer duty-free
goods to travelers leaving the European Union for countries like
the United States, Switzerland or Russia, while subsidizing
discounted liquor and other goods, though not cigarettes, to
travelers within the 15 countries _ all at the same airport stores.
</P>
<P>
   French and German airport operators forecast higher prices for
liquor and tobacco for travelers within the European Union, but
according to Wolfgang Schwalm, a spokesman for Frankfurt Main
International Airport, retailers will ``reduce profit margins to
maintain the current price level'' on such luxury goods as perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most curiously, ferries like this one will, as of
Friday, offer goods at French hypermarket prices _ two-thirds that
of many British shop prices because of lower excise taxes in France
_ but only when the vessel is halfway across the Channel and out of
British territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
   For Europe's supposed single market, that means Britons will pay
taxes to the French authorities for goods they consume back home in
Britain, robbing their own tax collectors of revenue. The price of
some purchases like Scotch whisky will stay the same, while
cigarettes become more expensive, but still less costly than in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a farce,'' said Jim Biggs, 48, from Deal in Kent,
who was planning to shop in a low-priced French hypermarket
Wednesday before returning to England. ``I think a group of men in
gray suits made a decision without understanding the economic
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   But the end of duty-free shopping also means the end of the
limitations that European authorities placed on just how many
duty-free cigarettes and bottles of liquor and perfume travelers
could import _ generally 200 cigarettes, one liter of spirits and
two liters of wine for each person.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they bring in the French taxes, we'll be able to bring in
as much as we like,'' said Melvyn Lethaby, a crane driver from
Dartford who was shopping with his daughter, Michelle May, and who
had just bought 24 cans of Foster's lager for half the British
price. (British customs officials say this is not exactly true:
travelers will be expected to honor an informal _ and nominal _
limit of 10 liters of spirits, 110 liters of beer and 800
cigarettes.)
</P>
<P>
   BAA PLC, the British airport authority that runs Heathrow,
London's principal airport, and six others, says it plans to spend
around $70 million a year on subsidizing the prices paid for some
goods, though not cigarettes or low-cost liquor, for sale to the 20
percent of passengers traveling within the European Union. The hope
is that ``where we are going to lose out by discounting, the
volumes will increase,'' said Abigail Rowland, a BAA spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   And Gail Isted, a spokeswoman for P&AMP;O Stena Line, which is a
unit of Peninsular &AMP; Oriental Steam Navigation Co., said,
``Duty-free was low volumes with high margins,'' acknowledging what
many travelers had suspected for years: that duty-free purchases
were not always the bargains they seemed.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the spread of duty- and tax-free sales from
liquor and tobacco to silk scarves and cameras had built a growing
business on the balance sheets of ferry and airport operators and
airlines. P&AMP;0 Stena Line, for instance, says that the $200 million
people spend each year on shopping, food and drinks contributes
one-third of its income.
</P>
<P>
   And BAA has increased landing fees by 5 percent to compensate
for lost income from duty-free sales, deepening the fear that
whatever is ultimately lost from ending the system will be passed
along to fliers in the form of higher fares.
</P>
<P>
   European duty-free shopping for travelers was introduced in
Ireland in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   But with the concept of a European single market taking shape in
the early 1990s, duty-free sales began to seem to some European
officials like an anomaly that gave some businesses an unfair
competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The argument went back and forth. In the end, Denmark persuaded
wavering members of the European Union to stand firm against the
urging of retailers and travelers that tonight's deadline be
extended. The Danes did so at their peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't buying their Danish bacon no more,'' Pointer said.
``That's for sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
