<HEADER>
A5238 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-FEES-BOS &LR;      06-30 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-FEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW FIRM IN TOBACCO CASE MAY SEEK ADDITIONAL FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The law firm seeking $460 million in legal fees from
an arbitration panel for its work on the Massachusetts tobacco
settlement said Wednesday it will consider seeking additional fees
from the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly said he would vigorously
oppose any such effort by Brown Rudnick Freed &AMP; Gesmer, which has a
contract with the state to share 25 percent of Massachusetts' $8.3
billion payment from the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the panel decides, it will be a massive amount of
money and at some point, enough is enough,'' Reilly said. His
predecessor, Scott Harshbarger, negotiated the 25
percent &UR;  &LR; contingency-fee contract in 1995 with five law firms to
pursue the case.
</P>
<P>
   A three-member arbitration panel, created out of the national
settlement between the states and the tobacco industry to negotiate
legal fees, was expected to announce its decision soon in the
Massachusetts case. The legal fee, to be paid by the tobacco
industry, is expected to be the largest ever received by
Massachusetts law firms.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Rudnick and the four other firms are asking for about $2
billion from the industry, claiming it is a ``fair and reasonable
fee.'' Under the attorney general's contract, the firms would be
entitled to an additional $2.075 billion, or one-quarter of the
money that Massachusetts is scheduled to collect from the national
settlement well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas M. Sobol, lead attorney for Brown Rudnick in the tobacco
case, said Wednesday that he accepts Reilly's reaction. ``It's
understandable that someone would need to act in a protectionist
way but, on immediate reflection, recognize the huge goal that we
collaboratively achieved,'' Sobol said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will take some time for the new leadership (at the
attorney general's office) to understand the depth'' of the
agreement ``and the true victory that was achieved,'' Sobol said.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger Wednesday said he agreed with Reilly's position to
resist making any payments from the settlement funds to the
lawyers. The arbitration panel, he said, was created to resolve the
issues of fees and take the place of the contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope they would find that kind of resolution
agreeable,'' Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   Sobol and Brown Rudnick Chairman Andre C. Jasse said the value
of the firm's arbitration award will not be known for at least 18
months, or until lawyers for all the states have undergone the
process. Only then, they said, will the firm know how much it will
receive per year under the $500 million annual cap established for
dispersing these legal fees nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Over 25 years or more, Sobol said, the award might be worth only
35 percent of its 1999 face value.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Rudnick, which will receive 23 percent of the award, spent
millions of dollars and invested tens of thousands of work hours in
a case that many legal observers believed was a long shot at best
when undertaken in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said he respects the risks the law firms took and the
work they performed. But he said both state law and the rules of
professional responsibility restrict lawyers to a ``fair and
reasonable fee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I am concerned, the arbitration panel will determine
what is fair and reasonable in these circumstances,'' Reilly said.
``And that should be the end of it. There should be no further
claims to any moneys that are due to the state of Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasse said Brown Rudnick's award from the arbitration process
might be subject to legal attack from the industry and other
states, and that ruling out an attempt to collect more money from
Massachusetts is premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have ongoing talks with the attorney general,'' Jasse
said.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Sobol argued, the measure of a monetary award is
not in dollars alone. ``If one looks for a quantitative measure,
the first and best measure is the results achieved,'' Sobol said.
</P>
<P>
   And those results, according to Brown Rudnick, include a
settlement that is toppling cigarette billboards, targeting teenage
smoking, establishing national foundations to combat tobacco use,
and funneling billions of dollars to the states to offset the cost
of treating smoking-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds to me like a good victory and the best
quantitative way to measure whether a lawyer has done his job or
not,'' Sobol said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said health care experts have estimated the value of
the settlement to be $65 billion in medical savings and other
costs, and in hundreds of thousands of life years for Massachusetts
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Sobol and Jasse said the firm will establish a committee to
study the merits of charitable requests, many of which have already
been received by Brown Rudnick. ``The firm has a long history of
giving to the community, and we clearly intend to seriously
consider that,'' Sobol said. ``There are a lot of important causes
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The arbitration panel, meeting in Denver, was scheduled to
announce its Massachusetts award by 2 a.m. EST Thursday. In
addition to Brown Rudnick, the other law firms hired for the
Massachusetts case are Schneider Reilly Zabin &AMP; Costello and
Thornton Early &AMP; Naumes, both of Boston; Ness Motley Loadholt
Richardson &AMP; Poole, of Charleston, S.C.; and Lieff Cabrasser
Heimann &AMP; Bernstein of San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
