<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-SUED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRED EMPLOYEE SUES FIDELITY INVESTMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A former midlevel Fidelity Investments executive and
one-time rising star who was fired last year for cheating on his
income taxes is suing the mutual fund behemoth, alleging that he
was unjustly forced out.
</P>
<P>
   The former executive, Robert G. Flater, was a $900,000-a-year
senior manager who was responsible for Fidelity's international
defined-contribution pension services, a unit with operations in
Canada and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Flater, 40, filed suit on Tuesday against the nation's biggest
fund firm in Suffolk County Superior Court. He is seeking
unspecified damages for wrongful discharge, breach of contract,
civil rights violations, emotional distress, violation of privacy,
and defamation.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we haven't seen the complaint, we don't believe it has
any merit or is legally justified,'' said a Fidelity spokeswoman,
Anne Crowley. She said that Flater's tax problems were not related
to Fidelity's operations.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, Flater was indicted on several misdemeanor and
felony accounts pertaining to his nonpayment of personal taxes and
failure to file tax returns between 1992 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He was arraigned on the charges in May 1998, paid the back taxes
and $50,000 in fines, and was immediately released, according to a
copy of his lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity fired Flater, who had been based in London, one month
later. He has been unemployed ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-evasion charges covered filing periods preceeding
Flater's employment at Fidelity. The Boston resident, who graduated
from Harvard Business School, joined Fidelity in December 1996 from
AT Kearney, where he was a vice president of the consulting firm's
financial institutions group.
</P>
<P>
   Flater's lawsuit said Flater was highly regarded at Fidelity,
where senior executives had considered promoting him to chief
executive of the firm's Japan operations. Flater sat on Fidelity's
European Operating Committee, an important group that takes
strategy and operational decisions. He reported to Robert L.
Reynolds, a top Fidelity executive who oversees Fidelity's $322
billion retirement business, the nation's largest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more or less, we feel, terminated illegally,'' said one
of his attorneys, Philip A. Tracy Jr., of Boston law firm DiMento &AMP;
Sullivan. Tracy confirmed Flater's tax problems but said Fidelity
had no right to fire him because it was a personal, not corporate,
matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
