<SLUG> BC-UNDERWRITING-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MARKET PLACE: SECURITIES UNDERWRITING DIPPED IN 2nd QUARTER  
 (bl)  
 By SHOLNN FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street's core business _ the underwriting of
stocks and bonds _ slowed slightly in the second quarter as market
interest rates rose.
</P>
<P>
   Securities firms and banks issued $553.1 billion of bonds and
stocks, according to Thomson Financial Securities Data, a drop of
nearly 11 percent from $620 billion in the second quarter of 1998.
It was also down 9 percent from the first quarter of this year. The
firms' performances were particularly weak in June, at $157 billion
in new issues, the smallest monthly total so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty about the outlook for interest rates knocked a chunk
out of the debt business. Over all, the volume of corporate debt
issued fell 11 percent, to $495.3 billion, in the quarter from a
year earlier. The amount of new high-yield securities, the
low-rated issues sometimes referred to as junk, fell 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of the year, only Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and
Salomon Smith Barney had more than $100 billion in debt
underwriting volume, while four firms did so last year. Morgan
Stanley's debt underwriting fell 28 percent from a year ago, while
that of Goldman, Sachs dropped by about 32 percent in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   The much-anticipated decision yesterday by the Federal Reserve
to raise a key short-term interest rate by one-quarter of a
percentage point could have helped clear the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors became cautious as interest rate fears took over the
market, especially by the last month of the second quarter,'' said
Ernesto Cruz, head of equity capital markets at Credit Suisse First
Boston. ``With the completion of the Fed's action we might see some
stability in interest rates and recovery in new issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch continued to lead securities firms in total
underwriting volume. In the second quarter of the year the firm
handled about 14 percent of the stock and bond volume. Salomon
Smith Barney placed second, followed by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
and Goldman, Sachs. Credit Suisse First Boston knocked off Lehman
Brothers to finish in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly rankings of securities firms, known as league
tables, are closely watched within the industry as an indicator of
which banks and brokerage houses are strongest. Goldman, Sachs led
Merrill Lynch by one key measure, underwriting fees, in large part
because of its lucrative business with hot Internet stocks. In the
first half of the year, Goldman, Sachs saw a 22 percent gain in
fees to $900 million. The other top firms reported sharp declines
in fees. Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley, which finished second
and third respectively, saw fees drop by more than 25 percent in
the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the coveted role of underwriting initial public offerings of
stock, Goldman dominated in the most recent quarter. It underwrote
$5.6 billion worth of new issues for 35 percent of the total
market. Goldman brought public Etoys and TheStreet.com, among
others. But its biggest issue was the $3.7 billion public offering
of Goldman itself. Without its own issue, Goldman would have edged
out Morgan Stanley, which handled $1.8 billion in initial stock
offerings, by just $200 million in the latest quarter. Morgan
Stanley had about a 12 percent market share.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman came close to doubling its market share in the much
bigger field of underwriting stock offerings by companies that are
already public. In all, the industry underwrote $56 billion in the
latest quarter, $3 billion less than a year earlier, in what are
called secondary equity offerings. After Goldman came Morgan
Stanley, which took second place away from Merrill Lynch. Salomon
Smith Barney and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette completed the top
five.
</P>
<P>
   Merger and acquisition activity fell by 19 percent, to $552
billion in the second quarter, from $681 billion a year ago, based
on the value of the announced deals. Goldman, Sachs won the race,
but lost market share, barely edging out Merrill Lynch. Goldman
handled $193 billion in U.S. deals, for a 34.9 percent share,
besting Merrill by a 0.1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
