<HEADER>
A5246 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ANCHORS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-30 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANCHORS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 OLD FACES IN THE NEWS: Networks' venerable anchors could be
the  last of their breed  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anchors away?
</P>
<P>
   Not at the top rung of television journalism _ not in this
decade, and not in the last half of the 1980s, either.
</P>
<P>
   A generation has come of age without a change among the major
anchors at ABC, CBS and NBC. And while the newscasts switch times
and titles at CNN, the cable network's main anchor has been in
place for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   Only Walter Cronkite and David Brinkley lasted about as long at
the top as Peter Jennings, Dan Rather, Tom Brokaw and Bernard Shaw.
Chances are, the stability of the current configuration will never
be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the anchor jobs have their rewards, including the
excitement of the news business and the allure of heavy paychecks.
Jennings, Rather and Brokaw are believed to make in the
neighborhood of $7 million a year. Shaw, whose salary may be less
than a million, is the ``poor'' man of the anchor bunch.
</P>
<P>
   But the jobs would also be daunting to ordinary working stiffs.
The work demands are fierce, a free weekend can be a rarity, the
work is sometimes dangerous, ratings are a constant if
unacknowledged worry, anchors' lives are governed by unexpected
events and, to a ridiculous extent, they are expected to be
authorities on practically everything.
</P>
<P>
   The last period of anchor turmoil was from 1980 to 1983. Shaw,
who'd been a reporter at CBS and ABC, joined CNN at its inception
in 1980. Jennings had been the London wheel on ABC's three-man
anchor team, becoming solo anchor after Frank Reynolds died in
1983. Brokaw was teamed with Roger Mudd in 1982 and appointed sole
anchor a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, as usual, was embroiled in the most controversy. He
replaced Cronkite, the most trusted news figure of his era. And
although Cronkite had been contemplating retirement or at least
semi-retirement for years, many people believed that Cronkite was
shoved aside prematurely in 1981 to make room for the brash Rather,
who'd been courted by ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Cronkite's heir apparent had been Mudd; some within CBS
resented Mudd being passed over for Cronkite. One of them was Mudd
himself, who quit and went to NBC.
</P>
<P>
   All that is far behind Rather now. His problems these days are
with the ratings, with the decline of broadcast network news in
general and with the slippage of the networks' evening newscasts in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   The audiences are smaller, the newscasts aren't the priorities
they once were, and much of the emphasis has shifted to the
prime-time newsmagazines as well as to the morning news programs.
</P>
<P>
   And with competition from cable, the advent of digital TV and
prospect of fusing TV and computers, the broadcast networks'
long-range commitment to hard-news coverage is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dinner hour is over,'' Kyle Pope of the Wall Street
Journal wrote in the current issue of Media Studies Journal. He
meant Americans' archaic habit of ingesting their electronic news
at 5:30 or 6 p.m. News, Pope wrote, ``is becoming a niche game'' in
a ``made-to-order TV news landscape'' where set-piece newscasts
aren't a factor.
</P>
<P>
   That seemingly could spell the end of the bigfoot news anchors.
Arguably, Jennings, Rather and Brokaw will be the last of their
breed. Shaw, whose role is more limited, is closer to the future
model.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, these news plow horses are in the same
harnesses they've worn for about two decades each.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll be the first to go? They all seem secure for the moment.
But if you must bet on the first departure, put the money on
Rather. It's easy to figure. He's the oldest, and the ``CBS Evening
News'' occupies third place in the Nielsen ratings. A year or so
ago, CBS nearly let Rather go to CNN, before raising his pay and
re-signing him.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens to Rather, he'll always carry a unique
distinction. He covered the John F. Kennedy assassination, the
Vietnam War, Watergate and dozens of major stories since he became
CBS' chief anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the Greek historian Herodotus and scan the world
pageant to the present. Probably no one, ever, has personally
witnessed more history than Dan Rather. There's a perk to add to
the paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
