<SLUG> BC-WORTHINGTON-SALE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARRIOTT PLANS TO BUY WORTHINGTON HOTEL IN FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SANDRA BAKER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, texas _ Marriott International plans to buy The
Worthington hotel, one of Fort Worth's most recognizable pieces of
real estate and a cornerstone of downtown revitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Center Hotel Co., an entity of the Bass Cos. of Fort Worth, has
agreed to sell the 504-room, four-star upscale hotel to Marriott,
the hotel told its employees in a letter. The two sides expect to
complete the deal in the next few months, probably by Aug. 25, the
letter says.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kolba, an executive with the Bass Cos., which is controlled
by Fort Worth's billionaire Bass family, declined to offer many
details regarding the sale Wednesday, except to confirm that the
hotel sent letters to employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, all I can say is, we are in very, very, very
serious negotiations with Marriott,'' he said. ``These negotiations
have gone on and on. We can see light at the end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolba emphasized that the sale is not final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either party can walk away from a deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Executives with Washington, D.C.-based Marriott could not be
reached to comment. Marriott officials referred calls to Kolba.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jameson, hotel president and general manager, says in the
letter sent to the hotel's 400 employees that once the deal is
final, employees will have to apply for positions with Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   However, all hourly employee will probably receive jobs when the
employment process is completed, the letter says.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel will schedule an employee meeting, at which Marriott
representatives will talk about the company, employment
opportunities and the transition process, the letter says.
</P>
<P>
   Which one of its nameplates Marriott would attach to the hotel
is unclear. Marriott operates hotels internationally through 13
nameplates, and The Worthington's letter to employees does not
specify which brand Marriott would use.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott operates three high-end hotel nameplates: Marriott
Hotels, Resorts and Suites; Renaissance; and Ritz-Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott Hotels, Marriott International's most visible
nameplate, is the company's line of upscale full-service hotels. It
has 246 upscale hotels in the United States and 85 internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance _ an upscale line of full-service hotels for
business travelers, group meetings, and resort travelers _ has 34
upscale hotels in the United States and 49 internationally.
Renaissance hotels typically offer multiple restaurants, business
centers, swimming pools and health clubs, and conference and
banquet facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ritz-Carlton, Marriott's renowned luxury nameplate, has 20 U.S.
hotels and 15 internationally. Amenities include 24-hour room
service and twice-daily housekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about a Worthington sale had circulated for a few years
but resurfaced in April, when Marriott took over the management of
the historic, renovated Blackstone Hotel in downtown Fort Worth.
The Courtyard by Marriott chain operates the Blackstone.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Region, executive director of the Hotel Association of
Tarrant County, said Wednesday that he is saddened to think about
The Worthington changing hands, referring to the property as one of
the best-operated hotels in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few hotels operate with a quality team as The
Worthington,'' he said. ``It seems like a closing of an era. I'm
sure Marriott will do a fine job; they are one of the better hotel
operators.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction of The Worthington began in 1978. The property
became an anchor in the Bass family's Sundance Square, the center
of a revitalization of downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel opened in 1981 as the Americana. The name was changed
to The Worthington in 1985, and the hotel became independently
owned and operated by the Basses.
</P>
<P>
   The Worthington would be the first sale of any Bass Family
property in the Sundance Square development, Kolba said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
