<SLUG> BC-TV-ANCHORS-PROFILES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG FOUR OF TV NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use with TV-ANCHORS-SFCHRON  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAN RATHER, ``CBS Evening News.''
</P>
<P>
   DATE OF BIRTH: Oct. 31, 1931, Wharton, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY STATUS: Married (wife Jean), two children.
</P>
<P>
   ANCHOR SINCE: 1981.
</P>
<P>
   BIG MOMENTS: Coverage of Hurricane Carla in 1961, for local TV
in Houston, brought him to attention of CBS News; famous news
conference confrontation with President Nixon (Nixon: ``Are you
running for something?'' Rather: ``No, sir, Mr. President, are
you?'') in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE POINTS: Reportorial intensity, Southern manners,
occasional penchant for bizarre incidents, flair for organizational
survival, Texasisms (``We're on that story like a raven on
roadkill'').
</P>
<P>
   LEISURE TIME: Fly-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACT EXPIRES: 2002.
</P>
<P>
   POST-ANCHOR CAREER: Insists that he wants to stay in journalism
as long as he's physically able. Jokes that he might become
Associated Press bureau chief in Alpine, Texas (population 5,637).
Actually, in Ratherese, that's about as likely as a stick with one
end.
</P>
<P>
   LIKELY SUCCESSOR: CBS correspondent John Roberts, not exactly a
household name, is being given some serious resume polishing. The
weekend anchor was sent to Serbia to cover the NATO bombing and has
just been named chief White House correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   TOM BROKAW, ``NBC Nightly News.''
</P>
<P>
   DATE OF BIRTH: Feb. 6, 1940, Yankton, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY STATUS: Married (wife Meredith is a former Miss South
Dakota), three children.
</P>
<P>
   ANCHOR SINCE: 1982 (sole anchor since 1983).
</P>
<P>
   BIG MOMENT: Was on the scene for dramatic coverage in Berlin in
1989, when exuberant Germans began tearing down the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE POINTS: Easygoing delivery, unflappable demeanor. Huge
capacity for work earlier in career won him half-joking nickname
``Duncan the Wonder Horse.'' Known as adroit NBC infighter. The
best ``pipes'' of all the anchors, though slight speech impediment
led to the josh that ``he doesn't use all 26.''
</P>
<P>
   LEISURE TIME: Fishing in Montana, travel to rugged, exotic
destinations worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACT EXPIRES: 2002.
</P>
<P>
   POST-ANCHOR CAREER: Would be ideal host for National Geographic
programs or cable travel and adventure series.
</P>
<P>
   LIKELY SUCCESSOR: Brian Williams, neat as a pin and anchoring at
MSNBC, is the most thoroughly groomed man-in-waiting since Prince
Charles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   PETER JENNINGS, ``ABC World News Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   DATE OF BIRTH: July 29, 1938, Toronto, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY STATUS: Married (Kayce Freed, a ``20/20'' producer, is
his third wife), two children from previous marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ANCHOR SINCE: 1965 to 1968 (beginning at age 26), then ``World
News Tonight'' in 1978 (became sole anchor in 1983).
</P>
<P>
   BIG MOMENT: Was in Cairo when Egyptian President Anwar Sadat was
assassinated in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE POINTS: Canada dry. A high school dropout who was derided
as a slick ``pretty boy'' during his first, disastrous anchor
stint, Jennings earned respect as ABC's Beirut bureau chief for six
years; has reputation as biggest internationalist among the news
anchors, and for understanding Arab points of view.
</P>
<P>
   LEISURE TIME: Boating, listening to jazz.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACT EXPIRES: 2002.
</P>
<P>
   POST-ANCHOR CAREER: Could turn to writing after the success of
``The Century,'' which was authored by Jennings and (mostly) Todd
Brewster.
</P>
<P>
   LIKELY SUCCESSOR: Hard to say. ABC splurged on talent for two
decades before cutting back recently, yet has no obvious
anchor-in-waiting. Diane Sawyer, a dutiful soldier these days on
``Good Morning America,'' would have to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   BERNARD SHAW, CNN.
</P>
<P>
   DATE OF BIRTH: May 22, 1940, Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY STATUS: Married (wife Linda), two children.
</P>
<P>
   ANCHOR SINCE: 1980.
</P>
<P>
   BIG MOMENTS: Covered early hours of Operation Desert Storm from
high-rise hotel in Baghdad, Iraq, with John Holliman and Peter
Arnett in 1991; shocked everyone in second presidential debate of
1988 by asking Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis if the rape and
murder of his wife, Kitty, would turn him in favor of capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE POINTS: Bluntness _ admitted after his Baghdad coup that
his wife had been in anguish because he was in harm's way and
added, ``No story is worth the loss of a human life. We were
pushing the margin in Baghdad. ... I have decided that I will never
put her and our children through that kind of stress again.
Never.''
</P>
<P>
   LEISURE TIME: Gardening, reading, listening to jazz.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACT EXPIRES: CNN refuses to say.
</P>
<P>
   POST-ANCHOR CAREER: Could vanish from public view, except to
pick up honorary doctorates, and devote himself to private life
with his family.
</P>
<P>
   LIKELY SUCCESSOR: Judy Woodruff if it's any time soon; she's
already sharing anchor duties with him. It's a crapshoot past that,
though Willow Bay is regarded as a rising star at CNN.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
