<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-STOCKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS RALLY OVER FED'S MODEST RATE HIKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve nudged up a key interest rate
for the first time in more than two years Wednesday but still
managed to tickle investors by dropping its stated ``bias'' toward
higher rates down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the celebratory mood on Wall Street, economists warned
the Fed action still leaves open the possibility for a further rate
increase later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   As widely expected, Fed policy-makers voted to raise the federal
funds rate _ that's the interest rate banks charge one another for
overnight loans _ by a modest quarter of a percentage point to 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, however, left the less-used discount rate unchanged at
4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a curve ball that's been coming at us for the last
two months,'' said Bob Dickey, managing director for technical
analysis for Dain Rauscher in Minneapolis. ``Everybody saw it
coming. It was not a surprise. In fact, it was a relief that we
finally got it out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Close on the heals of the Fed, numerous commercial banks _ led
by Bank of America _ announced plans to raise their prime lending
rates a quarter of a point to 8 percent. The prime is a bank's
benchmark rate often used to determine everything from car loans to
credit card rates.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the Fed lowered interest rates three times for a
total of three quarters of a percentage point because of concerns
about the effects of the world economic crisis on financial markets
here at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then, much of the financial strain has eased, foreign
economies have firmed, and economic activity in the United States
has moved forward at a brisk pace,'' Fed officials said in a
prepared statement. ``Accordingly, the full degree of adjustment is
judged no longer necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan had all but telegraphed the central
bank's intent to raise rates during testimony on Capitol Hill two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little children in Guatemala could have told you that,'' noted
Larry Wachtel, market analyst for Prudential Securities in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors were fearful the Fed would try to raise rates a
half a percentage point, although such moves are not consistent
with Greenspan's style.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors were pleasantly surprised, however, by the Fed's
announcement that it was assuming a ``neutral'' stance on monetary
policy, assuming no bias toward higher or lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owing to the uncertain resolution of the balance of
conflicting forces in the economy going forward, the (Federal Open
Market Committee) has chosen to adopt a directive that includes no
predilection about near-term policy action,'' Fed officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors took that statement to mean the Fed was not _ as
feared _ starting what would be a series of incremental rate
increases.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average, which had dropped about 50
points prior to the announcement, rebounded more than 200 points to
close at 10,970.80, up 155.45 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite, dominated by technology stocks, rose 44.11
to hit an all-time high of 2868.12, while the Standard &AMP; Poors 500
rose 21.29 points to close at a record 1,372.74.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market, meanwhile, rallied in response to the Fed
action.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 9/32
points, or $12.81 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves
in the opposite direction, fell to 5.96 percent from 6.06 percent
late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But investors may be reading more into the Fed's statement than
policy makers actually intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no clue, no trend, no reason to give us any kind of
direction,'' Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, back in 1994, the Fed raised interest rates six times
and assumed a neutral stance after every move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't necessarily mean that they're done,'' said Bryan
Jordan, economics analyst for Banc One Investment Advisors in
Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fed policy makers are conceding they are confused by
the current state of the economy, with its strong growth, extremely
low unemployment rate and barely perceptible inflation rate,
economists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we get a number that looks a little scary we get
another number that seems to balance things off,'' Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Fed officials will be watching the latest
unemployment data. If that information shows the labor market is
continuing to tighten, that could indicate pressure on employers to
raise wages, which could then spark more inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Fed decision makers also will be watching oil prices over the
next several weeks, since spikes in energy prices can affect costs
in numerous industries.
</P>
<P>
   Crude prices Wednesday jumped 85 cents a barrel to hit $19.29 a
barrel, their highest level since November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Fed officials opted to raise rates despite pleas from all parts
of the political spectrum. The National Association of
Manufacturers insisted a rate hike ``is simply not warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential hopeful Steve Forbes argued the Fed
``has no business hurting the economy in the name of a theory _ the
so-called Phillips curve, which posits there is a correlation
between prosperity and rising inflation _ that history has proven
to be utterly bogus.''
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney warned: ``Working families will
pay the price of a mistaken tightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rubin, the outgoing Treasury secretary, and Janet Yellen,
the head of the Council of Economic Advisers, said in a joint
statement: ``We believe that the economy will continue on a sound
path.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
