<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PRIVATELY HELD FORBES CONSIDERS IPO  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The Internet has a way of making old established businesses do
funny things.
<P>
   Take Forbes, for instance. Not only has the venerable New York
business magazine taken the unusual step of letting publisher Rich
Karlgaard keep his home base in Burlingame, but now the privately
held company is seriously considering an initial public offering
for its online units.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the markets are still strong, ``we look to do an IPO
this fall,'' Karlgaard said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has retained the investment bank Goldman, Sachs to
handle the offering, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is run by four brothers, the sons of legendary editor
Malcolm Forbes and the grandsons of B.C. Forbes, who founded the
magazine in 1917. (One brother, Steve Forbes, is running for the
Republican presidential nomination, but Karlgaard couldn't talk
about that.) ``It's like a big family farm,'' Karlgaard said. ``The
idea of not being a private company is so alien to the brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   But after watching newcomers like TheStreet.com and CBS
MarketWatch.com score millions of dollars in the stock market,
Forbes is ready to loosen its resistance to public ownership, if
only for the Internet division.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes.com is bulking up to an editorial staff of 40. It's
headquartered in New York, and it has a new executive editor, Kevin
McKean, who built Money magazine's Web site, and a new West Coast
bureau chief, former San Francisco Chronicle reporter David
Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   It's also launched an edgy new ad campaign that features young
slacker-types with slogans such as ``No salary earning, old
underpants wearing, billionaire on paper CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   An IPO would not only provide cash for further online expansion
and promotion, Karlgaard said, but ``it's critical to attract
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to Net stock status is accompanied by a general
improvement in the magazine's technology coverage, led both by
Forbes' new editor, William Baldwin, and by new Silicon Valley
bureau chief Elizabeth Corcoran, late of the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Although the magazine owes much of its style and success to
former editor Jim Michaels, who retired last year after 37 years at
the helm, Karlgaard said Michaels' emphasis on value investing and
his contrarian views led Forbes to fall behind in its technology
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had probably a too-negative tone about technology companies
in the '90s,'' said Karlgaard. ``It was the only thing Jim ever
called wrong in a glorious 40-year career.''
</P>
<P>
   Karlgaard, 44, who today marks his first anniversary as Forbes'
publisher, brought impressive tech credentials to the job. He had
co-founded Upside magazine in 1989, and went on to launch the
bimonthly tech supplement Forbes ASAP in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He said Forbes still will bring a contrarian tone to its Silicon
Valley coverage, and he derided competitors _ particularly Fortune
_ as ``cheerleaders.''
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, if you can't persuade the market that Internet stocks
are overvalued, you might as well create your own.
</P>
<P>
   SALON STRIKES BACK: After his company's initial public offering
last week, Salon.com President and CEO Michael O'Donnell took some
time off at Lake Tahoe. But he found the mosquitoes irritating: ``I
think I have that kind of skin that they love to go after.''
</P>
<P>
   The tiny stings come after several months in which media
mosquitoes have also been nipping at Salon.com. Its IPO may have
been trashed more than any other since Wired's was hounded from
ever reaching the market.
</P>
<P>
   Critics ripped Salon's business model as basically selling ads
for online literature _ a model, they said, that doesn't take
advantage of the medium, and is basically the same basis for such
money-losing journals of opinion as the National Review.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the IPO priced at a mere $10.50 and the stock
continued to fizzle, critics gloated that they were right.
(Yesterday it closed at $9.50, up 38 cents.)
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, freed from the shackles of the pre-IPO quiet period,
pointed out that the offering raised $26 million for the company,
on the heels of a $14 million private placement, and it did it
while Internet stocks were getting hammered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sector was down 30 percent from the time we filed to the
time we went out,'' he said. Salon now boasts a valuation of $102
million.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MEDIA01 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Salon will now double its sales staff and start updating stories
more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell said the company's 1.3 million unique users dwarf the
readership numbers at many elite offline magazines (Harper's, for
instance, has 215,000 readers), and that the magazine gets its
revenues from a variety of sources: online advertising, e-commerce
(it takes a cut when it refers purchasers to other sites, such as
online bookstores), subscriptions (through its subsidiary, The
Well) and through syndication deals with other media, such as
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed at how our media brethren took potshots
at us during the quiet period,'' O'Donnell said. ``A lot of media
were cheering for us to fail. It was disappointing for them ... But
we don't harbor any resentment. We're just going forward and doing
our job.''
</P>
<P>
   PO KNOWS WIRED: In some way, the party Wired magazine threw for
author Po Bronson last week resembled countless other Silicon
Valley launch fetes, even as it spoofed them.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Bronson was launching his book, ``The Nudist on
the Late Shift,'' with a soiree at the appropriately named Buck's
Restaurant in Woodside.
</P>
<P>
   People munched cookies emblazoned with a reproduction of the
Wired cover featuring Bronson and four of his subjects. Stacks of
hardcover books were given away like so much Silicon Valley
software. In his reading, Bronson was continually interrupted on
his cell phone in a staged haggle with a source over a story.
</P>
<P>
   He also produced a 44-pound box of nondisclosure agreements he
had to sign, which every Valley company always tries to foist on
journalists and any other person who represents a threat to the
secrecy of their plans.
</P>
<P>
   He honored none of them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With this book, Bronson, an accomplished novelist (``The First
$20 Million Is Always the Hardest''), has dived back into
nonfiction. ``The true story was always more interesting than the
made-up story,'' said Bronson. ``The little twists and turns that
really happen are such gems.''
</P>
<P>
   YEAH, BABY! It's been a long time coming, but the deal to make
Wired Digital a part of Lycos is all but complete. The Wired
shareholders put aside their bickering ways and voted Tuesday to
accept an estimated $285 million in stock. Look for an official
announcement today.
</P>
<P>
   Wired Digital _ once known as HotWired, and now cleaved from the
pioneering tech magazine _ employs 160 people, including 125 in San
Francisco. Inktomi, which provides the company with some technology
for its HotBot search engine, treated the San Francisco employees
to a free daytime showing of ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' at the new
Metreon cinema on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER CONVERT: Count Marshall Loeb among the latest to leave
the tactile satisfactions of print for the options-rich world of
dot-com journalism. Loeb, most recently the editor of the
prestigious Columbia Journalism Review, and before that the editor
of Fortune and Money magazines, now becomes a daily columnist for
the San Francisco financial news Web site, CBS MarketWatch.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been dying to do a lot of real-time writing,''
MarketWatch Editor in Chief Thom Calandra said. ``He'll either be
fabulously successful, or writing for a real-time Web site will
fizzle his circuits ... But he will have made our readers a lot of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   RADIO STARFISH: Philippe Kahn, the founder of such tech
companies as Borland International and Starfish Software and a man
who always seems to have the word ``flamboyant'' attached to his
name, debuted Monday as a radio talk show host on Santa Cruz's KSCO
1080 AM news and talk radio.
</P>
<P>
   On day one, instead of the info highway, Kahn stirred up
listeners with talk of a real highway, what he called, ``The death
trap _ Highway 17.''
</P>
<P>
   MEA CULPA: It doesn't get much worse than this. In last week's
column, I wrote about the Online News Association's efforts to
bring credibility to Internet journalism, and then I singled out
the corrections policy at the Industry Standard.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, I made a really dumb mistake. I referred to
Jonathan Weber, the editor in chief of The Standard, as Jonathan
Steinberg. (There really is a Jonathan Steinberg in the online
media world; he's the chief executive of Individual Investor. Why
Steinberg crept into my brain when I should have been typing Weber
is a mystery to me.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MEDIA01 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  If anything, I proved what everyone already knows: Newspapers
have been making mistakes since long before online journalism even
existed.
</P>
<P>
   GROK RULES: Since I owe Weber one, I might as well get it over
with. The Standard won six awards from the American Society of
Business Press Editors last week. While most of the booty was for
regional awards, the Standard's punchy e-mail newsletter Media
Grok, which critiques the technology press, won a national prize as
best original news section or newsletter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
