<HEADLINE>
RAPTORS-PACERS TRADE SPEAKS VOLUMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Toronto Raptors sent out a strong message Wednesday night
that they are tired of waiting. The Indiana Pacers sent a message
they are ready to start thinking about the future. Each team found
the other had what it wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers started their rebuilding program with the biggest
trade of the night, sending longtime strongman Antonio Davis to the
Raptors for the No. 5 pick. Toronto, selecting for the Pacers, then
took high schooler Jonathan Bender, who has some scouts drawing
comparisons with Kevin Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   It was a telling signal from the Pacers that what they had
wasn't enough in a league that is leaning more and more towards
athleticism. They found that out in their stunning loss to the
Knicks. Antonio Davis, who makes $4.2 million, became expendable
when Dale Davis decided not to exercise an opt-out clause in his
already substantial contract.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was soon joined by Serbian center Aleksandar Radojevic,
taken by Toronto with the 12th pick. The Raptors still don't have
the point guard they want, but still may be able to do something
with their cap space, although Davis eats away at some of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to send a message to our veteran players that we
want to win,'' said Toronto coach Butch Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors still have John Wallace, Charles Oakley and Michael
Stewart as free agents.
</P>
<P>
   More interesting is the Pacers' decision not to stand pat and
see their loss to the Knicks as an aberration. President Donnie
Walsh has long been seeking more athletic players, particularly at
small forward, which is where most NBA scouts feel Bender will
eventually play.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers have now used their first round pick on high school
players in each of the last two years, having taken Al Harrington
last season. Bender's stock had risen steadily as draft time
approached and Celtics' scout Leo Papile said that the Lakers were
trying to trade up to No. 2 to get the 6-11 forward from Picayune,
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana-Toronto deal was the only one which impacted the top
half of the draft. The Chicago Bulls, keeping everyone guessing to
the end, started things off by taking Duke's Elton Brand. The
ever-secretive GM Jerry Krause said the decision was a tough one,
but added Brand has long arms and big hands, a plus in any system.
</P>
<P>
   Brand was as much of a consensus No. 1 as possible in this
chaotic draft, but said, ``I didn't have the slightest idea'' when
asked if he thought he'd be taken by the Bulls. He will be their
power forward and will be joined along the front lines by St.
John's Ron Artest, who was taken 16th.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest shocker, by far, was Cleveland's selection of Trajan
Langdon at No. 11. The Cavs had taken Andre Miller at No. 8, the
pick they got from Boston in the Vitaly Potapenko-Andrew DeClercq
trade. Langdon was not thought to be a lottery pick - he went ahead
of more heralded Duke teammates William Avery and Corey Maggette -
and wasn't even present at the MCI Center, which is where the top
draftees were assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Cavs general manager Jim Paxson said the decision was made
solely due to Langdon's exquisite shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he was the second best shooter in the draft behind
Wally (Szczerbiak),'' Paxson said. ``He gives us someone who can
stretch defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggette went two spots later, 13th overall, to Seattle, giving
Duke three lottery picks in the same draft. It marks the first time
in the history of the lottery, which was instituted in 1985, that
three players from the same school have been chosen. In addition, a
fourth Dukie, Avery, went 14th to the Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   The saga of Lamar Odom, thought by many to be the most talented
player in the draft, ended quickly when he went fourth to the
Clippers. Odom had once been rated No. 1 by many scouts, but then
saw his stock drop in the last two weeks when he missed several
workouts, saw his agent resign, and then toyed breifly with the
possibility of returning to Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   This was a draft heavy in point guards and the top five were all
gone by the 14th pick. Steve Francis went immediately after Brand
to Vancouver and didn't look all that enthralled about it. The
Grizzlies rebuffed countless offers for the pick, and may
eventually deal Francis for the veteran power forward they feel
they need. Antonio Davis would have fit in nicely there.
</P>
<P>
   Baron Davis of UCLA (No. 3 to Charlotte), Miller (No. 8 to
Cleveland), Jason Terry (No. 10 to Atlanta) and Avery (14th to the
Wolves) were swooped up quickly. Radojevic was the first center
followed by another foreigner, Frederic Weis of France, who went to
the Knicks at No. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
