<HEADER>
A5253 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES01-CO     06-30 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker gets lesson in art of deception
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ On the plane ride here four days ago, Greg Maddux
found himself counseling John Rocker on the art of deception.
Rocker may have learned how to throw a slider for strikes but, as
he was harshly reminded recently, that is hardly half the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg was saying that when I come in when the game isn't on the
line, like with a five- or six-run lead, I should make a conscious
effort to pitch away from your pattern,'' Rocker said. ``Maybe go
out there and see if you can throw a full inning with no breaking
balls, so the hitters can't (A) get a look at the breaking ball,
and (B) catch what counts I throw it on.''
</P>
<P>
   That was something for Atlanta's closer to chew on the day after
his worst outing in the majors, serving the Expos a five-run ninth
inning, highlighted by Vladimir Guerrero's two-out game-winning
three-run homer. Rocker faced the Expos twice last week at home,
giving up a couple of hits, a walk but no runs.
</P>
<P>
   That had to be enough exposure for the Expos to decipher him. He
was victimized in his last visit to Olympic Park too, giving up a
ninth-inning homer to Chris Widger Sept. 9 in a 3-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like whatever I threw,'' he said, ``they were
exactly looking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the last questions posed on Rocker's scouting profile was
his ability to bounce back from failure. The depth of Rocker's
postgame anger Tuesday exceeded the major league norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you,'' manager Bobby Cox said, ``I think he
thrives on that, being hard on himself and being pysched up. Some
guys have to do that. He may be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm somewhere in that stage of my career where I'm
still trying to put up good numbers,'' Rocker said. ``Every
appearance to me is an opportunity to get my ERA down or protect it
from going up. Of course I'm a little more focused when it's a one-
or a two-run game.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Smoltz
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the elbow feels ready. No, he doesn't know how to make it
better.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz answered all the usual day-after questions after his
premature departure following just five innings Tuesday. It should
be known that coming out wasn't his idea, even while his elbow
stiffened up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to go another inning,'' Cox said. ``He was saying he
could go another one or two. But I said `No, let's shut it down
right now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, despite the stiffness _ Smoltz was shooting baskets
and passing a football Wednesday without difficulty _ he fully
expects to make his next start in New York Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is just pitch as much as I can and be ready for the
end of the year, don't jeopardize anything down the line,'' Smoltz
said. ``And that's just what Bobby did (Tuesday) night.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday night, the Braves had not lost a game after
leading by at least four runs in the ninth since April 18, 1993....
In the first eight games since Javy Lopez went on the disabled
list, Eddie Perez has caught 97.3 percent of the club's innings (71
of 73).... Since Ozzie Guillen began getting steady work at
shortstop in late May, he has picked up 98 points in his batting
average to .250.... Lopez, on the disabled list since June 21 with
a sprained knee, did not accompany the Braves to Montreal but might
join the team in New York for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
