<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-ADVANCE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pressure is on U.S. team in quarterfinal vs. Germany
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ The U.S. women's soccer team says it loves
nothing better than playing under pressure. The players might have
a chance to find out tonight in the World Cup quarterfinals against
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   They did it in the Atlanta Olympics, ousting Norway in a
dramatic overtime semifinal, then edging China in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   More than 55,000 fans are expected at Jack Kent Cooke Stadium
for the 7 p.m. opener of the quarterfinal doubleheader. A win by
the Americans would put them in the semifinals on July 4 against
either Brazil or Nigeria, who play at 9:30 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening the World Cup before a U.S. women's sporting-event
record of 78,972 in Giants Stadium, the American women have become
one of the biggest sports stories of the summer. They played before
an average crowd of 65,000 in group play, and ticket sales have
been brisk at Stanford Stadium and the Rose Bowl, where they would
continue their quest for the title.
</P>
<P>
   Their 3-0 win over North Korea on Sunday earned a rating of 1.92
on ESPN2, the best for a soccer match on the network that showed
the men's World Cup last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hearing that people who have never watched soccer are
starting to pay attention,'' U.S. defender Joy Fawcett said.
``We've always known what a great sport soccer is, and it's great
that other people are starting to see it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany, which gave up a last-second goal in a 3-3 draw with
Brazil on Sunday is coming off its best game thus far and is
quietly confident about its chances
</P>
<P>
   German defender Steffi Jones, whose father is an American, knows
enough Yank slang to say: ``We ain't gonna hide.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are 8-3-1 against Germany, earning a win and a tie
in two friendlies on U.S. soil last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're on the stage,'' American striker Cindy Parlow
said. ``But we don't feel any more pressure than what we put on
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
