<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Host Paraguay stumbles as Copa nears
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you believe Roberto Acuna's side of the story, he's
had to eat so much fish training for Paraguay's host role in the
Copa America that he's growing gills.
</P>
<P>
   The playmaking midfielder quit the team earlier this week,
citing coach Ever Almeida's fish-only diet. It's the latest bizarre
twist to the prelude of South America's biennial championship,
which began Tuesday under a cloud of prominent player no-shows and
other assorted disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   Before a booing crowd of 40,000 in the capital of Asuncion
Tuesday, Paraguay was held to a 0-0 draw with Bolivia, while Peru
held off Japan, one of two non-continental teams invited, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay goalkeeper Jose Luis Chilavert, his country's sporting
god, also is on the sidelines, protesting the money the government
is spending to host the 16-nation event.
</P>
<P>
   Acuna said a little more variety in his diet shouldn't be that
hard of a request to accommodate. ``They won't let me eat anything
else, but I can't eat fish all the time, and I certainly can't go
hungry,'' he said in a parting shot.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Brazil is bringing Ronaldo, Roberto Carlos
and a number of other top players, but striker Leonardo quit over
the weekend, apparently unhappy at being passed over for captain.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina will likely be able to contend, despite the omission
of strikers Gabriel Batistuta and Hernan Crespo, who apparently
have not gotten on the good side of coach Marcelo Bielsa.
Midfielder Juan Veron is recovering from a car accident, and
defender Jose Chamot and forward Claudio Lopez are sitting out,
fatigued after the recent end of the Spanish season
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay is hosting the 89-year-old Copa America, which ends on
July 18, for the first time, amid political and financial chaos.
Creaky stadiums got hasty renovations, and Brazilian fans had
enough serious concerns over security that they considered staying
home until government officials pledged more police protection.
</P>
<P>
   In March, vice president Luis Argana was assassinated, and a
former army general helping to organize the tournament was
implicated in the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to prompt Chilavert, the star of Paraguay's
second-round performance in the World Cup last year, to announce
his boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Fiorentina signs 2
</P>
<P>
   Two forwards on the outs with their club teams were picked up
last week by Fiorentina, which is seeking a new partnership up
front with Gabriel Batistuta. Italian Enrico Chiesa, released by
Parma after scoring 18 goals, came with a transfer tag of $18.8
million, while Yugoslav international Predrag Mijatovic was seeking
new employment after being relegated to the bench at Real
Madrid.... AS Roma spent roughly $10 million in outbidding Juventus
for Nigerian midfielder Sunday Oliseh of Ajax Amsterdam. Juve did
re-sign striker Alessandro Del Piero, who missed virtually all of
the season with a knee injury, to a four-year contract
extension.... Lazio, freed up with transfer cash after Christian
Vieri moved to Inter Milan, might be on the verge of picking up
Arsenal forward Nicolas Anelka and has added Swedish national team
and ex-Bologna forward Kennet Anderson.... French World Cup
defender Laurent Blanc has transferred to Inter Milan for a
reported $3 million.... Former Italian women's team star Carolina
Morace has been named coach at third division U.S. Viterbese,
becoming the first woman to coach a men's team in Italy's pro
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Valencia win also a loss
</P>
<P>
   After his team topped Atletico Madrid 3-0 Saturday to win the
Spanish Cup, Valencia manager Claudio Ranieri appeared to be
switching sides and moving to the troubled team in the Spanish
capital, which went through four coaches this season.... Mallorca
goalkeeper Carlos Roa, who has hinted at being torn between playing
the game and honoring his Seventh Day Adventist beliefs, has
retired to do full-time church work. Roa, who starred for Argentina
in the World Cup in '98, had attracted interest from several top
European clubs and was voted the top goalkeeper this season in the
Primera Division.
</P>
<P>
   England: Hoddle rebuffs Forest
</P>
<P>
   Former England manager Glenn Hoddle has rejected overtures by
Nottingham Forest to take over the club, which was relegated to the
First Division. Forest striker Pierre van Hooijdonk, who alienated
the team by holding out the first part of the season, has moved
back to Holland, joining Vitesse Arnhem for roughly $5.5
million.... Aston Villa, which lost goalkeeper Mark Bosnich to
Manchester United, has signed David James.
</P>
<P>
   France: Dugarry cited for doping
</P>
<P>
   Olympique Marseille striker Christophe Dugarry became the sixth
French player in the last two years to test positive for anabolic
steroids, when traces of nan-drolene were found in his system.
Dugarry, who could be suspended for six months, denied the report.
``I will do everything to show faults in the inefficiency of the
anti-doping controls,'' he told the French sports daily L'Equipe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
