<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. team's work focuses on early defensive lapses
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Getting to the U.S. defense early _ if not
always often enough _ has been the best way opponents have tested
the Americans in group play. It's a strategy that a more potent
Germany figures to follow tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team has shown few noticeable flaws so far, but some
gaps in its back-four alignment have been a lingering concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we need to be organized, because Germany is very
organized and precise on the attack,'' starting right defender Joy
Fawcett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams have been coming in to play us very fired up, and it's
taken us some time to get settled in.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said he plans no major lineup changes
from the first two matches, even though they revealed those same
vulnerabilities. Nigeria scored a goal in the second minute before
the U.S. team rallied for a 7-1 win. Denmark also made a threat in
the opening moments before falling 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the Germans to come out and expose us early,'' said
DiCicco, who has had the team working on defensive clearances
during training this week. ``We've got to take better care of the
ball earlier in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany also gave up an early goal on Sunday to Brazil before
surging ahead to build the 3-2 lead that it squandered on a
last-play goal that tied the game in stoppage time.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans will be missing one of their key offensive players,
midfielder Martina Voss, who is out with a pulled thigh muscle. But
the attacking tandem of Birgit Prinz and Bettina Wiegmann has been
strong, as has Inka Grings in a supplementary role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team has some weakness,'' German defender Steffi Jones
said. ``We hope we will find the Americans' real quick and make a
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   You want to talk to _ me?
</P>
<P>
   The wide-eyed look on Kate Sobrero's face seems permanently
fixed as the young starting central defender revels in her first
major playing experience with the U.S. squad.
</P>
<P>
   She just completed her college career at Notre Dame and has been
quickly embraced by her better-known teammates. Yet there are still
times she admits to being in awe of her surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being interviewed. Are you kidding?'' asked Sobrero, 23,
who is expected to start tonight after sitting out Sunday's win
over North Korea with a sprained ankle. ``When I got injured, it
was on the front page of USA Today. I mean, that's really hard for
me to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobrero, who has gone through light workouts this week, said she
is ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance boost Parts of the upper deck at Jack Kent Cooke
Stadium have been opened to ticket sales, with an expected crowd of
55,000 on hand for tonight's doubleheader. That number would
substantially boost the slow attendance figures in Washington,
which averaged about 18,000 for two doubleheaders in group play.
Those attendance figures were the lowest of any of the eight
venues.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke Stadium, the three-year-old home of the Redskins, holds
80,000, but its downsized World Cup capacity is listed at roughly
41,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's how many tickets had been sold as of Tuesday, a number
similar to the figures for the semifinals at Stanford Stadium,
where the U.S. team would play on Sunday. More than 60,000 tickets
have been sold for the July 10 finals in the Rose Bowl, much of it
driven by the possibility of a U.S. appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women have averaged 65,000 in their three group
matches.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
