<SLUG> BC-HONDURAN-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE OF HONDURAN BOY WHO TOLD TALL TALE IS MURKY, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
  (See also HONDURAN-IMMIG-COLUMN) 
 (nk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The future of Edwin Daniel Sabillon was as murky as
his tall tale of a 3,200-mile journey Wednesday, as New York City
officials began deliberating whether the 13-year-old boy should be
returned to relatives or allowed to begin a new life here as a
foster child.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators spent the day trying to sort out the boy's
elaborate, but now discredited, account of a solo journey from
Honduras to New York to find his only living relative, his father,
that devolved into a sad story of a Florida runaway apparently
traumatized by his father's death.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said the boy's family in Honduras had expressed
interest in taking care of Edwin. One of Edwin's aunts in Hialeah,
Fla., with whom he had been living when he ran away on June 24,
said she was due to have a baby in two weeks and did not believe
she could care for him in her two-bedroom apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the aunt, Aurora Sabillon, 23, said she hoped the
authorities would be able to find another home for him, perhaps in
New York, perhaps with a family of some means. ``I cannot have
Edwin, because maybe he is going to run away again,'' she said,
``and we don't have enough money to take care of him and the baby
that I am going to have.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials said it would be days before there was a decision
on Edwin's future. Until then, he will stay with the
Spanish-speaking foster family he was placed with after he turned
up alone in New York on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Honduran officials also spoke with Edwin on Wednesday as they
began considering their options. Although the boy's grandmother,
Paula Vasquez, has expressed interest in his return, Julio C.
Enamorado, the Honduran vice consul general in New York, said
officials had been unable to contact her in the small town of San
Buenaventura. Enamorado said the Honduran authorities also had not
been able to contact Edwin's mother, who is believed to live in the
northern Honduras town of Choloma.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives have said Edwin's mother gave the boy up when he was 3
months old, although the teen-ager initially told a much different
story to the New York police, describing his mother as dead, a
victim of Hurricane Mitch. When he finally broke down and told
detectives the truth on Tuesday night, one police official said,
the boy acknowledged that his mother was alive and said that he had
seen her several times.
</P>
<P>
   Enamorado said he found Edwin to be in good emotional and
physical health. ``He is very coherent and, of course, very
imaginative,'' he said. ``It is a 360-degree change from what we
heard on Monday, and we are shocked, but we'll support him, of
course. It's our obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives have said that Edwin had a problem accepting the death
of his father, Grevis Sabillon, last October. Even though Edwin
attended Sabillon's funeral in Honduras, his aunt said he would
often fantasize that his father was still alive. But the family
remained mystified about his impulse to go to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Edwin's relatives in Orange County, about 100 miles
north of the city, said Wednesday that they believed that the boy
may have been trying to reach them in Newburgh, where his father
once lived. The family of the boy's cousin, Ramon Sabillon, said
they would be interested in taking Edwin in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough room,'' said Hugo Quinonez, the stepson of
Ramon Sabillon, who boarded the boy's father in the basement of his
four-bedroom home several years ago when Edwin's father was working
in the area. Quinonez said the boy had told relatives at the
funeral of his plans to follow in his father's footsteps. ``He told
my uncle, `I just want to bury my father and then I am going to the
United States to live out his dreams,' '' Quinonez said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials Wednesday arranged a psychological screening for
the boy to determine if he needs counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the city's Administration for Children's Services
said they would ask Florida officials to assess whether any of his
relatives in Hialeah would be a suitable guardian. Edwin has a
second aunt there, but she could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   As a general practice, child welfare officials try to place a
child with a relative. If that is not possible, a child can be
classified as abandoned and then placed into foster care, officials
said. In this case, the process is complicated because Edwin is not
a citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials said that they had not been brought into
the case yet and that it was premature to offer specific comments.
But as a general policy, Mark Thorn, an Immigration and
Naturalization Service spokesman, said, ``We try to keep children
with their families.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
