A5260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT &LR;      06-30 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISCUES COST YANKEES AS TIGERS ROLL  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul O'Neill unleashed a sturdy throw from right
field to third base, but it bounced off the glove of Scott Brosius
and skipped high in the air. Andy Pettitte was casually backing up
the play and tried to corral the ball, but it trickled past his
fingers and sailed into the box seats. The ball spilled a fan's
beer onto a boy's new Yankees cap, and the soggy kid looked as
gloomy as the Yankees felt. Especially Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   Sluggish pitching, listless fielding and untimely hitting
plagued Pettitte and the New York Yankees Wednesday in an 8-2 loss
to the Detroit Tigers at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had won seven straight games, but they looked rusty
and played poorly in succumbing for only the fifth time in the last
18 games.
</P>
<P>
   On a lazy, gray afternoon, 39,749 fans journeyed to the Bronx to
watch the first-place team that had been so reliable lately.
Instead, many left after Tony Clark pounded a two-run homer off
Pettitte into the black center-field bleachers in the seventh
inning. The 429-foot homer terminated Pettitte's dreary start and
assured the Yankees of remembering this day for everything that
went awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was ugly,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``I'm glad we haven't
seen many of these. I hope it's a while before we see another
one.''
</P>
<P>
   From Pettitte pitching inconsistently and fielding questionably,
to Chuck Knoblauch making another glaring throwing error, to Bernie
Williams misjudging a fly ball into a rally-starting double, to the
Yankees stranding an astounding 15 runners off Brian Moehler and
four relievers, the game was filled with sequence after forgettable
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we got them all out,'' Joe Girardi said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were so disenchanted with their dismal performance
that many vacated the quiet clubhouse quickly, and some of the
players who remained had little to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is ridiculous,'' Knoblauch muttered when he saw about 25
reporters near his locker and then refused to comment on his 15th
error, which leads all second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte answered three questions before ending a two-minute
interview, miffed at the fans who booed him after he gave up seven
earned runs in 6 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can do whatever they want,'' Pettitte said. ``I'm out
there battling as hard as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Operating without his important cut fastball, Pettitte had to
depend on his sinker and his curveball, and it was a struggle.
Although some of the runs were aided by sloppy defense, including
Pettitte's, walks also contributed in three of the four innings
Detroit scored off the left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers scored a run in the first when Pettitte froze on Dean
Palmer's chopper and had it ricochet off his glove. After the
Yankees overcame Knoblauch being doubled off first on a fly ball
and tied it, Pettitte had a meltdown in the second.
</P>
<P>
   He walked the No. 9 batter, Deivi Cruz, on four pitches, plunked
Juan Encarnacion with a 1-2 cutter and walked rookie Jason Wood to
force in a run and make it 2-1. Bobby Higginson then lined a ball
off Pettitte that Knoblauch neatly grabbed and fired to first for
the out.
</P>
<P>
   But the misfortune returned in the fifth. Encarnacion stroked a
fly ball to center that Williams got a poor jump on, and it fell
for a double. Pettitte then made a shoddy decision by fielding
Wood's bunt and throwing late to third. Both runners were safe and
a walk to Higginson filled the bases. After Palmer's sacrifice fly
made it 3-1, Clark grounded to shortstop for what should have been
an inning-ending double play. It was not.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch received an underhanded toss from Derek Jeter, but he
whipped a sidearm throw across his body that was at least 12 feet
off line. Tino Martinez stretched and dived and still did not touch
the ball so the fourth run crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's erratic throwing is an issue that continues to haunt
the Yankees. ``All I want to do is get this thing fixed,'' Torre
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte walked Higginson in the seventh and Palmer singled to
right. That is when O'Neill's throw hopped around like a popcorn
kernel before knocking over a cup of beer and dousing one of the
caps that was given away to kids Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The wet boy was a fitting metaphor for the Yankees on what Torre
called ``a weird day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
