<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO REGAIN CONTROL OF A GENIE WAY OUT OF THE OWNERS' BOTTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss.) (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Silas was at the office early Wednesday morning preparing
for his first draft as head coach of the Charlotte Hornets. With
his team picking third, Silas was excited to be in position to
snatch one of the great young players in the NBA draft. He got his
wish, selecting Baron Davis, the 6-foot-2{-inch point guard from
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   This is the wave of the future and Silas is glad to be part of
it _ this year. ``If I'm in this position next year,'' he said,
``if we're ever in this position again to pick in the lottery, I
might as well go look for a job.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been a lot of hand-wringing over the NBA's young blood
problem. So many young players entering the league after one or two
years of college, some jumping directly to the pros from high
school. Last week, during the championship series, David Stern, the
NBA commissioner, proposed an age minimum, that players under 20
could not enter the NBA. The notion behind the age lockout is that
the players would be forced stay in school and mature.
</P>
<P>
   Silas doesn't like the idea. ``I don't necessarily think that a
blanket age requirement is going to fly, legally, No. 1, and 2, I
don't think it's necessary,'' he said. ``You have to take each
individual case. You have some kids coming in at a very young age
that are very mature and can handle a situation. The flip side is
that you have kids who do stay in school for four years and they
come in and they still are not mature.''
</P>
<P>
   Silas said he wasn't appalled that Jonathan Bender, the
17-year-old senior out of Picayune (Miss.) High School was drafted
No. 5 by the Toronto Raptors. Silas pointed out that those baseball
and hockey players who go from high school to the big leagues avoid
scrutiny and are not the object of ridicule or debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is up in arms when a kid who is talented in
basketball says, `I want to forgo college and I want to start
making a living,''' Silas said. ``Why is it OK in one instance and
it's not OK in the other? I don't understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA owners' real concern is not player maturity. The concern
is the diminishing control over talent as the league gets younger.
Latrell Sprewell is the chairman, and Allen Iverson is the
president of a generation of players who seem unwilling to be
controlled as players once were, by fear and intimidation. Many are
no longer in awe of the prototypical front office hierarchy
authority figure: usually white, male _ though not always _ with
whom they have little in common outside of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a kid today who is much more aware,'' Silas said.
``You can't just tell these kids that `It's going to be my way or
the highway. They still need guidance and discipline but you've got
to explain things to a young guy. They aren't going to just run
through that brick wall, like we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Silas has seen the evolution. He was drafted in 1964 by the St.
Louis Hawks in the second round (12th pick overall) and ended his
career with Seattle in 1980. ``It was a different day and different
time,'' Silas said. ``You're talking about the 60s, when the
revolution was just coming. You thought the people in power were
all-powerful, that you had no say and you were just happy to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Silas said the shift began in 1975, when the owners opened their
wallets and David Thompson signed an enormous contract with Denver.
``From that point on, the big dollars came in and that's when you
saw the change come,'' Silas said. ``Kids were making enormous
amounts of money, the league began marketing them more, they were
seen a lot more on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   In Silas' view, the NBA's problem is not the players but the
coaches and various front office types for whom they work. ``Most
of the powers that be in our league are 1, afraid and 2, they don't
want to rock the boat because they really think they need these
kids to keep their jobs,'' Silas said. ``They do not understand our
players. The players are going to test you and most of the time,
when the test comes, most coaches don't know how to handle it. They
will turn their back, shy away and think that the problem is going
to go away. If you meet these problems head on, the problems get
solved one way or the other. If you don't meet these problems head
on, you're not going to have a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're going to see an influx of head coaches that
know how to handle these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is undergoing a more profound transition than we
realize. The league is becoming younger, faster, more versatile.
There is no need to change rules to increase scoring. Change
attitudes. ``Coaches dictate style of play,'' Silas said. ``They
dictate scores. When you let these kids run up and down the court
and fire away, you're going to have better games, more scoring, and
it's going to be a much more exciting game. That's all that
happened to the Knicks: Jeff let those guys play. Let the talent
flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Young blood is coming. The marketing, the money, the allure, the
exposure has made players eager to get better, imitate, improve,
perform feats of ballet that Michael Jordan never imagined. Imagine
that: Lamar Odom, 19, a 6-10 forward, was drafted by the Los
Angeles Clippers at No. 4
</P>
<P>
   So stop the hand-wringing, commissioner. Stop the talk about
locking out the teenagers. You help set all this in motion; can't
stop it now.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Dr. Dick Barnett used to say: ``Too late: fall back,
baby.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
