</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-COPPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH IS SETTLING COPPER TRADING COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., which was accused by federal regulators of
helping finance and profiting from 1995 copper trades intended to
inflate copper prices artificially, announced Wednesday that it was
paying $15 million to settle the complaint without admitting or
denying the charges made by the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the announcement, the company said it was also settling, for
an additional 6.5 million pounds ($10.2 million), a similar action
brought by the London Metal Exchange, which had been ground zero
for the manipulative trading in copper futures by Sumitomo Corp.
and its rogue trader, Yasuo Hamanaka.
</P>
<P>
   Hamanaka, once nicknamed `` 5 Percent'' in wry homage to the
amount of the copper market _ both actual supplies and futures
contracts _ he controlled, pleaded guilty to criminal charges in
Japan in 1997. He is serving an eight-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators in the enforcement division of the CFTC had charged
that Merrill Lynch, through subsidiaries, provided Sumitomo with
$500 million in financing and credit, even though responsible
personnel knew enough about the activities of Sumitomo and a
start-up copper trading company, Global Minerals &AMP; Metals Corp., to
conclude that the copper trading activity was suspect.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint issued May 20, the CFTC charged that Martyn
Phillips, a Merrill Lynch employee, discussed copper trading
strategies with Global's chief trader, Carl Alm. The focus of the
discussions, the regulators charged, was how to control copper
supplies and drive up prices.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of an order filed by the commission Wednesday,
executives at Merrill Lynch, Pierce Fenner &AMP; Smith Ltd., a
London-based subsidiary, and Merrill Lynch International, based in
New York, knew that ``the manipulators owned most LME copper
warrants'' and ``were withholding such copper warrants from the
market'' and that consequently ``the price of copper was higher
than it would have been absent these activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The CFTC complaint also contended that Merrill Lynch was
profiting from the trades and providing trading advice.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement Wednesday, Merrill Lynch said it ``entered into
the settlements to bring closure to these regulatory proceedings
and to avoid the expense and distraction of protracted
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The complex arrangement fell apart in June 1996, leading to a
sharp drop in copper prices that ended up costing Sumitomo about
$2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, Sumitomo agreed to pay a $150 million fine to
resolve its complaints, without admitting or denying any of the
allegations. Of that total, $25 million has been set aside to pay
judgments awarded any plaintiffs who successfully sue Sumitomo.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators' complaint against Global Minerals &AMP; Metals; its
principal, R. David Campbell, and Alm is still pending, according
to Phyllis Cela, the acting director of the CFTC's division of
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in May, when the complaint was filed, H. Peter
Haveles Jr., a lawyer for Global Minerals, said the regulators'
complaint was ``based on an `Alice in Wonderland' view of the
facts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
