A5275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPENDING-AD-COLUMN-NY     06-30 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPENDING-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: STRONGER GAINS IN AD SPENDING SEEN FOR '99 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A leading forecaster of advertising spending has
raised his estimate for 1999 after cutting it earlier because of
concerns about the worldwide economic turmoil last fall.
</P>
<P>
   With those qualms virtually vanquished, and amid reports of
robust first-quarter ad spending in myriad media, Robert Coen,
senior vice president and forecasting director at the
McCann-Erickson USA unit of McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising,
is raising his predicted gain for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the last time Coen offered predictions, ``we saw
signs the economy was questionable,'' he said Wednesday in a
presentation at the Metropolitan Club in Manhattan, ``and we were
cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But 1999 is turning out to be so much stronger than anybody
expected,'' he added. ``We have a lot more stimulus than anyone
thought possible six months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, Coen also increased for a fourth consecutive
time his figures for how much marketers spent to advertise in 1998.
And taking his first look at 2000, Coen was bullish, forecasting
that ad spending would be stimulated significantly by elections,
the Summer Olympics, millennium hoopla and even advisories about
Year 2000 computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ad spending is carefully monitored because it is considered a
reliable way to assess the condition of the overall economy,
particularly the propensity of consumers to spend. Coen's optimism
dovetails with other signs that the economy remains robust, such as
the announcement Wednesday by the Conference Board that its index
of leading economic indicators rose three-tenths of a percent in
May after a small decline in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketplace looks very strong,'' said Coen, whose
projections are closely watched because he has been tracking
advertising and media trends for five decades for McCann-Erickson
Worldwide Advertising, now part of the McCann-Erickson World Group
unit of  &UR; Interpublic Group  &LR; of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Coen predicted that marketers would spend a record $213.9
billion this year compared with a revised figure of $201.6 billion
for 1998, which represents a 7.5 percent increase from the $187.5
billion spent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   National ad spending in 1999 is now expected to rise 6.4
percent, to $126.6 billion, compared with Coen's December estimate
of 6 percent. And local ad spending is now expected to grow 5.7
percent, to $87.3 billion, up from his previous forecast of 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   If Coen's 1999 forecast is correct, advertising as a percentage
of gross domestic product would reach a record 2.39 percent,
compared with 2.37 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, when Coen made his first estimate for 1999 ad
spending, he projected an increase of 6 percent. That was trimmed
to 5.5 percent in December because of the financial crises in the
Asia-Pacific region and Latin America, coupled with global stock
market swoons. In his presentation, he revised the figure to a gain
of 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While that gain would be the slowest growth since a 5.2 percent
increase in 1993, it would still be notable for a ``hammock'' year
between Olympics and elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraged by the upside revisions,'' said Karen Ficker,
managing director for advertising, publishing and new media at
Furman Selz in New York, which becomes ING Barings on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's talking about stabilization in Asia-Pacific now, if
not improvement,'' said Ms. Ficker, who attended the Coen
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   In revamping his 1999 figures, Coen cited first-quarter media
spending in several important national ad categories, including
airlines, computers, drugs and remedies, movies, resorts and tours,
restaurants and telecommunications. He also pointed to sharp gains
in categories like banks, brokers and mutual funds, cigarettes and
liquor.
</P>
<P>
   All that helped increase ad revenue in the first quarter for
cable television networks by 28 percent, newspapers by 12.6
percent, magazines by 7.7 percent and yellow pages by 7.1 percent.
In the local realm, there were good first-quarter results for
media, including radio, up 15 percent; yellow pages, up 5 percent,
and newspaper retail ads, up 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to ad spending overseas, Coen predicted an improvement,
based on the brightening outlooks for countries like Malaysia, the
Philippines and South Korea and continued growth in countries like
Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Spending outside the United States should total $212 billion, he
said, up 4.1 percent from a revised figure of $203.7 billion for
1998. That spending last year was a decline of 3 percent from $210
billion in 1997 and was the second consecutive decline after three
years of gains.
</P>
<P>
   Coen's worldwide total estimate for 1999, then, is $425.9
billion, up 5.1 percent from his final figure for 1998 of $405.3
billion, which would be the largest growth since 1995. The spending
last year represented a gain of 2 percent from $397.5 billion in
1997, the smallest annual increase since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Coen's initial worldwide forecast for 1999, made in June 1998,
was $440.5 billion, which was lowered to $435.9 billion in
December.
</P>
<P>
   And peering forward for the first time at 2000, Coen offered a
``guesstimate'' for snappy growth at home of 7.5 percent, to $230
billion, and respectable growth abroad of 5.7 percent, to $224
billion. The total: $454 billion, up 6.6 percent from 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot of similarities between 2000 and 1976,'' Coen
said, when ad spending in the United States was fueled by
Bicentennial campaigns as well as Olympic and election ads.
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst who attended Coen's presentation, Michael J.
Russell Jr., said that he agreed with the 7.5 percent increase
predicted domestically for next year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Year 2000 factors, said Russell, advertising
analyst in New York for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Company,
Madison Avenue will benefit from such new ``brand pipelines'' as
spending to promote prescription drugs to consumers and Internet
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet IPOs and business plans say `Give me money to
advertise,''' he added. ``There was never a time before when that
happened.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
