<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5278 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     06-30 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN'S ENJOYMENT DAMPENED BY LOSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Big Man ambles into the dugout of the Anaheim Angels, and
sits alone on the bench, peering stolidly out at teammates going
through their pregame ritual in preparation for the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   He will be on the field taking batting practice in a few
moments, but he's now taking a reflective pause, a somber-faced man
lost in his own thoughts about an Angel season that has not
unfolded as scripted in the bright optimism of spring.
</P>
<P>
   You approach the Big Man cautiously, figuring he's not in a mood
for mindless chit-chat, figuring that all those millions of dollars
that he's earning from the Angels aren't enough to neutralize the
frustration he must be enduring over his team's floundering ways.
</P>
<P>
   You shake his hand, and wonder if he can spare a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He nods amicably.
</P>
<P>
   You've interviewed enough ball players across the seasons to
know that you don't open such a session with a hardball question in
the tense atmosphere in which Mo Vaughn and the Angels find
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   You know the Big Man is a passionate competitor who's on edge,
and so you begin gently by asking him the differences he's found
between residing in Boston and Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have more of an open mind out here,'' says Mo
Vaughn, who's living in Newport Beach. ``I'm treated more as a
regular person out here. I can go anywhere, and people leave me
alone. In Boston, forget about it! It got so bad there I hated
leaving my house. I often felt like a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is way less stress out here on me. People out here are
accustomed to being around celebrities because there are so many of
them in both athletics and the movie business. People out here
don't give a damn if you wear green or pink hair. I love living out
here. It's just so much easier on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the Big Man was supposed to transform the Angels
into a serious contender in the A.L. West Division and give them
that left-handed power-hitting inspirational team leader that they
had notably lacked in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But a torrent of injuries to vital performers Jim Edmonds, Tim
Salmon, Gary DeSarcina, Ken Hill, Tim Belcher and, yes, Vaughn
himself has resulted in the Angels falling into last place in their
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely been tough ... very tough,'' acknowledges
Vaughn, shaking his head slowly. ``You come here, you expect big
things, and it just hasn't happened. It's disappointing, no doubt
about it. But we just have to keep playing hard, and not give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the injury to myself (a severely sprained left ankle in
the opener against Cleveland) has definitely slowed my production,
and also slowed the things I like to do in the clubhouse. I like to
get into the guys' head, tease them, even taunt them into playing
harder. But how can I do that when I myself was out for a while and
when I myself was struggling?''
</P>
<P>
   It was all supposed to fall apart in Boston when Mo Vaughn
signed with the Angels, but the Red Sox have been keeping pace with
the New York Yankees in the East Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Man says he's not surprised by the performance of his
former team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo Vaughn taught the Red Sox players how to play,'' he says.
``By that, I don't mean I taught them how to play baseball. What I
taught them was toughness and how to be consistent when under fire.
It took three or four years to do it, but the Red Sox are a team
with a bunch of tough guys who aren't afraid of anybody. I'd like
to think I played a major part in instilling that toughness in
them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Mo Vaughn's desire to instill a similar toughness into an
Angel team that has a sacred history of softness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so different out here,'' says Vaughn. ``If we were
struggling in Boston like we have been here this season, the Boston
fans would have crucified us. They'd have called us every name in
the book, and booed us unmercifully.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not here. People just seem to take it in stride. Don't get
me wrong. I know the fans here aren't happy with the way we've been
playing. But they come out to the park, and you don't hear any of
the nasty remarks you would if you were struggling in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Man still thinks the Angels will straighten themselves
out, even though their suspect pitching staff indicates otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to stay positive in this game,'' he says. ``Or it'll
eat you up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are your feelings about Terry Collins?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like him,'' says Vaughn quickly. ``He reminds me of me. He
just wants to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Man, who's listed at 6-1 and 245 even though he appears
heavier, insists he prefers Orange County to Boston despite his
team's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more fun for me out here,'' says Vaughn. ``I'm never
bothered, no matter where I go. It's not big news what I do here. I
was in a fishbowl in Boston. It would be perfect out here for me if
we just started to win more often ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
