<SLUG> BC-HEALTHEON-WEBMD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga.)  
 HEALTHEON AND WebMD PLAN TO BUY NEWS SERVICE  
 (bl)  
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Healtheon Corp. and WebMD Inc, the companies that are combining
in an attempt to dominate the use of the Internet by the health
care industry, are buying Greenberg News Networks, a privately held
medical news service, for $250 million in stock, people familiar
with the deal said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon, based in Santa Clara, Calif., agreed in May to buy
WebMD, of Atlanta, for stock then valued at $3.9 billion. Healtheon
has focused mainly on using the Internet to automate medical
transactions, like insurance claims. WebMD operates a site that
offers information to doctors and to patients, with revenues both
from subscription fees and from advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The companies plan to use the extensive medical information
created by Greenberg's Medcast service to enhance the WebMD Web
site, which has sections aimed at both medical consumers and
doctors. They will also create a medical news service that will
distribute articles to other news organizations, to increase
WebMD's exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Medcast employs 50 full-time editors, writers and graphic
designers and 20 freelance correspondents. WebMD and Healtheon have
much smaller groups of editors and rely mainly on content from
other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, also based in Atlanta, was started by Alan Greenberg,
a former vice chairman of Whittle Communications, where he was
publisher of Esquire magazine. At Whittle he was also involved with
the Medical News Network, a cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Medcast uses what has come to be called push technology to load
health news and information to doctors' computers when they are not
using them. It has developed elaborate multimedia tools to offer
physicians video news updates and interactive three-dimensional
medical diagrams. Like WebMD, it has sold subscriptions as well as
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon was started by Jim Clark, the founder of Netscape
Communications Corp., and David Schell, a doctor who is also a
partner in the venture capital firm of Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP;
Byers. WebMD was founded by Jeffrey Arnold, an Atlanta health care
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Given the astoundingly high valuations that Wall Street has put
on these companies, none of them has managed to attract many
customers. MedCast says it has 2,000 active subscriptions and
commitments from another 6,000 to buy its $300-a-year service.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD has fewer than 10,000 subscribing physicians. It does,
however, have commitments from Microsoft Corp. and Du Pont Co. to
buy $330 million worth of its $30-a-month service to give to
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Greenberg will be timed to close when the
WebMD-Healtheon merger closes at the end of the third quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
