<HEADER>
A5288 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MY-HOUSE-ON-YOUR-LAND     06-30 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MY-HOUSE-ON-YOUR-LAND-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MI CASA ES TU CASA
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By CLAIRE POOLE 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    HOUSTON _ For many people living in border towns across the
United States, owning their own home is part of the American dream.
But with incomes low, home prices high and mortgages difficult to
get, the fantasy is out of reach for many.
 &HT;    Corporacion GEO hopes to change that. The US$280 million (sales)
Mexico City-based company, the largest home builder in Mexico, is
working with Atlanta-based Beazer Homes USA to construct affordable
homes all along the U.S.-Mexico border and in Florida, too. The two
companies threw an initial $13 million into the venture, 60 percent
of which is owned by Beazer, 40 percent by GEO.
 &HT;    The two have already broken ground on a development in El Paso,
acquired land for a second development and are negotiating to buy a
third tract. Their short-term goal: to have 1,000 homes in the
ground by the end of the year. Their longer-term goal: to be
building 3,000 homes a year across the United States generating
sales of $150 million by 2001.
 &HT;    Expanding into the United States is an aggressive move for any
Latin American company, particularly in as competitive, cyclical
and inherently local an industry as home building. But Enrique
Carral, vice chairman of GEO-Beazer, as the joint venture is
called, says he's got the right target country and his low-income
houses are the right product. ``The U.S. and Europe are the only
parts of the world performing,'' he says. ``The market is
tremendous because no one is attending to the affordable homes.''
 &HT;    Sobani Warner, a Latin America construction analyst at New
York-based brokerage firm Bear Stearns, is excited about GEO's U.S.
prospects. ``It's a market that is underserved, the mortgage system
is better than in any of the other Latin American countries and
there's government support,'' she says. ``You see a lot of Latin
companies trying to diversify their revenue stream. So if (GEO) can
make a profit out of it, why not?''
 &HT;    GEO is well on its way. It's already sold 100 of the 430 homes
it's building in the Oasis Ranch development in El Paso and hopes
to deliver the first by the end of July.
 &HT;    But GEO is offering more than the boxy, concrete-block homes
that made it famous in Mexico. While they're using the same basic
Lego-like technology, the homes will have many more features, from
built-in closets, washer-dryer connections and central air
conditioning and heat to fenced-in yards and landscaping. The homes
will also be considerably bigger _ 1,200 square feet on average,
versus only 500 in Mexico. They'll also cost a lot more _ $39,000
for a two-bedroom home, versus $15,000 in Mexico. Still, ``The
alternative to that is a trailer,'' says Carral, who was a
construction manager at Mexico City's Santa Fe retail development
before joining GEO 10 years ago.
 &HT;    This is not Carral's first development outside of Mexico. The
53-year-old manager spent 15 months in Santiago, Chile getting
GEO's first international housing development off the ground with a
local joint-venture partner, Constructora SALFA. So far, it's been
a hit: GEO has delivered 4,400 homes and expects to move another
1,200 this year, despite high interest and unemployment rates as a
result of an economic slowdown in Chile. Argentina may be next.
 &HT;    Even with a local partner, operating conditions in the U.S. have
proven to be tricky for the Mexican homebuilder. Carral says the
permitting process is particularly onerous, with the approval for
the first development taking six months to secure, versus what
would take only a month in Mexico. He also complains about the
inspection process. ``Before you pour any slab, you have to get an
inspection from the city. Before you start the slab of the second
floor, you have to have that first floor approved,'' he says. ``It
adds time to the process.''
 &HT;    But because it's building low-income housing, GEO-Beazer is
receiving rich subsidies from the city, the state and federal
government-owned mortgage provider Fannie Mae, which is extending a
$3 million credit line through its Housing Impact Fund.
 &HT;    Now that it's hit a groove in El Paso, GEO is scouting for new
sites. Its first aim is Houston, which, like El Paso, has a large
Hispanic population but not a lot of affordable homes.
 &HT;    GEO's going to face some stiff competition. Last March,
Houston-based U.S. Home Corp. announced it was acquiring 13.3
percent of GIG Desarrolladores Inmobiliarios (GIDI), a Zapopan,
Jalisco-based homebuilder, for $12.8 million. As part of the deal,
the duo said they would build low-income housing along the border.
 &HT;    The two didn't waste any time. They've already delivered homes
in Dallas, have broken ground in Houston and are looking at sites
in San Antonio, El Paso and Arizona. Within five years, they aim to
deliver 2,000 units per year in 25 developments in 10 different
cities across the U.S., including the states of Florida, California
and New Mexico.
 &HT;    Bear Stearns' Warner is putting her money on GEO. ``They have a
great house, and they've been able to show that minor adaptations
of that house can sell in Chile,'' she says. ``If they can deliver
a decent home at a low price, there's a wide open market in North
America.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
