<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-CAMP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGUAGE CAMP PROVES POPULAR WITH BOTH PARENTS AND KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECILIA GOODNOW  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Camille Lucas, 6{, isn't shy about demonstrating her
grasp of Russian. With aplomb, she rattles off a Russian phrase in
an accent that sounds impressively authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't ask her to translate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forget what it means,'' Camille says good-naturedly.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Wednesday was just her third day of World Language
Summer Camp, a total-immersion program that immediately gets kids
playing games, singing songs and performing skits in one of eight
foreign languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun!'' says Camille, pausing on her way into Seattle's
Meany Middle School, where the two-week camp is housed.
</P>
<P>
   Without prompting, she launches into a spirited ``good-morning''
song, with Russian lyrics set to the tune of ``Frere Jacques.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful program,'' says her mother, Lisa Hashizume.
``It's so focused.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take any selling to convince parents of the benefits
of the two-week language camp, which offers classes in Swahili,
German, Spanish, Mandarin, Japanese, Korean, Arabic and Russian _
all for the low, low price of $15.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you better stand back. That ominous rumble is the sound
of 1,500 parents scrambling for one of 560 slots _ first come,
first served. Spanish, Japanese and Mandarin were the top three
language choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent this (application) in the first day I got it,'' said
Lenore Sargent, who knew the benefit of exposing kids to languages
at an early age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt hampered because I learned Spanish late in life,'' she
said, ``and I'm still not as fluent as I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Brief though it is, this exposure to Spanish may help her
daughter Kayla, who's almost 9, feel more at home when the family
embarks on a six-month stay in Europe next year.
</P>
<P>
   The language camp, for children entering grades 1 through 5,
started Monday. As of Wednesday, Spanish remained a very foreign
tongue to Kayla.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's having a hard time because she doesn't understand
anything,'' Sargent said, ``because they're very clever and they're
only speaking Spanish. But I taught her how to say, `I don't
understand.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Yates, 8, and her 10-year-old brother Casey are learning
Spanish for practical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to Mexico every once in a while so I figured it would be
probably the first place we'd take them,'' said their mother, Linda
Hebish, who speaks poco Spanish herself.
</P>
<P>
   The federally funded World Language Summer Camp started small
two years ago in the Seattle suburbs of Bellevue and Federal Way
with classes in Korean and Mandarin. Last year, when the program
moved to Meany, it grew to include five ``seldom-taught''
languages.
</P>
<P>
   This year the camp added three more languages _ Spanish, German
and Swahili _ with financial support from the John Stanford
International School, named after the late superintendent of
Seattle Public Schools.
</P>
<P>
   When the International School opens, in September 2000, it will
incorporate many of the language-immersion activities being
demonstrated at this summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   The camp also is a proving ground for native speakers who are
being trained to teach their languages in the regular classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Meany is abuzz with kids counting in unison, naming colors and
playing circle games in their respective adopted tongues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a world tour just going from classroom to classroom,''
said Wolfgang Hirsch, a German-language consultant for the state
who helped get the camp off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In the Swahili class, students have paired off to learn the game
mancala, which involves moving dried beans from one compartment to
another of the egg cartons that serve as game boards. Explaining
the rules in Swahili is a stretch for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we get two turns?'' a boy asks teacher Temma Pistrang, a
former Peace Corps volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Pistrang doesn't translate her reply, but her meaning is clear:
``No English.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids keep their spare beans in a paper cup, which they call
nyumba, the Swahili word for house.
</P>
<P>
   That word also shows up in a play they're rehearsing, which
involves a lake (ziwa), a frog (chura) and a rabbit (sungura).
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids went home last night and memorized some of their
parts,'' Pistrang said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Disney's ``The Lion King,'' Swahili wasn't totally
unfamiliar to the kids. Pistrang said they all came in knowing the
name Simba. From there, they went on to learn colors and numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday we jumped rope, counting,'' Pistrang said. ``Some of
them jump rope very fast, so they had to count fast.''
</P>
<P>
   One parent, Ellen Aagaard, said her 6-year-old son, Ben Corwin,
wanted to take Swahili because he'd learned some African songs at
Laurelhurst Elementary School, also in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real bonus is this (camp) has a lot more diverse student
population than Laurelhurst has,'' Aagaard said. ``There's a really
strong feeling of community with the whole school district.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben, tugging impatiently at the school's front door, had no
interest in small talk, in any language. He was too eager to get to
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go!'' he said, pulling his mother inside.
</P>
<P>
   Kids at the camp are grouped by language and by age, with
activities tailored to their developmental level. All the classes
are active, however. Teachers use a technique called ``total
physical response,'' which means students don't just parrot what
teachers say, they act it out.
</P>
<P>
   Students respond when the teacher instructs them to stand, sit,
turn around or take a turn at a game. Along the way, the children
learn one-word answers to more complex directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are quiet and don't want to respond, and some are
shouting out the answers on the very first day,'' said Steven
Whiting, Japanese head teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one expects students to become fluent after only two
weeks of camp, Whiting said, ``We hope they'll be comfortable with
the language and will have no fear of learning a language.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the state's strong foreign-trade connections and high
interest from parents, Washington schools offer little
foreign-language instruction before high school, camp leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   According to brain researchers, that's too late for optimum
learning _ and almost certainly too late to speak the language like
a native does.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch said schools should expose children to a second language
in the early grades, when they acquire language more easily, and
continue instruction through high school, with the adopted language
woven into the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kodama, principal of the John Stanford International
School, said the summer camp's glut of applications shows there's a
ready audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It confirmed,'' she said, ``that learning a world language is
very important to people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
