<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5305 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORTON-SPI &LR;      06-30 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORTON MAKING SURE HE'S NOT VULNERABLE ON HEALTH ISSUE AT
RE-ELECTION TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, D.C. _ At age 71, Slade Gorton would be retired from
many jobs in the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Senate, where septuagenarians could form their own
caucus, Gorton is young enough to be the son of one colleague,
96-year-old Strom Thurmond of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   As Gorton gears up to run for a fourth term _ at the end of
which he would be 78 _ he is bracing for the inevitable questions
about his age and fitness. The questions could be particularly
pointed because, Democrats say, Republican Gorton used the age
issue in his successful 1980 campaign to unseat Sen. Warren
Magnuson, who was then 75.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton denies that, but is making sure he isn't vulnerable on
the same score this year. Gorton made a minor splash last year when
he scaled the first 15 feet of the 65-foot climbing rock at REI in
Seattle, and he has challenged journalists curious about the age
issue to join him on one of his daily jogs.
</P>
<P>
   This reporter did run with Gorton recently, and found that after
a six-mile run around the Mall in Washington, D.C., Gorton was
huffier about the historical inaccuracies in his favorite movie,
``Shakespeare in Love,'' than he was from the physical exertion.
Gorton jogged steadily at a moderate speed, and offered a running
commentary on a variety of matters, including the new sculpture
garden at the National Gallery (skeptical) and the scaffolding on
the Washington Monument (positive).
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said that, despite a heart attack in 1994, poor eyesight
and a hole in his palate that causes a persistent, throat-clearing
cough, he is in good health.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the heart attack, he takes two pills a day, an
aspirin and a medication designed to lower his cholesterol. Always
thin _ Gorton said he hasn't gained weight since high school _ he
said he has nonetheless altered his diet in an effort to reduce
foods that might increase his blood cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton evinced no concern about his health, and although he said
he expects the next term would be his last, he passed up an
opportunity to pledge not to seek re-election to a fifth term in
2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my niche, the thing I enjoy doing most, the thing I
think I do best, so I don't see any reason to pay attention to the
clock,'' he said. ``I feel physically strong and mentally alert, so
there we are.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gorton did pledge complete candor about his health, and said
he or his staff would talk with reporters about any health problems
that might arise. He pointed out that he was open with reporters
when he had a heart attack several months after his re-election in
1994 _ allowing his staff and doctors to brief the news media, and
inviting reporters to question him on the first day he was released
from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said he is not sure what caused the heart attack, because
``there were no previous signs of this. I've never smoked, I drink
very rarely, I run all the time and my cholesterol was perfectly
within normal limits.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had an angioplasty after the heart attack to clear
his arteries, and then began taking the aspirin and the
cholesterol-reducing drug and more carefully watching his diet. He
said he did treadmill tests to monitor his heart condition
semiannually for several years, and now does them annually, and
that no problems have been spotted.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said the hole in his palate, which causes a noticeable
interruption of his speech pattern, is congenital. He said his
eyesight has been poor enough that he has worn glasses since age 5
and he now wears both contact lenses and reading glasses.
</P>
<P>
   The one declared Democratic challenger to Gorton, state
Insurance Commissioner Deborah Senn, is 50. Another potential
challenger, former Rep. Maria Cantwell, is 40. Party officials are
treating the issue somewhat gingerly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age as a rule doesn't matter, unless there's a hypocrisy
issue,'' said state Democratic Party Chairman Paul Berendt. ``When
Slade Gorton ran against Warren Magnuson, they made age an issue,
and it really opens Slade to the question of whether he should be
seeking another term.''
</P>
<P>
   Berendt also made it clear that Gorton's lengthy political
career could be used to depict him as out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time of greater sensitivity toward term limits, and when
everything in society is moving rapidly, that begs the question, is
this someone who is stuck in the '50s or '60s instead of the
'90s?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton flatly denies making an issue of Magnuson's age in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two very senior senators then, and one of our ads said
it was time to begin to build new seniority while Scoop Jackson is
going to be around, but I am quite certain that we never had an
advertisement that referred to Senator Magnuson's age,'' Gorton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told afterwards by some of his people that they were
convinced we were going to have a television ad with him getting
off the plane with excruciating slowness after the Mount St. Helens
eruption, but it was not something we ever considered doing.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gorton consultant at the time, Arthur Finkelstein, did hire a
camera crew to take a picture of Magnuson shuffling off Air Force
One when President Carter came out to inspect damage from the May
1980 eruption of Mount St. Helens. But it was never used in an ad.
(Magnuson suffered circulatory problems in his legs. His lower
right leg was later amputated.)
</P>
<P>
   Gorton often had his picture taken while jogging during the 1980
campaign. Democratic Rep. Al Swift was called on to tape a TV ad in
which Swift told voters: ``Let's concede the point. Slade Gorton
has a great pair of legs.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Gorton's TV spots featured a grandpalike figure in a
rocking chair. The narrator said that the time had come for
Magnuson to come home, and that Gorton had the vigor to become
``Washington's next great senator.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, before Gorton was officially in the race, he was quoted
in the Yakima Herald-Republic as saying of Magnuson:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looked like he's on death's door for 15 years, but I want
him alive. He is the best person for me to run against. If he
should die, and the governor were to appoint the incumbent, I think
it would be more difficult for me to win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton at the time did not deny making the comment, but said it
had been in an off-the-record editorial conference, and in response
to a questioner who said Magnuson ``looked like death warmed over.
Then he asked who would run if he were to die and wouldn't that be
better for me and the answer to that was `no.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, Gorton insisted that he was not making age an
issue in the campaign. ``Absolutely not,'' he said at the time. ``I
don't think it's appropriate to talk about personal qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton now says that although he is older than when people in
the private sector traditionally retire, it is not old for the
Senate, where at least four senators older than 70 are likely to
seek re-election. Increasingly, older people are seeking to remain
active in other realms as well, Gorton noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people in society as a whole are deciding that
they want careers after age 65, and that's simply a function of the
combination of the aging of the American people and the fact that
people are in better health,'' he said. ``This isn't something
that's confined to politics by any stretch of the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Joel Connelly contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
