<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5341 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-SETTLEMENT-SPI &LR;      06-30 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-SETTLEMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BANKCORP AGREES TO SETTLEMENT, WILL BREAK TIES WITH
TELEMARKETER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE HADLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Minnesota Attorney General Mike Hatch and U.S.
Bankcorp announced Wednesday that they had settled that state's
lawsuit against the bank for allegedly selling private customer
information to telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, U.S. Bancorp, the Minneapolis-based owner
of 194 U.S. Bank branches in Washington state, will no longer
disclose customer information to third parties for the purpose of
selling non-financial products.
</P>
<P>
   The bank can still disclose customer information to affiliates
selling financial products, but must notify customers of their
right to refuse to have their information disclosed. Financial
products would include stocks, loans, insurance, and other products
having to do with mortgages, such as appraisals.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit filed earlier this month, Hatch accused U.S.
Bancorp of selling customer inforation, including bank account
numbers, Social Security numbers, dates of birth, marital status,
occupation, and account balances, to a MemberWorks Inc., a
Connecticut-based telemarketing firm.
</P>
<P>
   In return, U.S. Bank was paid $4 million plus commissions of 22
percent of net revenue on sales made by MemberWorks, the suit said.
The telemarketer sold club memberships.
</P>
<P>
   In settling the suit, US Bancorp did not admit to any of the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   But the bank severed its relationship with MemberWorks a day
after the suit was announced, said bank spokesman Dan Waage.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Mierzwinski, a lobbyist for the consumer group US PIRG,
hailed the settlement as a good one for consumers that undermines
the posture the banking industry is taking in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   An intense battle was under way in the U.S. House rules
committee Wednesday night over the Markey amendment, which would
require that bank consumers be given the right to ``opt out'' of
having their information shared with bank affiliates. Banks have
already agreed consumers should be able to opt out of having their
information disclosed to independent telemarketers selling
non-financial products.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the banks are claiming the Markey amendment would destroy
banking as we know it,'' Mierzwinski said. ``The fact that U.S.
Bank has agreed to an across-the-board opt-out proves that you can
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jay Inslee, D _ Wash., who is a co-sponsor of the
Markey amendment, said it's critical to include bank affiliates in
the privacy protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't plug this loophole, banks could buy a
telemarketing firm, make it a wholly-owned subsidiary, and the same
sin would have been committed,'' Inslee said.
</P>
<P>
   Mierzwinski said that public indignation about companies
disclosing consumer's financial information has been rising sharply
in recent weeks. A majority of rank-and-file House members would
vote for the Markey amendment, Mierzwinski said, but House
leadership, heavily lobbied by the banking industry, may well
succeed in preventing the amendment from coming to a House vote, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups will continue the fight in the Senate and
also will attempt to attach the privacy protections to other
legislation the banking industry wants, such as a bankruptcy bill,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are building support for this over time. It's moved from a
fringe issue to center stage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer has reported on a variety of complaints
by consumers in recent months about the use of their credit card
and bank information.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers said they were billed for club memberships by
MemberWorks and BrandDirect Marketing, another Connecticut
telemarketer, that they didn't order or want.
</P>
<P>
   Other consumers complained that they gave Ticketmaster their
credit card number to order concert tickets only to find out later
that they were also being billed on their credit card for a
magazine subscription they didn't want.
</P>
<P>
   Waage, the U.S. Bancorp spokesman, said the bank is glad to be
out of the business of giving information to MemberWorks,
BrandDirect Marketing, Damark, and Health Benefit Services,
telemarketers that sold club memberships, travel products,
magazines and other non-financial products.
</P>
<P>
   They generated complaints from consumers and brought in
comparatively little revenue, he said. Oftentimes, consumers who
complained simply had forgotten that they had ordered the products,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the U.S. Bancorp's settlement with the state of Minnesota,
the bank also has agreed to contribute $1.5 million to Habitat for
Humanity in Minnesota, $500,000 to the state of Minnesota to help
pay the cost of bringing the suit, and $1.03 million to charities
in the 17 states in which the bank does business. It does the most
business in Minnesota, Oregon and Washington, Waage said.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also will be required to give refunds to customers who
bought any of the services from MemberWorks and were dissatisfied
with them and did not use them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990630.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
