<P>
   One of Gorton's TV spots featured a grandpalike figure in a
rocking chair. The narrator said that the time had come for
Magnuson to come home, and that Gorton had the vigor to become
``Washington's next great senator.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, before Gorton was officially in the race, he was quoted
in the Yakima Herald-Republic as saying of Magnuson:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looked like he's on death's door for 15 years, but I want
him alive. He is the best person for me to run against. If he
should die, and the governor were to appoint the incumbent, I think
it would be more difficult for me to win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton at the time did not deny making the comment, but said it
had been in an off-the-record editorial conference, and in response
to a questioner who said Magnuson ``looked like death warmed over.
Then he asked who would run if he were to die and wouldn't that be
better for me and the answer to that was `no.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, Gorton insisted that he was not making age an
issue in the campaign. ``Absolutely not,'' he said at the time. ``I
don't think it's appropriate to talk about personal qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton now says that although he is older than when people in
the private sector traditionally retire, it is not old for the
Senate, where at least four senators older than 70 are likely to
seek re-election. Increasingly, older people are seeking to remain
active in other realms as well, Gorton noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people in society as a whole are deciding that
they want careers after age 65, and that's simply a function of the
combination of the aging of the American people and the fact that
people are in better health,'' he said. ``This isn't something
that's confined to politics by any stretch of the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Joel Connelly contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
