<SLUG> BC-HKN-KARIYA-UPDATING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA SIGNS NEW DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 TERMS IN THIRD GRAPH-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- For months Mighty Ducks president and general manager
Pierre Gauthier insisted that there was no reason to worry. That
Paul Kariya would be signed, sealed and delivered by the time
training camp began in September.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier delivered on his promise nearly two months early when
Kariya signed a three-year contract on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya's new deal is worth $30 million over three years. The
contract equals the agreement signed by Peter Forsberg of Colorado
this past season.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Kariya and the Ducks were unable to agree to terms
until Dec. 11 after the left winger had already missed 32 games of
a season that turned out to be a disaster for both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither one of us wanted that situation (a holdout),'' said
Kariya. ``The most important thing now in my career is to play and
help the team win games.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides set things in motion after the season when Kariya
and Gauthier spoke about beginning contract discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed both parties wanted the same thing, something that
had some length of time to it,'' said Gauthier. ``And we were going
to get to it immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks accelerated when Gauthier met face-to-face with Kariya's
agent, Don Baizley last Friday in Boston, and an agreement was in
place by Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the player wants something and and the team wants the
same thing you can get things done,'' said Gauthier.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was done so quickly that Kariya, who has been
concentrating on working out and rehabing his broken foot, admitted
the news surprised him a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caught me off guard,'' said a beaming Kariya at the Edison
Field press conference when asked if he felt he got fair-market
value. ``I think the contract is perfect and I hope that at the end
of the contract that Disney and the Ducks are pleased with what
they got.''
</P>
<P>
   As a restricted free agent, Kariya's options were limited. He
could have signed an offer sheet once the free agency period began
today. But the Ducks had the right to match and Kariya admitted he
couldn't imagine playing elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart I knew I would be here,'' said the five-year
veteran, who has scored 168 goals and 373 points in 302 games for
the Ducks. ``It's a tremendous place to play, I love it here.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's no doubt Anaheim management loves having Kariya
wrapped up for three years, even though it means both Teemu Selanne
and Kariya's contracts will expire after the 2001-2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is our leader, our captain and as we attempt to reach our
goals I can't think of anybody else I'd want to captain our ship,''
said Gauthier.
</P>
<P>
   It's an Anaheim ship that is in much smoother waters than it was
in 1997, when the Ducks fired Ron Wilson just weeks after they had
advanced to the second round of the playoffs. And it's a difference
that Kariya can't have helped but noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really pleased with the direction of the team and I feel
confident that in the next three years we will be be a contender
for Stanley Cup,'' he said. ``We are making the right moves to get
us to a Stanley Cup and as an athlete that's all you want, a chance
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Many feel there was pressure placed on Kariya in '97 to sign a
deal that would set a standard for the league's superstars. This
time around that was not the case and Kariya believes that was a
factor in getting the new deal done quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing that helped was that there were contracts in
place we could compare with,'' he said likely referring to
contracts signed by Jaromir Jagr and Peter Forsberg last season and
a handshake deal that Eric Lindros made offical on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Kariya, always considered a serious sort, openly spoke about
his outlook on life changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think every year I'm going to become a better
person, player, handle the media better, the fans better,'' he
said. ``The contract and head injury (in Feb. 1998) gave me some
perspective on what is important and not to take things so
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sort of take a little Teemu (attitude) and ease up a bit and
enjoy myself and have some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   TOP SALARIES FOR 1999-2000
</P>
<P>
   1. Jaromir Jagr (Pittsburgh) $10.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   2. Peter Forsberg (Colorado) $9.0
</P>
<P>
   3. Eric Lindros (Philadelphia) 8.5
</P>
<P>
   4. Pavel Bure (Florida) 8.0
</P>
<P>
   5. Patrick Roy (Colorado) 7.5
</P>
<P>
   6. Mats Sundin (Toronto) 7.0
</P>
<P>
   7. Dominik Hasek (Buffalo) 7.0
</P>
<P>
   8. Brian Leetch (New York Rangers) 6.68.
</P>
<P>
   9. Curtis Joseph (Toronto) $6.1
</P>
<P>
   10. Several tied at 6.0
</P>
</TEXT>
