u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-ART-1STLD-W     06-30 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY FIRST: BULLS TAKE DUKE'S BRAND AT NO. 1
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Updates throughout)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They passed on the risk and potential of Lamar
Odom, the explosiveness of Steve Francis and an open invitation to
Wally Szczerbiak's world. In the end, the Chicago Bulls went
straight to the low post to rebuild their franchise, taking the
burly Duke University forward Elton Brand with the No. 1 pick in
Wednesday night's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of speculation over who would emerge first from
this year's class, Bulls general manager Jerry Krause went the
conservative route in selecting the 6-foot-8-inch, 260-pound
college player of the year before a nearly sold-out gathering at
the MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know who would go one,'' Brand said after his
selection, echoing the sentiment of most NBA observers. ``Lamar
Odom, Steve Francis, Wally Szczerbiak, they're all great players,
so I didn't know exactly where I would fit in this draft.''
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore became one of four Blue Devils selected in the
first round, along with Duke teammates Trajan Langdon, taken 11th
by Cleveland; Corey Maggette, taken 13th by Seattle, and William
Avery, the 14th pick by the Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver picked a disheartened Francis, the skywalking Maryland
junior, with the second pick, and Charlotte nabbed the UCLA point
guard Baron Davis with the third pick. Rhode Island's Odom, the
draft's biggest enigma, was taken fourth by the Los Angeles
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks, with the No. 15 selection, passed on the
local player, Ron Artest of St. John's, and instead chose Frederic
Weis, a 7-2 center from France.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of the evening involved the Toronto Raptors passing
on Szczerbiak, the Miami of Ohio all-American, and plucking
18-year-old Jonathan Bender out of Picayune (Miss.) High School.
Bender, Raptors officials said, was reportedly headed to Indiana in
a trade for Antonio Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Raptors needed to clear salary-cap room before the
deal was completed, the transaction may not be made before Aug. 1.
Still, their intention to acquire the 6-10, 205-pound Bender spoke
volumes about Indiana's desire to get younger and more athletic in
a changing Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana coach Larry Bird and the Lakers' team president, Jerry
West, tabbed Bender as the best athlete in the draft, and
apparently Bird became fixated on drafting the first high school
player taken.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak, the first senior taken, was drafted sixth by the
Minnesota Timberwolves. There was speculation that Cleveland might
try to make a deal to acquire Szczerbiak, whom the Cavaliers wanted
all along, in part because of his huge popularity in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   There was an absence of blockbuster trades and movement in
general, but the feeling among many teams is that with Aug. 1 the
first date that teams can sign free agents, more deals involving
drafted players would be made over the next month.
</P>
<P>
   The host Wizards had the seventh pick, and their selection of
Connecticut swingman Richard Hamilton nearly brought the house down
with applause. The only similar decibel level came about when
Francis raised his arms as he walked up to the podium to shake the
hand of Commissioner David Stern; in one, scintillating year at
Maryland, he became a D.C.-area fan favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Francis sounded too thrilled about going to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long he planned to remain a Grizzly, he said: ``As
soon as I can get this hat off. I hear it's cold, rainy, far away
from here and they take all your money,'' an apparent reference to
Canada's tax system. Mike Bibby expressed the same kind of
discontent a year ago as Vancouver's No. 2 pick, but eventually
settled in.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Cavaliers took Utah's Andre Miller with the eighth
pick. The Phoenix Suns took University of Nevada-Las Vegas forward
Shawn Marion with the ninth pick and the Atlanta Hawks, one day
after moving Mookie Blaylock to Golden State for Bimbo Coles, Duane
Ferrell and their No. 21 pick, took Arizona's Jason Terry with the
10th pick.
</P>
<P>
   Terry was one of five point guards taken in the first 14 picks
along with Francis, Davis, Avery and Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Brand, the first Duke player to be taken No. 1, seemed like the
logical pick given his production last season and that the Bulls'
starting center last season was Dickey Simpkins. Frontcourt help
was clearly needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of pressure playing for the Bulls, with the
heritage and the championships,'' Brand said. ``I am looking
forward to meeting that challenge. I don't know what my role is
going to be yet, but I'm ready to get out there and find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom created the most stir leading up to the draft, especially
after his whirlwind interview tour on Tuesday. Working out in Miami
in the morning for Heat coach Pat Riley, who was contemplating
trading up for Vancouver's second pick, Odom showed up at a
Washington hotel in midafternoon before catching a late flight to
Chicago to meet with Krause and Bulls coach Tim Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been hectic for the 19-year-old freshman, but it was
the only way he could push up his value after two weeks of skipping
scheduled workouts, missing the league's mandated physical, firing
his agent and briefly entertaining the idea of returning to Rhode
Island _ a notion that was scuttled by the NCAA and the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the decisions I made might not have been the best
decisions for me at that time,'' Odom said. ``But hey, I'm 19 years
old. It's a good thing I didn't make those mistakes when I was 29
and it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was smiling after being drafted by the NBA's
losingest franchise, he added, ``When the Bulls drafted Michael
Jordan, they weren't the best team in the NBA, either.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
