<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-MERGER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT ON UTILITY MERGER NEAR, EXECUTIVE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ The head of Western Resources Inc. on Wednesday
said the company was within days of reaching an agreement that
would clear the way for Missouri regulators to approve its merger
with Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely close to a settlement in Missouri,'' David
Wittig told more than 400 people attending Western's annual meeting
in Topeka. Wittig is Western's president, chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Western has been negotiating with the staff of the Missouri
Public Service Commission, the Office of Public Counsel and other
parties in the state critical of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri regulators would have to approve the agreement, but
Wittig said approval could be received before a decision by Kansas
regulators, which is expected before Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Wittig said that he expected to settle differences
with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission this fall and that
there was no reason the merger couldn't be closed by Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to get it completed by the end of the year,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wittig's comments surprised some of the other parties in the
talks, who declined to say where the talks stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was highly inappropriate,'' Martha Hogerty,
Missouri's public counsel, said of Wittig's comments that a
settlement was near. Her office represents consumers before the
Public Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Krueger, deputy general counsel for the Public Service
Commission, confirmed that the commission's staff was in talks with
Western but declined to discuss specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Among the thorniest issues holding up any settlement is whether
Missouri ratepayers would have to pay some of the premium that
Western paid for KCP&AMP;L. Missouri regulators have never allowed
that.
</P>
<P>
   Hogerty said she wouldn't be ``comfortable'' with a settlement
that would have ratepayers pay some of the premium but declined to
discuss details of a potential settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having some pretty good discussions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would combine Western's two electric utilities, KPL
and KGE, and KCP&AMP;L into a new company _ Westar Energy, which would
be based in Kansas City. Westar would have $8.2 billion in assets
and 1 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   Western's stock price has struggled in the past year, dropping
from the 40 level. On Wednesday it closed at 26 5/8. If Western's
share price is less than 29 25/32 just before the merger closes,
either Western or KCP&AMP;L has the option to kill the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be the first to say that no one is happy with our stock
price,'' Wittig said at the annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He said a $75 million reduction in rates since February 1997 and
the delay in getting the KCP&AMP;L merger approved had been big factors
in the stock decline. He said that plans called for shareholders to
get an annual return of 15 percent and that the company should be
measured against that over the next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
