<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBALONE-RESIGNATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEO OF GLOBAL ONE JOINT VENTURE RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) In a sign of continuing trouble at Sprint Corp.'s
unprofitable joint venture with France Telecom and Deutsche
Telekom, Global One said Wednesday that its chief executive, Gary
Forsee, would resign, effective July 16.
</P>
<P>
   Forsee, 49, is the former president of Sprint's flagship
long-distance division.
</P>
<P>
   After overseeing strong growth in that business, he was
handpicked in February 1998 to run Global One, which has been
dogged by management, operational and cost problems since its
inception.
</P>
<P>
   Forsee's departure comes on the heels of Deutsche Telekom's
unsuccessful bid for Telecom Italia SpA, which soured that
company's decadelong partnership with France Telecom and heightened
expectations that an already strained Global One could fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad blow for Global One, especially because Forsee
was named to shore up the venture,'' said Edouard
Vallette-Viallard, an industry analyst. ``It contributes to the
uncertainty hanging over the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The partners said Forsee was quitting to pursue other career
opportunities. And while Forsee's family still lives in the Kansas
City area, Sprint spokesman Bill White said Sprint had no plans to
rehire its former executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to take a look at what's out there,'' White said.
``He will not be with Sprint.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsee was credited with sharpening Global One's focus on data
services to help it compete with other international alliances. The
company's sales from data services rose 45 percent last year, more
than twice the pace of adjusted sales for the whole group. Even so,
Global One isn't expected to break even until 2001, more than a
year behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The three partners in the venture, which offers voice, fax and
data services to multinational companies, reaffirmed their
commitment to Global One in March after news reports that the
alliance was near collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors and analysts, however, contend that ending the
venture would be the best way for the three to pursue increasingly
divergent international strategies.
</P>
<P>
   White said Global One's partners continued to discuss the future
of the alliance, but provided few details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll have a resolution in the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect either Deutsche Telekom or France Telecom,
Europe's two biggest phone companies, to bow out of the venture.
The German company bid for Telecom Italia without first alerting
France Telecom. The French phone company is suing Deutsche Telekom,
saying it violated partnership agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim Kroeske, Deutsche Telekom's chief financial officer,
said earlier this month that the German company would buy France
Telecom's stake if the French phone company quit the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Forsee is traveling and unavailable for comment, said Global One
spokesman Klaus Czerwinski.
</P>
<P>
   Global One's rivals are likely to use Forsee's departure as an
opportunity to poach clients made skittish by the continued
uncertainty, some analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-99 2330EDT &QL; 
