<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS WON'T GO SHOPPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- After trading for defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky and
winger Ted Donato and with the possibility that some recent draft
choices are ready to make the jump to the NHL level, look for
Anaheim general manager Pierre Gauthier to take his usual
conservative approach to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   The market opens today, but it's unlikely that Gauthier will
become a shopper unless just the right deal comes along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (free agency) is not the same thing as other sports,'' said
Gauthier, who did his shopping late last summer when he signed
Fredrick Olausson on Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Olausson turned out to be a $1-million bargin as he scored 16
goals and 56 points, fourth best among NHL defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   But Gauthier insists hockey free agency is crap shoot. And
indeed the Ducks have had mixed results at best with free agents
Warren Rychel, Jari Kurri and Tomas Sandstrom before Olausson came
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to our fans to look at it and we might (jump in) or
we might not,'' he said. ``Expectations shouldn't be the same (as
in other sports). I dare you in the last three years to look at the
money spent by each team and (see) if they improved or went down
... it's a scary, scary answer.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier already feels the Ducks have improved their skill
level, especially on defense where it was needed most.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good team, we don't have to do anything,'' he said.
``Whether we do (make more moves) I don't know, but I know we are
better (than last season).''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Among the high-profile free agents -- barring any last-minute
signings -- are forwards Theo Fleury, Valeri Kamensky, Joe Juneau,
Joe Murphy, Dave Andreychuk, Pat Verbeek, Ray Sheppard. It's slim
pickings on defense with Ulf Samuelsson, Gerld Diduck, Alexei
Gusarov and Lance Pitlock. But don't expect the Ducks to target one
player in particular, Gauthier says that often times that leads to
big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wind up paying whatever it takes to get him and (he) winds
up falling flat on his face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
