 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Bela Crkva, Yugoslavia) _ There is a conflict of
aims and interests between the International Criminal Tribunal and
ordinary Albanians, who are putting off funerals as they wait, in
great expectation, for investigators to come. The Albanians want a
record _ photographs, autopsies, hard numbers of the dead _ and
their new politicians are angling to get it from the tribunal,
based in The Hague. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-U.S. (Washington) _ The CIA and other government agencies
had detailed reports of widespread human rights abuses by the
Chilean military, including the killings and torture of leftist
dissidents, almost immediately after a 1973 right-wing coup that
the United States supported, according to once-secret government
documents just made public. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-EMERGENCY-CARE (New York) _ They look like any of the
anxious patients who walk into the city's polyglot emergency rooms.
But there are telltale signs: Sometimes they arrive with luggage
and with tourist visas in their pockets. Often they hand over
crumpled notes from their doctors back home in China or Africa.
They are known as medical immigrants, poor or middle-class
foreigners who scrape and save to fly to New York, solely to seek
treatment at city emergency rooms, where federal and state law
mandates that they must be examined and treated if their problems
require immediate care. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   DETECTIVE-INDICT (Denver) _ Using deception and a network of
sources to ferret out personal information, a private investigator
built a million-dollar-a-year business here selling information
that ended up in the hands as diverse as the tabloid press or a
reputed member of the Israeli Mafia. But now the investigator,
James Rapp, 39, and his wife, Regana Rapp, have been indicted on
two counts each of racketeering, in a case that is the first known
criminal prosecution against the growing business of peddling
confidential information. The case against the Rapps is the biggest
test of whether practices that are deceptive are also illegal. By
Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT14) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART (Undated) _ Despite previous estimates that mitral
valve prolapse affects 5 percent to 35 percent of the population, a
new report has found that the condition, in which a valve in the
heart is abnormally long and floppy, is much less common and much
less serious. By Holcomb B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SBC-AMERITECH _ ``Yawn.'' That was the first word uttered
Wednesday by one highly respected telecommunications analyst
reacting to the merger-approval deal that SBC Communications Inc.
struck Tuesday with the Federal Communications Commission as a
condition of its acquisition of Ameritech Corp. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT23) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-FRAUD (Undated) _ Federal investigators hunting for
