<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5460 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     06-30 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ Thrice-champion Boris Becker, former king of
Centre Court, played his final match at Wimbledon on Wednesday,
confirming his retirement after losing to Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the story.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Courier lost three match points and ultimately a gripping,
emotional five-setter to Britain's great Wimbledon hope, Tim
Henman, in one of the longest matches, timewise, in the history of
the 123-year-old tournament. Then, in his news conference, Courier
set a record for clever one-liners and glib observations about
Henman, himself and life in general.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the story.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams rallied from a set down to take out Anna
Kournikova in a showdown between the surviving teen glamour girls,
after which Kournikova pronounced women less mentally tough than
men, saying: ``They tend to get more nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the story.
</P>
<P>
   The long-vanquished teen glamour girl, No. 1-ranked Martina
Hingis, was the subject of a color photo spread in one of the
morning tabloids, which ran pictures of her in a bikini on a beach
in Cyprus kissing her boyfriend, Ivo Heuberger, a marginal player
on the men's tour.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the story.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Courier's failure to advance, six Americans _ three men,
three women _ stormed into the quarterfinals, a surprising
resurgent show of force for our once-mighty tennis nation that has
been on the ropes of late.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the story.
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe and Steffi Graf advanced through another round of
mixed doubles competition, although not before McEnroe, in a
classic McBrat flashback, threw a temper tantrum, insulting a
lineswoman by calling her a `` guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But no, no, no, that wasn't the story, either. With Alexandra
Stevenson on the grounds, John and Steffi could have revealed their
wedding plans and not been the story.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, no one except true tennis mavens had so much as
heard of Stevenson, 18, a willowy 6-1 late bloomer from San Diego.
But now she's in the quarterfinals of the most important, most
scrutinized tournament on the planet, and she finds herself trapped
in an ongoing maelstrom of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Figures. Her mom is a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   And according to her birth certificate, as reported by the Fort
Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel, her dad is Dr. J, Julius Erving.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Stevenson, a stringer for the New York Times, was one
of the first women to break into the male-dominated world of
sportswriting and worked in Philadelphia when Erving played for the
76ers. She raised Alexandra, who was born in December 1980 in San
Diego, as a single parent and has gone to considerable lengths to
keep the identity of Alexandra's father secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk about that,'' Samantha has said on several
occasions during the fortnight.
</P>
<P>
   When confronted with the news of the Sun-Sentinal's revelations
by a colleague who is a longtime friend of hers, she issued no
denials _ but shed no light on the report, either.
</P>
<P>
   The father's name on the birth certificate is Julius Winfield
Erving II, the good Doctor's full name. Also, Alexandra's middle
name happens to be Winfield.
</P>
<P>
   But California law requires no proof of parenthood for names to
be registered. And Erving, who has been married since 1972 _ he and
his wife, Turquoise, have four grown children _ denied to the
newspaper he is Alexandra's father.
</P>
<P>
   This bit of beyond-bizarre intrigue follows on the heels of
Samantha Stevenson's threat to sue Wimbledon for not acknowledging
her daughter's professional status and thus planning to withhold
prize money from her, which is a tidy $80,000-plus with a spot in
the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra turned pro at the Wimbledon qualifier in Roehampton
but didn't appear to inform anybody, at least not the Women's
Tennis Association. Hence, she is listed as an amateur.
Nonetheless, that squabble has become a non-issue with Wimbledon
agreeing to fork over the cash, whatever the sum.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but there's more.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in an interview, Samantha also nebulously accused
women's tennis of rampant racism and lesbianism, never mind that
the specific racist incident she was citing happened on the junior
circuit. Alexandra said so after beating Lisa Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   As for the charges of lesbians in the locker room, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, through it all, the resolutely cheerful Alexandra has
found it possible to produce extended patches of brilliant tennis,
most recently rallying from a dreadful start against Raymond. She
dropped 15 of the first 16 points before steadying herself and
prevailing in three sets.
</P>
<P>
   And she might not be done. Her next opponent, Jelena Dokic,
clobbered the badly out-of-sorts Hingis in the first round. But
Dokic, 16, a fellow qualifier, is in similarly uncharted Wimbledon
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra began her news conference by reading an upbeat
statement that was intended to deflect questions about the racism
issue. It failed, of course, and then she would quickly get
broadsided by the paternity matter.
</P>
<P>
   What a day. About the only thing that didn't happen was rain,
and even that wasn't the story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
