<SLUG> BC-STEALTHBOMBER-SUCCESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B-2 BOMBERS EXCEEDED EXPECTATIONS DURING WAR, AIR FORCE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Missouri-based B-2 stealth bomber proved
crucial in the Yugoslav air war, but two Air Force generals stopped
short Wednesday of saying that more of the $700 million planes
should be added to the country's arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The B-2 exceeded all our expectations in terms of durability,
reliability and overall performance _ period,'' said Brig. Gen.
Leroy Barnidge, commander of the 509th Bomber Wing at Whiteman Air
Force Base. ``Airborne performance was remarkably similar.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnidge and Lt. Gen. Marvin Esmond, deputy chief of staff for
Air Force air and space operations, briefed the Military
Procurement Subcommittee of the House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Esmond said the six B-2s deployed from Whiteman flew only 1
percent of all bombing missions in Yugoslavia, all at night, but
accounted for 11 percent of all targets hit. The other three B-2s
at Whiteman were not ready for combat.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Ryun, a Kansas Republican, asked if the Air Force would
like to see more B-2s. There are 12 more being built, and some
members of Congress have advocated a larger fleet. Original plans
called for 132.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would take the B-2s if we were issued those, of course,''
Esmond said, evoking laughter. ``We think the balance of bomber
support aircraft and fighter aircraft with our lift and tanker
capabilities, ratio-wise, is about right.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnidge said the B-2s were intended to be used in ``lethal
environments with hard-to-get-at targets'' and not as a workhorse
bombing fleet sent out on mass missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am quite satisfied with what we have right now...,'' he
said. ``I leave it to you gentlemen and the leadership of the
military to decide what the exact right number will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one on the subcommittee proposed adding more B-2s to
the 12 in production, some expressed a sense of vindication over
the plane's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who fought long and hard, first to get 15
(planes), then to get another five and then another one, feel that
this is a day of reckoning when we recognize publicly...how well
the B-2 stealth bomber did,'' said Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri,
ranking Democrat on the Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some skeptics, but we can always make
something better,'' Skelton said. ``Let's aim toward that end.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem with the B-2 is a lack of ``forward bases'' overseas
to keep and maintain the plane so pilots wouldn't have to make long
round trips from Whiteman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get that done in the future,'' Esmond said.
``But again, we don't want to prematurely put (the plane) at risk
in forward locations at this point if we don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the subcommittee questioned whether two pilots,
taking turns, can get enough sleep on long missions or if room
should be made for a third pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in a cockpit twice in my life when planes were
refueled, and I could see the knuckles of the pilots holding that
speed and holding that height,'' said Rep. Norman Sisisky, a
Virginia Democrat. ``And it seems to me it would be a lot of
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnidge said he had the same concern about pilot fatigue, and
that he immediately asked every pilot returning from Yugoslavia
about it. The pilots said they got two to six hours of sleep on
``power naps,'' Barnidge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All said they felt good,'' Barnidge said. ``And perhaps more
significantly, all asked when they could go again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
